 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARABS (Cairo, Egypt) _ A bitter war of words between Iraq
and its Arab neighbors has followed last month's American-led
bombings, leaving Iraq more isolated than at any time since the
Persian Gulf war. As Iraq has accused the Arabs of failing to stand
by its side, Egypt has responded with particular scorn, all but
calling for the ouster of the Iraqi leader, Saddam Hussein. The
confrontation became even more intense Tuesday as Saddam called on
Arabs to rise up against leaders who have not given his regime
their full support. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NORTH (Pevek, Russia) _ Here in Russia's most northern
city, a winter's day is two hours of cheerless gray, the
temperature plunges to 40 below, and delays in getting wages are
measured in years. It is the edge of the world and the end of the
line for thousands of Russians drawn here during Soviet times by
promises of high pay and patriotic appeals. The colonization of the
north was one of the Soviet Union's most audacious ventures. Now
the dismal economics of the north has finally caught up with these
far-flung regions. Russia's new market economy cannot bear the
colossal cost of feeding and heating the northern outposts. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REBELS (Bogota, Colombia) _ President Andres Pastrana
said Tuesday that ending the civil war that has ravaged his country
for nearly 40 years depends on the rebels' willingness to help
stamp out drug trafficking in areas under their control. By Diana
Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-GUN-SUIT (New York) _ In a potentially precedent-setting
lawsuit against gun makers the surviving relatives of six people
killed by firearms in New York shootings are seeking to hold the
gun industry collectively liable, just as many recent suits have
attacked the tobacco industry as responsible for deaths and
illnesses from smoking. The suit is considered potentially
precedent-setting because it invokes ``the theory of negligent
distribution'' of guns, rather than charging liability on the basis
of the product's inherent harmfulness. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FARMERS (Greensboro, Ga.) _ While pleased by the public
acknowledgment of their plight, many black farmers say that the
settlement will do little to reverse the stunning decline of
independent black farming, a livelihood that has carried a special
nobility ever since freed slaves were granted 40 acres and a mule.
The relief, which calls for farmers who claim they were harmed by
discrimination to receive $50,000 tax-free and to be forgiven their
federal debt, is too little, they said, and it has come too late.
And it does not relieve them of the burden of commercial debt they
took in when they could not get government money. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISONERS-DRUGS (Undated) _ The proportion of new prison inmates
who were current drug users at the time of their arrest increased
this decade, while drug treatment in state and federal prisons fell
sharply, according to a study released by the Justice Department.
By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-DISCRIMINATION-SETTLE (Washington) _ Texaco Inc. has
agreed to pay $3.1 million to 186 of its female employees who were
found by the Labor Department to have been systematically underpaid
relative to their male counterparts, people involved in the case
say. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CAPACITY (Imabari, Japan) _ More than the credit crunch,
wasteful and unneeded production facilities are the biggest drag on
Japan's vast manufacturing sector, pulling down profits at
companies ranging from giants like Toyota and Hitachi to thousands
of anonymous mom-and-pop suppliers. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KELLOGG-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Kellogg Co., struggling to wake
up its sleepy breakfast business, said Tuesday that its chief
executive would be replaced by the executive who had been widely
expected to succeed him. By Dana Canedy and Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   TUCKER-AD-COLUMN _ It has long been said that anyone who
represents himself or herself in court has a fool for a lawyer and
a fool for a client. But the verdict may be somewhat different in
the case of a marketing executive who has had himself for an agency
and an agency executive who has had himself for a client.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOLIDAY-CROWDS (New York) _ Broadway shows and New York
museums set holiday records. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   CONFESSIONS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Private Confessions'': Liv
Ullmann, director; with Ingmar Berman, writer. With Max von Sydow,
Pernilla August, Samuel Froler. In Swedish with English subtitles.
Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd considers a presidential
bid by Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich on tv coverge of the Senate
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BERRA-STEINBRENNER (Little Falls, N.J.) _ Let the record
show that a celebrated grudge held for nearly 14 years was dropped
here a few minutes after five p.m. Tuesday when a contrite George
Steinbrenner arrived at Yogi Berra's doorstep and thanked the
self-exiled Yankee great for the opportunity to make this day
necessary. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
NBA labor showdown. The owners are taking a tough stance, and in
this instance, they may be right. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Feature on Curtis Martin, who
becomes even more important for the Jets as they prepare for a
second-round playoff game at Giants Stadium on Sunday that should
be just as cold as Bill Parcells wants it. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DOLPHINS (Miami) _ Feature on the Dolphins, who have now
lost two starters from their defensive line and play in Denver with
this statistic hanging over this weekend: they are 4-16 on the road
in December with Dan Marino as quarterback. By Charles Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JAGUARS (Undated) _ Feature on Fred Taylor, the standout
rookie running back for the Jacksonville Jaguars and a player who
may be crucial in Sunday's game against the Jets in view of the
fact that quarterback Mark Brunnell is nowhere near 100 percent. By
Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-FOOD (New York) _ For years, trend spotters have trotted
out the same old prediction: South American food will be the Next
Big Thing in New York restaurants. It's a sleeping giant, they
would say, coming any day now. Any day. Well, look around you. From
the basket of steaming arepas that arrives with the menu at
Orinoco, a new Venezuelan restaurant on the Upper East Side, to the
grilled Argentine skirt steak served at Ideya in SoHo, the next big
thing is finally here. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ROOTS (Undated) _ The first impulse of many uninitiated
cooks who happen upon root vegetables from Latin America in the
market is simply to shake their heads and walk way. These tubers _
brown, bumpy, sometimes even scaly _ look for all the world like
miniature logs that were tossed into the vegetable bin by mistake.
But nothing could be further from the truth. These vegetables are
bedrock culinary staples throughout Latin America and the Caribbean
and provide great culinary rewards for those willing to explore
them.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-TEACH (New York) _ With all due respect to New York's
great cooking schools, they are, for the most part, relatively cold
places, steely professional institutions that lack the warmth of
home and hearth. That's fine for anyone heading off to labor in
some restaurant dungeon. But for the rest of us there is often a
disconnect. Once _ and the tradition is nearly gone now _ we could
learn the secrets of home cooking alongside our mothers and fathers
by helping them chop, mix, and stir. Domestic cooking was not a
formal art. And yet beautiful food often emerged from those
informal kitchens. Fortunately, in loco parentis, there's a small
band of people who still offer latecomers a way into this domestic
tradition by teaching fine cooking in real, home kitchens. By Polly
Frost.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
