<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED DOLPHINS FOCUS ON HANDLING DAVIS, AND THE COLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The Miami Dolphins readily acknowledge that
Terrell Davis is the Broncos' most indispensable offensive player.
Trouble is, the Dolphins are also aware that their two defensive
linemen most responsible for holding the National Football League's
leading rusher to 29 yards late in the regular season will be
missing for the teams' rematch on Saturday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Jason Taylor of Miami broke a clavicle in Miami's
final regular season game. Then tackle Tim Bowens was lost in last
week's playoff victory over Buffalo with a torn right bicep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim did a great job of plugging the run lanes against Terrell,
and Jason was flying around, making a lot of plays,'' the
third-year defensive lineman Shane Burton said of the teams' last
meeting, won by Miami at home, 31-21, on Dec. 21. ``Those are two
of our main guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who along with the second-year tackle Barron Tanner will
try to fill that defensive gap on Saturday, senses the Broncos will
be trying to prove a point with Davis. His 29-yard game was an
aberration in a season that saw him rush for 2,008 yards, becoming
only the fourth player in NFL history to reach 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got away from their game plan the last time we played,''
Burton said. ``They're obviously going to try to run him now.
They've got to run him to have success.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dwight Hollier said the Broncos (14-2) are likely to
use the same playoff formula that worked last season, when they won
the franchise's first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got to the Super Bowl on the back of Terrell Davis, and
he's been a factor all year long,'' Hollier said. ``When he's
running well, playing well, everything else opens up for them. So
he is our main focus, doing the type of job we did last time on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As formidable as Davis figures to be in this American Football
Conference semifinal game, the 11-6 Dolphins have other concerns as
well. Two of their key pass-catchers are hobbling, and they carry
two historic albatrosses into this game _ they have not played well
on the road this time of year and have not fared well in cold
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson said on Tuesday that tight end Troy
Drayton's right ankle sprain appeared worse than believed, and that
the team's leading receiver, O.J. McDuffie, was limited by a right
foot sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably as banged up right now as we've been this
season,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have not won a road playoff game, excluding Super
Bowls, since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   They are a woeful 4-18 in road games in December and January
since 1988, 4-16 with quarterback Dan Marino healthy. Three of
those losses have come in the playoffs, most recently last season's
17-3 collapse at New England.
</P>
<P>
   It is projected to be between 30 and 35 degrees for Saturday's
game. In their history, the Dolphins have never had to play a
January game in weather that cold.
</P>
<P>
   But a berth in the AFC title game is at stake, and the Dolphins
on Tuesdayy tended to shrug off the possible impact of frigid
weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all fine and good,'' Marino said when informed of
Miami's troubles on the road in cold weather. ``But when you get
right down to it, you've got to execute and play football. That's
really what it comes down to. You've got to have a sense of urgency
any time you play in this league, no matter the conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Lamar Thomas, who caught three touchdown passes in
the first meeting with Denver, sheepishly acknowledged that he has
never played in a game with the temperature below 40 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm looking forward to it,'' Thomas, who played his
college ball at the University of Miami, said at the team's Nova
Southeastern University base. ``I want to play in a game where the
snow is coming down and you can see your breath. I always thought
that looked good on the highlights.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
