<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYANREACTION-HNS &LR;      01-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYANREACTION-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Regarding the nine seasons Nolan Ryan spent with the Astros, one
sentiment stands out among his former teammates.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were glad to be on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing hitters certainly didn't want to face Ryan, who earned
the reputation as baseball's greatest power pitcher ever.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ashby, who had the best view of Ryan's 100-mph fastball
from behind the plate for the Astros during the 1980s, still
recalls how hitters would walk to the plate, only to walk back to
the dugout, mesmerized by the newly elected Hall of Famer's
overwhelming dominance. Ashby, who also played for Toronto, was a
strikeout victim of Ryan five times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys would come to the plate and just make comments about
how ridiculous it was to come and try and get a hit off this guy,''
said Ashby, who caught Ryan's fifth career no-hitter Sept. 26,
1981, against the Los Angeles Dodgers at the Astrodome. ``What I
really remember is when he began to master the changeup. He still
maintained that great fastball and curveball, but once he started
to master the changeup, literally some of the best hitters in the
game would come to home plate and just say, `This isn't fair
anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   From A to Z, if a player crossed paths with Ryan, he likely was
one of a record 5,714 strikeout victims. Rod Carew struck out 29
times against Ryan, Reggie Jackson 23, George Brett 18 and Mike
Schmidt 15. Claudell Washington holds the dubious honor of striking
out the most against The Express _ 39 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ryan hasn't struck you out, you're nobody,'' said Rickey
Henderson, the 5,000th strikeout victim of Ryan in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most memorable Ryan encounters came June 10, 1981, at
Veterans Stadium, with the Phillies' Pete Rose needing two hits to
break Stan Musial's National League career record. The morning of
the game, Ryan read that Rose had predicted a few weeks earlier he
would break the record against Ryan in the series with Houston, and
it appeared he would deliver on that promise after leading off the
first with a single, tying Musial with his 3,630th hit.
</P>
<P>
   Rose batted three more times in the game, with Ryan striking him
out all three times using nothing but fastballs, except for one
curve that produced the second whiff. After the third strikeout,
Rose tipped his batting helmet to Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the confrontations between Ryan and Rose were just
classic, two of the greatest competitors of all time,'' Ashby said.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker was the opposing pitcher at the
Dome in 1968 when Ryan earned his first major-league victory in a
4-0 Mets win. Ryan's line: 6 innings, three hits, two walks and
eight strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we didn't know he was Nolan Ryan,'' Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker recalls the reaction from the Astros' dugout on another
occasion after Ryan uncorked several fastballs in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on our bench came off and to the rail, standing
there with mouths agape,'' Dierker said. ``Nobody had ever seen a
fastball like that. We'd seen Sandy Koufax, Bob Gibson and Tom
Seaver. We knew within three or four pitches in the first inning
that his fastball was something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who grew up in nearby Alvin, began his Astros career Nov.
19, 1979, when he signed a contract making him the first player in
baseball history to make $1 million in a season. Over the course of
the next nine seasons, he compiled a 106-94 record, helped the
Astros to division titles in 1980 and 1986 and became the majors'
all-time strikeout king.
</P>
<P>
   ``That broke new ground,'' said Astros president Tal Smith, the
club's president/general manager at the time of Ryan's signing.
``As you reflect on it, it was certainly to somebody that was
well-deserving. He earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ryan developed a reputation as a fierce competitor on the
field, he was equally as demanding of his teammates in the
clubhouse on days he pitched. That competitive nature is one of the
main reasons Ryan continued to pitch into his mid-40s while others,
years younger, bowed out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit the dugout, if he perceived in any way that guys
did not have their heads in the game or weren't vesting everything
they had, you would hear about it,'' Ashby said. ``He was really
one of the only pitchers I ever was around that you would hear
about it _ maybe him and Gaylord Perry. You'd absolutely hear about
it directly in your face in the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Reynolds, an infielder for the Astros from 1979-89, looks
beyond Ryan's mind-boggling numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was the huge impact his family had,'' Reynolds said.
``In a sense, his wife Ruth needs a plaque, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he won't don an Astros cap for Cooperstown, Ryan will
always be remembered as one of the organization's greatest heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved him as a fan,'' said owner Drayton McLane Jr., who
purchased the club prior to the 1993 season. ``After buying the
Astros, just to get to know him better it's all as advertised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
