<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AND SHARKS TIE, 3-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD _ Dave Andreychuk stood on crutches outside the
New Jersey Devils' locker room, trying to find a bright spot in
what had been a miserable night for the team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They squandered a lead in the third period against the San Jose
Sharks and settled for a 3-3 tie at Continental Arena, but that was
hardly the worst part. Andreychuk, the left wing on the Devils'
most productive line, broke his right ankle, which will sideline
him for about six to eight weeks, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it's not displaced, which means I won't have to have
surgery,'' said Andreychuk, who will have more X-rays Thursday.
``That's good news.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk, who has 11 goals and 11 assists in 29 games on a
line with Bobby Holik and Randy McKay, was injured at 7 minutes 51
seconds of the first period when he twisted awkwardly while trying
to make a play from his knees. He got caught under Sharks
defenseman Marcus Ragnarsson and remained face down on the ice
until being helped off by . Andreychuk, who had fractured his left
ankle in the final game of the 1996-97 season, said, ``You know
right away something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what was wrong here on Tuesday night wasn't as obvious
as Andreychuk's injury.
</P>
<P>
   McKay, who returned to action after missing five games with an
assortment of ailments, scored a first-period goal and assisted on
another, helping the Devils forge a 2-2 tie.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the second period, the Devils' Scott Stevens
mixed it up with San Jose's Jeff Friesen, and the two nearly came
to blows. As the teams left the ice and Stevens went past the
Sharks' bench, players shouted taunts at him. Stevens spotted
Brantt Myhres, who has twice left the Sharks to spend time in
alcohol rehabilitation, most recently last month. The Sharks said
Stevens told Myhres, ``Go have another beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Myhres said, ``I just said, `Why don't you pick on somebody a
little bigger?' and he comes back with a comment as far as
alcoholism goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's pretty classy coming from a guy who's got
someone sitting down from you on the bench who went through the
same thing for a year,''' Myhres added, referring to the Devils'
Ken Daneyko. ``He should think before he says something, but that's
just the mentality of Scott Stevens. An idiot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said it was all in the heat of battle. ``I was upset at
the time and he was yelling at me,'' Stevens said of Myhres. ``I
yelled something back. Sometimes you say something you regret. I
don't need him yelling at me. Yeah, he's been through some tough
times, but you know, sometimes you should be happy you're in the
league, and he's had a lot of chances as far as I'm concerned.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problems overshadowed a lackluster performance by the
Devils, who took a 3-2 lead at 5:08 of the third period when Holik
scored his second goal of the game. But the Devils gave that lead
away when Friesen knocked in a rebound with 9:53 to play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
