<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLAIBORNE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIBORNE TO TURN PRO, SOWARD TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When they made their recruiting trip to USC
together three years ago, wide receiver R. Jay Soward remembered
linebacker Chris Claiborne saying his college career would last
``three years and I'm out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne kept his promise Tuesday, when he officially announced
that he would skip his senior season and turn pro. Soward, who
entertained thoughts of turning pro, provided some relief to coach
Paul Hackett minutes later by announcing he would stay for his
senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would both leave after our junior years,'' Soward
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither decision was a surprise. Claiborne said the day before
the Sun Bowl that he was going to hire an agent, while Soward told
his father immediately after the game that he would return to
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready for a new challenge,'' Claiborne said. ``I had a
little bit of unfinished business at the university. We wanted to
go to the Rose Bowl. The best thing is that I felt comfortable
about the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett, while lamenting Claiborne's loss, understood the
decision after NFL people told him that Claiborne should at least
start off draft workouts by being among the top 10 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very torn,'' Hackett said. ``I didn't feel overly one
way or the other. I wanted to be selfish but I don't think either
of us lets selfishness override the discussion. I fully support him
and I think it's going to be marvelous.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my wildest dreams, I didn't think I would have the
opportunity to be around someone of Chris' caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``You build teams with people, and Chris, from the from the very
beginning, once he got over telling me he might transfer, was
really the model you want as a football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward's decision wasn't nearly as simple. He had heard he might
go anywhere from the late first round to the third round, which was
enough to dash his hopes of turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his father, Rodney, sounded in favor of his son going pro
following USC's 28-19 loss to Texas Christian in the Sun Bowl last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad probably still thinks I should have,'' Soward said.
``He wasn't very happy with the season I had. He didn't think I got
enough touches.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward said he intends to meet with Hackett to make sure coach
and wide receiver are on the same page next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and coach, we're going to sit down and have a lot of
planning to make things a lot better,'' Soward said. ``We're going
to come up with different ways to get me the ball. I'm going to be
a big part of this offense. I'm probably the biggest part of this
offense coming back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
