</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY PLAYERS CRITICIZE VOTING PROCEDURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ NBA players are gathering today in New York to
hold a vote that could determine the future of the league. But
before a single player could book a first-class ticket, many were
assailing the voting process itself.
</P>
<P>
   Players had less than 36 hours to make travel plans _ in the
face of a deadly Midwest storm no less _ to get to New York for a
mandatory, in-person vote.
</P>
<P>
   As far as anyone knows, proxy votes will not be allowed, so
failure to attend means forfeiting the right to be heard on the
weightiest of issues: whether to accept the NBA's final offer and
end the six-month lockout, or to reject it and risk cancellation of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   And even that choice is not so clear. According to reports out
of New York, players won't be voting on whether to ratify
commissioner David Stern's final offer. Instead, they will vote on
whether to support the union's decision to reject Stern's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the union had not informed players Tuesday how the
vote would be conducted _ by secret ballot or in an open session
prone to peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest blizzard may pale in comparison to the storms
brewing within union ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've definitely put us in a tough position,'' said Lakers
guard Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers guard Poor Richardson called the situation ``extremely
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And if players who don't go to New York forfeit their right to
vote?
</P>
<P>
   ``That means a deal is not going to be made anyway,'' Richardson
said. ``That means... there's no season. That means it's been
railroaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players felt misled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is (ridiculous),'' Miami's Keith Askins said. ``Who's
going to fly to New York on two days' notice after a blizzard?
Then, you want to vote on something, and they tell you you can only
vote on something else?
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a vote. This is out of control... This is wrong. I
feel ashamed to be part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's vote by players will be followed Thursday by a vote of
the NBA's 29 owners. If players again reject Stern's final offer,
owners could vote to cancel the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the union is betting otherwise _ that a full-membership
rejection of Stern's offer will force the NBA to resume
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that this will cause the owners to be a little bit
more pragmatic and a little bit more prudent,'' Hunter said.
``We're expecting (players) to vote in support of the position
promoted by the (union) negotiating committee.. We think the
message that we have to send to the owners is that our players are
still unified.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some agents, the union plans to hold an
open-session voice vote, and only after a pep talk from union
leaders aimed at maintaining a unified voice. That means peer
pressure could influence the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' said the Lakers' Eddie Jones, ``because that's
what it seems like. You get all these guys who are making minimum
(salary) into New York and try to intimidate them. You just can't
do that. You have to go in there as a man and do what you feel is
best for you.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials are already calling the vote a sham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to us more like a bargaining tactic than an example
of union democracy,'' NBA chief legal counsel Jeffrey Mishkin said.
</P>
<P>
   And the players? Many weren't sure what to think Tuesday as they
finished their morning pickup games at UCLA and prepared to make
travel plans. But most predicted a close vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only Richardson, who favors accepting Stern's offer, would
reveal how he plans to vote. Many said they wouldn't decide until
they got to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope guys do what's best for themselves,'' said Jones.
``Right now you have to be selfish, you have to do what's best for
you. Don't let anybody intimidate you. Do what's best for you and
your family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
