<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0286 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ABDUL-JABBAR-HNS &LR;      01-06 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ABDUL-JABBAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Although the Miami Dolphins have a future Hall of Fame
quarterback in Dan Marino, their coach is convinced the route to
the Super Bowl is not through the pass, but through the run.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson admits his team faces ``an uphill battle''
Saturday against the defending NFL champion Denver Broncos on their
snowy home field.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dolphins, 12-point underdogs and losers of eight
consecutive playoff road games, have almost no chance of winning
without a running game, regardless of whom they play. Since Johnson
became their coach in 1996, the team is 0-17 when running the ball
fewer than 25 times.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving in Miami, Johnson has continually pushed the
ground control issue. Last year he was so desperate for a running
back that he brought in the troubled Lawrence Phillips, who soon
departed. When the season ended, Johnson fired offensive
coordinator Gary Stevens ``because of problems we had running the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then rewrote the Dolphins' playbook, cutting out much of
the passing, and signed one of the NFL's most aggressive run
blockers in former Houston Oiler Kevin Donnalley. And with his 1998
first-round draft pick, Johnson chose a running back, Mississippi's
John Avery.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure was clearly on the incumbent running back, Karim
Abdul-Jabbar, to make a name for himself and keep people from
asking, ``Isn't that a basketball player?''
</P>
<P>
   Jabbar accepted the challenge. He doubled his time in the film
room and the weight room, becoming more knowledgeable and more
durable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be stronger at the end of the season, when
everyone else is wearing down,'' he explained. ``Last season, when
we got to the end, I was ready to take a nose dive. Had we gone all
the way, I would not have been ready.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he's ready to last the entire postseason _ if the
Dolphins surprise Johnson by taking it beyond Saturday. In Miami's
24-17 victory over Buffalo last weekend, Abdul-Jabbar rushed 27
times for 95 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But was that an anomaly?
</P>
<P>
   There were many times during the season when the third-round
draftee from UCLA ran like he was in the Everglades. Although he
held off the challenge of the quick but erratic Avery, Abdul-Jabbar
ranked only 12th in the AFC in rushing with 960 yards and a
3.6-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he made points with Johnson not only because of his work
ethic but because, well, he made points. He scored six times this
season, giving him 32 rushing touchdowns in three years, second
only to Denver's Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of turning it up when you get close to the goal
line,'' Abdul-Jabbar said. ``Sometimes I wish I could run as fast
on the 50-yard line as I do when we're down near the goal line.''
</P>
<P>
   He also runs faster when he has the holes to run through. He
prospered last Saturday when, led by the drive-blocking Donnalley,
the Miami offensive line dominated the Bills' estimable front
seven.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar had not seen that sort of blocking for several
weeks, as Miami's two best linemen were stymied by injuries,
Donnalley with a sprained knee and Richmond Webb with a torn
triceps.
</P>
<P>
   When Webb returned to left tackle last week, his capable
stand-in, Brent Smith, shifted to right guard, and a transformation
occurred: The Dolphins dominated the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar welcomes the improved blocking, but he's not
depending on it.
</P>
<P>
   He prides himself on making yardage when there's nowhere to run.
When viewing game video, he pays special attention to plays in
which the blocking breaks down. He studies ways to escape tacklers
and plow for yardage on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to make yards without great blocking,'' he declared
when the season began, anticipating what would come.
</P>
<P>
   He spends as much time watching video as some coaches. In fact,
he wants to be a coach some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten fanatical,'' he said. ``I want to be able to go to
the chalkboard and draw the plays like our coaches do. I want to be
able to put together a game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably would be a game plan to Johnson's liking, full of
running plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
