</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YOUNT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNY YOUNT BLOSSOMED INTO GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Physically, there wasn't much to Robin Yount when
he was a sophomore at Taft High in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 5-foot-7 and 135 pounds,'' said Ray O'Connor, Yount's
coach at Taft.
</P>
<P>
   But when Yount grew into his body _ and spent a summer living
with his older brother Larry, who was a pitcher in Triple-A _ he
became an All-City Section shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came from being not-a-too-great-or-outstanding junior ...
simply because he finally matured,'' O'Connor said of Yount, who
was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame on Tuesday. ``As a senior,
he was about 6-foot and maybe 160 pounds. Rob has a tremendous work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't leave after a practice without hitting him another
100 ground balls,'' he said. ``He wanted to work and he had his
sights well-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount, who graduated from Taft and went on to get 3,142 hits in
a 19-year career with the Milwaukee Brewers, is the second high
school player from the San Fernando Valley voted into the Hall,
following Don Drysdale, who went to Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who coached at Taft from 1960 until his retirement in
'82, said he couldn't have predicted a Hall of Fame career for
Yount, who was the City's player of the year in 1973. Yount was the
Brewers' No.2 choice in the amateur draft and an 18-year-old
starter at shortstop by 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a neat thing, isn't it? I'm just thrilled to death
for him,'' said O'Connor, who lives in Woodland Hills. ``He's a
hell of a neat guy. He's not one of these guys that is a great
athlete but a real (jerk). This guy is a first-class human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Miller, a teammate of Yount's at Taft, was a first baseman
and pitcher. Miller said he was more of a basketball player and he
planned on not playing baseball his senior year _ until Yount
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin coaxed me into coming out,'' said Miller, who sells
insurance and lives in Canoga Park. ``At the time I was 6-foot-5.
(Yount) told me, `You're a bigger goon than the other first baseman
and you're easier to throw to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yount told ESPN on Tuesday that he didn't take the Hall of Fame
vote seriously until a few days ago, when his ``stomach was tied in
knots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty incredible feeling,'' said Yount, who was
elected with George Brett and Nolan Ryan. ``I feel very fortunate
even to be mentioned in the same breath as those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett, who grew up in El Segundo, told ESPN he was pleased to be
inducted the same year as Yount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the guys I played against in 20 years,'' he said, ``I
probably enjoyed playing against him the most. I always looked
forward to playing against Robin.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount was an adequate player as a junior, O'Connor said, but it
wasn't until he got a taste of professional baseball with Larry
that summer in '72 did he dedicate himself to getting better.
</P>
<P>
   In his debut as a senior, Yount hit two triples against
Cleveland and went on to hit .487, O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``During that (summer), he just found himself,'' O'Connor said.
``He grew about three inches and put on about 20 pounds of weight.
He just blossomed as a senior.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were in high school, Yount got to work with Taft
graduates who were either playing or bound for the major leagues.
According to O'Connor, Rick Dempsey, Larry Dierker, Pete LaCock and
Rick Auerbachall were influences on Yount, who went on to win two
American League MVP awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a doubt in (Yount's) mind when he went up with
Milwaukee that he was going to be good enough,'' he said. ``He grew
up with guys around him that were extremely good players. He just
saw that there was no difference between he and they.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
