<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     01-06 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ALVIN _ In this scenic little farm town, where the principal
industry is honoring Nolan Ryan, immortality came to the favorite
son Tuesday just as everyone knew it would.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Baseball Writers' Association of America made it official by
electing Ryan, George Brett and Robin Yount to the Hall of Fame,
the first time since the shrine opened in 1936 that three players
were accepted in their initial year of eligibility. Ryan led the
way, his fans will not be surprised to learn, by being named on all
but six of the 497 ballots cast.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nolan stood on the stage of the Nolan Ryan Center for
Continuing Education, on the campus of Alvin Community College, and
fielded questions from the media mob whose cars and vans filled the
parking lot. He did it with the easy grace of a Tony Bennett
responding to requests from the audience for his all-time hits.
</P>
<P>
   Every nine or 10 years Ryan changed teams, and by then a new
generation of batters would have surfaced, all potential jelly for
his toast. It worked that way in 1971, when he fled from New York
and landed in Disneyland, and again in 1979, when he left the
Angels for Houston. ``I was very close to Gene Autry,'' he
confided, ``and it was hard leaving the Angels.'' Then, one more
time, he shed his skin and reappeared as a Texas Ranger. On one of
the walls of the Nolan Ryan exhibit center is a quote, describing
the pain experienced by the fans of the Astros on his departure:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will miss him every day of their lives, and some will
miss him every fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   Low points? He's had a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has peaks and valleys,'' he said. ``With the Mets, I
had control problems. Then there was my first elbow surgery with
the Angels. In those days, they didn't have sports medicine. I
didn't know if my career was over, if I'd be able to pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there wasn't a lower day in my life than the day I flew
back from the winter meetings in Atlanta after signing a contract
with the Rangers. I realized I was no longer an Astro, wasn't going
to finish my career in Houston, that I was changing leagues. It
presented a whole new set of problems. I had to move my family up
there, find a home, new teammates, new organization. And this was
very late in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   As matters developed, the move provided Ryan with a powerful
finishing kick to an already illustrious journey. With the Rangers,
Nolie peppered the record book with his sixth and seventh
no-hitters, became the first pitcher to strike out 5,000 batters
and added the final 51 of his 324 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, his career was cut short after just 27 seasons, and he
retired as a callow kid of 46 after blowing out his elbow at
Seattle in the final month of the 1993 season. He left with 53
major-league records. With the classic Ryan economy, he attributed
his Hall of Fame election to ``my longevity, and being able to
maintain a certain level in the later years.''
</P>
<P>
   When you think of all he accomplished over nearly three decades,
you feel a strong urge to tell him to sit down, that he deserves a
rest. But the eyes never revealed any fatigue, and the arm went
where the eyes led. He pitched over 5,000 innings, averaging a
strikeout an inning. This is power. This is consistency. This is
the essence of the game: the will of the solitary man to take on
the many.
</P>
<P>
   A package was handed out to the press Tuesday, 13 pages
detailing the highlights of his career, printed in that tiny type
that almost demands that you reach for a magnifying glass. But
neither words nor numbers are needed to justify Ryan's admission to
baseball's holy sanctuary. All you had to do was see him pitch.
</P>
<P>
   I covered his first win for the Mets, over the Astros and Larry
Dierker, on a Sunday in 1968, in front of his family and friends. I
have written about him off and on ever since, a fringe benefit of
this profession, but not one that entitles me to claim any special
intimacy. Nolan is most at ease with his neighbors, who have known
him all his life, and his former teammates, with whom he shared the
daily grind, the glory and the grief. This is part of his
character. You do not become his friend by lining up and taking a
number.
</P>
<P>
   He took note Tuesday of the campaign by the legendary Ted
Williams to have the Hall of Fame open its doors to Shoeless Joe
Jackson, banned for life after being tainted by the Black Sox
scandal of 1919.
</P>
<P>
   So Nolan used his new platform to work in a plug for one from
his generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind,'' he said, ``Pete Rose deserves to be in the Hall.
I saw Pete play the game. I saw him serve his time. I think he
ought to be honored for what he accomplished as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   This endorsement prompted a reference to the famous duel between
the two of them, when Rose was trying to break Stan Musial's
National League record for career hits _ on his way to Ty Cobb's
all-time mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the competitor Pete was and how hard it was to strike
him out,'' Ryan said, his eyes brightening at the memory. ``As much
as he was focused on getting the record off me, I was focused on
not letting him do it. He got the hit that tied the record his
first at-bat, then I struck him out the next three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole scenario was one of the most meaningful moments of
my career. After he struck out the third time, he broke his bat on
the ground walking back to the dugout. Then he turned around and
saluted me. As a professional, that was one of the highest honors I
ever received.''
</P>
<P>
   All Pete was saying, really, was that ``you're a better man than
I am, Gunga Din.'' He was saying what so many of us have always
felt about this modest farmer from Alvin who built his monuments
one brick at a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
