<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-06 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ Roy Kramer, the John DeLorean of the Bowl
Championship Series, is a happy man today.
</P>
<P>
   His silly little idea worked. His slick, style-over-substance
bowl scheme came away with a true winner in its first try at
unifying the national-championship race.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl ultimately deflected all
doubt about just which team was the best in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. It's Tennessee. BCS or no BCS, playoff or no
playoff, the Vols were a team that should have been No. 1 and
proved it. We have to believe the Vols would have found a way to
have us all whistling Rocky Top at the end of the season no matter
the circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer called it destiny. And after the
Vols' latest great adventure, we must believe.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a season highlighted by an escape at Syracuse, a
close win against Florida and the ball bouncing just the right way
against Arkansas. Monday night, the Vols put forth the lesser of
two ugly games in the Fiesta Bowl and again found a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Vols had faced a Florida State team at its best, we
have to believe they still would have responded and won.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Vols had had to scratch through a playoff bracket
instead of a one-game brawl for it all, we have to believe destiny
still would have been darling for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this is not to diminish what Tennessee accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But let's look under the hood of Kramer's DeLorean. Let's look
at how the Vols might have won and deserved the national
championship but how the nation seemed to respond to the BCS
inauguration with a collective ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   Like the DeLorean, the Fiesta Bowl was more glitter than
substance, with all the requisite Super Bowl-type hoopla in and
around Tempe. But the product fell well short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   There was bunting hung from the highest rafters of Sun Devil
Stadium. There were parachutists. There were fireworks popping all
around overhead. There were carnival-like activities bustling
outside the gates and special guests and celebrities arriving from
all over.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, it was all like the stainless steel on the
DeLorean. It all looked nice but deceived. The game sputtered and
coughed. The public's reception to the game was disappointing to
many.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Tennessee is the best team in the country. But it deserved
to be at its best and sharpest in this championship game and
wasn't. The same is true for the Seminoles, who might never have
looked worse in a big game.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for a ridiculous 21 penalties, most of them
of the brain-lock variety. They both made numerous other mistakes.
Worse, there was an inordinate number of injuries on both sides,
including one play on which the starting left tackle and left guard
for Tennessee had to be helped off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself something. Better yet, ask Roy Kramer: Would all
this ugliness have happened had Florida State not had a whopping
44-day break since its last game and Tennessee a 30-day break?
</P>
<P>
   Would these teams have been this out of sync and sloppy had a
college football playoff system been in place instead, during which
teams would have been more likely to stay in top form and focused?
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the Florida State team that we like to be out
there,'' Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden said after the game. ``But
Tennessee had the same problem. Man, 44 days. That's a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way. The break FSU had between its final
regular-season game and the Fiesta Bowl was longer than spring
training usually lasts.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only problem.
</P>
<P>
   Had a playoff system been in place, there would have been a
crescendo toward Monday night's championship game. There would have
been a steady association with these teams from the nation's casual
fans. Like what happens in an NCAA Tournament. Like what happens
with an NFL surprise playoff winner _ the Arizona Cardinals, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   More people would have fallen in line behind the likes of
Tennessee and Florida State, and by kickoff, the weeks of buildup
would have had TV viewers tuning in from Poughkeepsie to Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the host city obviously had no reason to feel giddy
about Tennessee or Florida State. Throughout the week, it became
obvious the Phoenix area couldn't care less, preferring to stay
home and watch Keith Jackson's ABC farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices outside the gates plummeted in the hours before
kickoff, with $135 face-value tickets going for as little as $15.
The Arizona Republic reported Tuesday that one person boasted of
getting a ticket offer of ``$10 and a sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you were a true college football fan or touched by
Jackson's television farewell, there was no reason to stay tuned to
this one past the first few blunders of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This inaugural BCS experience showed us more than the mettle of
a true No. 1. It showed us why we still should hope for a playoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
