<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     01-06 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS IS A BUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final returns are in, and America has reached a consensus
about the Bowl Championship Series (BCS): It needs to be flushed.
</P>
<P>
   College football's first attempt at producing a national title
within the structure of the bowls proved as successful as America's
first ventures into space. It did not achieve orbit.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred thousand football fans in Tennessee would disagree
with this, understandably so, as might a few dozen bowl directors.
But among those in the nation who do not know the words to Rocky
Top or own any garish bowl blazers, the BCS plan was as tasty and
as satisfying as spam.
</P>
<P>
   Did it produce a national champ? Yes. But a 13-0 Tennessee would
have been national champ regardless of what team the Vols beat in
the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Did it produce a great game? Just the opposite. Tennessee's
23-16 win over Florida State was one untidy bowl, leaving most
viewers numb. If this was the best college had to offer, then maybe
everyone needs to go back to high school. Those who say the layoff
between the regular season and bowls played a role moronically
forget there's always been a four-to-six-week layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Did it capture the imagination of the country? No. The rating
Monday for the first collegiate version of the Super Bowl was a
less-than-expected 17.2. The Rose Bowl between two also-rans in the
BCS world, Wisconsin and UCLA, posted a 17.6.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the BCS is concerned, these are the wrong questions.
The truth is, the BCS did exactly what it was created to do -- keep
the bowls in control of college football's postseason and insure
their own survival.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of this monolith said a lot about creating a fair
system with some integrity, but neither was listed on its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS selected a team in Florida to play in the Orange Bowl
over teams with better records and higher ranks. It gave an
automatic bid to a conference with a brief history.
</P>
<P>
   It created the kind of hype that can swallow college-age young
men whole. UCLA and Kansas State should have been proud of their
one-loss regular seasons; instead, they found their bowl assignment
to be a bummer, and played accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   It weaved computers into the system, only to find that some of
them can be as cantankerous as Hal in ``2001.'' The one system
considered the most reliable, Jeff Sagarin's USA Today model, had
Kansas State atop its listing the day after it lost the Big XII
title game. The New York Times computer had Florida State on top
most weeks despite having one loss.
</P>
<P>
   What all this does is further push people to the extremes:
College football either needs to go to a full playoff or junk the
BCS and go back to the old system. All of the other suggestions are
flawed.
</P>
<P>
   A two-team post-bowl title game? It wouldn't work. How do you
choose two teams out of four major bowl winners? And how do you
keep bowl business brisk? If you make the Fiesta Bowl a semifinal
of sorts, then 50,000 Tennessee fans don't visit go to Tempe. As it
was, it was a soft ticket in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A four team post-bowl playoff? Better on one hand, more
troublesome on the other. The Big Four bowls ostensibly would be
quarterfinal games; they would only sign on if they were part of
the post-bowl playoff rotation and could ratchet down Jan. 1
attendance expectations. Plus, there's greater chance at leaving a
quality team out of the field because of automatic conference bids
(i.e., Syracuse over Kansas State, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   A 16-team field? It has the best chance of working. The only
team crying its fate would be the ranked 17th. It would let players
like Tulane into the game. It would not necessarily kill the other
bowls; they could exist and flourish for those schools
bowl-eligible but not playoff-bound, like the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   First-round games would be planted on the home field of the top
eight seeds, giving the playoffs some good momentum heading into
the Jan. 1 quarterfinals. Traditional bowl ties could be maintained
in the Big Four games. And the whole process would be creating
identity and name recognition for the Final Four teams, rather than
pasting a national title bumper on a game between two teams from
the south.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure many NFL fans didn't know Falcon's quarterback Chris
Chandler from ``Friends'' Chandler Bing. But they do now.
</P>
<P>
   Or we could just go back to the understated way things were,
when tradition meant something and teams and conferences earned
their rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Take us back to a simpler time, and you still would have had
Wisconsin-UCLA in the Rose Bowl -- only the Bruins wouldn't be
wallowing over a national title slight. Poll and rank never
mattered before, and it produced some great games, like UCLA over
Ohio State in 1976, and UCLA over Illinois in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Send the Big XII champ to Miami for the Orange Bowl and the SEC
champ to the Sugar. Make the Big East earn a major bowl tie-in on
merit instead of politics. Tell those conference playing title
games that they do so at their own risk. Let the ACC and Gator Bowl
become partners and challenge the Fiesta for prominence, just as
the Fiesta once challenged the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Let the debates rage into the night. Because frankly, they're a
whole lot more fun than Tennessee-Florida State on a Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 0133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 xxx  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless Barry Switzer undergoes a broader conversion than the old
Soviet Union, the bet here is that Gary Pinkel is the next football
coach at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having a Husky pedigree, he has been successful on his
own, a Division I head coach for eight years. He's smart, smooth,
diplomatic, conservative, articulate, likable, good-looking and a
youngish 46.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the anti-Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   A Bob Bender in cleats.
</P>
<P>
   And he's anointed by grid god Don James, Hedges' principal
adviser and Pinkel's former boss as player and coach.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with his selection is that it will be greeted
with a yawn so massive it threatens to sprain jaws throughout
Western Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Pinkel? Wasn't he the guy who slinked out of town in 1990
after Keith Gilbertson usurped him as offensive coordinator? Is he
the best Washington can do?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and yes.
</P>
<P>
   To those steeped in the Husky mythology that depicts the UW post
as a great job, consider how it looks to an outsider with little
knowledge of Montlake politics.
</P>
<P>
   For non-specific reasons, Hedges fired an alum and 30-year
coaching loyalist who had the misfortune of one bad season, and
that bad season was 6-6, not 0-11, in a program hampered by Pac-10
sanctions. He had a 44-25-1 record and was co-champion of the
nation's toughest conference as recently as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month earlier, he received an unqualified public
endorsement from the boss who subsequently reversed herself and
fired him without warning. Word was that boosters, still infatuated
with the James legacy, intimidated her into the firing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who expects a coach the caliber of Barry Alvarez or Gary
Barnett to step into this flaming bucket, where they also have no
constituency or familiarity, is not in tune with college football.
</P>
<P>
   The best coaches in big-time Division I programs are highly
unlikely to make a move to Washington that's lateral at best and
messy at worst.
</P>
<P>
   In blowing up Lambright, Hedges also damaged her credibility
with candidates by going back on her commitment. Her statement last
week that the reversal was because ``that was November and this is
December'' sends the message that either she doesn't know what she
is doing, or she ignored problems until they suddenly became
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by a prospective coach, she might whisper the
evidence she had on Lambright, but that coach has to wonder what
would be in store for him.
</P>
<P>
   Consider also that when Hedges explained the department was on
the hook for only a year's compensation to Lambright instead of all
four years of his rollover contract, she said, ``That way we can
tell recruits he's on a four-year contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Only if he doesn't get fired first. Hedges' dissembling is the
kind of thing that adds nothing to the cachet of the job.
</P>
<P>
   But to someone familiar with the byzantine ways of the UW, the
problems are manageable. Although Pinkel's 11 years as an assistant
ended before Hedges was hired in 1991, he's familiar with the
institutional perils and views the rewards as worth it. He comes
from a mid-major university in Toledo, where he has succeeded
steadily. Twice in the past four years he has been named coach of
the year in the Mid-American Conference, where he has a 57-31-3
record.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkel flew to Seattle last night and will be interviewed
Wednesday. He won't pester Hedges about Lambright's misdeeds. The
coaches worked together for a decade and Pinkel, as well as his
boss at Toledo, ex-UW administrator Pete Liske, remain thoroughly
plugged in to the purple grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkel will offer up the words of his mentor, James, and will
insist his deeds will be similar, particularly in areas of program
management and public profile, which are big deals to Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   The job of Wednesday's big-time college coach includes a
considerable amount of kissing up and toadying, and not just with
recruits. That's because the public jock factories are always in
need of grander facilities to help seduce the kids, and the jock
crowd no longer dares go to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the UW's $70 million plan to upgrade its multiple
ballyards includes a $36 million solicitation from the big-bucks
boosters, Hedges needs a football coach that not only will win but
will be a slickster to help with the begging.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright was not the type. Hedges has known it for most of his
tenure. For her first few years as AD, Hedges was in a weak
position to challenge the coach for two stupid but tangible reasons
_ she was neither a Husky nor a man.
</P>
<P>
   But through her previous coach hirings, her fund-raising skills
and the uptick in many non-revenue sports, Hedges gradually built
the credibility and guts to pull the trigger on the biggest Dawg.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lambright's own football fumbles eroded his support
sufficiently that the inevitable dismay over his dismissal was
muted and manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Her problem now is that in reaching the coveted point of hiring
her own coach, the carnage has reduced the field considerably. When
Washington gets snubbed by the Oregon State coach, it is plain the
job comes with many more thorns than the roses imagined by Husky
adherents.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
