 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 415 - January 6, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 415 -- Jan. 6, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. NICK NOLTE WALKS THE DARK LINE Nick Nolte has done his share
of brainless Hollywood blockbusters, but now he says he's doing
only films he loves. Recently that means two dark dramas that may
earn him Oscar nominations : Terrence Malick's ``The Thin Red
Line'' and Paul Schrader's ``Affliction.'' Nolte talks about the
new films, the experience of working with the reclusive Malick, why
he thinks he fell victim to drugs and alcohol when he first reached
Hollywood and why the key to mastering his role in ``Affliction''
was coming to terms with his own capacity for violence. By Ian
Spelling. 1,400 words + photo. 2. PLACIDO DOMINGO INTERVIEW Placido
Domingo is far more than just one of history's most celebrated
tenors. As a burgeoning conductor and the artistic director of two
major opera houses, he is poised to be one of classical music's
most vital, versatile leaders of the new millennium. The
57-year-old Domingo is singing, conducting and promoting opera
around the world with his usual youthful zeal. Interview by Bradley
Bamberger. (Q&AMP;A format.) BPI. 2,500 words + photo. 3. JANIS JOPLIN
- PIECE OF HER ART An indelible icon of the '60s, Janis Joplin
drank Southern Comfort on stage, had affairs with women and men and
cruised the streets of Los Angeles in a Porsche 365 Cabriolet
painted in a psychedelic design. But the free-spirited blues
empress, who died of a heroin overdose at age 27, also talked
hopefully of marriage, babies and a traditional home. Nearly three
decades later, her story continues to tantalize Hollywood. Two
movies about her life are coming up - one is authorized by the
Joplin estate; the other is not. The history of the Joplin projects
proves just how difficult - and how desirable - it is to make
movies about rock legends. By Pat H. Broeske. From The Hollywood
Reporter. 1,800 words + photo. 4. EMILY WATSON Emily Watson's new
film, ``Hilary and Jackie'' is the real-life story of world-famous
cellist Jacqueline du Pri, who suffered from multiple sclerosis and
who died in 1987. Watson talks about the new film, how her Oscar
nomination for her role in ``Breaking the Waves'' changed her life,
how she learned to play the cello and portray the crippling effects
of MS for her latest role, and why she feels that some of the most
bizarre characters offer the best insights into real humanity. By
Jeanne Wolf. 1,200 words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____________ 5. KEVIN SPACEY : AN ACTOR'S ACTOR ON ACTING Every
decade has its ``actor's actor,'' and in the '90s it's Kevin
Spacey, who won a 1995 Oscar for ``The Usual Suspects.'' He had
memorable roles in other films such as ``Seven,'' ``A Time To
Kill'' and ``The Negotiator.'' There's already Oscar buzz about his
latest film, ``Hurlyburly -- and a different kind of buzz about his
other current film, ``A Bug's Life'' (his voice is used for the
villainous grasshopper in this animated film.) Spacey talks about
his new films, his decade-long dedication to the filming of
``Hurlyburly,'' his role as Hopper in ``A Bug's Life,'' his
memories of his winning night at the Oscars and why, to him, it is
incompatible to be both an actor and a movie star. By Cindy
Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
SEAN PENN IS RESTLESS On a night drive to nowhere in particular,
Sean Penn escapes a Woody Allen set, philosophizes about what's
wrong with Hollywood, trashes the paparazzi - and confides that
he's just got to quit the movie business, again. By Lynn
Hirschberg. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (6,500
words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
MEN WHO MADE 'MONSTERS' In 1957, director James Whale (he had
directed classic horror films such as ``Frankenstein,'') was found
dead in his Los Angeles swimming pool. There were rumours that the
Englishman had been the victim of foul play. Whale was openly gay
in an intolerant era when few dared to be. Now comes the film
``Gods and Monsters,'' starring Sir Ian McKellan, a speculative
look at the final days of Whale's life. It is a vivid and moving
portrait, both of Whale and of a Hollywood that no longer exists.
By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
EVERYBODY'S FAVOURITE BORG Since Jeri Ryan made her first
appearance as the Borg-turned-human, ``Star Trek: Voyager'' has
received a welcome boost in critical commentary, ratings and fan
buzz. Ryan talks about the series, the struggle of her
cross-country marriage to investment banker Jack Ryan - they
recently split up - how she approaches her unique StarTrek
character (complete with marriage proposals, look-alike teddy bears
and dress-alike fans.) By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I am
