<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The politics of a girl's dream
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It is the closing moments of the final
Dole/Clinton debate before the November election. After a weak
start, the candidates are finally on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton: ``I think what really matters is what we can do to help
build strong families. Strong families mean a strong economy. To
me, that means we have to go on and balance this budget while we
protect Medicare and Medicaid and education and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole: ``Young people are looking to us for leadership. They're
watching what we do, what we say, what we promise, and what we
finally deliver. When I'm president of the United States, I will
keep my word. My word is my bond.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate is over; the candidates step forward to congratulate
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good job, Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well done, Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, a girl can dream, can't she? Maybe it's only because it
has been such a Terrible, Horrible, No Good, Very Bad year in
Washington, but, since Elizabeth Dole's resignation Monday from the
American Red Cross, I find myself fantasizing about having a woman
for president.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, it's a long way from Dole's sorta-maybe
candidacy and November of 2000, but it's still heartening to hear
people talk about a woman's potential candidacy with something
resembling respect. What a contrast with the election of '84, when
Geraldine Ferraro was widely regarded as a drag upon the ticket.
(Never mind that the real drag on the ticket turned out to be
Walter Mondale.)
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget the words of the late Cincinnati anchorman Al
Schottelkotte as he broadcast the returns. The Democrats' dismal
showing, he proclaimed, was because of having a woman on the
ticket, ``and it will be a long time before anybody attempts
something that foolish again.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing red, I called a station manager the next morning. His
response, in a nutshell: ``He's a curmudgeon. What can you
expect?''
</P>
<P>
   We can expect better. And what better time, after an outrageous,
disappointing year, than to think of government in new ways?
</P>
<P>
   Dole has as good a shot at 2000 as anybody, predicts University
of Dayton associate professor David Ahern. ``Being a woman in
public office is no longer a negative, as it once was,'' Ahern
said. ``In fact, some argue it's a positive because of the growing
perception that women bring a different style of politics to the
table _ a more consensual, less combative style.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I think the time is ripe for a female candidate, given
Washington, D.C., today and discussions about the 'politics of
personal destruction.'''
</P>
<P>
   I would never vote for a woman I didn't respect or didn't agree
with on the issues. But I would take great joy in voting for a
woman or a minority I believed in. Why does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   Because it's about darn time. Since George Washington became our
first president in 1789, the Republic has sailed along with only
one woman, and not a single person of color, on a major-party
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Because Congress may well be one of the most segregated work
places, by gender, in America. There are only 65 women in Congress;
there are 470 men.
</P>
<P>
   Because diversity is important in government for the same
reasons it's important everywhere else. Women and minorities bring
different perspectives, could appoint a greater variety of people
in positions of power. A woman might give issues such as child care
and breast cancer the attention they deserve. Or health care. Or
child welfare. Or domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   A woman might even think there are more important issues in
Washington than a politician's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, a girl can dream.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
