</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-WRIGHTPATTERSON07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientist tours top U.S. lab
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A top Russian space scientist who visited
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base this week might have been impressed
by U.S. technology, but not its ability to deal with snow: The
storm that nearly paralyzed America's midsection last weekend
looked like a typical winter day in Moscow, a base scientist said.
</P>
<P>
   Nikoli Anfimov, first deputy director of Russia's Central
Research Institute of Machine Building, toured laboratories at
Wright-Pat and held ``very in-depth technical discussions'' with
researchers from Sunday through Tuesday morning, said Tom Daniel,
executive director of the Air Force Research Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   AFRL has its headquarters at Wright-Pat, and five of its 10
research directorates are located on the base, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian institute provides science, technology analysis and
testing for the Russian Space Agency. Anfimov's visit was the first
to Wright-Pat by a top official from a top member of that
institute, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's space program has made news recently mainly for its
financial problems, which have raised concerns in the U.S. about
its ability to deliver its share of hardware for the International
Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel said Russia's problems shouldn't overshadow its
tremendous space expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This financial situation they've found themselves in this last
few years is an extremely difficult one, but it doesn't negate the
fact that there are tens of thousands of superior scientists and
research engineers that have expertise in areas that we're very
interested in,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   He described Anfimov's visit as an initial contact that could
lead to closer ties between Russian and Air Force scientists,
especially in the area of high speed flight and spaceplane-type
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A face-to-face meeting like this is quite often the start of a
collaborative activity that may go on for years,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Anfimov might have suggestions for snow control, too.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel said Anfimov arrived in Washington on Saturday and was
scheduled to fly to Dayton the same day, but the storm that hit the
eastern half of the U.S. delayed his arrival here until late Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks there's nothing wrong with this weather,'' Daniel
said with a laugh. ``He said in Moscow they handle the snow much
better than we handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anfimov is also scheduled to visit Air Force research sites at
Kirtland Air Force Base in New Mexico and Edwards Air Force Base in
California. He was not available for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
