<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-RESOLUTIONS07     01-06 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-RESOLUTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to get rid of your closet chestnuts
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Even the professional closet-cleaner has
trouble with her own.
</P>
<P>
   An Oscar de la Renta silk cocktail dress, black with large
bright flowers, never seems to make it off the hangar and into
Lenore Ber's consignment-store pile.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she wears it, says Ber, a West Palm Beach wardrobe
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just had a hard time because it's such a beautiful
print.''
</P>
<P>
   Such hopeful foot-dragging, she's found, can backfire _ closets
jammed with wrong-size dresses, pleated pants or blouses with
Knot's Landing shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this might come back in style,'' clients say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just found a matching pair of slacks ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just needs to be taken in/let out a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Resist, says Ber. With holiday shopping over, it's time to
create some serious closet space.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that easy. To illustrate, we had employees of West Palm
Beach's recreation department delve into their closets.
</P>
<P>
   Why them? Well, last month the women dredged up some
less-than-happening duds to dress as ``Tacky Tourists'' for the
city's holiday spirit parade.
</P>
<P>
   Director Laura Schuppert went to Goodwill for part of her
outfit, a $1 navy vest printed with tiny Scottie dogs.
</P>
<P>
   She's decided to keep it. ``You know what? The reverse side
could work with silk black pants, as long as the puppies didn't
show,'' says Schuppert, who hasn't cleaned out her closet in 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her co-workers clean as many as four times a year. Yet,
all could find something that's always hanging around _ along with
an excuse for why.
</P>
<P>
   Here are Ber's advice and the rec department women's closet
finds _ some worn, some not, but all still there.
</P>
<P>
   Heave-ho!
</P>
<P>
   Tips from Lenore Ber:
</P>
<P>
   EVERY TIME you buy something, try to get rid of an item in the
same category. Bought a dress? Dump a dress. CLEAN THE CLOSET with
every lifestyle change _ new job, new husband, etc. GET HELP from a
friend who can tell you the ugly truth. FOR EACH ITEM, ask
yourself: Do you wear it? Can you wear it? DIVIDE the iffy clothes
into piles marked ``alterations,'' ``consignment,'' ``cleaners''
and ``toss.'' USE dark bags for the clothes you want to get rid of,
so you don't see them, weaken and pull them back out. REMEMBER,
nothing ever comes back in style exactly as it was before. NO
sneak-cleaning attacks on others' closets. It's rude. DON'T BE a
sucker for sales. A $5 paisley, poofy-sleeve blouse is still a
paisley, poofy-sleeve blouse.
</P>
<P>
   THE `CHESTNUTS'ANN TAYLOR COMBINATION DRESS/PANTS
</P>
<P>
   From: Leah Rockwell, assistant director
</P>
<P>
   Make: ``Rayon or polyester. It's not real, whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   When and where bought: 1992 in Michigan. ``I searched high and
low for it.''
</P>
<P>
   How much: About $110
</P>
<P>
   Why: For work
</P>
<P>
   Last time worn: Six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Number of times worn: About three
</P>
<P>
   What happened: It was out of style. And it didn't flatter her
5-foot frame.
</P>
<P>
   Status: ``I figured if I got pregnant, I'd cut it off and make
shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   How often she cleans closet: ``When I move.''
</P>
<P>
   EMBROIDERED VEST
</P>
<P>
   From: Rene Connors, recreation coordinator
</P>
<P>
   Make: Leather with polyester lining
</P>
<P>
   When and where bought: A gift _ the tag's still on.
</P>
<P>
   Last time worn: Never
</P>
<P>
   What happened: ``It's gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Status: ``It was probably hiding in the back of the closet. Some
Halloween I might need it.''
</P>
<P>
   How often she cleans closet: Two or three times a year
</P>
<P>
   SUNDRESS AND MATCHING JACKET
</P>
<P>
   From: Laura Schuppert, director
</P>
<P>
   Make: Rayon and polyester mix
</P>
<P>
   When and where bought: 12 years ago in a St. Louis department
store
</P>
<P>
   How much: ``Probably one of those $19.99 specials. It's one of
those that comes in every color.''
</P>
<P>
   Why: To attend a wedding
</P>
<P>
   Last time worn: Probably 12 years ago
</P>
<P>
   Number of times worn: One season
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Went out of style
</P>
<P>
   Status: ``I just thought it would come back.''
</P>
<P>
   How often she cleans closet: ``When I move.''
</P>
<P>
   BEADED EPAULETS
</P>
<P>
   From: Karen Lemire, secretary to the director
</P>
<P>
   Make: Beads and sequins with adhesive strip
</P>
<P>
   When and where bought: 12 years ago from a TV-shopping program
</P>
<P>
   How much: About $10
</P>
<P>
   Why: ``I thought I'd put them on a black dress for the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Last time worn: Never
</P>
<P>
   What happened: Too gaudy
</P>
<P>
   Status: ``I'll probably keep them, but I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   How often she cleans closet: ``About twice a year _ and it all
goes back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
