<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exclusive club lets in the riffraff
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eanes school district trustees laid a large egg
when they picked the supposedly members-only Austin Country Club to
interview their three finalists for superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   If this place is exclusive, then I'm a Mongolian sheepherder.
Trust me. They'll let any jerk in at this club.
</P>
<P>
   I know, because on Tuesday I managed to worm my way in for lunch
at the Austin Country Club. And I'm not a member.
</P>
<P>
   Any country club that would let me in off the street unannounced
has to be squirrely, right?
</P>
<P>
   So Eanes trustees were lucky Tuesday when country club officials
decided not to allow the Eanes superintendent candidate interviews
to be held there for fear the general public might show up for the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the trustees might have found themselves accompanied
by riffraff such as myself.
</P>
<P>
   It was around 11:30 Tuesday morning when I walked into the
Austin Country Club, off Loop 360, like I owned the joint.
</P>
<P>
   The young lady hostess by the front of the elegant,
high-ceilinged restaurant, called The Mixed Grill, asked me if I
was a member. I told her I wasn't. She asked if I was meeting
somebody. No, I said, I just wanted to look the place over. She
took down my last name, but I'm pretty sure she didn't recognize
it. You could tell by the way the hostess and the waiter were
exchanging odd glances that they figured I might be some rich club
member's crazy uncle. So they didn't dare ask me to leave.
</P>
<P>
   After the hostess seated me at my table, a couple of women even
older than me walked in and sat at the next table over. One was
wearing a fur coat, and the other was carrying one.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about saying, ``Looks like it's been a good hunting
season; what's the bag limit on muskrat?'' But I didn't want to
push my luck.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of The Mixed Grill, a polite old gentleman named
Ferdinand von Hapsburg, approached my table, wringing his hands. He
said he recognized my name, but I wondered how could he be sure who
I really was. He didn't ask me for an I.D. He explained the club
didn't take cash because it wasn't set up for it. He asked if I
could provide him with the name of a member, for billing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I guess one?'' I asked him. I was thinking about giving
him the name of some famous rich guy who might be a member, like,
say, developer Jim Bob Moffett. What the heck? He could afford to
spring for lunch for a walk-in, right? But von Hapsburg wouldn't go
for it. I think what really gave me away was I forgot to ask for
the Grey Poupon.
</P>
<P>
   For non-member gate crashers such as myself, the prices at the
Austin Country Club are extremely reasonable. My ``ACC Burger'' _ a
six-ounce patty of certified Angus ground chuck _ was priced at
only $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a membership at the club would have set me back
$40,000 down and $250 a month. But being a surprise guest, I didn't
have to concern myself with that. So you downtown winos might want
to check this place out.
</P>
<P>
   I should say that the service was swift. After all, I'm sure
they wanted me the hell out of there. And it was a really good
burger _ cooked medium rare, just the way I'd ordered it. And while
I was eating, von Hapsburg returned and hovered around my table,
like he expected me to steal the silverware.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if the club had problems with non-members like me
showing up for lunch. He said in the 15 years he'd worked there, it
had happened ``maybe seven times.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this with the conviction of a man who could remember in
great detail all seven loons who had done this.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is part of life,'' von Hapsburg said with a sigh.
``Every once in a while you get a little diversion, and you take it
with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've been here, are you going to name this hamburger
after me?'' I asked von Hapsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already been named,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Von Hapsburg was a patient man, and handled all this with good
humor. If I'd been in charge out there, I would have thrown me out.
</P>
<P>
   Before I left, I put a $10 bill on the table. If that's not
enough, I'll be glad to go back and wash dishes later.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
