A0912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislators would do well to pay heed to venerable statesman
 &HT;    Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Please don't pass any more laws,'' wrote Bill
Hobby, Texas' former lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby is in a position to know what is best for Texas. He is one
of Texas' most respected public servants.
</P>
<P>
   He presided over the Texas Senate from 1973 to 1991 as
lieutenant governor, an elective position considered the most
powerful in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby, a scholar of Texas government, passed along a lot of
sound advice to legislators.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Dear legislator'' open letter that appeared in the
Dallas Morning News, Hobby congratulated Texas House and Senate
members on their recent election but warned them that the easy part
is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill that really counts is the general appropriations
bill,'' Hobby wrote. ``In that one bill you will decide how well
Texans will be educated, regulated, imprisoned and medicated for
the next two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobby gave the lawmakers advice designed to cut through wasteful
grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spend every nickel you can on education,'' he advised. ``Every
nickel you don't spend now will cost dollars in the future for
welfare and prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   But after lawmakers pass the budget bill and put every nickel
possible on education, then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then go home,'' Hobby wrote. ``Please don't pass any more
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can Texas legislators go home after passing the
education-heavy budget and ignore the issue every Texas politician
promises to tackle as soon as he or she gets to Austin?
</P>
<P>
   Texas pols love to fight crime. That's why Texas taxpayers own
one of the world's largest and most expensive prison systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby could see this one coming. He spelled it out for incoming
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to amend the penal code probably thinks he is
'getting tough on crime' by creating another one. If we could
eliminate, or even reduce, crime by passing laws, we wouldn't have
built prisons. New laws in the penal code create more crimes and
more criminals. We already have enough criminals. So just vote
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to avoid more laws, criminals and expensive prisons,
Hobby advised lawmakers: ``Don't try to tell people what it is you
don't want them to put into the minds or bodies. (See above.)
Ungrateful louts that they are, they won't appreciate your advice
or even pay attention. So just vote no.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobby also has seen his share of bills promoted as improvements
to existing laws. Knowing that legislators will see more of these
better-solution bills, Hobby warned:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever somebody wants to 'reform' something, hold on to your
purse or wallet tightly. What that person really wants to do is
transfer money or power from some other group to his own group.
Maybe that is all right. In fact, that is why legislatures meet
every year or so _ to change power and money relationships to fit
the political realities of the day. But when somebody tells you
that he wants to 'reform' something, he is saying, 'Trust me.' Just
don't think the world is going to be a better place after it is
'reformed' _ or be disappointed when it isn't. So just vote no.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobby also warned lawmakers to not be ``silly.'' For example, he
told of a law establishing the amount of water needed to flush a
toilet and evolution laws. He might have added the Texas law
designed to punish people who insult Texas cows or vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Hobby warned lawmakers to put Texas ahead of partisanship and to
cut back in several specific government functions.
</P>
<P>
   Spend every spare nickel on education, don't be silly, cut out
unneeded government operations and just say no.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. But it's a the sort of advice that could
make the 76th Legislature the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
