u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAKESPEARE-WISDOM07-     01-06 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-WISDOM07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advice from the Bard
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Someone had all the questions and all
the answers long before Dr. Ruth, Abby and Ann or Miss Manners. He
had all the insight long before Freud, Einstein and Andy Rooney. He
wrote Lady Di's life story 370 years before it unfolded. Bill's and
Monica's, too.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers on the Titanic? Old story, done best by this fellow.
Your children driving you nuts? Done. Feel like a fool in love? The
Bard's been there.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Twelfth night is the last day of the Christmas feasting season.
Shakespeare had something to say about feasting, too. He had
something to say about everything we hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   His simplest lines hold meaning. ``Out, damn spot'' means one
thing to the owner of a Dalmatian, something else again to Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   We took in the new movie, Shakespeare in Love, a wonderful _ if
artistically licensed _ look at the Bard's own love life. It's the
309th film based on Shakespeare's works.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare is quite white, quite dead and quite male, but a
world without his writing is a world without irony, poetry and
insight. He was voted Man of the Millennium by BBC listeners in
Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Our research ended with a perusal of our old volumes for more of
the Bard's hidden meanings, his answers to questions asked by
today's parents, lovers, teenagers and national leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, he's timely.
</P>
<P>
   The Bard on impeachment:
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's big hope _ All's Well That Ends Well
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr introspects _ ``Wherefore do I do this? So the
question stands.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, to this end: we are all diseased
</P>
<P>
   And with our surfeiting and wanton hours
</P>
<P>
   Have brought ourselves into a burning fever.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry IV, second part
</P>
<P>
   Public reaction _ ``The first thing we do, let's kill all the
lawyers.'' Henry VI
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyer answers his phone _ ``Once more into the
breach.'' Henry V
</P>
<P>
   The Bard's advice to all of Washington, D.C. _ ``He that is
proud eats up himself.'' Troilus and Cressida
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen of Shakespeare's main characters took the
Kevorkian route to the next world:
</P>
<P>
   ``The drugs are quick. Thus with a kiss I die.'' Romeo and
Juliet
</P>
<P>
   ``It is silliness to live when to live is torment.'' Othello
</P>
<P>
   On marriage and family the Bard was not an optimist:
</P>
<P>
   ``Many a good hanging prevents a bad marriage.'' Twelfth Night
</P>
<P>
   ``I say we will have no more marriage.'' Hamlet (now there was a
dysfunctional family)
</P>
<P>
   On aging:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, call back yesterday, bid time return.'' Richard II
</P>
<P>
   ``For you and I are past our dancing days.'' Romeo and Juliet
</P>
<P>
   On the importance of kids doing homework and cleaning their
rooms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will come of nothing.'' King Lear
</P>
<P>
   On Mark McGwire's 70th home run:
</P>
<P>
   ``A hit, a very palpable hit.'' Hamlet
</P>
<P>
   How to address bad dogs and bad boyfriends:
</P>
<P>
   ``Out, dog! out, cur! Thou drivest past the bounds of a maiden's
patience.'' A Midsummer Night's Dream
</P>
<P>
   ``O me! you juggler, you canker-blossom! you thief of love.'' A
Midsummer Night's Dream
</P>
<P>
   ``What a piece of work is a man.'' Hamlet
</P>
<P>
   On the NBA lockout:
</P>
<P>
   ``To be, or not to be.'' Hamlet
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the winter of our discontent.'' Richard III
</P>
<P>
   How to respond when your HMO denies a claim:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the silliest stuff I have ever heard.'' A Midsummer
Night's Dream
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tale told by an idiot, full of sound and fury,
signifying nothing.'' Macbeth
</P>
<P>
   Advice to mothers-in-law:
</P>
<P>
   ``An honest tale speeds best being plainly told.'' Richard III
</P>
<P>
   To Nancy Graham and mayoral wannabes:
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the city but the people.'' Coriolanus
</P>
<P>
   On dealing with salesmen, suitors and would-be seducers:
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil can cite Scripture for his purpose.'' The Merchant
of Venice
</P>
<P>
   Get thee to the gym:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more flesh than another man, and therefore more
frailty.'' Henry IV
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that this too too solid flesh would melt, Thaw and resolve
itself into a dew.'' Hamlet
</P>
<P>
   The Bard anticipates Viagra:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it not strange that desire should so many years outlive
performance.'' Henry IV
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bawdy planet.'' The Winter's Tale
</P>
<P>
   Remember this when your teenager breaks curfew:
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind is my love to-day, to-morrow kind.'' Sonnet 105
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wise father that knows his child.'' The Merchant of
Venice
</P>
<P>
   On love:
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not love that do not show their love.'' The Two
Gentlemen of Verona
</P>
<P>
   ``Love comforteth like sunshine after rain.'' Venus and Adonis
</P>
<P>
   On assessing last year:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's done is done.'' Macbeth
</P>
<P>
   And some sage advice for the New Year (and life for that
matter):
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasted time, and now doth time waste me.'' Richard II
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
