<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-COX     01-06 2453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In one take this week.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or E-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, Q&AMP;A printed information about an
orphanage, maybe in Nevada, that recycles and sells used Christmas
cards. Can you repeat that? I have had my office workers and Sunday
school class save their cards for me.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're remembering St. Jude's Ranch for Children, a Nevada
community focusing on the needs of abused, abandoned and neglected
children of all races and faiths. It operates the St. Jude's Born
Again Recycling Program, which started more than 30 years ago.
Children take the fronts of used greeting cards of all occasions
(not limited to Christmas), glue them to preprinted card backs, and
sell the ``new'' cards to the public. It's important that donors
help by sending card fronts only, with no writing on the reverse,
that can be trimmed to fit 5-by-7-inch card backs. Each child earns
15 cents for each card he or she makes. Send to: St. Jude's Ranch
for Children, 100 St. Jude's St., Boulder City, NV 89005-1618.
Those wishing to buy Born Again Cards can send $6.50 for a package
of 10 to the ranch at P.O. Box 60100, Boulder City, NV 89006-0100;
the same address is for any other correspondence. For credit-card
purchases, call 1-800-492-3562. Other information: 702-294-7124.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For my planning purposes, can you list the dates and cities
of the next several Super Bowls after this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Super Bowl XXXIV, Jan. 30, 2000, Georgia Dome, Atlanta; XXXV,
Jan. 28, 2001, Raymond James Stadium, Tampa, Fla.; XXXVI, Jan. 27,
2002, Louisiana Superdome, New Orleans; XXXVII, Jan. 26, 2003,
49ers' new stadium, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Paul Harvey always tells incredible human interest stories on
his radio shows. Has he compiled a book of them, or is a tape of
them available?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harvey has compiled several books, but most are no longer in
print, said a spokeswoman for Paul Harvey News in Chicago. However,
two of them still may be available in paperback, she said: ``For
What It's Worth'' and ``Destiny,'' both published by Bantam.
Bookstores can order them, she added. Audiotapes aren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please refresh my memory: On what basis did President Gerald
Ford pardon the woman known in World War II as Tokyo Rose?
</P>
<P>
   A: As one of his last acts in office, Ford pardoned Iva Toguri
D'Aquino in January 1977 in the wake of support for a pardon that
had been building since the year before. That sentiment grew out of
a widely held belief that D'Aquino was a victim of anti-Japanese
fervor after World War II. D'Aquino _ the only American-born
Japanese woman out of a dozen or more radio propagandists all
termed Tokyo Rose by American GIs _ had gone to Japan for a visit
in July 1941 and was stranded there against her wishes when the
United States and Japan went to war. She took a job with Radio
Tokyo doing 15-minute broadcasts. After the war ended, she was held
by the U.S. government and indicted on eight counts of treason.
Convicted in 1949 on one count and sentenced to 10 years in prison,
she was released in 1956 for good behavior. At last report, she was
living quietly in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Henry Hyde being permitted to participate in the
Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton when he voted in the
House for impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   A: The role that Rep. Henry Hyde (R.-Ill.) is performing in the
Senate impeachment trial is different from the one he performed in
the House. He was among a majority of representatives who voted to
present articles of impeachment to the Senate for trial. This is
along the lines of a grand jury voting to indict someone on charges
requiring a court trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate trial, Hyde will head a group of 12 other
representatives who will act as ``managers,'' or prosecutors, of
the case against Clinton. They will try to persuade the Senate to
vote to convict. There are 100 members of the Senate and it takes a
two-thirds vote, or 67, to convict. If that happens, Clinton will
be out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The smallest of the octuplets born in Texas _ the one who
died_ weighed 10.3 ounches when she was born. What is the smallest
baby every born to survive?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer depends somewhat on your definition of survival.
The Guinness Book of World Records 1998 says the smallest,
longest-living baby to survive is a 9.9-ounce premature girl named
Madeline. She was born on June 29, 1989, at Loyola University
Medical Center in Maywood, Ill, and is now 9 years old. Smaller
babies have been born alive but survived for only short periods of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent news article said that someone in Louisiana had
developed a board game similar to Monopoly that made fun of
Louisiana politics. How do I get the game?
</P>
<P>
   A: The game is called Politricks and was developed by Kippy
Sumrall, a Baton Rouge entrepreneur who says he hopes one day to
run for public office. It is available at various retail outlets in
Louisiana. It may be ordered, however, from Kippy Productions Inc.,
13953 Perkins Rd., Baton Rouge, LA 70810. Cost, including shipping,
is $34.95, with payment by credit card or check. Kippy Productions'
phone number is 1-225-751-9606.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do glassmakers get the different colors in glass?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to Britannica, little is known about the actual
cause of color in glass beyond the fact that certain materials
added to and melted with certain glass mixtures will produce
various colors. The coloring agents are generally metallic oxides.
The same oxide may produce different colors with different glass
mixtures, and different oxides of the same metal may produce
different colors. Examples given by Britannica include these:
Cobalt normally provides a purple-blue color; chromium, a chrome
green or yellow; manganese, a violet; uranium, a canary; lead, a
pale yellow; copper, a peacock blue or green.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the identifying numbers on the hotdogs that were
recalled recently?
</P>
<P>
   A: The recall is for hotdogs and other packaged meats labled
with EST. P-261 or 6911 for Ball Park, Bill Mar, Bryan Bunsize and
Bryan 3-lb. Club Pack hotdogs, Grillmaster, Hygrade, Mr. Turkey,
Sara Lee Deli Meat and Sara Lee Home Roast brands. Call the Food
Safety and Inspection Service at 1-800-535-4555 if further
information is desired.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been using a credit card for some time that offers a 1
percent rebate on purchases, but it is discontinuing the rebate. Do
you know of any good gold or platinum cards that offer a rebate
other than Discover?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several firms that follow credit card offers and
publish information about them. One of the best-known is Cardweb
Inc. of Gettysburg, Pa. You may call 1-800-344-7714 for brief
ordering information, or contact its Internet site at
http://www.cardweb.com for more extensive information. The site
lists more than 50 rebate _ or reward _ credit cards of various
types offered around the nation. Once you reach the site, click on
Cardtrak, then on Card Surveys. Detailed information is provided
about some of the rebate cards, but you have to call others for
details of their offer. The site also provides information on other
types of credit card offers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton is censored rather than impeached, what
does censure mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: In simple, political terms, a vote by the Senate to censure
Clinton means he remains in office. A Senate vote to convict means
he no longer is president. In legal terms, ``Black's Law
Dictionary,'' considered the standard authority, defines censure as
``the formal resolution of a legislative, administrative or other
body reprimanding a person, normally one of its own members, for
specified conduct.'' And reprimand is defined as ``to reprove
severely, especially with authority,'' the type of authority a
Senate vote for censure would carry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was the compact disc developed, and what was the first
music issued on a compact disc?
</P>
<P>
   A: The compact disc was introduced in the United States in 1983,
according to ``Famous First Facts.'' It was manufactured by the
Japanese company Sony using technology pioneered in 1979 by the
Dutch company Philips. Information, whether it's music or computer
files, is stored on a CD, a plastic disc, as a series of digital
pulses that is read electronically. The first music _ or ``album''
_ sold on a CD was ``52nd Street'' by Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I fairly often hear people use the expression ``gone south,''
apparently to describe someone abandoning a responsibility of some
sort. What's the meaning or orgin of the expression?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gone south is used to convey two different meanings. The
``New Dictionary of American Slang'' says it means to disappear
quickly ``as if vanishing,'' and probably comes from the ``notion
of disappearing south of the border, in particular the Mexican
border, to escape legal pursuit and responsibility,'' especially in
the days of the Old West when outlaws slipped back and forth across
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Heritage Dictionary of Idioms'' says gone south
means to deteriorate or decline, as in ``the stock market is headed
south again,'' and is thought to allude to compasses and
two-dimensional maps where north is up and south is down.'' Both
dictionaries say a third possible source of the term is the
widespread Native American belief that the soul after death
journeys to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read in the newspaper that the U.S. Census Bureau is hiring
thousands of people to help with the 2000 census. How do I apply
for one of the jobs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the Census Bureau toll-free at 1-888-325-7733 for
information on the jobs. The government needs to hire several
hundreds of thousands of workers to complete the census.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article referred to ``reformulated
gasoline'' and ``low-sulfur gasoline.'' What are the differences in
the two fuels?
</P>
<P>
   A: To explain all the differences between the two gasolines
would require a chemical engineering degree but, basically, both
are gasolines designed to lower auto exhaust emissions to improve
air quality. Low-sulfur gasoline emits reduced amounts of nitrogen
oxides, which in turn lower ozone levels. Low-sulfur gasoline is
expected to cost a few cents more a gallon than regular gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Reformulated gasoline is an even cleaner burning _ and
considerably more expensive: perhaps 20 cents or more a gallon _
gasoline that reduces various exhaust emissions, including benzine,
a mixture of hydrocarbons. It already is sold in California.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is the Social Security cost-of-living increase so small
this year? Is Social Security running out of money?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1.3 percent cost-of-living increase for 1999 is the
smallest since 1986, when it also was 1.3 percent _ but it has
nothing to do with the amount of money in the Social Security trust
funds. The Social Security increase for 1999 is based on inflation:
the increase in the Consumer Price Index from the third quarter of
1997 through the third quarter of 1998. Because of low inflation in
recent years, Social Security cost-of-living increases have been
low for the last decade. The biggest increases ever were in 1980
and 1981 when Social Security rose 14.3 percent and 11.2 percent,
because inflation was unusually high those two years.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security's trust funds, the money that underwrites Social
Security payments, are sufficient at the current time to make full
payment to retirees. There is concern, however, that the growth of
the nation's retired population will strain the ability of Social
Security to make full payments beginning early in the 2030s. To
prevent this, government and private officials are studying what to
do to ensure the long-term financial stablilty of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My favorite postage stamp ever is the Sylvester and Tweety
32-cent stamp, but with the change to 33-cent postage, I am afraid
it will be phased out. Who do I write to request that Slyvester and
Tweety be reissued as a 33-cent stamp?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not just your favorite; it seems to be everyone's.
Sylvester and Tweety's portrait was the top-selling stamp of 1998.
The Postal Service says nearly 38 million stamps featuring the
battling cat and canary were saved by collectors during the year,
beating their nearest rivals by several million.
</P>
<P>
   What U.S. postage stamps are issued is not decided by a single
agency, but the place to begin is the Citizens Stamp Advisory
Committee, 475 L'Enfant Plaza SW, Room 4474EB, Washington, DC
20260. If it helps your feelings, a 33-cent Daffy Duck stamp will
be issued in 1999. First-class postage rises from 32 cents to 33
cents on Jan. 10. The first 33-cent stamp to be issued will be the
Year of the Hare, one of a series of U.S. stamps celebrating the
Chinese astrological calendar. It goes on sale Jan. 5 in Los
Angeles, and in the rest of the nation the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the regulations regarding overtime pay to employees
who don't work at least 40 hours in a week, but may be required to
work 12 hours or more on a single day?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal law that governs overtime pay applies only to more
than 40 hours worked in a week, not to the number of hours worked
in an individual day, according to the U.S. Department of Labor. An
employee may be required to work 10 or 12 or more hours in a single
day without overtime pay so long as he or she doesn't work more
than 40 hours that week.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering posssible financial problems relating to Y2K,
would U.S. government securities be the safest investment haven for
a concerned retiree?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is disagreement about how much Y2K _ the potential
failure of computers to recognize ``00'' as the year 2000 rather
than 1900 _ will cause financial recordkeeping problems for the
government and private companies. In general, however, there is
little or no disagreement among investment professionals about the
safety of U.S. government securities. U.S. Treasury bills, notes
and bonds are ``the safest possible investment,'' said Grace
Weinstein, author of ``The Lifetime Book of Money Management.''
U.S. securities are direct obligations of the U.S. government and
are exempt from state and local income taxes. Their downside is
that their rate of return is generally lower than private
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Bessonette writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
