<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-COX     01-06 2453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In one take this week.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or E-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, Q&AMP;A printed information about an
orphanage, maybe in Nevada, that recycles and sells used Christmas
cards. Can you repeat that? I have had my office workers and Sunday
school class save their cards for me.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're remembering St. Jude's Ranch for Children, a Nevada
community focusing on the needs of abused, abandoned and neglected
children of all races and faiths. It operates the St. Jude's Born
Again Recycling Program, which started more than 30 years ago.
Children take the fronts of used greeting cards of all occasions
(not limited to Christmas), glue them to preprinted card backs, and
sell the ``new'' cards to the public. It's important that donors
help by sending card fronts only, with no writing on the reverse,
that can be trimmed to fit 5-by-7-inch card backs. Each child earns
15 cents for each card he or she makes. Send to: St. Jude's Ranch
for Children, 100 St. Jude's St., Boulder City, NV 89005-1618.
Those wishing to buy Born Again Cards can send $6.50 for a package
of 10 to the ranch at P.O. Box 60100, Boulder City, NV 89006-0100;
the same address is for any other correspondence. For credit-card
purchases, call 1-800-492-3562. Other information: 702-294-7124.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For my planning purposes, can you list the dates and cities
of the next several Super Bowls after this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Super Bowl XXXIV, Jan. 30, 2000, Georgia Dome, Atlanta; XXXV,
Jan. 28, 2001, Raymond James Stadium, Tampa, Fla.; XXXVI, Jan. 27,
2002, Louisiana Superdome, New Orleans; XXXVII, Jan. 26, 2003,
49ers' new stadium, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Paul Harvey always tells incredible human interest stories on
his radio shows. Has he compiled a book of them, or is a tape of
them available?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harvey has compiled several books, but most are no longer in
print, said a spokeswoman for Paul Harvey News in Chicago. However,
two of them still may be available in paperback, she said: ``For
What It's Worth'' and ``Destiny,'' both published by Bantam.
Bookstores can order them, she added. Audiotapes aren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please refresh my memory: On what basis did President Gerald
Ford pardon the woman known in World War II as Tokyo Rose?
</P>
<P>
   A: As one of his last acts in office, Ford pardoned Iva Toguri
D'Aquino in January 1977 in the wake of support for a pardon that
had been building since the year before. That sentiment grew out of
a widely held belief that D'Aquino was a victim of anti-Japanese
fervor after World War II. D'Aquino _ the only American-born
Japanese woman out of a dozen or more radio propagandists all
termed Tokyo Rose by American GIs _ had gone to Japan for a visit
in July 1941 and was stranded there against her wishes when the
United States and Japan went to war. She took a job with Radio
Tokyo doing 15-minute broadcasts. After the war ended, she was held
by the U.S. government and indicted on eight counts of treason.
Convicted in 1949 on one count and sentenced to 10 years in prison,
she was released in 1956 for good behavior. At last report, she was
living quietly in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Henry Hyde being permitted to participate in the
Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton when he voted in the
House for impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   A: The role that Rep. Henry Hyde (R.-Ill.) is performing in the
Senate impeachment trial is different from the one he performed in
the House. He was among a majority of representatives who voted to
present articles of impeachment to the Senate for trial. This is
along the lines of a grand jury voting to indict someone on charges
requiring a court trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate trial, Hyde will head a group of 12 other
representatives who will act as ``managers,'' or prosecutors, of
the case against Clinton. They will try to persuade the Senate to
vote to convict. There are 100 members of the Senate and it takes a
two-thirds vote, or 67, to convict. If that happens, Clinton will
be out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The smallest of the octuplets born in Texas _ the one who
died_ weighed 10.3 ounches when she was born. What is the smallest
baby every born to survive?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer depends somewhat on your definition of survival.
The Guinness Book of World Records 1998 says the smallest,
longest-living baby to survive is a 9.9-ounce premature girl named
Madeline. She was born on June 29, 1989, at Loyola University
Medical Center in Maywood, Ill, and is now 9 years old. Smaller
babies have been born alive but survived for only short periods of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent news article said that someone in Louisiana had
developed a board game similar to Monopoly that made fun of
Louisiana politics. How do I get the game?
</P>
<P>
   A: The game is called Politricks and was developed by Kippy
Sumrall, a Baton Rouge entrepreneur who says he hopes one day to
run for public office. It is available at various retail outlets in
Louisiana. It may be ordered, however, from Kippy Productions Inc.,
13953 Perkins Rd., Baton Rouge, LA 70810. Cost, including shipping,
is $34.95, with payment by credit card or check. Kippy Productions'
phone number is 1-225-751-9606.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do glassmakers get the different colors in glass?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to Britannica, little is known about the actual
cause of color in glass beyond the fact that certain materials
added to and melted with certain glass mixtures will produce
various colors. The coloring agents are generally metallic oxides.
The same oxide may produce different colors with different glass
mixtures, and different oxides of the same metal may produce
different colors. Examples given by Britannica include these:
Cobalt normally provides a purple-blue color; chromium, a chrome
green or yellow; manganese, a violet; uranium, a canary; lead, a
pale yellow; copper, a peacock blue or green.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the identifying numbers on the hotdogs that were
recalled recently?
</P>
<P>
   A: The recall is for hotdogs and other packaged meats labled
with EST. P-261 or 6911 for Ball Park, Bill Mar, Bryan Bunsize and
Bryan 3-lb. Club Pack hotdogs, Grillmaster, Hygrade, Mr. Turkey,
Sara Lee Deli Meat and Sara Lee Home Roast brands. Call the Food
Safety and Inspection Service at 1-800-535-4555 if further
information is desired.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been using a credit card for some time that offers a 1
percent rebate on purchases, but it is discontinuing the rebate. Do
you know of any good gold or platinum cards that offer a rebate
other than Discover?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several firms that follow credit card offers and
publish information about them. One of the best-known is Cardweb
Inc. of Gettysburg, Pa. You may call 1-800-344-7714 for brief
ordering information, or contact its Internet site at
http://www.cardweb.com for more extensive information. The site
lists more than 50 rebate _ or reward _ credit cards of various
types offered around the nation. Once you reach the site, click on
Cardtrak, then on Card Surveys. Detailed information is provided
about some of the rebate cards, but you have to call others for
details of their offer. The site also provides information on other
types of credit card offers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton is censored rather than impeached, what
does censure mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: In simple, political terms, a vote by the Senate to censure
Clinton means he remains in office. A Senate vote to convict means
