<P>
   BERTIE-HIGGINS _ TAMPA, Fla. _ Bertie Higgins almost had it all.
Just like Bogey and Bacall. Straddling a meteor and whooping all
the way, the singer rode his song, Key Largo, to the top of the
charts 16 years ago. When the meteor petered, it dropped him back
in Tarpon Springs, Fla., the Greek sponge-diver tourist town where
he grew up, about 75 miles northwest of Tampa. With no new hits and
no record deal, he found himself playing the same beach joints
where he started. And then it all got worse. (Lomartire, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-WISDOM _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Twelfth night is
the last day of the Christmas feasting season. Shakespeare had
something to say about feasting, too. He had something to say about
everything we hold dear. We took in the new movie, Shakespeare in
Love, a wonderful _ if artistically licensed _ look at the Bard's
own love life. Shakespeare is quite white, quite dead and quite
male, but a world without his writing is a world without irony,
poetry and insight. Our research ended with a perusal of our old
volumes for more of the Bard's hidden meanings, his answers to
questions asked by today's parents, lovers, teenagers and national
leaders. As usual, he's timely. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-RESOLUTIONS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Even the
professional closet-cleaner has trouble with her own. An Oscar de
la Renta silk cocktail dress, black with large bright flowers,
never seems to make it off the hangar and into Lenore Ber's
consignment-store pile. Not that she wears it, says Ber, a West
Palm Beach wardrobe consultant. ``I've just had a hard time because
it's such a beautiful print.'' We'll take a funny look at fashion
faux-pas. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
