   BOOK-NOTES _ Eight years ago, Decatur, Ga., author Nora DeLoach
was a former social worker suffering from empty nest syndrome. To
deal with her boredom, she bought a computer and began writing a
mystery novel about a mother and daughter who solve crimes. Critics
dubbed heroine Grace Covington ``an African-American Miss Marple,''
and DeLoach is now the author of a series of ``Mama'' mysteries.
DeLoach talks about her road to success and her new novel, ``Mama
Rocks the Cradle.'' Also, because of Epictetus' role in Tom Wolfe's
``A Man in Full,'' HarperCollins is pushing two new editions of the
Greek philosopher's works: ``A Manual for Living'' and ``The Art of
Living.'' (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m EST.
