<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON     01-06 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 When Word Changes Your Name  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  About two months ago, Microsoft Word suddenly
decided that my name, which is Jeanne, should be spelled Jeannie.
Every time I type my name, it changes the spelling. This is making
me nuts! My daughter suggests the easiest way to fix the problem
would be to go down to the DMV and change the spelling of my first
name! Do you agree, or is there something I can do?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Have you seen the lines at the DMV? You'd be there for
hours. Besides, you can fix the problem yourself pretty easily.
First, here's what probably happened. At some point, someone typed
Jeanne and Word thought it was misspelled, because it wasn't in the
program's dictionary. The spell checker offered Jeannie as an
alternative, and the typist mistakenly clicked on AutoCorrect. From
that point on, Word figured Jeanne ought to be Jeannie.
</P>
<P>
   AutoCorrect is actually a nifty feature. It lets you assign
words that you often misspell, along with the correct spellings.
Then it automatically fixes mistakes as you type.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, however, perhaps it should be called AutoScrewup.
In any case, here's what you do: Choose AutoCorrect from Word's
Tools menu. Scroll down the list until you come to your name. Then
delete the entry. That should do it.
</P>
<P>
   My Favorite Things
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me how to back up my Favorite Places and Address
Book in the new 4.0 version of America Online?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. Both the Address Book and Favorite Places are stored in
a file that bears the same name as your screen name. The file also
contains your Personal Filing cabinet, which includes any mail or
messages you've downloaded. You'll find the file in the folder
labeled Organize inside the main AOL folder on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   To back up the file, simply save it to another place on your
hard drive, or to a floppy or Zip disk. You can also save your
Favorite Places by clicking the Favorites icon on the toolbar,
right-clicking the Favorite Places folder and choosing Save Folder
As ...
</P>
<P>
   The Right Stuff
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are a small nonprofit which is about to move into a larger
space and will need about half a dozen new computers that can
network with one another. Everything we have is old and
incompatible. We mostly use WordPerfect and Word and we don't need
fancy programs. But we do need e-mail and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of equipment do we need, and can you suggest a
reliable, well-priced hardware system?
</P>
<P>
   A: With so few PCs involved, you don't really need a full-blown
local area network in which a ``server'' computer manages the
others. You can get by with what is called a ``peer-to-peer``
network, in which all the computers are linked to each other with
cables. They can share files, documents and messages, as well as
peripherals like printers.
</P>
<P>
   Another, increasingly popular way to go is to create a wireless
network. Several companies, such as WebGear of San Jose, make
wireless networking equipment that can have your PCs talking to
each other in a jiffy, for less than $200 per PC.
</P>
<P>
   With a simple peer-to-peer network, you can hook up all the PCs
to a single phone line and give everyone Internet access. The
drawback is that only one person at a time can be on the Web. If
more than one person must be online at the same time, you should
opt for a more traditional type of network configuration.
</P>
<P>
   That means each PC will need a network interface card (NIC).
You'll also need a small device called a hub to connect the
computers. And you'll need a high-speed leased line to provide the
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   As for which computer system you should get, virtually any new
PC can be part of a network. And all major PC manufacturers have
lines of computers optimized for small businesses such as yours.
Check out the possibilities from Dell, Gateway, Micron, Compaq and
IBM in a copy of Windows magazine or PC World.
</P>
<P>
   The Fate of Files
</P>
<P>
   Q: On my computer when I delete anything it goes into the
Recycle Bin, which I eventually empty. When the bin is emptied,
where do the files go? Are they still stored in the computer, or is
it totally gone from the system?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's gone. Dead. Finished. Extinct, Kaput. So be careful. The
Recycle Bin is your last chance to change your mind and restore a
file after you've deleted it from the regular file system. When you
empty the bin, everything in it is erased from the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to add an extra layer of protection, so that you can
recover erased files, you can install something like Norton
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there are experts who can recover files even after they're
erased from the hard drive. That's because a ``ghost'' of the file
remains on the disk. The only way to completely erase it is to
overwrite the entire disk with random information many times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A San Leandro reader contributes this week's suggestion: For
easier Web surfing, use a ``metasearch'' engine, which
simultaneously uses a number of top search engines and returns the
best results from all of them. Three such searching powerhouses are
www.metacrawler.com, www.infind.com and www.isleuth.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-30-98 2150EST &QL;
</P>
