<SLUG> BC-CPT-EDLIFE-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY: NOTES FROM CYBERCLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  Bruce Weber is national cultural correspondent for The New York
Times. 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adult education, the concept, has never much appealed to me.
Volunteer for more school? No thanks. I was quite pleased, more
than 20 years ago, when it was done with the first time. Every now
and then I still have that dream about being unprepared for a final
exam. (For some reason, the exam is always in French.) There's
something about entering a classroom that feels like a withdrawal
from the actual business of the world, participation in which I'd
earned by virtue of enduring two degrees' worth of pedagogy. I'm
not one of those people who get nostalgic about college: I like to
get paid for my work, not graded on it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, augmenting one's education isn't anything you can
really be against, and I decided to go back to class, via the
Internet, spurred by an interest in exploring cyberspace and an
instinct that self-improvement wouldn't feel so burdensome if it
were a little more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by many measures, going to school online is convenient.
You can go undressed. You can go in the middle of the night. You
can go in Kansas City. You can participate in discussions to
whatever extent you choose, sounding off overbearingly or keeping
smugly silent, without having to observe the ordinary etiquette of
classroom decorum. You can, in other words, construct your own
private experience.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this ends up having its burdensome side. For
convenience, you pay with responsibility and accountability. Online
school is a venue for self-starters, which may be one reason that,
though 10 people enrolled in the class I took, only half were ever
heard from after the first few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first problem any prospective student faces is simply
deciding what school to attend. The global reach of Internet
technology obviates geography and transportation as considerations
in making such a choice. From my home in Chicago I could get to
class at the University of California as easily as at the New
School for Social Research in New York, or to any of the hundreds
of places that now offer Internet classes. Any thorough perusal of
online catalogues is so time-consuming as to be daunting. I gave up
rather quickly, choosing the New School (www.dialnsa.edu) after
checking out only one or two others because it offered the class I
wanted _ a playwriting workshop _ and because it was familiar.
Until a year or so ago, I lived in New York, not far from the
campus. Call me homesick.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine other people who enrolled in the same class, all but
one were New Yorkers. The exception was Angela Davis, a federal
prosecutor in Los Angeles. Ms. Davis, whose contributions to the
class documents were as voluminous and thorough as legal briefs,
told me that she chose the New School because she was impressed by
the resume of the instructor, Robert Montgomery (particularly that
he had attended Yale Drama School and had had a play of his own
produced at the Joseph Papp Public Theater), and because she wanted
a drama class taught in New York, which is, after all, the center
of drama. ``I was delighted that I had the opportunity to take this
`New York' class from my home in Los Angeles,'' she wrote to me in
an e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is one of access. In one way, real school is
a passive experience. You show up in class, the curriculum gets
flung at you and maybe, if you're not asleep, it sticks.
Cyberschool is a bit more active; you find your classroom and
negotiate around it. There's a facility to be learned _ the deft
burrowing of a computer mouse, not necessarily a natural thing for
a middle-aged man who is habitually behind the techno-curve. It
took me about an hour to get comfortable with the mechanics of
going to school. (OK, not as onerous as settling into a dorm room.)
</P>
<P>
   How it works at the New School is this: after online
registration _ and payment via credit card (the nine-week class
costs $450 for a non-credit student) _ I was sent a set of
passwords that granted me access to the online campus, which is
essentially a set of Web sites. A handful of them are accessible to
all students, no matter what classes they are taking. One is an
orientation site, where tips for efficient campus travel are
dispensed. One is a student lounge, where students can mingle,
posting messages either for general consumption or for individual
correspondents. (The tone of the conversation was distinctly eager
and friendly _ ``Hi everybody! This is my first online class and
I'm really psyched!'' _ much like what I remember freshman
orientation to have been so many eons ago. Some things transfer to
cyberlife undisturbed.) For some reason, there is also a room set
aside specifically to discuss movies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is a separate site for each class for which a
student has registered, and inside that site is another set of
sites set up by the professor. In the playwriting class, Montgomery
had his own ``podium,'' as it were, from which he gave
``lectures,'' providing, about once a week, disquisitions on
elements of playwriting _ things like story, character, dialogue _
mostly tips for us students to keep in mind as we composed our own
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Each of us had our own site as well, in which we were to post
our work for the consumption of our classmates and in which
Montgomery and our classmates could post commentary. Since we all
had access to all sites, we were able to keep tabs on our mutual
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Once I got the hang of it, I found it remarkably efficient and
ingenious. There were some obvious drawbacks. Any classroom
certainly is meant to take advantage of social intercourse and the
dynamic that develops when people are in actual contact with one
another. Online this is lost, by definition, but in a playwriting
seminar what is also lost is the opportunity for the writers to
hear their work read out loud, which it is, of course, meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence thing, that's what's missing,'' Montgomery, who
also teaches playwriting in ``real space'' at the New School, told
me in a phone interview after the course was over, when I announced
my intention to write about the class. ``As a playwright you have
to know how to include it, the presence of an actor, in your
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the semblance of a writing seminar became quite
persuasive; the discourse involved healthy doses of both insightful
criticism and self-serving blather, just what aspiring writers
sound like when they gather in person. And because people are
forced to write out their reactions, the communication was
relatively lean. In writing, the speaking-to-hear-yourself-speak
impulse is curtailed. There's no blurting. People take care to say
what they mean, not just what has crossed their minds, so even when
someone had something silly to say, it was clearly expressed. (For
that alone, gratitude is in order.) Writing focuses thought; I've
rarely found that illustrated so acutely as I did during this
class.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a funny way, even without the familiar interaction in a
classroom, the human dynamic asserted itself. Personalities became
evident. People were supportive mostly, testy occasionally.
Alliances were formed. And a general allegiance to Montgomery was
forged, even though none of us ever laid eyes on him. (In four
years of teaching online, he told me over the phone, ``this is the
longest conversation with a student I've ever had.'')
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, 52, who has taught playwriting for 20 years, is the
author of several produced plays, including ``Subject to Fits,'' a
musical takeoff on Dostoyevsky's ``Idiot,'' which featured Ben
Kingsley when it was produced in London in 1972. He proved to be a
careful, diligent reader and critic, offering firm but gently
worded suggestions that were both conceptual and quite specific
(for instance, line cuts and phrasing changes). I have a terrible
time beginning things, but something Montgomery wrote early on _
that each scene is like a play in microcosm, with the characters
wrestling with conflict and moving to resolve it _ helped me decide
that my play should start with the two main characters already
angry at each other. Otherwise, I'd have had them dithering around,
trying to make each other mad, but only frustrating the audience as
they frustrated themselves.
</P>
<P>
   My classmates _ a diverse bunch and distinctly adult, with
several, like me, in their 40s _ included an
actress-turned-hospital administrator, two massage therapists, a
nurse and an executive with a finance company. They were all, at
least the ones who stuck around, serious about writing for the
stage. I had wanted to take playwriting because it is a skill I
admire, and because I write about the theater as a journalist. It
couldn't hurt to get a little closer to my subject. But it was
daunting to hear about the projects the others were working on,
most of which were more ambitious than my own, an ostensible comedy
about two old friends in a battle over a cheap Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis had already made considerable progress on a historical
drama set in 16th-century England. Another was adapting Dickens's
``Christmas Carol'' with gay characters in a contemporary Manhattan
setting. A third was writing about a man who, unhappy in love, was
getting nighttime visitations and advice from the ghosts of
historical figures like Lord Byron, who spoke to him in rhymed
couplets. The hospital administrator was working on a play about
Anna Mae Aquash, an American Indian activist whose 1976 murder in
South Dakota has never been solved.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some of the writers were more polished than others,
but overall the reading was absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   That was a blessing, as there was a lot of it. Those taking the
course for credit were required to produce 15 finished pages, and
even with half the class falling by the wayside, several people
proved to be prolific revisers. (I'm a prolific procrastinator
myself, and by the end, I'd only offered an opening scene of four
pages. The verdict was that they were promising. Yeah, yeah.)
</P>
<P>
   But more than the actual scripts, what also had to be read was
the ongoing discussion, and herein lies the main difference between
real school and online school. The latter may be more user-friendly
than the former, but inattention costs more. Though there are no
occasions to show up for, that doesn't mean there are no classes;
rather, what it means is that the course is one continuous,
semesterlong session. In real school, if you cut a class, it is
gone, over, unreclaimable. Online, however, you never miss
anything. Whatever commentary is offered by the teacher or by
classmates is recorded, and whenever you sign on and check in, it
is all there, a linear record of what has gone on in your absence.
Which means that if you don't check in for a week, a week's worth
of discussion is there to be perused. Once, when I didn't sign on
for 10 days, there were nearly 200 entries waiting for me when I
returned, well over 100 pages of reading before I could begin
crafting any of my own responses to my classmates' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing is that people think an online course is
going to be easier than a classroom course, but I've spent a lot
more time with this one than with the others I've taken at the New
School,'' said Joseph Carman, 42, one of the massage therapists,
who is finishing a degree at the New School, both online and in
class, that he left incomplete at Fordham University more than a
decade ago. ``It takes an awful lot of time, logging on, and then
deciding where to go first, and reading other people's work and
making a thoughtful response.''
</P>
<P>
   Carman, who said he signed into class about four times a week,
finished two long scenes during the semester and said he was going
to re-enroll so he could finish a draft of his play. His was the
one with the Byronic couplets. ``It would be interesting to get
everybody in a room without identifying ourselves,'' he said, ``to
see if we could pick out who's who.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking about re-enrolling myself. I'd only managed to sign
on for class about once a week, and I'd only managed to produce
those four pages. My classmates reacted to me accordingly. In the
end, my Web site had less activity than any of the others. The
salient point, I realized, is that whatever I got out of the class,
I earned. Which may be the ultimate definition of adult education.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-02-99 1827EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
