 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
In enough free time, a Web page can be built for free 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once upon a time, you were part of the high-tech elite
if you had an e-mail address and knew Yahoo! was more than an
especially disgusting soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, of course, you need a home on the Web. Having one is
pretty easy; some Internet accounts come with the provision for
free Web space. Even if that isn't the case with your account,
there are other sites that offer free Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``free'' is the operative word for today. I'll tell you
how to find your own free home in cyberspace, then we'll talk about
some free tools and techniques that can make your Web site into a
good home.
</P>
<P>
   For today, I'm going to assume you don't have a home page on the
Web and walk you through the steps for creating one in semi-logical
order. Pay attention, because it's going to be a brisk walk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free Web space: There are literally dozens of sites offering
Web space for free (in return, the service usually puts an ad of
some type on your page). To get a complete list, use your favorite
search engine and the terms ``free'' and ``Web.'' Or you can take
my advice and try one of these two sites:
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities at http://www.geocities.com or Angel Fire at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.angelfire.com/.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free software: Now that you have a place to stash it, you'll
need to create a home page. Don't let your favorite Web-head scare
you away with talk about HTML (the language used to create Web
pages) and Java (one of the programs used to add special features
to a page). We're going to do things the easy way with a program
(it won't cost you a dime) called AOLpress. Don't let the name fool
you, AOLpress will create a page that you can use on any service,
not just AOL. You can download it at http://www.aolpress.com/. It's
easy to use and amazingly sophisticated _ creating links to your
favorite sites, placing images and automating many tasks, including
adding color or unique typefaces. There are plenty of other free
page-creation programs out there, but this one is my personal
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free images: Don't tell your mom, but we'll do some stealing
as we go along. Many pages use public domain images and artwork,
and you're welcome to grab them right off the page. Just
right-click on the image you like, then select ``Save Image As...''
and you will be able to use the image on your own page. Also use
your search engine to find the hundreds of sites offering free clip
art. I'll list just one (but this one site has half a million free
images): Cool Graphics on the Web at
http://www.fishnet.net/(tilde)gini/cool. Once you've found the
images you like, use AOLpress to include the images on your page.
</P>
<P>
   _ (Almost) free photos: You'll probably want to use some
photographs on your page. But unless you have a scanner at home (I
recommend it, and good ones sell for less than $100 now), you'll
need another source for the electronic images. Shop around for a
photo finisher that offers free or nearly free electronic images.
Some photo labs include electronic images along with the prints at
very little additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other free stuff: We're nearly out of space, so we'll have to
move fast now. But check out these Web sites for other nifty free
stuff such as guest books and software that will keep track of the
folks who visit your page.
</P>
<P>
   Guestbooks:
http://titan.guestworld.tripod.lycos.com/registration.cfm;
Autoresponders (send out e-mail automatically):
</P>
<P>
   http://www.pagetools.com; and for a visitor-tracking program
try:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.superstats.com.
</P>
<P>
   There's one free item I can't furnish. That's the free time
you'll need to get all this done. But if you have the time, I have
the free stuff.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
