<HEADER>
A0965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGY REVIVES OLD DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technologies may be new, but the debate that promises to
dominate the patent industry this year dates from at least the days
of Thomas Edison and Alexander Graham Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The debate now centers around whether methods of doing business
over the Internet, known as electronic commerce, should be
patentable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred years ago, the Supreme Court struggled with the same
issues that we struggle with today _ how to make our laws
responsive to new technologies,'' said Rick Nydegger, a patent
attorney who represents Microsoft Corp. and other companies and
teaches intellectual property law at Brigham Young University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question that is being raised with e-commerce was raised
with the telegraph and telephone,'' Nydegger said. ``At the time,
no one had envisioned using electricity as a way to communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to decide in the coming weeks
whether to review a July ruling by the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the Federal Circuit that, according to some patent experts,
represents a potential windfall for those who were among the first
to file electronic commerce patent applications. Although no
statistics are available, many experts speculate that the case,
State Street Bank vs. Signature Financial, has set off a stampede
of new electronic commerce applications to the Patent Office.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling affirmed and broadened earlier court decisions as
well as Patent Office guidelines on software patents, including
electronic commerce patents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-1980s, when I used to lecture on software patents,
I would get laughed out of the room,'' said Robert Greene Sterne, a
patent attorney in Washington. ``I'd get booed. I'd be called a
capitalist pig by software entrepreneurs who thought it should be
owned by the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sterne notes, filings from companies like Microsoft, which
initially rejected the idea of software patents, are tumbling in.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Aharonian, a patent-search consultant, has long been
critical of the quality of the nation's software patents, and he is
no more sanguine about electronic commerce patents. ``The
e-commerce patents are about as valid as software patents in
general, which aren't very valid to begin with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aharonian contends that the Patent Office does not have the
proper resources to research what is known as ``prior art'' _
previous inventions that are similar to a new technology. For
example, he says, a score of software patents have been issued
recently covering solutions to the Year 2000 problem, but none of
them mention a paper on the subject produced by IBM in 1986. Such
oversights make a patent more vulnerable to legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely relevant,'' he said. ``But none of the issued
Y2K patents have cited it. That's just gross failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Todd Dickinson, acting commissioner of the Patent and
Trademark Office, says his agency is doing an admirable job and
adds that 20 new patent examiners have been hired recently for the
division responsible for reviewing most electronic commerce
patents.
</P>
<P>
   How successful have patent-wielding companies been in licensing
their electronic commerce technologies so far? It's hard to say:
Patent licenses are not publicly recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Sterne, who represents several dozen software companies, says
patents are important for small enterprises mostly because they
help attract investment capital and provide momentum for initial
stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patents are having a major impact on financing,'' he said.
``The investment banking community, the venture capital community
and the angel investing community are becoming very interested in
intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   But Aharonian remains skeptical about the value of electronic
commerce patents. ``Until they end up in court, nobody's going to
know whether they're valid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-03-99 1519EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT05-COX     01-06 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT05-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Finally, a site for ig-pay atin-Lay 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bell bottoms, disco and Donnie and Marie have made
comebacks. So did John Travolta and Richard Nixon. About the only
things from the 1970s that haven't returned are TV variety shows
and pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, variety shows will stay gone. The world doesn't
need another weekly hour of Tony Orlando and Dawn. But the Web
could do a lot for pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of sites offer text translators. You type in a line of
text or, in some cases, a Web address, and the application turns it
into pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, check http:/www.rinkworks.com/dialect/ or
</P>
<P>
   http://voyager.cns.ohiou.edu/(tilde)jrantane/menu/pig.html. One
site turns the word of God into pig Latin, from Enesis-gay to the
Book of Ob-Jay,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.well.com/user/earl/Ible-bay.html.
</P>
<P>
   The rules behind the language are simple enough: You take the
first consonant of most words, put an -ay behind it and stick it at
the end of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Simple, but time consuming for chunks of text. It would take
minutes to translate the opening words of Lou Gehrig's famous
farewell speech. A Web translator can do it in seconds. ``Odaytay,
Iyay onsidercay yselfmay ethay uckiestlay anmay onyay ethay acefay
ofyay ethay earthyay.''
</P>
<P>
   There are Web translators that change text from one language to
another, like Spanish to English, but those probably have some
practical application. What good is the Web if it also can't be
used for things with no definable purpose?
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance savings available on Internet
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can cost you money: Usually, you have to buy a
computer with a modem and access fees to reach it. But once there,
some things you find actually save you money.
</P>
<P>
   A few new studies by the Telecommunications Research &AMP; Action
Center show how.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC found that in some cases long-distance customers can cut
their monthly bill in half by signing up for service over the
Internet. Internet long-distance service requires you pay your bill
with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC publishes a study called Tele-Tips at its Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.trac.org. This month's study compares rates for
dial-around phone codes. The study found dial-around access offers
some competitive rates, but some have hidden fees that can hit
hard. The report warns that, shockingly, the advertising for the
dial-around codes can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC is a nonprofit, tax-exempt consumer group that works to
inform long-distance customers
</P>
<P>
   Test your knowledge of 'Sesame Street'
</P>
<P>
   If television is indeed wet nurse to a generation of children,
``Sesame Street'' is the good milk. The children's television
stalwart turns 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the anniversary, the ``Sesame Street'' Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ctw.org/sesame/trivia/0,1736,,00.html, has put
together a trivia game.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know which ``Sesame Street'' characters were inspired by
the movie ``It's a Wonderful Life'' and the year ``Sesame Street''
made its debut? Do you know how big Big Bird really is?
</P>
<P>
   If you knew Bert and Ernie owe their existence to Frank Capra,
the morning show debuted on public television in 1969 and that Big
Bird stands 8 feet, 2 inches tall, there might be no need to play.
</P>
<P>
   The game tallies answers for everyone who plays. If you thought
Fozzy Bear, instead of Bert and Ernie, owed his creation to ``It's
a Wonderful Life,'' you could see how many others were similarly
misinformed.
</P>
<P>
   Take a sneak peek at some famous recipes
</P>
<P>
   If the year between Girl Scout cookie deliveries seems like 10
years, a Web site of copycat recipes might lessen the distance.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.copykat.com is devoted to recipes for well-known
food, like Girl Scout Thin Mint cookies; macaroni and cheese from
Boston Market; and fried chicken from KFC.
</P>
<P>
   There are also recipes for lesser-known delicacies, such as the
Pea Salad from Knott's Berry Farm and the Oyster Bar Trash from
Willie G's.
</P>
<P>
   Most online job help is for nontechies
</P>
<P>
   CareerMosaic, an online job site, released a study showing most
jobs listed on online sites are nontechnical.
</P>
<P>
   The CareerMosaic Index found three of the top 10 most popular
online job searches were related to technical jobs, engineering,
computers and computer programming.
</P>
<P>
   The index found the most popular keywords used in searches were
``manager/management,'' ``engineer,'' and ``sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Online job hunting reflects seasonal trends as well. Teaching
positions ranked 22nd in July, but fell to 28th in August and 30th
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Other job categories among the top 25 were, ``finance,'' ``human
resources,'' ``nurse'' and ``package handler.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by CareerMosaic between July and
September. More than 14 million keyword searches were tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
