<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Jan. 6, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CELEBRATION (San Francisco) _ Predicting that next
New Year's Eve celebration in San Francisco will be big as people
ring in the millennium, city officials are calling for stepped-up
planning _ starting now _ to avoid a scene like last week's rioting
downtown. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-EDUCATION (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Teachers would judge the
performance of other teachers and influence who gets hired and who
gets fired at public schools under a many-layered education plan
California Gov. Gray Davis will unveil this week. By ROBERT
SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WILLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Despite the national debate about
death and dying sparked by Dr. Jack Kevorkian, few New Yorkers have
a living will or a health proxy, two kinds of documents that
outline the medical care someone wants, or doesn't want, at the end
of their life. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   SNOW-REMOVAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Think plowing snow isn't an art?
Think again. Before the first flake hits the pavement, thousands of
maintenance workers with the New York state Department of
Transportation meticulously spread salt and sand on 42,000 miles of
state roads. Once the snow hits, an army of 3,200 snowplow
operators crisscross the state, pushing, loading and dumping the
stuff out of harm's way. By THEOLA S. LABBE
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS-WARNING (San Antonio) _ Thousands of South Texans may
have been infected with hepatitis C after getting potentially
tainted blood from the South Texas Blood and Tissue Center, the
facility's medical director said. By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-PEARLS (San Francisco) _ Many workers deprive themselves
of success because they're too skeptical to set goals and lack the
confidence to move up, an author and CEO says. Her book is the
recently published ``Ten Pearls of Wisdom.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-RETENTION (San Francisco) _ I would bet the 80/20 theory
_ 20 percent of people have 80 percent of the wealth, 20 percent of
your time accounts for 80 percent of your productivity, 20 percent
of the politicians wipe out 80 percent of the ozone layer _ applies
to hiring as well. In other words, it would be harder to replace
the best 20 percent of your workers than the remaining 80 percent.
By DAVE MUPRHY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEPPANYAKI-CHEF (Albany, N.Y.) _ The hibachi before chef Johnny
Chen is not merely a cooking surface; it is Chen's searing
playground. There, he builds Mount Fuji from a funnel of onion
rings that billow flame and smoke; he flips shrimp tails in the
air, teasing, ``this one's for you, this one's for me,'' as one
tail lands directly under the nose of the patron, while the other
flies into his shirt pocket. By MICHAEL LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ Because your stereotypical
modern American athlete has only as much memory as he needs to get
through that day's workout, there is at least a 50-50 chance that
the Atlanta Falcons will think they are in deep clover this
weekend. That's because they beat the San Francisco 49ers the last
time the two teams played and they are planing at home. By RAY
RATTO.
</P>
