<SLUG> BC-CPT-EDLIFE-SOFTWARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE: TOONSVILLE TUTORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   Josh Barbanel specializes in computer-assisted reporting for The
New York Times. 
 By JOSH BARBANEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that I could walk past the study, see the children
huddled in front of the computer screen fighting over who would
hold the mouse and sigh with relief: At least they weren't watching
television.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, they might as well be. There is Arthur, from the
PBS program, looking guiltily at his mom, in a software version. Or
Steve, a grown man who wanders through a cartoon adventure with a
blue dog in ``Blue's Clues,'' on Nickelodeon. And there are many
other software programs like these.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the titles competing for shelf space in computer stores
seem to have sprung, fully grown, from the heads of the
merchandising staff members at television and film companies,
especially now that there is more competition in the software
market for very young children.
</P>
<P>
   Take some dazzling media characters, provide some animated
scenes, add some familiar, certifiably ``educational'' activities _
this seems to be the formula for success. The age of celebrity has
come to preschool.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is a price. Originality is sacrificed, and
familiarity is glorified. The quality of animation on CD-ROM's has
improved so much that entertainment value is the main event. And so
I walk by the study, wondering whether playing on the computer will
soon offer no more rewards than television's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   TV'S ARTHUR, A BIT AT SEA
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur's Computer Adventure,'' one of the many merchandising
tie-ins for Arthur, the aardvark with big ears and big glasses, is
a completely circular product. It is a CD-ROM based on a book,
popularized by a television series, about Arthur's struggles to
play a computer game, ``Deep Dark Sea,'' on his mom's computer. A
version of that game (and not a very impressive one at that) is
included.
</P>
<P>
   The book, by Marc Brown, is called ``Arthur's Computer
Disaster.'' Perhaps the marketing department thought ``computer
disaster'' would turn off novice computer users. ``Arthur's
Computer Adventure'' is in the form of a ``living book,'' with text
at the top of the screen and words highlighted as they are read by
a narrator and the character. (Wouldn't it be cozier to have mom
read it at bedtime rather than a narrator at a computer?)
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the text, Arthur and his family act out the story.
Arthur, driven by his search for sunken treasure, disobeys his mom
and seems to have broken her computer. Children can click on
various animated objects _ a helicopter that can be flown about the
page, ghosts that fly out of cabinets. Also among the five
activities are the somewhat basic ``Deep Dark Sea,'' in which
children maneuver a diver past sharks and sea creatures to find
treasure. In ``Frankenfish,'' young adventurers can click on fish
and learn a simple fact about each one, then mix and match parts of
the fish to make their own strange creatures.
</P>
<P>
   There is a word-recognition game and a counting game, both
simple, but parents will not find enough weighty educational
treasures to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur's Computer Adventure,'' $29.95, The Learning Company;
www.learningco.com. Windows 3.10, Windows 95 or Macintosh. Ages
3-7.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE ON HOW TO HAVE A PARTY
</P>
<P>
   The television program ``Blue's Clues'' might have been modeled
after an interactive CD-ROM. Steve, the human host, lives in an
animated-storybook environment. In each episode, Steve invites
young viewers to help him solve the day's puzzles, presented in
nonverbal clues through Blue, his puppy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the rough plot of all interactive CD-ROM's; ``Blue's
Birthday Adventure'' is no exception. In four separate episodes on
two CD-ROM's, Steve needs help planning Blue's birthday party. Blue
has left three blue paw prints around the house and yard. Children
click through the rooms, searching for the paw prints. Once found,
they can be put in notebooks, a handy place to ponder the paw
prints' meanings.
</P>
<P>
   What does Blue want to give her guests? What does Blue want to
eat at her party? What does Blue want to do at her party? What game
does Blue want to play? These are the questions that will try
children's minds.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, children make a birthday card, bake a cake and
pursue other inventive activities that integrate nicely into the
clue hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Videos of Steve against a cartoonlike background appear
throughout, just as they do on television. But there is one
significant difference. On television, each episode ends with a
solution. At home, children are in charge. Sometimes, it seems easy
to get lost: Children who miss a clue sit in silence as they try to
figure out where to go next. Steve, too, stands silent, rocking
slightly from side to side, and Blue wags her tail. Some children
may give up.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, neither Steve nor the game's creators offer enough
clues or energy to sufficiently interest young users in following
through and learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue's Birthday Adventure,'' $29.99, Humongous Entertainment;
www.humongous.com. Windows 95 or 98 or Macintosh Power PC. Ages
3-6.
</P>
<P>
   DR. SEUSS'S BUSY WORLD
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine the Cat in the Hat administering an IQ
test. But ``Dr. Seuss Kindergarten'' provides such an unusual blend
of whimsy and earnest skill-learning for studious 5-year-olds that
you can almost picture the cat pulling a Stanford Binet test out of
its hat.
</P>
<P>
   Like Arthur and Blue, the Dr. Seuss franchise is hot. ``Dr.
Seuss Kindergarten'' provides the familiar and fanciful characters,
bright music and songs and colorful Seussian scenery. A zoo is
being built in Seussville, and children must travel to far-off
locales on a colorful train in search of exotic animals to populate
it. At each stop, children are asked in rhyme to complete
skill-building exercises: There is matching, letter recognition,
addition and subtraction (Barbaloot math), phonics, measurement,
estimation, sorting _ all the essential skills children must master
to be promoted to first grade.
</P>
<P>
   The Seuss characters add charm and fun, but the drill-sergeant
nature of the material shows through. In one exercise designed to
teach basic addition, the Barbaloots and the Lorax are picking
Truffula fruits. Children are asked to drag the correct amount of
fruit into two wheelbarrows. The fruit is then combined in a third
wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   But pity the poor child who doesn't know his numbers. ``Put the
Truffula fruit in the barrow,'' the narrator says repeatedly as
each mistake is made. ``Put the Truffula fruit in the barrow. Put
the Truffula fruit in the barrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Each exercise has three levels of difficulty, and parents can
monitor their offsprings' progress. Children may find this mix of
fancy and challenge appealing for a while. But I wonder if this is
software they will return to again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Seuss Kindergarten,'' $19.95, The Learning Company;
www.learningco.com. Windows 3.1, Windows 95 or Macintosh. Ages 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE GIRL DRAMATISTS
</P>
<P>
   First came the dolls, then the books. Now comes the software.
The American Girls is a set of popular, if expensive, dolls that
portray girls from different periods of American history.
</P>
<P>
   But while the dolls just sit there, ``The American Girls
Premiere 2d Edition'' allows young devotees to do something with
them. It is essentially an animation program in which children add
recorded or synthesized voices, lighting, period scenery, props and
costumes. They can move characters _ ranging from Felicity, in
Colonial America, to Molly, from the World War II era _ around a
stage. Then they can play back the whole thing, or print out the
script.
</P>
<P>
   It is very high-concept, marrying a technology to a historical
concept with some success. But the animation process is complex. As
in the cartoons, a child has to create the action and overlay the
sound, then match up both elements as closely as possible. Be
prepared for some frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Girls Premiere 2d Edition,'' $34.95, The Learning
Company; www.learningco.com. Windows 3.1 or 95 or Macintosh;
microphone recommended. Ages 8-12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-02-99 1823EST &QL;
</P>
