<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CLASSICAL07-COX     01-06 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLASSICAL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Estonian composer evokes ancient visions of another world
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about ``old school'': Estonian composer Arvo Part seems to
summon the stately, ethereal choruses he so adores from the very
web of time itself. It's music that evokes ``the haunts of ancient
peace'' as a fellow seeker, Van Morrison, has put it. There's such
a powerful aura to his work _ which draws on sacred texts from the
Russian Orthodox Church and the sublime austerity of Minimalism _
that it can be positively trance-like, a shimmering window into
another world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kanon Pokajanen,'' Part's latest in a series of devotional
titles, is exactly that. Based on the Canon of Repentance by the
7th Century composer St. Andrew of Crete, this 93-minute piece
features the Estonian Philharmonic Chamber Choir in a 1997
performance at a Tallinn cathedral. At once a beseeching cry for
forgiveness and deliverance and a thoroughly haunting echo of a
distant age, it's music whose simplicity functions like a psychic
balm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kanon okajanen''
</P>
<P>
   Arvo Part ECM New Series 11 tracks/2 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Stirring sacred choral music is timeless,
transcendent
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar is a writer for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
