NYT-01-06-99 1155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MINIREVIEWS07-C     01-06 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MINIREVIEWS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CDs
 &HT;    By Richard Eldredge and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayflower''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bicknell.
</P>
<P>
   Self-released. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Four years in the making, this second solo project from Atlanta
singer-songwriter Richard Bicknell was well worth the wait.
``Mayflower'' finds Bicknell, the former frontman of the Lost
Angels, in a wildly adventurous mood. He chooses his material
wisely, combining his beautifully crafted roots-rock originals with
covers of songs by musical heroes: Robin and Linda Williams, David
Olney, Eric Taylor and others. The bonus? Olney and the others
popped by the studio to lend their talents to the project. Through
it all, Bicknell's mournful vocals anchor everything with their
rich, emotional rawness. Highlights include the reflective
``Barrymore Remembers'' and the gorgeous ``Secret Remains.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``400 Degreez''
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile. Cash Money Records.
</P>
<P>
   16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to urban radio you had to have heard Juvenile by
now, ha? Can't get the rapper's infectious single ``HA'' out of
your head, ha? Especially because every line in the single is like
this, ha? Now you're thinking his whole album might be really good,
too, ha? No, it's not. As smart and comical as ``HA'' is, the rest
of Juvenile's sophomore effort, ``400 Degreez,'' quickly withers
into your average rap album of boasts (``Flossin Season'') and
slightly more engaging keyboard-crafted beats. And while ``Back
That (Expletive) Up'' is _ ahem _ memorable, is making a catchy
song out of condescending remarks about women good use of
Juvenile's randomly spotted talent? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama Drama''
</P>
<P>
   Mia X. No Limit Records. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Though she's the only woman on rapper Master P's seemingly
endless No Limit Records roster, Mia X wields more power than that
might suggest. On this one album, the distinctively Southern Mia
sounds like a fun 20-year-old partying in a club on Saturday
(``Imma Shine''), a soul-minding sister who takes her two children
to church on Sunday mornings (``Whatcha Wanna Do''), and a loud
neighbor cursing her babies' father in the apartment next door
because she came back from service and found him still on the sofa,
drunk (``Bring It On''). Mia obviously don't take no mess. And
``Mama Drama'' is proof that she doesn't make any, either.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Eldredge and Sonia Murray are staff writers for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
