<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SIGHT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Superb cast, on-target directing help make this film `Out of
Sight'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Another winning adaptation of a book by Elmore Leonard, the
brain that cooked up ``Get Shorty.'' It also happens to be one of
the best movies of 1998, beautifully directed by Steven Soderbergh
(``sex, lies, &AMP; videotape''). George Clooney plays a courtly bank
robber and Jennifer Lopez is the federal marshal he kidnaps when
she catches him making a jailbreak. In outline, it sounds like a
screwball romantic comedy. It just happens to be propelled by
firepower, betrayal, bloodshed _ and the erotic gravitational pull
between the two leads. Then there's the killer supporting cast,
including Ving Rhames and Steve Zahn as Clooney's accomplices,
Albert Brooks as a white-collar criminal who becomes their target
for burglary, and an uncredited Michael Keaton, playing an FBI
agent. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Also starring George Clooney: ``One Fine Day,'' ``Batman &AMP;
Robin.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
