</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-STELLA07-COX     01-06 0210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-STELLA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of movies recently released on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' (R) _ The screen version of
Terry McMillan's novel tries to distract us from its lack of plot
with visual opulence. Angela Bassett plays a 40-something
investment banker who takes a trip to Jamaica with her best pal
(Whoopi Goldberg), where she falls for a 20-year-old local (Taye
Diggs). Luckily, Bassett roots the picture with a glowing
performance, sharing with us Stella's unexpected moments of
emotional rediscovery. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Disturbing Behavior'' (R) _ Disturbingly lame. This
teens-in-peril flick is a high-concept pitch with zero
follow-through _ it's ``The Stepford Teens'' with a touch of
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers.'' James Marsden plays a newcomer
to a small-town high school who encounters a band of frighteningly
clean-cut students. With the help of the school psychiatrist (Bruce
Greenwood), these fascist Archies ``recruit'' a new classmate into
their group every few days. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
