<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BLOQUE07-COX     01-06 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BLOQUE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polycultural fever from Colombia
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Promiscuity is a virtue in Bloque's polycultural rock songs. The
eight-member Colombian rock band, introduced to U.S. audiences with
this debut on David Byrne's Luaka Bop label, is all about a
hothouse flowering of rhythms and idioms tangled up in a sweltering
urgency. It's a fusion that's constantly verging on meltdown as
cumbia and rumba collide with glassy shards of jazz guitar
feedback, roiling organ grooves or the staccato riffing and
heart-of-midnight pulse of reggae.
</P>
<P>
   Like tropicalismo, the 1960s Brazilian movement that combined
Beatles-inspired pop attitude with sexy polyrhythms and subversive
social commentary, the hybrid sound of Bloque has it both ways: The
music is rude and infectious, a party gone way out of bounds; the
Spanish-language lyrics, at once bemused and fatalistic, form
postmodern blues songs. They're vocalized by frontman Ivan
Benavides as a kind of manic-depressive Dadaist, a guy whose life
is crumbling yet who accepts the chaos as somehow life-affirming.
(It's something Bloque has in common with the films of Pedro
Almodovar and classic New Orleans rhythm-and-blues music.)
</P>
<P>
   Benavides, an imposing character with a bald pate and a
comedian's rubbery face, calls the band's sound psychotropical. And
he's right.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fevered, hallucinatory energy _ a sense of perilous
engagement _ that's been shamefully absent from American-made rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bloque''
</P>
<P>
   Bloque. Luaka Bop/Warner Bros. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A great album in any language.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
