<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CELEBRATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO PREPARES FOR THE MILLENNIUM CELEBRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Predicting that next New Year's Eve celebration
in San Francisco will be big as people ring in the millennium, city
officials are calling for stepped-up planning _ starting now _ to
avoid a scene like last week's rioting downtown.
</P>
<P>
   City supervisor Michael Yaki has requested that Mayor Willie
Brown convene a New Year's Eve task force that would be charged
with developing a well-orchestrated, city-sponsored celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to repeat what happened this year,'' Yaki said.
``We want something more structured, more safe and more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco police thought they had a good plan in place this
year, when 650 officers virtually closed off parts of downtown and
corralled celebrants into cordoned off ``designated standing
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   But apparently unwilling to play by the rules, a group of
several hundred rowdy revellers broke away and began vandalizing
cars, trashing newspaper racks, setting fires, smashing shop
windows and taunting cops. Police made 35 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scary situation in such a closed area,'' said Police
Chief Fred Lau, describing the chaos. ``We had to escort
firefighters into the area, as they were being assaulted.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the third year in a row that New Year's Eve celebrations
on the streets of San Francisco have gotten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   While police officials this week begin to dissect what went
wrong with their crowd-control plan and map out a new scheme for
next year, The city's politicos also want action. Yaki and others
on the board said it is imperative for San Francisco officials to
start planning for next New Year's Eve, which is expected to draw
huge crowds to the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
