<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS MOVES TO IMPROVE CALIFORNIA'S EDUCATION SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Teachers would judge the performance of
other teachers and influence who is hired and who is fired at
public schools under a many-layered education plan California Gov.
Gray Davis will unveil this week.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial peer review system, which is used in only a
few cities around the country, is part of a $444 million package of
education proposals the new Democratic governor has included in his
1999-2000 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also wants a new system to deal with the worst-performing
schools. Two hundred schools, randomly picked from the bottom 50
percent, would be given extra money and two years to improve.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't improve, Davis aides say, they would face serious
consequences, a vague threat that could include a takeover by the
state Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, students would be required to take a test to
graduate from high school _ a Davis campaign promise that the
influential California Teachers Association has questioned because
there appeared to be no safety net to help students who fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens if they fail and have to be kept behind?'' said
Mike Myslinski, a spokesman for the 280,000-member CTA. ``Is the
financing going to be there for schools that already are strapped
financially in California to handle these students?''
</P>
<P>
   California recently introduced a statewide assessment test,
called STAR, that measures performance for several grades but not
the senior year of high school. Many school districts require a
test to graduate, but Davis wants to raise the minimum standard for
those tests and take it statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Randlett, political director for Technology Network, a Palo
Alto-based business group that advocates for education reform, said
the test would give parents of high school students a way of
knowing whether their kids' schools are failing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are going to hold schools accountable,'' Randlett
said. ``What you have to do is show them: Your kid didn't pass the
test and only 30 percent of your kid's class did pass the test.
That says something.''
</P>
<P>
   The test would not be given until 2003, when next fall's high
school freshmen become seniors. Davis administration officials said
schools would likely have to find money in their own budgets to pay
to educate seniors who fail the test.
</P>
<P>
   Davis made education his major campaign theme, and his ideas
helped him capture the governorship with one of the largest margins
of victory in state history. Now his staff is releasing, with
limited details, some of the plans Davis will announce during his
State of the State address Wednesday evening and in the state
budget Friday.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Schools Superintendent Bill Rojas, who met with
Davis' education aides Tuesday, said he was encouraged by the tone
of the new administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have much more confidence in their ability to look at
(education reforms) holistically,'' Rojas said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Davis administration aides said the governor's plans were
designed to encourage the best schools and the best teachers and
punish the worst performers in California's massive, 1,000-district
public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals that have been previewed are modest but
important to teachers, like eliminating the $60 fee for a teaching
credential.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also wants to spend an undisclosed amount to buy
literature, not just textbooks, for school libraries. Specific
proposals like that pleased teachers and principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot of thinking about how to update our titles,
but our funding is very limited; it's about $3 per child,'' said
Rose Barragan, principal of Argonne Alternative Elementary School
in San Francisco. She said teachers need new literature books in
the classroom as well. ``What you want a child to do is always go
to a book. When there is nothing else to do, take out a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' plan for teacher peer review is a $100 million hybrid of
an already-existing teacher mentoring program. The peer review
system is slowly gaining acceptance across the country. Last year,
the 9,000-delegate National Education Association assembly voted to
embrace the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Under peer review, beginning teachers and any tenured teacher in
need of help are assigned a teacher mentor, who provides assistance
and support.
</P>
<P>
   The mentor evaluates the teacher's progress and competence,
reports back to a governing board and may ultimately suggest a
teacher be fired.
</P>
<P>
   The CTA, the powerful teacher's union, supports peer review but
believes it should be enacted by local districts in conjunction
with local unions.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are increasingly clamoring for change in public schools.
California is projected to add more than 500,000 students over the
next eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The state has about 5.6 million kindergarten through 12th-grade
students and 250,000 teachers _ 30,000 of them newly hired and
working with emergency credentials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
