<SLUG> BC-LIVING-WILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS SAY PEOPLE NEED TO CONSIDER LIVING WILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Despite the national debate about death and dying
sparked by Dr. Jack Kevorkian, too few New Yorkers are having those
kind of discussions with their physicians and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey of 58 hospitals, only one in three
people admitted for either congestive heart failure or elective
surgery had a living will or a health proxy, two kinds of documents
that outline the medical care someone wants, or doesn't want, at
the end of their life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Congress recognized the need for more people to
undertake end-of-life planning and passed a law requiring
hospitals, nursing homes, HMOs, home health and hospice agencies to
provide information about advanced directives to their patients and
maintain those documents on file.
</P>
<P>
   But a study of 56 New York hospitals found that only 64 percent
of elective surgery patients and 63 percent of congestive heart
failure patients received any information about advanced directives
before or during admission. Of the 43 patients who died in this
study, 37 percent did not have an advanced directive documented in
their chart.
</P>
<P>
   The study is part of a statewide effort to increase awareness
about advanced directives and to encourage more providers to bring
up the topic with their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be more routine,'' said Dr. Charles Stimler,
clinical coordinator for IPRO, the state's largest independent
health care quality review agency. ``There's still a lot of room
for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced directives, including living wills and health care
proxies, are written instructions that kick in when individuals
can't communicate their own wishes because of coma, chronic
illness, traumatic injury or brain death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of people who struggle with ethical issues,''
said Jayne Prendergast, a critical care nurse at St. Peter's
Hospital near Albany. ``It's very difficult for families if things
weren't discussed beforehand and it's difficult for physicians and
nurses.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the New Jersey Supreme Court in 1976 allowed doctors to
remove Karen Ann Quinlan from a respirator after being in a coma
for years, all 50 states have recognized some form of advanced
directives to allow patients to withhold certain treatments.
</P>
<P>
   However, advocates believe that only 10 to 20 percent of
Americans have done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously hard to talk about critical illness, death and
dying,'' said Dr. Christine K. Cassel, a medical ethicist at Mount
Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians, in particular, need to start talking more about
end-of-life issues, before a patient becomes ill, she said. IPRO
researchers also believe that hospitals need to be more aggressive
in providing patients with information about advanced directives
prior to their admission or after their discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Villari, a retired bookkeeper in Niskayuna, is
determined not to leave her end-of-life care to chance. In 1990,
the 73-year-old filled out a health care proxy, assigning her
husband or her two daughters to act on her behalf. She's told them,
as well as specified in writing, that she does not want to be kept
alive by life support if she has no chance of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to be in that position,'' said Villari. ``I
want my wishes written down so my relatives know my beliefs.'' She
also doesn't want her family to struggle alone with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone not filling one out is being very selfish to their
family,'' she said. ``It's a kind thing to do. It makes it so much
easier on the family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
