<SLUG> BC-SNOW-REMOVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW PLOW OPERATORS GO BACT TO SCHOOL AT `SNOW UNIVERSITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By THEOLA S. LABBE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Think plowing snow isn't an art? Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first flake hits the pavement, thousands of
maintenance workers with the state Department of Transportation
meticulously spread salt and sand on 42,000 miles of state roads.
Once the snow hits, an army of 3,200 snowplow operators crisscross
the state, pushing, loading and dumping the stuff out of harm's
way.
</P>
<P>
   No two storms are alike, however, and super-slick conditions,
plus changing technology in snow equipment makes frequent and
timely training a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for more ways to improve performance, more than two
dozen supervisors reported to ``Snow University'' this week, a
three-day crash course where attendees are taught how to
troubleshoot equipment, review equipment operations and learn the
finer points of proper salt-spreading techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Part pep rally and part technical review, the sessions at the
state office campus of the DOT were started five years ago by
Terrence Vennard, a DOT safety training specialist, as an offshoot
of an annual training session held for snowplow operators around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   State training officials felt that supervisors, responsible for
carrying out a snow plan and managing a crew of workers, could
benefit from the voluntary training. ``We wanted something to touch
the supervisors so they could take the technical knowledge back to
the operators,'' said Vennard.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors spend half the time in the classroom and the other
half in a garage, testing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got prisoners, vacationers and adventurers,'' Vennard
told the class. ``The goal is to get you walking out here wanting
to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   A slide show of basic truck maintenance kicked off the morning
session. Equipment instructor Diane Quillinan solicited feedback as
she showed slides of well-maintained, and rusty snow trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people lube all the chains?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   A few hands shot up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't lube them all the way, then run them, because the
chains get rusted up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some nodded and scribbled notes, others stared at the projector
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The next slide, a rearview of a truck, showed rusty, bent flaps,
or ``skirts,'' which help control the spread of the salt on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does that look?'' said Quillinan, who drove a snow truck
for 14 years and travels the state to teach proper equipment
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad,'' some in the crowd replied.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Roe, a Green County operator and part-time supervisor,
nodded throughout the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning something,'' he said, glancing down at his notes.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lamana, who supervises a 17-person crew in Albany County,
and has worked for the DOT for 17 years, was attending Snow
University for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a refresher course for me. Anytime you can learn
something, it's good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga County engineer Charles Vieny shared his personal
experiences to inspire the supervisors to strive for excellence,
and focus on serving the customer: the driving public and each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fighting a war out there; a war against snow, ice and
people,'' said Vieny. ``Be committed _ personally to each other,
and to excellence.'' The school has helped to cut down on the
number of broken vehicles and reduced accidents and salt usage,
said Vennard, who has taught at each of the seven Snow Universities
held around the state since last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get people who really want to come to work now,'' Vennard
said. ``I get verbal feedback. I know it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   After a final exam, students will receive a degree of Associate
of Snow and Ice Control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
