</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EURO'S SPLASHY DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of things you wouldn't give two cents for. But
hard-eyed currency traders on Monday voted with their computer
mouses, and bid up the brand new euro by two cents before it
settled back a penny to $1.18 against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The 6 percent gains rung up Monday on the stock markets of
Germany, France, and Italy ratified the currency traders'
instincts. It was a ``go'' for the euro in Euroland. And the mighty
buck now has a strapping young challenger prowling the planet's
currency markets. While Congress remains besotted by the bizarre
and self-destructive impeachment process, the rest of the world
reels into the last year of the 20th century. The right-wing
Republicans fiddle furiously while they try to burn Emperor Bill's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A shooting conflict with perennial troublemaker Saddam Hussein
didn't stop the House Republicans from impeaching Clinton. So the
successful launch of the biggest threat to the US dollar this
century may not be enough to yank the Senate Republicans back to
the reality of global economic strife.
</P>
<P>
   The euro already has all the muscle it needs to horn in on
America's currency as the world's most-coveted medium of exchange.
There are 290 million Europeans living in the 11 countries
(Germany, France, and Italy being the largest three) that left the
British dithering in the dust and plowed ahead on New Year's Day
with the most far-reaching currency innovation of this long and
bloody century.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's place as the currency of choice for people who want
to save and invest is now at stake. A decade ago we thought it
would be the Japanese yen that might displace the greenback as the
world's premier reserve currency, the place to have your pile when
famine, flood, war, recession or the asteroid hits. But Japan's
creaky, jerry-built governmental system, imposed on that devastated
island nation after World War II, never took proper root.
</P>
<P>
   The economists and the business types rail about Japan's
bloated, top-heavy, artificially propped-up commercial banks and
financial houses. And it is true that the big Japanese banks are
probably all bankrupt, in that they went along with the
government's shortsighted dictates. Japan's banks are where the US
savings and loans were a decade ago _ overextended,
undercapitalized, and led down a blind alley by a government system
that feasted on corrupt campaign contributions and backhanded
off-the-books favors.
</P>
<P>
   The true cause of Japan's impotence in the current economic
crisis, which sees deflation eroding the innards of the world's
second-largest national economy, is the paralysis of the Japanese
political system.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hard lesson here for Americans. And it is rammed home
by the remarkable _ but not unexpected _ successful launch of the
euro. In this interdependent world economy, where capital flows at
the flick of a computer mouse, there is no sympathy for a nation
whose political system begs for a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a heavyweight free-for-all. Does the fighter with
the tide running in his direction suddenly stop punching because
the other guy is weakened? Of course not. That's when you move in
for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   That's why George Soros broke the Bank of England, when
Britain's foolhardy gamble on maintaining the pound against
inexorable market pressures gave currency speculators a fantastic
payoff. And that is why Japan's feckless politicians are unable to
make any substantial reversal of the deflation that is threatening
Japan's economic security.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such thing as a ``timeout'' in the rough game of
economic supremacy. Which is why these fools in Congress risk much
more than their own seats, or the Republican Party's prospects in
the next election. They are playing with your 401 (k) money, your
pension, your Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   While they fiddle with Monica's underwear and Bill's cigar, the
euro is creeping up on the dollar. Two years from now, it is not
impossible to see the euro sucking money out of the US. The dollar
is not gold, it is paper. It is only as good as foreigners think it
is. And they now have a spanking new currency, backed by the
economies of a Europe united as never before, with an incredible
array of bargains and efficiencies built-in.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy chocolates, perfume, airline tickets, and automobile
factories now denominated in euros, so you don't have to fuss with
conversion rates in marks, francs. lira, pesetas, etc. As of
Monday, you can buy European stocks and bonds and commercial paper
in one clean, simple, cheaper deal.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the euro made Europe more competitive, eliminated
currency calculations and commissions, and opened up a market
bigger than ours to the latest computer-aided techniques in
investments and speculation. The rest of the world thinks we are
loony to go after Clinton in this way, at this juncture. Our
Congress behaves like the Bank of England, just before Soros hit
the pound below the water line.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott, the Mississippi mis-manager of our Solons on Parade,
probably doesn't know the euro from a eucalyptus tree. Because if
he did, he wouldn't be screwing around with this dump-Clinton
effort at this juncture.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
