</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL FUMBLES BY NOT HIRING AFRICAN-AMERICAN HEAD COACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; sports headline in Sunday's New York Times said, ``Green's
success lifts black coaches' stature.''
</P>
<P>
   A caption under an accompanying photograph said, ``If Dennis
Green's Vikings win the Super Bowl, having a black head coach may
become quite fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying column by Dave Anderson began: ``Dennis Green
doesn't deserve the burden of being a beacon. But the more games
that Green and his Minnesota Vikings win in the Super Bowl XXXIII
playoffs, the more visible other black candidates should be in the
fog that seems to surround most National Football League club
owners when searching for a new head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us cut through the fog to see what is really being said. A
brother has to go 15-1 before other brothers can get ``stature.'' A
brother has to win the Super Bowl before other brothers can become
``fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   A brother has to be nearly perfect to convince owners in the
National Football League that brothers can coach.
</P>
<P>
   The column was well intentioned to the point that Anderson said
it was ``embarrassing'' that the last 18 _ now 19 _ head coaching
jobs in the 30-team National Football League have gone to white
men. But the headline, the caption, and the notion that the
aspirations of other African-American coaches are tied to Green's
performance are maddening reminders of the racist double standard
that surrounds the hiring of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the players in the National Football League
are African-American. But at the beginning of the 1998 season, only
10 percent of the head coaches were African-American, and that
percentage could drop to 6 percent with the recent firing of Ray
Rhodes of the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the modern NFL with two current African-American
head coaches _ Green and Tony Dungy of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers _
and two former African-American head coaches _ Rhodes and Art
Shell, who coached the Los Angeles Raiders from 1989-'94. All four
coaches made the playoffs at least once. Their combined record in
the regular season is 178-137-1.
</P>
<P>
   Shell's regular-season record with the Raiders was 54-38, a
winning percentage of 59 percent. He made the playoffs three times.
He will be interviewed for the head coaching job in Cleveland next
week.
</P>
<P>
   That does not get around the fact that he has not had a serious
head coaching offer since his departure from the Raiders. When the
1998 season began, 13 of the teams had coaches who were retreads,
men who had been head coaches of another NFL team. Only three of
those 13 retreads had a regular-season winning percentage higher
than Shell's. The NFL has only nine white coaches _ one out of
every three _ who can claim Shell's achievement of three playoff
appearances in his first five full years.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL says it is curing itself of racism by bolstering the
lower ranks of coaches. But bolstering is not the same as
advancement. Head coaches usually come from the ranks of offensive
or defensive coordinators. It took Tony Dungy 12 years to go from
coordinator to head coach, longer than it took for any white
coordinator to become a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Among white head coaches, the average time from coordinator to
the head job is six years. Fifteen of the league's 20 white coaches
advanced from coordinator to head coach in six years or less. While
it can be said that Rhodes advanced from coordinator to head coach
in four years, it took him until his 15th season of NFL coaching to
become head coach. No other white head coach had to wait as long
once they entered the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   No one is so obviously waiting as Sherman Lewis. Lewis, 56, has
coached in the NFL for 16 seasons. He has been offensive
coordinator for the Green Bay Packers for seven.
</P>
<P>
   His team won a Super Bowl. Two men under his command are now
head coaches. Steve Mariucci (no years as a coordinator and five
years of NFL experience) was hired two seasons ago by the San
Francisco 49ers. Jon Gruden (three years as a coordinator and seven
as an NFL coach) was hired last year by the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lewis still waits for his own head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on Dennis Green ignores the fact that no white coach's
performance lifts or sinks the stature of white coaches. While the
African-American coaches have won 57 percent of their games, the
NFL was content to begin this season with nine white coaches whose
winning percentage was 45 percent. Of the 13 retreads, nine were
hired by a new team after failing to post a winning record in their
final year with their previous team.
</P>
<P>
   It is disgusting for anyone to intimate that an African-American
coach must post a 15-1 record for black coaches to become
``fashionable.'' We are not talking about a mysterious talent pool.
Every NFL coach in 1998 was a former college or pro player. There
should be no more stories about black coaches rising on the
fortunes of Dennis Green. It is about how the NFL crushes
African-American coaches despite having the biggest talent pool for
black leadership than any other business in the nation save for
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
