<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW ERA IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SACRAMENTO, Calif. --- As pompous rancor racked the capital of
the largest government in the country, cheerful civility marked the
passage of power in the capital of the second-largest government.
In the calm of a foggy winter Monday, neither partisan screeching
nor feckless strategizing greeted Gray Davis as he took the oath to
become the 37th governor of California.
</P>
<P>
   The first Democrat elected governor in 16 years, Davis, 56,
succeeded Republican Pete Wilson, ineligible for reelection because
of term limits. He invited Wilson to the inaugural, then saluted
him: ``As we pass the torch, I could not have asked for more
cooperation or a better attitude during our transition, and I thank
you for more than 30 years of service to California and America.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis then proceeded to bash Wilson's programs: ``The era of
wedge-issue politics in California is over. . . . You can finally
ring down the curtain on the politics of division. . . . Blaming
teachers, as some have done, is no solution. . . . My
administration will not flinch in the face of the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   These candid criticisms ignited cheers in the partisan crowd,
but at the end of his inaugural speech, Davis invited Wilson and
Vice President Gore and their wives to raise hands together on the
stage. The message was: We can disagree and still be civil. How
mature, how mellow, how Californian, how un-Washingtonian.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a Clintonesque ``new Democrat'' without Clinton's
excess of charm. After he took the oath, a three-minute standing
ovation rattled the 1920s-Moorish rafters of Memorial Auditorium,
punctuating an end to the Democrats' exile. Justice Stanley Mosk
told the crowd how long such droughts can be. ``It was 60 years ago
that I participated in the inauguration of Governor Culbert Olson,
the first Democratic governor of this century,'' Mosk said. ``I
later became his chief of staff. Now we have high expectations as
we inaugurate Gray Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Democratic governors between Olson and Davis were the
Edmund G. Browns, Senior and Junior. Pat Brown personified the
big-spending optimism of the late 1950s, building highways, water
projects, and universities. Jerry, elected in 1974, called his time
``an era of limits.'' (The younger Brown has returned to politics,
becoming mayor of Oakland at the same hour Davis, his former chief
of staff, became governor.)
</P>
<P>
   California Democrats have often lurched leftward, and
Republicans predict that Davis will do likewise. But his inaugural
speech shunned what he called ``rigid ideologies'' to say: ``I am a
moderate and a pragmatist by nature. That is how I campaigned. And
that is how I will lead this state into the future. I will govern
neither from the right nor from the left but from the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis baptized his first term ``the era of higher
expectations,'' saying his primary mission as governor will be ``to
restore California's schools to greatness.'' The state ranks first
in the number of students, 5.6 million, but 41st in annual spending
per pupil. The Silicon Valley state ranks 47th in students per
computer.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget is $150 billion, but mandated programs will
force Davis to honor his inaugural promise to be ``tight with your
tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has another role model in Gore, who visits California's 54
electoral votes the way other people visit the grocery store. Davis
once called Gore ``my charisma tutor,'' but compared with the new
governor, the vice president could be Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Is Davis ambitious for higher office? Nearly every politician
is. Michael Dukakis, here to congratulate the new state treasurer,
Phil Angelides, had one piece of advice for Davis: ``Don't run for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   In his serviceable speech, Davis shunned editorial advice to
become inspirational. ``We are among the most fortunate people ever
to inhabit planet Earth,'' he told Californians. For an apolitical
electorate, that may be inspiration enough.
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
