<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TOOK A TEAM FOR `CIVIL' ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the record, there were three partners in the Boston law firm
that represented the Woburn, Mass. families in ``A Civil Action.''
Jan Schlichtmann was only one of them.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the narcissistic trial lawyer who favored
hand-tailored suits and Hermes ties, who embodied both '60s
idealism and '80s greed, was central to the 1986 courtroom drama
that comes to the big screen this week in its much-anticipated
Boston premiere.
</P>
<P>
   It was Schlichtmann who convinced his more cautious partners,
Kevin Conway and Bill Crowley, that an upstart, three-man personal
injury firm could prove that two Fortune 500 companies had poisoned
Woburn's well water with chemical solvents and caused the cancer
deaths of five children and one adult.
</P>
<P>
   It is not those deaths, but the David and Goliath matchup
between the tiny firm of Schlichtmann, Conway &AMP; Crowley and the
corporate giants of Beatrice Foods and W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. that forms
the narrative core of ``A Civil Action,'' Jonathan Harr's riveting,
disheartening account of the realities of civil litigation in our
time.
</P>
<P>
   As inevitable as it was that Schlichtmann would be portrayed in
the film version by an actor with the star quality of John
Travolta, it was just as certain that Kevin Conway and Bill Crowley
would be played by actors with names like Tony Shalhoub and Zeljko
Ivanek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just those kind of guys,'' smiles Conway, who stepped
out of character to buy, rather than rent, the tuxedo he'll wear to
the movie gala at the Wang Center. ``Flashy isn't a word that comes
immediately to mind when you think of me or Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   It took more than style, however, to mount one of the most
complicated medical liability and environmental pollution cases in
US history. Schlichtmann was the undisputed star in the well of
Judge Walter J. Skinner's federal courtroom, but he was propped up
on those Bally shoes by an office staff that swelled to 18 at the
height of the case. They called their softball team The Kooks.
</P>
<P>
   Conway conducted many of the depositions in the case. Crowley
assembled most of the exhibits. Sylvia Chin-Caplan, the office's
attorney-nurse practitioner, examined all of the medical records of
the Woburn families. Ron Homer, then a paralegal and now junior
partner in the reconfigured firm of Conway, Crowley &AMP; Homer, ran
errands and polished Schlichtmann's Porsche and the conference room
table of bird's-eye maple that Schlichtmann ordered from a man who
had designed a similar one for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a team in the best sense of the word,'' recalls
Crowley, who poured the proceeds of every other case he settled
during those years back into the Woburn litigation. ``We were in it
together. We were on a crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every crusade ends in triumph, however. The Woburn case
ended with a token $8 million settlement from W.R. Grace, and no
admission of guilt on the part of either corporation. Schlichtmann,
Conway &AMP; Crowley was broke after years of doing battle with the
likes of Hale and Dorr and Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers themselves were nearly broken. Schlichtmann declared
bankruptcy and ran off to Hawaii to nurse his psychic wounds.
Conway and Crowley were no less disillusioned with the law, but
Hawaii was not an option. They had families to support. Both men
rejected bankruptcy as an out. They hunkered down, scrambling to
salvage the firm they had almost lost.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, they have yet to put all the financial
burdens of Woburn behind them. That's why Conway's wife, Ginny,
still hasn't read ``A Civil Action.'' Why would she? Wednesday's
night's hoopla notwithstanding, there is not a lot she wants to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   The deeds to the Conway and Crowley homes were collateral for
all the loans the firm had secured to finance the Woburn case. ``I
remember reading the papers from the IRS. They said I would be able
to keep my clothes and my books, but everything else would be
auctioned off to settle our tax debt,'' Ginny Conway recalls. ``I
thought, `That's not too bad. My children are healthy, and I get to
keep my books.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it never came to that. ``It was a nightmare. We
were all scared,'' says Michele Crowley, ``but we never lost sight
of who the real victims were in this case. We got to tuck our
children in at night.''
</P>
<P>
   The three remain friends. Schlichtmann is gone, in practice in
Beverly, Mass., but Conway and Crowley fought their way back. The
centerpiece of their firm's new office, on Congress Street in
downtown Boston, is that bird's-eye maple conference table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
