<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REMISSION-MISSION-ART     01-06 1546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMISSION-MISSION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER REMISSION, A MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. FRANKLIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Slipping forward in her chair at the dining room
table of her condo, Margie Levine is so natural, so ``what you see
is what you get,'' that she puts you at ease with the long line of
scars from stitches on her body, as if she were showing a cat's
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to see my scar? It goes from my midriff to my torso,''
she says of the track left there when a surgeon cut a cancerous
tumor from her left lung.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Levine, 52, has outlived the trauma and is free of
cancer, no small feat given that, nine years ago, four doctors gave
her the same diagnosis: less than a year to live.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes her tale all the more riveting, especially this
time of year, is Levine's message that the cancer led her to
reorder her life's priorities. She became more centered and even,
in the end, happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I vowed that if I lived, I would dedicate the rest of my life
empowering other cancer patients who feel desperate to harness
their coping skills,'' Levine says.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she spoke last spring at the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute, telling her story to 150 physicians. Last fall, she
spoke before 200 health professionals at a convention of the
American Lung Cancer Association. Last month, she spoke at Lesley
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous when I spoke at Dana-Farber because my story is
traumatic and I had never shared it publicly,'' Levine recalls.
``But they cheered me when I finished,'' and applauded loud and
long. Some listeners bought her book, ``Embracing Challenge,'' a
self-published 41-step guide to wellness. ``Even my doctor stood in
line to shake my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   That doctor, David Sugarbaker, is chief of thoracic surgery at
Dana-Farber/Brigham and Women's Hospital. And he says he's all too
happy to celebrate Levine's life. ``She is the one who during her
treatment constantly coached others in a thumbs-up, positive way,''
says Sugarbaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the longest-known cancer-free survivor in the world of
pleural-mesothelioma, or asbestos cancer,'' Levine says. She still
has 100 metal clips around her heart. But except for an old back
injury, she is healthy, a marvel whose case is studied at Harvard
Medical School and whose longevity is turning heads in the medical
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her living this long says something went right. Her case is
very encouraging,'' says Sugarbaker.
</P>
<P>
   Now she counsels others with cancer, like the people she met
last summer at Polly's Place, a support group on Cape Cod. ``We had
to turn people away for space,'' says Karen Rudman, who leads the
group. ``Margie is so inspiring because she is an ordinary lady who
has done remarkable things.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what one woman, diagnosed with incurable cancer at 43,
did to put CAT scans and hospitals behind her. Much of her advice
might apply, too, to anyone who'd like a more fulfilling life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to rush through my meals and eat helter-skelter, and
now, before each meal, I stop and appreciate for a moment where my
food comes from, and I savor every bite,'' Levine says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get upset if I spilled red wine on a white couch.
Now I realize it's a thing that can be fixed,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to save money for a rainy day. Now I indulge myself,
even frivilously, on clothing or furnishings for my home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a human doing, and now I strive to be a human
being,'' she says, a broad smiling breaking across her face like a
TV game show contestant who has just won the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our culture most of us are human doings _ doing, going,
going. It's a status symbol to say to a friend, `I'm fine, I'm
great, oh yes, I've been very, very busy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1986, Levine was one of those people.
</P>
<P>
   A public school health education coordinator who taught some
college on the side, she was newly married to Ralph, her husband of
14 years, was playing in tennis tournaments and was running six
miles a day. She liked to design greeting cards and travel, to
Asia, Europe, and the Caribbean. Then one day Levine fell at work,
giving rise to the lumbar disc problem that sent her into bed for
two years. ``That's when I learned the coping skills, the survival
skills that helped me face the cancer,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Keys to coping with the back injury included tuning in to her
body, undergoing treatment, and taking charge of her healing, as
well as gathering friends for support. ``She has an incredible zest
for life. She cultivates friends as one cultivates flowers,'' says
Margie Stein, a friend of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the cancer. Levine says she cried all night after her
diagnosis, and passed through the darkness repeating the mantra,
``Let go and let God, let go and let God.''
</P>
<P>
   Pity, she knew, would have gotten her nowhere, but neither would
passivity. ``Of course, there were times when I said, `why me?' but
the answer always came back `why not?' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   So Levine got to work wrestling the grapefruit-sized tumor
growing inside her. She traveled from Boston to New York to discuss
her options with oncology specialists. The more she learned, the
more she became less of a victim and more of an advocate for her
own treatment and recovery. It was then, Ralph Levine says, that
the couple learned ``the fine line between being assertive and
aggressive with the medical community.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine says she worked with her doctors at Dana-Farber and
Brigham and Women's to design her own protocol, ``modeled from a
procedure developed at Memorial-Sloan Kettering Cancer Center,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the most resourceful person I know,'' says Ralph, ``and
she doesn't take no for an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Before surgery, Levine prepared to die. She telephoned old
friends to say goodbye. She hired a lawyer to prepare a will. She
threw away diaries, gave away a treasured doll. ``But I never gave
up hope,'' says Levine.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery, Levine learned she was the first patient in
Boston to have had interpleural chemo drugs poured into her chest
during lung surgery. It was the kind of aggressive treatment many
would not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Levine not only survived, she thrived. By combining aggressive
medical treatment with holistic techniques like acupuncture, diet,
meditation, and visualization tapes made using her voice, Levine
convalesced and eventually recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very aware that I am one in a million. Sometimes, I'll be
walking along the beach and I ask myself, `Why am I alive?' The
answer is `because I haven't fulfilled my purpose yet, spreading
the light and the healing to others,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   How does Levine live these days? ``Striving for balance between
work and play, joy and pain, service to others and giving to
oneself, movement and rest,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She splits her time living between her city apartment and a
house on Cape Cod, whose backyard gardens lead to the marshes of
Weir Creek in West Dennis. The Cape house is very important to her,
she says, because she and Ralph, an accountant, love to garden. ``I
need a balance of water, skies, trees, and fresh air,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Levine credits part of her recovery to being able to
return to Cape Cod and the ocean during her illness. After every
cancer treatment, Levine picnicked by the sea. If weather made that
impossible, she ate at a restaurant with an ocean view. Levine and
Stein laugh as they recall the day six months after Levine got out
of the hospital when they picnicked on the snowcapped dunes of a
Cape beach. ``It was five below zero, but we brought our beach
chairs,'' says Levine. ``We laughed and laughed,'' says Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Levine chairs the Boston chapter of the worldwide Institute of
Noetic Sciences. Founded by astronaut Edgar Mitchell after a
mystical experience on the way back to Earth from the moon, Levine
says the institute studies scientifically documented research and
education on human consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Hepner Brody has been a friend for 20 years. She says
the illness changed Levine because it made her more vulnerable to
others. Whether it was allowing friends to help clean her house or
sharing such traumas as losing her hair during chemotherapy, Levine
was forced to accept the unconditional love of friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone knows they are accepted totally for themselves
and as they are, it reshapes them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Levine's doctors are delighted with her health and outlook.
``The most important thing you can do for cancer patients is to let
them know appropriately that there is hope. When you have a Margie
Levine around, who's had the problem and faced it, you can say to
the next patient, `There is hope,' '' says Sugarbaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``She defied the odds,'' says Dr. Karen Chayte-Marcus, a
radiology oncologist at Dana-Farber. ``It's wonderful that she
offers hope to others. For a cancer patient, having someone who has
been through it is an incredible inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Levine, ``There is a divine plan for each of us. I believe
I am alive because I am supposed to be doing this work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
