<HEADLINE>
JONATHAN HARR: STILL GETTING USED TO FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON, Mass. _ Several months ago, Jonathan Harr was
channel-surfing one afternoon when who should pop up on his
television screen but actor Robert Duvall.
</P>
<P>
   Duvall, whose film ``The Apostle'' had just come out, was being
asked by interviewer Charlie Rose about current projects. Duvall
replied that he was filming a legal melodrama based on the
bestselling book ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Oh,' says Rose, `you mean that one about the cancer cases
written by. . . . by . . . ' '' Harr recalls. ``And Duvall goes,
`Yeah, right, the book by . . . by . . . geez, I can't think of the
writer's name.' They're both fumbling around while I'm sitting
there screaming at the set, `The name, guys. What's my name?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the sweet anonymity of authorship, Hollywood-style. Harr of
course lost much of his professional anonymity back in 1995, when,
after nine years of monkish labor and financial uncertainty, his
book about the Woburn, Mass. toxic-waste case was published by
Random House, to near universal acclaim. At the time, Harr was
hoping to earn back his $80,000 advance and maybe enough extra cash
to fix a leak in his roof.
</P>
<P>
   Two years of runaway hardcover sales and more than a million
paperback copies later, the 50-year-old Harr is instead living out
a dream that would strike most first-time authors as pure fantasy.
The flip side of a chemical-spill nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe the sensation,'' he acknowledges,
sitting recently in the living room of his rambling Victorian-style
house, a few blocks from downtown Northampton.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the frenzied bidding for the film rights to his
book, Harr observes, ``This has not all been unalloyed joy. It's
scary. I've felt exposed by all the publicity. I've asked myself,
what does all this mean? What will the fallout be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had done a pretty good job on the book, but being
suddenly in the spotlight made me wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaning forward in a leather chair, Harr says with quiet
intensity, ``I'm actually glad I did not have this kind of success
in my 20s or 30s. I never could have handled it. It still doesn't
feel quite real.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgive him for pinching himself, but this is one dream that
won't seem to quit. Harr, who needed a speech coach to make it
through his first transcontinental book tour, is now on speaking
terms with literati and glitterati on both coasts, from Tina Brown
to John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   Film rights to his book sold to Robert Redford's production
company for a cool $1.25 million. A major motion picture version of
``A Civil Action'' is now in release, generating Oscar-friendly
reviews. Harr parted ways with his former agent and signed on with
superagent Andrew Wylie, whom he impishly refers to as ``the
barbarian at the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment specialists call the Harr house day and night (Harr
refuses to unlist his phone number _ on principle, he says). He and
his wife, Diane, a part-time teacher at Smith College, recently
completed house renovations so lavish that the $300,000 makeover
was featured in the House &AMP; Home section of The New York Times.
Both Harrs are avid cooks, by the way, and now have a kitchen
worthy of their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Still working on a three-piece contract he signed with the New
Yorker in 1994, Harr is also shopping around for a new book
project, which he plans to have finalized by early spring. He says
he is leaning away from covering another legal case _ been there,
done that _ and toward an area like cutting-edge medical research.
Whatever subject he chooses next, two things seem certain. One,
Harr will demand total access to the real-life players involved.
And two, bidding on the book will start at an ample six figures and
skew upward from there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to the author's delight, ``A Civil Action'' has
become a standard textbook at law schools across the country, where
Harr, who never formally studied legal theory, is suddenly hotter
than William Rehnquist and John Grisham combined.
</P>
<P>
   Each new twist to what Harr describes as a ``once-in-a lifetime
experience'' compounds the amazement of a once-struggling writer
who managed to produce one of the big nonfiction books of the
1990s. If the Woburn case were Mount Everest (in many ways an apt
analogy), then Harr would be its Jon Krakauer, climbing into thin
air against difficult odds and ultimately to the pinnacle of his
profession.
</P>
<P>
   How dizzying has the ascent been? Harr recalls a pre-publication
lunch in Manhattan with Harry Evans, then the top man at Random
House. Evans predicted that Harr's book would sell 400,000 copies,
a jaw-dropping number for any publisher to throw around. He then
asked Harr what else he was working on (apparently Evans had no
trouble remembering his author's name). Harr replied that he was
writing a New Yorker piece about the National Transportation and
Safety Board. The only hitch, said Harr, was that while editor Tina
Brown (who happens to be Evans's wife) wanted 5,000 words, he had
already written 15,000 words _ and was not finished yet.
</P>
<P>
   Evans summoned for a telephone and, according to Harr, promised
to ``take care of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Harr with a laugh, ``The next day I get a call from my
editor at the magazine saying, `Listen Jon, is there some problem
here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB piece, needless to say, ran at triple the assigned
length. Harr is currently 16,000 words into another New Yorker
piece, this one a profile of a black lawyer from Florida who has
risen from humble beginnings (his parents were migrant farm
workers) to become one of the country's most successful
personal-injury attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last lawyer story,'' promises Harr, who despite Brown's
departure has been assured by New Yorker editor David Remnick that
his deal with the magazine is alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   So too is Harr's admiration for Steve Zaillian's film. Unlike
crusading attorney Jan Schlictmann (portrayed by Travolta), Harr
was not a paid consultant on the project. Nevertheless, Harr says,
he developed a close relationship with Zaillian, who wrote the
screenplay and sought Harr's advice on the arc of the story. Like
the book, the film faced a formidable task in boiling down years of
complex legal maneuvering into a compelling and coherent story
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Steve cut out of earlier versions was mostly confusion,''
says Harr, who has seen at least three versions during the final
editing stages of the film. ``I was prepared to say all the right
and diplomatic things about the movie, but after the first couple
of minutes I forgot about the story and my book and was completely
hooked by the performances.''
</P>
<P>
   His warm feelings notwithstanding, this week's (Jan. 6) release
of ``A Civil Action'' thrusts Harr back into a spotlight that has
often made him uncomfortable. News accounts of million-dollar film
deals and squabbles over rights to the Woburn families' stories
have pained Harr, who has maintained close ties to many of the
families. At one point he told the film's producers that he would
not involve himself in negotiations with the families. Years ago he
took a similar stance with Schlictmann and his law partners,
informing them that he would only do the book if he had full access
to, and control over, the Woburn story.
</P>
<P>
   As Harr explains it, drawing the line at who could profit from
the book was not only just, given the years he labored on it
without promise of much reward, and because his reporting depended
on that arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, say, the Woburn families had an interest in it,'' says
Harr, ``how would Jerry Facher'' _ the Beatrice Foods attorney
portrayed by Duvall _ ``feel about sitting down and talking to
me?'' Harr adds that he makes a distinction between the book and
movie (for which the Woburn families were paid an undisclosed
rights fee by Disney) because ``although the movie arises from my
book, it is not my thing. I've already done my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What most amazed Harr about watching ``A Civil Action'' being
filmed, he continues, was seeing the Woburn case come full circle
in a sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was this thing that had once employed dozens, maybe
hundreds of people,'' says Harr, ``and then gotten to the point
where only one person was interested in it _ me _ suddenly, after
going into the dustbin of history, started employing hundreds of
people again. I found that quite extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, ``being the author of a bestseller is not
like being a movie star,'' says Harr. ``I can walk down the streets
of my hometown and nobody recognizes me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harr seems grateful for, as well as protective of, whatever
anonymity he has left. For successful writers in this
show-me-the-money culture, that's may be the hardest act of all.
Even harder than laboring for nine years on a book that could have
bombed at the box office and left Harr working at Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I never try to talk to writer friends about is
money,'' says Harr. ``Money is not what's important anyway. What's
important is the work. I believe that. I really do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
