<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S MEETING TIME FOR THE PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Evaluation week is upon us, and a few
sessions between Bobby Grier, Robert Kraft, and certain Patriots
coaches and players may not be flattering to head coach Pete
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Tackle Bruce Armstrong left the Foxboro Stadium parking lot
Monday without speaking to reporters, but he did have a sitdown
with Grier, the team's vice president of player personnel, and
Kraft, the owner. The subject was Armstrong's take on the season,
including Carroll's handling of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who was returning to his home in Alpharetta, Ga., is
one of the key veterans who has the ear of the front office and he
is not said to be one of Carroll's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran has a strong relationship with Kraft and Grier, and
his opinions are valued. Armstrong was one of the Patriots who
joined Kraft at a Connecticut rally to celebrate the move to
Hartford. He also does appearances and functions on behalf of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and quarterback Drew Bledsoe were the two veteran
players who addressed the team immediately following last Sunday's
25-10 loss to the Jacksonville Jaguars that ended New England's
season.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who is a Carroll supporter, also has met with the front
office, and strength and conditioning coach Johnny Parker is due in
shortly to discuss, he said, ``a number of things involving a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who ran the Patriots' program under Bill Parcells for
four years in which the team had the fewest injuries in the league,
is trying to pick up the pieces of a season in which 16 starters
missed game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to do a better job,'' said Parker. ``This is a
bottom-line league. All anyone wants to know on Monday is, `Did you
win or did you lose? ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the rash of injuries might have been just bad
luck, Parker said, ``I don't believe in luck. You mean, we had a
four-year run of luck? If that's the case, some of that luck is
down the road in Long Island.''
</P>
<P>
   According to one player, Parker hasn't had the complete
authority under Carroll that he did under Parcells. Parker chose to
stay in Foxborough when Parcells left because he wanted to keep
living in the area. He signed a mulityear deal, believed to be for
about seven years, and in fact was under contract before the
Patriots named Carroll coach.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who is as tough as a drill sergeant, blames himself for
not getting a total commitment from the players to his offseason
program. Asked whether the Patriots were a well-conditioned team,
he said, ``Any team that has this many injuries couldn't be a
well-conditioned team.''
</P>
<P>
   While the team does a lot of conditioning work during the
season, Parker said, ``If you don't pay the price in the offseason,
it's too late by the start of training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the core of his program has remained intact, though
he adds new wrinkles every year. Last winter, he introduced
sandbags into the routines, which helped players with the shifting
of weight they experience in games. Parker has more new wrinkles
planned for this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a number of ideas that I'll discuss with Coach Grier
and the head coach,'' said Parker.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he was dissatisfied with the conditioning of
players such as Terry Glenn, Parker said, ``First of all, people
shouldn't point fingers at Terry. It's our job to get him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker is certainly open to players seeking their own
conditioning routines. Ty Law, for example, worked in the offseason
in St. Louis with Bob Kersee on his speed and running. He got
himself into track shape and became one of the best corners in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said of Armstrong, ``He's never shown up but he's been to
six Pro Bowls. I know that he's working out today.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker wouldn't say exactly when he would meet with the front
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come shortly,'' he said. ``Right now they have bigger
fish to fry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
