<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH SHOULD SLOW, BUT THE FUTURE IS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all their cool rationality, most economists
trying to divine where America is headed in 1999 rely on a
thoroughly unscientific proposition in their latest forecasts _ the
nation can't possibly continue to spiral upward without hitting
some kind of substantial glitch.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, both the economy and the stock market managed such
skyward climbs in 1998. And true enough, the policymaker most
responsible for maintaining their rising trajectories, Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, still has plenty of maneuvering
room to keep the good times going.
</P>
<P>
   But for another whole year?
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has gotten so good it can't possibly stay this
way,'' said David A. Wyss, chief economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's
DRI in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't forecasters simply declare that the good times will
finally come to a close in 1999? The reason is that the traditional
killer of expansions, inflation, is nowhere to be found. And the
country has survived a string of other ailments over the last year
_ from Monicagate to a near- meltdown in financial markets _ that
in any other time would have snuffed out growth.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the lesson of 1998 seems to be that the US
economy can take a licking and keep on ticking _ perhaps
indefinitely. That has seemed especially so in recent weeks when a
combination of President Clinton's impeachment and a
US-orchestrated attack on Iraq led many to predict that the stock
market would tumble while oil prices leaped. The very opposite
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the economy's top-line numbers, they look
spectacular,'' said Mark M. Zandi, chief economist with Regional
Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``It's only when you look
below the surface that you begin to see the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   The cracks in this case are slowing corporate profits, consumer
spending that outstrips income, a downturn among the nation's
manufacturers and continued instability overseas. Most analysts
agree that these trends spell slower growth in 1999 and a greater
risk than at any time in recent years of something worse occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm truly in awe of the economy's performance'' in 1998, said
Maureen F. Allyn, chief economist of Scudder Kemper Investments
Inc. in New York, ``but there is a lot of potential for getting
whipsawed'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, a dozen economists interviewed in recent weeks
predicted that the nation will grow about 2 percent from the fourth
quarter of 1998 through the fourth quarter of this year. That is
considerably slower than the approximately 3.7 percent rate at
which the economy expanded last year. Still, it is growth, not
contraction, and would push the 1990s boom to within shouting
distance of becoming the longest expansion in US history.
</P>
<P>
   But what a wild ride the last year has been! And what a wild
ride this one could be!
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts began 1998 convinced that the Asian crisis would
finally slow America's sunny economy by damaging the markets for
its exports. But the crisis also directed a flood of foreign
capital into this country, driving interest rates down, consumer
spending up, and US stocks through the roof. The resulting
headiness lasted until mid-summer, when Russia abruptly devalued it
currency and defaulted on its foreign debt. By all rights, the
Russian debt default should have been a minor event. In economic
terms, the country was no bigger than the Netherlands, and by the
time of its implosion, most of the developed world had weathered
worse and still prospered.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the US stock market chugged upward throughout the first
half of the year despite riots in the Far East and rising warnings
about corporate profits. And even when it faltered in mid-July, its
long-anticipated correction was extremely well-tempered. The Dow
Jones industrial average, which had risen more than 25 percent from
mid-January, gave back less than half that gain by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia became the first of two economic cotter pins for
1998, pivots around which other events turned. The Russian crisis
played on Americans' fear they had paid too much for their US
stocks and had come to rely too heavily on the rest of the world
remaking itself in America's economic image.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, economic euphoria gave way to fear. The Dow and
other major market measures fell sharply enough to meet the
definition of a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The panic reached a crescendo in mid-September, when the
goverment revealed it had orchestrated the bailout of an obscure
firm called Long-Term Capital Management out of fear that collapse
of the Greenwich, Conn.-based investment fund might bring down the
entire global financial system.
</P>
<P>
   At this juncture, the second of the year's cotter-pin events
occurred _ Greenspan and the Fed began cutting interest rates .
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the chairman's finest hour,'' said David M. Jones,
chief economist of Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed will do whatever it takes to keep this economy on
track,'' predicted Richard D. Rippe, chief economist of Prudential
Securities, also in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how unusual the Fed's fall rate cuts were, it is
necessary to remember that, until their announcement, the central
bank had been single-mindedly dedicated to fighting inflation. And
although prices have barely budged in recent years, the
unemployment rate has dropped to an almost 30-year low, a move that
until recently would have been considered the first step toward
higher wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how difficult the Fed's job of managing the economy
is likely to be in the coming year, one need only notice two
results of its rate cuts _ a stock market recovery that has sent
share prices back above levels that Greenspan had suggested were
insupportable and the continuation of a consumer
borrowing-and-buying binge that had previously worried the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the most debated statistic of the holiday season may
have been a Commerce Department finding that US household savings
have dropped from a vaguely-acceptable 6 percent of income in 1993
to negative territory. Some analysts dismiss the figure as a
statistical aberration. But others say it illustrates how
vulnerable the economy is to trouble, especially given that
consumer spending has been the mainstay of growth for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system has taken on a degree of leverage that's
worrisome,'' said Scudder Kemper's Allyn. ``It's like walking
across a sidewalk crack in platform shoes: A little tip can turn
into a very big tilt.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, pessimistic forecasters predict that the economy will
slow to a crawl this year as profit-squeezed companies trim capital
spending and lay off workers, and as tapped-out consumers finally
put away their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, optimists believe that the nation is in for more
growth, and they discount the danger of serious trouble. ``This
economy is so strong it can absorb all but the most dramatic
shocks,'' said Conference Board chief economist Gail D. Fosler,
whose 3 percent-plus growth forecast for the year is among the most
bullish of any mainstream analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But even Fosler agreed that with an impeachment trial of
President Clinton, the risk of another Russia-like financial
catastrophe, and perhaps even mounting worries about the year-end
Y2K computer problem , 1999 may serve up as many shocks as 1998
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly some candidates out there for the kind of
event that causes people to say `Whoa, the world is a very
different place than I thought it was,' '' she conceded. Different
enough, indeed, that they stop spending and investing as much as
they have, steps that could make 1999 a very different _ and
considerly darker _ year than the one just ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
