<HEADLINE>
TAINTED BLOOD MAY HAVE INFECTED THOUSANDS WITH HEPATITIS C 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tainted blood may have infected thousands of
people in Texas with hepatitis C, according to the medical director
of the South Texas Blood and Tissue Center, which distributed the
blood.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 3,000 people who got blood or blood-related products
from the center from 1988 to 1992 are being notified by letter that
they may have been contaminated with hepatitis C and should be
tested for the virus, said Dr. Norman Kalmin, the center's
president and medical director.
</P>
<P>
   Since symptoms can take 20 years to surface, people infected
with the virus are often unaware until years later.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 4 million people in the United States are infected with
hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that the disease can be managed with medication and
lifestyle changes.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Congress ordered U.S. blood banks to notify people who
received blood transfusions before 1992, when reliable tests became
available to detect hepatitis C, which was first identified in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C is considered the most serious of the hepatitis
viruses, which include A, B and D.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C is most often spread by contact with blood through
such means as intravenous drug use, blood transfusions,
self-inflicted tattoos and body piercing, and sex with multiple
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easily transmitted,'' said Dr. Fernando Guerra, the
health director for the city of San Antonio. He added that people
who live with a person who has hepatitis C can avoid infection by
taking measures such as not sharing razors or toothbrushes.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra also assured the public San Antonio's current blood
supply is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Victor Ostrower, who served on a hepatitis C working group,
said anyone diagnosed with the virus shouldn't drink alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two really don't mix very well,'' Ostrower said,
explaining that hepatitis C can damage the liver seriously over
time without alcohol. ``Alcohol is not just an additive. It's more
like an accelerant.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalmin revealed Tuesday afternoon during a news conference at a
health district clinic that the local blood supply may have been
partially tainted as recently as 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Before that year, blood, plasma and platelets from donors
couldn't be screened effectively for hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, some of the center's previous donors have
tested positive for the virus, Kalmin said, adding that residents
who got blood or blood-related products from those donors may have
been infected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the implication,'' said Kalmin, part of a 15-member
team of public and private medical professionals that's worked for
the past six months to forge a local plan to halt the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
