<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRINKING: A BORING STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you know that awful feeling, when a drunk sits down next to
you at dinner and just won't shut up? Or worse yet, when a
recovering alcoholic plants himself and starts expatiating on the
virtues of Virgin Marys? Now you know what it's like to read ``Note
Found in a Bottle: My Life as a Drinker,'' the despicable, wooden
memoir just out from Susan Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   There's money in these loser/boozer screeds, as Pete (``A
Drinking Life'') Hamill and Caroline (``Drinking: A Love Story'')
Knapp can attest. But will there be any money left for John
Cheever's little girl? Or has the reading public sobered up on this
woozy category?
</P>
<P>
   What's hateful about this book? Where to begin? The entire
premise, that alcohol prompted Cheever to become a depressive,
serial adulteress who unsurprisingly failed at three marriages,
rings false. The inescapable conclusion of ``Note'' is that Cheever
is a horrible person, engorged with self-regard, who has been
masticating the corpse of her dead, successful father for fun and
profit. Not much fun perhaps; then mainly for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1984 tome, ``Home Before Dark,'' juicily aired out her
family's dirty laundry, including Daddy's homosexual flings,
drunkenness, and feelings of social inadequacy. Her father had been
dead just two years; how odd that some family members, including
her mother, voiced reservations. (``My mother is no one,'' Cheever
said in a 1994 Globe interview. ``She's not a mother, and she's not
a writer. I'm everyone.'') In ``Note,'' the third memoir of her
brief life, the 50-something Cheever invokes Papa John both at
random and at length. A generous excerpt from one of her father's
stories proves to be the best writing in this book.
</P>
<P>
   OK, drunks do bad things, but why does Cheever, supposedly now
sober, drag otherwise unsullied reputations through her miasma of
boozy licentiousness? I wonder how biographer Robert Massie, New
Yorker writer Calvin Tomkins, and Ramparts founder Warren Hinckle
feel about being named as the three men Ms. Cheever bedded on one
particular day way back when? Here's another hilarious anecdote:
Cheever and a pal once sent William Styron a box of dog feces after
he published a displeasing review.
</P>
<P>
   Name-dropping abounds, and it is sickening to see Julia Child,
Joan Didion, Francis Coppola, and about a dozen others sucked into
the sewer of Cheever's existence. At least Knapp humiliated her
friends privately, by disguising their names. ``Where the ethics of
life and the ethics of art converge,'' Cheever once said, ``That's
where I live.'' Well, there goes the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In a book swollen with narcissism, ``Note'' introduces
meta-narcissisms that redefine the genre. Like every tiresome
boomer hack, Cheever wants you to know she really, really loves her
children. Indeed, on Page 163, she tells us she ``would have died
for Sarah,'' her newborn daughter. Yet on the next page she's
skipping off to Havana for a week with her lover, leaving Sarah,
afflicted with chicken pox, in the care of her father. ``In my
heart I was reenacting a separation of mother and daughter that
resonated from before I could remember,'' Cheever writes. Does
anyone know what she's talking about?
</P>
<P>
   Cheever keeps telling you how pretty she is, a subject on which
reasonable people can disagree. (I used to work in the same office
as she.) Then she tells you, more than once, how she's mastered the
craft of writing. But there's plenty of evidence to the contrary.
In my borrowed copy of ``Note,'' Cheever blathers on about the
French mistral ``turning the leaves of the poplar over and
flattening the mimosa against the rich Provencal earth.'' This is
where the previous owner of my book scrawled in the margin: ``Look,
Ma! I'm writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of it is _ and you knew this was coming _ that
Cheever has found God. I have never felt so sorry for God in my
life. Gilbey's; God; what's the next enthusiasm? Gorgonzola? In her
final chapter, Cheever writes, ``It seems as though my belief in
God should take up more space in this book, but it is intensely
private and truly beyond my ability to describe.'' And the reader
thinks: If only she felt this way about sex, or about drinking, or
about her father, the world would be a less ugly place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
