<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CIVIL-BOS &LR;      01-06 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CIVIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOMBER MOVIE THAT MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A CIVIL ACTION 
Written and directed by: Steven Zallian (based on Jonathan Harr's
book) 
Starring: John Travolta, Robert Duvall, Stephen Fry, James
Gandolfini, Dan Hedaya, Zelijko Ivanek, John Lithgow, William H.
Macy, Kathleen Quinlan, Tony Shalhoub, Bruce Norris, Sydney
Pollack, Mary Mara, David Thornton, Ned Eisenberg, Peter Jacobson,
Paul Ben-Victor, Daniel Von Bargen 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some storng strong language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great thing about ``A Civil Action'' is that it plays like
real life, with all its messiness and complication, and not like
the Hollywood movie it is. Packing nine years of legal battling
into two hours, it recounts the tortuous chronicle of eight
working-class families in Woburn, Mass. who hired a flashy
personal-injury lawyer to take on two giant corporations they
accused of dumping carcinogenic chemicals into their well water,
causing leukemias that killed their children. One reason it's the
most compelling legal thriller of the decade is its avoidance of
the cliched courtroom heroics, the clear-cut events and the ringing
triumphs of the usual Hollywood legal excursion.
</P>
<P>
   In short, writer-director Steven Zaillian has respected the real
events grippingly described in Jonathan Harr's landmark book. In
turn, the real-life story imparts to ``A Civil Action'' an impact
that few films in any genre can come anywhere near. Filmed with
grave clarity, somber and monochromatic, unafraid of assuming a
mournful tone, it's built around something of an antihero. As
played by John Travolta, attorney Jan Schlichtmann is arrogant and
materialistic. When finally prodded into a response by the
importuning Woburn families he had put off for months, he's about
to write them off forever when his Porsche is stopped for speeding
on a bridge and he notices lots of foam on the river flowing under
it.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued enough to soil his Bally shoes, he traces the
effluents back to an old tannery. Where the anguished Woburn
families see the contaminated river as a toxic swamp, Travolta's
Schlichtmann sees it as a gold mine when he notices the W. R. Grace
name on a dumpster. Flush from lucrative personal injury
settlements, he can't resist taking on a couple of deep-pockets
antagonists he blames for the mess, Grace and Beatrice Foods. In
short, he goes into it for the money, beginning with a speech about
how much better a job he can do if he remains emotionally
uninvolved. Before it's over, of course, he's involved to the max.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in ``A Civil Action'' is simple, including
Schlichtmann's motivations. Even when he decides to go the distance
no matter what, even when he finds himself outgunned, we feel him
at least as much driven by hubris as idealism. He may be on the
side of the angels, but it isn't angelic behavior that gets him
there. In the end, he gambles everything he owns on taking the case
to the limit, and it isn't an easy case. He must first prove that
the companies dumped the toxins, then prove the toxins entered the
drinking water by seeping into and contaminating nearby wells, then
prove they caused the fatal illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to learn that workers at the tannery used to call
the site in question ``the swimming pool.'' It's another to find
witnesses willing to testify, especially when the families realize
that the case has taken on a life of its own and that legal
procedures can take precedence over a search for truth. As
Schlichtmann, Travolta is mesmerizingly chameleon-like, never
glossing over the flaws, exposing character weaknesses, sometimes
even making them seem sympathetic and humanizing, as when we feel
him squirm inside when some high-powered adversaries remind him
what a small-time ambulance chaser he is in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of his well-heeled opponents' tactics consists of
wearing him down, throwing up procedural roadblocks in court,
finding ways to exclude evidence and witnesses unfavorable to them,
and using Schlichtmann's impatience against him, especially when it
becomes apparent that John Lithgow's vinegary and imperious
presiding judge doesn't like his style. Zaillianand his cast allow
a pall of desperation and despair to settle over Travolta's
Schlichtmann and his law partners and their panicky accountant,
played with unexpected humor by William H. Macy.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is keenly incisive, starting with Travolta's superbly
shaded Schlichtmann, in whose gradual and subtle transformation
from cockiness to compassion we believe. Between ``Primary Colors''
and now this film, it becomes indisputably clear that Travolta has
moved from being one kind of movie star _ pop culture icon _ to
another _ mature character actor. As the wiliest and deftest of his
courtrooom opponents, Jerome Facher, Robert Duvall delivers what in
most cases would be a film-stealing performance, playing on
Facher's eccentricities with delicious virtuosity. Tony Shalhoub
and Zeljko Ivanek are convincing as law partners caught up in
Schlichtmann's increasingly erratic gravitational pull. And Sydney
Pollack is droll as an opponent expert at reminding Schlichtmann of
his social shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action'' (filmed at several Boston-area sites, but
not, ironically, Woburn, which had changed too much to be used)
also reproduces _ perhaps too realistically for some _ the sense of
fearful drift felt by professionals who feel their case is slipping
beyond their control. But the film is admirable precisely because
it flies in the face of what's considered conventionally commercial
in a courtroom drama. Almost all of the interesting things here
take place outside the courtroom, and they register as
intelligently and as incisively as we would expect from the writer
of ``Schindler's List,'' ``Awakenings,'' and ``Searching for Bobby
Fischer.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaillian realizes that the strength of his film ultimately
derives from the weight of decency and rightness conveyed by the
presence of the Woburn residents. These portrayals, especially
those of Kathleen Quinlan as Anne Anderson, instrumental in
initiating the suit; David Thornton as Richard Aufiero, muffling
his grief at the loss of his son; and James Gandolfini, as the
worker who finds the courage to go public, are, ultimately, the
source of the film's authority. ``A Civil Action'' is a film that
matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
