<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL WAS A GO THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Somehow it all worked out. After a season's worth
of fretting and grumbling about the way things were done and the
way things weren't done, college football got it right.
</P>
<P>
   The best team is the national champion. No questions. No
controversy. Clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I'm sure you'll hear some muttering in Columbus, Ohio, and
maybe out in Madison, Wis., or down the road in Tucson, from the
people who felt their teams _ Ohio State, Wisconsin, Arizona _
deserved consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Sure they do. And perhaps one of those teams would have emerged
as national champion in a traditional playoff format. Maybe they
deserved the chance to compete for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the system that is in place. What happened Monday
night in the Fiesta Bowl _ when No. 1 Tennessee beat No. 2 Florida
State, 23-16 _ was college football the way it is in 1999 and the
way it will be in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers won a game that was much better in the second
half than in the first, for those of you who bailed out midway
through the nearly four-hour marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a classic? Hardly. Too many penalties (12 by Florida
State, 9 by Tennessee). Too sloppy. Too many false starts, fumbles.
It looked more like a game from early September than early January.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer and Florida State coach Bobby
Bowden conceded that the layoff _ 45 days for FSU _ was probably
too long. But that's the way the system works.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that college football staged its first
unified national championship game, and it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee finished 13-0, the best record in the school's long
and storied football history. It won its first national
championship in 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Vols the nation's best team? Probably. But who really
knows? As Fulmer said at Tuesday's final Fiesta Bowl press
conference, ``All we had to be was the best team on 13 different
game days. And we were.''
</P>
<P>
   So they were. They overcame injuries. They handled the
competition from teams such as Florida and Georgia in their own
conference. They had some luck. They also had some toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, which finished off another superb season at 10-2,
was a 5-point favorite in the Fiesta Bowl and took the Vols to the
final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here as underdogs,'' said Fulmer. ``And that's the
way we liked it. It was a challenge to us, and this team has met
every challenge presented to it since spring practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's championship should not come as a stunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations at Tennessee are always high,'' said Fulmer.
``And they should be. You should be able to win at Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vols' problem is that they have had a tough time winning
their own division in the Southeastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have gotten out of the East a few times in the
past couple of years, we might have had a chance to win two or
three more of these,'' said Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, Fulmer added that he still favors a playoff
system. He knows that the fates turned his way and allowed him to
compete for the national championship in a 1-vs.-2 game. He easily
could have been in the position of an Ohio State or Arizona _ with
only one narrow loss keeping him from the opportunity of playing
for the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd still like to see a playoff,'' said Fulmer. ``I don't have
the answers to how it could work, but I'd like to see something
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   But having seen the intensity Monday night, seeing bodies
wheeled and helped off the field in the most pressure-filled
setting, you wonder whether a playoff at this level makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   There seems little chance that either Tennessee or Florida State
could have come back in a week or even two weeks and played someone
else for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   They were too banged up, too emotionally spent.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Bowl Championship Series has done its job. It
produced a national championship game in a setting that drew
national attention.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from perfect, and it may not even be fair. But the
best team won.
</P>
<P>
   And no one can really make a strong argument against that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
