<HEADLINE>
A `TASTE OF JUDAISM' WHETS AN APPETITE FOR RELIGIOUS INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Inside a basement lecture room at Temple Beth
Shalom here, Rabbi Rifat Sonsino was leading a discussion on a
passage from Deuteronomy focusing on the ethical demands God makes
of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   As Sonsino described the different ways to interpret a passage
that talks about obligations to the poor, someone in the audience
chimes in: ``It always seems like the chapter is never closed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' Sonsino replies. ``That is the story of Judaism . . .
Nothing is black and white. We are always dealing in grays. If it
were black and white I could just e-mail you the information and
you could read it at your leisure.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some of the roughly 25 students have come to Sonsino's
class after a long day at work precisely because they find appeal
in a religion that does not necessarily offer clear-cut answers to
complex theological questions.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Judaism places a high premium on wrestling with the many
meanings that can be gleaned from the Torah. It is this kind of
rich intellectual inquiry that forms a cornerstone of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the messages Sonsino is trying to convey during a
two-hour introductory lecture on Jewish ethics. His class is part
of a highly popular introductory program to Judaism offered at
synagogues nationwide that has helped ignite a renaissance in
Jewish religious life.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 14,000 people around the nation have taken ``A Taste of
Judaism'' since the program was started about 4 1/2 years ago by
the Reform branch of American Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've certainly been very pleased with the response,'' said
Kathy Kahn, associate national director for outreach for the Union
of American Hebrew Congregations, the New York group that
represents the country's Reform congregations.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of the first 2,000 people who took the three-week
program showed that two-thirds of the students went on to take more
Jewish educational programs. And nearly 1 out of 5 of those
surveyed ended up joining a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reach those Jews who, for whatever reason,
because of negative experiences in their childhood, or because they
are in interfaith relationships, feel they might not be welcome in
a synagogue,'' said Kahn, who helped develop the course, which was
first offered in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give people a taste and, hopefully, they would be
hungry enough to want the whole meal,'' Kahn added.
</P>
<P>
   At the classes at Temple Beth Shalom, Ruth and Harvey Miller and
Kim Neger represent the two groups of people who are typical of
most students enrolling in ``A Taste of Judaism'' courses across
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers, who live in Newton, are Jewish but were never fully
exposed to their faith, were not very active in a synagogue, and
did not practice Judaism at home in any significant way.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Neger, a Natick resident, is not Jewish but her husband is
and they have decided to raise their children as Jews. So Neger
said she felt she needed to start learning about Judaism so she can
help her children.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kahn, ``A Taste of Judaism'' is split about 50-50
between Jews and non-Jews. ``We assumed it would be primarily
people in interfaith relationships but we got a lot of people born
Jews saying, `I feel so ashamed. I have no Jewish education and I
was never brought up with anything formal,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Miller, 78, said she would often attend synagogue services,
but found herself ``just reading the words and realizing that I
wasn't learning anything.'' An advertisement for ``A Taste of
Judaism'' in a weekly community newspaper caught her eye and she
decided to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was particularly interested in learning more about the
religion so I could speak more intelligently,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the course, Neger, 41, said she wants to learn more
and plans to enroll in a much more comprehensive introductory class
to Judaism that runs for 18 weeks. ``There is still so much to
learn,'' Neger said, adding that she and her husband are deciding
on which synagogue to join. ``This has been really great.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
RELIGION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --For those who missed the Dalai Lama's much-celebrated visit to
Brandeis University last year _ or if you just want to own a record
of the trip _ Brandeis is selling a video of the Tibetan Buddhist
monk's two-day stay on campus. Highlighs include his address to
7,100 people at the Gosman Sports and Convocation Center and his
speech on Buddhism and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the 100-minute video, send a check for $23 made
out to Brandeis University with ``Dalai Lama Video'' on the memo
line to: Professor Gordon Fellman, Sociology Department, MS 017,
Brandeis University, Waltham, MA 02454-9110.
</P>
<P>
   --In Spain, religious history was made late last month. For the
first time in more than five centuries Jews in Spain held a public
Hanukkah celebration. Jews were evicted from Spain in 1492 in the
culmination of a long campaign of repression.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 20, Jews lighted candles in a public space in Girona,
Spain, where Jews sought refuge in the 1390s from the brutal
anti-Semitic campaigns that were prevalent at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emotional and unforgettable day,'' Mayor Joaquim
Nadal told the gathering outside the ruins of Gironella Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanukkah celebration was overseen by Eliahu Bakshi Doron,
chief rabbi in Israel of Sephardic Jews, who trace their ancestry
to Spain. ``It moves me to be standing at this spot,'' he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   (Diego Ribadeneira can be contacted at Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; e-mail, religion(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
