<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-HANCOCK-BOS &LR;      01-06 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HANCOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MASTER OF UNMAWKISH REALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One long-ago summer day, sculptor Walker Hancock was swimming in
his Gloucester, Mass. quarry with his friend Andrew Wyeth when
Wyeth began to giggle. Why? Hancock wanted to know. ``I was just
thinking that if we were both to drown,'' Wyeth replied, ``it would
be the end of realistic art!''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, who died at his home Dec. 30, remained a realist
throughout his long career, an heir to the tradition of Augustus
Saint-Gaudens and Daniel Chester French. Arguably the last heir:
Hancock worked in an academic, figurative style now sadly debased.
He kept it alive nearly as long as he lived, swimming against the
tide of abstraction, the dominant current of 20th-century
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   He was 97 when he passed away, just one year younger than the
century whose great personages, events, and institutions he
translated into bronze or stone. He designed his last great public
monument, a ``Flight Memorial'' for the US Military Academy at West
Point, N.Y., when he was 90. The memorial's lone figure seems on
the verge of ascending to heaven, rising from a base of flames,
arms opening like a flower welcoming the sun. His thigh is
discreetly attached to the base, leaving his feet free, which adds
to the sense that he's airborne. Like those Renaissance depictions
of a St. Sebastian utterly serene despite being shot through with
arrows, Hancock's figure has shed earthly pain.
</P>
<P>
   He has also shed his uniform, a metaphor for leaving life
behind. The generals who descended on Hancock's studio to watch the
work in progress were at first bothered by the nudity, Hancock
later recalled. The artist triumphed in the end, though; anyone who
ever met Hancock could see why. His was a radiant spirit, tactful
yet tenacious, as sculptors who work in the public realm must be in
order to hold their own among architects and bureaucrats. Had
Hancock felt like it, he probably could have persuaded those
generals to lay down their arms and become pacifists.
</P>
<P>
   Prodigies in sculpture are rare; there aren't many Mozart
equivalents. Hancock, who made a model of the Parthenon at age 9
and sculpted little figures to fit its pediment, qualifies. At 18,
he was awarded his first public commission _ for a World War I
memorial for Central High in St. Louis, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   What brought Hancock to Gloucester in 1920 was Charles Grafly, a
portrait sculptor and the young artist's idol. An attack of shyness
led Hancock to bolt from Grafly's doorstep, but he plucked up his
courage and enrolled in Grafly's class at the Pennsylvania Academy
of Fine Arts shortly after. Eventually, he taught at the school,
even when that meant commuting to Philadelphia from Gloucester.
He'd fallen in love with Cape Ann, with its Finnish community, and
with one Finn in particular, Saima Natti, whom he married.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's head of a Finnish orphan, Toivo Helberg, won the
artist the prestigious Prix de Rome. The somber, solitary child is
``a portrait of innocence alone in the world,'' wrote Timothy
Crouse in the fine catalog of a 1989 Hancock exhibition at the Cape
Ann Historical Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Neither in the head of Toivo, nor in his commissioned monuments,
nor in the many sculptures he made of his own daughter, Deane, does
Hancock display any of the treacly sentimentality that mars so much
other figurative work nowadays. ``There's a tremendous revival of
interest in figurative sculpture,'' Hancock said last summer, ``so
tremendous that there is a lot of extremely poor work being
produced by people who don't know how to do anything but copy what
they see. But you have to design sculpture, compose it. And you
have to avoid mawkishness.''
</P>
<P>
   He did all the above, brilliantly. Perhaps his most majestic
design was for the 36-foot-tall ``Pennsylvania Railroad War
Memorial'' at the 30th Street Station in Philadelphia _ an angel
lifting a fallen soldier out of the flames of war, a perfect
marriage of form and feeling, in perfect sympathy with its
architectural setting. The long vertical feathers of the angel's
wings echo the fluting of the great columns that flank the piece.
Hancock, who worked both in a rounded, naturalistic style and in a
patterned Art Deco mode, began by making the angel's hands flat
horizontals, but eventually gave them an eloquent softness that
presses into the soldier's flesh, giving you a sense of his weight.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy who had sculpted figures for the pediment of his
model of the Parthenon grew up to sculpt the figures for the
pediment of the Postal Service Building in Washington, D.C.,
creating an elaborate allegory of mail by air and sea. Hancock's
public commissions _ including the monumental rhytons standing
guard at Girard College in Philadelphia, the Stone Mountain
Memorial outside Atlanta, figures of presidents and poets _ were
complemented by the many informal, intimately scaled studies he
made, sketches in bronze. While his public pieces often favor
stasis, these smaller figures _ wrestlers, swimmers, basketball
players _ lunge, dive, or whirl nimbly. He let the neighborhood
kids swim in his quarry, and he built them a basketball court on
his property, so he could study their motions. He found, and
captured, the truth in their gestures.
</P>
<P>
   He viewed art as problem-solving, taking on the challenges of
suggesting the ephemeral or even the invisible in bronze and
marble. A highly literate man _ fluent in three languages and an
opera buff _ he consulted Shakespeare when commissioned to create a
depiction of ``Air.'' He chose a line in ``Hamlet'' _ ``This most
excellent canopy, the air . . . this brave o'erhanging firmament''
_ and made a figure that hovers like a canopy over earth.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow Gloucester artist of a younger generation, Ken Hruby,
was a second-year sculpture student when he helped Hancock decide
how best to make a bust of Chief Justice Warren Burger meet its
base. Hancock ``wanted to engage me in the effort and coach me to
the solution,'' Hruby recalls. ``He gave an enormous boost to my
developing skills of observation. He had a generous spirit, a
gentle nature, and great talent. And, above all, there was about
him an aura of grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, while there are small works by Hancock sprinkled around
New England, the Boston area has no major public piece by him. The
Cape Ann Historical Museum has on view a group of small Hancock
bronzes. Judith McCulloch, the museum's director and longtime
Hancock friend, praises him for being ``one of those people who was
entirely genuine in his person and in his work. He wasn't just
good; he was whole and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock works including a model for the ``Pennsylvania Railroad
War Memorial,'' one-third the size of the real thing, are in a show
called ``America's Sculptural Heritage'' at Gloucester City Hall.
The show has been extended through May. The Boston Museum of Fine
Arts owns several small Hancocks, which it plans to put on view in
its study center by early this month. MFA curator Jonathan
Fairbanks, who first met Hancock in 1953, remembers him as ``a shy
person with no chitchat, a profound person.'' Fairbanks recalls
Hancock's calling a Calder mobile a new art form _ but not
sculpture. ``It was admirable,'' Fairbanks feels, ``that in the
face of change he didn't lose his sense of personal direction. He
was a master of classical realism, and he wasn't going to be
diverted by new inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   I met Hancock only once, last summer. Enchanted by a plaster
model I'd seen of the West Point ``Flight Memorial,'' I called to
ask him for an interview. He called back and said, very gently,
that he wasn't sufficiently interesting for me to bother with.
Others intervened on my behalf, and he relented.
</P>
<P>
   So I made the pilgrimage down the dirt road that leads to his
fairytale house with its medieval-looking turret, arbor supported
by slim columns, and massive stone fireplace, a home as elegant as
its occupant. Just steps from the house is the quarry, whose still
waters suggest those in the paintings of an earlier Gloucester
artist, Fitz Hugh Lane.
</P>
<P>
   We spent what was, for me at least, a magical hour: Hancock's
radiance spilled over to those in his presence. He was pale and
slim and wore a beatific smile. He had that translucence that some
people acquire in great old age, like a candle burning itself away
before your eyes _ or like the flames that were a signature in his
sculpture. That's how I think of him _ as one of his own noble
figures, silently rising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
