<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      01-06 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING EVIL; ANIMAL MAGNETISM; BRET LOTT'S LOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The romanticization of evil has become an increasingly
disturbing feature of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a commendable attempt to see the world in all its
gray complexity and ambiguity has gone, in the wrong hands, to
indefensible extremes. Too many filmmakers or writers have applied
a patina of glamour to monstrous crimes, and too many academics
have championed ``wrongly convicted'' sociopaths, secure in the
belief they will never have to live with the consequences of their
words and images.
</P>
<P>
   The evil-is-cool crowd might find it instructive to read the
January issue of The Atlantic Monthly, in which Roger Shattuck
lucidly deconstructs the moral implications of a ``blindness to
history'' that has ``spawned overwhelming state terrorism'' twice
during this century.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck does so in an intriguing way. Since we absorb our ideas
about evil from what we read and see, he enunciates four categories
of evil and examines the ways they have been filtered into our
consciousness by such authors as Baudelaire, Hawthorne, Pascal,
Emerson, and Nietzsche, along with (vastly) lesser figures like
Quentin Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck is enlightening on the very different ways Dostoevski
and Chekhov wrestled with the concept of evil, and persuasive when
he argues that the movie ``Pulp Fiction'' is ``complicit with the
criminal violence it depicts.'' He argues that Clarence Darrow, in
defending Leopold and Loeb, advanced a line of reasoning devoid of
``any guiding principles of good and evil, sanity and madness,
innocence and guilt.'' Shattuck does not say, because he does not
have to, how that kind of reasoning has corroded our judicial
system today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Birds do it, bees do it, even scorpion flies do it: flirting.
</P>
<P>
   Psychology Today reports that the come-hither glances and body
language of flirtation evolved from our evolutionary ancestors'
need to ``quickly and safely (judge) the value of potential mates''
by gauging their health and reproductive fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Flirting, says writer Joann Ellison Rodgers, is ``wired into
us.'' Like pheasant spurs and lion manes, it is designed ``to
advertise ourselves to the opposite sex.'' It turns out that the
human male's approach to flirting _ studied by psychologists who
``spent months in dimly lit lounges documenting these flirtation
rituals'' _ closely resembles that of a baboon.
</P>
<P>
   That information may not come as news to many women. In fact, as
with a lot of psychological research, some of the findings Rodgers
writes about are not exactly jaw-droppers. For instance, we might
have been able to guess that attractive people have more sex
partners. But there are some intriguing tidbits here. Who knew that
the across-a-crowded-room moment of attraction ``mimics a kind of
brain damage''? And who would have imagined that lookism flourishes
even in the insect world, where scorpion flies choose mates
according to how symmetrical their prospective partners' wings are?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bret Lott enjoyed early success as a writer, publishing two
novels and a short story collection by the time he was 30. Then
Lott began to encounter systematic rejection from publishers _ one
book was turned down 12 times _ and his faith in his ability began
slipping away. Like many another novelist, he began asking himself
the big question: ``Why write at all?''
</P>
<P>
   In Poets &AMP; Writers magazine, Lott describes his journey through
authorial limbo and back to publication. His story may have a happy
ending, but he makes clear exactly why constant rejection can be a
career-ender for writers: because it shakes ``the confidence
necessary to make language new, to step into the void of the blank
page and create.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott writes that ``this deadening of one's gift by learning not
to believe in it is the most dangerous time in the life of the
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Also worth reading in Poets &AMP; Writers is Dan Wakefield's warm
and perceptive reminiscence of James Baldwin, whom he got to know
in the Greenwich Village of the '50s. Wakefield's assessment of
Baldwin as a writer is enriched by his knowledge of Baldwin as a
man. Baldwin apparently had a lasting effect on those he met: Lott,
too, cites a Baldwin remark as an influence on his writing life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wired takes a close look at Salon, which was launched three
years ago as an on-line magazine focusing on literary culture but
has recently waded into the Washington political wars with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Salon has been rewarded for its saturation coverage of the
Clinton/Lewinsky story with massive increases in page views. The
Webzine even got denounced by Republican congressmen as a tool of
the Clinton White House when it published the story of the
three-decade-old infidelities of Judiciary Committee chairman Henry
Hyde. Now, luxuriating in the resulting notoriety and limelight,
Salon editor and CEO David Talbot is trying to turn Salon into what
Wired writer Warren St. John calls a ``global media giant.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John paints an intriguing portrait of Talbot as
half-idealist, half-opportunist, a new-media entrepreneur who may
become the William Randolph Hearst of the on-line world, or may
fall victim to the contradictory goals he has established. ``Salon
. . . has become a confusion of impulses _ a high-minded tabloid
that wants respect but needs buzz,'' writes Talbot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
