<HEADLINE>
EXPORTERS HAIL THE ARRIVAL OF THE EURO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aided by Europe's new single currency, Quaker Fabric Corp.'s
brocades, twills, and chenilles may one day cover as many couches
on the continent as they now do in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to European furniture makers currently represent a
sliver of the sales of upholstery fabrics woven at the company's
Fall River mill, which supplies Broyhill, Ethan Allen, and other
American furniture makers.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Liebenow views conversion to a single currency, the
euro, as a boon to Quaker Fabric's ability to compete aggressively
with European textile companies on their turf. With a common
currency upon which to value products, the company will be able to
zero in on competitive local prices for its wares, whether selling
in Austria or Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The bustle surrounding the biggest currency conversion ever
seems to have barely rippled on US shores. In truth, American
exporters like Quaker Fabric have been grappling for months with
how to respond to the currency conversion _ one that was years in
the making, often seemed near failure and then, on Jan. 1, suddenly
came into existence.
</P>
<P>
   With the euro barely in place, exporters say that they already
see far more advantages than disadvantages to a single-currency
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Euro-pricing ``may accelerate sales,'' said Quaker's Liebenow,
who is chief executive. ``If we're able to price in the euro, that
will in essence make us almost the same as if we were manufactured
in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Euro coins and bills won't be issued until Jan. 1, 2002, after a
three-year transition. Business is a different matter: Transactions
in euros are now permitted, including credit card purchases.
Traveler's checks denominated in euros are also available.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the 11 countries _ Austria, Belgium, Finland, France,
Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Spain, and
Portugal _ agreed to unify their monetary systems, US companies are
under pressure to unify European operations to stay abreast of
European competitors that do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you can expect is increased competition for a lot of
products in Europe, because it's going to be much more a one-market
(system) than it is now,'' said Michiel van der Lof, a senior
manager for Ernst &AMP; Young in New York and member of the firm's euro
group that consults to clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``No compulsion, no prohibition'' is the unofficial guideline
heard throughout Europe to describe the transition. Essentially,
this means businesses are not required to use euros _ nor can they
refuse payment in euro terms.
</P>
<P>
   Some American companies view being ``euro-ready'' as a marketing
tool. Some as a survival strategy. If, for example, a European
customer wants to pay prices based on euro values, the business may
comply _ or lose a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a legal perspective they have until 2002. But from a
client perspective they don't have until 2002 at all,'' van der Lof
said.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is banks, which are required to offer customers'
bank balances in both local currency and the euro. They must also
offer euro checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for a day when all transactions are in euros, Bud
Robertson, chief financial officer of Bedford-based Progress
Software Corp., set up a ``dual system'' for billing customers in
euro and local currency terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be in business in Europe, you have to have
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But increased cross-border competition worries some businesses,
because it will make comparison shopping easier for buyers. These
businesses have used currency differences to disguise higher prices
for their products in some countries.
</P>
<P>
   A new car may cost 17,000 euros in Spain (about $20,000 based on
an exchange rate of 1.17 euros per dollar) and 19,000 euros
($22,230) in Germany. In that case, a Berliner might be willing to
travel to Spain to save 2000 euros. That, in turn, would force
Berlin _ and all German _ car dealers to lower their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Similiar pressures are expected, over time, to level prices of
everything from Gillette razors to Polaroid film or The Economist
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist ``is twice as much in Austria as it is in
Portugal. Austrians are wealthier and they're willing to pay
more,'' said David Currie, a professor of economics at the London
Business School. With euro-pricing, it will ``be harder to sustain
those price differences, and that means a hit on the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   But exporters in Massachusetts, which shipped nearly $4 billion
in goods to the 11 countries embracing the euro, welcome the
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro is going to be fantastic,'' predicted Robert
Giegerich, vice president of worldwide marketing for Cynosure Inc.
Nearly one-third of the Chelmsford company's $37 million in annual
sales of lasers, which are used in cosmetic surgery, are in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Since lasers are listed in dollars, Cynosure translates each
sale to the customer's local currency. The euro will be much
simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I had to remember pesetas. I had to remember francs
and marks and lira. What was bad is the customer wants to pay 1.7
million lira. It means $120,000 on some days _ it means $110,000 on
others,'' Giegerich said. With the euro, on any given day, ``I can
now compare Spain to Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the old system allowed customers to use exchange rate
moves to their advantage, he said. If the local currency
depreciated against the dollar, causing the buyers' effective price
to rise, customers might bargain for a better deal before buying.
Rarely would they offer to pay more if their currency strengthened,
increasing their buying power.
</P>
<P>
   The euro is expected to be far more stable than individual
currencies, thus reducing Cynosure's exchange-rate risk.
Large-volume currencies are typically more stable. The volume of
trading in the euro is expected to eventually be second only to the
US dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Such firms as Quaker Fabric believe it will be easier to
undercut competitors' prices if they all are working in euros.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye to raising its profile in Europe _ which accounts
for only 4 percent of annual sales of $220 million _ Quaker Fabric
opened a distribution center two years ago outside of Rotterdam,
the Netherlands, to house Massachusetts-made fabrics for fast
delivery to customers on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that over the next several years our highest growth
rate will come from the international markets, including Europe,''
Liebenow said. The euro ``will be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   For American or European retailers and manufacturers, increased
competition could also mean lower prices for supplies and raw
materials purchased on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kuna, vice president of finance for Staples International
in London, which operates stores in the United Kingdom and Germany,
said it will be easier for Staples to comparison shop for the best
price of, say, pens. If a Dutch pen supplier isn't willing to meet
his price, a German one might.
</P>
<P>
   Although Staples plans a slow conversion to the euro, Kuna said,
the ``challenge will confront us in the not-too-distant future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
