<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC STORMS BATTER SOME NATIONS; OTHERS SEE RAINBOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Economics has been called the dismal science, but
the past year has been a study in downright cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter of the world slipped into recession, and yet the US
economy continued its long-running expansion. Collapsing commodity
prices hurt a range of developing nations, while keeping prices low
for gleeful US consumers. Renewed poverty brought riots to
Indonesia and mayhem to Russia, while Europe set aside its
divisions to embrace a common currency and to pave the way for new
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has the distance between the world's haves and have-nots
been so starkly demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   Now analysts are forecasting a modest improvement in some of the
economic trouble spots of the world, but they warn that
unpredictable forces could arise. ``We continue to see significant
risks, risks that are overall for the world economy predominantly
on the downside,'' Flemming Larsen of the International Monetary
Fund's research department said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, which has orchestrated massive bailouts for five
nations, last month said the world economy would grow 2.2 percent
in 1999, a downgrade from the 2.5 percent growth it forecast in
September. Growth last year was also 2.2 percent, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank has been even less optimistic, predicting growth
of 1.9 percent this year.. It said 1998 growth was 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the predictions will be political developments in two
troubled nations: Japan, the world's second-largest economy, and
Brazil, the largest economy in South America. But there are
troubles elsewhere, as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The economy declined by between 2 percent and 2.5 percent last
year, the second full year of recession in Japan. But a midyear
election prompted government leaders to take several steps toward
improvement, at least in name.
</P>
<P>
   They approved a spending package of about $200 billion to spur
economic activity, on top of previous packages of nearly equal
size. They also set aside about $500 billion to clean up the
troubled banking sector.
</P>
<P>
   But many doubt that the government will follow through on these
plans or that the money will be used well.
</P>
<P>
   The $200 billion spending plan is actually worth about half that
amount, because of various accounting maneuvers, said Rick Katz, an
economist and author of ``Japan: The System that Soured.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is the question about which public works will
really take place,'' Katz said, noting that the cooperation of
financially-pressed local governments is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many analysts say that Japan's banking solution is
inadequate. They say it merely gives money to banks to write off
the bad loans they made on half-used factories, over-valued
apartment buildings and the like. Instead, the critics say, the
government should force banks to sell off these over-valued assets
at their true value.
</P>
<P>
   Under a worst-case scenario, Japan could watch its reforms
stumble and a major bank fail. That would kill consumer confidence
and prompt banks to cut back on loans, further slowing economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Many forecasters predict the economy will contract by 0.5
percent in 1999, but Nariman Behravesh, chief international
economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in Lexington, said the decline
could be as high as 2.5 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Asia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a horrendous year, the signs look good for three nations
that agreed to IMF rescue packages: Thailand, South Korea, and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   In Korea, a banking cleanup has met some success. As a result,
investors have stopped dumping currency, allowing banks to lower
the interest rates that had been raised sky-high to keep currency
in the country. And exports to the United States from all three
nations are rising, partly because prices are low as a result of
their battered currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's economy will grow 1 percent this year, after
shrinking 8 percent last year. The Philippines will grow 2.5
percent, after contracting by 0.6 percent, the IMF predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF says South Korea will still contract this year, by 1
percent, but its performance will be better than the 7 percent
decline of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, which has seen rioting in recent months that led to a
change in political leadership, and Malaysia, which moved to limit
the role of foreign investors in its economy, face deeper problems.
Indonesia will contract 3.4 percent in 1999, after a devastating 15
percent fall in economic output last year, the IMF says.
</P>
<P>
   The economies of India and China have been relatively isolated
from the worst effects of the Asian financial crisis. The IMF
predicts solid growth for both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia is not out of the tunnel yet,'' said Behravesh. ``But it
looks like the light at the end of the tunnel is really the end of
the tunnel, and not a train.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Latin America &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's problems continue. Despite reaching agreement on a $42
billion IMF bailout, the Brazilian government has at times shown
itself unwilling to approve tough austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is forecasting a 1 percent fall in economic activity.
But Michael Mussa, the IMF chief economist, recently said that he
would not be surprised if the agency revises that number downward
in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil accounts for half of economic activity in Latin America,
excluding Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the region are expected to post solid growth next year.
Behravesh says Mexico will grow by 2.5 percent after 4.4 percent
growth in 1998. The IMF sees even greater growth for Mexico, and it
says most economies in the region will continue to expand. One
possible exception is Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity prices could force economists to revise the estimates.
Falling oil prices have hurt Venezuela, Mexico, and Ecuador, but
they have helped Argentina, an oil importer. Chile has been hit
hard by falling copper prices. Continued price decreases would hurt
the exporting nations even more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Falling oil prices have crippled Russia, where the financial
meltdown could well get worse. The IMF predicts that economic
output will shrink 8.3 percent this year, worse than the crippling
5.7 percent drop of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation could surge to 56 percent, more than double the 26
percent forecast for 1998. Analysts believe it is likely that
investors will pull even more money from Russian banks and
businesses, further hurting the economy. Many say the government
has done little to improve the banks or fix the notoriously lax
tax-collection system. These problems, combined with a currency
devaluation last year and a government default on some debts, have
stripped investor confidence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Europe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Britain refusing to join, 11 European nations launch the
euro this year, which over time could provide an economic boost. A
single currency is expected to make transactions more efficient and
ease trade. It might also force companies to compete squarely on
costs, as comparisons among goods will no longer be complicated by
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that might be more wishful thinking on the part of the
Europeans,'' Behravesh said. ``And the effect may not be felt for
several years.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Union countries are expected to grow by 2.2 percent
this year. Even Central and Eastern Europe are forecast to do well,
excluding Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
