<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' STRATEGY IS A REAL DRAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amateur Night continues at Foxboro.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better way to describe the events unfolding within
the Patriots organization, events that are consistent with what has
gone on with the team since Bill Parcells left town.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: They say they are going to take three weeks to
decide whether Pete Carroll should be head coach next year.
</P>
<P>
   They've known the guy for two years, have seen him in operation,
and they still don't know whether he should coach the team?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and his assistants are being held hostage, while Bob and
Jonathan Kraft, with recommendations from team vice presidents
Bobby Grier and Andy Wasynczuk, write up reports.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the way things are done at Harvard Business
School, but not in the National Football League, where great head
coaches, like Hall of Fame quarterbacks, are a rare commodity.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the man with the best winning percentage in NFL
history, George Seifert, signed on with Carolina. That means,
obviously, that he is not available to New England, should the plug
be pulled on Carroll. Seifert reportedly was the man the Patriots
wanted instead of Carroll when Parcells opted for the New York Jets
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in the league would say that the two most
outstanding coaches available this offseason were Seifert and Mike
Holmgren. Holmgren said Tuesday that he will decide within a week
whether to leave Green Bay. He has plans to visit Seattle _ where
many think he will end up _ Baltimore, and Philadelphia. One friend
of Holmgren's said Tuesday, ``He and his family are headed for
Seattle. They are going to offer him something like $4.5 million a
year, and he will probably sign the deal right away.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the Patriots are busy writing those important (give me
a break) reports, they will have missed the chance to go after the
two best coaching prospects out there.
</P>
<P>
   While the study class is in session in Foxborough, Holmgren will
be shopping, and the teams looking for head coaches _ San Diego,
Seattle, Baltimore, Philly, Chicago, and Cleveland _ also will be
talking to the rest of the so-called ``candidates'': Brian Billick
of Minnesota, Jim Haslett of Pittsburgh, Terry Donahue of UCLA, and
two recently fired coaches, Dom Capers of Carolina and Dave
Wannstedt of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The guessing at the moment is that Holmgren goes to Seattle;
Steve Mariucci leaves San Francisco and goes to Cleveland when the
49ers' season ends; Billick winds up in San Francisco to fill that
vacancy; and the rest of the teams with openings get to pick over
the remains.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it is grossly unfair to keep around an assistant coach for
three weeks if he is eventually going to get fired. Last year
offensive coordinator Larry Kennan would have had two chances to
get another job before he learned that Ernie Zampese was being
brought in to replace him. By the time he left Foxborough, there
were no other jobs open.
</P>
<P>
   To quote one AFC general manager on the Patriots' strategy:
``What they are doing is the dumbest (expletive) thing I have ever
heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Coughlin knows his Jaguars face an uphill battle against the
Jets in New Jersey Sunday. ``They have great execution,'' said the
Jacksonville coach. ``Over the last six games, they have played
extremely well. This looks like a Bill Parcells team. Penalties are
limited. No turnovers. Everything is done with efficiency.
Offensively, they are difficult to deal with because they have so
many weapons and Vinny Testaverde is on a roll. You look at their
defense and you don't see any holes. Nothing stands out that you
can really exploit. And their kicking game is excellent. The
addition of Dave Meggett is a plus for them. Any team that can beat
its toughest three division opponents the final three games of the
season, and two of them on the road, is playing at a high level.''
. . . Parcells on Jacksonville, after viewing film: ``Their offense
will be very hard to deal with. This kid (Fred) Taylor is some kind
of runner. Two hundred and thirty pounds, with blazing speed. He
can make plays every time he touches the ball. The two wide
receivers (Jimmy Smith and Keenan McCardell) are outstanding, and
(Pete) Mitchell, the tight end, is a good receiver. The two tackles
(Tony Boselli and Leon Searcy) are special, two of the best in the
league. Defensively, they have played very well the last two games,
shutting down New England and Pittsburgh in two games they needed
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Jimmy Johnson wrote a letter to Doug Flutie Tuesday
apologizing for jumping on a box of Flutie Flakes in the
celebration last Saturday after the Dolphins beat the Buffalo Bills
in an AFC playoff game. ``Jimmy didn't mean any harm,'' said
Dolphins public relations director Harvey Greene. ``It was just
done for fun. There is no way he wanted to demean anyone. He knew
it was being filmed for NFL Films, so he just went along with it.
Jimmy has a great deal of respect for Flutie and would never do
anything to hurt him in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
