<SLUG> BC-WOM-HAYDENETTES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRECISE ONN THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALPOLE, Mass. _ Most of the time, the skaters remind you of the
Rockettes on ice, all grace and smiles and locked arms. But then
the 20 young women will suddenly break into two groups and hurtle
themselves toward each other at what seems like warp speed and you
cringe the way you did when Ulf Samuelsson slammed into Cam Neely.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no collision, no crunch. Instead, one group splices
itself through the other, never slowing and showing no fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very skilled at this level,'' said coach Lynn Benson.
``They know where they need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' are the Haydenettes, a synchronized skating team named
after their home rink in Lexington, Mass. and long considered
perhaps the best precision squad in the nation. Winners of nine
national championships and often placing in the top three in
international competition, the team will be among 17 in three
divisions competing Thursday through Saturday at the Citizens Bank
Snowflake International Synchronized Skating Competition in Warwick
and Providence, R.I., hosted by the Warwick Figure Skaters.
</P>
<P>
   Benson founded the Haydenettes in 1979 after watching many of
the singles skaters she coached leave the sport at 14 or 15 when
they started to realize the odds against becoming the next Dorothy
Hamill. Now 49, Benson was once a national-level competitor and
later skated with the Ice Capades. ``I remembered just loving
skating for the precision team,'' she said after leading a
four-hour practice the morning of New Year's Eve. ``I thought, this
is a way of getting those kids at Hayden to keep skating. It's such
a shame to quit. This is another area where they can keep skating
at a high international level.''
</P>
<P>
   Although still in the publicity shadows of singles and pairs
skating and not yet in the Olympics, the synchronized version of
the sport is the fastest-growing of the five disciplines under the
auspices of the United States Figure Skating Association, with more
than 400 teams and 7,200 athletes in this country alone. In
competition, teams of 12 to 20 skaters perform complex programs at
up to 25 miles per hour, sometimes with their legs outstretched and
skate blades aimed directly at each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would never give those maneuvers to kids who aren't strong
skaters,'' said Benson. ``They'd kill themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some synchronized skaters are quite strong individually
but, either because of body type (there aren't many 5-foot, 1-inch
jumping beans among the 25 members rehearsing this day at Iorio
Arena), personality type, or both, gravitate toward team
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity to share everything with everybody
else and to succeed personally,'' said 17-year-old Sharon Liff, who
began skating when she was 4 and moved up through the ranks to the
Haydenettes after she turned 14, the minimum age. ``You want to do
well for yourself, but also for your coaches and the other people
on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   That camaraderie, said Benson, is the biggest difference between
singles and synchronized. ``It was almost isolated, in a way,''
said Benson of her singles career. ``I had friends, but I never had
anybody who wanted me to win as much as they wanted to win. We have
24 people who want you to skate your very best out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't? After all, a mistake by one skater during a
20-person routine affects the other 19; a fall sends the judges'
scores plummeting for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have thought this,'' said Benson, of the
reaction. ``Usually, she is surrounded by the other girls saying,
oh, that's OK, don't worry about it. Every girl knows how easy it
is to catch an edge, or that the girl who falls isn't always the
one who causes the fall. I would never have guessed that. I would
have thought, boy, whoever falls are they going to get it in the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   But the amount of consoling is in direct proportion to the
overall diligence of the unfortunate performer. ``If the skater who
fell is one who hasn't shown up for rehearsals,'' said Benson,
''then it doesn't go like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not something that happens often on the Haydenettes, which
last year finished fifth out of 19 teams at the World Challenge Cup
in France, the top international tournament in the sport. In 1996
and 1997, they placed fourth. The group also skates frequently in
exhibitions, such as Harvard's annual ``An Evening With
Champions,'' and has often performed on television, including a
segment last week on the ``Today Show'' from the outdoor rink at
Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   After the competition in Providence this week, the team will
travel next month to Rouen for the French Cup, which they won in
1997, and hopes to again represent the United States at the World
Cup in April in Goteborg, Sweden. The first official World
Championship in the sport will be held in 2000, in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is pretty amazing to Benson, who 20 years ago had
to scratch for 45 minutes a week of ice time to practice for a
sport that had few rules and less structure. ``If anybody had ever
told me it was going to be an international sport, I would never
have guessed,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   How the team has lasted long enough to see the evolution may
have something to do with Benson's attitude: the process is more
important than the result, the only realistic goals are those that
can be met, the idea is to work hard but enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   All three philosophies helped the Haydenettes through their
first competition two decades ago, just months after they were
formed. Benson didn't want the girls to be disappointed, so she
announced that their goal was not to come in last.
</P>
<P>
   When they finished seventh out of nine teams, Benson recalled,
``you saw all the girls and myself jumping up and down, we were so
happy. Someone came up and said, they were seventh. I think they
thought we read it wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
