<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARIONETTE-OPERA-BOS &LR;      01-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIONETTE-OPERA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARTSTRINGS IN CINDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETERBOROUGH, N.H. _ Thick sheets of ice coated the plush red
seats where audiences once watched performances, icicles hung from
rails and rafters, and broken glass and charred debris littered the
sooty stage.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Leach stood amid the rubble of the New England Marionette
Opera, which was destroyed by a New Year's Day electrical fire, and
wondered what would be next for himself and the theater he founded
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   All he managed to save were some books on puppetry, a sewing
machine, a few marionette parts, and one badly burned marionette _
Escamillo, the bullfighter in the opera, ``Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Leach and his troupe of puppeteers are trying to tally their
losses, assess the significance of what they created, and decide
where they go from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I had was in this theater,'' said Leach, 56,
fingering a velvet stage curtain that broke like ribbon candy in
his hand. ``Everything I made, I put back into it . . . Where do I
start again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get over losing 200 kids,'' said Roger DuPen 32,
the theater's artistic director, referring to the more than 200
marionette characters that burned in the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time making and molding them, and the
puppeteers brought them to life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work with marionettes long enough, they become little
humans with their own personalities,'' DuPen said. ``This is like
multiple deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the theater was the only one of its kind in the
Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe the fire began in the theater
basement sometime New Year's Day morning. Leach was in the control
room on an upper balcony, editing video footage from a recent
production of ``Porgy and Bess.'' He smelled smoke but kept
editing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the smoke became more pervasive, Leach left the control room
and made his way through the blackened theater and out a fire door.
Then he ran to Roy's, a small grocery store nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call 911,'' he yelled to a startled clerk shortly after noon.
``I'm on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   It took firefighters 28 hours to contain the three-alarm blaze,
which continued to burn in the theater's trap doors, hollow walls,
and innumerable crevices. A small fire erupted in the attic Tuesday
morning, but it was quickly extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   The building was insured, ``but we'll take a big hit,'' Leach
said, because so many of the losses are incalculable. It took at
least 10 days to make each of the more than 200 marionettes used in
the nine operas that the company performed, and a year to develop
each different show, Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   Leach launched the New England Marionette Opera after being
captivated by the marionette opera in Salzburg, Austria. He had
never seen a puppet show before, but he liked opera and thought the
combination made opera accessible to a wider audience and also
provided an unusual creative edge.
</P>
<P>
   As DuPen explained, with marionettes performing to recorded
music, ``audiences didn't have to deal with the persona on stage,
they could get straight into the characters and the story line. It
wasn't Pavarotti, it was Lt. Pinkerton or Rudolfo.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a scale model designed by DuPen, they constructed a
theater scaled to puppet proportions in a converted Baptist Church
on Peterborough's Main Street. They made their own sets and props
and marionettes, with costuming help from designers like Masako
Hayashi, who had worked for the Boston Opera Company and the New
York City Opera.
</P>
<P>
   They found puppeteers among teachers, musicians, writers,
editors, and circus performers, united by a love of theater.
</P>
<P>
   And they gave 80 to 100 performances a year to audiences,
primarily adult, that typically filled about 85 percent of the
theater, Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   Marionette opera has been popular for ages in Europe, but it was
a hard sell in the United States. ``Opera is not an acquired
American taste, and people think marionettes are for kids,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To make opera more appealing, Leach used surtitles _ English
translations projected above the stage _ and shortened the
productions to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly four years, the theater has made a profit. In 1996,
the company embarked on its first international tour. In 1998, it
performed for three weeks at the Emerson Majestic Theater in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exhilarating,'' said Karen Carter, 40, a puppeteer from
Lyndeborough, N.H., whose parts included the lead character in
``Tosca,'' and Rosina in ``The Barber of Seville.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing else like this in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say what they'll do next, Leach and DuPen said.
Followers have sent many messages of support, saying they hope the
opera will rebuild in Peterborough or perhaps find a new base in
Boston. But for now, the company is still grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still riding something, maybe denial,'' Leach said. ``I'm
moving ahead. I just don't know where I'm headed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
