<HEADER>
A1254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HN     01-06 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Jan. 6, 1998    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Democratic senators reject any
need for witnesses at President Clinton's trial, but members of the
Republican majority say witnesses should be heard. The Republicans
continue to haggle over how to conduct the historic Senate trial
that starts Thursday. The White House predicts victory, regardless
of the trial's format. By JUDY HOLLAND and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CASE (Washington)_ In a full Senate trial, House
``managers'' would present arguments for the perjury and
obstruction-of-justice articles of impeachment against President
Clinton that the House approved last month. The White House would
try to demolish their arguments. We outline the case each side
would make. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUMER-POTHOLE (Washington) _ Even before Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., is sworn in as his state's junior senator, he shakes loose
$500,000 in federal highway funds for Ogdensburg, a small upstate
town. Schumer makes it clear he will be another ``Senator
Pothole,'' caring for his constituents' needs, just as his
predecessor Alfonse D'Amato was. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ A look at the parallels between
the impeachment trials of Presidents Andrew Johnson in 1868 and
Bill Clinton today. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
