<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREERS-PEARLS-HNS &LR;      01-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-PEARLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE THE WORLD YOUR OYSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Many workers deprive themselves of success
because they're too skeptical to set goals and lack the confidence
to move up, says a CEO and author of a new book on career planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times when you hear that talk about specific plans and
specific goals, you say, `That's for the business world. That's for
the professional world. That's not for me,''' said Eleanor Jacobs,
president and CEO of the United Way of Santa Clara County and
author of the recently published ``Ten Pearls of Wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said her life changed after she read a self-help book in
1971 and realized how much control she had over her life _ once she
started setting goals and taking action to achieve them. In her
book, she tells people to set the goals and then spend at least 15
minutes a day thinking about the goals and her 10 pearls:
</P>
<P>
   _ Believe. Have the attitude that you can do whatever you set
your mind to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember. Write a list of your achievements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decide. Choose a specific goal you want to work on first.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan. Determine what specific steps you need to take to
achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Actuate. Get moving. Start taking the steps you've identified.
</P>
<P>
   _ Habituate. Take at least one action on your plan each day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pretend. Imagine how you will be once you achieve your goal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refine. Using the image of yourself as you're achieving your
goal, smooth out any bumps that might be in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Claim. Have the deep-down feeling that you deserve the
success.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expand. Once you have achieved your smaller goals, aim at
bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start with something small,'' Jacobs said in an interview.
``Start with something fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jacobs' case, she always had trouble finding any affordable
clothes she liked in her size, but she found that she was very good
at following hunches. So she went into the Stix, Baer &AMP; Fuller
store near St. Louis, where she grew up, with the goal that she
would find the right dress. She did.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' she wrote, ``day by day, week by week, month by
month and year by year, I continued to set a goal, pay attention to
my instincts and gut feelings, follow that guidance, achieve the
goal, and move on to the next one. I began to see myself
differently, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer did I feel at the mercy of circumstance or fate. I
began to realize that I could mold and shape circumstances to my
own personal desires.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of her challenge was going back to college, even though she
was in her 20s and older than most students. The whole idea of
going for a bachelor's degree and then a master's in social work
from St. Louis University sounded intimidating for someone who had
gone out into the working world after just one year of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath all of that,'' she said in the interview, ``there
was that tiny internal voice that I allowed to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   She recommends writing your goals _ ``The action of writing
makes it stick with you'' _ and, for career-related goals, paying
particular attention to the pearls of believe and claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down within yourself, feel that you deserve that job,''
Jacobs said. ``Feel that you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't see yourself deserving that job, she said, think
about what is blocking you. Is there some skill you're lacking that
the job demands? ``The specifics will bubble up _ the specifics
that you feel you need to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   With career goals more than with most others, Jacobs said it is
crucial to do research, whether by reading or asking others. People
often find that the career they're aiming at might not really be
the one best suited for them, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs realizes there are roadblocks to success within society,
but those aren't the biggest hurdles for people to overcome. ``I
think we stop ourselves a lot more than something stops us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any rich uncle,'' she said. ``I didn't have an
`in' with the academic people who helped me. What I had was belief
and action.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you get yourself headed in the right direction, however,
you will find there is help, Jacobs added. ``People will begin to
give you advice. They will mentor you. Then it opens up.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that people will experience setbacks along the way, but
urges them to reduce the ``wallowing time'' when something goes
wrong. ``It's so easy to succumb to the negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said that whenever you make goal-setting or something
else _ good or bad _ a habit, it becomes easy for you to follow
that pattern. That can happen when people become hopeless and begin
constantly complaining about their career and life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't hold yourself away,'' she warned. ``Don't automatically
exclude yourself from getting promoted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
