   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH and CONGRESS &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories on impeachment and
the convening of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Developments as Congress convenes and
begins to grapple with impeachment questions: Caucuses argue over
what kind of trial to have in Senate and how disruptive Democrats
should be in the House. Managers re-appointed. By Alison Mitchell.
(1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ A grim scene as both houses open
their '99 session with the impeachment trial dwarfing all other
agendas. Party dueling in the Senate ; House games, plus the usual
fresh chaos. By Francis X. Clines. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LOTT (Washington) _ Sen. Lott, the Republican majority
leader, and his party wrestle over impeachment issues, with
concerns over their duty, their political future and their strong
feelings about Clinton. By Eric Schmitt. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR (Washington) _ New documents give a view of the
arguments from both the White House and from Kenneth Starr's office
on the investigation into accusations that the Starr illegally
leaked grand jury evidence. By Neil A. Lewis. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE (Washington) _ A new speaker is elected and makes his
first speech; House gets down to its bristling agenda and fights
about rules. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-HASTERT (Washington) _ A Man-in-the-News profile of Rep.
Dennis Hastert, the new speaker. Soon there may be a new Washington
trivia question: Who was the speaker between Gingrich and Gephardt?
Yes, he's pleasant, but that may not be enough to keep the job. By
Lizette Alvarez. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ETHICS (Washington) _ The first order of business in
the new Congress will be to tinker with the ethics rules, making
them a little easier on staff and harder on outside consultants to
Congress. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-NY (Washington) _ The new faces in the New York and
other Northeast delegations take their new jobs; N.Y.'s Sen.
Schumer holds his first press conference. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER GOVERNMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE (Washington) _ Leaders of the federal advisory panel
propose major changes in Medicare. By Robert Pear. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILES (Washington) _ The Cox committee investigating
technology transfers to China may be extended today. Questions over
how White House is handling report. By Jeff Gerth. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SURPLUS (Washington) _ President Clinton and Vice
President Gore announce the budget surplus is even greater than
forecast, thanks to the booming economy. That will make it even
more difficult to avoid spending extra money on new programs. By
Richard W. Stevenson. (825 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE-STATES (Boston) _ A dozen states have already ended
parole and replaced it with judges setting specific sentences, a
proposal that has now been put forward by New York's Gov. Pataki.
By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   (See also NY-PATAKI, below)
</P>
<P>
   MD-CLOGGED-COURTS (Baltimore) _ Murder charges were dismissed
against four defendants here, because their trial was postponed
repeatedly, often because no courtroom space was available. The
ruling was based on a recent decision by the state Court of Special
Appeals, which threw out the sex crime conviction of a man because
his case had been postponed nine times for lack of a courtroom. By
Michael Janofsky. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK REGION &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PATAKI (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. Pataki delivers the State of the
State Message, which is expected to center on criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   CT-ROWLAND (Hartford, Conn.) _ Gov. Rowland is inaugurated for
his second term. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECT (Dateline to kum) _ Developments out of the U.N.
and Washington on reports that U.N. arms inspectors had a role in
U.S. electronic spying in Iraq. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FRANCE (Paris) _ The French prime minister criticizes the
U.S. for attacks on Iraq and says France will present a new plan
soon. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Saying ``Netanyahu is dangerous to
Israel,'' another military man, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, formally
enters the race for prime minister under the banner of a centrist
party. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-UNREST (Cairo, Egypt) _ President Khatami praises the
Intelligence Ministry for an ``honest'' investigation into
killings; some see chance for Khatami, a moderate, to exert more
control over security forces. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ Political crisis deepens as Prime
Minister-designate gives up on trying to form new government. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EDWARD (London) _ Royal wedding bells to ring here
again: Prince Edward is to marry his longtime girlfriend, Sophie
Rhys-Jones. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow industrial average breaks above
9,400. At midday, it was up 124 points, or 1.3 percent, at
9.434.75. The Nasdaq index was up 45 points, or 2 percent.
Elsewhere, prices rose 1.8 percent in Tokyo and 3.5 percent in Hong
Kong. They rose 3.4 percent in Frankfurt, 3.1 percent in London and
2.5 percent in Brazil. They declined 0.4 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was down 2/32 point, with the
yield at 5.21. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T may say in an SEC filing today that it is
changing its plans for meshing its operations with those of
Tele-Communications Inc., which it is acquiring. With the change,
the target company's cable operation will be kept distinct from
AT&AMP;T's core long-distance business by being grouped in a
``tracking'' stock with AT&AMP;T's wireless operations.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The government's last witness
in the Microsoft trial, Franklin M. Fisher, an economist at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, continues on the stand. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   GRUMMAN-WARNING (Undated) _ Northrop Grumman issues more bad
news. It says profit in 1999 will miss estimates by as much as 20
percent because sales are slumping more than it forecast a month
ago. It cites Boeing's production cuts. Northrop also says it is
taking pretax charges of $125 million for the 1998 fourth quarter
to reflect increased costs of building the fuselage for Boeing's
747 aircraft and to reflect delays in completing tests for an
infrared countermeasure system for the American and British
military. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   CABLETRON (Undated) _ Folo on reports that Cabletron has put
itself up for sale and is seeking a premium of 66 percent above its
stock price, which today is up as much as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Wrapping up the industry's December
reports, General Motors releases sales data. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ICG-MINDSPRING (Undated) _ICG Communications sells assets of its
Netcom unit to Mindspring Enterprises for $245 million in cash and
stock. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH-GUCCI (Rome) _ LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton raises its
stake in Gucci to above 5 percent from 4.9 percent, prompting
speculation that it may make a takeover bid and sending Gucci
shares up more than 20 percent. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NISSAN (Tokyo) _ Nissan of Japan, continuing to shed
assets, sells a major portion of its textile-machinery subsidiary
to Toyoda Automatic Loom Works, the company that gave birth to
Nissan's chief rival, Toyota. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-REPORT (Undated) _ Walt Disney had ``too many'' films
last year that were not profitable because they were either
unpopular or their production and marketing costs were too high,
the company's chairman, Michael Eisner, says in a letter to
shareholders in Disney's annual report. Also today, Salomon Smith
Barney lowers its earnings forecast for Disney. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
