<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring joins Net giantswith $245 million acquisition
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MindSpring Enterprises joined the ranks of the giants of the
Internet today when it announced the planned purchase of the
domestic consumer base of Netcom from ICG Communications.
MindSpring will pay $215 million in cash as well as $30 million in
MindSpring stock in a deal worth $245 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call today, MindSpring Chairman Charles Brewer
and President Michael McQuary, the Atlanta-based Internet
provider's chief operating officer, talked about the challenges and
opportunities that now face the company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would give MindSpring about 400,000 individual customer
accounts as well as 3,000 commercial Internet accounts and 18,000
Web hosting customers. The acquisition of San Jose, Calif.-based
Netcom would more than double MindSpring's subscriber base and
place the company on a par in size with Internet giants such as
Earthlink, AT&AMP;T WorldNet and the Microsoft Network, which all claim
more than a million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is the nation's largest provider with 15 million
paid subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is subject to regulatory approval and is
expected to be completed during the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this acquisition will put MindSpring over the one
million dial-up subscriber mark,'' said Brewer, the company's
founder. ``It also makes us a larger and more credible spokesperson
and will help the company in its negotiations with cable and phone
companies for last-mile high-speed access as well as a more
attractive potential partner. ...This acquisition is consistent
with our mission to become a major player in the telecommunications
industry of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer also said MindSpring will benefit from having a presence
in Silicon Valley and cited increased marketing opportunities and
affiliations the company could now take advantage of, but he did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Netcom was the first Internet provider to cross the half-million
mark. It was founded in 1988. McQuary said the challenge is to
infuse Netcom, an Internet pioneer with flat subscriber growth,
into a growing company with the reputation for service and support
MindSpring is known for.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring stock was up 4 3/4 to 71 5/16 late this morning. ICG
was down 15/16 to 22 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
