<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     01-06 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Activities of the solons
 &HT;    (Eds: A bonus ShortTakes column this week; either this or the
one that moved yesterday may be used.)
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever else happens, the difficulties the Senate had in
setting up a simple impeachment trial are troubling. Events seem
headed toward a straight partisan vote. Hard-core Republicans would
like to see Bill Clinton hanged. Some senators virtually slaver to
play a role in a trial. House Republicans broadcast in plain
language the desire to see the Senate do their dirty work _ or
else.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Robert Byrd seems a special case. He has
re-emerged to assert the Senate's dubious dignity, quoting from
obscure and ancient Romans to make his point. (Flatulantus Maximus:
The Ethics of the Solons.)
</P>
<P>
   Two ideas keep emerging as irritants. The first is the What Will
We Tell Our Children Factor. What we tell our children, it seems to
me, is none of the Senate's, or House's, business. I can mislead my
heirs without the help of some congressional windbag.
</P>
<P>
   The second is the repeated assertion that ``The Senate is the
greatest deliberative body in the world.'' Who says? Now that we've
seen the Senate actually deliberate on the tube, we know its
opinions are every bit as various and as lame-brained as any of the
rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Spare us the self-congratulations. Keep government out of our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
