   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Daily news story as White House
warily watches trial negotiations in the Senate. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Senate members to get sworn in as
impeachment trial jurors on Thursday. Watching developments. (Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLEMENTS _ WASHINGTON _ Although Congress four years ago
restricted the authority of the Food and Drug Administration to
police the companies that make and sell vitamins and other dietary
``supplements,'' a new government data base will enable consumers
to do their own research on the products. The National Insititutes
of Health Office of Dietary Supplements unveils Wednesday an
Internet site (http://dietary-supplements.info.nih.gov) that
contains thousands of published scientific studies of the
increasingly popular alternative medicine supplements. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The federal antitrust trial of
Microsoft Corp. continues with the final government witness facing
cross-examination. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECONOMY _ BEIJING _ China, the world's fastest-growing
economy, stopped boasting about its two-decade-long ``economic
miracle'' on Wednesday and instead warned of hard times ahead as
the Asian economic crisis finally hits home. This unabashedly bleak
economic outlook for 1999 helps explain why President Jiang Zemin
issued dire warnings last month about the need to guarantee social
stability, saying any attempt to ``undermine'' order must be
``nipped in the bud.'' It also helps account for a security
crackdown, launched in November, that has sent at least 10
pro-democracy dissidents into prisons and labor camps for alleged
attempts to challenge the monopoly rule of the Communist Party.
(Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 2 p.m. EST in both the International and
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   STAMP _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The price of a first-class stamp
will rise to 33 cents on Sunday. Checking on other rates. (Donald,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-AGENDA _ ATLANTA _ Christian Coalition will announce
it's 1999 Georgia legislative agenda in a Wednesday press
conference in the Capitol rotunda in Atlanta. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-GAYS _ The Georgia Holocaust Commission asked that all
references to Nazi treatment of homosexuals during the Holocaust be
deleted in a teacher guide on the Holocaust that a law firm
provided to several states. The two paragraphs were removed in only
the 6,000 copies distributed in Georgia. The paragraphs contained
descriptions of Nazi treatment of homosexuals that the Georgia
Holocaust Commission said were too sexually explicit for middle
schoolers. Steve Uhlfelder, manager of the law firm's Tallahasee,
Fla., office, said the firm, Holland &AMP; Knight, did not agree that
the paragraphs needed to be removed, but deferred to the Georgia
commission in a spirit of cooperation. The Georgia version still
teaches that homosexuals were among groups targeted by the Nazis.
(Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-BOX _ The two passages about homosexuals deleted from
the Georgia version of a teacher guide on homosexuals. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-KIDS _ State representative Georganna Sinkfield, who
chairs the children and youth committee, has promised to look into
creating an ombudsman for the child protection system and changing
laws to provide for emergency short term for children whose parents
are temporarily incapacitated or unable to provide care for them
because of illness, accident or incarcerated. Such laws keep
children who are without care because of a temporary crisis from
becoming ensnared in a system meant for abused children. 30 inches.
(Oglesby-Segal, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-WRIGHTPATTERSON _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A top Russian space
scientist who visited Wright-Patterson Air Force Base this week
might have been impressed by U.S. technology, but not its ability
to deal with snow: The storm that nearly paralyzed America's
midsection last weekend looked like a typical winter day in Moscow,
a base scientist said. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
