<HEADER>
A1333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEPMOM-FILM-TEX     01-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPMOM-FILM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS A `STEPMOM' A GIRL COULD LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't care if my colleagues, the movie critics, and my best
friend dismiss ``Stepmom'' as a cheap, manipulative tear-jerker of
a film. I still understand why it's packin' em in to theaters.
After all, what movie title better characterizes American families
in the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   We can blame ``Cinderella'' for the bad rap placed upon
stepmoms. The storybook stepmonster is everything from annoying to
wicked, a characterization that is not only unfair but untrue. The
stats prove it: With one out of three Americans a stepparent,
stepchild, stepsibling or stepsomething, the state of stepness is,
like it or not, almost average.
</P>
<P>
   Stepmoms, on the average, are, well, pretty normal. That means
they come in good versions and bad, just like real moms.
</P>
<P>
   And I know from stepmoms; I've had three.
</P>
<P>
   I got my first stepmom when I was 8. She was 19, so it was a
tricky proposition for both of us. How she knew what to do to win
me over is still a mystery, because I was hugely unlovable at that
age _ and remained so, perhaps predictably, for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the little girl in the movie ``Stepmom'' is much
nastier to Julia Roberts than I ever was to my stepmom No. 1 _ a
fact that even she admitted after we saw the movie together last
week _ my stepmother still had to find a well of patience to put up
with me. She continues, as one of my greatest friends now, to tell
the story of the time I was so bored that I took the funny papers
into my bubble bath. (Who knew the ink would stain the bathtub?)
</P>
<P>
   Like the Julia Roberts character, my stepmom was young, hip and
cool. She let me wear a little lip gloss and fixed my hair into a
sassy flip. It was with her that I first experienced eating
McDonald's french fries, shopping for no reason at all and making a
pallet on the floor to watch bad TV, late into the night, with
squealing girlfriends. She taught me how to laugh to the point of
tears over stupid things such as buying the ugliest Christmas tree
on the lot because it was the cheapest, and how we could use the
money we saved for other fun stuff _ like a new purse!
</P>
<P>
   My own Mom adored this stepmom because she made my dad happy
again; Mom was rational enough to know Daddy deserved that. She
also found it wonderfully amusing that my stepmom made fun of my
dad's dark moods. When Mom loaned all her ski clothes to my
stepmom, my friends thought the whole thing was way too weird, but
I loved it. In my family, it made perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics show that 60 percent of marriages end in divorce,
and second marriages are not immune. My first wonderful stepmom
quit that job when I was 16, leaving me with two terrific siblings,
but also, in time, with Stepmom No. 2, about whom it is best to say
nothing, except perhaps that her arrival shot the stepmom pendulum
back toward the evil end. Fortunately, she eventually unblended
from our family, opening the doors for Stepmom No. 3 _
statistically speaking, yet another happy confirmation that 75
percent of divorced people eventually do marry again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, my personal stepmom-o-meter reels again to the positive
side. She and my dad seem to listen to each other as married people
should. They make each other laugh long and hard, and she's a
rocket scientist, which I find very, very cool.
</P>
<P>
   So kill me if I cry real, not manipulated, tears as Julia
Roberts stitches together a relationship with her stepkids on the
big screen, showing that stepmoms can be good. I know perhaps
better than anyone that stepmoms can indeed be fabulous _ but it's
a tough, tough job, and one that is mostly thankless.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I'm not surprised, and I'm even thrilled, that
``Stepmom'' is the first film endorsed by the Lincoln, Neb.-based
Stepfamily Association of America. OK, so the film is heavy-handed,
but isn't it time society finally smashed that stepmonster myth?
Because life after remarriage, while often complicated, can be a
decent, even very happy, place.
</P>
<P>
   (June Naylor Rodriguez can be reached at
junebug(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
