<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-RETENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES MUST WORK TO KEEP THEIR `BEST' WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I would bet the 80/20 theory _ 20 percent of
people have 80 percent of the wealth, 20 percent of your time
accounts for 80 percent of your productivity, 20 percent of the
politicians wipe out 80 percent of the ozone layer _ applies to
hiring as well. In other words, it would be harder to replace the
best 20 percent of your workers than the remaining 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think so, let your mind drift back to when
professional basketball games were played at this time of year. If
you ran the Chicago Bulls, would you rather start with Michael
Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Phil Jackson, or the other 10 players
and any two assistant coaches?
</P>
<P>
   That's more of a no-brainer than Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The workplace game is changing, and employers who are slow to
react will end up losing. Workers aren't as loyal as they used to
be, and baby boomers are getting to the age when they can think
about retiring early or starting their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? Those who can do that are usually your best
workers, the ones you'll have a hard time replacing.
</P>
<P>
   So how can you keep your top people? Here are four suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Think outside the ``bread'' box.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive salaries and good health and retirement packages are
great cornerstones, but they've become routine. What can you do to
stand out?
</P>
<P>
   Are your health benefits useless to someone who is covered
through a spouse? Worth magazine reports that USAA, the insurance
and financial services company, lets its workers who opt out of the
health care program take the money it would have spent on premiums
and use it however they wish.
</P>
<P>
   At a lot of companies, the main form of exercise is shaking the
vending machine. Yet many that end up paying those superfluous
health insurance premiums wouldn't think of using that money to
reimburse workers who join a health club or buy a treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Is your sick leave policy basically useless to dedicated
workers? More companies are offering ``personal'' days, letting
people take the time off for whatever reason they wish, or offering
bonuses to those who don't call in sick for three months or a year.
</P>
<P>
   You need to be more creative, even if you can't spend extra
money. If you have a shorter workweek than your competitors for the
same pay, that's a huge recruiting advantage. If you offer job
sharing or other part-time work, you can attract and keep people
who might otherwise retire early.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Little'' things aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune magazine's Jan. 11 issue has its annual list of ``The
100 Best Companies To Work For,'' and one of the things that stands
out is that the companies do more than offer nice frills. They
offer humanity. They make employees feel as if their opinions
count, and they have things like mentoring and career counseling.
</P>
<P>
   How about this for a ``little'' thing: Studies have shown that
many people function better after a 15-minute nap. Yet how many
bosses would roll their eyes if you asked them to set aside a quiet
room with a couch? Or have a break room with video games or
exercise equipment to relieve stress?
</P>
<P>
   _ Think of commute hours as work time.
</P>
<P>
   Your employees do. If you had to pay people for the time and
money they spend commuting, would you do things differently? If
people commute an hour each way, changing their workweek from five
eight-hour days to four 10-hour days saves them two hours, plus one
day's transportation costs. Letting them telecommute one day
accomplishes the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   In his excellent book, ``Managing Telework,'' Jack M. Nilles
reports that telecommuters' productivity generally increases 10 to
20 percent over working in the office, according to their
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of insecure managers, though, are as frightened by
telecommuting as they are by couches and video games. Companies are
so concerned with making sure that their worst workers don't
exploit the system that they don't do enough to encourage their
best people.
</P>
<P>
   If telecommuting and the compressed workweek are impractical for
your company, could you give workers cell phones or training tapes
so they could make productive use out of their commute and spend
less time at the office?
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it easier for employees to do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Companies pressure workers to continue learning and keep up with
technology, yet management can be awfully slow when it comes to
updating equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a high-priced consultant to tell you that people
work better when they aren't constantly interrupted, yet workers
are bombarded by e-mails and phone calls. Can your employees check
their e-mail once or twice a day without worrying about missing
something urgent? Can they screen phone calls to distinguish the
crucial from the routine?
</P>
<P>
   When so much is going on, sometimes you don't appreciate the
urgency of a message until it's too late. Unambitious workers have
learned that the hard way. Unambitious employers will, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Dave Murphy is the career editor of the San Francisco
Examiner. E-mail him at murphyexaminer.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
