<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT IN A POLITICAL TIME LOOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it deja vu, or has time stood still for two weeks? Here I am,
back from a year-end vacation, and the headlines are exactly the
same as they were in mid-December 1998: presidential impeachment,
America vs. Iraq, the usual suspects gearing up for the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Has the Bill Clinton-Monica Lewinsky sex scandal really been
around for a year? Is the greatest nation on Earth locked in some
sort of time warp that makes every day just like the day before?
Has real life, as some quipsters have suggested, turned into the
movie ``Groundhog Day,'' with all of us playing the role of the
frustrated weather forecaster who wakes up every morning to
discover that the calendar is stuck on Feb. 2?
</P>
<P>
   The American people _ most of them, anyway _ have been begging
the media and the politicians to let go of the scandal, to deal
with Clinton's misdeeds in some appropriate and proportional manner
and then get on with the business of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the media love the story too much to let it die _ and
Clinton's political enemies hate him too much to let Monicagate
assume its rightful place on the trash heap of history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thus confronts each day as the second U.S. president to
be impeached and the one who could become the first to be removed
from office through the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have repeatedly stated the public's wish that Clinton
remain in office. But the Clinton-haters and their congressional
minions are convinced that if only they can prolong the pursuit,
they can eventually persuade the people to demand the president's
head on a platter _ or at least demand that he turn in his keys to
the White House and crawl back to Arkansas in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no other explanation for opposition to Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott's proposal to short-circuit a long and
tedious Senate trial on the articles of impeachment voted by the
House. Figuring that the anti-Clinton forces will never muster the
two-thirds vote needed to convict the president, Lott recommended
disposing of the matter quickly _ without calling witnesses _ and
then taking up the more appropriate alternative of censure.
</P>
<P>
   No way, the Clinton-haters screamed. We need to get Monica into
that Senate chamber to describe every disgusting moment of her
tawdry encounters with Bill. We need to get Linda Tripp to tell the
country under oath what she already told a federal grand jury about
her secondhand perception of the Lewinsky-Clinton affair.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable citizens might wonder: What possible purpose could
such testimony serve? Doesn't just about every American who hasn't
spent the past 12 months in outer space or in a groundhog burrow
already know every slimy, salacious detail of this scandal?
</P>
<P>
   Don't the American people know that Clinton lied about the
affair _ to us, to Paula Jones' lawyers and even to the grand jury?
</P>
<P>
   Of course we know.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans nevertheless believe that Clinton should be
allowed to finish the term of office to which he was duly elected.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress wants to rebuke him for his pathological lying and
compulsive philandering, fine. Rebuke him till the cows come home.
</P>
<P>
   If archenemy Ken Starr wants to prosecute Clinton, then by all
means the independent counsel should wait by the White House gates
and slap the cuffs on the ex-president when he leaves office in
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Even folks who believe that Clinton has done a good job as
president concede that he should pay some price for what he did.
</P>
<P>
   But ``some price'' is just not enough for the Clinton-haters.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the makeup of the Senate _ 55 Republicans, 45
Democrats _ suggests that conviction is impossible, the
head-on-a-platter devotees can't stop believing that some way,
somehow, they might prevail.
</P>
<P>
   So they clamor for an all-out Senate trial, clinging to the
desperate hope that one more rehash of the scandal that never ends
will finally cause the rest of us to realize how wrong we've been.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
