<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS &LR;      01-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS MUST REPEAT THE RIGHT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Because your stereotypical modern American
athlete has only as much memory as he needs to get through that
day's workout, there is at least a 50-50 chance that the Atlanta
Falcons will think they are in deep clover this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For one, they beat the San Francisco 49ers the last time the two
teams played, 31-19, although the tenor of play suggested a wider
margin. For two, they are playing in the unsightly but thoroughly
friendly Georgia Dome where they have won their last 10 games
(after losing 11 of their previous 14), while the 49ers lost their
four road games against playoff opponents this season. And for
three, they have Jamal Anderson, happy, healthy and honking himself
for the MVP trophy.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Falcons are acting the part the 49ers have played
since almost forever.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, though, have all the memory they could ever use for
the NFC divisional playoff game, which they fully intend to use in
hope of breaking the wills of their upstart betters this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   They have won 11 of their last 14 games with Atlanta, by an
average score of way too much to not even close (36-17, if you're
looking for exactitude). They have held Atlanta at arm's (and
leg's) length for almost the entirety of the last two decades. And
they've been the most persistent postseason entrants in NFL
history, while Atlanta's participation has been not quite sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   Taken another way, the Falcons have 20 players with playoff
experience totaling 76 games. The 49ers have four (Jerry Rice,
Steve Young, Ken Norton and Charles Haley) totaling 78 games, and
still have 198 more left over for the rest of the roster. Smart
folks hired by large networks owned by Australians call that an
intangible.
</P>
<P>
   If only it mattered at the time.
</P>
<P>
   See, the 49ers have all that history at their backs, and it is
handy to know ahead of time and helpful to use during the postgame
show, but that pesky three-hour block between those two stretches
is the part that's unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about it, but you know once the game starts, you have
no idea,'' safety Tim McDonald said. ``Not to the point where
you'll ever see it in the game. You might see something in the
films the next day where you could say, `Oh, that might have
mattered,' but nothing at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, history breaks at odd points, usually to the benefit of
the lecturer. Why else does nobody measure 49er history in the
pre-1981 period? Because it isn't relevant to playoff discussions,
that's why. But why couldn't you start counting history after their
last Super Bowl, just for the hell of it? Because they turn into
the Kansas City Chiefs, that's why.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, whatever value all that experience and pedigree has, it
loses its meaning once it leaves the broadcast booth, the rec room
or the third stool at Dexter's Midnight Lounge. Fact is,
intangibles here or intangibles there, the Falcons hold most of the
tangibles, from the home-field advantage to the second-ranked
defense to the offense that holds the ball longer and more
efficiently than any other in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To their credit,'' quarterback Steve Young said, summarizing
the one thing that may negate the Falcons' relative lack of
pressurized living, ``we chased them for two months and never
caught them. They never balked. You have to give them a lot of
credit, they won the division, and rightfully so.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think about it, considering all the history the 49ers can
bring to bear, the Falcons have already beaten back the ghosts of
the past. If the specters of those bad old days didn't crush the
Falcons' spirits as frontrunners in November and December, there is
no sensible reason to think that they'll work now, when all the
measurable advantages are Atlanta's.
</P>
<P>
   No, the 49ers are going to have to work this one strength
against strength, man against man, fist against knee and helmet
against ribs _ without benefit of their long and proud history to
bluff them through the tough spots. They'll have to take an early
lead to force the Falcons to work from behind, and they'll have to
avoid contributing to Atlanta's preposterous plus-20 turnover
ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as head coach Steve Mariucci said when asked how the 49ers
can overcome their struggles on the road: ``You win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, to win, you have to win. Now that's history even
older than the 49ers'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
