A1399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANICS-RADIO-TEX     01-06 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-RADIO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH-LANGUAGE RADIO A POPULAR VOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EULESS, Texas _ When Rosalba Medina needs to brush up on events
in her native Mexico, she turns to the same place that keeps her
informed about her home in Euless: Spanish radio.
</P>
<P>
   Medina can tune in to at least nine radio stations in the
Metroplex that broadcast in Spanish. She can learn not only about
the political climate back home but about the latest chapter in
President Clinton's impeachment saga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to know what's going on,'' said Medina, who
does not speak English fluently.
</P>
<P>
   Across the region, 266,602 Hispanics speak primarily Spanish,
according to federal census data. As the number of Hispanics in
Texas grows, Spanish-language radio helps keep them informed about
everything from the Cowboys to the reconstruction of Honduras in
the wake of Hurricane Mitch to whether Elizabeth Dole could become
the first female U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone listens to the radio,'' said Cesar Ramirez of Euless,
a popular news anchor and reporter on three Spanish-language radio
stations. ``In all parts of the Metroplex, there are Hispanics.
People want to be informed about what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said his goal is make sure that listeners are not only
up-to-date on what's happening at the local, state and national
levels but to ensure that Hispanics know how events effect them.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas radio market, which includes Tarrant County, ranks
ninth in the United States in the number of Hispanic residents. It
ranks seventh in the number of people who speak primarily Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The area Spanish-language radio industry has gone from
mom-and-pop-type businesses with block programming to
corporate-owned stations that cater to every market niche: sports
talk, religion, news and music. It's a nationwide trend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, 213 Spanish-language radio stations broadcast in the
United States. Now there are 520, according to Katz Hispanic Media,
a radio sales firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are attracted to the Metroplex by its healthy economy.
Most come from Mexico, but many come from El Salvador, Guatemala
and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is growing,'' Ramirez said. ``Immigrants are looking for
a state with opportunity and job potential and money.''
</P>
<P>
   They also long for news of home. So when tragedy strikes in
Mexico or in Central America, Spanish-language radio programs
become valuable information sources to immigrants, said Ramirez,
who started in radio at age 10 in his native Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Mitch tore through Honduras, Ramirez called a
radio station in the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa to get the
news at the source. The result was Honduras La Fabulosa Esta
Contigo, an effort that raised more $80,000, plus food and medical
supplies, for the Central American country.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Day, Ramirez called the Honduran radio station to
wish Hondurans a merry Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch is perhaps the best example of how vital
Spanish-language radio is to Hispanics across Texas, said Dax
Venegas, a consul agent for the Honduran Consulate in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of Hondurans who are here can't speak English,'' Venegas
said. ``The radio is what helps us. We use the radio. It's easier.
All the Hondurans listen to the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is the same for the estimated 60,000 Salvadorans
who live in the Metroplex. Salvadoran immigrants learned whether
the hurricane damaged their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful to count on that medium,'' said Rosanna
Gutierrez, consul general for El Salvador in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The stations do more than report about tragedies. Hispanic think
tanks were called this week to comment on Elizabeth Dole's chances
of becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that has to do with our people, we send our reporters
to cover those problems _ from abuses to discrimination,'' Ramirez
said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
