A1410 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     01-06 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOREDOM IS SHELVED WITH COOKBOOKS UNTIL KIDS GROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people think that our lives change like the seasons:
spring, summer, fall and winter. Others say that we go through
stages from infancy to infantile. I kind of like to think of life
as one long line with a point of origin that swerves and curves
until it extends to areas beyond our sight. That's my philosophical
view. But practically speaking, my life has been divided into two
distinct halves: B.K. and A.K. That's before kids and after kids.
</P>
<P>
   Before kids, I could define the word ``boredom.'' I had many
days, in fact, entire weeks when I had nothing in particular to do
but eat and pay taxes on my purchases. (Keep in mind that I was
young and not gainfully employed.) I did not make lists or own a
day planner. I had a calendar that my insurance agent gave me, and
I would jot down important events like parties and dinner dates. I
didn't really need the calendar, though, because at that time I
could actually remember where I was supposed to be and when. Before
kids, I wore silk and really sheer pantyhose. My car was never
dirty for more than 24 hours. I even prepared food with exotic
spices and sauteed onions from my library of cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   I managed to keep most of my sanity and frilly clothing after
the first child. But since the second one came, well, just stick a
fork in me, 'cause I'm done.
</P>
<P>
   Two parents are no equal for two or more children. My little
emperors just took over the place! Before they could even speak,
they dictated when we slept, if we slept. They decided where we
went and how long we stayed. They changed my wardrobe from Donna
Karan to Don't Kare. Stain on the blouse? Before kids, I changed
blouses. After kids, Don't Kare. Run in the hose? Don't Kare.
Zipper broken? Glue it together and don't drink anything. Places to
go, teachers to see.
</P>
<P>
   I have three wall calendars, a day planner and lists of my
lists, but I still forget that they changed basketball practice
from 5 p.m. to 4 p.m. And cooking is a snap. My mashed potatoes
have potatoes, milk and butter in them _ nothing else. I cannot use
any ingredient that has a different color or texture; they won't
eat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, what is this stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I just left the skin on some of the potatoes. It's good;
just try it.''
</P>
<P>
   After merely sniffing the potatoes, my kids declare: ``I hate
it. It's nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   My cookbooks are in the attic. For meatloaf, I just take the
ground beef out of the package, lay it on a cookie sheet and bake
it. It's dry and it looks like a cow patty, but that's the only way
they'll eat it. Sometimes I slice the meat, put it on a bun and
call it hamburgers. Come to think of it, that meatloaf and my car
are about the same color. I really need to wash it. I think it was
blue when we bought it.
</P>
<P>
   After kids, I can define the word ``frenetic.'' Did I spell that
right? Actually, what does that mean? I can't remember where the
dictionary is. Maybe it's with those cookbooks in the attic. See
what I mean? I've got to go drink some water now, and wash
yesterday's meatloaf down my throat. Today we're having canned-tuna
souffle.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
