<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PYRAMID07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL THURSDAY JANUARY 7
 &HT;    Pyramid power: Eating from the four food groups
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If last month's gorging has given way to this month's cabbage
soup diet, by now you are hungry.
</P>
<P>
   I know. You resolved to lose that five pounds of Christmas
candy, turkey stuffing and eggnog by the end of the month. Or maybe
you've set out to starve off that 20 pounds you picked up last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But tell that to the grumbling gremlin in your stomach. Starving
is no better than bingeing. Balance is the fulcrum of a healthy
diet, a healthy life.
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to stop you from examining or experimenting with
any of the diets out there. But distinguishing between the numbing
number of plans can be difficult, especially if your concept of a
healthy diet is still framed by the ``basic'' four food groups.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the basic four have been out for a while and that
little pyramid that appears on so many food labels now is in. But
just how much do you know about that pyramid and how much do you or
should you follow it?
</P>
<P>
   ``The pyramid gives a much better visual depiction of what a
healthy diet should look like,'' says Marietta nutritionist
Kathleen Zelman, who developed for us seven daily menus based on
the food guide. Her plan and recipes are inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pyramid shows that the base of your diet should be
primarily vegetarian, with grains, fruits and vegetables,''
explains Zelman. ``The four basic food groups seem to suggest we
should eat equally from all types of food. That isn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The pyramid, adopted by the U.S. Department of Agriculture in
1992, was the result of a broad effort of nutrition experts across
the country, who relied heavily on research to create a tool that
would be useful to the widest possible audience.
</P>
<P>
   Some nutrition and diet experts have criticized the pyramid for
being too broad; some argue that it's too heavy on carbohydrates or
too vague on fats and oils.
</P>
<P>
   Zelman explains that the pyramid is a tool for building a diet
plan, but that individuals should modify it according to their
health needs.
</P>
<P>
   Some diabetics, for example, may be advised by doctors to pay
careful attention to the types of carbohydrates they consume. And
the pyramid is based on about 2,000 calories a day. Those trying to
lose weight need to choose the lower number of suggested servings
when a range is given and especially limit fats, oils and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   Other pyramids have been created to help address specific
populations, such as vegetarians. In 1993, the World Health
Organization, Harvard School of Public Health and the Oldways
Preservation and Exchange Trust promoted a Mediterranean diet
pyramid that emphasizes grains but distinguishes between types of
meat and fats and allows for wine. Others have been created to
reflect how certain ethnic cuisines, such as Mexican, would work on
the pyramid model.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing all pyramid guides have in common is an emphasis
on what you can eat. ``You can have lots of food. This is not about
deprivation, but rather abundance,'' Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, six to 11 servings a day of grains and bread are
recommended, along with two to four servings of fruit and three to
five servings of vegetables. Meats are part of the plan but have a
smaller role than we are accustomed to. Servings are small,
totaling only about 5 ounces a day, which moves meat to the side of
the plate rather than the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of food. Once you adopt this style, you will
ultimately prefer it,'' Zelman said. ``You will feel full, but you
will feel lighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Take steps toward healthy eating with the diet that's not about
deprivation
</P>
<P>
   We take a look at a weeklong menu of healthy eating, including
recipes and hints for hitting the suggested servings.
</P>
<P>
   Bran cereal  &QC;  1 grain
</P>
<P>
   Skim milk  &QC;  1 dairy
</P>
<P>
   Sliced fresh fruit  &QC;  1 fruit
</P>
<P>
   Whole-grain toast  &QC;  1 grain
</P>
<P>
   Jam &AMP; margarine (1 tsp.)  &QC; 1 optional
</P>
<P>
   Turkey Swiss sandwich  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   2 grains, 1-2 meat, 1 dairy
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes, sprouts,
</P>
<P>
   lettuce  &QC;  1 vegetable
</P>
<P>
   Light mayonnaise  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 optional
</P>
<P>
   Grapes  &QC;  1 fruit
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces cranberry juice, seltzer  &QC;  1/2 fruit
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Potato Shrimp Gumbo  &QC;  1-2 meat, 2 vegetable
</P>
<P>
   Rice  &QC;  2 grain
</P>
<P>
   Spinach salad  &QC;  1-2 vegetable
</P>
<P>
   Low-fat dressing  &QC;  1/2 optional
</P>
<P>
   French bread  &QC;  1-2 grain
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla low-fat yogurt with pineapple and orange  &QC;  1 dairy, 1
1/2 fruit
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla wafers  &QC;  1 grain
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan Walker is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
