<HEADER>
A1421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PYRAMID-RECIPES0     01-06 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PYRAMID-RECIPES07-2NDTAKE </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Brassica
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   This spicy, sassy preparation of chicken is anything but
ordinary, proving low-fat doesn't mean no-flavor. Greens and things
make this dish hearty and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoning mix:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons onion
</P>
<P>
   powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried
</P>
<P>
   oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic
</P>
<P>
   powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground
</P>
<P>
   coriander
</P>
<P>
   Chicken:
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken (3 pounds), skin and fat removed, cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chopped onion, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped green pepper, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced mushrooms, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped collard greens, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups defatted chicken stock, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 (14 1/2 ounce) cans diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine the paprika, basil, salt, onion powder,
oregano, garlic powder, mustard, white pepper, thyme, black pepper
and coriander. Preheat a heavy 5-quart pot, preferably nonstick,
over high heat about 4 minutes. Sprinkle all surfaces of the
chicken evenly with 5 teaspoons of the seasoning mix and rub it in
well. Place the chicken in the pot and cook, turning once, until
browned on all sides, about 10 minutes in all. You may have to cook
the chicken in batches. When the chicken is brown, remove it from
the pot and set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   To the pot, add 2 cups of the onion, 1 cup of the pepper, 1 cup
of the mushrooms, 1 cup of the greens, the bay leaves and the
remaining seasoning mix. Cook, scraping the bottom of the pot
frequently, until the vegetables begin to stick, turn brown and
seem in danger of burning, about 5 minutes. Add 1/2 cup of the
stock, scrape the bottom of the pot clear, and cook, scraping
occasionally, until the stock is almost absorbed, about 6 minutes.
Blend in the flour and cook until it starts to brown, about 3
minutes. Add the tomatoes with their liquid and the remaining
onion, green pepper, mushrooms and collards and bring to a boil.
Add the chicken and any juices that have accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the heat to medium-low and cook, covered, until done,
approximately 20 minutes. Serve over rice. _ From Paul Prudhomme's
``Fork in the Road,'' (William Morrow &AMP; Co., $24.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 315 calories, 35 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 24), 24 grams carbohydrates, 92
milligrams cholesterol, 539 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Pear Cranberry Crisp
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 very ripe pears, peeled, cored and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vanilla frozen yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a medium bowl, combine the
pears, cranberries, maple syrup and lemon juice and toss. Set
aside. In another bowl combine the oatmeal, brown sugar and flour.
Cut in the butter until the consistency resembles coarse crumbs and
the dough just barely holds together. Spoon the cranberry mixture
into an 8-by-8-inch baking dish and spoon the dry mixture over it.
Bake for 10 minutes, or until the topping is brown and crisp.
Reduce the heat to 350 degrees and bake for 20 to 25 minutes more
or until the fruit is bubbling. Serve with vanilla frozen yogurt. _
From: Martha Stewart's ``Healthy Quick Cook,'' (Clarkson Potter,
$32.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 288 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 16), 61 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 52 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pan Seared Pork Chops
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 5-10 minutes Cooking time:
18-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Trimmed of its fat, pork is a good lean choice. The key here is
portion size, with each pork chop weighing about 4 ounces. So put
the extra-thick cut away and let the flavor of the wine sauce
satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 pork chops, trimmed of fat (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs of fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken stock or low-sodium canned
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup marsala wine
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salt and pepper and dried thyme and rub on the pork
chops. Press a sprig of thyme into each chop. Heat the olive oil in
a nonstick skillet over medium-low heat and add the pork chops,
thyme side down. Sear 5 to 7 minutes per side, or until just
browned and the interior is no longer bright pink. Transfer to a
warm plate. Pour off the fat from the skillet, return pan to the
heat, add the stock and wine, and bring to a boil. Cook until
slightly thickened, about 10 minutes. Spoon the sauce over the pork
chops and serve. _ From Martha Stewart's ``Healthy Quick Cook,''
(Clarkson Potter, $32.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 233 calories, 25 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 24), 1 gram carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 52 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Blueberry Corn Muffins
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 muffins Preparation time: 15-20 minutes Cooking time:
18-22 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Those extra-large muffins from the local bakery you so love to
munch on for breakfast are loaded with fat and sugar. Try to make
smaller and healthier muffins at home, starting with these, which
deliver texture and taste without all the calories. Fresh or frozen
blueberries can be used.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Lightly coat 12 muffin cups
with vegetable oil spray or line with paper liners.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk together the flour, cornmeal, baking
powder, salt and cinnamon. Add the blueberries and toss to coat
with the flour mixture. In a small bowl, whisk the egg with the oil
until smooth. Whisk in the honey and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Add the milk mixture to the flour mixture and stir gently just
until blended, trying not to break the blueberries. Spoon into the
prepared muffin tins and sprinkle the tops with the sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the muffins are golden and well-risen and a tester
inserted in the center comes out clean, 18 to 22 minutes. Serve
warm, or cool the muffins on a rack and serve at room temperature.
(Freeze for up to 2 weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   Note: If using frozen blueberries, do not thaw them. Simply
rinse off any ice crystals and pat dry gently on paper towels. Toss
separately with about 2 tablespoons of the flour, then stir them in
after adding the liquid to the batter. _ From the American Medical
Association's ``Family Health Cookbook'' (Pocket Books, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 181 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 25), 31 grams carbohydrates, 18 milligrams
cholesterol, 148 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan Walker is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
