<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PYRAMID-RECIPES0     01-06 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PYRAMID-RECIPES07-1STTAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep interested in eating routine with new dishes
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooking by the pyramid doesn't need to be difficult or dull.
</P>
<P>
   We think one of the best ways to jump-start an eating regimen is
to invigorate your routine with some new dishes. And we know the
best way to control what goes in your mouth is to cook it in your
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, we offer these additions to your recipe file. How
about starting the day with Blueberry Corn Muffins? Leftover lunch
sounds better when it's Lemon, Tuna and White Bean Salad. And what
better way to get your greens than with spicy Chicken Brassica?
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid power comes from including flavor and fun in your diet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Lemon, Tuna and White Bean Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Standing time: 10
minutes to 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   This makes a light dinner or a satisfying replacement for the
mayonnaise-laden version of tuna salad at lunch. It's easy,
requiring assembly rather than cooking.
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (16 ounces each) cannellini beans or other white beans,
rinsed and drained, or 4 cups cooked cannellini beans
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bottled clam juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh
</P>
<P>
   thyme or 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh oregano or 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 can (6 ounces) water-packed tuna
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch arugula, rinsed and dried
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, combine the beans and onion. In a separate
bowl, whisk together the lemon juice, clam juice, oil, thyme,
oregano, lemon peel and pepper. Add the dressing to the beans and
onion, and toss to mix. Add the tuna and parsley and stir gently to
combine, just enough to break the tuna into clumps. Taste and add
the salt if desired. Let the salad stand for 10 minutes to blend
the flavors or refrigerate up to 1 hour before serving. To serve,
spoon over a bed of arugula and garnish with tomato wedges. _ From
the American Medical Association's ``Family Health Cookbook''
(Pocket Books, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 400 calories, 30 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 18) 53 grams carbohydrates, 12
milligrams cholesterol, 186 milligrams sodium, 10 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Winter Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   and Whole Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time:
50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When slowly roasted, vegetables caramelize and become sweet,
while garlic softens. You can substitute other firm vegetables,
such as white or sweet potatoes, fennel bulbs or pearl onions.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound carrots (about 8 slender carrots), peeled and cut in
2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 pound white turnips (about 4 small to medium turnips), peeled
and cut in 2-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 pound winter squash such as Hubbard or butternut, peeled and
cut in 2-inchchunks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme or 2 tablespoons chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 whole head of garlic
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a large, shallow roasting pan,
combine the carrots, turnips and squash. Drizzle with the olive oil
and sprinkle with the dried thyme (if using fresh thyme, add later
in recipe), salt and pepper and toss until the vegetables are
well-coated with oil. Break the garlic into individual cloves,
removing and discarding as much of the excess papery outer skin as
possible. Add to the roasting pan and toss with the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the vegetables, uncovered, for 10 minutes. Reduce heat to
350 degrees and continue to cook, stirring once or twice until the
vegetables are tender and lightly caramelized, 40 to 50 minutes. If
using fresh thyme, sprinkle it over the vegetables during the last
5 minutes of cooking. Season to taste with additional salt and
pepper before serving. Squeeze the garlic out of its skin and
combine it with the other vegetables. _ From the American Medical
Association's ``Family Health Cookbook'' (Pocket Books, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 111 calories, 2 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 40), 18 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 58
milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Potato and Shrimp Gumbo
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time: 35
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Part soup, part stew, gumbo is a wonderful winter warmer. This
one combines shrimp and sweet potatoes, an unusual pairing, but we
think it works. It's a great way to include sweet potatoes in your
diet _ they are power-packed with nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup tomato juice (6 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, stemmed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound okra, stemmed and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups canned crushed tomatoes or tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   24 fresh or thawed frozen shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   6 cups cooked, hot white rice
</P>
<P>
   In a large frying pan, heat tomato juice over medium-high heat.
Add the onion, bell pepper, okra and celery and saute until wilted
and softened slightly, 5-7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add wine and vinegar and bring to a boil. Stir in sweet
potatoes, tomatoes or puree, chili powder and cayenne and cook
until mixture returns to a boil. Reduce heat to low, cover and
simmer, stirring occasionally, until the sweet potatoes are tender,
20-25 minutes. Add the shrimp and stir to combine. Cover and cook
until the shrimp are pink, about 5 minutes. To serve, divide the
rice among individual bowls. Top each with an equal amount of the
gumbo. _ From the ``Mayo Clinic/Williams-Sonoma Cookbook'' (Time
Life Books, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 362 calories, 14 grams protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 5), 72 grams carbohydrates, 49
milligrams cholesterol, 397 milligrams sodium. 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed Baked Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-30 minutes (plus additional time for baking
potato)
</P>
<P>
   A baked potato can be total comfort food. But rather than stuff
it _ and yourself _ with high-fat cheese, try this version using
low-fat ricotta. Additional stuffing can be baked in custard cups.
</P>
<P>
   4 large potatoes, baked (about 7 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup low-fat or skim milk, warmed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup part-skim ricotta
</P>
<P>
   2 small cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, if desired
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly gound black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped, cooked broccoli (stems or flowerets) or spinach
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grated Parmesan, divided
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Take thin slices off the potatoes
lengthwise. With a melon baller or small, sharp spoon, carefully
scoop out the flesh without tearing the skin. Reserve the skins
(but not the slices).
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mash the potato with the warm milk. Combine it
well with the ricotta, garlic, salt, pepper, broccoli or spinach
and 2 tablespoons of the Parmesan. Stuff the potato mixture into
the potato skins, piling it high. Sprinkle the stuffed potatoes
with the remaining cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place the potatoes in a pan, and bake them for 20 minutes
(longer if the potatoes were cold to start with). _ From Jane
Brody's ``Good Food Book'' (W.W. Norton &AMP; Co., $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 316 calories, 15 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 19), 50 grams carbohydrates, 23
milligrams cholesterol, 359 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
