<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE07-COX     01-06 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't overlook Web for weighty matters
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it's coming from Washington or your bathroom scale,
retribution is in the air. 'Tis the season to pay the piper for all
those lusty holiday indulgences. The candy, the cakes, the cookies,
the nuts, the stuffing, the sweet potato pie, the ham and turkey
sandwiches right before bedtime when you weren't even hungry. It's
time to redress, rehab, re-evaluate, repent and reduce.
</P>
<P>
   It's been estimated that the average person gains 7 or more
pounds over the holidays. That's 7 pounds you don't need as you set
out on the countdown to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, when slack seems so hard to come by, the prospect of
shaping up may be too daunting. Groveling, sniveling and making
excuses may seem the easy way out. But before you succumb to this
quagmire of shame and despair, check out the Internet, which can be
gentle and forgiving even for the most recalcitrant among us.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, five minutes spent browsing ``The Body Beautiful:
Your Complete Diet and Fitness Center'' at
http://homearts.com/depts
</P>
<P>
   /health/00dietc1.htm and you can't help but pick up at least a
bit of information to put you on the right track. For example,
under ``Restaurant Rx'' there are generic restaurant menus
representing many types of cuisines. Click on something that you
might want to order, then look to the bottom of the page. A
sentence of friendly advice will appear, encouraging you to
``enjoy'' the appetizer of grilled calamari over radicchio but
gently warning you that the excess fat in an entree featuring
broccoli and garlic sauteed in olive oil may undo some of the
health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Next click on the ``Burn Barometer.'' You will find a list of
more than 100 activities from aerobics to golf, housework to yoga
and yes, sex. Enter the amount of time that you spend doing any of
the activities and find out how many calories you have burned.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a wonderfully simple-to-use calorie and nutrition
calculator. Ditto a body mass index calculator. Then there is the
``Fitness Finder.'' Here they ask you to answer some personal
questions to get an idea of your personality and how you feel about
exercise in general. With this information and a click of the
mouse, they come up with an exercise program personally suited to
you.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other departments, including a section on how
to take the fat out of your favorite recipes and lots of great
recipes (like the one below).
</P>
<P>
   Other sites are brimming with fabulous-sounding low-fat recipes
to keep you from feeling deprived. We especially liked
http://www.healthychoice.com/kitchen/html/Kitchen.cfx, which
proclaims: ``To get the most out of life, they say you should seize
the day, or, if that doesn't work, seize the fork.'' Find more
scrumptious low-fat recipes at
http://www.countryliving.com/gh/food/0197lff1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is http://lyra.simplenet.com/recipes/lowfat.html,
which besides a treasure-trove of low-fat and no-fat recipes offers
an opportunity to chat with others on the same quest.
</P>
<P>
   We know misery loves company, but this is turning out to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Scallop and Asparagus Stir-Fry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
12-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced, peeled ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons reduced-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds asparagus, trimmed and cut into 2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed
</P>
<P>
   red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed fresh basil leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Rinse scallops under running cold water to remove sand from
crevices. Pat scallops dry with paper towels. In bowl, toss
scallops with ginger and 1 tablespoon soy sauce. In nonstick
12-inch skillet, heat 1 tablespoon vegetable oil over medium-high
heat. Add garlic and cook until golden brown, stirring often. With
slotted spoon, remove garlic to bowl. In same skillet, cook
asparagus and crushed red pepper until asparagus is tender-crisp,
about 7 minutes. Remove asparagus to bowl with garlic. Add
remaining 1 tablespoon oil to skillet; add scallop mixture and
cook, stirring frequently, until scallops turn opaque throughout, 3
to 5 minutes. Add asparagus, garlic and remaining soy sauce to
skillet; heat through. (Add a little more oil if it starts to
stick.) Toss with chopped basil. Spoon mixture onto platter;
garnish with basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 202 calories, 23 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 36), 11 grams carbohydrates, 37
milligrams cholesterol, 489 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Parham is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
