cajole Latin American governments to half-heartedly condemn the
U.S. embargo.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s nearly everyone _ from Mexican national hero Lazaro
Cardenas to Jean-Paul Sartre and Stokely Carmichael _ made the
pilgrimage to Havana. Today the swarms of revolutionaries,
intellectuals and advisers from the golden age of glory are nowhere
in sight. What you see instead are middle-age Spanish, Italian and
Mexican tourists who come to take advantage of Cuba's beautiful
beaches, cheap prices and readily available sex.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cuban cultural presence is far less than it was 30
years ago, or even as recently as the 1980s, the island's sway
among writers, singers, painters, academics, poets, actors and TV
and movie directors is still disproportionate to its tiny size and
meager resources.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the paradox: the Cuban Revolution has left a much more
lasting imprint among novelists than political ideologues, among
painters than student activists, among musicians than labor
organizers _ in short, among cultural than political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Having once wielded enormous influence over the politics of
Latin America and to an extent the world, today Cuba's strategic
value is highly reduced: Russia prefers IMF dollars to
nuclear-tipped missiles pointed at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   And yet hundreds of graduates from Gabriel Garcia Marquez's
School of Cinema and Television in San Antonio de los Banos are
scattered across the influential cities of Latin America. At the
University of Buenos Aires, a Che Guevara rotating chair
inaugurated in early 1997 still attracts hundreds of attentive
students. In Mexico, La Jornada, the mass-circulation daily where
Carlos Fuentes and Octavio Paz published their columns and
commentaries on current events as recently as five years ago,
continues to flaunt its enthusiasm for everything Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller than ever, but nonetheless impressive number of Latin
America's most distinguished cultural icons remain fast and true
friends of Cuba _ from Garcia Marquez to Chilean playwright Ariel
Dorfman, from Ecuadorian painter Guayasamin to Uruguayan
teeny-bopper idol and best-selling novelist Mario Benedetti, from
Brazilian songwriter and folk hero Chico Buarque to the dean of
Latin American sociologists, Mexico's Pablo Gonzalez Casanova.
</P>
<P>
   The continued loyalty to Cuba of these and many other major
figures on the Latin American cultural scene stems in part from the
status and activities of the region's intelligentsia. During the
long night of authoritarian rule in Latin America, intellectuals
frequently spoke out at home and abroad against abuses and
atrocities, and helped to replace banned or weakened political
parties. When democratization finally arrived, that role greatly
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Cuban regime is now so discredited in Latin
American politics that the most a fellow traveler to Cuba can get
away with is to call for an end to the U.S. embargo and harassment
from Miami; but in the field of culture there is greater leeway.
Artists are less accountable to the public than politicians, who
have to face the media and the voters. Artists and performers face
only their audience and youthful, radical fans, most of whom tend
to share their political views. Few openly pro-Cuban politicians
are left in Latin America, but there are still many pro-Cuban
cultural figures.
</P>
<P>
   The festive times of the Cuban Revolution ended many years ago,
as did the heyday of its influence _ political, cultural and
otherwise. What remain are memories and regrets, as well as
vestiges of a singular experience in Latin America history: the way
in which a small island with no particular claim to fame was
transformed into a cultural beacon and haven for many of the
greatest writers the region has ever known, and for some of its
finest thinkers, musicians and painters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is perhaps a fitting tribute to Cuba and to Che
Guevara that they both made a greater mark in the shining field of
Latin culture than in the mundane, mediocre world of politics.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a new, emerging left in Latin America, it is largely
because the Cubans have been banished from political life in the
hemisphere. But if the region's cultural realm maintains its
marvelous vitality, it is partly because of Cuba's contribution to
it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
