<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-HOMESTEAD-2TA     01-06 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-HOMESTEAD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET PRESENCE: IF NO ONE SEES A WEB SITE, IS IT REALLY THERE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Homesteading on the World Wide Web can be a lonely proposition.
</P>
<P>
   I learned this the hard way, when a book I wrote caught the
attention of a stranger named Greg O'Brien. First, O'Brien sent me
fan e-mail. One thing led to another, and before long, O'Brien, a
software consultant in Marlborough, Mass., who is well versed in
the Web, was volunteering to build a Web site for the book.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't have been more pleased. The book _ ``The House at the
Bridge'' (Scribner, 1995), a nonfiction work about Germany in the
wake of reunification _ had long since disappeared from Books in
Print. A Web site might be just the way to give it new life.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, not long after O'Brien entered my life, the
online retailer Amazon.com started a new program for out-of-print
books in which an author or small publisher, armed with cartons of
unsold copies, could become the distributor, shipping books in
batches as small as two or three for Amazon to sell when ordered.
The Web site, O'Brien and I decided, would feature a link to
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   After a month or so of working in his spare time, O'Brien
created a rich, visually engaging Web site, complete with sketches,
photographs, prose from the book, a bibliography and links to other
sites. I expected that dozens of scholars, students and anyone with
a more than casual interest in modern Germany would come to the
site every day, using it as an efficient source of information and
perhaps even buying the book through Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   That is not what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with erecting a virtual shrine to your out-of-print
book, unpublished novel, love of border collies or anything at all
is that the mere existence of the site does not mean anyone will go
there.
</P>
<P>
   If Yahoo, with more than a million visits daily, is as visible a
destination as the Eiffel Tower, then home-brewed sites like mine
are like so many identical trees in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't count on people stumbling across your
site. They will find it only if they are looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing exactly how many people were visiting the site was easy.
Soon after the site went up, in May 1998, O'Brien devised a way to
monitor traffic, through a service called Nedstat
(usa.nedstat.net). Nedstat not only tells you how many visitors, or
page views, your site gets each day; it also breaks down the
statistics into page views per hour and page views per week and
presents the results in colorful bar charts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien pointed me to the Nedstat link on a day last fall. When
I went there, I found a prediction for the day's traffic.
``Forecast for today: nine page views.''
</P>
<P>
   That was sobering news, especially considering that several of
the page views came from O'Brien himself as he walked the virtual
grounds of his creation. The high point came on Nov. 9, the
anniversary of the fall of the Berlin wall: 25 visits.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on www.thehouseatthebridge.com needed a boost.
</P>
<P>
   For months I had been receiving junk e-mail from various
companies offering to increase Web site traffic. The most
persistent entreaty came from an outfit called Traffic Accelerator.
The offer was difficult to refuse: for $39.95 my site would be
submitted to 900 search engines and directories. I perused the site
(which is no longer functioning under that URL) _ and began to
surrender my credit card information.
</P>
<P>
   As I clicked through the sign-up process, the service tried to
goad me into buying the far more expensive $159.95 option, which
promised to resubmit the site repeatedly over several months. I
resisted, and stuck with the $39.95 one-time service.
</P>
<P>
   I asked O'Brien to help me monitor the results. Yes, he had
heard of these submission services, he told me. I wondered aloud if
the server he used for the site would be able to withstand the
increase in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, a taciturn man to begin with, went dead silent.
Finally, he said gently, ``Don't be disappointed if it doesn't
amount to much.'' He said he had already submitted the site to
several of the major search sites and directories, like Yahoo, Alta
Vista, Lycos and Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   But surely the 896 others would yield some new traffic. A few
days after buying the service, I called up the Nedstat page.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic had not risen that day. In fact, it had reached an
all-time low of six visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic that did increase was my e-mail. A few messages came
from sites that must have received my submission because they were
writing to invite me to visit the link they had created. But when I
went to look for it, I found nothing. Further, the sites I visited
_ devoted to direct marketing and country music _ had no
discernible connection to Germany, modern or medieval.
</P>
<P>
   More unsettling, many of the sites looked unsavory. Still worse,
for the next couple of weeks, I was spammed with e-mail from dozens
of other submission services.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on my site, in the meantime, held steady at about 10
visits a day. Despondent, I called my friend Nate Saal, who runs a
Web-based software updating service in Palo Alto, Calif. When I
explained my problem, Saal told me, almost apologetically, that his
site got tens of thousands of visitors each day.
</P>
<P>
   He offered this advice: ``You need to narrow down the market so
that people who might be interested in your topic find out about
your site.'' He suggested that I find other sites devoted to the
Berlin wall and offer to create a reciprocal link.
</P>
<P>
   Saal also stressed word-of-mouth advertising. ``Create a means
and a reason for people to tell others,'' he said. Saal, for
instance, had created a ``tell a friend'' page on his site, making
it easy for people to tell friends about the site and giving them a
chance to win a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   I rejected the T-shirt idea but took his advice about reciprocal
links and sent e-mail to people whose Germany and Berlin wall pages
were prominently featured in search engines, offering to link to
them in exchange for a link to me. I heard nothing in reply.
</P>
<P>
   I continued, compulsively you might say, to call up the Nedstat
page, thinking there might be a delayed effect from the submission
service. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I called Evan I. Schwartz, a writer whose book,
``Webonomics'' (Broadway Books, 1997), is closely tied to his Web
site, Webonomics.com. If anyone could give me tips for
cross-promoting a Web site and a book, Schwartz could.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do people know about your Web site?'' I asked. Schwartz
replied: ``The URL is on the book. It's in big red fluorescent
letters on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of my book, published a good year before URLs
started showing up on dust jackets, that was a moot point. Schwartz
also offered his opinion about search engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that people don't find things through
search engines,'' he said. He explained that tens of thousands of
sites contained any of my key words and phrases _ Berlin wall,
modern Germany, Potsdam, World War II. ``You're a needle in a
haystack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While I was on the phone with Schwartz, an e-mail message
arrived with ``Link Request'' in the subject line: ``Hi. I am Larry
Steele and I just visited your site at
http://vancouver-webpages.com/global-URL-list.html and thought we
might help each other. Your prospect is similar to mine; someone
interested in his or her appearance. Would you consider putting a
link on your site to mine at http://www.logsdons.com/hair? We have
a very special video called `No More Bad Hair Days.' Here is copy
of our advertisement to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Why not?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
