<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     01-06 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE BAD AREN'T PREYING ON THE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hark, the heralds are singing good news about decreasing crime
in America.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI reported last month that serious crime dropped 5 percent
in the first half of 1998, extending a six-year trend of declining
criminal activity. Using preliminary figures from police
departments nationwide, the FBI showed drops in all seven major
crime categories.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question to follow such remarkable news is: ``Why?
What are we doing that is contributing to this decline?''
</P>
<P>
   Academic experts, law enforcement authorities and elected
officials are quick to cite a litany of reasons that contributed to
the decline, without pointing specifically to one factor. The aging
of the baby boomers beyond their crime-prone years; community
policing programs; zero-tolerance efforts and stiffer sentences,
particularly for young offenders; a strong economy; and a reduction
in crack cocaine use and the gang wars that occurred between groups
selling the stuff _ all are listed as reasons for turning the
corner on criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent, however, from the tune being sung by
officials trumpeting the good news is the increase in the number of
states that allow law-abiding citizens to carry concealed guns.
</P>
<P>
   It makes perfect sense that people bent on doing harm will think
twice before attacking others who might efficiently and effectively
defend themselves. Shouldn't that consideration be included in any
explanation for why serious, violent crime may be dropping in this
country?
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid that someone in officialdom should present a
possibly unbiased account of what personal gun ownership might mean
in the grand scheme of the better America.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of personal firearms was sure-as-shooting part of
the reason why the crime rate in Australia is rising. In 1997, the
Australian government enacted a law that forced gun owners to
surrender personal firearms. According to the Australian Institute
of Criminology, more than 640,000 guns (including .22-caliber
rifles and shotguns) were destroyed in a program that cost the
government more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since the ban went into effect, criminal activity
Down Under has increased dramatically. On Oct. 28, the ``Sydney
Morning Herald'' reported that homicides were up 3.2 percent,
assaults were up 8.6 percent and armed robberies were up a whopping
44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It does not take a Y2K computer reprogrammer to calculate the
correlation between an armed citizenry and crime rates. Italian
jurist and criminologist Cesare Beccaria figured it out more than
two centuries ago when he wrote ``On Crimes and Punishments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``False is the idea of utility that sacrifices a thousand real
advantages for one imaginary or trifling inconvenience; that would
take fire from men because it burns, and water because one may
drown in it; that has no remedy for evils, except destruction,''
Beccaria wrote in 1764.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws that forbid the carrying of arms are laws of such a
nature. They disarm only those who are neither inclined nor
determined to commit crimes. Can it be supposed that those who have
the courage to violate the most sacred laws of humanity, the most
important of the code, will respect the less important and
arbitrary ones .... Such laws make things worse for the assaulted
and better for the assailants; they serve rather to encourage than
to prevent homicides, for an unarmed man may be attacked with
greater confidence than an armed man.''
</P>
<P>
   Beccaria was highly respected by his American contemporaries,
men who would go on to play significant roles in the development of
this nation's ideas of personal rights, liberties and defining
laws. John Adams quoted from his text; Thomas Jefferson kept a
written copy of it, in the original Italian, in his ``Commonplace
Book,'' according to Les Adams, author of the Second Amendment
Primer.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits who contend that the Second Amendment of the
Constitution has nothing to do with personal firearm ownership need
to go back and read the works of the historical figures who
influenced the thinking and philosophies of this nation's Founding
Fathers. The only governments that prefer their citizens to be
unarmed are tyrannies and despotisms.
</P>
<P>
   The next time a government report is issued citing reasons for a
downturn in crime, remember this basic, ages-old reality: Bad
people are reluctant to prey on good people who are likely to
strike back.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe &LR; star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817) 390-7599.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
