<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPS TO INSTALLING AN ELECTRICAL BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a house the electrical wires run from the main service panel
to receptacles, switches and fixtures. The National Electrical Code
specifies that the wires must be protected with either heavy-duty
plastic vinyl sheathing, flexible armored sheathing or metal
conduit.
</P>
<P>
   Few circuits run from the panel to a receptacle without an
in-line wiring connection. The code also specifies that these
connections must be contained in an approved galvanized steel or
plastic box. Similar boxes are available for switches and
receptacles.
</P>
<P>
   The code requires that the boxes be mounted on framing members
and that they remain accessible. Therefore they should never be
covered with drywall, paneling or any wall covering.
</P>
<P>
   Electrical boxes are available in different shapes (rectangular,
square and octagonal) and in several depths. Each box must be large
enough to accommodate the receptacle and all the wires without
crimping or damaging the connections. Undersized boxes should be
upgraded with larger boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Since exposed connections pose a fire hazard, homeowners should
check the wiring in their houses to make sure that there are no
open splices. Generally this is not a problem in newer homes --
although electricians sometimes leave an exposed splice in
unfinished basements or utility rooms. The problem is more acute in
older homes, because the wiring may have been installed before many
building codes were in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Installing an electrical box is not difficult. The first step
whenever working on any electrical circuit is to make sure the
power is turned off. Do this by flipping the appropriate circuit
breaker or removing the correct fuse. Avoid touching any bare wires
until you have tested the circuit to make sure that it is indeed
cold.
</P>
<P>
   You can test the circuit with a circuit tester. Carefully remove
any electrical tape or solderless nuts to expose the wire
connections, then touch one probe of the circuit tester to the
black connection, the other probe to the white connection. The
tester light should not glow. If it does, return to the service
panel and try another breaker. After making certain that the
electricity is off, uncouple all the splices.
</P>
<P>
   Steel boxes have ''knockouts'' _ disks that are not completely
cut loose from the sides of the box. These can be punched or
knocked out with a steel punch to make an opening for the incoming
wires. Punch out one opening for each cable entering the box; leave
the other knockouts in place.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor the box to a nearby framing member (Junction boxes have
small holes so you can nail or screw them to a stud or joist).
Thread a cable clamp onto each cable, then tighten the clamps with
a screwdriver. Be careful not to overtighten the clamp or you could
damage the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Push the wire into the box so the threaded end of the clamp
protrudes inside. Each cable clamp has a locknut that must be
screwed on from inside the box. Tighten the locknuts pushing
against the lugs on the sides of the nut with a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   When all the cables are securely in place, make the connections
inside the box. Use solderless connectors (also called wire nuts)
to join the wires together. First twist the wires together, using
needlenose pliers, then screw the connector onto the twisted wires.
When the connector is in place, it should completely cover the bare
wire ends.
</P>
<P>
   If the circuit has ground wires _ usually these are bare copper
wires _ connect them together and add a short length of wire to run
from the connection to the green grounding screw on the back of the
junction box. Carefully push all the wires inside the box and
attach a cover plate. Return to the service panel and turn on the
power.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to protecting the connections inside, junction boxes
also provide mounting points to attach light fixtures. Actually,
modern electrical codes now prohibit mounting a fixture directly to
the junction box. Instead, it should be bolted to a mounted strap
that is anchored to the box.
</P>
<P>
   To install a low-voltage thermostat or a doorbell system, you
will need to connect a step-down transformer to an existing
circuit. You can tap the transformer into a power circuit through a
junction box. First turn off the power, then remove a knockout from
the box. Thread the transformer wires through the hole and connect
them to the appropriate circuit wires. When the connections are
made, replace the cover and restore power.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
