<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; When a Site Won't Load &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My Web browser crashes when I try to look at a certain page.
Every other page I want to look at loads fine, so is something
wrong with the page?
</P>
<P>
   A. A number of things could be causing the problem, so try to
eliminate some possibilities. Try to call up that Web page on
another computer (or ask a friend to try) and see if it will load
properly. If the page won't load on different computers, it's very
likely that something is wrong with the page file.
</P>
<P>
   If the page loads for someone else, check your own system. Make
sure you have enough RAM to meet the minimal system requirements
for the browser program.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web pages are designed with more than just the basic HTML
(hypertext markup language) coding. Java applets and browser
plug-ins like Flash are some of the newer technology used to
animate and spice up Web pages. Older browsers _ early versions of
Netscape Navigator, Microsoft Explorer or America Online's browser
_ can't support some of these newer features.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, upgrade your browser to the most current version
and make sure that you have all the popular plug-ins. If your
computer can't handle the newer, more RAM-hungry browsers, consider
switching to a low-cost, low-RAM alternative like the Opera browser
(www.operasoftware.com), which can run on even a 386 processor.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
