<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-RARE-BOOKS-ART-2T     01-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-RARE-BOOKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE, DELICATE BOOKS YOU CAN MAUL TO YOUR HEART'S CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL JOSEPH GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Octavo, a company that puts rare books onto CD-ROMs, avoids the
sound and fury of quick-time movies, computer animation and musical
scores. Instead, lush printed pages are the bells and whistles of
Octavo's elegant, searchable, printable, magnifiable renderings of
first editions by Milton, Shakespeare, Copernicus and other masters
of the printed medium.
</P>
<P>
   With those kinds of authors, Octavo CD-ROMs don't need any
multimedia gewgaws to capture the interest of their readers, said
Patrick Ames, chief executive of the Palo Alto, Calif., company.
And the format is practical, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can play with it, print it out, spill coffee on it, print
it out again,'' Ames noted. ``With a real rare book, you have to be
extremely careful. It's fragile. You can't really read it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Octavo's founding in late 1997 by John E. Warnock,
chairman and chief executive of Adobe Systems Inc., and by Ames
(who formerly headed Adobe's publishing arm), the company has built
a catalog of a dozen titles straddling popular and scholarly
markets. These range from the collected works of Geoffrey Chaucer's
to Robert Hooke's ``Micrographia,'' the lavishly illustrated
17th-century entomological text. They are priced from $20 to $75.
</P>
<P>
   The company takes its name from a printing term that refers to a
size of paper or a book whose leaves are one-eighth the size of a
standard printing sheet.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of octavo books in the mid-15th Century, Ames
said, ``Information wasn't locked in the monasteries or the
churches anymore. You could carry it around. Everybody could read
it. That's how the Renaissance came.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames admits that Octavo's sales so far have been meager: He
estimates that the company sold fewer than 2,000 CD-ROMs last year.
Yet he said that revenues have doubled every month since February
1998, which marked the arrival in the market of Octavo's first
product, a first edition of Shakespeare's Sonnets, from Warnock's
personal collection of rare books.
</P>
<P>
   And the company (octavo.com) scored a public relations coup last
fall by having its books chosen to be among Salon magazine's staple
giveaway goodies, given to new subscribers, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Public Library recently granted Octavo exclusive
digital rights to its entire collection (an Octavo edition of Alice
in Wonderland, with original drawings by Sir John Tenniel, is
planned); the Library of Congress, the Library Company of
Philadelphia, the Bridwell Library at Southern Methodist University
and the National Academy of Sciences have all signed similar
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Octavo recruits scholars to contribute introductory essays and
commentary for each title, and in some cases commissions new
translations.
</P>
<P>
   Octavo's technical production process is laborious. Each book is
laid in a custom-built cradle, then painstakingly lit to capture
all details of the binding, paper texture, ink spread and
impressions left by printing apparatus. The books are photographed
using a Better Light digital camera, also used by NASA for
technical analysis and by metropolitan police departments for
criminal forensics work.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting images have a resolution of 8,000 by 10,000
pixels, and use about 750 megabytes of memory per page. The
standard television screen is 640 by 480 pixels. The images are
compressed to about 10 megabytes each, and then processed and
formatted into PDF's (portable document files) by a bank of Apple
G3 computers running round-the-clock. At this point, the entire
book may be set in live text, so it will be completely searchable.
</P>
<P>
   Most Octavo editions have around 1,000 bookmarks to help readers
navigate them. Browsing the books with Adobe Reader software
(included on each disk), users can magnify any part of any page by
up to 800 percent without compromising the sharpness of the images.
</P>
<P>
   The executive editor of Octavo, E.M. Ginger, said such
fastidious processing is necessary. ``You get just as much
information from the type and the paper and the way it's laid out
as you get from the text itself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she described in detail the trail of a bookworm that
burrowed through Octavo's version of Copernicus, which led her in
turn to an even more passionate narration about foxing (marks made
left by fungus or moisture, named for their resemblance to the
color of the animal's coat) that marks Octavo's edition of Benjamin
Franklin's ``Experiments and Observations on Electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   The only subject on which Octavo officials are less than
articulate is marketing. Nobody at the company really knows who's
going to buy the books. Ames said the disks, which are available at
www.amazon.com, barnesandnoble.com, a few independent bookstores
and directly from Octavo's Web site, are selling to ``bibliophiles,
librarians, academics and students, professionals and digerati.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But whether this will translate into profits remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what the desires in this market are, because
there is no market,'' Ms. Gringer said. ``It's a very difficult
position for a company to be in. This is not books, this is not
software, this is something else entirely, and that's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not anybody buys this, or whether it becomes a
sensation, or whether we're even going to get into the black is
anybody's guess. We don't know.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One reason they don't know is that the company does not have a
full-time marketing person. For now, Octavo does its marketing
research mostly by surfing the Internet. A Stanford University
graduate student in English who works part-time at Octavo spends
her days looking, for instance, for Episcopal groups who might buy
the company's first-edition ``Book of Common Praier'' in bulk, or
for Latter-Day Saints who might snap up Joseph Smith's original
``Book of Mormon,''
</P>
<P>
   None of this should be too surprising, given the origins of
Octavo. Although the company hopes to turn a profit, it was created
by Warnock, an avid collector of old manuscripts, as more or less a
labor of love. Of course, it is easier to let labor be ruled by
love when one is head of a major, if somewhat embattled, software
company.
</P>
<P>
   Octavo's second funding cycle begins early this year, and
although Ames said he and Warnock were courting a variety of
venture capitalists, he's hoping for an investor who will provide a
no-strings cash infusion. Octavo is also considering partnerships
with conventional publishers, but Ames said he's not making serious
overtures to the incipient electronic book market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our core charter is accessibility and affordability, it's
not very smart for us to put a lot of our efforts into that,'' he
said, citing the high prices of the electronic books and what he
calls the ``pitiful'' screen resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   The company's strategy, at this point, is clearly scattershot,
driven primarily by the employees' own enthusiasms. ``I'm choosing
things that I think are fascinating,'' Ms. Ginger said.
</P>
<P>
   At an Octavo marketing meeting not long ago, Ames and Octavo's
seven employees gathered in the company conference room to hear Ms.
Ginger's sales pitch for a new Octavo edition: the 1524 Tory Book
of Hours.
</P>
<P>
   She began by explaining the genre. Between the late 13th century
and the early 16th century, wealthy Christians in Europe
commissioned the illustrated prayer books. They were the ultimate
status symbols in Christendom, so prized that noble families
sometimes went broke to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times in half an hour, Ms. Ginger used the word
``incredible'' to describe the ``Book of Hours'' (produced by
Geoffrey Tory, the first royal printer in France), which she'd just
seen at the Library of Congress. Showing a reproduction of the
book's elaborate illuminations, she exclaimed, ``The bugs! The
twigs! The sheer beauty of this piece just overwhelmed me!''
</P>
<P>
   An employee mentioned merchandising possibilities: ``Could we
make posters with some of these pictures? Screen savers? Mouse
pads?'' But mostly, the conversation was limited to a discussion of
the book itself.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked exactly how the book's first readers used the
texts, Ms. Ginger said: ``It's a certain kind of day, so you'd go
to the book to find out what prayer you should say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like, `How can I get past the marketing meeting?''' offered
one employee.
</P>
<P>
   Ames looked him in the eye, not missing a beat. ``Exactly,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
