<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDNEW-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AND OUT ... THAT`S WHAT FASHION IS ALL ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It seems like a distant memory _ those
``Titanic'' necklaces sporting giant blue rhinestones, sexy dresses
bearing religious icons, Zegna ties just like the president's.
</P>
<P>
   Those ``it'' items that seemed so fashion forward in 1998 now
are sooo last year. But thanks to a healthier economy, some
nostalgia-driven films and a political scandal or two, the last 12
months offered fads galore _ even a few that may survive the
finicky fashion front and live well into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Chanel No. 5 perfume, capri pants, mules, flannel pajamas,
twinsets, swing dancing and black-and-white movies all made a
comeback even before we visited ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   Feathers and faux-fur trim showed up on everything from tank
tops to ball gowns, accompanied by a gradual return of real fur
after spending a decade on fashion's black list.
</P>
<P>
   If you bought into any of it, keep it. 1950s mania, including
the Hollywood glam of that era, will be with us throughout 1999,
predict fashion experts, including Tommy Hilfiger and L.A. designer
Judy Rabineau. The designer for Mica dresses, Rabineau has included
several ``Pleasantville'' housedresses in her spring collection,
and she thinks full skirts hemmed below the knee will be the next
big trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Vogue pattern company has also gone retro, reintroducing
some of its best post-World War II suit patterns, which may
introduce Gen Xers to home sewing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Neiman Marcus spokeswoman Beverly Morgan says
everyone is looking forward to the return of color in our
wardrobes, and L.A.'s Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising
spokeswoman Maggie Murray agrees, especially in the shoe
department. The curator of the school's annual exhibit of
Oscar-nominated costumes, Murray says pastel-colored flats and
high-heeled sandals will be hot tickets in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   And the city's rising young designer Eduardo Lucero claims hot
pink and olive green will be the color combo of the year. Or at
least spring.
</P>
<P>
   The continuation of classic American sportswear is what Saks
Fifth Avenue fashion director Kelly Bevan Spirer predicts we'll be
seeing and wearing. She added that it's everywhere, even on
European runways.
</P>
<P>
   Among the styles associated with American sportswear is the
drawstring waist, which Lucero put on ball-gown skirts two years
ago but found the public wasn't ready for it. Now they are, and
you'll be seeing that waist style on men's and women's clothing by
a number of designers, even though it's very unflattering to all
but Kate Moss and Calista Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of menswear details, Fashion Association spokesman Leon
Hall says the long-sleeved polo shirt will be the next big trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was shiny shirts and matching ties that made men
feel special about the way they looked, but now it's a
silk-and-cashmere blend polo shirt in cherry red, rust or camel
worn under a blazer or suit,'' says Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Denim is in again. Not just the newer dark denim Levis with the
'50s-inspired cuff, but denim prairie skirts with white cotton
petticoats and denim motocross jackets teamed with peasant blouses
that look like the kind sold on Olvera Street in downtown Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Ethereal fabrics are still hot, especially if they're in a Maid
Marian dress, but gingham, eyelet and wrinkle-free linen are
fresher.
</P>
<P>
   Knits remain strong, so St. John suits will still reign as the
lunch-bunch uniform, but as spring approaches you may want to
consider a girlish dress like the kind Donna Reed wore when she
served cookies and milk to the kids. Or a ``Sabrina'' dress with a
full skirt and spaghetti straps.
</P>
<P>
   Dressing up in general, and the etiquette that goes with
black-tie galas, continues to be hot, although you're going to see
more invitations with ``cocktail attire'' as the suggested dress
code.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the office, there's a backlash to the casual Friday
dress code, so expect to see men wearing dress shirts with French
cuffs more often than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, it may be a challenge for history's hemline
watchers since the economy is up, but hemlines are down, hovering
between the bottom of the knee and the top of the ankle. However,
women's pants are getting shorter.
</P>
<P>
   On the must-have list for '99 are all lengths of capri pants and
clam diggers designed to expose a well-turned ankle, much like the
skirts worn at the turn of the last century. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
