r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-06 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND BREATHES DEEPLY AS BROWN BEGINS TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Oakland's first day with Jerry Brown as mayor
began in stereotypical Jerry Brown fashion _ with a meditation at
his industrial-sized live-work space near Jack London Square.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, a meditation is pure Jerry Brown, who was dubbed
``Governor Moonbeam'' when he was California's top elected official
25 years ago. But as someone at the early Monday morning session
pointed out, it isn't all that different from the prayer breakfast
held 22 years ago when Lionel Wilson became Oakland's first African
American _ and rare Democratic _ mayor, breaking the political grip
of conservative white Republican men.
</P>
<P>
   To Zach Wasserman, an attorney who has advised past Oakland
mayors, Brown's election is comparable to that of Wilson in 1977.
``People voted for change,'' Wasserman said. ``There is now a sense
of new hope, of renewal, just as there was when Lionel was
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's mayoralty ushers in yet another, ill-defined turning
point for the East Bay's largest city, overshadowed as it is by San
Francisco. Brown moved from San Francisco five years ago to
continue an eclectic political journey that has included several
presidential runs.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolic of Oakland's new phase was the meditation led by Sharon
Salzberg for about 200 people of different races and faiths.
Salzberg began by pointing out the virtues of breathing deeply,
relaxing and allowing one's mind to conjure up images and inner
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   One meditates to ``check to see what assumptions we hold'' and
to learn to ``take care of what's right in front of us, which sets
the stage for what comes next,'' Salzberg said. ``We are all
interconnected ... No one is really isolated ... We meditate to
recognize a vast web of interconnectedness.''
</P>
<P>
   She then led the group in a ``friendship'' meditation that
lasted 20 minutes, a ``practice to honor our sense of community, (a
practice that tells us) no one can make it alone and that we can
inspire one another.''
</P>
<P>
   That message meshed with what the Brown said later in his
inaugural address in the newly refurbished City Hall Plaza before
an attentive and enthusiastic crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I make a solemn promise to be a catalyst for change.
But I cannot work for change alone. I need each of you to commit
yourselves with me to work change for the common good. ... We must
change and move beyond inwardly turning self interest to interest
in the common good. We must see one another as brothers and
sisters,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I am only one person with flaws, and in my 60 years
I have made mistakes, but I commit to each of you that I will
strive to my utmost to continually change within myself. I do not
pretend to know all the right questions, much less have all the
right answers. And even if I did, it wouldn't make much difference
unless the government I propose becomes an ongoing dynamic process
in which all of you are not only heard, but truly engaged. Only
then can a consensus of action emerge which speaks the will of the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual inspiration is one thing. Connecting to the gritty
secular world of urban problems of which Oakland has an abundance
is quite another. So Brown pledged a fourfold agenda: Reduce crime,
bring 10,000 people to live downtown, help parents establish public
charter schools, encourage arts and cultural expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural day ended with a rousing festival of performing arts
and neighborhood information booths. Public Oakland was upbeat on
Jerry Brown's first day as mayor. He has instilled hope and
excitement in a city that has more often than not sulked in the
wake of negative perceptions. All in all, a noteworthy start of a
new political era.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (William Wong is an independent journalist and San Francisco
Examiner columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
