<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Nurturing Lantanas &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This fall I saw a collection of beautiful lantana trees at
Planting Fields Arboretum in Oyster Bay, N.Y. I thought lantana was
an annual flower plant and was stunned to see the trees. Where can
I purchase one? Do they have any special requirements? Are they
hardy?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The common lantana, L. camara, is a woody shrub in warm
climates, an annual anywhere it encounters freezing temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Though lantanas are not difficult to grow (in the tropics,
they're weeds), considerable training is required to turn them into
the seven-foot trees you saw at Planting Fields, which are known in
the trade as standards.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dose, the greenhouse manager at Planting Fields, says it is
easy enough to do the training, but it is tough to winter the
plants in a home setting. They drop their leaves and go almost
dormant, but they cannot be stored in a basement because some light
is still needed. At Planting Fields, they are crowded into a cool
greenhouse. You could use a north-facing room that stayed at about
50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In case you do have a place to store them _ or want to try the
technique on a fuchsia, hibiscus or heliotrope, to name three other
common tropicals that take well to standardization _ here is how:
start with a small plant that has a long central stem. Supply it
with a stake that can act as a guide and anchor until the standard
can stand up straight on its own (somewhere between three years and
never).
</P>
<P>
   Take off the side branches, and as the plant grows, pinch out
all of the side shoots. Tie the stem to the stake frequently, so it
doesn't sag. Keep it up until the stem is about three-fourths of
the height you want. Be sure there are at least 8 or 10 growth
nodes below the top, then pinch off the tip to encourage branching.
Pinch the branches of the plants once they get going to make them
branch again.
</P>
<P>
   You will have something presentable in two or three years.
Alternatively, you can buy one ready-made, and though it will not
be as magnificent as the 20- and 30-year-old specimens at Planting
Fields, it will still look pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   Standard lantanas are not a mail-order item, but are widely
offered in spring by large garden-supply stores, like Frank's,
which buy from wholesale suppliers of patio plants.
</P>
<P>
   Look for a straight, undamaged trunk (with no signs of trouble
around the graft), and main branches that are evenly distributed
around the top.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terrace Wintering &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently relocated my potted trees and shrubs from a
terrace open to the elements to a covered terrace with wind, some
sun and no rain. Should my trees and shrubs be watered over the
winter? Is it necessary to wrap the pots with burlap?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Wind can be very hard on plants, but unless the former
location was unusually well protected, yours should be used to it.
Same story with the sun; it doesn't sound as though too much is
going to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing to watch out for is a narrowly southern exposure.
Trunks and branches that get strong heat on one side while the
other side stays cold can develop cracks.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be on watering duty big time next summer, but during the
winter, be careful not to overdo. Your plants should be dormant _
or close to it _ by now, and although they still need some water,
too much will lead to rot. All that's necessary is enough to keep
the roots moist.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Christo question, the thing you would want to wrap
with burlap would be the plants, not the pots.
</P>
<P>
   Burlap is an overcoat that shields trees from drying wind,
scorching sun and branch-breaking ice and snow. But I wouldn't use
it unless I absolutely had to. Burlap's sun-block aspect means
plants can bleach or starve if you don't take it off soon enough.
The dank environment it creates can lead to fungus problems. And
you have to look at it.
</P>
<P>
   As long as your new terrace isn't absolutely arctic, you can
just group the plants away from the wind, near an inside wall, and
let them wait out the winter relatively undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
