<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GARDEN-DESIGN-2TA     01-06 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GARDEN-DESIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL GARDENING: LOSE MORE THAN CALLUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Katherine Whiteside is a gardening writer. A book she wrote with
Madison Cox on garden design will be published by Henry Holt this
year.  
 By KATHERINE WHITESIDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Make no mistake: making a garden is outdoor work. So I was a bit
skeptical of garden design software promising that ``you can create
an outdoor paradise without leaving your chair.''
</P>
<P>
   I have been a garden writer for 16 years and, for the last 6
have been wrestling a one-acre plot into some sort of garden that
makes design sense. So I know that I can write about gardens
without leaving my chair, but creating an outdoor paradise means I
have to get up and get out there.
</P>
<P>
   But checking out a few brand-new tools is always appealing. I am
redesigning the stone entryway into our garden, and maybe one of
these programs could streamline my usual technique of hauling stuff
around the yard until it looks right. I have some pictures ripped
out of magazines, and I've scribbled down some ideas on paper, but
it could be a terrific time saver to have a garden design program
that shows me how the new entrance will look before I start lugging
those big rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, as the first snows start falling, a design program might
hold some appeal for the many garden enthusiasts who are already
thinking ahead to next spring and want to get a jump on their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Because I know a lot more about gardening than I do about
computers, I examined these programs with Paul Heuston, a
consultant in software development for training and education who
has extensive experience with computer-driven interactive teaching.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Paul has a lovely old house and a three-acre
undeveloped garden that he has been bugging me about for two years.
Other great helpers in these reviews were Brian Higley, a landscape
architect; Madison Cox, a principal in Madison Cox Designs, an
international garden design firm, and Anne Symmes, a garden
designer who is a graduate of the New York Botanical Garden
Landscape Design Program.
</P>
<P>
   Our review team was large, and each of us had real reasons for
wanting these design programs to work. But in the end, all the
programs had at least one major area of underdevelopment that
canceled out any hopes for usefulness, even though various programs
handled some aspects of gardening fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   Higley summed up our joint frustration by saying, ``You can hand
a person all the hammers, files and nails that a blacksmith uses,
but unless that person knows horses, the shoe is just not going to
go on that hoof.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, gardening people are eternally optimistic. At the end of
the review process, we brainstormed on what sort of software would
truly be helpful for both amateur and professional garden makers.
We agreed that one would be a good plant encyclopedia, compiled by
a botanical garden or some other reliable source.
</P>
<P>
   Cox found the CD-ROM of Michael A. Dirr's Photo-Library of Woody
Landscape Plants (Plant America; $149.95) to be useful. Ms. Symmes
agreed and said she was considering buying it. She mentioned that
she had looked at the Plant Master 5.0 CD-ROM (Acacia Software,
$350), a database intended for landscape professionals that
includes a catalog of more than 5,000 North American plants, at a
New York Botanical Garden symposium on gardening software and liked
the fact that Plant Master could be tailored to the needs of the
user.
</P>
<P>
   We tacked on a wish for a CD-ROM on garden history _ perhaps a
combination of The Oxford Companion to Gardens, Thacker's History
of Gardens and other classic references. With that, the three
professionals left _ one to inspect 20 antique apple trees, another
to conduct a site visit and the last to finish a watercolor for a
client presentation.
</P>
<P>
   I went home and lugged rocks around the garden. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRO LANDSCAPE 5.0  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Autodesk; $795.95; Windows 95 and NT.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, like some gardeners, you have inherited a gene for always
picking out the most expensive thing in the store, your first
choice for garden-design software would be Autodesk's Pro
Landscape, an $800 program designed for professionals in the garden
business.
</P>
<P>
   It made me a little nervous that the box said the software was
for landscape architects, designers and contractors, with ``no
previous drawing experience necessary,'' because it seemed as
though all those people really needed to know how to draw. Also
``SHOW AND SELL!'' was written in big red letters right over a
photograph of a really hideous front yard with a pink tree, a white
shrub and six little blobs plopped in what appeared to be
neon-green Astroturf. But if the hype was off-putting, the
installation was straightforward _ until we decided to plug in the
tutorial. Then it crashed two times.
</P>
<P>
   Only after we succeeded in getting Pro Landscape running did we
begin to realize that its problems might not be limited to the
technical aspects of the program. Take plant hardiness zones, the
information every potential garden maker needs to know before
planning a landscape. The hardiness zone system is simple, with 10
zones (10 being really hot and 1 really cold) that cover the entire
United States. Zone maps are widely available in every garden book.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison, N.Y., where Paul Heuston has his garden, is on the
border of Zones 5 and 6. The Autodesk program, however,
categorically stated that he was in zone 6, failing to take into
account that elevation and exposure makes some areas a bit colder.
Given that, he would be much safer starting out with Zone 5
material instead of the riskier plants suitable for the warmer
temperatures of Zone 6. Important information had been
oversimplified.
</P>
<P>
   Next we scanned in a photograph of Heuston's house so we could
begin messing around with the design. The house popped up on the
screen, but there was no room to design a garden around it, and
there was very little depth of field. Heuston has three acres, but
the only room given for plant placement was right against the
house.
</P>
<P>
   But Heuston was still optimistic about getting his place fixed
up, so we moved on to the plant choice section of the program. When
he typed in ``trees, Zone 5'' I was dismayed to see only three
types of cherry trees listed and confused to see false aralia
listed. False aralia (Dizygotheca) is native to New Caledonia and
Polynesia and would croak outside a steamy Zone 10.
</P>
<P>
   We went back and picked out one of the program's house images to
try to play designer again. Even with an image supplied by the
program (and I can't figure out what help it is to create a garden
for a nonexistent house), the field of design was so narrow that we
ended up, in a rather childish fashion, obscuring the house with
three giant, garish evergreens, one enormous cotton-candy blob of a
cherry tree and a harvest-gold carpet of ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness to the Autodesk product, I also asked Brian
Higley about his professional experience with Autodesk's Auto Cad,
and he said that such muscular design programs required a lot of
time, perhaps a year, to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software can be a great tool for repetitious drawing, some
imaging and sharing information,'' Higley said, ``but it cannot
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``The programs can do cool things like move from
one-quarter-scale all the way up to full scale. But, frankly, I do
not use any software at all for design purposes. It takes me too
far from real design.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPLETE LAND DESIGNER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra; $49.95; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Complete Land Designer was the only box that had a
nice-looking garden and, because it came with four features _ 3-D
Landscape, Photo Land Designer, Garden Encyclopedia and 3-D Deck _
this computer amateur was hopeful about getting some help with that
stone entryway.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Autodesk program, scanning photos was not helpful.
There was no way that this program could help me imagine the
possibilities of my walkway because there was no depth of field, so
we gave up and looked at the images the program offered. (Once
again, I cannot figure out how using a picture of another house
would be helpful. It's like trying to make an apple pie using only
oranges.)
</P>
<P>
   The design process was confusing. Even after choosing Zone 5,
the program allowed Paul Heuston to select and plant the following
up against the brick wall of a generic house: a datura (the one
that showed up was definitely a tropical species), a bonsai (by
definition, a potted dwarf plant), an impossibly huge pink begonia
(brown mush by the first frost), and a nice Liquidambar tree that
totally obscured two windows. We looked for some ornamental grasses
but were shown only seven, each one identically labeled
``ornamental grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Heuston picked one and accidentally ``grew it'' (by hitting the
wrong button) to a giant size. As a joke, we then moved the
impossibly large clump to the roof of the house and found that we
couldn't get it off again. There were not enough Undo choices, and
there just wasn't enough control over the program.
</P>
<P>
   We installed the separate Garden Encyclopedia, but the scarcity
of material was far too evident. We printed out the selections for
``Zone 5, partial sun, white flowers, vine growing to 15 feet,''
but I only got two choices. The printout on one choice, Rosa
wichuraiana, said it was 6 inches tall and 25 feet wide. I wondered
where all this would lead a gardening novice: the program seemed to
require an experienced gardener on hand to correct such
misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Heuston spent more hours than he would tell me in
the 3-D section of the software, drawing a top view of his house.
The next day, he showed me how he could also rotate this into a 3-D
front view and how we could move around (to the sound of footsteps)
_ although nothing on the screen reminded me even a litle of
Heuston's house or the land around it.
</P>
<P>
   He also designed a rudimentary garden (a few trees and shrubs)
with several features like front steps and an arbor, and he even
treated himself to a backyard hot tub. The program then provided
him with an astonishing and highly unlikely piece of information:
His garden would cost exactly $17,141.04.
</P>
<P>
   In the end we decided that Sierra's program was user-friendly
over all, but not useful. Heuston summed it up as ``a combination
screwdriver, wrench, pole vault.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Higley, a landscape architect, agreed. ``The software
doesn't know much about lay of the land or sun orientation,'' he
said. ``An unsuspecting person could design a bed of sun-loving
herbs right underneath a huge shady canopy of oak. The program does
not support good or even sensible design.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LANDSCAPE ARCHITECT  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Softkey; $19.95; Windows 95 and 3.1 or higher.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The title of the third choice _ Landscape Architect _ might make
landscape architects bristle. ``A landscape architect has
university degrees and board certifications,'' said Brian Higley,
who is one. ``Would you buy software called Pediatrician for
$19.95?''
</P>
<P>
   After he calmed down, we found that installation was painless,
but once again the ``photo-realistic'' renderings were more than
painful. The images supplied had a rather offputting cartoonish
aspect. Higley soldiered on, but he stopped after one hour and
said: ``I can't even figure out how to make a line. This is the
most fundamental reflex in beginning a drawing, but I can't get
this to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The icons were not helpful, either. I looked in the booklet for
help, and the first item under Design Concepts read, ``Every object
in Landscape Architect knows what objects it contains and what
object contains it.'' Sure enough, there are bunches of little
bridges and fences, but design is not just dropping objects into a
garden.
</P>
<P>
   But we pressed on and looked into other Landscape Architect
features. I wanted to check out the plant database but was confused
by the information under General Deciduous Shrubs. For example, it
listed: ``Botanical name _ oval mound blue; maximum height _ 1.8;
age _ 8; height _ 1.2; Dormant _ not applicable.'' I'm familiar
with plant shorthand, but I couldn't decipher the code.
</P>
<P>
   The Deciduous Trees section was just as confounding. I looked up
the familiar weeping willow and was told: ``Maximum Height _ 10;
age _ 6; height _ 3; width _ 3.3; visible and growing _ all
seasons; dormant _ not applicable.'' Once again, the offering was
very confusing. Weeping willows grow to more than 10 feet tall, so
I wondered if the numbers referred to meters. But other parts of
the problem were in acres, not hectares, so that remained a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   A final foray into the program's ``see your garden in different
seasons and through the years'' was weird. As I moved through
spring, summer, fall and winter, fake trees around the generic
house changed from pink to green to red to gray. When I moved
through the years, the trees just suddenly shot up and hid the
house. Trust me: This is not how Mother Nature and Father Time act
in your garden. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
