<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLINTSTONE-HOUSE-ART-     01-06 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLINTSTONE-HOUSE-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 BUILDING UP TO BEDROCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAMY, N.M. _ Designing a home can be fraught with anxiety. In
Norah Pierson's case, it was a real cliffhanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be on the cliffs, in the drama,'' Ms. Pierson said
of the simulated rock house she designed to blend in with the
sandstone cliffs of Lamy. ``I guess I'm a drama queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Known locally as the Flintstone house, Ms. Pierson's wondrous
polyurethane-foam creation, which she scales occasionally, might be
called design on the rocks with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Encased in a rocky shell, the 2,300-square-foot home, which Ms.
Pierson, 58, a jeweler and artist, designed for herself in this
rugged speck of a railroad town about 20 miles southeast of Santa
Fe, may be the only house in America architecturally inspired by a
40-foot-long, 14-foot-high polyurethane stegosaurus.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pierson describes herself as a ``compulsive doer'' who, if
stuck on a desert island, would probably ``color-code the sand.''
In the early 1980s, she began camping out in the valley below these
stark, white Dakota sandstone cliffs at the edge of the Galisteo
basin. She knew she wanted to build a house but worried that it
would be ``a minus for the land.'' So she began exploring ways to
build a house and disguise it, to make a statement that ``nature is
more important than man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the legacy of cliff dwelling in New Mexico dates back
nearly 1,000 years, Ms. Pierson did not actually want to live in a
cave. ``I wasn't ready,'' she said, somewhat apologetically. ``I
didn't want a free-form interior where you can't own a book or hang
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Pierson, a daughter of the late Yale historian Charles
Wilson Pierson, is a professional jewelry designer, accustomed to
shaping abstract forms out of solid blocks of wax. It was doubtless
this conceptual ability that allowed her to see the sculptural
possibilities suggested by a nearby family of polyurethane-foam
dinosaurs _ nearly life size and gloriously visible from Interstate
25 _ that Larry Wilson, the president of a Santa Fe insulation
company, had built for his granddaughters in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything technically,'' Ms. Pierson recalled.
``But I had a fantasy about these dinosaurs, so I called him.''
</P>
<P>
   Her concept was to design a conventional frame-and-cinder-block
house on the cliff top and then camouflage it with foam _ about
10,000 pounds of it, as it turned out. Although Wilson's company,
Thermal Coatings and Insulation, had done only one house, a
geodesic dome, he saw no technical reason why Ms. Pierson's
spray-as-you-go design project couldn't be built.
</P>
<P>
   The material itself hardens to a tough shell and is typically
used to insulate roofs and walls.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Greg Ohlsen, a local builder, Ms. Pierson
designed and constructed a relatively straightforward house, on
five levels, with 20-foot ceilings and three fireplaces. She lived
in it for more than a year, studying the cliff forms below, before
covering the entire surface in wire lath and two-by-fours molded
into boulder outlines. They formed an armature for the foam
exoskeleton, applied with spray guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot more difficult than I anticipated,'' she recently
said of pseudo-cliff design. ``It was seat-of-the-pants. I hadn't
made a model.'' To make the lath into true-to-life shapes and
angles mimicking the rock face, complete with realistic overhangs,
she recalled, ``I would run down the cliff, look at the house and
say tilt!'' Essentially, she created a giant pinata.
</P>
<P>
   The house-spraying was not just artistically challenging, but
also an expensive and time-consuming task that lasted almost two
years (Ms. Pierson estimates that her foam rock shell wound up
costing three to four times more than a conventional surface). At
high altitudes, spraying is not for the impatient, since it
requires days of at least 50 degrees. In windy conditions, it is
also, in Ms. Pierson's words, ``a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to dedicate a full set of clothing and a pair of
glasses to it,'' she said. ``It gets all over everything, including
your eyelashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although historic Santa Fe has some of the strictest zoning in
the country, houses in Lamy, which is in Santa Fe County, are not
subject to architectural guidelines, said Rudy Garcia, the county's
land-use coordinator. Since Ms. Pierson's house was conventional in
structure, it conformed to local building codes, he said. Ms.
Pierson had no mortgage, but underwent what she calls
``unbelievable contortions'' to get insurance: she said the
unconventional surfacing material tripled her rates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pierson heightened the realism by painting the foam with a
tinted sealer, adding dark shadows in places to imitate lichen.
</P>
<P>
   Local birds knew better. Cavity-nesting red-shafted flickers,
who like synthetic materials, pecked through the fake sandstone to
roost. The noise was deafening, recalls Deborah Newberg, a painter
who housesits frequently. ``It was like living inside a tree,'' she
said. (Much to Ms. Pierson's delight, a pair of falcons recently
took up residence.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, from certain angles, the Flintstone house is indeed
inconspicuous _ though from a distance, both it and the cliffs
glint in the New Mexico sun like the mythical kingdom of El Dorado.
Closer, it resembles a moonscape.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Ms. Pierson's home feels light, cozy and not the least
bit surreal, except for a few foam crags visible through the
windows. A long staircase descends steeply from the entrance into
the bermed interior. One side contains the living room, bedroom and
kitchen; the other, her studio, where she designs pieces in a style
she calls ``ancient futurism,'' many of them vaguely Etruscan. Both
her jewelry and the house _ shared with two cats, a dog, three
turtles and assorted fish and frogs _ are informed by a passion for
animals, archeology and bones.
</P>
<P>
   She has filled the house with stones, African goddesses and
other objects that reflect a girlhood in which Yale's Peabody
Museum was, as she said, her ``baby sitter.'' A love of jewelry was
born in the Egyptian galleries of the Metropolitan Museum of Art,
where said she left ``fingerprints and nose prints'' all over the
glass.
</P>
<P>
   After art school, Ms. Pierson lived in Rome, where she started
her career. In 1981, she opened her store in Santa Fe, the Golden
Eye. Before long, she was planning her house. ``Jewelry is one inch
by one inch,'' she said. ``To do something on this scale was so
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The product of a singular imagination, her house fits into a
grand New Mexican tradition of alternative architecture, from
stage-set plaster pueblos to Route 66 curio shops. Chris Wilson,
author of ``The Myth of Santa Fe'' (University of New Mexico Press,
1997), links Taos communes and houses made from straw bale, tires
and beer cans _ even the ubiquitous adobe revival style itself _ to
the romantic ideal of New Mexico as a place that is ``wind-swept
and water-shaped, an exotic, aboriginal landscape that lends itself
to the idea of growing out of the soil.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Flintstone house has itself become a
roadside attraction. It is a landmark on the Santa Fe Southern
Railway, a tourist and freight train that has revived the 18-mile
spur line between Lamy and Santa Fe, laid out in 1880 for the
Atchison, Topeka &AMP; Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get so immersed in the process you forget that what you're
doing is unusual,'' Ms. Pierson.
</P>
<P>
   At night you can sometimes find her up on the roof, listening to
coyotes and communing with the moon, surrounded by a landscape both
real and unreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
