<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FINANCES-ONLINE-N     01-06 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FINANCES-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB LUST: MORE MONEY, MORE STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A person can live blissfully for 37 years without a coffee
table, then one day suddenly look at the big empty area in the
center of the living-room rug and realize: it's all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This epiphany occurred at a party recently, as I watched my
guests awkwardly balancing plates of food on their knees. Soon
after, I embarked on a search for the perfect coffee table with the
sort of zealous fervor usually associated with a religious convert.
</P>
<P>
   I dragged home two tables from a secondhand furniture store, but
one proved too small, the other too red. I returned them. From an
antiques store, I borrowed a table with a more expensive price tag
of $350; it was rickety. For a while, a round one with a glass top
was promising. But the baby crawled under it, got stuck and flailed
on her back like a specimen in a petri dish.
</P>
<P>
   The universe of available coffee tables suddenly seemed small.
Luckily, the Internet can provide a Big Bang. While questions may
remain about the original cosmic explosion, I can attest that the
online version has more than once expanded my choices miraculously.
So I went to  &UR; www.hotbot.com &LR;  to search for Art Deco furniture.
</P>
<P>
   This is how I ended up at  &UR; www.modernism.com &LR; , belonging to a
furniture dealer in Coral Gables, Fla. On the site, I saw a
snapshot of, well, the most beautiful coffee table in existence.
Not too big, not too small, not red at all. Eagerly, I sent a
polite e-mail inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The prompt response came on Nov. 25. ``Dear Michelle, the price
is $4,500, which includes packing, insurance and shipping within
the continental United States.''
</P>
<P>
   I read that repeatedly, trying to process the fact that a piece
of wooden furniture, 44 inches in diameter, cost roughly as much as
my first car. Quickly I replied, declaring the table to be beyond
my budget.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next few days, as I hauled home and later returned
a sharp-cornered, orangish $50 table on which the baby managed to
cut her lip, I kept returning to my computer to stare at the very,
 &UR; very &LR;  expensive coffee table. Have I mentioned that it was
constructed of African rosewood (whatever that is)?
</P>
<P>
   The impulse that led me to the Internet in the first place _ the
fact that I hate to be thwarted _ had now planted a dangerous idea
in my head: I had to get that table.
</P>
<P>
   On a practical level, I realized that even toying with the idea
of throwing away my children's college funds was a severe
indictment of my character. But I no longer cared. They can get
scholarships, I thought. Meanwhile, I will entertain beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   But first, I needed to rationalize the purchase. So I went to
Moneyminded  &UR; (www.moneyminded.com) &LR; , a Web site whose goal is to
help women get control of their finances. My covert goal:
persuading this Web site to convince me that my finances were in
better shape than they appeared to my accountant.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a nice selection of quizzes that allow you to plug
in figures like household income and projected investment returns
to determine if you are headed for retirement-on-a-yacht
commercials or for a broken, penniless old age.
</P>
<P>
   I was taken aback when a quick scan of the site yielded no
``Should you buy that expensive coffee table?'' quiz. However, I
lingered for a while on the amusing ``How Much Should That Home
Repair Cost?'' calculator. There I learned that a plumber charges,
on average, $72 to fix an overflowing toilet. In the New York area,
add 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amusing, yes, but not what I needed. It occurred to me then that
a house without the perfect coffee table could be considered a
broken house, in need of repair. If one applied the plumbing
equation to a broken house, it would be necessary to factor in an
hourly labor rate for time spent fretting over a coffee table. (I
think $100 an hour would be fair, $150 if it occurs when you should
be asleep.) Figuring, conservatively, that there was one hour of
fretting, that's $150 right there. And this is to say nothing of
the cost of cleaning up spilled party food ($3.99 for carpet
fluid), the broken plate ($6), plus a modest $1,000 settlement for
pain and suffering endured by the owner of the broken home. This
would bring the average cost to $1,159.99, plus a 32 percent
differential in the New York area: a grand total of $1,531.19.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this method of calculation was flawed, because the
total came nowhere near the cost of the rosewood coffee table. But
elsewhere on the Moneyminded site, I could ascertain the general
state of my household's financial health. To see if I was saving
enough for retirement, I entered annual income, number of years
until retirement, savings and investments, and then pressed the
key.
</P>
<P>
   I had anticipated the response: ``Wow, you've been diligent. So
go out and treat yourself to that coffee table.'' Instead, I got:
``Caution! You need to get serious about saving for retirement and
simply can't afford to wait any longer.'' The Web site advised me
to increase my retirement savings by $8,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Panicky, I reviewed my answers, and then hit on a solution: What
if I changed them? What if I projected a 15 percent annual return
on retirement investments? And increased the number of years left
until retirement from 30 to, say, 50? After all, my husband and I
are writers, not professional athletes. Why would we ever have to
retire?
</P>
<P>
   It worked. The new response: ``Take it easy! You may be saving
for retirement too aggressively.'' It recommended saving $0 a year
for the rest of our lives _ instantly freeing up valuable coffee
table funds.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I fully understood the state of my household finances,
I realized I was a rich woman. I could afford the coffee table. I
peeked at its image again and realized ... I no longer wanted it.
But I do have my eye on a $9,800 mirror-paneled night table that
recently caught my eye.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
