<HEADER>
A1550 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     01-06 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE SHOWS ITS COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a barrage of introductions that blended
technological prowess with a delightful sense of style and fun,
Apple Computer this week introduced a powerful new line of desktop
computer systems in a color scheme it calls translucent blueberry
and ice, as well as an array of improved iMac computers that come
in an assortment of colors including blueberry, grape, lime,
tangerine and strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Although translucent blueberry is its major color theme, Apple
is clearly not singing the blues any more. At the Macworld Expo
trade show here, Apple disclosed that it is in the black for the
fifth consecutive quarter after a disastrous two-year stretch that
nearly pushed the fabled Silicon Valley company into irrelevance.
</P>
<P>
   PC Data, a market research company, recently calculated that
Apple had doubled its share of the domestic computer market in
1998, to 10 percent, in large part because of the sale of 800,000
iMac computers since the model was introduced less than five months
ago. According to Apple, 32 percent of those iMacs went to people
who had never bought a personal computer before, and 13 percent to
people who were switching from Windows systems.
</P>
<P>
   Added up, all those numbers confirm momentum for Apple. Even
people who use computers based on Microsoft Windows should be
cheered, because Apple is doing a better job than any other PC
company today at bringing excitement and innovation back to an
industry that has often been boring and beige.
</P>
<P>
   Apple still does not have a computer that competes in the
under-$1,000 price category, which has been a magic level for PC
companies, although it did cut the price of the iMac this week by
$100, to $1,199. And there were no signs here of the
much-anticipated ``consumer portable,'' a low-cost Mac laptop that
Apple promises will be ready in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those modest disappointments, Apple's new blueberry
Power Macintosh G3 desktop computers, which start at $1,599, are
very likely to turn Mac users, and even some Windows PC users,
green with envy. It is too soon for a formal evaluation _ the
machines were closely guarded until Tuesday's introduction _ but
first impressions appear to bear out Apple's claims that the G3s
match or exceed any other PCs, whether used for work or play.
</P>
<P>
   Just as with the original iMacs, the first thing you notice
about the G3s is the distinctive blue-and-white design. From the
side, they resemble a big pillow, with peaked but rounded corners
that conveniently and cleverly serve as handles. The side opens
easily from the top, folding down to display, in relatively
uncluttered fashion, all of the expansion slots and bays that most
users will want to fool with.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, no other personal computer on the market makes it so
easy to get inside the box to add more memory or extra storage
devices. The open-door design is so elegant that some of us will
probably leave it open all the time, just to admire the components
and circuitry laid out like a scale model of a silicon city's
buildings and streets.
</P>
<P>
   On the G3's pretty blue backside is an array of high-speed
connection ports, including two Universal Serial Bus outlets (for
connecting the new generation of USB-compliant monitors, printers,
keyboards, mice, scanners and other common peripherals) and,
looking to the future, two very fast Firewire connection ports that
some day soon will be useful for connecting digital video cameras,
high-speed storage devices and other high-end peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   USB represents a significant improvement in performance and ease
of use over older connection schemes like the Apple Desktop Bus
(ADB). Apple has retained one ADB port to enable people to connect
their older peripherals. But, Apple warned, the ADB port will
eventually be eliminated, joining the SCSI (``scuzzy'') connection
scheme in obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who have SCSI peripherals that are not yet ready
for the scrap heap, Apple offers a $50 adapter card that plugs into
one of the four expansion slots inside the G3.
</P>
<P>
   The USB ports will make it easy to replace the icky mouse and
keyboard that are standard with the new G3 desktops. Some people
have come to love, or at least tolerate, the hockey-puck mouse and
skeletal keyboard that Apple introduced with the iMac, but I am not
among them. Gamers will also want to add a decent set of USB
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Such quibbles over feeble peripherals should not overshadow the
power of the new G3 models, however. There are three, increasingly
powerful versions of a new Power PC microprocessor that uses a
copper wiring scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The base G3 model, which costs $1,599, includes a 300-MHz Power
PC chip with 64 megabytes of DRAM, 512 kilobytes of level 2
backside cache, a 6-gigabyte hard disk, a 24X-speed CD-ROM drive,
an Ethernet network connection port along with USB and Firewire
and, in an improvement certain to excite game players, an ATI Rage
128 graphics controller with a whopping 16 megabytes of video
memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The ATI Rage 128 chip, in fact, is now included in all the G3
Macs, which simply means that the Macintosh is now a screaming game
machine. Owners of Windows-based machines can come close to
achieving similar performance by adding a $200 graphics card to the
fastest PCs, but Apple has chosen to make such performance standard
on the G3 line.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of midlevel G3 machines, at base prices of $1,999 and
$2,499, employ a 350-MHz version of the Power PC chip and 1 MB of
cache memory, further enhancing the machine's performance. The
$2,499 model includes a Zip drive and an extra 64 MB of DRAM, as
well as the other features of the base model.
</P>
<P>
   At the high end, $2,999 will buy a G3 Mac that includes a
400-MHz chip, 128 MB RAM, 1 MB of backside cache, a fast 9-GB hard
disk and a CD-ROM drive. At the really high end, both in terms of
performance and price, the new G3s can be rigged with a staggering
1 GB of system memory and more than 100 GB of internal storage,
consisting of a trio of 36-GB hard drives that Apple says will be
available soon.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve its goal of becoming the best game machine, Apple has
to convince more game developers to resume writing software for the
Mac. To that end, Apple also provided an early peek at the Virtual
Game Station, a $50 software product from the Connectix Corp. that
allows Macs to play most of the games available for the popular
Sony Playstation game console.
</P>
<P>
   The superb graphics capabilities of the G3 models deserve to be
shown off on a high-quality display, and Apple has three new ones
to offer.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have $1,499 to spend, a big, stout desk and no
fear of hernias, Apple's massive new 21-inch monitor is a luxurious
and impressive display. Graphics professionals will admire its
automatic color-calibration abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have considerably less desk space will appreciate the
revamped 15-inch Studio Display flat-panel monitor, which has a
newly lowered price of $1,099. For everyone else, there is a new
17-inch monitor with a wallet-friendly $499 list price. All three
displays share the blueberry and ice color scheme of the new G3
desktop Macs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new iMacs, the technical improvements over the
original models consist of a slightly faster processor (a 266-MHz
G3 chip) and a bigger hard disk (6 GB). Otherwise, the major
changes are the addition of all the new colors and the lower price.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp., meanwhile, reaffirmed its commitment to the
Macintosh community here by releasing two new Mac software products
_ the Internet Explorer 4.5 Web browser and the Outlook Express 4.5
mail manager _ as well as a new Internet Web site devoted expressly
to Macintosh users (www.microsoft.com/mac). As before, the price of
the programs is right: free. And you get far more than you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer 4.5 in particular is a welcome upgrade, with a
number of compelling performance advantages over its main rival
from Netscape, including features that are not available on any
Windows browsers. Microsoft claims that the new Mac version is
easier to download and install, more reliable (i.e., it crashes
less frequently), faster to boot into memory and more clever in
keeping track of pages that have been viewed already.
</P>
<P>
   One of many praiseworthy features is a new ``print preview''
function that allows people to print copies of Web pages much more
easily than before, without chopped margins and paper-wasting
second sheets for those few lines of ancillary junk at the bottom
of many Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   With print preview, pages can be shrunk to fit on a single sheet
of paper, cluttered backgrounds can be eliminated, white text on
colored backgrounds can be transposed to black on white, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Apple reopened its online Apple store
(www.store.apple.com) this week after shutting it down over the
holidays. In a case of welcome failure, the site was temporarily
overwhelmed, apparently by people eager to place orders for the new
Macs. Apple must be tickled pink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
