<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNER JOURNEY HAS DANGEROUS PATCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, I'm on my way to Mississippi on ice, and my heart has taken
up residence someplace outside my chest. Not permanently. Not in
any one place. It moves frequently between my chest and my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I am so tense that I speak only to tell Jimmy to slow down, to
watch that car, or to warn Jamila, forever thinking out loud, to
quiet down.
</P>
<P>
   I notice Asha, at peace in the seat behind her father, reading
another of those Baby-Sitters Club books that she loves so much. I
wish for the days when Jamila was more this way, so much so that
the words break loose from my lips like water overflowing a dam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamila, you used to be so sweet,'' I sputter. I want to take
the words back, but they hit the air so hard that they break into a
thousand little pieces.
</P>
<P>
   I start to apologize, but before I can get the words out, Jamila
tells me, ``Well, Mama, people change.''
</P>
<P>
   Before I can respond, her father, forever composed, adds, ``But
you should always try to become better, not worse.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't speak. For miles, his words hang over me. I wish I could
be more like him. I think about the New Year and resolutions. I
hear my mother's voice singing, ``Search me, Lord.'' I search
myself. Wonder what I might change about me.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constant humming of highway traffic, I resist being
too hard on myself. I reason that some people live a lifetime and
never change, never even see the need. They go through life as if
fixed forever. But nothing is forever, really. The Earth is always
shifting, generations are always being born, and I have been made a
thousand times over.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, I've never made a New Year's resolution. Never
promised myself I'd lose a pound (I love to eat too much to lie
about not eating). Never promised to quit, well, anything.
</P>
<P>
   But something inside of me inevitably forces me to take stock of
my life, and not just on New Year's. So every now and then, I make
deliberate attempts to change who I am, to give up bad habits, to
add a new and better one. Other times, it seems, change has simply
forced itself upon me.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the old year gives way, I think about the new one and
how I might be different, better than in 1998. Should I change my
hair or the way I dress? Maybe, at my age, I really shouldn't eat
so much. Maybe I should finally add real exercise to my daily
routine, and not rely so much on working up a sweat doing
housework. Maybe I should resolve to become debt-free. I've managed
that feat before. Of course, before there were children.
</P>
<P>
   I inhale deeply and wonder, ``What's this about? Jamila's
revelation? Jimmy's? The new year? Resolutions? Should I have to
think so hard about this?''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it possible to go to bed one night, wake up one morning or
simply walk through a door you've known all your life and discover
between inhaling and exhaling that the self you've sewn together
isn't measuring up, is, as the Scripture says, as dirty rags?
</P>
<P>
   I resist these thoughts the way I struggle with Jimmy's reckless
driving. I reason that it is much easier to give a name to the evil
without than to locate the terror within.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, in a world seemingly drunk on fine old freedom, it is
much easier to ignore one's own faults. I resolve to not do that,
to start over when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I start to worry. Worry about how life's circumstances can
cause us to break even the most solemn vow. I think, ``What's the
use?'' I think what I really need, for starters, is a change of
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
