<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Jan. 7, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polar air will return to the Northeast on brisk breezes from the
west after a cold front moves offshore on Thursday morning. Snow
showers will be frequent along the east shores of Lakes Erie and
Ontario, but sunshine should return east of the Appalachians during
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the cold front moves into the Carolinas and Tennessee Valley,
jet stream winds will begin to blow parallel to the front causing
it to stall. Moisture from the Gulf of Mexico will stream northward
over the stationary front producing considerable cloudiness and
patches of light rain in the Gulf States.
</P>
<P>
   A mound of frigid, dry air centered over Indiana will quickly
glide east allowing milder, moist air to return to the Ohio Valley
later in the day. Clouds will rapidly increase and patches of snow
and ice will develop in parts of the southern Appalachians during
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and light snow will cover the western Plains as a strong
disturbance exits from the Rockies. A windstorm is possible along
the east slopes of mountains near the track of the storm in
Colorado. A wedge of dry air in the northeast Plains and southern
Great Lakes will promote sunny skies, but very cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest will notice more clouds with a little rain on the
Coast and showers in the Bitterroots. A ridge of high pressure will
move toward California. The clockwise circulation around the fair
weather system will cause offshore winds which will direct warm,
dry air into southern California. Fog trapped in the Central Valley
will change little.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Siege of Fog
</P>
<P>
   Visibility lowered to 300 feet in parts of California's Central
Valley early Wednesday as the siege of dense morning fog grew to
six days. In the early afternoon, however, visibility typically
improved to at least one mile once fog lifted into a deck of low
clouds. But, with the January sun hanging low in the sky, weak rays
of sunlight merely reflected off the top of low clouds instead of
penetrating thin spots and encouraging clouds to evaporate. With
low clouds staying intact by day, the stage has been set for clouds
to lower to the ground at night, causing the foggy cycle to recur.
</P>
</TEXT>
