<SLUG> BC-CIR-DISCO-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAME THAT MELDS FIGHTING AND DANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dance Fever'' meets Mortal Kombat.
</P>
<P>
   Parappa the Rapper meets ``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to discern the rationale behind Bust-a-Groove, a
strobe-lighted disco combat game developed in Japan. But if there
is a rationale, it has to do with dancing and fighting and how a
video game blurs the edges between them. There is a vocabulary of
moves, a kinesthetic grammar. In a video game, as in a martial arts
movie, combat is extremely formal and highly stylized. Just like
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   In Bust-a-Groove, you maneuver the controller to the beat of the
rhythm. If you execute a bunch of complex combination moves in sync
with the music, your character throws sparks on the dance floor and
the camera moves in for a close-up. The more camera time you get,
the more your Enthusiasm Gauge rises and the more dynamic your
overall performance. The object is to hog the camera, win over the
crowd and upstage your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the combat part comes in. Because each of the
game's 10 characters has a signature weapon _ fireballs, poison
gas, pistols, giant hamburgers, swirly tornadoes of pink hearts and
so on _ that will wreak havoc on their opponent's Enthusiasm Gauge.
</P>
<P>
   If it looks as if you're going to lose, you can unleash one of
these weapons. But you have to do it on the fourth beat. And it's
possible to dodge these groove-destroying projectiles. But you have
to dodge on the fourth beat. Everything happens on the fourth beat.
And there's a disco ball. And flashing colored lights under the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Like any fighting game, Bust-a-Groove pits you against
outlandishly dressed adversaries. If you beat them all, you face a
giant monster in the pyrotechnic showdown. In this case, the big
boss is a 50-foot robot re-enacting Madonna's ``Vogue'' video atop
a Tokyo skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very stylish robot.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very stylish game _ whoever designed these characters
obviously spent some time on the Tokyo rave scene. The pants are
right. The hats are right. The sneakers and sunglasses are right.
The characters are a multiethnic grab bag of teen-agers and
20-somethings, all wildly charismatic and telegenic, with their own
back stories and occupations: artist, street thug, office girl,
space alien, budding mad scientist.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite is Kitty Nakajima, age 16, star of the hit
television series ``Litterbox Warriors 5.'' After receiving her
first big paycheck, the manual informs us, ``Kitty N. bought out
the entire top floor of the tallest building in the city.'' It
adds, ``From that vantage point, she prances around in bright
lights, not minding if any adoring fans happen to catch her in
their binoculars.'' In a white cat suit, platform boots, cartoon
kitty mask and green pigtails, this character does not look like a
human being.
</P>
<P>
   But then, neither do the virtual gladiators, action heroines or
athletes who run, jump and parry their way across our computer
monitors and television screens in a thousand video games. Many of
their movements, however, were originally performed by human beings
_ martial artists, dancers and sports stars rigged with sensors and
recorded in 3-D. Digital skins are wrapped around the data. The
animation is fine-tuned, shuffled and recombined. And voila, the
virtual black belt. Or the virtual white polyester suit. Ready to
jump, fight, shoot, score. Ready to dance.
</P>
<P>
   As in a fighting game, the human movement in Bust-a-Groove makes
everything seem less mechanical and more realistic (even the
50-foot robot moves like an aerobics instructor). The difference is
what happens after you win. In a fighting game, after you win, you
get the satisfaction of seeing your opponent whimper on the ground
in a convincing way. And after you beat everyone, that's it. That's
all there is.
</P>
<P>
   In Bust-a-Groove, after you win, you see your opponent whimper
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   And after you beat everyone, you can make your own music video.
It's a reward for winning: instead of following a routine, you are
allowed to program your own. String together the steps. Play with
camera angles.
</P>
<P>
   You can fiddle with the tempo _ in the absence of human physical
constraints or gravity, these characters can go into Keystone Cops
hyperspeed or instant-replay slow motion. If you slowed them all
the way down and put the camera behind them, you could probably
teach yourself a bunch of hip-hop dance moves. I'm sure that
somewhere in Tokyo, a bunch of eighth graders have brought this
process full circle. Playstation-a-go-go. Coming to a dance floor
near you. (Fireballs optional.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bust-a-Groove, developed by Enix and published by 989 Studios;
$49.95; Sony Playstation; for all ages.)
</P>
<P>
   author's e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
