<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS JOIN THE CALL FOR ALTERNATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
UNDATED: time,'' Canady said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of resistant pneumococcal pneumonia, for example.
It used to be you could just open a vial of penicillin in the same
room with pneumococcus and the patient would get better. We had a
standard regimen for treating pneumonia with penicillin, and it
worked every time. It would be considered negligent to treat you
like that if you came in with pneumonia today,'' Canady said.
``There's a one in five chance it wouldn't be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE EXPECT ANTIBIOTICS
</P>
<P>
   One component of the antibiotic overuse, Canady said, is that
the public's perception of the drugs is often inaccurate. A new
survey, conducted by the American Society of Health Systems
Pharmacists, which includes more than 30,000 pharmacists who work
in institutional health-care settings, shows that consumers lack a
consistent understanding of how and when to use antibiotics:
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the adults between ages 18 and 34 who were polled
said they had not finished an antibiotic prescription before it was
completed because their symptoms went away.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine percent said they have saved leftover antibiotics
and taken them at a later time.
</P>
<P>
   One in 10 reported they have shared antibiotic prescriptions
with someone else.
</P>
<P>
   More than half (57 percent) said they believe that antibiotics
are the best medicine for viral infections caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are consequences to not taking antibiotics properly, and
our research shows that many consumers aren't aware of them,''
Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because someone on antibiotics begins to feel better does
not mean that his or her body has completely fought off the
infection. When consumers stop taking their antibiotics before the
prescription is completed or save their antibiotics and use them at
another time, they are allowing bacterial strains to grow stronger
and more resistant to the drugs that are supposed to fight them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Canady said, ``absolutely'' patients expect their doctors
to prescribe antibiotics whenever they have any type of infection,
sore throat or bad cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to a physician with a problem, you leave with a
piece of paper. If you don't, you think you are not getting good
care or the doctor just doesn't realize how sick you are. The
expectation is that treatment equals good care; advice doesn't
count,'' Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   JUST SAY NO
</P>
<P>
   To stop the antibiotic fever that has hit our country, Mary Ann
Block said, doctors, patients and, in the case of children, parents
must work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have to say no to patients and parents who demand
antibiotics when they are inappropriate,'' she said. ``We have to
educate patients as well. Ninety percent of ear infections will
heal on their own. Patients need to know that if they develop
serious pneumonia, there may not be an antibiotic available that
will work for them when they need it to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bodies are incredibly good at healing themselves, and we
are not giving them that opportunity,'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to help our kids short term, she said, is hurting their
immune systems in the long term. The antibiotics do the job our
immune systems should be taught to do.
</P>
<P>
   As for Olivia Booth, her mother said she hasn't had an ear
infection since she let her suffer through that last one, with the
help of Block's manipulation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia did have strep throat a few months ago, and Block
prescribed an antibiotic after a throat culture identified it as
strep.
</P>
<P>
   The drug treatment cured the strep without causing any allergic
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she just had too many different antibiotics in her
little body for a while there,'' Linnea Booth said. ``Her body was
rebelling against them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
