<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIBIOTICS-ALTERNATI     01-06 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIBIOTICS-ALTERNATIVES-2000(2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS JOIN THE CALL FOR ALTERNATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olivia Booth was first prescribed amoxicillin for an ear
infection when she was 6 weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Grapevine, Texas, infant reached 9 months of
age, she had had eight or nine ear infections and had taken almost
that many kinds of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Her pediatrician recommended ear tubes, which helped for a while
_ until the left one fell out in January 1998, when Olivia was not
yet 2. Otitis media, the most common disease of early childhood,
returned with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Olivia is not alone. Ear infection is the most common disease of
early childhood, affecting an estimated 24 million American
children each year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all those kids are prescribed antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a nationwide love of antibiotics that some medical
experts say is getting out of hand. Last year, according to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, an estimated 18 million
prescriptions were written for antibiotics to combat nonspecific
respiratory infections, most prescribed to meet public demand
during the cold and flu season.
</P>
<P>
   The misuse of antibiotics and the associated increase in
drug-resistant bacteria has been debated in medical journals for 10
years, but the answer has always been to develop newer, more
powerful antibiotics. Now, some doctors are looking for
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Those leading the anti-antibiotic charge say that the drugs are
overused and misused and, more important, are to blame for the
development of ``superbugs,'' strains of bacteria that are
resistant to the most potent antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   When Olivia's ear infections came back, antibiotics caused an
additional complication. The little girl, who weighed just 19
pounds, broke out in hives. She had welts the size of dollar bills
on her back and chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did Ceclor, Biaxin, Augmentin, Zithromax, you name it,''
said her mother, Linnea Booth. ``One infection lasted six or seven
weeks because we had to keep taking her off the different
antibiotics. We would stop everything for a week and then try
another. We also were giving her a steroid for the hives. I was
watching her every second, because I was afraid the allergic
reaction would cause her throat to swell shut and she wouldn't be
able to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Booth sought out Mary Ann Block, a Tarrant County
osteopathic physician and author of ``No More Amoxicillin,'' a book
on preventing and treating children's ear and respiratory
infections without antibiotics. Block recommends avoiding
antibiotics for all but the most serious life-threatening
infections to prime the body's own immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so afraid of being sick that we are literally killing
ourselves with the overuse and misuse of antibiotics,'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   To treat Olivia, Block temporarily removed any allergy-provoking
foods, including dairy foods, which she said may weaken the immune
system. She began giving Olivia very gentle osteopathic
manipulation (much like massage) to help drain her ears and sinuses
and clear the lymph system to boost natural immunity.
</P>
<P>
   She taught Olivia's mother manipulative techniques to do at home
and emphasized that her daughter needed to be sick long enough to
develop natural antibodies that would help to protect against
future infections.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to wait and watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning you think, `If I don't get my child on
antibiotics, it's going to end up hurting her hearing for life.'
It's really scary,'' Booth said.
</P>
<P>
   A CALL FOR ALTERNATIVES
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Canady, president of the the American Society of
Health-System Pharmacists and a doctor of pharmacy, is one expert
who has joined recently appointed Surgeon General David Satcher in
the call to stop prescribing so many antibiotics so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started overusing antibiotics as soon as they became
available,'' said Canady, who is also a clinical professor of
pharmacy and medicine at the University of North Carolina..
</P>
<P>
   ``We started using them for everything we thought they could
possibly make better.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent report in the ``Journal of the American Medical
Association'' estimates that 90 percent of upper respiratory
infections, including colds and bronchitis, are caused by viruses,
and that the antibiotics prescribed for them are almost always
useless.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the overuse and misuse of antibiotics in this
country are contributing to the increasing death rate from
infections, the third-leading cause of death. According to Satcher,
the U.S. death rate from infectious disease, excluding HIV//AIDS,
rose by 22 percent between 1980 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional response in the medical community has been
relatively simple almost since the time penicillin first came on
the market nearly 60 years ago: If an antibotic doesn't work
anymore for a patient, develop a stronger one. Canady said that at
some point, the upward spiral must stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there is hope that we can keep developing stronger
and stronger antibiotics, but if we ever hit the wall with this
thing, we will be in trouble,'' Canady said by telephone from Las
Vegas, where the society held its annual meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the science gets better, it enhances our ability to fight
infections, but we are always just one drug ahead of an epidemic as
we develop resistance problems,'' Canady said. ``We are always just
a step away from disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The misuse of antibiotics is troublesome to health-system
pharmacists, who practice in hospitals, nursing homes and other
organized health-care settings where dangerous infections are
rising because of resistant bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a problem for us for a long time. We have the
sickest people, with the worst bugs, and most of them have already
been fighting those bugs with all kinds of drugs for a long time,''
Canady said. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
