<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FIRE-PREVENTION-AR     01-06 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-PREVENTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE ANYONE YELLS `FIRE!' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(editors: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tuesday was a busy day at the Banco Popular on 116th
Street in East Harlem, but Joyce Lynes wasn't lining up for the
teller or an ATM. She was in a throng surrounding a table arrayed
with fire extinguishers, smoke detectors, a circuit breaker and
coloring books with a fire-safety theme.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of fires that have killed 20 people since early
December in New York City, the Fire Department was out in force,
trying to seize the moment to teach a few lessons about fire
prevention as part of a citywide program. In English or in Spanish,
neighborhood residents voiced their concerns. How could they sort
through the fog of myths and misinformation about what to do if a
fire broke out?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the first thing I'd do,'' said Ms. Lynes, a transit
worker, recalling a fire she experienced as a child more than 30
years ago. ``When my brother yelled that there was a fire upstairs,
we all ran out of the room, and the ceiling collapsed onto the
floor behind us. A kid was trapped and jumped out the window, and
his brother caught him. Then his aunt came running out with her
hair on fire.'' Ever since, Ms. Lynes has slept near a working
smoke detector. Now, she said firmly, ``I'd take my family and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Bennette, the community coordinator for the Fire
Department's education unit, asked her, ``Do you live in building
with a fire escape?'' If so, getting out of the building would be
the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Ms. Lynes lives in a six-story city-owned
building that meets the city's standards for fireproof construction
_ it is built with materials that will contain a fire to one
dwelling unit. As long as the fire was not in her own apartment,
she would probably be just as safe closing the metal apartment door
and staying put until firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder that in a city with more than 800,000 dwelling
units in multiple-residence buildings, there appear to be at least
800,000 ways to plan for a fire emergency. While some people may
remember their single-file march during a school fire drill, many
are now realizing that they are ill prepared to choose among a
bewildering range of strategies, some of them more suitable for a
brownstone than a high-rise, better for city housing than a walk-up
with a fire escape.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Brian Dixon, a department spokesman, urged New Yorkers to
tailor their safety plans to their buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make generalizations,'' he said. ``New York has so
many different varieties of buildings. You need to know what kind
of building you're in, first, and that will determine what you
should do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Management companies are not required to inform tenants about
fire-safety preparations, but several new approaches are being
explored. Starting soon, a pamphlet for high-rise dwellers prepared
by the Real Estate Board of New York, an industry group, and the
Fire Department will be distributed regularly to managers and
agents for buildings where 300,000 people live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't ignore it the way 95 percent of us ignore the safety
cards in airplanes,'' said Steven Spinola, president of the real
estate board. He said the pamphlet will be distributed at least
twice a year and will be posted throughout buildings and included
in new leases and renewal packages. The possibility of asking
tenants to acknowledge receipt of the pamphlet, as they are now
asked to complete window-guard questionnaires, has also been
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets complicated when you ask people to start signing,''
Spinola said. ``Some tenants are reluctant to sign anything. They
think they're giving up their right to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some management companies are renewing fire-safety efforts on
their own. ``We'll make arrangements for the Fire Department to
give a talk to any assembled group of people or board members on
request,'' said Eric Kornfeld, executive vice president of Heron
Management, which operates more than 80 residential buildings in
New York. ``I've set up three in just the last two weeks. But quite
truthfully, we only do it when a board expresses interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Kirschenbaum, the general counsel for Insignia Corp.,
which manages more than 320 residential buildings, said that
distributing the high-rise safety pamphlet ``is on our agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell people to wait for O.J. Simpson to rush up the
stairs,'' he said, alluding to a rescue in ``The Towering
Inferno,'' the 1974 film.
</P>
<P>
   The portrayal of fires in disaster films like ``Inferno'' and
``Backdraft'' actually hinders the Fire Department, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People die from smoke inhalation,'' he said. ``Hollywood can't
show smoke. It's too dark. In the movies they always show fire.
It's more dramatic. But flames are not really the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Disaster films ``make people think they can go up to the roof
and a helicopter will pick them up,'' he added. ``That's not going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The best approach, he said, is to remember a mantra: ``Have a
smoke detector. Have a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents can start by asking whether their building has
fireproof construction. Michael Carter, vice president of the
Uniformed Firefighters Association, noted that most high-rises have
such construction, as do city housing projects. He offered a tip:
if there's a fire stair with self-closing metal doors, the building
typically meets the ``fireproof'' standard; if there's a second way
out, like a fire escape, it probably doesn't. If the building
manager or superintendent can't tell you what kind of building it
is, he said, the certificate of occupancy will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Here are some basic precautions suggested by fire safety
professionals for all types of housing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop a drill with an escape plan and practice it often
enough to make it a ritual. Agree on a rendezvous point outside the
building, so everyone can be accounted for easily. ``You'll be more
logical even if you panic,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place smoke detectors within 15 feet of sleeping areas, but
not in or near kitchens or bathrooms. (A detector with a
three-minute delay outside the kitchen will give you time to fan
off the smoke from the roast.) Since 1989, the city building code
has required that new buildings with three or more dwelling units
provide smoke detectors that are wired into the electrical system.
Change batteries in detectors at least annually.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 12- to 18-inch-tall fire extinguisher marked ``ABC'' (for
multipurpose) should be kept in the kitchen, but it should be used
only on small grease, electrical or wastepaper fires. ``Don't use
it to delay calling 911,'' said Dixon, adding that it's important
to place yourself between the fire and the door. ``Don't put
yourself in a corner without a way to back out,'' he said. ``You'd
be better advised to get everyone out.'' Baking soda is effective
in dousing small grease fires. If furniture catches fire, leave
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call 911 as soon as you safely can.
</P>
<P>
   _ Close the door behind you as you leave a room or an apartment.
``People have been propping doors open as they leave their
apartments,'' said Carter of the firefighters' association. ``It's
a psychological thing. They can't bring themselves to close the
door in case others might need to escape after them.'' He also
suggested closing doors to children's bedrooms every night.
</P>
<P>
   If your building doesn't meet the ``fireproof'' standard, here
are some safety strategies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Exit immediately if fire breaks out. Feel the front door to
see if it's hot, and check the staircase outside.
</P>
<P>
   _ If there is smoke, go to the fire escape. If you see smoke
there, or it's hot, don't use it; try to get to a fire escape in
another apartment. Know your building and all the ways out of it,
Dixon advised.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some brownstones don't have fire escapes. It may be possible
to use a window as an emergency exit. Get advice on an escape plan
from the neighborhood fire station.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in a ``fireproof'' building, experts say you should
do the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ If a fire occurs in your apartment, leave immediately, closing
the door as you go.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the fire is elsewhere in the building, resist the urge to
flee down the stairwell. Be aware, too, that smoke rises, so going
upstairs can be dangerous. Stay put. As Dixon put it: ``I know it
sounds counterintuitive _ `Stay in place! Your building is burning
down.' But we'll get to you. In most instances, you're safer in
your apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said that in the Upper West Side fire that killed four
people in the building where members of Macaulay Culkin's family
lived, the apartments next to the unit where the fire started were
not damaged at all, while the people who died were in a stairwell 8
to 10 floors above.
</P>
<P>
   _ If smoke is coming in from outside the building, turn off the
air-conditioner and close the windows.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the hallway is full of smoke, close all doors between you
and the smoke. Open the window a crack at the bottom to let in air,
and a crack at the top to let out smoke, if any filters in. If
there's a lot of smoke in the hallway, stuff wet towels along the
bottom of the door. Move to a less smoky room, closing doors as you
retreat and opening the window a crack to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you call 911, give your name, address, floor number and
the position of your unit in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell them `I'm in 4K,' '' Carter said. ``If you say `I'm
on the south side,' I know where to look for you. And don't go in
the bathroom where they don't have windows. I'd want you to go to
whatever room faces the street, where you can signal and can be
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   EVERYONE'S QUESTION: HOW HIGH WILL THE LADDER REACH?
</P>
<P>
   Some common questions about fire safety were addressed by Chief
Brian Dixon and Gladys Bennette, the community coordinator for the
Fire Department's education unit:
</P>
<P>
   How should I plan an escape from a brownstone with one staircase
and no fire escape? (Get help from the nearest fire station in
devising a plan.)
</P>
<P>
   Will a firetruck ladder reach a 10th-floor apartment? (No. It
will go only about eight stories.)
</P>
<P>
   If there's smoke in the hall and the apartment has a balcony,
should I go out there? (Only if the sound of a firefighter knocking
on your door can be heard from there. And don't lock yourself out.
If smoke is rising from below, don't stay out there.)
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Department offers fire-safety presentations to groups
like co-op boards, school classes and building managers. The number
is (718) 999-2343.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
