r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEPPANYAKI-CHEF-HNS &LR;      01-06 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEPPANYAKI-CHEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEPPANYAKI CUTS ITS WAY INTO AMERICAN COOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The hibachi before chef Johnny Chen is not merely
a cooking surface; it is Chen's searing playground.
</P>
<P>
   There, he builds Mount Fuji from a funnel of onion rings that
billow flame and smoke; he flips shrimp tails in the air, teasing,
``this one's for you, this one's for me,'' as one tail lands
directly under the nose of the patron, while the other flies into
his shirt pocket. He sets his fingertips on fire for a little
candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a chef at Miyako Japanese Steak House in Albany, N.Y., is
demonstrating the cooking style of teppanyaki, or the Japanese
steakhouse, that is a fairly recent culinary tradition of Japan
and, now, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Teppanyaki restaurants got their start in Japan some 30 years
ago. At first, the cooking was a rather staid grilling style, said
Audrey Yamaguchi, who helps her husband, Toshi, owner of Miyako.
The cooking style, she said, gradually became more entertaining,
with the now-famous flourish of knives and speed.
</P>
<P>
   The chain restaurant, Benihana, introduced Americans to the
grill-side cooking show when founder Rocky Aoki opened the first
Benihana in New York City in 1964. The chain has since grown to 60
restaurants, including 12 licensed franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Aoki, according to Benihana's corporate headquarters, borrowed
teppanyaki-style cooking from his father, Yunosuke, who cooked on
steel grills in his Tokyo restaurants. Teppanyaki evolved from one
of Japan's oldest cooking practices, yakimono, or searing.
</P>
<P>
   The cooking in Japan does not quite reach the feverish crescendo
that it does in the United States. ``Over here, it's more
entertaining than the shows in Japan,'' Audrey Yamaguchi said.
``The American people come here to relax, and to laugh. They make
more fun than in Japan. In Japan, it's still more closed, and more
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chen wheels out a cart loaded with cut lemons, slices of
raw beef, chicken and vegetables, and bottles of oils and sauces,
you know he means business.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has been a chef for more than five years, but has been
honing the craft for 15 years. ``He's quite expedient,'' Yamaguchi
says with some understatement.
</P>
<P>
   He twirls a two-pronged fork and spatula like a Western
gunslinger. Once he sets a rapid fire, with a whoosh, Chen quickly
slices and dices a tender, flavorful combination of mushrooms,
carrots, onion, the shrimp and the meats. Though this burst of
flavors, enhanced by ginger and mustard dipping sauces, is what
really counts, you'll also experience the cathartic laugh of
watching Chen goofily discover a seasoning shaker that he's thrown
up in the air and caught in the red chef's hat atop his head.
</P>
<P>
   There is no step-by-step method behind teppanyaki. Chefs and
restaurateurs describe a tricky process. The grill temperature must
be exact, because the food sticks if the surface is too hot.
Conversely, food becomes a watery goo at low temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Yamaguchi, of Miyako, is trying to learn hibachi cooking
by practicing the crisscross pattern of cutting in a frying pan
when preparing family meals. While all the rapid slicing makes for
high entertainment, she points out that speed actually is a
necessary element to teppanyaki. Overcooking can happen all too
easily.
</P>
<P>
   And in Japanese cooking, something as simple as an imperfect cut
can spoil the texture of the meat. (Such precise carving is
especially essential when presenting sushi and sashimi).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
