<P>
   SUPPLEMENTS _ WASHINGTON _ Although Congress four years ago
restricted the authority of the Food and Drug Administration to
police the companies that make and sell vitamins and other dietary
``supplements,'' a new government data base will enable consumers
to do their own research on the products. The National Insititutes
of Health Office of Dietary Supplements unveils Wednesday an
Internet site (http://dietary-supplements.info.nih.gov) that
contains thousands of published scientific studies of the
increasingly popular alternative medicine supplements. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service).
</P>
