<HEADER>
A1718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MACK-ARTSCOUNCIL     01-06 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MACK-ARTSCOUNCIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS COUNCIL CHAIRMAN RESIGNS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By FELICIA R. LEE   
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earle I. Mack, an arts patron and former real estate developer
who helped restore financial aid to the arts in New York state to a
level not seen in nearly a decade, has resigned as chairman of the
New York State Council on the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who was appointed in 1996 by Gov. George E. Pataki, said
he would remain on the board but would resign as chairman as of
next Monday to spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter to Pataki, Mack said that the council
had met virtually all of the goals that the governor had
envisioned. He said that before Pataki's first inauguration, the
state arts budget had been cut by 56 percent over a five-year span,
morale was low and the arts infrastructure at the council and
around the state was eroding.
</P>
<P>
   When Mack became chairman the council's budget stood at $31.6
million, after a series of cuts during the state's economic
downturn; it now stands at $46 million. The increase ``has not only
resurrected the nonprofit cultural sector in New York state,'' said
Mack's letter, dated Monday, ``but also the council as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The council distributes grants ranging from hundreds to many
thousands of dollars to more than 1,000 museums, cultural heritage
groups and performing arts companies around the state. From April
1995 through December 1998, it gave $138.5 million for 9,000 grants
to 1,300 arts organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Norma P. Munn, the chairwoman of the New York City Arts
Coalition, a citywide advocacy group, said the general consensus
among her colleagues was that Mack had served the council and the
arts world well. A deliberately low-key man, he won a reputation
for being energetic and finding common ground with upstate and city
legislators for financing and programs, despite the initial
suspicion that his appointment was a favor for financial support of
Pataki's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found Earle to be extremely hard-working,'' Ms. Munn said.
``I found him sophisticated about the political atmosphere in
Albany. One would expect him to have connections to the governor,
but he had connections to the legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm devastated he's leaving,'' said Randall Bourscheidt,
president of the Alliance for the Arts, an advocacy group in New
York City. ``He understood the bottom-line need was for a
restoration of funding. In three years he's accomplished an
incredible amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his political connections, Mack assumed his post
under the skeptical eye of many artists and arts organizations, who
were well aware of his role in organizing a major fund-raiser for
and making a $25,000 contribution to Pataki's 1994 campaign and top
contributions to Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's 1993 campaign.
Although he served on the board of the City Ballet and Dance
Theater of Harlem, Mack was better known as a senior partner of a
family-controlled real estate and investment business, Mack Co. of
Rochelle Park, N.J., and for serving on the board of the state's
Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   He became chairman of the council at a time of intense
frustration with Republican cuts to the arts at the national and
local level. He had the challenge of succeeding the immensely
popular Kitty Carlisle Hart, who served on the arts council through
five administrations.
</P>
<P>
   During Mack's tenure, though, Mrs. Hart called his budget
increase victories ``nothing short of miraculous.'' He also won
points for organizing the first state arts technology conference;
putting together three studies on the economic impact of the arts;
establishing an arts partnership program in the public school
system and helping to make available a license plate to salute and
promote the arts. The $39.50 ``State of the Arts'' plate includes a
$15 contribution to the council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
