<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BOMB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB EXPLODES AT HIGH SCHOOL, INJURES 11 STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL and PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Northeast High School was expected to open
with extra security today after a bomb exploded in a locker
Tuesday, injuring 11 students and destroying three lockers.
</P>
<P>
   Six students were taken to hospitals with debris in their eyes
and ringing in their ears. One of the six may have a broken arm.
Five other students were treated at the school for bruises,
scratches and other minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the explosion, students identified a suspect for
police. Police were questioning witnesses Tuesday night but did not
have a suspect in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Police and school officials did not have a motive for the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 1 p.m., the school's vice principal, James Harrison,
heard students screaming and went to the first floor. He told
police he saw sparks shooting from a locker and several students
running from it. The hallway was crowded with students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing 20 feet away, and I saw this girl open a
locker,'' said April Appleton, a freshman. ``She opened it and
boom! The noise hurt my ears.'' Appleton said she heard two quick
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Danyelle Judie said she heard two explosions and then
saw the locker doors pop off their hinges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locker blew off in that girl's face,'' she said. ``Her
face looked all messed up. Smoke and stuff flew everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Tyree Thomas said she could feel vibrations from the
explosion on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   The blast sent students running from the building, said
sophomore Roneice McHenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what was going to happen next, like if another
bomb was going to go off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Students were evacuated from the school and stood outside in the
cold before moving to the warmer gym. Anxious parents stood around
the school waiting for their children, who were dismissed at 1:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Lance Loewenstein arrived at the school
within moments of the blast. Loewenstein said many students were
angered by the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so proud of the kids,'' Loewenstein said.
``They are very upset. They're naming names. I don't think it will
take too much time to figure out who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion knocked a tile from the false hallway ceiling and
blew three locker doors off their hinges. The locker in the middle
of the three, which was not assigned to a student, was thought to
have housed the bomb, police and fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of the bomb were sent to a lab to be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   After everyone was evacuated, federal Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms officers took a bomb-sniffing dog through the school, but
no other devices were found.
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein said students reported no problems at the school
this year that may have provoked the bombing. Reports of gang
activity have plagued the school and neighborhood in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
