<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIL ABOUT OIL AND SENIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Returning to the real world of work after December's
leisurely routine is always a frightful reality check, but it can
be made a good deal more agreeable with a little help from your
friends.
</P>
<P>
   For me, those friends are the readers whose missives were being
reserved for a holiday mailbag column that never got written. So,
in the interest of putting off honest toil for at least one more
turn, my choice is to ease into the new year by letting the readers
write today's column.
</P>
<P>
   The first draftee is a correspondent who can't understand why
falling prices cause problems for the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were building houses and the price of lumber went down, I
would make more profit because my costs were lower. So, why are the
oil companies losing money because the cost of their material is so
low? It seems that low crude oil prices would be the best thing oil
refining companies could ask for.'' Dear Wondering:
</P>
<P>
   They don't call them oil companies for nothing. If you were
building houses, chances are you wouldn't be producing your own
lumber, shingles, nails, wiring and such. Thus, theoretically at
least, you could boost your profits by pocketing the savings from
lower material costs. The integrated oil company is in a different
situation. It invests large amounts of capital to discover oil,
drill for it, transport it to refineries, process it into various
products, and market what it produces. When a global glut of crude
depresses oil prices, it becomes difficult for the oil company not
only to sustain its profits, but also generate a reasonable return
on its capital investment. This jeopardizes the stock price. Thus,
the merger of the biggies is a defensive move to reduce overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, almost every mailbag column has at least one
Social Security question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me why seniors who want to work are restricted in
their earnings? ... This seems very unfair. ... Has anyone ever
challenged the government over this one?'' Dear Outraged:
</P>
<P>
   Social Security's designers conceived it as more than a pension
program. It also was a way to help younger job-seekers by
encouraging older workers to retire. One way to achieve this is to
restrict how much a beneficiary can make at a job without incurring
a benefit reduction. The restriction, incidentally, ends at age 70.
As for fairness, what's the point of government paying a pension to
somebody who chooses to continue working? It's bad enough that
retired plutocrats are allowed to get Social Security benefits
they'll never need while collecting millions in dividends, interest
and executive pensions.
</P>
<P>
   A column several months ago on Dilbertisms brought some
responses from readers wanting to share the most idiotic statements
they'd heard from the ranks of management. The most amusing
contribution was from a local automotive plant employee whose angry
boss decreed, ``We're going to continue having these meetings every
day until I find out why no work is getting done.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, which is probably apocryphal, was attributed to a
British naval officer, who posted the following ship's order:
``Daily floggings will continue until morale improves.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHEDRE-THEATER-REVIEW     01-06 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHEDRE-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHEDRE': A MIX OF LUST, ANGER AND CHIC
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review)  
 (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
(bl)  
By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you live in the world of Jean Racine, the
17th-century French tragedian, you definitely don't want to mess
with Venus. The goddess of love is also, as one of the dramatist's
characters puts it, the ``goddess of pure remorseless cruelty.''
She's implacable and unbeatable, and she takes no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't stop the ever-imperious Diana Rigg, in the title
role of the London production of Racine's ``Phedre'' that opened
Tuesday night for a limited run at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's
Majestic Theater, from putting up a battle royal against the deity.
She may be doomed from the start, but this Phedre goes down
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching at her velvet-encased torso as if to wrest the demon
of unholy love inside her by some act of radical, self-administered
surgery; howling at the heavens in an ocean-deep voice that would
surely cow any human adversary, Ms. Rigg turns Phedre's protracted
suicide into something like an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   She is a woman born to command who is aghast to find that a
force beyond her control is now commanding her. As a Greek queen
unhinged by her illicit lust for her stepson, she brings to mind
someone who, having known robust health all her life, is suddenly
consumed by cancer. She cannot get over the vicious, unspeakable
betrayal of her own body. Venus has fastened onto her like a tiger,
as Ted Hughes' stark new translation puts it, and Ms. Rigg's Phedre
makes you feel the claws digging in.
</P>
<P>
   The pyrotechnics of Ms. Rigg in high dudgeon are always a
spectacle worth watching. As anyone who saw her Medea of several
seasons ago can testify, few actresses can anatomize anger with
such intelligence and precision. Unfortunately, Ms. Rigg has more
to struggle against here than the predations of Venus.
</P>
<P>
   This Almeida Theater production, directed by Jonathan Kent, Ms.
Rigg's collaborator on ``Medea'' and ``Mother Courage and Her
Children,'' is as intense and mannered as its star. But unlike Ms.
Rigg's performance, the production itself, which runs through Jan.
17 in repertory with Racine's ``Brittanicus'' (opening Friday),
seems to work from the outside in, rather than the opposite. Kent
has spoken of his wish to turn ``Phedre'' into something more than
a marmoreal museum piece, a stately study in the pathology of
passion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a rigid, solemn self-consciousness informs the evening, a
sense of pomp and posture as stylized and exaggerated as anything
the Comedie Francaise might have come up with a century ago. The
look of the show, designed by Maria Bjornson with lighting by Mark
Henderson, is breathtakingly, ponderously chic.
</P>
<P>
   The single setting, a palatial corridor presided over by a
menacingly severe statue of Venus herself, brings to mind Cocteau's
cinematic fantasies of the midcentury, exuding an aura of ominous
enchantment. It is an indication of Kent's literal-mindedness that
there is also a fountain on stage, from which the overheated
characters periodically and vainly try to cool themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The costumes, accordingly, bring to mind the era of Balenciaga
and Charles James. There are sculptured cowls and panniers on the
women's dresses, cumbersome trains and capes that swish through the
air and drag the floor, inhibiting natural movement.
</P>
<P>
   Hippolytus (Toby Stephens), the innocent object of Phedre's
ruinous lust, wears a drapey metallic pullover and pleated leather
pants that give him the look of a glitter-rock disco boy, while his
father, the king and Phedre's husband, Theseus (Julian Glover), is
clad in a bizarre red velvet breastplate that does much to
undermine regal dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, these costumes are meant to suggest the confinement
of public roles, of court personae. But clad in such a manner, who
can resist the urge to sashay and strut? As Aricia, the beautiful
dispossessed princess wronged by Theseus and loved by Hippolytus,
Joanna Roth works her voluminous off-the-shoulder cloak like a
runway model. The overall effect is both glamorous and deadly
earnest, a dangerous combination, and the periodic laughter from
the opening night audience was surely not always welcome to the
performers.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that Kent encourages his actors to assume
melodramatic poses that seem to belong to the age of Sardou, like
flattening themselves against the walls in moments of anguish, and
that are curiously at odds with the muscular leanness of Hughes'
free-verse adaptation. Stephens is the worst offender in this
respect. Though Hippolytus is routinely described as a haughty
stoic, an impenetrable man of stone, this actor wears the stricken
soul within on his metal mesh sleeve from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   There's emotional fire in Stephens' performance, but it burns
far too bright. He always appears to be on the verge of hysteria,
and when Ms. Rigg's Phedre makes her tormented confession of love
to him, the scene feels absurdly out of kilter. His tremulous
discomfort is too close to hers, and it makes more of a case for
Phedre's misreading of Hippolytus' reactions than is called for.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cast, in fact, seems to be performing at the same
fever pitch, as though trying to match the suspenseful, Gothic
tones of Jonathan Dove's music, which wouldn't be out of a place in
a remake of ``Rebecca.'' There's a pervasive sense of
hyperventilating emotion without any solid anchor of character.
</P>
<P>
   The estimable Barbara Jefford, as Phedre's nurse and confidante,
glows toxically with vicarious power lust as she counsels her
mistress to perform disastrous acts in the name of
self-preservation. Yet she seems like an abstract instrument of
Phedre's unhappy destiny; you have no sense of the history these
women have shared, of what their relationship might have been
before. David Bradley, as Hippolytus' tutor, brings a
palate-cleansing dryness to his performance, and his climactic
account of his pupil's death is beautifully rendered.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is Glover, however, who affectingly and fully registers the
damage wrought in ``Phedre.'' Theseus arrives late in the play, but
you feel you come to know this character, a blustering adventurer
who has always assumed he can bend life to his liking, in a way you
are not allowed to know anyone else, Phedre aside. His gradual
deflation from kingly arrogance into bereft humility is genuinely
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   So is Ms. Rigg's portrayal of a woman who is never spared the
awareness of her degradation, who must be a conscious, condemning
witness to her every act of folly. The actress' keen, slightly
glacial intellect serves her well here, giving a stinging
credibility to a guilt induced, after all, not by illicit action
but the mere contemplation of it.
</P>
<P>
   When Sarah Bernhardt first took on the same part in the 1870s,
she was famously advised to push for the character's pain rather
than the rage. Ms. Rigg gives us both: a righteous cosmic anger and
a pathetic, human sense of suffering that continually feed off each
other.
</P>
<P>
   From her early days as the deliciously cool Emma Peel of ``The
Avengers'' to her triumphantly vengeful Medea, she has always been
the image of unfailing resourcefulness and confidence. To see her
play a character for whom those traits finally mean nothing is as
harrowing an astonishment to us as it is to Phedre herself.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PHEDRE'
</P>
<P>
   By Jean Racine, in a new version by Ted Hughes; directed by
Jonathan Kent; design by Maria Bjornson; lighting by Mark
Henderson; music by Jonathan Dove; sound by John A. Leonard. The
Almeida Theater Company, presented by the Brooklyn Academy of
Music, Bruce C. Ratner, chairman; Harvey Lichtenstein, president
and executive producer. At the Majestic Theater, 651 Fulton St.,
Fort Greene, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Diana Rigg (Phedre), Toby Stephens (Hippolytus), Barbara
Jefford (Oenone), Julian Glover (Theseus), David Bradley
(Theramene) and Joanna Roth (Aricia).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
