<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Cal., Ill, Mass., N.Y., Va.)  (af) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANITY, THY NAME IS: (INSERT ISP) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard fans of the band Kiss can do more to show devotion to
their rock idols than just buy CDs. They can now join
Kissonline.net, the official Internet service provider of the band.
</P>
<P>
   The service offers unlimited Web access for $19.95 a month,
which is no great deal, but it has perks like access to
members-only content and an affinity e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL and Earthlink cater to the general populace. If you're a
Kiss fan, you want an ISP that caters to you,'' said Mike
Brandvold, Webmaster for Sony Pictures, a Sony merchandising
company that organizes content for the Kiss site and ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Kiss is on the cutting edge, but the band is not out there
alone. David Bowie, the heavy-metal band Megadeth, the Ohio Society
of Certified Public Accountants, the alumni association of the
University of South Florida and the Vanguard Group, a financial
services company, are among many organizations that have recently
sponsored private label ISPs. On the information superhighway,
these ISPs are vanity license plates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These bands and businesses do not operate the services
themselves; they contract out the technical side to one of several
providers that coordinate access to a national network of dial-up
numbers and furnish technical support.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Laser Link Communications, based in Media, Pa.,
provides all the back room and technical operations for
Megadeth.net, and Ohio-CPA.net, among several others. It is up to
the sponsors, like Megadeth, to do the marketing and provide extra
content for their official sites.
</P>
<P>
   It is now possible to establish these special services because
it is more economical and less complex to operate a national ISP.
Much as Visa and Master Card do with their affinity charge cards,
companies like Laser Link create a generic product, then let the
sponsors stamp it with their own brands. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRISH DEBATE FORUMS ARE REINED IN BY AOL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America Online has decided that subscribers who favor or oppose
Irish nationalism can continue their heated disagreements in AOL's
online forums, but they're going to have to be more cordial about
it.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 11, AOL, the world's largest online provider, pulled the
plug on 23 Irish Heritage discussion forums. AOL said it had done
so because the political debates had included too many personal
attacks and ``vulgarity and profanity,'' which violated AOL's terms
of service.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, AOL reopened the discussion groups after ``cleaning
them up,'' said a spokesman, Jim Whitney. In a note to visitors to
the discussion groups, AOL stated, ``We encourage you to make this
a more amiable place where any person, regardless of faction, can
openly discuss political issues and current events.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage and remind you to debate issues only and not
resort to personal attacks or member harassment,'' the note
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Some Irish nationalists who favor Irish rule for Northern
Ireland dispute AOL's account. On The Irish People Web site
(inac.org/IrishPeople/top/121998/121998aol.html), critics contend
that AOL is seeking to silence outspoken Irish nationalists to make
the service more appealing in Britain, where AOL is trying to build
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney denied that AOL's actions were motivated by that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL STAFF MAY INCLUDE A &UR;  &LR; NEW `TECHNOLOGY BUTLER' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staffs at a few Ritz-Carlton Hotels in the United States will
soon be glad to turn down your bed, fluff up your pillow and answer
your questions about configuring software.
</P>
<P>
   For that last service, the hotel chain, owned by Marriott
International, will offer the use of a ``technology butler,'' a
staff member whose sole job is to help customers with questions
about hardware, software and the Internet. The 248-room
Ritz-Carlton in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, began the pilot project in
August with great success, said Stephanie Platt, a spokeswoman for
the chain.
</P>
<P>
   She said that in Kuala Lumpur, an employee was on call from 8
a.m. to 11 p.m. to answer questions by phone or visit individual
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll help with Internet questions, fax connections, software
problems,'' said Ms. Platt, who noted that the service was free and
used primarily by business travelers. Ms. Platt said Ritz-Carlton
had preliminary plans to test the service next at three U.S.
hotels, two in California and one in Virginia. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SURF THE NET BY TELEPHONE? THAT MAY BE POSSIBLE SOON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several high-tech companies are working on a ``telephone
browser'' that will enable users to surf the Internet by speaking
into the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a user could ask for basic information, like
sports scores or the temperature, and the software will translate
that into a data query and retrieve the information from the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone browser combines voice-recognition programs from
Lucent Technologies and data-mining software from Spyglass, a
provider of software and services for making devices work with the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Yurtin, director of business development for Spyglass,
based in Naperville, Ill., said a commercial product could be
available within a year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORGET THE OSCARS, HERE COME THE WEBBYS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The digerati should already be picking out formal gowns and
making sure that their shoes match their mouse pads. Yes, the
International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences on Wednesday
announced nominations for the 1999 Webby Awards, the ``Oscars of
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   And the nominees are. ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are far too many to mention, 110, in 22
categories, including arts, education, humor, music, politics and
law, technical achievement, and _ because it's the Web _ the weird.
Each category has five nominees. The entire list of nominees can be
found at www.webbyawards.com/best.
</P>
<P>
   For those keeping score at home, there also is an interesting
development behind the scenes. The three-year-old Webbys are the
creation of International Data Group, based in Boston, the
publisher of magazines like PC World and Computerworld. To
establish credibility for the awards, the company last year created
the International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences to act as
nominators and judges.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, it is an academy, like the Motion Picture Academy,
that establishes an awards show, not an awards show that creates an
academy of voters and judges. ``In this case, it is the other way
around,'' conceded Tiffany Shlain, executive producer of the Webby
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The awards ceremony, scheduled for March 18 in San Francisco,
seeks to mimic the prestige of the Oscars. But the Oscars may want
to copy one welcome aspect of the Webbys: winners' acceptance
speeches are limited to five words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
