<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Jan. 7. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACH (Washington) - Thursday, one of the most extraordinary
legal proceedings in American history begins. The country's most
powerful 100 men are entering unexplored waters, and there is not
telling when or in what condition they will emerge. Although there
are few recognizable landmarks, Arizona Sen. Joh Kyl tells us that
a GOP caucus he attended Wednesday morning was told to be braced
for a tough fight. For one thing, they expect Democrats to insist
on a full vote of the Senate to approve of the appearance of each
witness. The result is that the process in the Senate could be just
as raucous and partisan as it was in the House. By JEFF BARKER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACH-INTERNET (Phoenix) - As the Senate begins its first
impeachment trial in 130 years, there are powerful forces on the
right and left trying to monkeywrench the process. The right,
largely through the Internet and talk radio, is pushing a
six-year-old rumor, resurrected by a supermarket tabloid, that
President Clinton has an illegitimate son by a prostitute in
Arkansas. The editor of the ``Star'' tabloid, quoted by the
Internet's Drudge report, said the story ``could be a 13-year-old
hoax,'' but that hasn't stopped talk radio from spreading it across
the airwaves in an apparent effort to pressure GOP members of the
Senate. By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
