</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-SETTLE (New York) _ The NBA and the players' union
reached an agreement today to end the 6-month-old lockout and save
what's left of the season. After a secret all-night bargaining
session between commissioner David Stern and union head Billy
Hunter, the deal was struck sometime around 6 a.m. _ hours before
the league's Board of Governors was set to vote on canceling the
remainder of the season. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ The 106th Congress convened Wednesday
speaking plaintively of new agendas and an end to partisan rancor,
yet already preoccupied with the impeachment of President Clinton
that left the previous House enflamed and divided. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-HASTERT (Washington) _ A man-in-the-news profile of Rep.
Dennis Hastert, the new speaker. Hastert, who was catapulted from
obscurity and drafted for the job of speaker only three weeks ago,
has earned a reputation as a ``nice guy.'' He knows how to listen,
stifles his temper and keeps his word, which is why he swiftly
received the backing of moderate Republicans and conservatives
alike. But, no matter how congenial and hard working, Hastert,
faces a daunting double-barreled challenge: He comes to the job of
speaker as one of the most untested leaders in memory, a no-name
congressman new to the battles of top tier politics, and he
confronts one of the most sharply divided, least forgiving,
Congress' in years. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Nothing but up. That's what stock
markets around the world delivered Wednesday, wowing investors with
jumps of at least 2 percent and in some markets overseas more than
3 percent one-day gains. So far, 1999 has been a banner year for
equities. The boffo performances look a lot like last year, only
better. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ANOMALY (Nanjie, China) _ In an age often marked by an
economic free-for-all, the village of Nanjie is a dinosaur: its
farm, its factories, its housing are all collectively owned and
managed. Residents must attend regular study sessions of Mao's
teachings, and their take-home pay does not exceed $30 a month.
Nanjie is often cited as a paragon by China's ``leftists.'' But the
very fame of this strange showcase suggests just how anomalous it
is today _ and how far those leftists have fallen. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE-STATES (New York) _ Gov. George Pataki is proposing to
take New York down a road already followed by 16 other states in
eliminating parole and sentencing convicts to fixed prison terms.
But eliminating parole so far has not been found to have any direct
effect on crime rates, while having enough unexpected consequences
that three states _ Connecticut, Florida and Colorado _ have
reinstated it. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
