</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT JUDGE ENTERS HIS OWN COURT EXHIBIT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial queues.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After having admitted thousands of e-mails,
depositions, market surveys and other documents into the Microsoft
antitrust trial, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on
Wednesday volunteered his own piece of evidence _ one that may
signal how he will eventually rule in the historic case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Court Exhibit No. 1'' was a newspaper column about America
Online Inc. that Jackson had read over breakfast in The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   In his debut column for the paper, veteran Post editor David
Ignatius quoted AOL chairman Steve Case as saying it would be
``crazy'' for him to pick a fight with Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why Microsoft is the most valuable company on
earth,'' Case told Ignatius. ``I have a lot of respect for
Microsoft. I continue to live in fear of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Case also said in the interview: ``We have no flight of fancy
that we can dent in any way, shape or form what is a monopoly in
the operating system business. ...It's hard to imagine that
(personal computers) won't be the dominant way people connect with
the Internet for many years to come, and Microsoft has a pretty
amazing lock on that business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, joined by 19 states as plaintiffs, has
charged that beginning in mid-1995, Microsoft sought to crush
Netscape Communications Corp., Microsoft's rival in the Internet
browser wars, by using illegal business tactics. The alleged motive
was in part because Microsoft feared the popular browser might one
day undermine its Windows operating system near-monopoly for
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial had recessed for the holidays, Jackson had
noted from the bench that the planned $4.2 billion merger between
AOL and Netscape ``might be a very significant change in the
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyer Michael Lacovara was pursuing that theme with
the government's final witness, economist Franklin Fisher of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, when the judge interceded,
calling a brief recess so the column containing Case's comments
could be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial resumed, Jackson read several paragraphs to the
witness and said: ``The question I have of you is ... is this
consistent with your understanding of what the impact of the
consortium will be, insofar as developing viable competition?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is,'' Fisher replied.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official who has attended the trial since
its inception in October said it was ``highly unusual'' for the
judge to intervene in the middle of the case to present his own
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a highly unusual case, added the official, Jeffrey
Blattner. ``It has some aspects of a major antitrust trial. But
it's also akin to a legislative hearings. And then, of course,
there's the daily media show outside the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   For the bone-chilled camera team, David Boies, the government's
lead attorney, termed the potential impact of the AOL-Netscape deal
a ``red herring.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the witness stand, Fisher conceded that the
planned merger ``will have some relevance,'' calling it ``hopeful
sign'' of renewed competition in the industry. But he added: ``It
won't have changed the fact that Microsoft took actions to reduce
the threat from Netscape's browser.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacovara told Jackson that he plans to complete his
cross-examination of Fisher on Thursday. Microsoft will then begin
its defense Monday, with the company's witnesses being
cross-examined by Boies and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
