<SLUG> BC-SCHUMER-POTHOLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER TAKES ON MANTLE OF `SENATOR POTHOLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Introducing New York's new ``Senator Pothole'':
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schumer, 48, hadn't even been sworn in yet Wednesday as
his state's junior Democratic senator when he was on the phone
shaking loose $500,000 in federal highway funds for Ogdensburg, a
small upstate city along the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just spoke with the Federal Highway Administration,''
Schumer beamed at a news conference shortly before he took the oath
administered by Vice President Al Gore. ``Ogdensburg is going to be
getting the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attention to local matters proved a successful political
formula for Schumer's predecessor, Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
who earned the nickname ``Senator Pothole'' for his commitment
during his 18 years in Congress to helping local officials tease
money from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   And Schumer said he's proud to don the mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I campaigned against Sen. D'Amato, one thing I never did
was demean the title Senator Pothole,'' Schumer said. ``I think
that is an important role for a senator, although certainly not the
only role.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, during his campaign last fall to unseat D'Amato,
Schumer ran a political advertisement making fun of an unnamed
lawmaker who filled potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, in one of his first acts since changing addresses on
Capitol Hill, where he previously was a congressman representing
Brooklyn for 18 years, asked Kenneth Wykle, who heads Federal
Highway Administration, for federal funds to help convert the
Ogdensburg post office area into a downtown economic hub. Wykle
obliged.
</P>
<P>
   The request had come from the town's mayor. ``I'll be on the
phone to let him know the good news,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page out of D'Amato's play book, New York's new senator
has traveled around the state since his victory to meet with local
officials and offer his help.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he was in Albany telling local leaders that he would
help them get federal funds to improve roads to the city's airport.
</P>
<P>
   He has traveled several times to Fort Drum, home of the Army's
10th Mountain Division, to reassure leaders there that he
understands the base is the economic lifeblood of the region and
should remain open.
</P>
<P>
   When upstate New York was socked in by a winter storm earlier
this week, Schumer said he was on the phone with local leaders ``to
see if Buffalo needed any help. ``I've always wanted to be two
kinds of senator at once,'' he explained, ``a senator who
legislates and a senator who is able to handle the specific
individual requests.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to working on matters with national implications
like Social Security and education, Schumer said he intends to
serve as his state's top cheerleader urging corporations interested
in relocating to consider New York.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to aid economically depressed areas, Schumer said
he will ask companies located in New York City to open branch
facilities in such places around the state where labor costs and
taxes are less burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer defeated D'Amato in November after an often acrimonious
campaign. But he praised his predecessor Wednesday, calling him
``gracious'' in seeing that Schumer had a smooth transition into
his new post. The new senator promised he would continue to work on
some projects that D'Amato had championed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
