<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHRISTO-2TAKES-NYT     01-06 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHRISTO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF CHRISTO WRAPS IT, PEOPLE WILL COME 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By   CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christo and his wife, Jeanne-Claude, waited 24 years
for the German government to allow them to wrap the Reichstag in
Berlin in more than 1 million square feet of aluminum-colored
fabric; 10 years for permission from the French authorities to
swathe the Pont Neuf in Paris in 454,178 square feet of a
champagne-colored textile that shimmered like silk; seven years to
plant a forest of giant umbrellas in the rice paddies near Tokyo
and along the open hillsides of Southern California, and 32 years
to veil 161 trees in black-and-white polyester mesh in a park in
Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   If persistence pays off this year, the Bulgarian-born artist and
his wife will have spent more than 20 years on their project to
erect 11,000 steel gates in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on it. In 1981 the New York City Parks Department
denied Christo a permit to put up the gates, which would stand 15
feet high and be topped by free-flowing panels of woven
saffron-colored nylon stretching along 27 miles of walkway.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons for the denial cited in a 107-page report
issued by Gordon Davis, then te parks commissioner, was the crowds
``The Gates'' were expected to generate. (Officials at both the
Parks Department and the Central Park Conservancy said recently
that if the ``Wrapped Reichstag'' attracted more than 5 million
visitors, New York could expect even more people to converge on
Central Park if ``The Gates'' were installed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christos have a wonderful racket, but we don't need them
here,'' said Henry J. Stern, the parks and recreation commissioner.
``If they want public attention, why not try wrapping Trump
Tower?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the couple remain undeterred. ``It's not patience, it's
passion,'' Christo said. ``We're not giving up. Of course there
will be traffic in Central Park, but we will have more than 2,000
people monitoring the project day and night. The park will be
cleaner and safer than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple often encounter the kinds of costs, delays and
hurdles more familiar to real estate developers than artists.
Although most of their installations are up for about two weeks,
their choice of populated sites means there are always zoning and
planning boards to be dealt with, not to mention insurance
companies. There are also the inevitable problems and politics that
come with public art projects.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, whose first collaborations were executed in 1961,
are persuasive. He was born Christo Javacheff, though he uses only
his first name (as does his wife and collaborator, who was born
Jeanne-Claude de Guillebon). He is a short, inquisitive figure with
an intense stare; many people have said he resembles Woody Allen.
She is perhaps best identified by her decisive manner and flaming
red hair, a color chosen by her husband).
</P>
<P>
   They finance their projects with the money they make selling
Christo's artwork: drawings and collages of projects as well as
early works from the 1950s and 1960s of wrapped objects. A recent
book about their umbrella project sells for $750. They say the idea
of accepting sponsorship is an anathema. ``If we had sponsors, we'd
lose our freedom,'' Jeanne-Claude said. ``We'll sell anything but
our son.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping the Reichstag was a $13 million project. Placing the
umbrellas in Japan and California cost $26 million. They haven't
drawn a bottom line on the cost of the ``Wrapped Trees'' in Basel,
but she estimates that it was under $1 million. The cost of ``The
Gates'' in Central Park could reach more than $30 million, but the
couple say they never know the true cost of a project until it is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Christo and Jeanne-Claude were both born on June 13, 1935, he in
Bulgaria, she in Casablanca, Morocco. They met in Paris in 1958,
but it was only four-and-a-half years ago that they began putting
both their names on their projects. (From the beginning, she has
been the manager on every project.) Since they came to New York 34
years ago they have lived and worked out of a 200-year-old building
in SoHo that was an ammunition depot during the Civil War. ``When
we arrived here there were no other buildings around it,'' said
Christo. ``It was empty, and we rented one floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they own the building and use the second floor as a gallery,
the third floor for framing and shipping, the fourth floor as part
home, part office, and the top floor as Christo's studio. All day
long they communicate by walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Every project requires years of planning, nightmarish logistics
and specialists. When they wrapped the Reichstag they employed 210
construction workers, including 90 specially trained rock climbers,
as well as 17 office workers and 600 guides to answer questions and
control crowds. The umbrella project took 2,800 workers, and the
Basel installation required the services of 37 professionals,
including rock climbers and pruners, as well as 200 people to
control the traffic and crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds must be monitored, as the couple know only too well. Two
deaths resulted from ``The Umbrellas, Japan-U.S.A., 1984-91.''
During the dismantling of the umbrellas in Japan, a 51-year-old
crane operator died when the arm of the crane he was operating
touched a 65,000-volt power line. In California, high winds blew an
umbrella across a road and crushed a 33-year-old woman against a
boulder. ``These accidents were devastating for us,'' said
Jeanne-Claude.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the threat of accidents that has the Parks
Department and the Central Park Conservancy opposed to ``The
Gates.'' Officials cite environmental reasons too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Christo fan,'' said Marc Matsil, chief of the Natural
Resources Group for the New York City Parks Department. ``But in
this case Christo has gone from post-modern to post-mortem. It's
unconscionable to drive stakes and piles into one of the greatest
parks in the world. It could contribute to a slow or quick death to
some of the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira M. Millstein, the chairman of the Central Park Conservancy,
said he didn't see how ``The Gates'' would add to the enjoyment of
the park. ``It's the conservancy's role to protect the park for the
benefit of the public, and that's what we're doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple contends that no harm will be done to the trees or to
the park environment. ``We will insert sleeves that will be driven
hydraulically into the ground,'' Christo said. ``We will avoid
roots and rocks. We are very responsible people. When we take the
gates down, we will fill the holes with good soil. Nothing will
remain when the project is over and nothing will be harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   So determined are the couple to turn ``The Gates'' into a
reality that they hired the social psychologist Kenneth B. Clark to
conduct what they call a human impact study based on interviews
with 660 New Yorkers. They said it showed that the majority of the
respondents were in favor of the installation. `` `The Gates' would
be like a giant floating roof over the park,'' Jeanne-Claude said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fabric is the common denominator in every project. ``For over
5,000 years, artists have been fascinated by folds and pleats and
draperies,'' Jeanne-Claude said. ``The greatest example is Rodin.''
</P>
<P>
   His first version of Balzac was of a naked figure, Jeanne-Claude
recalled. But Rodin was not satisfied with the sculpture, so he
took a cape, put it in wet plaster and draped the figure. ``By
wrapping the sculpture, he left only the essence of Balzac, which
is exactly what we did to the Reichstag and the Pont Neuf,'' she
said. ``We removed the details and left the shape and the
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabric selection can be a project in itself. The black and white
polyester mesh used for the ``Wrapped Trees'' was woven in Germany
in 156 separate patterns, since most of the 178 trees, some of
which were as tall as 85 feet, had definite silhouettes that
required specific tailoring. The 500,000 square feet of black and
white polyester mesh had to be transparent enough so that when the
sun was behind the trees every branch was visible. ``Our fabrics
are full of motion, they're not static,'' Jeanne-Claude said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple are testing different kinds of fabric for yet another
project in the planning stages: creating a six-mile wave of fabric
panels 10 to 23 feet above the Arkansas River in Colorado. Approval
of that one will require running a gantlet of 27 Federal, state and
local agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever permit they get first _ for ``The Gates'' in Central
Park or ``Over the River'' in Colorado _ will determine which
project they will concentrate on in earnest. Each has its
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has an opinion or discussion about a painting a painter
hasn't painted,'' Jeanne-Claude said. ``But everyone discusses in
advance what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's the ephemeral quality of each Christo project that
creates much of the magic, they say. ``It gives our art a
once-upon-a-time quality,'' she said, to which her husband added:
``It's a once-in-a-lifetime experience.e do something, we'll
never do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
