<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GHOST-GALAXIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DWARF GALAXIES DENSER THAN PREVIOUSLY THOUGHT, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Hawaii, Calif., Conn.) 
 (nk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Compared to luminous giant galaxies like the
Milky Way, dwarf galaxies are faint and fuzzy, like celestial
ghosts. Yet they may outnumber the giants and apparently harbor far
denser concentrations of invisible dark matter, the enigmatic stuff
that constitutes nearly all the mass of the universe, astronomers
reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new research, announced at a meeting of the American
Astronomical Society, shows that these small galaxies with a
scattering of bright stars have dark-matter densities about 100
times greater than the density of matter in the more imposing
galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dwarfs may look insubstantial, but they are like
cannonballs to a giant galaxy,'' said Dr. John Kormendy, an
astronomer at the University of Hawaii in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Because the high densities of the faintest dwarfs appear to be
comparable to the assumed average density of the early universe,
these objects could be remnants of the earliest time of galaxy
formation. Astronomers also said the findings could provide new
insights into how dark matter affects galaxy formation. The nature
of the elusive dark matter and its role in shaping the universe are
among the foremost mysteries in cosmology.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small fraction of the cosmic mass is composed of visible
stars, planets and other ordinary matter. At least 90 percent is
something else, most of which is presumed to be exotic subatomic
particles created in the Big Bang, the theorized origin of the
universe. The existence of this ``missing mass'' is inferred from
its gravitational effect on the shape and motions of galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   In another report at the meeting, astronomers studying the
Hubble Space Telescope's infrared images of the faint halo around
the spiral galaxy NGC 5907 found evidence of a surprising abundance
of low-mass stars. The observations support the concept that some
of the dark matter in galaxy halos could be small stars that have
gone undetected. In that case, both low-mass stars and exotic
particles may contribute to galaxy formation and structure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vera Rubin, an astrophysicist at the Carnegie Institution of
Washington, who pioneered dark-matter studies in the 1970s, said
the work of both research groups was impressive, but left
astronomers still groping for a solution to the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the Dark Ages about dark matter, and we're
looking for a Renaissance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kormendy and Dr. Kenneth C. Freeman of the Australian National
University and Mount Stromlo Observatory based their research on
studies of 43 galaxies ranging from large bright spirals to the
faintest dwarf galaxies known. As suggested by other recent
observations, they found that the less luminous galaxies have lower
densities of stars but higher densities of dark matter.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible part of Earth's home galaxy, the Milky Way, is
about 50 percent dark; the smallest dwarf galaxies are almost
completely dark, with no more than 1 percent of their matter in the
form of stars.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers think they have an explanation. Because smaller
galaxies have less of a firm gravitational grip on their contents,
the dispersed gases from their first stars to die in explosions may
vanish into intergalactic space, leaving the dwarf galaxy with less
gas to form new generations of stars. The explosions, on the other
hand, have little effect on exotic dark matter.
</P>
<P>
   Kormendy noted two other implications of the new research. One
is that the higher dark-matter densities indicate that the smallest
dwarf galaxies are not shreds torn from colliding large galaxies,
as had been theorized; if they were, they would probably have lower
densities than their parent galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are real galaxies, not little fragments pulled out of big
galaxies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, means that the number of dwarf galaxies is not
somehow tied to the limited number of galaxy collisions that have
occurred in cosmic history, Kormendy said. And since these dwarf
galaxies have so few stars and are hard to see at best, many more
of them are out there beyond human vision.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin agreed. ``If something is not forbidden by physics, it
probably exists,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The research on NGC 5907's dark matter was conducted by Michael
Liu, a graduate student at the University of California at
Berkeley, working with Dr. James Graham of Berkeley, Dr. Steve Zepf
of Yale University and astronomers in England, France and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   It was what they did not see that intrigued them. Looking into a
patch of the galaxy's dim halo, they expected to see more than 100
giant stars that would have accounted for the faint glow, but
detected only a handful. They estimated that at least 20 times more
light in the halo comes from low-mass stars too faint to be singled
out than from visible giants.
</P>
<P>
   Liu said this was ``the first direct evidence of a substantial
population of stars which is essentially all dwarf stars.'' Some of
the dark matter of a galaxy had been detected, and it is ordinary
matter, but this was not enough to hold this galaxy together. So
the search for what else there is must continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
