 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release January 7, 1999, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-MAIN _ What to do with the name NetCom, which is many
folks' internet address. Will MindSpring create a junior brand?
We'll get into the finances and personnel stuff. What will happen
to both companies. Where does this put MindSpring in the ranking of
ISP's? Will MindSpring be able to handle the growth smoothly. Is
this part of a trend of consolidation. Are there other likely
targets? Is MindSpring still one of them, or is it getting too big
to get bought? Chart of top five ISPs, with number of subscribers.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/ MINDSPRING-CUSTOMER _ What this means to the many customers
of MindSpring in metro Atlanta? When MSp bought PSI, there were
slowdowns. What does it mean for others, including NetCom
customers. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-NETCOM _ Profile of Netcom, one of the pioneers in
Internet. It was the first way regular people could get Net access
and was the first ISP to reach half a million subscribers. Any
Atlanta and Georgia operations? (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-THEDEAL _ How did the deal come together. Hope for
detail about how Charles Brewer decided to buy the first internet
service provider he ever used. (Haddad/Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-MICROSOFT _ SAN FRANCISCO _ As Apple Computer tries to
persuade the software industry to produce games and applications
for the Macintosh, it has a strong ally in a seemingly unlikely
place. Microsoft Corp. maintains a division of about 200
programmers who focus exclusively on software for Macs. Making his
annual appearance at Macworld, the general manager of the division,
Ben Waldman, is one of the most enthusiastic Mac supporters and he
sometimes tweaks his employer to make points with the sometimes
skeptical Mac loyalists. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman). 18.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN _ Joseph Corr will step down as chairman and chief
executive of AirTran and will be replaced by Joseph Lenard,
president and chief executive of AlliedSignal's aerospace marketing
division. Corr was hired in 1996 to lead the restructuring after
the ValuJet crash. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RICHS-CHAIRMAN _ Russell Stravitz, chairman of Federated's
Atlanta-based Rich's/Lazarus Goldsmith's division, is leaving. His
replacement is Arnold Orlick, president and COO of
Rich's/Lazarus/Goldsmith's. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GA-BARNES-TECH _ Georiga Gov.-elect Roy Barnes on Thursday will
talk about his plan to bring high-tech companies to Atlanta and
Georgia. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
