<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-MICROSOFT07-COX     01-06 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-MICROSOFT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mircosoft scores big at Macworld
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a freshman at Harvard University in 1985, Ben
Waldman wrote software programs for the Macintosh because he liked
the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, he went to work for Microsoft Corp., long
regarded by some as the arch enemy of Apple Computer Corp.'s arch
enemy, which makes the Macintosh. But his job is to produce
Microsoft software than runs on Macintoshes.
</P>
<P>
   This week at Macworld Expo in San Francisco, the work of Waldman
and his staff won plaudits from Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Word 98 software for the Mac won the Software
Productivity Award at Macworld and the Excel spread sheet program
was runner up.
</P>
<P>
   As general manager of the 200-employee Macintosh Business Unit,
Waldman works closely with Apple and Mac users. His appearances at
with Apple's interim
</P>
<P>
   chief executive Steve Jobs at Macworld make him one of the most
</P>
<P>
   visible Microsoft executives with Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to bring features first and only on the
Macintosh version of our product,'' Waldman told the audience on
Tuesday, thrusting his arms toward the crowd while walking back and
forth on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft employs one of the biggest Mac software development
team outside of Apple, according to both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Mac staff may seem small, but it demonstrates the
importance of having widely used software available for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mac users have mixed emotions about Apple's alliance with
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Tom Miller, an Oakland, Calif., businessowner
whohas used Macs for 10 years, watched a Microsoft employee
demonstrate Office 98 to a large crowd at Macworld. He plans to buy
a copy of it for his small music-production company.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he won't switch to Microsoft's World Wide Web
browser, Internet Explorer, because he believes Microsoft has
treated Netscape Inc. unfairly, as the U.S. Justice Department
alleges in the antitrust trial currently underway in fedeal court
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of bias, to be honest with you, because of
everything that has gone down with Bill Gates and the federal
case,'' Miller said. ``I would never consider using Internet
Explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's interim chief executive Steve Jobs periodically reminds
Macintosh users, as he did this week at Macworld in the Moscone
Convention Center, that Apple and
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft are partners, not foes.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mac users, who are fond of pointing out ways in which
Windows
</P>
<P>
   does not measure up to the Mac system, were shocked at the
summer 1997 Macworld in Boston when Jobs announced that Microsoft
was coming to Apple's rescue with a $150 million purchase of Apple
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs also noted that Microsoft's software support was crucial
toApple, especially since many developers gave up on the Mac
platform as Apple sank into financial trouble in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft isn't sticking with Apple out of kindness or to
show critics that it helps some of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 10 million customers using our software on the
Macintosh,'' Waldman said
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
