<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-TRIAL-HNS     01-06 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT TRIAL TO OPEN WITHOUT AGREEMENT ON FORMAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate prepared to open the first impeachment
trial of an elected president Thursday amid a continuing partisan
dispute over whether witnesses should be summoned to testify about
President Clinton's cover-up of a sexual relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., huddled separately
with his 54 GOP colleagues, with Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., and with House Republicans in an effort to map
trial procedures that Lott said would give ``all parties a fair
chance to make the case and get to a conclusion that's an equitable
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impeachment trial opens Thursday when 13 members of
the House, led by House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., formally present two articles of impeachment against
Clinton to the Senate. The articles accuse Clinton of committing
perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist will then swear in
the 100 senators as jurors to weigh the articles of impeachment
approved by the House last month. The next action is expected
Monday, though no one could say what will happen then.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats said the price for bipartisanship in the Senate
trial would be Republican agreement not to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers urged the Senate to hear testimony from
Lewinsky, presidential secretary Betty Currie and Clinton
confidante and Washington superlawyer Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, the leader of Senate Democrats, declared that there was
``universal, unanimous opposition'' to calling witnesses among the
45 Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican senators expressed concern that summoning
Lewinsky to the ornate Senate chamber would be distasteful,
inappropriate and politically damaging to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a possible Republican presidential
candidate in 2000, said he was ``very skittish'' about calling
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the door to calling witnesses also raised the risk that
Clinton would be called upon to testify _ forcing the embattled
chief executive to either show up and publicly admit that he lied
or to reject the Senate summons, precipitating a constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way it would be disastrous,'' said Alan Dershowitz, a
Harvard law professor and Clinton defender.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has received no commitment from Senate leaders
that the trial will be limited only to evidence gathered by special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr, according to White House Press Secretary
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the White House hoped that a bipartisan
arrangement might still emerge to enable the nation and Clinton to
avoid a prolonged Senate trial featuring televised testimony about
the president's sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what trial procedures the Senate eventually
adopts, Lockhart predicted that Clinton would prevail in any Senate
impeachment trial. If 67 senators vote to convict Clinton of one or
both of the impeachment charges, he would automatically be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the facts and based on the Constitution, the
president will prevail,'' Lockhart declared.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, continuing to portray himself as routinely at work
despite his impeachment, appealed for bipartisan cooperation on
legislation in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot use anything as an excuse not to deal with our
pressing priorities,'' Clinton declared. ``I do not intend to do
that; I do not think the American people expect us to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton remains ``focused on doing his job,''
adding that the president wants the Senate to agree on trial
procedures ``and let us know so we can properly prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like some GOP colleagues, Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., said he
favored ``the option of witnesses.'' Hagel said arrangements could
be made to enable witnesses to avoid ``getting into the specifics''
of the sexual relationship between Lewinsky and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could take testimony without getting into the lurid aspects
of the whole slimy episode,'' Hagel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said the Senate had to determine
whether it had ``an obligation to do a significant amount of
discovery as an integral part of a trial or can we rely on the
record of the House?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said senators remained confused about
how to conduct the first Senate impeachment trial since senators
weighed the removal of President Andrew Johnson in 1868 in a
dispute over the severity of federal occupation of the defeated
Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who became president after the assassination of Abraham
Lincoln, escaped removal from office by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mapping a Senate impeachment trial is ``an arcane, unusual
process,'' Graham said. ``We're stumbling around in the library of
ancient history where the lights have been turned off.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined to say whether the president's lawyers
would call defense witnesses. ``That involves legal strategy, and
I'm not going to get into legal strategy,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
