<HEADER>
A1788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      01-06 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: REMEMBERING PARIS IN THE `JAZZ AGE;' NAMING A
BRAZILIAN AIRPORT; `NOCHE FLAMENCA' RETURNS; HONORS FOR RUSHDIE AND
NICHOLSON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va, D.C., Miss., Cal., Spain, France, Iran)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showcasing luminaries like Josephine Baker, Sidney Bechet,
Hugues Panassie, Cole Porter and Man Ray, the Smithsonian
Institution's 1997 exhibition ``The Jazz Age in Paris, 1914-1940''
is taking to the road. Three reduced versions of the original, each
featuring nearly 100 evocative images of artists, entertainers,
posters and other memorabilia will visit 20 states. The show places
the early jazz movement in historical context and highlights the
contributions of American expatriates. ``The Jazz Age in Paris''
opened &UR;  &LR; Thursday at the Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial Library in
Washington and the Newport News Public Library in Virginia. On
Wednesday it goes to the Delta State University Archives in
Cleveland, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN FLIGHT PATH
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the bossa nova. Brazil has renamed Rio de Janeiro's
international airport in honor of Antonio Carlos Jobim, the
guitarist, pianist and composer who popularized the modification of
samba known as bossa nova. President Fernando Henrique Cardoso of
Brazil said: ``All of us know what Tom Jobim means to Brazilian
culture. He means an incredible amount.'' Jobim died in 1994 at 67.
</P>
<P>
   FIERY ANDALUSIAN FEATS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just in time to inject some heat into winter, ``Noche
Flamenca'' returns to New York for two performances this weekend at
the Kaye Playhouse at Hunter College. With Soledad Barrio leading
the troupe, seven musicians, singers and dancers will conjure up
the earthy essence of flamenco as passed down from Andalusian
Gypsies. With sinuous armwork, volleying footwork and flashing
skirts, the performances are scheduled for 8 p.m. Saturday and 7
p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER CHAPTER
</P>
<P>
   The novelist Salman Rushdie will receive France's most
prestigious literary award in London this month. The French Embassy
announced Wednesday that Rushdie, author of ``The Satanic Verses,''
who has lived under a threat of death since 1989 for allegedly
blaspheming Islam, was to be made a commander in the Order of Arts
and Letters. The honor reflects his popularity in France, where he
has many admirers.
</P>
<P>
   PRIZE PERFORMER
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicholson may not need another award from the Hollywood
Foreign Press Association. After all, he has five of its Golden
Globes. But he's going to get one anyway next month. Nicholson, who
won a Golden Globe only last year for his performance as the
misanthropic writer in ``As Good as It Gets,'' will receive the
organization's honorary Cecil B. DeMille award for ``outstanding
contribution to the entertainment world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
