<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCE-ENGAGED-BOS &LR;      01-06 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-ENGAGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCE EDWARD TO WED LONG-TIME GIRLFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Determined to succeed where his siblings failed, Prince
Edward, Queen Elizabeth's youngest son, announced Wednesday that he
and his longtime girlfriend, Sophie Rhys-Jones, are going to get
married.
</P>
<P>
   No date was set, but the prospect of a royal wedding _ and even
more so, the prospect of a durable royal marriage _ is a welcome
diversion for a monarchy that has been on the defensive since
Diana, Princess of Wales, died in a Paris car crash 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   All of Edward's three siblings, including Prince Charles,
Diana's ex-husband, have divorced. Loveless marriages were common
to monarchies in previous centuries, when unions were arranged
around political and financial considerations. But even in the
latter half of the 20th century, when royals have been allowed to
marry for love, few of the Windsors have made it work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most royal watchers, including Jennie Bond, the BBC's
royalty correspondent, and Ingrid Seward, Edward's biographer, give
this marriage a much better chance of succeeding. First, they point
out that Edward and Rhys-Jones have been going out steadily for
five years. Second, they suggest that Edward is without ambition
within the royal family. Finally, they say Rhys-Jones is far more
mature than either Princess Diana or Sarah Ferguson were at the
time of their weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Edward, 34, was said to be conscious of the pressure to emulate
his parents, who have been married for 51 years. That is one of the
reasons he held off on popping the question for so long. According
to friends, he wanted to make sure that Rhys-Jones was the right
one.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Rhys-Jones, who works for a public relations firm
in London, is described by friends as independent and hardly
determined to become part of the royal family. While Diana and
Fergie became mothers, party girls, and clothes horses after
marrying, Rhys-Jones said she intends to keep working.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rhys-Jones bears a resemblance to the aristocratic
Diana, she is a commoner. Her friends describe her as uncommonly
easygoing and confident. While Diana battled eating disorders and
various neuroses as she tried to fit in with a family that did not
like her, few expect Rhys-Jones to have difficulties fitting in.
She is already a fixture at royal family gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before a bevy of photographers and reporters, Edward
said he and his future wife are ``the best of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the 1981 storybook wedding of Charles and Diana,
which brought the nation to a standstill, Edward and Rhys-Jones
want a wedding that is considerably less grandiose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think getting married is a very personal thing,'' Rhys-Jones
told reporters. ``Naturally, there is going to be more interest in
us than there would be in other people. But it is a personal
matter, and it is a family occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Seward, Edward's biographer, said the long courtship and
Edward's timing of the announcement was in character with his
independent streak.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his brothers, Edward hated the military and quit the
Royal Marines after just four months, angering his father. Edward's
dislike of soldiering, love for the theater, and lack of a serious
girlfriend in his 20s led the tabloids here to suggest he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Edward, seventh in line to the throne, produced a documentary on
Britain that was broadcast last year on PBS. In another documentary
about his great-uncle, Edward, Duke of Windsor, he suggested the
royal family had been too harsh in denying a title to another
commoner, Wallis Simpson, the American divorcee for whom his
great-uncle abdicated.
</P>
<P>
   A royal couple seen as marrying for love could be just what the
monarchy needs, as it battles to regain the popularity it lost when
Diana died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
