<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-ANALYSIS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The NBA labor battle has just begun, experts say
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to be a tough, hard-fought NBA season _ and that's
off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Players and owners might have salvaged some of their season, but
they've got long-term fallout to contend with, labor experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Owners walked away from the negotiating table with hard-earned
concessions, and players go home with the prospect of making even
more millions, but the compromise doesn't ensure future labor
harmony. And the patience of fans of all pro sports is wearing
thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``These strikes tend to damage . . . professional sports,'' said
Les Hough, director of the W.J. Usery Center for the Workplace at
Georgia State University. ``Baseball is just now recovered from its
(1994 strike) in terms of attendance and revenues. It has taken
(three) full seasons before the industry was back to pre-strike
levels in attendance and revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA fans tend to get very upset when players and owners can't
come to agreements. It damages attendance, sales of (souvenirs).
Only time will tell whether NBA attendance recovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the issue of egos and earnings has been settled, who
won?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know if either side won, from a labor point of
view,'' said Richard Ray, secretary-treasurer of Georgia's AFL-CIO,
which represents 300,000 members in about 200 unions. ``It sounds
like they split the difference. The union gained more in the (Larry
Bird) exception rule, while owners gained in the revenue
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelmingly for the next few seasons, both sides have lost,
because revenues will be down, attendance will be down and so will
TV-audience viewing,'' Hough said.''It will be hard to get the
(television) networks to cough up money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
