A1818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-TV07-COX     01-06 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-TV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA TV situation may be ``murky''
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the NBA's television carriers finally were able to exhale
after a Wednesday agreement ended the lockout, NBC and Turner still
did not know about its programming for the abbreviated season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC said it would not comment until it gets official
notification from the league, a position shared by Turner Sports
vice president Greg Hughes, who would say only, ''Obviously, we're
pleased with the latest developments.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's television partners were reluctant to comment because
it seems unlikely that their current schedules will be joined in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still murky,'' said Fox Sports South vice president
Hunter Nickell, whose regional sports network has packages with the
Hawks and Hornets. ''What will the NBA release as a new schedule is
the key piece of information, and all we can do right now is wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA has a 13-week regular season, as projected, that
should mean at least 39 games for Turner, which will have games
Monday on TBS and Tuesday and Friday on TNT. Additional games are
possible, either as part of a doubleheader on those three nights or
on a different night.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's current schedule, slated to resume Feb. 7, has 23 games
remaining. As a result the NBA's carrier on ``free TV'' might not
be affected beyond the current loss of nine telecasts and the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   While Turner has been able to substitute movies that get similar
ratings to regular-season NBA telecasts, the cable carrier, as its
network counterpart at NBC, has taken a big hit in the key male
demographics that advertisers find most attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Both networks have sponsors with long-term deals on their NBA
packages, so they should not have to start from ground zero to get
advertising for the shortened season. But getting all of the spots
sold will be a much tougher task.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our sales people have stayed in contact with the sponsors and
advertisers,'' Nickell said. ''And my feeling is that the sponsors
and advertisers have been terrific about hanging in through the
process. But we won't know until the schedule is confirmed how it
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   A major concern for NBC will be timing of the NBA Finals, which
almost certainly will not be held in the first week of June.
Viewership levels tend to drop as the summer advances, and ratings
for the Finals could plunge if the playoffs drag into the first
week of July.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the radio side, the sales staff at WSB faces tghe
challenge of drumming up advertising for the Hawks' package in less
than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to jump in there and do our best,'' WSB Radio vice
president Marc Morgan said. ``Right now, we're not sure of the
total impact (the lockout) has had. But, hopefully, all the fan
rage and any uncomfortable feelings will begin to subside.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
