<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAQ&AMP;A07-COX     01-06 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAQ&AMP;A07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A on NBA lockout
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is there a clear winner now that a basic settlement is agreed
upon?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not totally. The owners got what they wanted, which is cost
certainty, but the price is high, too high for some. However, now
the NBA will get labor peace for at least six years, with the
league holding an option for the seventh. That gives the game time
to recover and win back its fans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a loser?
</P>
<P>
   A: Union executive director Billy Hunter is hardly a winner
after vowing to ``kick David Stern's butt'' and falling far short.
The high-end players will suffer a little, because their salaries
have been topped out. That is an unhappy result for Scottie Pippen,
for example, who hoped he would be able to break a couple of banks
with his next deal, since the 35-year-old rule would remain in
effect even for players eligible for the maximum contract. It means
that no player who will reach age 35 during the term of a contract
can sign for more than four years.
</P>
<P>
   Q What are the maximums for ``Larry Bird'' free agents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Players through the first six years can start as high as $9
million. Hawks free-agent Alan Henderson is an example of a player
in that range. Players in years 7 to 9 can start at $11 million.
Players with 10 or more years of service can start as high as $14
million. The maximum raise for Bird players is 12 percent, based on
year 1. The maximum for everyone else is 10 percent. That means
that instead of going for a $100 million-plus deal from Minnesota
next season, Stephon Marbury could sign for $9 million, with annual
raises of $1.08 million a year for the duration of his agreement.
It is a significant victory for the NBA and for small- to
middle-market teams. No club will be held hostage again in a Kevin
Garnett situation.
</P>
<P>
   Q What about David Falk, who for years was able to intimidate
teams into paying huge salaries?
</P>
<P>
   A: This deal does wound Falk. As it works its way through the
next few years, many players will realize that the slotted salaries
will make high-powered agents far less effective. Instead of paying
as much as 4 per cent of salaries, they might choose agents who
charge an hourly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Q When can teams talk to players and sign free agents?
</P>
<P>
   A: After ratification of the agreement, which is expected to
take 10 days. Training camp and free-agent signings will start the
next day.Q What about Michael Jordan? Will he play?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one knows for certain, but the betting is that he will
retire. The scenario presented by his good friend Charles Barkley
is that Jordan waited until a deal was in place to make his
announcement so he would not undercut his friend and agent David
Falk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any chance this agreement will fall apart?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, although there might be a little of kicking and
screaming. Both sides could balk over details and threaten to blow
it up, but that's not going to happen. The deal will be made.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, when does the season start?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not certain, but the players think they will go to
training camp on Jan. 18 and start play Feb. 2, with the season
running to May 1. Each team will have a week in which it plays
three nights in a row, and the schedule is said to be in the 50- to
52-game range.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to the old schedule?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's basically gone. No tickets will be sold until a new
schedule is in place, and season patrons apparently will be able to
exchange their old tickets for new. It is reasonable to assume that
the NBA has been working with a number of scheduling scenarios.
Each team probably will play the majority of its games within its
own division and conference. Some traditional East-West rivalries
will be retained, if possible, but arena days will rule the day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the principal compromises that made the deal
possible?
</P>
<P>
   A: The union and the league met at a 55 percent split for the
players in years four, five and six. In year seven, the players
will take home 57 percent, but only if the league exercises its
option.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   A: For this season, it will be $30 million, about $1 million
less than had been projected. But next season, the cap jumps to $34
million, great news for a team like the Hawks, who finally get Ken
Norman's contract off their cap. For example, this season, Norman
is slotted at $3.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the cap exceptions?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are two. The agreement retains the $1 million exception
to be used every other year, and the so-called average-salary
exception is being phased in at $1.75 million this season,
increasing to $2 million, $2.25 million and then to the average
salary of the league. This exception is available every year to
teams over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Q What about rookies?
</P>
<P>
   A: The NBA prevailed here, too. First-rounders will sign
three-year deals, with an option for a fourth year after the second
year. In year 5, all teams retain the right of first refusal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
