<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-PREVIEW07-COX     01-06 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-PREVIEW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PGA season for 1999
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The PGA Tour's offseason is about as short as a gimme putt. It
resumes today _ in limited fashion but with the first official
money of 1999 available _ with the first round of the Mercedes
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament moved this year from its traditional venue, the
LaCosta Resort in Carlsbad, Calif., to the Kapalua Plantation
Course on the Hawaiian island of Maui. It features just 30
tournament winners from 1998 out of a possible field of 35.
</P>
<P>
   For players such as Fred Couples, who when last seen was
lamenting a President's Cup loss to Australia in mid-December, it
seemed as though time away from competition ended almost before it
started.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Christmas was over, I couldn't believe six days later I
was getting on plane,'' Couples said.
</P>
<P>
   Rough duty, it isn't. While the Midwest digs out from another
blizzard, 30 players compete in 80-degree temperatures for a purse
of $2.6 million, an increase from $1.7 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Four players in the field have won the previously unofficial PGA
Tour event there. Couples and Davis Love III were two-time
champions at Kapalua, and Mark O'Meara and Jim Furyk each won once.
</P>
<P>
   LaCosta, for all its Southern California splendor, regularly had
trouble with January rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine with me, moving here,'' Couples said. ``The course
is fantastic. The guys will miss LaCosta, but this is a good spot.
It's a playable course, but it can play hard. When the wind blows,
you can get the ball going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Five players were eligible but are not attending for various
reasons. The absentees are England's Lee Westwood, who plays mainly
on the European Tour; the recently married Ernie Els of South
Africa; Olin Browne, recovering from a wrist injury; Zimbabwean
Nick Price, who usually doesn't appear on the PGA Tour until Doral
in March; and Hal Sutton, whose wife will deliver twins soon.
</P>
<P>
   For two players in particular, the challenge to match 1998's
successes will be formidable. Former Georgia Tech player David
Duval won four times, captured the money title with $2,591,031 and
won the Vardon Trophy for the lowest scoring average (69.13).
Player of the Year Mark O'Meara, 41, became the oldest player to
win two majors, taking the Masters and the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is coming off a season that lacked victories _ his
only PGA Tour win came at Atlanta's BellSouth Classic _ but
produced $1,841,174 and 12 top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes begins a landmark year, with the introduction of
three World Golf Championship events, each with $5 million purses,
beginning with the Andersen Consulting World Match Play
Championship, Feb. 24-28 at LaCosta.
</P>
<P>
   For the Atlanta area, big-time golf in 1999 enjoys an expanded
forum. The BellSouth Classic and the Masters will be played in
consecutive weeks to begin April.
</P>
<P>
   Other questions to be answered in the coming months:
</P>
<P>
   Will Greg Norman win again at 43 during his comeback year from
shoulder surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Will Nick Faldo, who disappeared last year as quickly as Norman
did on Sunday at Augusta in 1996, climb back up the world rankings?
</P>
<P>
   Will Tom Lehman, another victim of shoulder surgery, regain the
form that made him the PGA Tour Player of the Year in 1996?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
