<HEADER>
A1821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON07-COX     01-06 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN SHADOW OF HISTORIC TRIAL, CLINTON SOLDIERS ON
 &HT;    490&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About to become only the second president in
history to face a Senate impeachment trial, President Clinton spent
Wednesday much as he has spent the past year: juggling his public
duties as chief executive with behind-the-scenes efforts to manage
a complicated legal and political campaign to save his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   While officially the White House described his mood as
''concerned,'' Clinton, by his own telling, is a man torn by deep
emotions: shame over his own conduct, frustration with the
predicament it has landed him in, and anger toward those he blames
for using his troubles as a weapon against him.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, though, the president and his senior aides are
projecting the image of a chief executive fully in command of his
office, and engaged, if not obsessed, with doing the people's
business.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's mood hasn't changed since the last time you
asked me this,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters
Wednesday. ''He's focused on doing his job; He is concerned about
how this process will unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate trial scheduled to ceremonially open Thursday,
Clinton staged a press event on Wednesday to highlight good
economic news.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by key members of his economic and budget team, Clinton
announced that the budget surplus for this year is expected to top
$76 billion _ a record. He used the estimate, which normally is
released along with the Feb. 1 issuance of the annual
administration budget proposal, to claim credit for ending three
decades of federal budget deficits, declaring that ''the era of big
deficits is over.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth day in the past five that Clinton has trotted
out some element of his 1999 legislative agenda. He proposed
increased defense spending on Saturday, tax credits for long-term
health care on Monday, and a plan for combating crime and drugs on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, even as the Senate soberly takes up the formalities
of his impeachment trial, Clinton plans to spotlight yet another
initiative, a plan for helping working Americans pay for
after-school care for their children.
</P>
<P>
   It's normal for presidents to use the first working days of the
year to lay out early priorities, as Congress returns from its
year-end recess and begins to gear up for the work ahead. The idea
is to build momentum for the White House agenda in the weeks
leading up to the president's annual State of the Union address,
which Clinton is preparing to deliver on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, there's an added mission to the message.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Clinton's continuing popularity _ polls continue
to show that roughly 7 in 10 Americans approve of the way he's
doing his job _ is that the public generally believes he's hard at
work on issues that matter to most people.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that image, through a continuing stream of
theme-of-the-day events, if need be, is a cornerstone of the
president's survival strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   White House officials won't say how much time Clinton spends
each day coordinating his legal strategy with the battery of
personal lawyers and White House counselors that will defend him
against charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't really have the answer to that question. I think the
lawyers are unlikely to be specific about it,'' said James Kennedy,
spokesman for the office of White House Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will officials spell out the president's role in working
with Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., to try to come up with a
compromise that the White House hopes will lead to a speedy trial
ending in acquittal or, at worst, censure.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is spending the appropriate amount of time he needs to on
this,'' Lockhart said, referring to the legal side of the effort to
save Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kennedy, ''the bulk of his time remains on his other
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met Wednesday, for instance, with his economic and
budget team to try to put together remaining pieces of his proposed
budget for the fiscal year that begins next October, a massive
package of some $1.7 trillion in taxes and spending that will form
the centerpiece of his 1999 agenda.
</P>
<P>
   He also spent an hour meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, national security adviser Samuel Berger, Defense
Secretary William Cohen, and other national security principals,
surveying an array of foreign policy challenges ranging from the
ongoing conflict with Iraq to efforts to bring peace to the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's official duties, however, are set against the
extraordinary backdrop of the first Senate impeachment trial of a
president in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   No one is pretending that it's business as usual for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For while the White House contends that the charges against
Clinton don't warrant his removal from office, a trial is still a
trial, and whether at the end of it two-thirds of the Senate would
vote to remove Clinton from office is, at the moment, impossible to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on the Constitution and based on the facts as we know
them, I don't see how they could,'' said Lockhart. ''That doesn't
mean that they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
