<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First day on the job for Governr Jeb Bush
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ On his first full day as governor, Jeb Bush
exercised, had a bran muffin for breakfast, and held private
meetings with the Senate president and House speaker _ despite a
constitutional requirement that meetings among the three be open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a courtesy meeting,'' Bush said of his separate
20-minute meetings with Toni Jennings and John Thrasher, adding
that they discussed ``in a broad, general way'' the state budget
and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Constitution states that meetings between the
governor and either presiding officer called to find agreement on
``formal legislative action that will be taken at a subsequent
time, or at which formal legislative action is taken, regarding
pending legislation . . . shall be reasonably open to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the budget _ which this year could top $47 billion _ and
any tax cuts would require legislation passed by both chambers.
Bush Wednesday asked the two leaders' permission to postpone the
due date for his first budget from Jan. 16 to Feb. 15 and also
asked for assistance from their budget staffs.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Thrasher, before he entered his meeting, said he
planned to discuss education and tax cuts. Senate President
Jennings blamed Bush for failing to post any required notices of
the meeting but urged leniency. He called her Tuesday to invite
her, and it was his responsibility, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my meeting,'' she said. ``Let's give him a week to
know what's happening and then we'll jump on him about secret
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I do not believe the governor intentionally
violated the spirit or the letter of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, backed up by his general counsel Carol Licko, argued that
Wednesday's meetings don't fall under that requirement. For
instance, Bush said, the subject of his tough gun-crime initiative
called ``10-20-life'' never came up with Thrasher, even though a
House committee passed a bill creating the harsher sentencing rules
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no specific discussion,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   That explanation is not good enough, said Barbara Petersen of
Tallahassee's First Amendment Foundation. ``I think he's splitting
hairs, and he's violating the spirit and the intent of the law,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Bralow, the lawyer for the Florida Society of Newspaper
Editors, said the new governor may not be accustomed to the strict
openness under which government operates in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding wanting to give the new administration the
benefit of the doubt, in Florida we've always erred on the side of
access not on the side of closure. . .,'' Bralow said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his top staff have since Election Day said they intend
to be the most open, most forthcoming administration in history
regarding open meetings and public records. Wednesday's face off
with capital bureau reporters, however, was the latest in a series
of disagreements between the media and Bush over what constitutes a
public document or an open meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's team released ``questionnaires'' filled out by
prospective administration appointees on Dec. 31, weeks after
requested by The Palm Beach Post and only after The Post and other
newspapers prepared to file a lawsuit to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Transition team lawyers initially argued that Bush was a private
citizen in the two months between his election and his
inauguration, even though he had access to a $2 million transition
budget, occupied state buildings and posted a Web page on a state
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, Florida
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
