<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ETHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LIFTS RESTRICTIONS ON INEXPENSIVE GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Utah)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR,
HOUSE-HASTERT, HOUSE, CONGRESS-NY and IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(js) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives voted Wednesday to
allow members to accept modest gifts, like inexpensive meals and
souvenirs, easing a strict limit on gifts that has been in force
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The change, which took effect immediately, was agreed to by a
voice vote, and no one spoke against it.
</P>
<P>
   House rules now conform to the Senate's, allowing noncash gifts
worth up to $50. A House member may not accept more than $100 worth
of gifts from one person each year. Gifts worth less than $10 do
not count toward the annual limit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old rules, House members and congressional staff
members could not accept gifts or meals except under narrow
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were part of a broad revision of the House rules
that was adopted Wednesday. Most of the changes involved
legislative procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The gift limit was changed in part because so many members were
applying to the Ethics Committee for exceptions to allow them to
accept trivial gifts. Examples of items that now are exempt from
controls include a greeting card, baseball cap, or T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were worked out by a bipartisan group of lawmakers
and were offered on the House floor by Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah,
who heads the Ethics Committee, and Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif,
its senior Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned more than I ever wanted to know about the gift
rule, and I think everyone who has had to deal with it feels the
same way,'' said Hansen, who is stepping down as chairman. ``The
fact is that under the current rule, modest and inexpensive gifts,
which raise the least ethical concerns, still raise questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Ethics Committee had issued about 1,500
opinions about exemptions to the rule, and that sometimes members
had to ponder whether to accept something as simple as a box of
candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't have to have a lawyer stand by your side to tell
you what is and isn't acceptable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules change did not alter a longstanding loophole that
allows lawmakers to take junkets like expenses-paid trips to
meetings of business groups at resorts, on the grounds that such
appearances are part of their official duties.
</P>
<P>
   The House also clarified its rules to require that consultants
working for House members and committees follow the same ethics
rules as House members and full-time employees, limiting their
lobbying activities. Last year, House Democrats objected when two
Republican consultants to a committee investigating the teamsters'
union continued to work as lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   And the House agreed to let junior staff members receive payment
for writing, speeches and other activities not related to their
official duties. Congressional employees were not covered by a 1995
Supreme Court decision that let other government workers earn such
outside income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
