<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE REGENERATES STRONG EMOTIONS IN FAMILIES OF DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the families whose lives are partially depicted in
``A Civil Action,'' Wednesday's premiere brought a jumble of
conflicting emotions: excitement and grief, anticipation and anger.
</P>
<P>
   While most agreed the film starring John Travolta is a powerful
and accurate ``Hollywoodization'' of the lawsuit brought against
two major corporations for allegedly poisoning town water wells,
they say it offers no closure, or comfort for their continued
suffering. Some said they could not even bear to watch parts of the
film, such as the death of 3-year-old Jarrod Aufiero.
</P>
<P>
   The well-water contamination with toxic chemicals is believed to
have led to the deaths of five children and one adult. All died of
leukemia suspected by the plaintiffs to have been caused by toxins
dumped into the water system by W.R. Grace and Beatrice Foods Inc.
The case was settled for $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Aufiero, Jarrod's father, said he had one mission in
attending the opening at the Wang Theatre: To confront Walter Jay
Skinner, the judge who presided over the case, and Jerome Facher,
the attorney for Beatrice Foods. Skinner was not expected to
attend, but Facher planned to.
</P>
<P>
   Aufiero, whose son died in 1982 from acute lymphocytic leukemia,
blames Skinner for not allowing the plaintiffs to take the stand
and for being ``hostile'' toward them and their laywer, Jan
Schlichtmann, Travolta's character. He blames Facher for cutting
what he believes was a backroom deal with Skinner so the case would
favor the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I see them, I am going to ask them how they
could live with themselves, and ask what their Makers are going to
say about how he handled this,'' said Aufiero, his voice rising
with anger. ``They're not God, and I'm going to let them know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aufiero, like several other Woburn family members
interviewed, said they hope the film encourages other people to act
as they did: Speaking up when they find something wrong and not
backing down to corporations that pollute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people come away from the movie realizing what our
motives were,'' said Anne Anderson, whose son, Jimmy, died of
leukemia at age 12 in 1981. She is played in the film by Kathleen
Quinlan. ``We wanted accountability from these companies; we wanted
the world to know we were harmed by what they did and that it
caused too many of our children to become ill and too many to die.
I hope the movie encourages people to seek the truth in their own
areas of concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the original eight families who joined in the lawsuit
still live in Woburn, most in the same homes. Many said the
emotional ties to a place where their children were born, played
and died is incentive alone to stay. They drink bottled water or
have filters fixed to their faucets. They wryly note that Woburn
now has some of the purest, most highly monitored drinking water in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honestly very happy about the movie coming out, but
sometimes it's hard to know how to feel,'' said Donna Robbins,
whose son Robbie, died, of leukemia in 1976 at age 9. ``It's
exciting that all this is happening, that people know about what we
went through and tried to fight. But it's also upsetting because
our children are gone and that kind of pain doesn't end.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said she had hoped the families would be seen more in
the movie, which focuses on the lawyers in the case. She also
wished the film were more accurate in its portrayal of her. The
writers gave a highly emotional line to the Anderson character
that, in reality, was said by Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out to hurt or destroy the movie or the people in
it,'' said Robbins. ``I'm very glad it's out there. It reminds
people what went on in Woburn and makes sure the kids don't get
forgotten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
