<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BATES JR., 69; EDITOR AT BOSTON HERALD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ George William Bates Jr. of Somerville, an editor at
the Boston Herald and the former managing editor of the Paris
Herald Tribune, died of cancer Tuesday in Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center in Boston. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bates was born in Nashville, where he began his newspaper
career delivering the Tennessean at the age of 12. After graduating
from Vanderbilt University in 1950, he served in the Navy during
the Korean War before returning to the Tennessean as a sports
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He then was a news editor at the Miami Herald before joining the
staff of the New York Herald Tribune in 1964. He then was managing
editor of the Paris Herald Tribune (now the International Herald
Tribune).
</P>
<P>
   After his return to the United States in 1977, he was managing
editor of the short-lived Trib in New York City. He then became a
news and features editor at the Boston Herald, where he worked
until last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Mr. Bates was known for his strong grasp
of international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a really good eye for stories. He understood the
dynamic of the international stuff, which was unusual in those
days,'' said Bob Sales, former executive editor of the Boston
Herald.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real perfectionist and did a tremendous job to make
sure everything was absolutely right and historically correct,''
said Norman Gray, current Herald news editor.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Betsy Buffington Bates, and many nieces and
nephews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
