<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOST-GALAXIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMERS SUSPECT EXISTENCE OF GHOST GALAXIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Astronomers still don't know what the mysterious ``dark
matter'' that constitutes 90 percent or more of the universe is,
but Wednesday they reported discoveries that may go a long way
toward showing where it is.
</P>
<P>
   Entire galaxies may be made up almost entirely of invisible dark
matter, ghostly galaxies that perhaps far outnumber _ and outweigh
_ the billions of galaxies that are brightly visible, astronomers
from the University of Hawaii reported at a meeting of the American
Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   And, said astronomer John Kormendy, there is reason to believe
that there are even greater numbers of galaxies that are completely
invisible galaxies and contain no ``normal'' stars at all.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have long known that normal galaxies contain large
amounts of invisible matter, perhaps made up of anything from
unknown subatomic particles to huge black holes or something in
between. But it turns out that these smaller ``ghost'' galaxies
contain a far higher density of dark matter than the normal ones.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers know that the dark matter, whatever it may be, has
to be there because of the way its gravitational pull affects
visible things nearby. Careful studies of the way stars and
galaxies move has shown that more than 90 percent of the universe's
mass is made up of dark matter.
</P>
<P>
   Kormendy described observations of a ``galaxy that's almost not
there, that looks like being almost nothing. They look
insubstantial, so gossamer that you can hardly see them.'' And
that's why, until the development of ultra-sensitive electronic
detectors for telescopes to replace photographic plates, the
ghostly galaxies had not been found earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By painstakingly studying the motions of the few stars seen in
these faint galaxies, Kormendy and colleagues Karen Rehbock of
Hawaii and Kenneth Freeman of Mt. Stromlo Observatory in Australia
learned that they pack a greater density of dark matter than
ordinary galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   That means that these nearly invisible galaxies ``may look
insubstantial, but they are like cannonballs,'' Kormendy said. They
are about 100 times denser than normal, bright galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the density indicates they are true galaxies that
may have been among the earliest to form in the universe, he said,
not simply fragments of larger galaxies that were torn apart in
collisions with other galaxies. If they were only fragments,
Kormendy said, their density would have to be lower than that of
normal galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   The faintest dwarf galaxies are ``almost pristine remnants of
the earliest time of galaxy formation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And as faint and ghostly as they appear, such galaxies could
constitute a substantial portion of the mass of the universe --
perhaps even most of it. ``There might be a large population of
dark galaxies that contain too few stars to discover,'' he said.
``They may outnumber all the luminous galaxies combined.''
</P>
<P>
   The smaller and fainter the galaxies, the less likely they are
to be discovered. But even the tiniest ones probably contain as
much matter as 10 million suns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Rubin, an astronomer at the Carnegie Institution of
Washington who was one of the first to discover the existence of
dark matter, said the findings illustrate how ``every time we start
studying something in detail we find new puzzles.'' They raise the
question of whether there are ``galaxies that are so faint we can't
see them. I think the answer is probably yes.''
</P>
<P>
   By finding evidence that tiny, invisible galaxies may exist in
great numbers, she said, Kormendy and his colleagues ``have done a
great service.'' The nature of the dark matter remains a mystery,
and studying it is as if ``we're in a dark room doing an all-black
puzzle. We don't know where the pieces are, and when we find them
we don't know how they fit.'' The findings at least add ``new
pieces to the puzzle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
