<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABIES-FIGHT-HNS &LR;      01-06 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABIES-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TAKES TO THE SKIES IN ITS WAR AGAINST RABIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Texas has taken to the skies in its war against
rabies.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth straight year, three bright yellow Twin Otter
airplanes are dropping millions of fish meal baits containing oral
rabines vaccine over tens of thousands of square miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're flying along the border ... and are trying to get in
three rounds a day,'' said Doug McBride, a spokesman for the Texas
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted animals _ coyotes and gray foxes _ will eat the
baits, especially in colder weather when traditional food sources
may be scarce and when fire ants are dormant.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the drives will spread bait over 34,000 square miles
in 48 counties over the next four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall goal is to contain and then eradicate canine
rabies in South Texas,'' said McBride. ``Through November 1998, we
have five cases, so obviously the virus is still there among the
coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Health Department statistics show a marked decrease in
rabies in the area since the campaign began to counter a rapid
increase in the virus in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the outbreak began in South Texas in 1988, we've had 704
cases of canine rabies. The high year was 1995 with 142 cases in
South Texas. Last year we had five,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last human case of rabies in South Texas was in 1994, the
year before the program began,'' he said. ``Since 1990, we estimate
3,000 people in South Texas have taken rabies treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   During that time, two people died of canine rabies.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said regular analysis of coyotes shows that a high
percentage consumed the bait and significant numbers have developed
an immunity to canine rabies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In South Texas, the latest tests showed that 82 percent of the
tested coyotes have eaten at least one bait, and of those,
two-thirds had an immunity to rabies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The aerial drive to contain rabid gray foxes will involve
dropping bait along a horseshoe-shaped course in Central and West
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The foxes, which carry a different strain of rabies, will be
offered oral vaccine in dogfood baits.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said the programs will continue until rabies is
eliminated in the wild canine populations.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials are also looking into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico officials are interested in possibly applying the same
techniques there because when you have a common border, as we do,
what's ours is theirs and what's theirs is ours when it comes to
diseases,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
