<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS DIFFER WITH MOVIE'S PORTRAYAL OF WOBURN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forget the fact that they're portrayed as defenders of
companies who poison little children.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for the defense in the lawsuit that became ``A Civil
Action'' have a different complaint: Hollywood overlooked the fact
that they won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saddens me to the extent that people jump to the conclusion
that merely because somebody is injured some corporation must
pay,'' said Jerome Facher, a partner at Hale &AMP; Dorr in Boston.
``There was no case against Beatrice.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keating, whose character was merged with that of William
Cheeseman, a fellow partner at Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot in Boston, said
the toxic chemicals in the groundwater that made the Woburn
children fatally ill had been there long before W.R. Grace or
Beatrice Foods were on the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind if it was a fair portrayal of what we did,''
Keating said. ``From our point of view, these were not just legal
defenses, these were true.''
</P>
<P>
   Facher and Keating say they are accustomed to hearing vicious
attacks in the courtroom, but outraged at the movie's
characterization of Judge Walter Skinner as biased against Jan
Schlichtman and the Woburn families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The depiction of the judge is grossly unfair,'' said Keating.
``I think he was actually doing everything he could to help Jan
Schlichtman out, particularly in the beginning when he did not seem
to be up to the task in a case with such high stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Lyons, Skinner's clerk for many years, said he
hand-delivered an invitation to Wednesday night's film premiere to
the judge, but that Skinner did not plan to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've distorted him to make the judge look like a monster,''
Lyons said of the jurist who, he insisted, is widely regarded as
fair and even-tempered. ``I've sat with 50 federal judges over the
years and he's top shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Facher said that, in the wake of the book's success, he has been
castigated in anonymous letters and e-mails as ``slimy,'' but that
his sympathy is for Skinner, who has been unable to defend himself
because of ethical rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge was not partisan to anybody and certainly did not
favor me,'' said Facher. ``We were not colleagues or classmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Facher said he considered himself a ``somebody'' after teaching
for 30 years at Harvard Law School and trying some sizable cases.
But when Robert Duvall was cast as Facher, he made no effort to
adopt his looks or mannerisms _ which convinced Facher that the
movie was, after all, a Hollywood product.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm going to play you the way I feel like playing
you,' '' Facher said. `` `Because nobody knows who you are.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
