<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EDWARD-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: PRINCE EDWARD TO MARRY LONGTIME GIRLFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Queen Elizabeth's youngest child, Prince Edward, is
finally to follow his royal siblings' path down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Putting an end to periodic rises and falls of expectation,
Buckingham Palace announced Wednesday that the 34-year-old brother
of Princes Charles and Andrew and Princess Anne, all of whose
marriages ended in divorce, would wed his longtime girlfriend,
Sophie Rhys-Jones, 33, this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision has been taken yet regarding the venue and date
for the wedding,'' the announcement of the engagement said.
``However, Prince Edward and Miss Rhys-Jones hope that it might be
possible to use St. George's Chapel, Windsor, in the late spring or
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The palace said the queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, Edward's
father, were delighted at the news.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor, in suburban Berkshire, is the queen's favorite
residence and would provide a symbolically fitting spot for a
restorative moment in the life of a family recently unaccustomed to
happy events.
</P>
<P>
   It was a devastating fire at the castle in November 1992 that
capped what the queen called her ``annus horribilis,'' the year in
which all three of her children either separated or divorced,
exposing the palace to levels of intrusive publicity it had never
known.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, however, also provided the story for a successful
television documentary made by the prince, who, as Edward Windsor,
film producer, has led a life independent of royal duties as the
head of his own company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a glorious piece of architecture, and it's somewhere
different,'' Edward said Wednesday, talking of Windsor as just the
kind of retreat from pageantry and publicity that might do the
family good. ``I think there is no such thing as a private wedding,
but I hope that it will be predominantly a family wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure in recent times to wed Miss Rhys-Jones, whom he
began dating five years ago, the bachelor prince told friends that
he would make that decision only when his company, Ardent
Productions, was secure. An earlier venture failed, and Ardent lost
$2 million in 1997 but now can point to several well-received films
and a contract with the William Morris Agency that has brought it
financing for future projects as proof that the first Windsor to
have an outside job is making a success of it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impression lent by her hyphenated name, Miss
Rhys-Jones is not an aristocrat but the head of her own public
relations firm who was raised in a Victorian farmhouse in the Kent
village of Brenchley, 35 miles southeast of London, and never went
to a university. Her father is a former car salesman who later
worked for a tire company selling to Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Her age, her middle-class upbringing, her stable family life and
her working experience have been cited by friends as guarantees
that her entrance into the royal family will not be as traumatic as
that of the younger and more impressionable Diana Spencer, the wife
of Prince Charles, and Sarah Ferguson, the wife of Prince Andrew.
Edward is also not her first extended romance; she spent a year in
Australia with a ski instructor she met in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   With the tacit approval of the queen, she and the prince have
been intermittently living together in royal apartments and on
royal travel, and they attend ceremonial and intimate family events
as a couple. The arrangement has afforded her a chance to
accommodate herself to the demands of royal life that the Princess
of Wales and the Duchess of York never had.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday how she felt about joining the royal family,
Miss Rhys-Jones said, ``I am fully aware of the responsibilities,
and I feel I am ready for it.'' She added, ``I have had a few years
to get used to it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of Edward's siblings, Princess Anne at 23 was the first to marry
and to divorce, but also the first to remarry. Wed to Capt. Mark
Phillips in 1973, she divorced in 1992 in order to marry her
current husband, Cmdr. Timothy Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, then 33, married Diana, who was 20, in 1981, and
their divorce was announced in 1996. She died in a car crash in
Paris in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Andrew and Sarah Ferguson, both of whom were 26, were wed
in 1986 and divorced in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Edward pays for his own business travel, often stays with
friends rather than in hotels and tells anyone who asks to call him
Edward Windsor. Consequently, he has been able to avoid the kind of
publicity that has dogged the rest of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the newly betrothed couple strolled hand in hand
during a photo call in the gardens of St. James's Palace, she
showing off her Asprey Garrard diamond engagement ring and he
bantering with reporters pressing him on why he waited so long to
propose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible for anyone else to understand why it has taken
me this long,'' he said, ``but I don't think it would have been
right before and I don't think Sophie would have said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Hopefully by the fact that she did say yes, I must
have got the timing right.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple took notice of one another for the first time in 1993
when she was doing publicity for a charity sports event that Prince
Edward headed. Before then Edward had been linked with a number of
actresses and models, but from that point, the romance with Miss
Rhys-Jones became a constant.
</P>
<P>
   In the family tradition, Edward had entered the military after
graduating from Cambridge, but in a show of independence he quit
the commando course of the Royal Marines in 1987, resigned his
commission and returned to civilian life to pursue a career in the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for three years as a production assistant for Andrew
Lloyd Webber's Really Useful Co., doing backstage jobs at the
musicals ``Cats,'' ``Starlight Express'' and ``Phantom of the
Opera'' in the West End of London. In 1992 he and friends set up a
theater production company, which collapsed a year later, one
million dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
   His Ardent Productions, now five years old, has had its largest
successes with royal subjects, one the story of his great-uncle
Edward VIII called ``Edward on Edward''; another a series called
``Crown and Country,'' which was shown on PBS in the United States
in September and will reappear in a sequel in February; and
``Windsor Restored,'' the documentary on the $61 million project to
resurrect Windsor Castle after the 1992 fire.
</P>
<P>
   The couple will live in Bagshot Park, a sprawling estate in
Surrey that Queen Victoria built for her favorite son, Prince
Arthur, Duke of Connaught, and that Edward took over on a
50-year-lease in 1997 to house his business headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Both will continue their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business as usual,'' Miss Rhys-Jones, chairwoman of RJH public
relations, said Wednesday. And he will try to be just Edward
Windsor, joint managing director of Ardent Productions, formerly
known as prince.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
