<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOMSDAY-FLARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERFLARES' SEEN AS DOOMSDAY PRECURSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Stars just like the sun occasionally send out
``superflares'' with enough explosive energy to destroy the entire
ozone layer, disable all satellites, knock out all electric power
grids, and create spectacular auroras worldwide, astronomers
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, they hasten to add, they are quite sure that our own sun
has never produced an outburst with that much energy and never
will. That's good news, they say, because the loss of the ozone
layer would allow deadly ultraviolet light to penetrate the Earth's
atmosphere, wiping out the food chain for years and leading to mass
starvation.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative theory holds that a large planet with a strong
magnetic field, similar to Jupiter, would have to be orbiting very
close to the sun to produce such giant flares.
</P>
<P>
   And, added Yale University astronomer Bradley Schaefer, if our
sun were capable of emitting superflares, descriptions of the
events would surely be found in Earth's historical records, and
their effects would be detectable on the moons of other planets. No
such evidence has been found, he said, so ``our sun does not have
superflares, as far as we can tell. . . This isn't going to happen,
so don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer presented the evidence of superflares from nine other
sun-like stars at a meeting of the American Astronomical Society.
The findings emerged from a study of more than a century's worth of
astronomical observations.
</P>
<P>
   One such event was reported just a century ago, in 1899, by
astronomers in three countries. They simultaneously noticed that a
star called S Fornacis suddenly became more than 10 times brighter
than normal, and later that night returned to its normal
brightness. Schaefer said most of the superflares he has found
evidence for appeared to last only about an hour, although some
lasted a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rubenstein, another Yale astronomer, theorizes that the
superflares are caused by the interaction of a star's magnetic
field with the magnetic field of a giant planet orbiting very close
to it. Recent searches for planets orbiting other stars have found
numerous examples of large, close-in planets, and Rubenstein said
that the stars that have produced superflares should become prime
candidates for searching for such planets.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery was an outgrowth of Schaefer's search for stars
associated with enigmatic events that astronomers call gamma-ray
bursts. As part of his research, he made a systematic search of
astronomical records, looking for episodes of brief, unexplained
changes in a star's brightness. Many kinds of stars are known to
vary regularly in brightness, but Schaefer was looking for changes
in a type of stars where variability was not expected. He
concentrated on F- and G-type stars, similar to the sun, which is a
G-type.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer's search turned up superflares from 100 to 10 million
times more powerful than the strongest flares ever observed from
our sun. Some flares from our sun produce vivid auroral (Northern
Lights) displays, interfere with delicate electronic systems on
orbiting satellites, and occasionally cause power surges in
electric powerlines that cause blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   From the small number of cases he found, Schaefer estimated that
sunlike stars produce superflares about once a century, but he
added that the uncertainties are such that the timing could be
anywhere from once a decade to once a millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Had our own sun produced a superflare in the last century or
two, it undoubtedly would have been seen and its effects would have
been apparent. Auroras produced by a superflare anytime in the last
few millenniums would most likely have been recorded, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer also calculated that such an outburst would have melted
much of the ice on moons as far out as Saturn's, causing vast, flat
floodplains that would have refrozen and would be clearly
detectable even now if the flare had occurred anytime in the last
billion years or so. So, he concluded, the sun is apparently not
one of the stars able to produce superflares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
