<SLUG> BC-ART-EXHIBITS-PLACES-1STLD-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, FIXING THE SPELLING OF WORD TO LA SAMARITAINE
THROUGHOUT STORY)  
 THE WANDERING MUSEUM: OUTREACH TAKES ON NEW MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)  
 (Eds: Please use this version)  
(dal) 
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Art gets around. Museums are pretty well stuck in one spot, but
their treasures keep on truckin'. At a time when museums build
buildings that tend to be more significant than the collections
they shelter, some centers have gone the less expensive route of
converting existing industrial centers into galleries. A few others
are experimenting with putting art, at least temporarily, into
essentially unconverted places that respectable museums would once
have thought dreadfully infra dig: marginal retail areas,
department stores, dance halls.
</P>
<P>
   If a museum can install art in abandoned banks and garages, if
the New Museum in SoHo can call itself a museum though it has no
permanent collection, if the Contemporary Museum in Baltimore can
operate with neither collection nor home, has the museum been
redefined as merely a state of mind?
</P>
<P>
   A museum is still a museum if it's closed for a year or two, but
its exhibition potential drops alarmingly. At the Pompidou Center
in Paris, the permanent collection has been closed since September
1997 while the galleries are being restored, though the
contemporary galleries remain open for temporary exhibitions until
mid-1999. (The entire museum will then close until the year 2000.)
But France's modern treasures have not been stashed in mothballs.
Bernard Blistene, vice director for contemporary art of the
Pompidou, says with a tinge of horror in his voice that putting
such a great collection into storage for two years would amount to
confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Pompidou, a national museum and well aware that not
everyone can travel to the capital, considers decentralization part
of its mission. Already the biggest lender in the world, according
to Blistene _ approximately 6,000 items every year _ the Pompidou
is sending out more than 100 loan exhibitions while its doors are
shut. Among them are major shows of Kandinsky and Giacometti for
regional museums in France, 120 ``masterpieces of the collection''
for Tokyo, and the exhibitions of 20th-century art currently at
both branches of the Guggenheim in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Blistene is also organizing an enormous exhibition in a Paris
department store for March. This will occupy an entire floor _ more
than 16,000 square feet _ of La Samaritaine, a store where you can
buy a lipstick, a bike and a hamster in one outing. La Samaritaine
has never before regarded itself as a branch of the national
museums of France.
</P>
<P>
   This store, an early example of an emporium where people
discovered they could buy floor mops and frou-frou in one place,
will house a festival of art by young contemporary artists, many of
whom are marrying conventional arts to unconventional media. The
exhibition will include fashion, performance, music, dance,
lectures and happenings, all free. Blistene says he would ``like to
reconsider the generosity and diversity of art of this century, the
intensity and efficiency of contemporary art, not art as just a
dead object.''
</P>
<P>
   Why a department store? Michael Kimmelman pointed out in The New
York Times that in America, from the late 19th century to the
1950s, certain department stores maintained the populist ideal by
giving lowly shoppers a taste of high art. Some of these
exhibitions in the land of commerce were mounted with the aid of
museums. In the 1930s, the Museum of Modern Art's ``Machine Art''
show traveled to department stores in the Midwest. The French have
only occasionally shown art in a department store; depending more
heavily on Louis XVI than Thomas Paine, they have been more
inclined to use national fairs than commercial outlets to educate
the public taste in art.
</P>
<P>
   Blistene, however, is delighted with the opportunity to put art
where once only shoppers dared to tread. He notes that people go
where things are happening _ the Armory, for instance, the Piers
and the Gramercy Park Hotel in New York when they open up to art.
And he was looking for an empty place and a site for stimulation
and activity, ``a way to react against the temptation of being
melancholy,'' as he puts it.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that nostalgia is currently being used as a barrier
against contemporary reality but insists that art must remain
involved as well as critical. ``People think it was better
yesterday,'' he says. ``I think it's always better tomorrow.'' One
might think shopping was the way to cure melancholy in today's
society; perhaps La Samaritaine will provide an avant-garde
alternative to the capitalist anodyne it ordinarily prescribes.
</P>
<P>
   It seems only fitting that at a moment when museums are creating
virtual department stores within their precincts, the jazziest art
of the day should take up residence in the realm of the ladies who
lunch. And it is delicious to think that someday at Bloomingdale's
or Saks the mechanical voice that now and then pretends to be an
elevator operator might call out, ``Lingerie and intimates on four;
fifth floor, Pollock, Rothko and de Kooning.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who will not go to the mount of Parnassus, Parnassus
will obligingly come to them. Art long ago joined the rounds of
daily life via public sculpture in parks and airline terminals and
on occasional billboards and advertising pages. Museums, too, want
to creep into quotidian consciousness, to play a role in the
texture of ordinary, 9-to-5 life.
</P>
<P>
   They also need more space for display and are conscious that
they need to address different audiences. The Los Angeles
Contemporary Museum opened not one but two temporary spaces and,
like the man who came to dinner, they stayed on. In the late 1970s,
the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts had a wandering exhibition on an
``art truck'' until insurance and conservation permanently put on
the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half years ago, the WPA/Corcoran, part of the Corcoran
Gallery of Art in Washington but independent of it, began putting
on shows of emerging regional artists, many of them recent
graduates of art schools in the Baltimore, Washington and Richmond
area. The shows now appear in Project Space, temporary quarters in
a former nightclub called the Insect Club in a slightly rundown
business district. Metal grasshoppers as large as hallucinations
still stand guard by the door while the bar looms darkly along one
wall.
</P>
<P>
   This decor is appropriately rakish for the kind of installation
art that sends aluminum-foil leaves wafting across the gallery to
the sound of grinding gears, or displays suits that look like
torture instruments, with artists strapped into them on weekends.
MCI, the communications company, opened a sports arena nearby late
in 1977, and Nadine Gabai-Botero, the program director for the
WPA/Corcoran, says the area's economic good fortune will probably
drive out unprofitable contemporary art. Then art will be on to the
next marginal area, perhaps to spaces that are available only for a
month or two, prime for a lightning strike by the art corps.
</P>
<P>
   This is a guerrilla art tactic, to invade a location where art
never lived and billet the art troops there for a while, a maneuver
not usually employed by established museums. In the late 1960s and
70s, when artists were vigorously questioning and frequently
repudiating the role of museums, alternative spaces sprang up to
shelter art that did not want entry to museums, or could not gain
it. After a while a few museums saw the usefulness of such places
and began to set up their own alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Contemporary Museum has made guerrilla artfare a
modus vivendi. A museum without a museum, the Contemporary is a
full-time nomad, a homeless institution that not only has no
collection but has no location either.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1989 and headed since 1996 by Gary Sangster, the
Contemporary puts on two shows a year, one in, and in conjunction
with, a local institution and the other in some highly improbable
place, like a former Polish convent, a former Buick car dealership,
an abandoned bus garage without electricity and the former Famous
Ballroom, without either fame or heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish Dreamin','' a project by Alison Saar, was installed on
a 1959 Chevy pickup and driven into 80 neighborhoods in four states
over a period of five months, giving the term ``traveling show'' a
down-home dimension. ``Too Jewish?,'' a show organized by and first
shown at the Jewish Museum in New York, was exhibited in Baltimore
in a vacant shopping mall, a notable instance of art taking up
where commerce leaves off.
</P>
<P>
   This doggedly temporary Contemporary Museum first made a
national name for itself in 1992 when it worked with the Maryland
Historical Society to install Fred Wilson's ``Mining the Museum,''
an ironic look at the neglect of black people and American Indians
in historical displays. A show last spring, ``Mysterious
Voyages/New Photography,'' a bold exploration of the current search
for meaning in photography and art by artists like Sophie Calle,
Adam Fuss, Andreas Gursky and Thomas Struth, was in the vacant
ground floor of a downtown office building three blocks from
Baltimore's red-light district and two from a police station.
Visitor records revealed an audience drawn from both the
surrounding area and the art world; the attempt to reach a local
community must be working.
</P>
<P>
   Sangster says: ``We operate in the discourse of ideas about the
visual. We're not here just to expose artists or artworks but ideas
that influence the community through visual means.'' The
Contemporary asked visitors, including some local critics, to write
their own labels for ``Mysterious Voyages''; eventually three were
put up for each piece.
</P>
<P>
   Sangster would now like a more permanent space _ ideally an
aircraft hangar in the middle of Baltimore, if only he could find
one _ to give the museum a stronger identity. In the meantime he is
eyeing the Web, having already done one show on it, as the most
likely means to preserve the explorations of a museum that cannot
afford to publish. The Web, in fact, may be  &UR; the &LR;  outreach museum
of the future, bringing art straight to your desk at any hour.
Numerous museums and galleries beam it into your home right now,
unfortunately at a resolution not much more convincing than the one
you made on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   So what is a museum, and where? It may be whatever a director or
curator says it is, a rather new twist on Marcel Duchamp. Back in
the 1920s, Hannes Meyer, an instructor at the Bauhaus, thought that
museums should all be rededicated as soccer fields. The history of
art takes many curious turns; we may yet live to see soccer fields
rededicated as museums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
