r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     01-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREW JOHNSON AND BILL CLINTON: PARALLELS IN THEIR CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the possible exception of Richard Nixon, no
former president has been mentioned in the news as often during the
past year as Andrew Johnson, who succeeded to the nation's highest
office with the assassination of Abraham Lincoln and who, before
Bill Clinton, was the only chief executive ever impeached by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few Americans know much about Johnson. Until 1998, he was an
obscure figure in history. Now, because of Clinton's impeachment
and trial, analysts are finding a number of parallels between his
life and Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Like the current president, Johnson was a product of the South.
Also like Clinton, he was reared by a mother who remarried after
the death of her first husband. Both boys knew poverty when they
were small.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson certainly is not listed among the great or near great
presidents. In fact, in most lists he ranks near the bottom, where
Clinton will probably be.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson had an unusual achievement: He is the only president
to serve in the Senate after the end of his White House tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Having been a member of the Senate from 1857 to 1862 and
president from 1865 to 1869, Johnson was returned to the Senate by
the Tennessee legislature in 1875. He died in office two months
later.
</P>
<P>
   When the South seceded from the Union in 1861, Johnson was the
only lawmaker from a Confederate state who remained in the Senate.
A Democrat, he had supported the presidential bid of Democrat John
C. Breckinridge of Kentucky in 1860 against Republican Abraham
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But once it became clear that Lincoln had won, Johnson,
according to historians, electrified the Senate when he declared:
``Though I fought against Lincoln, I love my country. I love the
Constitution and swear that it and the Union shall be saved, as
`Old Hickory' Jackson did in 1832. Senators, my blood _ my
existence _ I would give to save this Union.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, there was an ironic parallel between Johnson's
career and that of Andrew Jackson, the idol he referred to.
Jackson, in vetoing the charter of the second Bank of the United
States in 1832, incurred the animosity of business and banking
leaders in the eastern half of the nation. For that action, he was
censured by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jackson censure was later expunged from the record.
Johnson, after being impeached by the House, was saved by a single
vote from a guilty verdict in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators who oppose censure for Clinton, preferring that the
Senate find him guilty of impeachable offenses, point to the
Jackson experience to substantiate their contention that censure
would merely be a slap on the wrist that could be eradicated from
the record when Democrats reclaim control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was not an evil man, although he reportedly had a
fondness for liquor and was somewhat intoxicated when he was sworn
in as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   His is a classic American story of a poor, uneducated boy who
taught himself to read and write and diligently worked his way up
to the highest office in the land.
</P>
<P>
   As teen-agers, Johnson and his brother William became indentured
servants, bound by law to work as apprentice tailors for a man in
Raleigh, N.C., who would provide them with food and clothing and
teach them the tailoring trade.
</P>
<P>
   After two years, they broke their bond and escaped to Carthage,
N.C., where Andrew Johnson made money as a tailor. Later, they
moved to Greenevillle, Tenn., where Andrew married 16-year-old
Eliza McCardle, who bore him five children and helped him learn
reading, spelling and math.
</P>
<P>
   While still in his 20s, Johnson was elected mayor of
Greeneville. From that office, he began a steady political
progression that saw him serve in both houses of the state
legislature and become a U.S. senator, vice president and then
president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson was a Democrat and Lincoln was a Republican,
Lincoln chose him for vice president in 1864 to strengthen his bid
for a second term. Two years earlier, Lincoln had appointed Johnson
as military governor of Tennessee, which had been reclaimed by
union forces.
</P>
<P>
   A month and eight days after Lincoln's second inaugural, the
president was shot and Johnson succeeded to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's No. 1 priority was to protect the Union. It was not to
extend constitutional rights to freed black slaves or to deal
harshly with the defeated Confederacy. He wanted to follow
Lincoln's policy of restoring full legal status to white residents
of Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was considered a traitor in the South, he became
embroiled in a bitter power struggle with Congress, which was
dominated by radical Republicans who were determined to punish the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Congress was just as determined as Johnson to dominate
Reconstruction policy.
</P>
<P>
   Over Johnson's veto, it passed in 1868 the ``Tenure of Office
Act'' that denied that president the right to remove certain
government officials, including Cabinet officers, without Senate
approval. Johnson immediately violated the law by firing Secretary
of War Edwin Stanton, a powerful leader of the Radical Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House swiftly voted 11 articles of impeachment and the
Senate trial began. But after all the charges and counter charges
had filled the atmosphere with venom, seven moderate Republicans
joined Democrats to save Johnson from conviction and ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson served out the remaining eight months of his term and
returned to Tennessee, where in 1875 he once more became a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the current Clinton case, the fight against Johnson did
not involve perjury and obstruction of justice. It was purely a
political battle over power. But then as now, political
polarization poisoned the process. That is yet another parallel
between the 17th and 42nd presidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
