<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SURGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES SURGES TOWARD THE MYTHICAL 10,000 MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American investors disregarded impeachment worries
and profit concerns Wednesday to send the US stock market to new
highs, with the Dow Jones industrial average edging ever closer to
the mythical 10,000-mark.
</P>
<P>
   Investors poured year-end bonuses and the gains of previous
deals into the market creating an upward cycle of money chasing
money that lifted the Dow 233.78 points, or 2.5 percent, to a
record 9544.97, its first time ever above the 9500 level. Other,
broader market measures were also up.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the sharp rise in share prices reflected renewed
confidence in the market's and the economy's ability to grow, a
marked turn-about from the fears of last fall when it appeared that
the financial system might be headed for a crack-up.
</P>
<P>
   But in the very swiftness of its rise, the market left many
investment professionals uneasy Wednesday, fearful of being left
behind, but also unable to justify the prices being paid for many
of the hottest stocks, especially Internet shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a capitulation to exuberance,'' said Richard B. Hoey,
chief economist and equity research director at $120
billion-Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are throwing money at the market. It's kind of scary,''
said Thomas M. O'Neill, chief investment officer with the $60
billion Fleet Financial Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there was some good economic news during the day.
The government said that new home sales reached record levels in
November, and General Motors, Toyota and Honda posted
stronger-than-expected auto sales for December. Both are signs that
the American consumer, who some economists had worried was tapped
out, is continuing to buy at a furious pace, a trend that's likely
to keep the economy growing for some time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, analysts said there are few signs of economic
trouble that could act as a damper on investors, and what few there
are can be easily handled by policymakers at the Federal Reserve.
``What you've got is an economy that will not roll over and play
dead,'' John F. MacNeil, an equities strategist with Salomon Smith
Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts conceded that the presence of good economic news
and the abense of bad is hardly enough to explain stocks' latest
rise. Neither is Corporate America's profit picture.
</P>
<P>
   Although the profits of companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
stock index grew during the September-through-December quarter, an
improvement over their June-through-August performance when they
shrank, Charles L. Hill, research director of First Call Corp. in
Boston, said that the growth was almost certainly less than four
percent. That's anemic compared to the 20 percent-plus quarterly
growth during much of the decade, and there is little reason to
expect much improvement this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be lucky to make in the 4 percent range,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Without economics or profit growth to point to, most analysts
fell back on some varient of the money-chasing-money explanation
for Wednesday's market climb, and several expressed reservations
about the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about earnings; it's not about dodging a slowdown
in the global economy,'' Robert Froehlich, chief investment
strategist for Scudder Kemper Investments told Bloomberg News.
``You put more money into this market and the market's going to go
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans traditionally pump money into investments in January
as they receive year-end bonuses and make decisions about their
retirement plans. A new report suggested that as in te recent past
a substantial fraction is going into stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For a third week running, investors shoveled money into US stock
funds, according to Trimtabs.com, a California research firm that
tracks fund flows. About $3.13 billion in new money went into stock
funds in the week ended Monday, or about the same as the $3.16
billion the previous week, Trimtabs said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, much of the new money in the market has gone to
shares of a few large companies, a trend that worries some who say
that it shows that many investors are looking for safe havens. Much
of the rest has gone into wildly speculative Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said there was some evidence Wednesday that cautious
investors are beginning to venture beyond big company shares as
virtually all market indexes rose.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Dow, the S&AMP;P 500 Index gained 27.56 points,
or 2.2 percent, to close at a record 1272.34. The Nasdaq Composite
Index rose 69.59 points, or 3.1 percent, to close at a record
2320.86. Even the Russell 2000 Index of smaller stocks, which
trailed the broader market last year, climbed 5.70 points, or 1.4
percent, to close at 427.79.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the investment spectrum, there were few
signs of speculative investors cooling to Internet shares, an
enthusiasm that has many investment professionals worried. Shares
of Amazon.com, the on-line bookseller jumped 13 1/2 to 138 while
those of CMGI Inc., a firm that invests in Internet companies in
hopes of taking them public, lept more than $30 to 151.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greater-fool theory of investing,'' said Scott Black,
president of Delphi Management in Boston. ``Total speculation, a
``casino mentality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest mania I've ever seen in my career,'' added
Fleet's O'Neill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
