<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-BONUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EISNER'S BONUS CUT TO $5 MILLION AS DISNEY PROFITS WEAKEN 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Eisner, chairman of Walt Disney Co., is about to have
his bonus cut in half, to $5 million from $9.9 million, because of
the company's weak performance in the 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would revamp the formula that determines the
bonus but did not elaborate on a new formula, saying only that it
planned to submit a revised plan for shareholder approval and that
nothing would be carried out until the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's $750,000-a-year salary and his bonus have never been
the chief source of his wealth. His stock options, however, made
him hundreds of millions of dollars, and he always said he had
preferred to benefit if the company had done well. Disney's
performance in 1998 was weak compared with previous years, with net
profit rising just 4 percent, to $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner joined the company in 1984, and Disney's stock soared
until recently. Faced with problems at its ABC television network,
among other issues, however, Disney's stock closed Wednesday at
$30.9375, down from its high of nearly $42.80 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Although some critics have said the size of Eisner's option
grant was incredibly rich, the company made no mention Wednesday of
changes in his stock-option plan. In the 1997 calendar year, Eisner
exercised options on 21.9 million shares for a profit of $550
million. He still holds options on 24 million shares. The so-called
strike price of the options _ the price he will pay when he is able
to claim them _ is $21.18 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner has a incentive to improve performance. He cannot start
to exercise those options before September 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has asked that the bonus formula be renegotiated because
it is based primarily on earnings per share. It appears that Eisner
benefited significantly because of the increase in earnings per
share after the company bought Capital Cities/ABC Inc. in 1996. He
now has the potential to benefit from last year's purchase of a 43
percent stake in Infoseek &UR;  &LR; because it could also improve earnings
per share. The company said it planned to revamp the bonus, taking
into account that it could be inflated by an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, however, will not have to give back any of his 1997
bonus, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to shareholders in the company's annual report,
Eisner also said the company's performance in its fiscal year ended
Sept. 30 was affected by key strategic investments and new
initiatives that would raise profits ``down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1935EST &QL; 
