<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-THRIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY FILES TO LAUNCH THRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual fund
firm, hopes to launch a federally chartered thrift, according to
documents filed Wednesday with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's parent, FMR Corp., filed papers with the Office of
Thrift Supervision in Washington to open a Boston-based bank called
Fidelity Personal Trust Co. The institution would not be a
full-purpose traditional bank making loans and the like; instead,
it would serve to allow Boston-based Fidelity to grow its trust
business, which caters to wealthy investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always look for ways to enhance the service we provide our
trust customers, and this is a first step in that process,''
Fidelity spokesman Jim Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is the latest financial services outfit to seek to
launch a thrift. From insurers to former bank executives looking to
go it alone, financial players have deluged regulators in recent
years with applications to open thrifts, which are subject to
different regulations than savings banks. Insurance companies are
especially keen on the move: the nation's largest insurer,
Travelers Corp., which is merging with Citibank to form Citigroup,
applied to set up a thrift last year.
</P>
<P>
   Among asset management firms, however, thrift charters are
relatively rare.
</P>
<P>
   Thrifts are no longer synonomous with the costly, failed savings
and loans of the 1980s. As the regulatory walls separating banks,
asset management firms, insurers, and brokerages come tumbling
down, financial companies are looking for new ways to offer a
broader array of services. Under a thrift charter, a company can
more easily offer trust and other services in different states.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which manages around $715.9 billion in assets and has
14.4 million customers, hopes to boost fund sales and other
revenues by capturing a greater portion of the new wealth generated
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Fidelity's empire building, setting up a
thrift is probably more the result of them looking for a new
business opportunity,'' said Jim Lowell, editor of the independent
Fidelity Investor newslettter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's application may draw fire from critics of the
mutual fund behemoth. Fidelity said its thrift, like other small
banks, would not have to make the community investments required of
more traditional banks under Federal law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
