<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POISONED-DOGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS STUMPED IN DOG POISONINGS; REWARD UPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Law enforcement officials remained stumped Wednesday by
the post-Christmas poisonings of six dogs in Milton, a Boston
suburb, prompting an animal humane society to increase the reward
in the case to $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are kind of getting frustrated that no one has come forward
yet with any solid leads,'' said Robert Fennessey, deputy director
of law enforcement for the Massachusetts Society for the Prevention
of Cruelty to Animals. ``People have just called and given their
opinions who might have done this.''
</P>
<P>
   The $6,000 reward, which was increased Wednesday from $4,000
with contributions from other humane societies and an MSPCA
emergency fund, is the largest in the society's 130-year history,
Fennessey said.
</P>
<P>
   Five dogs died and another was seriously injured Dec. 26 after
eating meatballs believed to have been laced with
strychnine-treated seeds left in the yards of their homes in the
Pope's Pond neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   State pesticide regulators said the sale and use of products
containing strychnine have been outlawed in Massachusetts for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Oats and grains treated with the highly toxic chemical had been
commonly used to rid orchards and farms of crop-raiding rodents,
said Steven Antunes-Kenyon, toxicologist at the Massachusetts
Pesticide Bureau. But the products were eventually banned because
they also attracted and killed birds.
</P>
<P>
   Antunes-Kenyon said unused products were supposed to be returned
to retailers once the prohibition went into effect, but it was
impossible to know if everyone complied. According to Fennessey,
the products have a 100-year shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dog owners said Wednesday they would hold a rally at
a neighborhood park Jan. 17 to express community outrage over the
poisonings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will let their dogs out anymore,'' said Gerald
Kawadler, whose dog, Lucy, was the only one to survive the
poisonings but whose daughter's two dogs were killed. ``Everyone is
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   (Anyone with information in the case should contact the MSPCA at
1-800-628-5808 or Milton police at 617-698-COPS. Donations toward
the reward fund or to help defray the cost of the investigation may
be sent to the MSPCA, 350 South Huntington Ave., Boston, MA 02130.)
</P>
</TEXT>
