<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON WORKERS UNHAPPY WITH UNION LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Almost three years after angry Raytheon Co. workers
voted in new union officials, dissatisfaction within Local 1505 of
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers has led to a
backlash against those leaders and a labor board complaint alleging
misrepresentation.
</P>
<P>
   Already, five months before the union's scheduled election in
June, one former Raytheon employee has openly declared plans to run
for president, a seat vacated recently when Arthur Osborn Jr.
stepped down to take a management job at the company. In addition,
at least one employee has indicated plans to challenge incumbent
business manager Michael Zagami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing, `The company says, the company says.'
The company has always said, but the union used to say, `No,' ''
said 36-year-old Janet Griffin, a laid-off worker who kept her dues
current so she would be eligible to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Added George Noel, a 41-year-old radar tester who intends to run
for business manager: ``The company doesn't take us seriously, and
the grievance procedure is a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel feels Zagami has grown too close to the company's
management. He also said Osborn's decision to take a managerial
position with the Lexington defense contractor was particularly
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's announcement in October that about 1,200 workers
would be laid off and the Waltham plant would be shut has
contributed to the members' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 19 Raytheon employees, transferred from the company's
printed wire fabrication unit to the advanced device center after
the unit's work was shipped to Texas, have filed a
misrepresentation claim with the National Labor Relations Board in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Filed in November, the complaint alleges the union violated a
provision in its 1995 to 1998 contract guaranteeing seniority
rights to workers targeted for reassignment, reclassification, or
layoff because of changes at the $20 billion industrial giant.
</P>
<P>
   The workers contend that people with less seniority were given
positions they should have received, violating their seniority
rights. They also blame Zagami for a letter of intent that amended
the contract language to allow for the change.
</P>
<P>
   Zagami was traveling and at meetings this week and did not
respond to several attempts to reach him at the union office in
Bedford. Raytheon spokeswoman Toni Simonetti also declined to
discuss the complaint. ``We have not been in receipt of this
complaint and feel we cannot comment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees maintain the changes occurred after Raytheon's $9.5
billion purchase of Hughes Aircraft, a division of General Motors
Corp.'s Hughes Electronics Corp. After the purchase, Raytheon
developed what it calls ``centers of excellence,'' including a
center for printed wire fabrication that consolidated the work in
Texas. As a result, workers in Massachusetts who had held a ``B''
or a ``C'' classification in that unit found they were about to
lose their jobs. Under the contract, however, they should have been
permitted to ``bump'' or displace less senior workers, they claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation where a lot of these people had bumping
rights, but they were prevented from exercising them because the
union agreed to a letter of intent or an amendment to the
contract,'' said Noel, a former steward. As a result, some of the
``B'' classified workers wound up in a lower classification, with
less pay.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin gave up her union steward job last year prior to being
laid off, to protest what she described this week as an unfair
change in seniority. She said the action contributed to tensions
within the local, which has been ravaged by a series of layoffs in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin also has a grudge: She was suspended from the union last
year for wearing a T-shirt that said, ``No Zagami, Yes to
Seniority,'' when John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, visited
workers at the Andover plant.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, however, workers ousted business manager Joseph
Kelleher, who had battled hard to keep defense jobs from leaving
the state, because of anger over concessions. Now, their anger is
directed at Zagami and Osborn.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Guthrie, a Raytheon electrician who plans to support Noel
in his bid for business manager, is upset about Osborn's recent
switch to management. He believes it raises questions about the
loyalty of Local 1505's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an apparent betrayal,'' he said. ``We have got to demand
more from our leaders. I think they should take a pledge'' against
making such moves to management in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do their loyalties lie?'' asked Guthrie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
