<SLUG> BC-CONGO-MASSACRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGO REBELS SAY 400 HUTU DIED IN BATTLE, NOT MASSACRE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda _ Congolese rebel leaders admitted late Wednesday
night that some of their soldiers had killed about 400 Hutu
militiamen last week, but denied that they had massacred 500
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday a Roman Catholic news agency reported that rebel
soldiers had shot and hacked to death hundreds of people, many of
them women, children and elderly people, in eastern Congo over
three days ending Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, confusion over the incident only widened, though
it does appear that something happened near Uvira, on the western
shore of Lake Tanganyika not far from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   The Missionary Service News Agency, which originally reported
the killings, said the violence began when rebels were kidnapped
along Lake Tanganyika and forced to help unload weapons that came
ashore for fighters loyal to President Laurent Kabila. Several of
the rebels were killed, the agency said in a report based on a
survivor's account.
</P>
<P>
   The news agency said a larger rebel group then attacked
Makobola, near the lake in the Kivu region, because residents there
were believed to have helped the pro-Kabila fighters who had
kidnapped their comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day a leader of the rebels, Ernest Wanba dia
Wanba, said he would investigate the news service's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is true, then those responsible will be punished,''
Wanba, president of the rebel group, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy, told reporters Wednesday in Goa, in eastern Congo. ``But
we cannot say if it's true or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Wednesday night the rebels released a statement denying an
attack on civilians. Rather, the statement said, the killings were
the result of a military engagement with forces they accused of
attacking from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no civilian victims in the course of the
fighting,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' explanation contradicted accounts by some leaders
Tuesday that the area has been quiet recently.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation, if true, would also represent a continuation of
the deadly and seemingly endless clashes between members of the
Tutsi ethnic group, which is the driving force behind the Congo
rebellion, and the Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   Neither account, from the missionaries or the rebels, has been
verified by any outside authority.
</P>
<P>
   But Emmanuel Nzahiro, a spokesman for the Rwandan Defense
Ministry, strongly denied that any Rwandan soldiers could have been
involved in any massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no military personnel in that area,'' he said. ``We
can only wait to hear from the others what they find out from the
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, backed by Rwanda and Uganda, are an increasingly
divided group of Congolese soldiers, former officials in the Kabila
government and former loyalists to Mobutu Sese Seko, the longtime
dictator of Congo when it was called Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila is supported by Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad. And
just as the rebels are supported by ethnic Tutsi, Kabila is largely
supported by Hutu. He has also gained backing among factions of the
Mayi-Mayi warriors, a loose band with no particular ethnic
allegiance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
