<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-JORDAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE MAY BE A SEASON, BUT WILL MICHAEL BE PART OF IT?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the big question of whether there will be a National
Basketball Association season has been settled, one more big
question remains:
</P>
<P>
   Will there be an NBA season with Michael Jordan, perhaps the
best player ever and certainly the highest paid?
</P>
<P>
   Even before the 191-day lockout of the players by the owners
ended Wednesday, there were questions whether Jordan, who will turn
36 on February 17, would return for his 14th pro season or, as he
has often hinted, retire. Jordan is a free agent, and David Falk,
the all-powerful agent for Jordan and other NBA stars, said Jordan
had not decided yet whether he would play for the Bulls or anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Falk did not say where Jordan was, and no one else seemed sure.
While outlining a course of action for Jordan, Falk gave no clue on
what Jordan would decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is out of the country right now,'' Falk said. ``When he has
an opportunity to review the deal, see what direction the Bulls are
taking and look into his own heart, he'll make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speculate on the timetable. I think Michael is the
only human being who knows. Any speculation that a short season
dictates he'll play or retire would be like reading tea leaves. I
think Michael would still like to play, but I think a number of
things have to coalesce in order for him to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no gut feeling on it. He has to make whatever decision
makes him happy, and I'll support whatever decision he makes. He
needs to see what the rules of the new agreement are so he can see
what the big picture looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan wants to play, the money will certainly be there. Last
year, the Bulls paid him $33 million, the highest one-year salary
for any athlete in any sport, and he earned an additional $40
million or more from commercial endorsements, notably McDonald's,
Nike, MCI WorldCom and Gatorade.
</P>
<P>
   The collective bargaining agreement reached Wednesday allows a
team to pay any player 105 percent of his previous season's salary.
That would allow the Bulls to pay Jordan $34.7 million for a full
season or, if this season is trimmed to 50 or so games, a pro-rated
salary of $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   Th 6-foot-6-inch Jordan is probably America's best-known
athlete. He has led the Bulls to six NBA championships in the
1990s, three in the last three seasons. He has won 10 scoring
titles plus five most-valuable-player awards during the regular
season and six in the playoff finals.
</P>
<P>
   Some friends, including Charles Barkley of the Houston Rockets,
say Jordan has indicated he will retire. He retired once, sitting
out the 1993-94 season for an uneventful minor league baseball
career. And in June, after the Bulls had won their most recent
title, he said, ``I wouldn't miss it at all, as much as you may
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is known to be upset that Phil Jackson, who coached the
Bulls to those championships, is no longer there, and he fears that
the Bulls will not make strong efforts to keep Scottie Pippen and
Dennis Rodman, both free agents. In all, the Bulls have nine
unsigned free agents and only four signed veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league could survive without him,'' said Bill Wennington,
the Bulls' center and also a free agent, ``but it would really be a
setback. ``People love to watch him play. I love to watch him
play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
