<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ARMY CHIEF OF STAFF ANNOUNCES CHALLENGE TO NETANYAHU 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, the telegenic former army chief
of staff, formally announced his centrist candidacy for prime
minister on Wednesday, casting his first dart, a particularly
pointed one, at the incumbent, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu is dangerous for Israel,'' he said, the harsh words
emanating from a casual, genial man dressed in an open-neck shirt
and sports jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Shahak's announcement was a sore disappointment to Labor Party
leaders. They failed to persuade him to join forces with them
despite the intervention of President Ezer Weizman and Leah Rabin,
the widow of Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister who was assassinated
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But based on polls, Shahak, 54, believes his chances of beating
Netanyahu are stronger than those of the Labor Party leader, Ehud
Barak. And Shahak's colleagues said defeating Netanyahu is
sincerely and urgently important to him.
</P>
<P>
   With no party, no platform and no experience, Shahak is a wild
card in what now cannot be the traditional Israeli race between
conservative Likud and liberal Labor candidates. He is very popular
here at least partly because he has never before been sullied by
politics, and partly because he radiates the decent integrity of a
favorite type: the citizen-soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Tel Aviv at a news conference broadcast live on both
Israeli television channels, Shahak introduced his political self
in military terms _ as a civilian ``recruited'' to the ``mission''
of defending Israel, this time from internal battles, divisions
that he said Netanyahu exploited for political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here today because I am worried,'' he said. ``How did it
happen that in this wonderful country of ours, in which we were
able to do so many good and proper things, that we became torn by
internal differences, hatred and violence? How is it that hope
drifted away?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two and a half years, since Benjamin Netanyahu was
elected prime minister, those differences, legitimate as they may
be, became an abyss of hatred. Secular against religious, veterans
against newcomers, Ashkenazi against Sephardi, right against left _
a country in war, in war with itself, an internal war that could
bring disaster if we do not stop it in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahak went on to paint a picture of a nation overcome by a wave
of lawlessness, intolerance and violence. He cited the bias murder
of an immigrant soldier, the high rate of car accidents, even
wife-beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you noticed that people on the street are not smiling as
much?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shahak is clearly calculating that the Israeli public is
exhausted and upset by the vociferous internal struggles, and wants
at least the uplift of healing words.
</P>
<P>
   What he revealed of his politics did not seem very different
from those of Labor, particularly on foreign policy issues. He said
he believed the peace effort must move forward, and that only a
negotiated solution with Syria could permit the Israeli Army to
withdraw from Lebanon. But on social issues his emphasis was
somewhat different. He went out of his way, for instance, to
underscore how important he considers immigrants to Israel's
economy and well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But he sharply criticized Labor for a being a dinosaur party,
aiming squarely for what Labor, in trying to remake itself as ``the
New Labor,'' believes to be its Achilles' heel _ a perception that
it is elite and out of touch with young, Sephardic, Russian and
religious voters.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's advisers have reportedly counseled him to steer
clear of attacks on Shahak. Wednesday his Health Minister, Yehoshua
Matza, defended him, branding Shahak as a leftist and accusing him
of ``inciting'' against the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Shahak trouncing Netanyahu in the second round of
voting if he survives the first against Barak. The elections are to
be held on May 17, and it is probable there will be a runoff on
June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders, too, are uncomfortable with the thought of going
after Shahak, especially since any center-left government would
probably see them linking forces. But in the first round of voting
he is their competition, and so the barbed assessments of his
inexperience began lobbing his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Shahak on the phone,'' Yossi Beilin, a senior
member of the Labor Party, said in an interview earlier this week.
``I said, `I really respect you and like you, but we're going to
have to go after you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a contradiction between his appearance as a modest
person and his ambition to be prime minister in his first bid for
elected office, no? It takes a lot of experience and finesse to
manage the political body in this country, but maybe he doesn't
know this, like the kid who pulls at the tail of the cute little
Rottweiler and doesn't know he is danger''
</P>
<P>
   Disarmingly to some, Shahak conceded that he has ``no political
experience, that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he made it clear that he would present that as a
selling point. ``I am not a politician,'' he said. ``But I didn't
land here from another planet, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
