<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      01-06 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE TALK OF BIPARTISANSHIP, BICKERING OPENS NEW HOUSE SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mo., N.J.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR,
HOUSE-HASTERT, CONGRESS-ETHICS, CONGRESS-NY and IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dennis Hastert was sworn in as the 51st
speaker of the House Wednesday and immediately tried to set a tone
that would salve the destructive politics that have paralyzed the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions to problems cannot be found in a pool of
bitterness,'' the 57-year-old Illinois Republican said as the new
Congress convened and he sought to treat the House's wounds, left
raw by the tumultuous tenure of his predecessor, Newt Gingrich, and
by last month's near-party-line vote to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats responded warmly to the tone that Hastert set
Wednesday and in his 18-day run-up to becoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's bury the hatchet,'' Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the
Democratic leader, said as he presented the gavel to Hastert.
``Let's put to rest the poisonous politics which have infected this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the curtain fell on the day's formal ceremonies,
the parties lapsed back to their old bickering. They squabbled over
proposed changes in House rules, which Democrats said watered down
their rights as the minority party. Republicans quashed a
Democratic attempt to boost their representation on committees to
reflect the same ratio of Democrats to Republicans that has been
elected to the full House. All votes ran strictly along party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the real fury between the parties erupted as Democrats
sought to re-hash last month's bitter impeachment debate and even
overturn the outcome. The venue was discussion over a requirement
that the new House sworn in Wednesday reappoint the 13 Republicans
that the old House appointed last year to act as prosecutors in the
impeachment trial of Clinton in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans tried to treat the measure as a mere housekeeping
matter. But Democrats took it as a chance to reassert to the nation
that the Republicans' vote to impeach the president was highly
unpopular with the public and only demonstrated that in their zeal
to punish the president, the Republicans were ignoring more
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., led the way, warning the House that
a vote to reappoint the managers ``would be tantamount to voting to
remove the president from office.'' As Democrats monopolized the
floor, Rep. Steven Rothman, D-N.J., declared: ``This impeachment
should never have occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   But after debate, the House voted 223-198 to reappoint the
managers, with 218 Republicans and five Democrats _ the same five
who voted for impeachment last month _ voting in favor. Opposing
the measure were 197 Democrats, one Independent and no Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling was a sign of what some say will be the real
guiding principle of this Congress _ the narrowness of the
Republican majority. With Gingrich's resignation from Congress
Wednesday afternoon, there are 222 Republicans, 211 Democrats, one
Independent who leans Democratic and one vacancy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gingrich's seat in his heavily Republican suburban-Atlanta
district is to be filled in a special election Feb. 23. Robert
Livingston, who had been chosen to follow Gingrich as speaker but
is quitting Congress in the wake of his acknowledgment of
adulterous affairs, is leaving in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, the parties quickly agreed on one
piece of legislation _ to relax their self-imposed restrictions on
accepting gifts from lobbyists. They have been chafing since 1996
over their rule that they could accept gifts only from family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday they adopted by voice vote the same language that
guides the Senate, allowing members to accept gifts up to $50 from
lobbyists, with an annual $100 limit on items from any single
source. They left in place a loophole that allows private
organizations to sponsor both foreign and domestic travel by
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the message of the day was bipartisanship and a kind of
back-to-basics value system. Shucking the loftiness of his new
position and showing his affinity with the rank and file from which
he had emerged, Hastert stepped down from the podium and delivered
his 17-minute acceptance speech from the floor. It ran half the
length of Gingrich's acceptance speech in 1995 and was void of
Gingrich's high-blown oratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stalemate is not an option,'' he said in vowing to meet
Democrats at least half-way. ``Solutions are.''
</P>
<P>
   He made no mention of impeachment, although he was one of the
Republicans to vote for it on Dec. 19. Instead, he called on
Clinton to work with him on saving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they went back to battle on the House floor, members of
both parties said that Hastert's speech had pointed them in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged because I know Dennis Hastert,'' said Rep.
Henry Waxman, D-Calif. ``The rancor and raw partisanship and
nastiness to which the House sunk in December shocked members of
both parties. And I think that many on both sides of the aisle want
to start reaching out to deal with the issues that voters sent us
here to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., said, ``Members are tired of not
getting enough work done. We all have issues, we all have bills we
think will help the people we represent and we want to see them
considered!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
