<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHS-CHAIRMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chairman of Rich's unit will leave Federated
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Russell Stravitz will end a 30-year career with
Federated Department Stores, stepping down as chairman of its
Atlanta-based Rich's/Lazarus Goldsmith's division, the company said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stravitz will be replaced by Arnold Orlick, who has been
president and chief operating officer of the division since May
1997. The change is effective Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Orlick's position is Edwin J. Holman, known as a
tenacious numbers man who will likely boost efficiency and
productivity in the Rich's/Lazarus Goldsmith's division.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the consummate operations executive. He's going to get
goods to the floor faster and improve logistics at every level,''
said colleague Bob Mang, chief executive of Monet Group, a New
York-based costume jewelry manufacturer. Mang and Holman ran former
Washington, D.C., retailer Woodward &AMP; Lothrop during its
reorganization in the mid-1990s. Federated nearly bought the chain
in 1995 following bankruptcy proceedings, but was outbid by May
Department Stores and J.C. Penney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Holman was most recently chairman and chief executive of Petrie
Retail Inc., a Secaucus, N.J.-based women's apparel chain that
operated stores under the Stuarts and Marianne nameplates. In 1996,
Holman was brought in to shepherd bankruptcy proceedings Petrie
began the previous year. Petrie recently liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues do not characterize Holman as a ``slash and burn''
type, but they do expect him to further trim expenses under a
Federated model that is already cost-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's, along with the nearly identical Lazarus and Goldsmith's
chains, is Federated's third-largest division behind Macy's East
and Macy's West. Rich's currently has 13 stores in metro Atlanta.
The division operates 75 stores in the Southeast and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Stravitz's departure was no surprise to Prudential Securities
analyst Wayne Hood, who noted that beyond divisional leadership
posts, opportunities at Federated are limited. ``I think
opportunities outside the company will be more challenging for
him,'' Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Rich's division since 1993, Stravitz has
overseen a new strategy and major remodelings in metro Atlanta to
help the chain better compete with specialty retailers, discounters
and a growing consumer demand for brand name apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Stravitz was executive vice president and a merchandise
manager at Federated's Bloomingdale's division in New York, where
he began his career in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Stravitz, 50, indicated he was taking a break from the retail
track to spend time with his family before making his next
professional move.
</P>
<P>
   Other management changes at Federated:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ron Klein has been named chairman and chief executive officer
of Stern's, succeeding Matthew D. Serra, who left the division in
September. Klein has been vice chairman and director of stores at
Federated's Macy's East division since February.
</P>
<P>
   -- Peter R. Sachse has been named vice chairman and director of
stores at Macy's East, succeeding Klein. Sachse was executive vice
president/general merchandise manager at Macy's East.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
