A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: White House continues wider focus
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago this week, Newt Gingrich appeared before the Cobb
County Chamber of Commerce to outline an ambitious agenda for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming year, the Republican speaker proposed taking
serious steps toward saving Social Security, reforming education
and the tax system and resolving the big questions over health
care. He challenged his listeners to begin thinking much more
long-range about the generational problems that confront the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the tape forward a few weeks and Monica Lewinsky's name
appears.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the tape up to the present and we have Gingrich, his
speakership not only given up but in its second generation of
successor, addressing the future in a much different speech to a
gathering of conservatives in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most we can hope for,'' Gingrich advised, would
be to block liberal initiatives in Congress and ``set the stage''
for a Republican to get elected president in Y2K. He advised the
assemblage of right-wing notables to adopt a ``do no harm'' policy
for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The stupendous national opportunity that was missed in the year
between those speeches would be the real story of 1998, if inaction
could qualify as a story.
</P>
<P>
   The big 21st Century problems Gingrich spoke of remain untended.
Instead of thinking over decades, as he urged last year, the
congressional attention span has shrunk to a point where, less than
24 hours before Bill Clinton's impeachment trial was to begin, it
was not clear in the Senate how it will proceed or _ the question
that preoccupies Washington as another year begins _how long it
will take to finish.
</P>
<P>
   What had so much to do with Gingrich's undoing now rests
uncomfortably in the lap of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who
on the eve of the trial was still struggling to hold the reins on a
process he has been unable to foreshorten.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, was announcing the second straight budget
surplus, a projected $76 billion for the coming year, on a day when
the Dow, the Nasdaq and the S&AMP;P 500 all were flirting with record
highs. He spoke as optimistically as Gingrich did a year ago about
reforming social security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say that this task will be too complicated for the
Congress and the administration to achieve,'' the president said,
enlisting his jurors in the great work.
</P>
<P>
   No real progress can be made toward such a goal during an
impeachment trial, of course, and little serious thought seems to
have been given to what the atmosphere will be like after it's
over.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the White House can demonstrate a longer view and
wider focus than the Republican Congress, however, it holds the
political high ground. The most easily dismissed suggestion of the
year so far was that Clinton postpone his Jan. 19 State of the
Union message, a speech that provides a grand opportunity if there
ever was one to draw a contrast between wide and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   The great opportunity to put the nation on a firm footing for
the new century lingers, meanwhile, but health care costs are
creeping back up and the international economic problems that
seemed so threatening a year ago have not eased. Opportunities
don't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you, but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
