<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT OVERSHADOWS OPENING OF NEW CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 106th Congress formally opened Wednesday with
the election of Representative Dennis Hastert as House speaker, but
his promises of comity and cooperation were met with immediate
skepticism by Democrats who tried unsuccessfully to halt the Senate
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of a new congressional session is normally a time to
put aside partisanship and celebrate the democratic system that
peacefully elects representatives and senators. On the surface,
Wednesday was no different, as House members allowed their children
to roam the floor, with babies bawling and young girls clutching
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear this was no ordinary opening day as soon as
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt ceremoniously handed the
gavel to Hastert, of Illinois, who was elected speaker 220-205.
Republicans narrowly control the House with 222 seats, while
Democrats have 211, plus one Independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's bury the hatchet,'' Gephardt said. ``Let's put to rest
the poisonous politics that have infected this place.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar sense of unreality pervaded the Senate side. Vice
President Al Gore swore in the senators even as Republican leaders
were meeting to discuss how to proceed with an impeachment trial
that _ if it results in Clinton's conviction _ would make Gore the
new president. Republicans control the Senate 55-45, with a
two-thirds vote necessary to convict and remove the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hours after House leaders vowed cooperation, there
was a heated debate as Democrats tried in vain to prevent
Republicans from re-appointing the 13 House ``managers,'' or
prosecutors, for the Senate trial. While the managers had been
appointed last month by the outgoing 105th Congress,
parliamentarians determined that the new Congress had to vote on
the matter again, partly because funding will be required to pay
their expenses during the trial. Republicans said no such new tally
was needed on the articles of impeachment. The measure to reappoint
the managers was approved 223-198.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the House voted to ease the 1995 gift ban, allowing
members to accept meals and other items up to $50, and up to $100
in gifts from one source per year. The measure is similar to the
gift rules followed in the Senate and was widely supported by House
members who said the existing gift ban was so complicated it was
impossible to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, 57, a former high school teacher and wrestling coach,
kicked off the day's public ceremonies with a speech on the House
floor that few Democrats could find objectionable. He vowed to meet
Democrats more than halfway, pledged to take Clinton's Social
Security reform plan seriously, and declared that ``stalements are
not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions to problems cannot be found in a pool of
bitterness,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats filed out of the House chamber, they said they
liked what they heard, noting how moderate Hastert sounded in
comparison to his predecessor, Newt Gingrich, who resigned after
Republicans lost five seats in the November elections. While
Hastert had little choice other than to seek bipartisanship due to
the Republicans' slim majority, many Democrats have said they could
work with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Charles Rangel, a New York Democrat,
underscored the concerns of his party when he wondered aloud
whether Hastert would control the House, or would the House
minority whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, who is widely seen as the
driving force behind the impeachment effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on whether DeLay is pulling the strings,'' Rangel
said. ``I want so badly to be optimistic, but DeLay hasn't given me
any reason for optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative William Delahunt, the Massachusetts Democrat who
sits on the House Judiciary Committee, said there was a ``surreal
quality'' about the day. He welcomed Hastert's words coming after
``we just saw a totally partisan breakdown in terms of this major
constitutional crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who had Gephardt preside over the House, walked to the
well to deliver his speech. ``Nearly a year ago, President Clinton
came here to give his State of the Union address'' and ``called for
Social Security reform,'' Hastert said. ``This year, I invite him
to return to give us his reform plan. He has my assurance that it
will be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said his other priorities included Medicare reform,
education, lower taxes and more money for national defense.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the scene was Gingrich, who resigned both as
speaker and as a House member. Representative Robert L. Livingston
of Louisiana, who initially was tapped to replace Gingrich of
speaker, had stepped aside after admitting to marital infidelity.
He plans to resign from the House later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was known as an ideological firebrand, who pushed
through parts of the Contract with America after he led the
Republican takeover of the House in the 1994 election. Hastert, by
comparison, is being counted on by his colleagues to be more a
conciliator in the mold of former House Minority Leader Bob Michel,
also of Illinois. Hastert takes control with such a slim majority
that he must worry whether Democrats can pick up the seats
necessary to win back control in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, where members are elected to six-year terms, 34
senators were elected or reelected in 1998, including four new
senators from each party.
</P>
</TEXT>
