<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mindspring joins net giants with 400,000 subscriber acquisition
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_MindSpring took a giant step toward becoming a major
Internet player Wednesay with the purchase of Netcom's 400,000-plus
subscriber base.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will put the Atlanta-based Internet service
provider over the million mark in subscribers and propel it into a
league with some of the Net's biggest names.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a little pack up there,'' says MindSpring founder
and chairman Charles Brewer referring to the nation's top ISPs,
including AT&AMP;T's WorldNet Service, Earthlink, CompuServe and the
Microsoft Network which all now claim one to two million
subscribers each. America Online leads the pack with 15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was finalized at 6 a.m. Tuesday and MindSpring
executives including chairman and founder Charles Brewer, president
and COO Michael McQuary and chief financial officer Michael
Misikoff discussed the deal in a 9 a.m. conference call with
analysts who spent most of the question and answer period
congratulating Brewer on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer size of the combined companies will help advance the
company's long term goals, but McQuary says he knows it won't be
smooth sailing to grow that fast and keep customers happy on a
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement is announcing the acquisition,'' he said in an
interview, ``but it's like watching a duck swimming on the pond. It
looks very elegant on the surface, but you don't realize that under
the water there is a lot of furious paddling.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take some paddling to incorporate the ailing Netcom into
the prosperous MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 400,000 dial-up customers, MindSpring also
acquired Netcom's 3,000 commercial Internet accounts and 18,000 Web
hosting customers.
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said the addition of Netcom's Web hosting services
combined with MindSpring's own hosting services will give the
company about 38,000 Web hosting customers, making MindSpring a
player in the SOHO (small office/home office) market.
</P>
<P>
   The sale also includes other assets including leased operations
facilities in San Jose, Calif. and Dallas, Texas. MindSpring also
acquired the U.S. rights to the ``Netcom'' name as well as select
software and equipment. ICG communications retains its network
assets and international ISP customers in Canada, Brazil and Great
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the company plans to borrow the money to cover the
deal against cash on hand. Subject to regulatory approval, he said
the deal should close in February.
</P>
<P>
   It's a particularly exciting challenge for Brewer, who says he
was a Netcom customer in the ISP's earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've wanted to jealously buy Netcom for a while, even when
ICG bought it'' a year ago, Brewer said. ``Netcom hasn't grown, nor
has it achieved profitability. I think we can fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer says the company's increased size will give it leverage
in areas in which it wants to play. ``I do think it helps,'' he
says. ``It makes us a more credible spokesperson (for the industry)
and it makes us a more attractive partner for the ``last mile''
owners, meaning that cable and telephone companies will view
Mindspring in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   With the Netcom deal, MindSpring finds itself fighting a war on
two fronts. The company may be able to capture the attention of
federal regulators, advertisers and potential business partners
with its new and improved subscriber base. But if it's hunger for
growth, power and influence comes at the expense of the stellar
customer service and ``core values and beliefs'' the company has
built it's reputation upon, MindSpring could lose its impressive
new market share and all the perks that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   McQuary flew to San Jose Tuesday evening for a day of
Bible-thumping with Netcom's 400 employees. ``I'm out here meeting
with employees because it's important to understand how to treat
each other and the customers, as well,'' said McQuary in a phone
interview Wednesday morning. ``It's all going to begin and end with
the customers.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Brewer both say they'll be jetting back and forth to
oversee the transition. They both say that while Atlanta will
always be home, having a presence in Silicon Valley will be a
definite asset.
</P>
<P>
   However the immediate challenge is at the customer level. The
MindSpring executives must devise a way to take Netcom _ a company
with sinking membership and outsourced customer service _ and apply
MindSpring's philosophy of treating employees, customers and
investors with equal measures of respect. McQuary says it will take
some time to ramp up the flagging Netcom to the same levels of
service and support that brought MindSpring its legions of loyal
subscribers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   The company eventually plans to replace Netcom's customer
service operation, which Netcom currently outsources, and begin
adding additional staffers to MindSpring-owned and operated call
centers in Atlanta, Phoenix, Seattle and Harrisburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal is to resurrect Netcom to a top flight ISP
based on MindSpring's emphasis on service and support. However, the
company has no plans to turn Netcom upside down overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Netcom may be a lacking as an ISP, but MindSpring management
knows Netcom is an established Internet brand which, despite its
troubles, still has subscribers who might not want to change
addresses. McQuary says he expects a certain amount of resistance
from Netcom subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netcom was the leader in taking an ISP national,'' McQuary
says. ``So there's also a lesson for MindSpring in this. You have
to constantly work hard and rededicate yourself to your customers.
Being the first pioneer doesn't mean you're going to be the one to
hold on to it.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring also will own the Netcom name in the U.S. and plans
to continue using it for now. The company is unsure how it will
fold Netcom into the rest of MindSpring, but it must be done in a
way that makes Netcom customers comfortable, McQuary says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is a change of control and your credit card
bill has a new line on it, people will evaluate their options,'' he
says. ``Some of the 400,000 Netcom customers we have won't make the
transititon to MindSpring. But we plan to scramble like crazy to
get those subscribers to know who we are and how we can perform.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring execs say, despite the challenges facing them, they
are still interested in growth through acquisition. ``There are
still lots of other opportunities out there,'' McQuary says, ``but
we have to get our arms around this one first. We won't be blind to
other opportunities. We have an appetite to continue doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
