</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT-WIRETAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRIBUTOR ALLEGES COCA-COLA ENTERPRISES USED WIRETAPPING AND
OTHER TACTICS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Md., Ark.)  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In court papers disclosed this week, Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.,
the world's largest Coca-Cola bottler, is accused of engaging in
fraud, wiretapping and other tactics in an effort to drive a small
Maryland soft-drink distributor out of business.
</P>
<P>
   In an amended version of its original lawsuit, the distributor,
B.K. Miller of Clinton, Md., contends, among other things, that
lawyers for Coca-Cola Enterprises submitted false reports to a
federal court from a private investigation company in an attempt to
prove that B.K. Miller illegally had shipped Coke products outside
its assigned sales territory.
</P>
<P>
   The papers filed by lawyers for B.K. Miller say, ``CCE attempted
to persuade the court to rely on documents which it knew were so
fraudulent that its general counsel was recommending to Coke USA's
general counsel that the matter be turned over to law enforcement
authorities.'' (Coke USA is the American unit of Coca-Cola Co.,
which makes soft-drink concentrate and sells it to Coca-Cola
Enterprises and its other bottlers.)
</P>
<P>
   Documents in the case, which began in 1997 in U.S. District
Court in Greenbelt, Md., were unsealed on Tuesday at the request of
The New York Times. Over all, they form a rare public portrait of
the sharp edges of the soft-drink business that emerge when two
parties clash.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides refused to comment on the case, citing
the litigation. A jury trial is scheduled to begin on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Coca-Cola Enterprises called the allegations
``totally without merit,'' and added: ``It is the policy of
Coca-Cola Enterprises to fully comply with all laws applicable to
our business operations, and we are taking this matter very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the case is B.K. Miller's contention that
Coca-Cola Enterprises tried to take over Miller's customers, which
include vending machines and small stores. Miller says that
Coca-Cola Enterprises, which supplied Miller with products, imposed
a price increase and shifted strategy to include controlling highly
profitable vending machines after the bottler's local management
changed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since at least the summer of 1996, CCE has engaged in a
deliberate campaign to destroy B.K. Miller's business,'' contends
one document filed last year by Miller's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for CCE, although agreeing that the bottler's
strategy shifted, say the company was simply engaged in normal
competition. ``B.K. Miller was never targeted for extinction,'' one
response said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, CCE has accused B.K. Miller of engaging in
``trans-shipping,'' or selling Coke products outside its assigned
territory, for which Coca-Cola Co. levies fines of $5 a case that
it then largely gives to the bottler in whose territory the offense
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Miller denies trans-shipping. But Coca-Cola Enterprises has
tried hard to make its case.
</P>
<P>
   One agent hired by Coca-Cola Co. to investigate trans-shipping
by a number of distributors ``falsified his daily activity logs,''
according to one document. Although the validity of that report and
others was being questioned by company officials, the reports were
submitted last year to the Federal judge presiding in the B.K.
Miller case as support for CCE's claim.
</P>
<P>
   David Miller, the president of B.K. Miller, said Wednesday that
he planned to see the case through to its conclusion. ``I want the
ability to market the products I own the way that I think I
should,'' he said. ``I play by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The family-owned B.K. Miller, which is named for David Miller's
grandfather, sells about 1.6 million cases of Coke products a year.
David Miller's brother Thomas V., who is known as Mike, is a
well-known state senator in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The company is an uncommon hybrid in the soft-drink business,
being both a customer of Coca-Cola Enterprises, from which it buys
products for its store, and a competitor, because it resells some
of those products through vending machines and other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The documents filed by Miller's lawyers include reports by a
private-investigation company that Coca-Cola Enterprises hired
around the time the lawsuit was filed to look into business
practices at B.K. Miller, among others. Senior executives at
Coca-Cola Enterprises, including Henry A. Schimberg, now the chief
executive, were kept up to date on the investigation of B.K.
Miller, internal memorandums show.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Epic Investigations, was hired by a Coca-Cola
Enterprises executive who insisted on secrecy, instructing that all
bills be sent to his home, not to his office, according to a
document filed in the court proceedings by Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises paid Epic $21,000 in cash to set up a sham
company with the goal of catching B.K. Miller and others in the act
of selling soft drinks outside their designated territory, the
Baltimore-Washington area. That effort failed to turn up any
evidence of violations by Miller, the documents say.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls by Coca-Cola Enterprises employees as well as
B.K. Miller workers were recorded, in most cases without the
knowledge of both the caller and the recipient, the documents say.
Miller's lawyers said Maryland law forbids secret telephone
recordings, though Coca-Cola Enterprises said the calls took place
across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was identified by Coca-Cola Enterprises to other
distributors as a company that had violated the trans-shipping
rules. In two cases cited by Miller's lawyers, companies stopped
selling Coke products to Miller as a result.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the documents show, a Sam's Club owned by Wal-Mart
was featuring an unusually low price for the soft drink in May
1997, and B.K. Miller tried to take advantage of the sale but was
turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were grave concerns of Wal-Mart about their relationship
with their supplier (Coca-Cola) if they did what David Miller was
asking,'' Mark S. Levinstein, a lawyer for B.K. Miller, states in
the transcript of a conference call among lawyers and the judge in
the case. In another example, a Giant supermarket also refused to
sell to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Coca-Cola Enterprises countersued B.K. Miller,
contending breach of contract, fraud and other offenses in
connection with the trans-shipping accusations. ``CCE has suffered
damage as a result of B.K. Miller's trans-shipping,'' the lawsuit
contends, ``and its intentionally false promises and
misrepresentations to CCE about B.K. Miller not trans-shipping
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises says it has documents that show evidence
of the trans-shipping activity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
