<HEADER>
A1904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-COX     01-06 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After disappointing 1998, AirTran names new CEO
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Struggling AirTran Airways made a leadership change Wednesday,
naming one-time Eastern Airlines executive Joseph B. Leonard to
replace D. Joseph Corr as top executive.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows a disappointing 1998 for Orlando-based AirTran,
the successor to ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   The low-fare airline failed to achieve a predicted profit
rebound, and stock in parent AirTran Holdings fell as low as $2.14
a share. Shares rose 31 1/4 cents Wednesday to $3.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Corr, 58, whose contract didn't expire for almost another year,
said the decision to leave early was his own. The self-described
turnaround specialist said he achieved his goal of rebuilding the
carrier ``to the point that it runs like a real business'' and
wanted to return to his home and other business interests in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Corr said he remains convinced AirTran will succeed, adding he
advocated Leonard's selection as the new chairman, president and
chief executive of AirTran Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who is leaving as CEO of AlliedSignal Inc.'s Aerospace
Marketing, Sales and Service unit to take the AirTran job, said he
foresees no immediate strategy shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go in and take a look from A to Z at the
operation, but not with any pre-set notion of what changes should
be made,'' he said. He starts work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first order of business is to make AirTran as profitable
as we can be, and we'll go where the path leads us after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The move marks a return to the airline field for Leonard, 55, an
Augusta, Ga. native and Auburn University(AL) graduate.
</P>
<P>
   He previously worked at Eastern, Northwest and American
airlines. At Eastern, he was chief operating officer during the
stormy ownership of Frank Lorenzo and was involved in
management-union wars that led to the carrier's 1991 demise.
</P>
<P>
   He was customer service chief at Northwest before joining
AlliedSignal in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said he has long known not only Corr but also Robert
Priddy and Lewis Jordan, the two ValuJet co-founders who sit on
AirTran Holdings' board and own big chunks of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Corr succeeded Jordan as ValuJet's president and CEO in late
1996, shortly after the carrier resumed flying in the wake of the
government-ordered shutdown that followed the Flight 592 crash in
Florida. Corr led ValuJet into its merger with AirTran in 1997,
then launched a product and marketing overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   The airline earned its first post-shutdown profit in the second
quarter of 1998, but fell back into the red in the summer quarter.
Corr said he expects close to break-even results for the fourth
quarter ended Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
