<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      01-06 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAST DIFFERENCES BETWEEN CLINTON-JOHNSON IMPEACHMENT TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The deeper Congress and the White House wade into
the fearful waters of a historic impeachment trial that begins
Thursday in the Senate, the deeper the two branches dig into a
constitutional crisis, the deeper the differences between the
tragedies of Andrew Johnson and Bill Clinton appear.
</P>
<P>
   But with the chief justice about to swear in 100 senators as
presidential jurors, these differences are emerging as more than
simply historical curiosities. A look back at the bitterness and
betrayal that marked the Johnson trial during the most contentious
days of the Reconstruction period 130 years ago tells us a lot
about our own age at the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
   For all the modern dangers facing America at century's end _
global economic uncertainty, the threat of terrorism, worries about
arms proliferation _ the United States is a secure, mature nation
in 1999. It is the oldest democracy in the world. In 1868, it was
an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   For all the divisions among us _ religious, racial, gender,
language, sexual orientation, region, wealth _ the United States is
basically one nation in 1999. That was not at all clear in 1868,
when memories of the Civil War were fresh, when the continent was
still riven with sectional tensions and when whole parts of the
country were under military occupation. Today we are more
pluralistic than we were in 1868, but no one would think of the
term ``United States'' as a plural noun. Then the United States
were. Today the United States is.
</P>
<P>
   For all the resentment between the legislature of one party and
the White House of another, the two branches are far closer to each
other in 1999 than they were in 1868. President Johnson
deliberately and repeatedly antagonized his congressional rivals,
thwarting their initiatives, defying their will, stomping on their
prerogatives.
</P>
<P>
   Though President Clinton has just been impeached, lawmakers of
both parties Wednesday asserted their intentions to treat the
president fairly and to work with him on matters of substance.
Indeed, in the past several years, compromises between the
Republican Congress and the Democratic president have produced an
overhaul of welfare and a budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Clinton is likely to survive his brush with
history is he was elected twice by large popular margins.
Lawmakers, themselves answerable to the public, are chary of
questioning the wisdom of the very voters who placed them in office
and in the position of deciding the destiny of the president.
Johnson wasn't elected to the presidency; he ascended to the White
House after the assassination of Abraham Lincoln in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the stakes were so high in 1868 was there was
no vice president to succeed Johnson. Next in line for the
presidency was Benjamin F. Wade, the president pro tempore of the
Senate, a figure described by a fellow Ohio lawmaker (and future
Republican president), James A. Garfield, as ``a man of violent
passions, extreme opinions, and narrow views; . . . a grossly
profane coarse nature who is surrounded by the worst and most
violent elements in the Republican party.'' Wade's high-tariff and
soft currency views would have been a major departure in 1868. Vice
President Al Gore's views on important issues do not differ
substantially from Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the reasons the nation may be taking the Clinton
impeachment and trial in stride _ and not rushing the doors of the
Capitol, as the men in suits and women in hoop skirts did in 1868 _
is that consequences of the episode are so much less critical now
than they were in Johnson's time. At stake in 1868 was not only the
rule of law, but also the course of Reconstruction, which was the
process of building a nation from the rubble and resentment of the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the nature of Reconstruction _ how to reinvite
the Confederate states back into the Union, who should govern those
states, how the rebels should be punished, and how racial justice
should be defined and won _ is at the heart of why the Civil War
was fought and at the heart of what America's founders meant when
they talked about securing ``the blessings of liberty to ourselves
and our posterity.'' That struggle also raised questions of whether
one branch of government, the executive, had the option of not
enforcing the laws that were duly passed by the legislative branch.
</P>
<P>
   Great issues are, to be sure, in play in 1999, including the
implications of a president lying under oath to a grand jury and
obstructing justice, the two charges Clinton faces. Under question
here are the public consequences of the private morality of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1868, the question was the national morals of the
country. The overriding issues 130 years ago were the nature of
American democracy and the reach of American liberty, issues about
slavery and freedom left unresolved in the Constitution. It took a
Civil War and Reconstruction to answer those questions. But a
century later, it took the civil-rights movement to transform that
answer into reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
