A1907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-KIDS     01-06 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-KIDS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State rep wants more oversight over Georgia child care systems
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Already chock-full of children, Georgia's foster care
system barely has room for the abused, abandoned and neglected
minors who need to be in it.
</P>
<P>
   However, last year judges allowed caseworkers from the Division
of Family and Children Services to place at least eight children
into foster homes and shelters, only to have authorities later
determine that they did not need to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Newborn twins remained separated from their mother for 10 days
until Gov. Zell Miller ordered an immediate investigation which
sent them home the day he learned about the case. And six Atlanta
children went without their parents for 179 days until Tommy
Olmstead, commissioner of the state's child protection agency,
ordered a review of their case. They went home 36 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, during this legislative session, Rep. Georganna
Sinkfield (D-Atlanta) plans to pursue legislation that will protect
families who don't grab the attention of high-placed state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, like several other states, she said, should be able to
provide emergency, temporary care for children whose parents are
suddenly and temporarily unable to take care of their children
because of illness or accident.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws only allow for care if judges give the state
custody of the children. To get the children back, parents must
follow the same procedures and timelines established for those
suspected of abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Lolade Delu, lost custody of her twin daughters when
she returned to the hospital from complications related to the
delivery. Delu said she expected to be treated and released. When
doctors decided to admit her, she had no one to watch her 5-day old
babies. The hospital contacted DFACS, and Delu lost custody of the
girls.
</P>
<P>
   When she was being discharged two days later, Delu found out she
would have to go to court to get her twins back, she said. After
she became hysterical, doctors committed her to a psychiatric unit
where doctors determined she was not mentally ill, just
heartbroken, a nurse said. They released her.
</P>
<P>
   Delu said she is pleased that Sinkfield is pursuing a system of
care that would spare other parents from the trauma she endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' Delu said. ``I think they should
take children from people who are not taking care of them, but they
should not take children away from people who are taking care of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several states already provide up to 72 hours of care for people
in Delu's situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sinkfield said she also will pursue establishing an ombusdman
program, which exists in some form in 24 states. Ombudsmen in the
child protection system advise parents and children of their rights
and provide third-party review of cases to make sure that state
agencies follow appropriate procedures before removing children
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are issues of great importance,'' said Sinkfield who is
the chairwoman of the House Children and Youth Committee. ``The
least we should do is make sure we examine it and see how we could
fit them in with our programs.
</P>
<P>
   Peg Peters, DFACS director said she has concerns about the
length of time a child could remain in emergency care, but still
supports the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things being done locally, but I wouldn't be
opposed to doing something on a state-wide basis _ anything that
will help the children,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   However, her support of an ombudsman program is conditional.
``It depends on what the situation is and what they are looking for
and the parameters under which the examination would be,'' she
said. ``My belief is the process we've got works well.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Young and Edna Pittman said an ombudsman would be a great
service to children and parents. Their six children were in state
custody for 179 days after a caseworker removed them without
investigating a neglect claim.
</P>
<P>
   When children are not in immediate danger, DFACS policy requires
caseworkers to investigate claims before seeking the removal of
children from their parents. State laws require DFACS to present
evidence to a judge within 72 hours to justify the removal.
However, in Young's case, the caseworker did not investigate the
claims before taking the children and Fulton County juvenile court
judges granted several continuances and allowed the case to linger
155 days before hearing testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Pittman repeatedly called DFACS officials and
politicians, including the governor, attempting to get their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Media inquires prompted Olmstead to request a case review, and
the reviewer found that the family needed some support services,
such as child care subsidies and parent aides, but the children did
not have to be in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   While DFACS rescues thousands of children from harmful family
situations, it's possible some unjustified removals happen,
Sinkfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been flooded with calls, especially after the article
about the six children,'' she said. And DFACS could benefit from
such oversight, she said. ``They should be glad to have
something,'' Sinkfield said, because the department could benefit
from having someone make sure that the agency doesn't remove
children unnecessarily. ``The ombudsmen play that role.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
