<SLUG> BC-GRUMMAN-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHROP GRUMMAN TAKING CHARGE ON LOWER-THEN-EXPECTED EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman Corp., the nation's largest maker of airframes
for commercial aircraft, said Wednesday that it would take a $125
million fourth-quarter charge and that 1999 annual profits would be
about 20 percent below expectations because of the downturn in
demand by Asian countries for Boeing 747s.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based Northrop produces the fuselage for the
Boeing 747 jumbo jet, popular with Asian airlines. Last December,
as Asian countries saw a dramatic downturn in air traffic as the
region's economy weakened, Boeing announced it was cutting 747
production to two airplanes a month, from five a month just two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ripple effect of the Asian economy has hit Northrop as it
regroups after a proposed takeover by Lockheed Corp. was called off
last July because of government objections. Northrop's stock traded
as high as $108 a share just before the takeover was halted. It
then tumbled and had begun to recover slightly last fall before the
Boeing announcement in December knocked it down again. Wednesday,
the stock closed at $69.3125, down $3.9375.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, Northrop projected it would earn around $6.33 a share,
or $1.18 a share less than the $7.51 consensus of equity analysts.
``We believe the current analysts' consensus estimate of $7.51 is
overstated,'' said Northrop chief executive Kent Kresa. The company
will announce its 1998 earnings Feb. 3. In 1997, the company had
sales of $9.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $125 million fourth-quarter charge, a total of $105
million is due to the 747 production cutbacks along with an
increase in costs of fuselages currently in production. The rest is
due to delays in a series of tests on a joint defense program with
the British and U.S. defense departments that have resulted in $20
million in unrecoverable costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northrop is being pretty up front in defining these numbers,''
said Howard Rubel, an aerospace analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
``The hardest part was coming to a conclusion of what the numbers
would be and Northrop has done a good job of quantifying it.'' Each
of the 153-foot main 747 fuselages that Northrop makes generates
around $10 million for the company, which has been the 747s
principal airframe subcontractor since the 747 program began in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   The new write-off adds to a previously announced 1998 accounting
charge of $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also in the midst of reducing its work force of
54,000 by about 17 percent, or 9,000 workers, in 1999, through
layoffs and attrition.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian downturn also caused Allied Signal Inc., the world's
10th- largest aerospace company, to realign its aerospace business
to save $30 million to $50 million. The Morris Township, N.J.,
maker of aircraft equipment, facing the same slowdown in global
demand for commercial aircraft, said it expected to reduce costs
through layoffs and consolidation in its supply chain.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not provide information on how the aerospace
business would be realigned. But investors reacted more favorably,
with the stock closing at $44.6875, up 87.5 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
