<SLUG> BC-GOSPELMUSIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Saturday, Atlanta hosts gospel's Stellar Awards
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta adds another notch Saturday to its growing
reputation as a mecca for gospel music when it hosts the 14th
annual Stellar Awards, gospel music's premier awards show.
</P>
<P>
   The affair begins at 5 p.m. at the Atlanta Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be big,'' said Eli Smith, disc jockey for gospel
radio station WYZE-AM (1480). ``The Stellar Awards are the gospel
version of the Grammy Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   And like the Grammy ceremony, the Stellar Awards will feature a
parade of celebrities, including Kirk Franklin, Fred Hammond &AMP;
Radical for Christ choir, Dottie Peoples, Take 6 and Donnie
McClurkin.
</P>
<P>
   The show's presenters will be as famous as its honorees. They
include comedian Steve Harvey, star of the WB sitcom ``The Steve
Harvey Show''; actress Lynn Whitfield, who starred in the 1997 film
``Eve's Bayou''; and Bobby Jones, host of BET's ``The Bobby Jones
Gospel Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's spotlight will also shine on Atlanta, a growing
center of gospel music. In recent years, the Stellar Awards were
held in Nashville. But program organizer Don Jackson decided to
change the location after Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell personally
persuaded him to make the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew of the great gospel tradition that was here in
Atlanta,'' Jackson said. ``I also made the decision because of the
size of Atlanta's black population.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's decision marks the second time recently that a major
gospel event has moved to Atlanta. In October, Gospel Heritage
Weekend, a concert honoring the nation's top gospel artists, was
held in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's vibrant black church scene has also been a steady
source of support for many major gospel artists who regard the city
as a must-stop for their national tours.
</P>
<P>
   While in Nashville, the Stellar Awards ceremony averaged about
2,000 people. Jackson said he ``easily'' expects about 4,000 to
attend the Atlanta event, which would make it the largest Stellar
Awards show ever.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets range from $15 to $75. For additional information, call
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Blake is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
