A1910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    4 hours on Mississippi not enough for anyone
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One thing's guaranteed: By the time PBS' four-part
documentary ``The Mississippi: River of Song'' concludes, you may
never want to hear Creedence Clearwater Revival's ``Proud Mary''
ever, ever again.
</P>
<P>
   With its ``Rolling, rolling, rolling on the river'' refrain, the
'60s rock classic is the unofficial _ and overdone _ theme for an
ambitious, engaging, but not entirely satisfying musical tour of
the Mississippi from northern Minnesota to Delacroix Island, La.
That singular American sprawl, the production suggests, feeds
nearly every conceivable kind of folksy root music _ from the
fiddles of Scandanavian immigrants and the punk rock of
loft-dwelling city kids to the more obvious blues, R&AMP;B, gospel and
zydeco sounds of Memphis, Mississippi and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The series, which begins at 10:30 tonight on WGTV and continues
at the same time for the next three Thursdays, is a noble effort on
the part of the Smithsonian Institution, which has released a
two-CD set and a book to accompany it, and producer John Junkerman.
But, tonight's opening segment, ``Americans Old and New,'' feels
like a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of drummer Lori Barbero of the Minneapolis
punk trio Babes in Toyland with a classroom of immigrant Laotian
youths learning traditional Hmong qeej (bamboo reed) rituals, sure
looks nifty. But does it really establish anything?
</P>
<P>
   Big cities are magnets of opportunity for all kinds of people
and cultures. Give me a camera crew and an afternoon, and I'll find
as interesting a contrast in metro Atlanta. I'll even use the Big
Chicken as a metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, though, the river makes a compelling symbol, even
when it doesn't always shake out. ``You can't deny it,'' says Brian
Henneman, guitarist for Festus, Mo., rock band the Bottle Rockets,
featured in next week's segment, ``Midwestern Crossroads.'' A group
whose unshakably regional status Henneman credits to an
uncommercial insistence on fusing George Jones with Aerosmith, the
Bottle Rockets have always felt the psychological tug of the
Mississippi. ``That is the unexplainable thing. The river is there.
There it is! I don't know what it means, but you always knew it
meant something.''
</P>
<P>
   Junkerman contends the river is simply an organizing principle.
``I wanted to find a way of representing American contemporary
music in its wide scope and its many facets,'' he says, ``and we
hit upon the idea of following the Mississippi River partly for
personal reasons. I made a trip to New Orleans about 10 years ago
and fell in love with the area. I wanted to see what happened as we
followed the river northward.''
</P>
<P>
   The series improves as it moves in the opposite direction. The
farther south, the more seemingly disparate musical styles and
makers overlap _ and the more significant becomes the presence of
the Mississippi. No better illustration exists than in the final
hour, ``Louisiana, Where Music Is King.'' Early on, crusty country
singer Merle Haggard sits in with 98-year-old legend Jimmie Davis,
a former governor of Louisiana and a pioneering gospel artist who
penned ``You Are My Sunshine.'' Next, D.L. Menard, ``the Cajun Hank
Williams,'' joins performer Christine Balfa as she sings a familiar
melody at a country picnic. ``I'm content to be a Cajun,'' she
sings in the localized French dialect. But the tune, which passes
for traditional, is actually Haggard's ``Okie From Muskogee.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those scenes, familiar to anyone who's attended the
New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage Festival, that you'd love to linger
with, but there's always more ground to cover.
</P>
<P>
   That's a constant frustration with ``River of Song,'' which in
its rush to embrace vibrant characters (whether it's bluesman Big
Jack ``the Oilman'' Johnson or St. Louis R&AMP;B stars Fontella Bass
and Oliver Sain) spreads itself too thin for a mere hourlong
segment. You wish Junkerman was lazier in his quest or had another
four hours of airtime.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Seen and Heard
</P>
<P>
   Legal eagles on TNT
</P>
<P>
   TNT has acquired the off-network rights to reruns of ``Law &AMP;
Order.'' The Emmy-winning drama now airs in reruns on A&AMP;E. In the
deal, TNT gets episodes from this season for up to a maximum of six
seasons, starting in September 2001. The cable network also has
second-run rights to ``Law &AMP; Order's'' first 181 episodes, starting
in September 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the boy bands
</P>
<P>
   MTV's second season of ``Ultra Sound'' starts at noon Saturday
with ``Revenge of the Boy Bands'' . The show looks at the rise of
Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync and Five. There's also a visit to the
training camp of C-Note, a quartet being trained by Backstreet Boys
guru Louis Pearlman. The show is followed at 12:30 p.m. by `` 'N
Sync's Favorite Videos.''
</P>
<P>
   Swinging on VH1
</P>
<P>
   VH1's ``Hard Rock Live'' swings in at midnight Saturday (832039)
with performances from the Brian Setzer Orchestra and Big Bad
Voodoo Daddy. Setzer's group will play ``This Cat's on a Hot
Roof,'' ``Since I Don't Have You,'' ``The Dirty Boogie,'' ``Stray
Cat Strut'' and ``Jump Jive an' Wail.'' Voodoo Daddy will perform
``You &AMP; Me &AMP; the Bottle Makes 3 Tonight (Baby),'' ``Mr. Pinstripe
Suit'' and ``Go Daddy-O.''
</P>
