<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICAL CHANGES PROPOSED FOR MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of a federal advisory commission on
Wednesday proposed radical changes in Medicare, under which the
government would offer a fixed amount of money, or a voucher, to
each beneficiary to buy private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the commission agreed to draft a detailed proposal
for such changes, along the lines recommended by the chairman, Sen.
John B. Breaux, D-La., and the co-chairman, Rep. Bill Thomas,
R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would gradually increase the eligibility age for
Medicare and would provide coverage of prescription drugs for many
beneficiaries. ``Drugs are as important today as a hospital bed was
in 1965,'' when Medicare was created, Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Republicans on the panel endorsed the idea of redesigning
Medicare in the image of the Federal Employees Health Benefits
Program, which covers nine million people, including members of
Congress. The views of other Democratic members ranged from
skeptical to open-minded.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, people on Medicare could _ like federal
employees, retirees and their dependents _ choose from a wide range
of traditional insurance plans and health maintenance
organizations, and they could switch plans once a year.
</P>
<P>
   The government would pay a certain proportion, say 90 percent,
of the average premium charged by all health plans participating in
Medicare. Beneficiaries would pay the remainder, averaging perhaps
10 percent. But people who chose more expensive plans would have to
pay a larger share of the premium. The federal contribution would
be increased or reduced to reflect local differences in prices.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of this proposal contend that the competition among
private health plans would hold down costs _ a hope dismissed as
``total fantasy'' by Bruce C. Vladeck, a commission member who ran
the Medicare program from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal builds on changes made in Medicare in 1997. Those
changes have had limited success. Rather than rushing to compete in
the Medicare market, some HMO's have pulled out because they
consider the federal payments inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said his proposal would also include these ideas, which
appear to have support from many commissioners:
</P>
<P>
   _ Private insurance policies that fill gaps in the traditional
Medicare program would have to cover prescription drugs. Medicare
HMO's might also be required to provide such coverage, as some now
do voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   _ The eligibility age for Medicare would be gradually increased
by two years, to 67 from 65. The change would occur over a 24-year
period starting in 2003. People age 65 and 66 might be allowed to
buy Medicare coverage if they were willing to pay the full,
unsubsidized price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare officials would have more authority to choose the
doctors, hospitals and other health care providers who supply goods
and services to the elderly. Officials could use this authority to
select the best providers offering the lowest prices.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's proposal would also reduce Medicare's role in paying
for the training of doctors, and this would save money for
Medicare. The direct costs of graduate medical education, including
salaries and fringe benefits of interns and residents, would no
longer come out of the Medicare trust fund. The money would be
subject to annual appropriation by Congress, and medical schools
fear they would get less.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Breaux's proposal say that elderly people can
become smart shoppers, like federal employees. Future retirees will
have had decades of experience with HMO's and other forms of
managed care, they note.
</P>
<P>
   But Marilyn Moon, a public trustee of the Medicare trust fund,
said: ``One-third of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries are
unlikely to participate in a competitive market because they have
major medical problems or are struggling with Alzheimer's disease
or mental illness. That makes them much more conservative about
changing health plans. They are more likely to stick with one plan,
even if it becomes more expensive. And they probably won't be
sought out by health plans in their marketing campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-member commission, which completed a two-day meeting on
Wednesday, is studying ways to solve Medicare's long-term financial
problems. It must submit its recommendations to Congress and the
president by March 1. Recommendations made to the commission need
at least 11 votes to win approval.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's proposal appears already to have 10 votes, with support
from all 8 Republican appointees and 2 Democrats, Breaux and Sen.
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska. Breaux said he hoped to win support from
several other Democrats, so the package would have more than the 11
votes needed for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said the panel, the National
Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare, should seek an
extension of the March 1 deadline for its report. With President
Clinton's impeachment trial scheduled to begin on Thursday, he
said, ``the Senate will be absorbed in other issues.'' Five of the
17 commissioners are senators.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux rejected the idea of an extension, saying that any delay
would increase the probability of Medicare's becoming entangled in
the politics of the next presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Under Breaux's proposal, the original Medicare program would
remain an option for all beneficiaries. But the government-run
program would have to compete with private health plans and would
receive the same federal subsidy as private plans, so it would be
under the same pressure to keep down costs, commission members
said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats like Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV of West
Virginia have said they fear that healthy people would desert the
original Medicare program in favor of private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a smaller and smaller fee-for-service Medicare
program, with older, sicker and poorer people,'' Rockefeller said.
Private HMO's will not compete aggressively for Medicare business
in rural areas or in states like West Virginia, where elderly
people generally have low incomes, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
