<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTMUSEUM-GIFT07-COX     01-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTMUSEUM-GIFT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantan gives museum highly prized collection assembled by late
wife
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The High Museum of Art has started the new year on an
auspicious note, receiving a gift of 16 major contemporary works
from the collection of Atlantans Burton and the late Lenore Gold.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 artists would make most curators' Who's Who list. Among
the works are a print by the late pop artist Roy Lichtenstein, a
black velvet painting by Julian Schnabel, a ghostly female figure
by sculptor George Segal and a photo-installation by French artist
Christian Boltanski. Although the museum declined to reveal the
monetary value of the promised gifts, the collection could be
estimated at $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a quantum leap forward for any museum in the
country,'' said Frank Robinson, director of the Johnson Museum at
Gold's alma mater, Cornell University, who knows the collection and
the family well. ``Together, Burt and Lenny had a brilliant eye.
They bought difficult, challenging art before people knew they were
classics. These are works of art that express the profoundest
emotions and concerns of our time. Any museum of any size would be
thrilled to get this, and it is extraordinarily generous that Burt
wants to share it.''
</P>
<P>
   High director Ned Rifkin said the donation marks ``a significant
advance'' for the museum's contemporary art collection. ``We are
acquiring works by artists we would otherwise have wanted to
purchase, and they are all really prime examples of their work,''
Rifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Curator Carrie Przybilla says the gift fills important gaps,
citing a sculpture by German artist Anselm Kiefer as ``an important
example of a European artist considered one of the most important
of his generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gift also establishes a certain level of excellence,''
Przybilla said. In turn, it makes the High more attractive to
potential patrons. ``Collectors seem to want to give where a
collection is already prominent,'' she said. ``Perhaps others will
see that they can make a difference here, but also that ours is a
collection worthy of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Friend and collecting companion Judith Taylor described the
Golds as informed and active collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Lenny's passion . . . and he (Burton) was a great
partner,'' she said. ``Lenny had a great eye. She knew all the
dealers and would take a lot of time learning not only about a
particular artist but also what was going on in the art scene. She
always wanted to get the best piece possible. I don't know where
there's another contemporary collection in town of this caliber.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golds, both native New Yorkers, started collecting before
they moved to Atlanta in 1969. They have four daughters. Gold, who
lives in Atlanta, was chairman and CEO of Stratton Industries, a
carpet manufacturing business he sold in 1986. He has focused his
philanthropic and volunteer efforts on the Jewish community. Mrs.
Gold died in a car accident in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenore was far ahead of me in understanding art,'' Gold said
Wednesday. ``She made the decisions. She would usually show me
something she was interested in, and I deferred to her, unless I
really hated it. Then we wouldn't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the Golds were featured as one of America's top
collectors in Arts &AMP; Antiques magazine. She was quoted as saying,
``I'd rather buy art than eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for her hats, her ever-present toy poodle and a big purse
that always contained transparencies of one artwork or another,
Mrs. Gold was also passionate about the High Museum. She served on
the museum board and helped found the Contemporary Art Society. The
Golds were founding members of the Collections Council.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gold built her collection with the High Museum in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many times she would say, `Well, I hope you
like this, because it's coming to the museum,' '' Przybilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold recalled as well that his wife frequently made purchases
with an eye to how they would fit into the museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for Atlanta,'' said Peter Morrin, director of
the J.P. Speed Museum in Kentucky and the High's first curator of
modern art. ``It's a wonderful fulfillment of a process, which
began 20 years ago, in which Lenny was interacting with the museum,
exchanging opinions. She really wanted the best for Atlanta. She
galvanized and helped foster ambition in everyone around her.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gold, ``It is a special privilege for me to commemorate and
honor Lenore's total commitment'' through this gift.
</P>
<P>
   Selections from the Lenore and Burton Gold Collection will soon
go on view at the High. An exhibition is scheduled for March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catherine Fox is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
