<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-WARM07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't touch that thermostat: Make your own warming trend without
overheating co-workers
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some like it hot _ in the office.
</P>
<P>
   You know the types. They huddle under a blanket, always wear a
thick sweater or wrap their hands around a hot drink, fantasizing
about turning the thermostat to high.
</P>
<P>
   But in many workplaces, messing with the thermostat is a no-no.
And you certainly don't want to start an office incident over a few
degrees. Besides, what's warm to some may feel unbearably hot to
others.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sujatha Reddy, who practices obstetrics and gynecology at
Emory University (Ga.), says some people just have less tolerance
to cold than others. ``The hypothalamus, the part of the brain that
regulates a person's temperature, is simply set at different
settings for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although women seem to be more cold-natured, says Emory
endocrinologist James H. Christy, we don't really know why. ``We've
been debating that for 100 years. We don't know if it's
psychological or physiological. It could be genetic,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of fat tissue also makes a difference in how well a
person tolerates temperature extremes. ``Sometimes, thin persons
feel the cold more than people who carry more fat on their
bodies,'' Reddy says.
</P>
<P>
   To chase away winter's chills, we found the following items to
keep you comfy. Some you wear, others sit on your desk to warm up
your space. Best of all, these won't cause your co-workers to get
too hot under their collars.
</P>
<P>
   Create your own comfort zone
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the peace (and heat) in the office
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  IN THE HOT SEAT. Not only does this heated massage pad, in a
gray-and-black tweed, keep you warm, it also gives you a
personalized massage. Since it's portable, you can use it in your
car or home as well as in the office. The pad runs on AC power or a
12-volt car battery. $70 at Brookstone stores in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A HOT CUPPA . . . Nothing chases winter's chill away faster
than a hot cup of java or cocoa. Home Trends' electric coffee
warmer, with a metal heating unit, will heat up a cup in a jiffy
($5.97). At Wal-Mart stores. (Cup is not included.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLOWING HOT &AMP; COLD. This handy contemporary heater/fan from
Brookstone's Hard-to-Find Tools catalog is small enough to set on
your desk yet powerful enough to keep you warm. A tilting base
directs the heat exactly where you need it. And, in the summer
months, the handy item turns into a fan. ($54.99). For catalog,
call 1-800-926-7000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WRAP IT UP. If your legs get cold, throw on a throw. They're
available in wools and synthetics; the rayon style shown here is 50
inches by 60 inches with a 12-inch knotted fringe. It's soft,
lightweight and lustrous. And when spring arrives, take your throw
home and toss it on your sofa to dress it up. ($49.99). At Rich's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRENDY AND TOASTY. To ward off chills, opt for this boiled
wool sweater jacket ($79.50) from Lands' End catalog. When wool
gets steamed (boiled), the fibers permanently join, thus becoming
denser, stronger and warmer. And wool's natural ``breathability''
holds and releases heat, keeping you comfy. This lightweight
jacket, which can be stashed at your desk, looks good with either
pants or a skirt. For a catalog, call 1-800-356-4444.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THERMAL LAYER. Forget those long johns your great-grandfather
used to wear. The newest styles are cut from silk interlock. They
not only keep you warm but feel luxurious on the body _ a practical
indulgence. For him and her: long-sleeve crewnecks and pants banded
at the ankles (below); each piece is $29.50, from Lands' End
catalog (1-800-356-4444). Silk undies are also available at REI
stores, where the crewneck tops are $28 and the ankle-length
bottoms are $26. Colors for her: natural and black; for him: navy
and green.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marylin Johnson is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
