<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT TO ASK TRIPLING OF SCHOOLS PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will propose Thursday tripling,
to $600 million from $200 million, funding for after-school and
summer-school programs, giving priority to school districts working
to end the practice of ``social promotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to announce the proposed increase to end social
promotions _ in which students are promoted without regard to
whether they meet requirements to succeed at the next grade level _
at a White House ceremony, where he will be joined by Vice
President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The after-school and summer-school grant program is one of the
most highly competitive ever managed by the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   Boston and Massachusetts were among the top grant recipients
last year. Massachusetts received roughly $2.2 million of last
year's total of $200 million. Boston's share was $305,977.
</P>
<P>
   That money helped fund Opening Doors to Schools and Learning,
run by the Boston public schools. The program offers tutoring,
arts, and cultural activities, as well as substance-abuse and
violence prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement is part of his practice of providing
peeks at the most popular aspects of his fiscal 2000 budget in
advance of his State of the Union message, scheduled for Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, he announced a proposal to provide a $1,000
tax credit to aid disabled Americans needing long-term care and
their caretakers. Last week, he said he would seek a 12 percent
increase, or an extra $105 million, for food safety and increase
defense spending by $100 billion over six years.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the proposed increase for after-school
programs builds on his earlier success at getting Congress to boost
the current funding of $200 million from $40 million in fiscal
1998. The program started with only $1 million in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials estimate that the proposed $600 million
would help 1.1 million children nationwide to participate in
after-school and summer-school programs run by local school
districts. More than 190,000 children in 800 schools in 46 states
and the District of Columbia already are participating in
enrichment activities, tutoring, and recreation through the grant
program.
</P>
<P>
   Because the grants are so competitive _ the Education Department
last year received applications to fund programs in 6,000 schools _
Clinton will ask that schools be given extra points if they have
comprehensive programs to end social promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials view the after-school programs
as essential to responding to the needs of parents, who are
increasingly in the work force.
</P>
<P>
   More than 28 million school-age children have both parents or
their only parent in the work force. At least 5 million children,
and possibly as many as 15 million, are left alone at home each
week. Many experts agree that unsupervised school-age children are
far more likely to use alcohol, drugs, and tobacco or commit
crimes, receive poor grades, and drop out of school than those
involved in constructive supervised activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2004EST &QL; 
