<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-HUNTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE ON HUNTER BROUGHT AGREEMENT CLOSER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For six months, the members of the National
Basketball Players Association were as unified as a chorus as they
followed the lead of union executive director Billy Hunter and
president Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure began to mount, and the moment of truth was
upon them as David Stern, commissioner of the National Basketball
Association, issued the owners' final proposal this week and urged
the players to vote or else face the cancellation of the season
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pressure, the voices of unity began to crack and a
groundswell of opposition toward the union's 19-man negotiating
team started to take shape. Suddenly, Hunters' invitation to the
league's 430 players to join in solidarity and vote the owners'
proposal down Wednesday looked like an invitation for an uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Star players like Shaquille O'Neal of the Los Angeles Lakers and
Hakeem Olajuwon of the Houston Rockets were on their way here to
voice their opposition to the union leadership. Over 30 players had
called Isaiah Thomas, a former union leader, and asked him to part
the stalemate and take control of negotiations. All-Stars including
Jayson Williams of the New Jersey Nets were adamant about getting a
deal done and not calling Stern's bluff. And many other players,
like Miami's Keith Askins and Toronto's Kevin Willis, were adamant
about voicing their approval of the owners' final deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's union was splintering before his eyes. Preventing what
could have been the downfall of the union's leadership and chaos
among players, Hunter met with Stern through the night and reached
an agreement to save the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, the players took control of their own destiny,''
said Thomas, who did not fly to New York Wednesday upon learning an
agreement was being put in place. ``Enough blood had been shed.
There wasn't a revolt but there was the potential for one.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and agents grew anxious as the league's deadline to
cancel the season approached. On Dec. 29, the union's negotiating
committee _ which had been given the authority to approve or
disapprove the owners' proposal _ rejected what Stern said was the
owners' final proposal and refused to put it before their
membership for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   As a tense week passed, several players spoke out and pleaded
for a chance to vote. When Hunter relented on Tuesday, and invited
every NBA player to town in order to vote to reaffirm the
negotiating committee's stance, the union was confident they had
the support of their membership. In a 24-hour period, that
confidence eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys were fed up, and that's why a lot of guys came
and were going to give their opinions,'' Charles Oakley said.
``They were going to do that rather than scrapping the whole
season. Billy and them heard a lot of feedback from a lot of the
guys coming to town. And a lot of guys weren't coming to vote no to
the owners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
