<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYERS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIMACES, RATHER THAN HIGH-FIVES, AS PLAYERS LEARN NEWS OF
SETTLEMENT  
(JT) 
 BY JUDY BATTISTA   
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no high-fiving in the elevators or
chest-thumping in the lobby of the GM Building as scores of NBA
players, grimaces chiseled on their faces, made their way from
Wednesday's meeting to ratify the new collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The high spirits that dominate so many games were nowhere to be
found as players _ who had made their way to New York expecting to
vote on whether they supported the union's negotiating committee in
rejecting the previous league proposal _ instead learned that a
deal had been struck late in the night that ended the 191-day
lockout. Many left the building with little or no comment, making
their way through a horde of hundreds of autograph seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm upset,'' said Jalen Rose. ``I spent $2,000 on a plane
ticket and I'm getting dressed and I hear they got a deal done and
I'm like `Why did I come?'''
</P>
<P>
   But most players were more relieved _ and resigned _ then angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they came to an agreement,'' said the San Antonio
Spurs' David Robinson after the two-hour players' meeting. ``The
whole issue is we were going to take a pay cut no matter what. We
knew we were going to go backwards. Most guys understand this is
business, not personal. We don't have anything against David Stern.
He's obviously done a great job building up this league. The
players have done a great job building up this league, and it's now
time for us to get back together and re-establish some confidence
with the fans. This thing was really ugly _ not just ugly for us,
but for fans, for the people who work at arenas, for all the people
who love the NBA. It's time for us to show them how much we do care
about playing this game.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was obvious that the tension that has permeated the
lockout lingered still at the meeting. In the days leading up to
the settlement, an increasing number of players had expressed
discontent with negotiations. Terry Cummings of the Knicks
predicted that players, many of whom he thought were ill-informed
about the negotiations, would have been divided if the original
vote to endorse the negotiating committee's actions had been taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't that far apart, and every time we got off the
issues, we got more involved in ego and pride and that was
hindering the process,'' Cummings said. ``The fans deserve better.
The game is more important than the players and the owners. The
owners pay the players to play the game and the fans pay the
salaries for players to play. We have to understand the economics
of the game. We can't afford to let something like this happen to
our game. Our game is not as old as baseball and we can't afford a
lapse like baseball had. We have to be more concerned about the
overall perception of ourselves and our game.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' Jayson Williams had been one of the most outspoken
critics of the way negotiations had progressed, and had repeatedly
suggested that an arbitrator be brought in to expedite a
settlement. Last week, the Knicks' Patrick Ewing, the union
president, criticized Williams for taking his complaints public. In
Wednesday's meeting, Williams _ who had not attended earlier
gatherings _ came face to face with Ewing, a meeting Williams said
was ``intense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking credit for this thing,'' said Williams, when
asked if he thought his comments had spurred the union to cut a
deal. ``Give it to the guys on the executive board. I just did what
I had to do to get them to play basketball. I wasn't going against
the union. I'm still with Billy Hunter. I'm 100 percent union the
whole time. I'm proud of David Stern and I'm proud of Patrick
Ewing. They'll probably hate me for the next two or three weeks,
but I'll make them love me again.''
</P>
<P>
   If Williams was in his usual mood to joke, few others were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' said Kenny Anderson. ``The last two nights I
couldn't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Charles Barkley, who is never at a loss for a quip, seemed
somber as he made his way to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair enough and we have to accept it,'' Barkley said.
``We couldn't cancel the season. Obviously there's been some damage
done to the game. Both owners and players have done a disservice to
the game. Some of the fans are going to be mad. But you can't worry
about that. I'd say to the fans, `If you want to come to the game,
come. If you don't, we still have to do our jobs.'''
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, it seemed, players were grateful that at least
they had a job for the next few months. Kevin Willis, who in recent
weeks had been critical of the union, said he expected the
animosity that had driven this lockout would now end.
</P>
<P>
   ''My thing is to start playing basketball again,'' Willis said.
``Forget about the nonsense, the greed, and seeing how much money
you can get. If we can split the money, so be it. Anything else is
absolutely ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
