<HEADER>
A1933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FANS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA MAY NOT FIND FANS SO FORGIVING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LENA WILLIAMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were fans like James Lowry of Chicago, a Bulls
season ticketholder for 20 years, who were overjoyed by the news
that the National Basketball Association and the NBA Players
Association had finally settled their labor differences and were
ready to begin play February 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning a party to celebrate the return of our extended
family,'' Lowry said by telephone from the offices of his
Chicago-based diversity firm. ``During the lockout, some of us
die-hard fans went to the Big Eight College Basketball Tournament,
but we realized it just ain't the same. So we consoled ourselves by
watching videotapes of old Bulls games. We really need an NBA
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the reaction of dozens of fans interviewed
Wednesday on the streets of midtown Manhattan to the snow-covered
sidewalks of Chicago and Denver and inside popular sporting haunts
like Manhattan's All-Star Cafe, the NBA needs to be fixed and more
than a few had suggestions as to how.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should show up for their first few games,'' said Paul
Thorn, who identified himself over lunch at the All-Star Cafe as a
``disgruntled fan.''
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Robert Riley, a telecommunications specialist, plans
to stage a self-imposed protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm canceling cable,'' he said. ``The only reason I have cable
was for the NBA games.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Oguntuase of Jamaica, N.Y., hopes both the owners and
the players end up losing ``a ton of money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they owe the fans an apology,'' said Oguntuase who's spent
the past few months getting reacquainted with some football.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how apathetic or angry the fans were over the 191-day
lockout, now that the teams will be back on the court, it's only a
matter of time before the crowds return to a game many admit they
admire in spite of its faults.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like me will go back,'' said Charles Bock, a Manhattan
lawyer who goes to more than 10 New York Knicks games a year.
``It's just a fun experience. Basketball doesn't have the tradition
of baseball, but it's got the speed, the moves and it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel DePasquale of Denver doesn't even mind that the level of
play, and players, may be somewhat rusty after a six months layoff
or that the league's 82-games season will be reduced to only a
semblance of itself at 52 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy about it,'' said the 23-year-old assistant manager
of The Sports Fan, a sporting goods store in downtown Denver.
``I've missed Sundays on the couch with those tripleheaders. I've
had that with football, but it's almost over and hockey doesn't do
it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion about the labor dispute have run the gamut from
apathy to anger. While many fans acknowledged they had only cursory
knowledge of the specific contractual issues that pitted
multi-millionaire athletes against multi-millionaire owners, the
overwhelming sentiment expressed by the man and woman on-the-street
was that both sides were greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't figure out how to divide $2 billion?'' said Keri
Donohue of Bayonne, N.J. drawing nods of approval from her friend,
Gail Mulewski. ``The only people I feel sorry for in all this are
the vendors. The owners and the players should be made to
compensate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, more than a few fans said that the big men had forgotten
about the little men and women without whose support there wouldn't
be an NBA. To those suffering from a case of selective amnesia, the
fans had a two-word antidote: baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took baseball five years and an historic home-run race to
recover from its strike,'' said Rob Uttrich, a disc jockey at the
All-Star Cafe. ``Basketball is going to need a Mark McGwire and a
Sammy Sosa to win back the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Uttrich based his assessment on an informal survey of the
restaurant's patrons. He asked lunchtime diners to indicate by a
show of applause whether they were happy the strike was over, which
drew a smattering of applause, and whether they wished the lockout
had continued, which solicited medium applause. The loudest ovation
came in response to the question: who doesn't care at all.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey conducted by the Simmons Market Research
Bureau last Spring, 70.3 percent of Americans said they
``occasionally'' watch, listen to, or attend basketball games
during the year. Those likely to be show little interest in the
game tend to be older, working-class Americans who live in small
towns and rural communities. The game's biggest supporters tend to
live in major urban areas like New York, Chicago and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at the United Center are socialites, not fans, and will
continue to go to games because it's something to do,'' said Troy
Agler, 26, of Chicago. ``Maybe, teams in the smaller markets will
be hurt because they are more community-based and are patronized
more by actual basketball fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many fans said the players, more so than the owners,
will bear the brunt of the fans rage, others were reluctant to lay
blame in either court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business,'' said Timur Cagarli, a 16-year-old high
school student who was visiting the Guggenheim Museum in New York
with his class. ``It revolves around the almighty dollar sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lowry, the Chicago Bulls loyalist, said the joy in
the windy city is tempered only by the thought that the season may
be tipping off without Michael. (everywhere, it seems, there's only
one Michael).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan may come back because it's a shortened season,'' said
Lowry in a moment of wishful thinking. ``Most of us think he's
coming back. I love this game, but without M.J. it's not going to
be the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
