r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-QUESTIONS-LAD     01-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-QUESTIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ON NBA LOCKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA came within 29 hours of becoming the first North
American sports league to cancel an entire season because of labor
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Only an all-night bargaining session on the eve of a
self-imposed ``drop-dead'' date saved the NBA from that horrible
fate, and today owners are voting to ratify an agreement, rather
than a death certificate.
</P>
<P>
   The 190-day lockout is expected to end officially with the vote
in New York, leaving precious little time to pull together a
truncated season.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some questions and answers on the minds of NBA fans:
</P>
<P>
   Q. So why did it take so long to resolve the lockout?
</P>
<P>
   Because $2 billion in annual revenue _ and the league's
long-term financial stability _ was at stake. The sides were miles
apart when the lockout began July 1, and neither side budged much
in the first five months, each waiting for the other to flinch. It
took the threat of a canceled season to force a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Owners had demanded an absolute cap on player salaries and
wanted to limit the players' overall share to 52 percent of league
revenues. The players union wanted a share of up to 60 percent and
opposed any limits on individual salaries. They met in the middle
at 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will there be more labor trouble in the future?
</P>
<P>
   Not immediately. The labor contract is for six years, with a
league-controlled option for a seventh year. Of course, if the deal
doesn't work out to the players' liking, they could always strike.
But labor peace seems assured until at least 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can the NBA win back its fans?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it could slash ticket prices, admit kids for free, donate
a hundred million dollars to charity, force players to sign
autographs for an hour a day and maybe sign Mark McGwire to a
contract. None of that is likely to happen, so instead, the league
will rely on its vaunted marketing genius, some catchy Nike
commercials and the hope that Michael Jordan plays at least one
more season.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So will Jordan be back, leading the Bulls to a seventh
championship?
</P>
<P>
   That's the 34.7-million-dollar question _ the amount Jordan can
make if he returns to Bulls _ but so far he's mum on his plans. His
agent said Jordan will study his options. Jordan confidante Charles
Barkley of the Houston Rockets has insisted Jordan is done. If
that's the case, the Bulls might also lose Scottie Pippen and
Dennis Rodman, and their reign is over.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will the Lakers and Clippers look like?
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, a lot like they did last season. The Lakers have
nine players under contract, led by Shaquille O'Neal, Eddie Jones
and Kobe Bryant. The Clippers have 10 players under contract, led
by Lamond Murray, and have added No.1 draft pick Michael
Olowokandi. But once teams are allowed to sign free agents and make
trades, about a week from now, expect some significant changes. The
Lakers are expected to trade Elden Campbell, and the Clippers will
look for a new point guard, possibly by trading one of their
forwards. Also, the Clippers have to hire a coach after failing to
replace Bill Fitch after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the best free agents available?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan tops the list, but only the Bulls can pay him the $34.7
million. The group of stars looking for work includes Barkley,
Pippen, Phoenix's Antonio McDyess, Minnesota's Tom Gugliotta,
Portland's Damon Stoudamire, Washington's Rod Strickland and New
Jersey's Jayson Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does a short season mean with regard to the schedule?
</P>
<P>
   The usual 82-game schedule is impossible, so each team will
probably play 52 games, starting about Feb. 2. The reduced schedule
still allows each team to play the 28 other teams at least once,
but not all teams will visit all cities. In order to play 52 games,
teams will occasionally have to play three consecutive nights, and
the NBA Finals will wrap up in late June.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I buy tickets yet?
</P>
<P>
   For now, only season tickets are available. Once the NBA devises
the schedule, probably this weekend, individual game tickets will
be sold through TicketMaster.
</P>
<P>
   !arrowQ: How does the shorter season affect season-ticket
holders?
</P>
<P>
   They made a profit, perhaps the only party to do so. During the
lockout, the NBA ordered teams to refund unplayed games, plus 6
percent interest. They are otherwise unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does this affect the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   The logical answer is the NBA would drop the first round, reduce
the field of teams and make the playoffs more meaningful. But the
NBA and TV networks aren't about to sacrifice that revenue, so the
playoffs will remain intact. But the postseason will start a couple
weeks later than usual, and teams probably won't get to hold
minicamps between regular-season and postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there enough time for players to get ready for the season?
It depends on the player. Many have been playing pickup games daily
since last summer. But others, notably Cleveland forward Shawn
Kemp, have gone flabby during the layoff and won't be in shape in
time. Teams will be cautious during training camp and in the first
few weeks of the season. Still, expect training rooms to be
standing-but-limping-room-only with hamstring pulls and ankle
sprains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
