A1936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX     01-06 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DREAMSVILLE: Doing the bop in Tishomingo, Okla.
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (''Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   N. Loutrelle Williams has come a long way from Tishomingo, Okla.
_ ``to Los Angeles, Montana, Dallas and various other places'' _ in
search of her dreams. Never mind that she ended up in Antlers,
Okla., just 75 miles from her childhood hometown. Here's her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to Randolph Scott? I think he and some of my
other old acquaintances might still be sighted if I sat quietly in
the old picture show on a Saturday afternoon:
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy Rogers and Gene Autry may still ride the range. Joan
Crawford may still be there, tough and dramatic, and Ava Gardner,
soft and sexy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I picture my hometown of Tishomingo in my mind, the
Thompson Theater pops into view there on Main Street. Other
landmarks appear as readily:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our old swimming hole, the Millpond; the soda fountain behind
the big glass window in Cobb drugstore; the U-turn signs at the
east and west ends of Main Street. These were the boundaries of my
youth, my world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't wait to get our driver's license and join the
Saturday night parade down Main Street, starting at dusk and
continuing until preview time, 10:45 p.m., at the picture show.
Everybody had dates for the pre-showing of the Sunday movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the Thompson Theater that I first held hands with a
boyfriend. His name was George.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie was 'She Wore a Yellow Ribbon.' The following Monday
at school most of the 13- and 14-year-old girls wore yellow scarves
or ribbons for that 'certain someone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``No X-rated movie today can compare to the sexual tension and
excitement present when George's arm dropped and his hand slowly,
ever so slowly, snaked over my arm, and his hand closed on mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those good old days, our summers were spent at Millpond in
one-piece bathing suits with modesty flaps. The beach was littered
with towels and bottles of baby oil laced with iodine. Someone had
a portable radio playing loudly such hits as 'Jambalaya!' or
'Maybelline.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys vied to perform the best swan dives and half-gainers,
while we girls lay on our towels and admired them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, we all piled into somebody's car and drove to the
drugstore for cherry limes, vanilla Cokes or milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``From grammar school on, we dreamed our dreams of going to the
moon, or to New York City _ both seemed equally removed from
Tishomingo. Some of us simply dreamed of a house, two children, two
cars and a boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In search of my dreams, I moved to Los Angeles, Montana,
Dallas and various other places. But whenever I felt crowded or
stressed or lonesome, wherever I was, I turned to memories of my
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my best reveries, I'm dancing a jitterbug or a bop on a
sandy beach. There is a watermelon chilling in Millpond.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story you'd like to share, send it to
``Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas,
75915. If your story is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
