NYT-01-06-99 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-DONATE-COX     01-06 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-DONATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tangle of strings on Turner's U.N. gift
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What in the world could be easier than giving away
money?
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything, if you ask the people who run the U.N.
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was set up a year ago this week to administer
Atlanta entrepreneur Ted Turner's gift of $1 billion over 10 years
to U.N.-related projects. Its task is to give away $100 million a
year to projects connected with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch: They're supposed to do it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``John D. Rockefeller once said that it's harder to give away a
million dollars effectively than it is to make a million dollars
honestly,'' said Tim Wirth, president of the U.N. Foundation. ``And
that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a dime of grant money could be awarded, a welter of
details needed attention. Office space had to be found, of course,
and staff members hired.
</P>
<P>
   A board had to be formed. Goals had to be set, and suitable
projects identified and evaluated. The new foundation's
relationship to the United Nations itself had to be defined, which
involved, even, the creation of a new office in the U.N.
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Rules governing the accountability of projects _ how the
foundation can keep tabs on whether the money is being used
effectively _ had to be decided upon and legal documents drawn.
</P>
<P>
   And then the board had to sift through proposals, and decide
which were deserving of grants and were most likely to make some
difference in the world _ either by inspiring other donors to ante
up as well, or by serving as pilot projects that could be emulated
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from Wirth, a former congressman, U.S. senator and U.S.
undersecretary of state for global affairs: Doing this job presents
a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most difficult thing I've ever done,'' he said.
``There's no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Foundation operates out of a flatiron building on
Connecticut Avenue in Washington. The powder-blue flag of the
United Nations flies from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Wirth occupies a triangular, well-lit office on the seventh
floor. As staff of 18 full-time employees (which may grow to 25 or
30) occupies the surrounding offices.
</P>
<P>
   The board has been set: It includes Wirth; Andrew Young, the
former U.S. ambassador to theUnited Nations and former Atlanta
mayor; Ruth Cardozo, the first lady of Brazil and expert on
children's issues; Graca Machel, a former education minister of
Mozambique and the wife of South African President Nelson Mandela;
Emma Rothschild, the director of the Center for History and
Economics at King's College at Cambridge, England; Maurice Strong,
a Canadian businessman who was secretary general of the Rio Earth
Summit; Muhammmad Yunus, founder of the Grameen Bank of Bangladesh,
which pioneered small-scale credit programs for women; and Turner,
a man whom Wirth describes as very focused, smart, disciplined _
and ``fear-instilling'' in his blunt drive for perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation aims to support the United Nations in several
ways _ by strengthening the secretary-general; promoting
cooperation between different U.N. agencies; and creating support
for the United Nations among the American people, which might
induce the American government to pay off its arrears, which the
United Nations says now stands at $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the board decided to concentrate its grants in
three broad areas: children's health, the environment and issues
relating to women and population control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they're areas of concern to Ted,'' said Wirth.
``And they were things the secretary-general seemed to think made
sense. And they are issues that are difficult to do politically.''
</P>
<P>
   In two rounds of grants in its first year, the U.N. Foundation
gave money to projects with goals as diverse as providing vitamin
supplements to mothers in West Timor, Indonesia, ($860,000 over two
years) to the demobilization of child soldiers in the African
nation of Sierra Leone ($1.1 million over one year).
</P>
<P>
   Other projects that have received funding aim to reduce violence
against women in Latin America, increase the production in Burkina
Faso of shea butter (a fat from the seeds of the shea tree used in
making moisturizing soaps and lotions), and prevent female genital
mutilation in six African countries.
</P>
<P>
   You've got an idea and want some of that money? It doesn't work
that way.
</P>
<P>
   All proposals must come from U.N. agencies. The proposals
relating to vitamins for mothers and demobilizing child soldiers,
for example, came from UNICEF, the United Nations Children's Fund.
The shea butter project is run by UNIFEM, the U.N. Development Fund
for Women.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Foundation people will be happier when they receive a
greater number of proposals that involve more than one U.N. agency,
such as the one designed to reduce violence against women, which is
a joint project of eight of them.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. agencies cannot make their proposals for Turner money
directly to the U.N. Foundation for fear that might weaken the
authority of the U.N. secretary-general rather than strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they must submit their proposals to UNFIP, the newly
created U.N. Fund for International Partnerships, which decides
whether they are worthy of being passed on to the U.N. Foundation.
The head of UNFIP reports directly to Secretary-General Kofi Annan
so that, in essence, no projects can receive funding without
Annan's approval.
</P>
<P>
   With all that to do, the actual granting of money has lagged
behind schedule. Instead of $100 million in 1998, the U.N.
Foundation gave away $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   A new round of grants will be announced late this month, and
this year should be better, said foundation spokesman David
Harwood.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, agrees that more money is better _ or
that donating any money at all to U.N. agencies is a worthwhile
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete waste of money,'' said Michael Maren, an
author and former aid worker whose book ``The Road to Hell''
chronicles in excruciating detail the devastation that
international development aid can sometimes wreak.
</P>
<P>
   Maren argues that, by pouring money into the United Nations,
which he says is ``bureaucratically moribund'' and horrendously
ineffective, Turner is throwing good money after bad. And $100
million a year, compared to the U.N.'s annual budget of about $4
billion for development projects, is a piddling amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be better off opening CNN bureaus in all these countries
and hiring and training local people,'' Maren said. ``These are
permanent things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maren pointed out, too, that the United Nations is composed of
its member governments and cannot act against their will. Those
governments, he said, are often the cause of poverty and need to be
replaced, but instead they use aid to prop themselves up.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, not surprisingly, has a different view.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N., like any large institution, is overly bureaucratic,
but that does not justify inaction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving toward globalization,'' he said. ``We're in an
era where we have to play the international game. As the world's
sole superpower, we have to be engaged and be involved in the
United Nations. We need to show leadership. And we can't just do it
by dropping bombs on people. We've got to try to help them, too, or
else everybody else is going to be against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he is aware that, on a global scale, his gift is not
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred million is a very small amount,'' he said. ``We know
that. But maybe we can set an example. Maybe we can get other
people of great wealth to try the same thing. We're trying to do
kind of a pilot project here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the comparatively small size of the gift makes it all the
more important that the money be invested wisely, which he called
``a daunting task.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at the situation as hopeless, so let's just drink
a lot and go to Las Vegas and gamble,'' he said. ``Or we can roll
up our sleeves and try.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes the job so difficult, Wirth said, is the high
expectations he and others at the U.N. Foundation put on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What, at the end of the 10 years and $1 billion, would Wirth
consider evidence of success?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, if we found 20 other Ted Turners,'' he said. ``If we
had eliminated a couple of diseases, and we had developed a number
of other institutions like our own, elsewhere _ you know, if there
were a U.N. Foundation in Germany and Brazil and China and India.
If we had a strong constituency in the U.S. so that we paid off the
debt, and U.N. funding was something everybody agreed with. And if
we had on our board three or four very, very significant private
sector people who had really committed their institutions to trying
to get other private sector groups engaged, then that would be a
success.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a tall order and more, Wirth acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pull it off, it'll be terrific,'' he said. ``And you
know, we might pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
