<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-ART-720     01-06 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REURN TO THE ROUTINE OF DEMOCRACY, WITH GUARDED JOY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Neb., N.Y.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR, HOUSE-HASTERT,
HOUSE, CONGRESS-ETHICS, CONGRESS-NY and IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(ART ADV: Photo (NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all the impeachment foreboding washing about
the corridors of the Capitol Wednesday, the new Congress first
faced the vital routine of democracy and the unabashed joy of its
political survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the House reading clerk had to buck the celebratory
buzz of a fresh crop of winners waiting to be sworn in as he
dispatched one piece of business as just another routine bit of
congressional foolscap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without objection, the letter of resignation of the honorable
Newt Gingrich will be inserted in the record,'' the clerk rapidly
concluded. The floor chatter of happy political survivors
overwhelmed this postscript to the career of former speaker
Gingrich, the grand winner of the 1994 elections, now gone
completely from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revolution? What revolution?'' asked Rep. Peter King, smiling
gently at the once celebrated ``Gingrich revolution'' of 1994 as if
it dated to the sepia days of the Teapot Dome. King, like most
congressional survivors, threw a simple office party for himself
and his constituents. And on this wintry day of impeachment
anxieties, it became an occasion to consider some of the passing
wonders of politics as well as the fate of President Clinton
pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess democracy is just stronger than the people who take
part in it,'' the New York Republican said rather hopefully. ``It's
going to outlast all of us. Our country has amazing resilience.''
</P>
<P>
   National resilience was the patriotic watchword as both houses
offered an opening day of Breughelesque sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The laughter and wails of small children laced the House floor
as their beaming parents pledged their oath for a better nation.
Off the floor, the president's harshest critics continued to
propose that the Senate consider scrofulous hearsay tales in
documents in a House evidence room even though they received no
credit in the formal impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the Capitol's other half, the Senate chaplain, the Rev.
Lloyd Ogilvie, prayed above the lawmakers at the nation's ``awesome
moment.'' He beseeched the Almighty, ``Save them from the seduction
of human power.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators soon were offering one another serial standing ovations
of bipartisan applause, as if for Darwinian survival itself, as
they were sworn in to fresh terms in groups of four.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the corridors, a shadow of grim ritual impended as staff
experts announced the formal details of the Senate's impeachment
trial, down to the doorway Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist will
use as he arrives to preside. In a side room, news photographers
closed in on an inert oddity on a desk top: a pile of impeachment
trial tickets the public already is reported clamoring for.
</P>
<P>
   Returning senators told of being buttonholed furiously about the
trial by constituents. ``This has divided the country bitterly,''
said Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., exuding gloom at the uncertainties of
the trial. ``I wish people felt so strongly about other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the visitors gallery, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the
donnish New York Democrat, arrived for ``the meeting of the
eights'' _ a private bipartisan conference of 16 senators who
searched through the day for a workable trial procedure, struggling
into the very eve of the trial's opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the subject of witnesses, I'm arriving as the Federalist
man,'' Moynihan sprightly declared. He brandished a dog-earred
paperback copy of ``The Federalist Papers,'' ready to quote
Hamilton to the gathering. He did not hesitate to share some aloud
in the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most extraordinary things are being written about what
this new office of president will be,'' read the senator, obviously
savoring Hamilton's counsel across time. He had marked the founding
father's satirical, if now prescient, reference to critics'
warnings that Americans studying their presidents might some day
have ``to blush at the unveiled mysteries of a future seraglio.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the meeting of the eights, Moynihan closed the book and
spoke for himself. ``If we can just get a trial without
witnesses,'' he said, sounding near prayerful, ``We will take all
the time necessary. But we won't get into something the nation has
had enough of.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The opening day's smattering of public debate revealed one House
newcomer having trouble smartly pronouncing the word
``divisiveness.'' But fresh opportunities will undoubtedly arise,
according to the cautions from veterans about the ``poisonous
politics'' ever infecting the place. At dusk, partying House
members were interrupted for a roll-call vote to reappoint
Republican members who will be arguing the Senate case that Clinton
should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go from here?'' the new speaker, Dennis Hastert,
asked the House after the welcoming round of bipartisan applause
had passed. The simple question seemed poignant in the face of the
political wreckage the new Congress was inheriting from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully plain-spoken rather than fiery, Hastert took a moment
to remember a predecessor. ``Thank you, Newt,'' he said, looking up
as if into the political ether. ``Good luck and God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   King did not deny that he counted himself a happy survivor as he
played host at his re-election party. But he thought briefly of
Gingrich, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago Newt was literally Moses, the Messiah, whatever
_ he was everywhere,'' said King as he began his fourth term
sounding grateful to constituents but wary at the knife-edged ways
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``How harsh a business politics can be,'' King observed amid the
celebration's happy scene. ``And how unforgiving it can be. When
you're gone, you're gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
