<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1946 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-NY     01-06 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SALES UP AND MARKETS LIKE THAT DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn., Texas, Mass., Germany, Brazil)  DOLLAR UP, OIL UP, By GRETCHEN MORGENSON 
 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing but up. So said stock markets around the
world Wednesday, wowing investors with one-day gains of better than
2 percent and in some markets, more than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only three days old, 1999 already looks like a banner year for
equities. The Dow Jones industrial average has risen 3.96 percent.
The Nasdaq composite index, which gained just under 40 percent last
year is up 5.84 percent. Germany's benchmark DAX index has risen
8.28 percent, and the Bovespa index of Brazil, which was beaten
down in 1998, has leapt 7.97 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All the major U.S. stock gauges _ the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the
Nasdaq composite index and the Dow industrials _ are trading at
their highs. The Dow closed Wednesday at 9,544.97, up 1.8 percent
from its former peak of 9,374.27 on Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Driving this euphoria is a conviction among investors that
gloomy economic predictions have been overstated. ``It's a show-me
market,'' said John L. Manley Jr., senior equity strategist at
Salomon Smith Barney. ``Investors are saying, `We've been waiting
for this recession for so long now and it hasn't materialized.' Now
they're saying `Prove to me we're going into a recession or I'm
going to buy stocks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Early January jumps in stocks are not unusual. In 1988,
according to Birinyi Associates, a money management firm in
Greenwich, Conn., stocks rose 3.9 percent in the first day of
trading. In the first two days of 1987, stocks began the year up
3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that stock prices often rise in January is the
tendency among investors to change where they put their retirement
accounts when they open a new calendar. Although most can make
changes in their accounts any time, investors often decide to
switch investments with the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   The most common change is to shift more money into whatever
performed best during the previous year. It is likely then that
investors moving money around now are doing two things.
</P>
<P>
   First, they are probably increasing their holdings in technology
stocks, which dominate the Nasdaq Composite, and have given the
biggest boost to that index.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they are likely shifting money from funds that have
lagged behind the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 _ more than 90 percent of
actively managed funds underperformed their benchmarks last year _
into those like the Vanguard 500 that mirror this index.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of these changes can be found in the disparity early
this year in the performance of big company stocks, like those in
the S&AMP;P 500 and the Dow, the small company stocks in the Russell
2000 index. While the Dow Jones and the S&AMP;P 500 have both blown
through their former all-time highs, the Russell 2000 is still 7.7
percent below its peak of last July. The small-stock index is up
only 1.4 percent in 1999. Although Wednesday's advance in big
company stocks was fairly broad, it did not lift all boats. For
every two stocks that gained, one declined. IBM, for example, fell
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors contributed to the broad market rally. The
Commerce Department reported that sales of new homes rose in
November to a record high, indicating that the economy is strong
and demand for appliance, furniture and other consumer goods to
fill these houses will continue to be robust.
</P>
<P>
   Another lift came from oil prices, which rose more than 3
percent following the news that oil inventories in the United
States had taken their biggest decline in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher oil prices, while a pain in the neck for consumers, are
a positive for developing countries,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, chief
investment strategist at Advest Inc., in Boston. ``Anything that
tends to ease their financial stress is good for world markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The freefall in commodity prices, a sign of slow or negative
growth around the world, seems to have been stopped, leading some
investors to conclude that the worst of global economic turmoil is
behind us. The Commodity Research Bureau's index, which stood at
187 on Dec. 15, closed Wednesday at 197.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CRB was the last thing hanging out there that indicated a
problem in world economic growth,'' said James Paulsen, chief
investment office at Wells Capital Management in Minneapolis. But
firming commodity prices will also help U.S. corporations, Paulsen
argues, by allowing them to increase their prices and bolster their
profit margins. Companies have found it difficult to raise prices
in recent years, which has slowed earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Because corporate earnings felt the pinch of Asia's economic
woes in the first quarter of 1998, investors also suspect the first
quarter of this year will look good in comparison. For investors
who still care about old-fashioned things like earnings growth,
improvements from a year earlier usually translate into higher
stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   As stocks ran away Wednesday, some market strategists speculated
that the overall market had been infected by the fever that has
Internet stocks sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning? When investors are willing to pay 80 times
revenues for Amazon.com or 366 times sales for Ebay Inc., why not
push Microsoft shares to 64 times estimated earnings? That lofty
level seems cheap in comparison, even though it is three times the
historical market average.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks and bonds also benefitted Wednesday by a sharp rise in
the dollar against the Euro. That currency, in its first days of
trading, fell from 1.1720 against the dollar at the close of
trading in Europe to 1.1568. Traders said that when Euro traders in
Europe went home, a lot of the support for the currency
disappeared. When trading shifted to New York, the market started
to dip and found little support. With the dollar rising, the
Treasury market bounced as well, and bonds closed at their highs
for the day. The move in the dollar also gave a kick to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest propellant for stocks so far this year is the
explosive growth in the supply of money in the United States, a
factor that has contributed to higher stock prices for months.
Money supply is growing at an annualized rate of 11 percent, far
above what's needed to finance the growth in the nation's gross
domestic product. An enormous amount of the excess money is finding
its way into the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   This makes for an interesting dilemma for the Federal Reserve
Board, points out Ned Riley, chief investment officer of
BankBoston. ``The Fed has resurrected the irrational exuberance it
was trying to temper earlier,'' he said. ``The creation of all this
money and lower interest rates have tended to fuel more
speculation.'' The next meeting of the Fed's policy-making
committee, in February, ``is going to draw a lot of attention to
this speculative frothy market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nobody thinks the federal bank will change its stance on
interest rates, which is toward lower rates, not higher. As long as
the bank isn't going to step in and spoil the party by raising
rates, stocks will likely remain on a power trip.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many professional investors were puzzled by Wednesday's
move in stocks. Frederick E. Rowe Jr., head of Greenbrier Partners,
a money management firm in Dallas, echoed the views of many big
investors when he said: ``I don't pretend to understand it, but I
don't want to get in the way of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
