<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-GAYS07-COX     01-06 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-GAYS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passages on Nazi horrors deleted from school guide
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teaching students about the Holocaust, which the Georgia
Commission on the Holocaust has been doing since 1986, involves
putting some horrible, obscene facts before children in order that
they understand what can happen when hatred goes unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   So the commission's decision to delete two paragraphs about the
treatment of homosexual victims of the Nazis in a teacher guide
that is being distributed to middle and high school teachers around
the state, has created an uncomfortable but firm disagreement
between the commission and others who otherwise strongly support
the commission's work and goals.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm of Holland &AMP; Knight, which sponsored the
publication of the teacher guide in three states and is funding the
Georgia commission's student contest this year, disagreed with the
commission's opposition to the two paragraphs, but agreed to remove
them in a spirit of cooperation, said Steve Uhlfelder, managing
partner of the firm's Tallahassee office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if we were not dealing with a state commission that we
had agreed to work with, I would've basically not agreed to do
it,'' Uhlfelder said. The firm, which has a reputation for freedom
of press work and for donating time to the public good, insisted on
restoring the passages for later press runs of the 92-page guide
that went to Florida and San Francisco teachers, although it cost
his firm $14,000 to make the change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Equality Project, an advocacy group for gay,
lesbian, bisexual and transgendered political equality, admires the
work of the commission, said Harry Knox, director of the Equality
Project. But in this instance, he said after reading the passages
Wednesday, the commission made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language is horrifying,'' he said. ``But everything about
the Holocaust should horrify us. Erasing persecution of gays from
the history of the Holocaust repeats the tragic silence of most
Germans in the Nazi years. And it's a shame that children in
Georgia would be led to ignorance and silence by the Holocaust
Commission out of an apparent fear that Legislators will punish
them for telling the truth about gays under the Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Wygoda, director and chairperson of the Holocaust
Commission, insisted that the passages had to be removed. ``We felt
that it was our duty to inform the law firm that, number one, it
wasn't even necessary to the content of the book, and number two,
it is not our place to put sexually graphic material into the
schools.'' She said the fact that the commission receives almost
$210,000 a year from the Legislature had nothing to do with the
decision. ``This is a judgment we arrived at as educators,'' she
said. Although it is a teacher guide, she said the commission had
no way of knowing whether students would have access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Wygoda and Uhlfelder both had Jewish relatives killed in death
camps by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Triangles, Badges, &AMP; Stars: Remembering the Mosaic of Victims
of the Holocaust'' gives teachers passages from a variety of
writings on the theme of the variety of groups victimized by the
Holocaust. This is also the theme of this year's student writing
and art contest being held by the commission. In addition to Jews,
six million of whom were systematically murdered, the Nazis
targeted Gypsies, Jehovah's Witnesses, Communists, African-Germans,
the mentally and physically disabled and other groups of people,
including homosexual males.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuals are mentioned in at least four places that list
victim groups in the 6,000 copies of the guide printed for Georgia.
But the only two extended descriptions of their victimization were
deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Wygoda said the problem with the passages is strictly that
sexuality, even heterosexuality, has no place in the commission's
work when it is not age-appropriate for the classroom. She said the
decision was quite clear and non-controversial to the commission,
and she hoped it would not divert people's attention from the
important message of the dangers of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
