</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ZOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. PAUL M. ZOLL, 87; PIONEERED ELECTRICAL HEART STIMULANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Three dead brought back to life,'' said the headline
when it was announced that Dr. Paul M. Zoll had restarted the
hearts of three patients at Beth Israel Hospital through
noninvasive electrical stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like science fiction when the headline appeared in The
Boston Globe on Feb. 22, 1953, but the technique has now become an
accepted part of medical practice that has lengthened the lives of
millions of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul M. Zoll of Newton, the cardiologist whose research led
to the first defribrillators and pacemakers for failing hearts,
died of respiratory arrest Tuesday in Heathwood Rehabilitation and
Nursing Center in Newton. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Zoll was a clinical professor at Harvard Medical School and
a physician at Beth Israel Hospital for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dr. Seigo Izumo, director of cardiovascular research
at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, said Dr. Zoll was a
``revolutionary person'' who was the first to use electricity for
therapeutic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   He said Dr. Zoll's research also led to the development of the
electrocardiogram and made possible open heart surgery, which
requires the stopping the restarting of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Izumo, Dr. Zoll's work led the saving of
millions of lives.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Boston, he graduated from Boston Latin School,
Harvard College, and, in 1936, Harvard Medical School. He interned
at Beth Israel Hospital and at Bellevue Hospital in New York City.
He returned to Boston to join the medical research department at
Beth Israel in 1939. It was then that he started his work in
cardiology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973 he was a winner of the Albert Lasker Clinical Medical
Research Award, considered the leading scientific prize in this
country, for his many contributions in the treatment of heart
disease. A citation noted that his original and outstanding work
led to the development of the pacemaker, closed-chest
defibrillator, and cardiac monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The citation pointed out that he had demonstrated for the first
time in 1952 that when a human heart stops it can be induced by
electrical stimulation to resume beating. It went on to say:
``Pacemakers, which have saved tens of thousands from sudden and
unpredictable death, are Dr. Zoll's invention.
</P>
<P>
   ``One measure of the good that pacemakers have done and the need
there is for them is the fact that more than 60,000 Americans have
received pacemakers and an estimated 12,000 to 15,000 new
pacemakers are implanted annually.'' That was in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The citation also said: ``In addition, Dr. Zoll developed the
theory and technique of continuous cardiac monitoring of heart
rhythm, and was the first to apply this method clinically. The
coronary care unit now found in every well-equipped hospital is a
further development of this life-saving concept.''
</P>
<P>
   For his invention of the cardiac pacemaker, he also won the John
Scott Award of the City of Philadelphia, the Polytechnic/Wunsch
Prize in Biomedical Engineering, the Ray C. Fish Award, and the
Texas Heart Institute Medal.
</P>
<P>
   He was made a research fellow in medicine at Harvard Medical
School in 1941; served in the US Army Medical Corps in World War
II, first in the Aleutians and later as a cardiologist at an army
general hospital in England; became chief of the Cardiac Clinic at
the school in 1947; and assistant professor of medicine at the
school and visiting physician at Beth Israel Hospital, both in
1954.
</P>
<P>
   He also was made associate editor of the heart journal
Circulation in 1956 and wrote many articles for professional
journals, mostly on coronary heart disease and external electrical
stimulation of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, he founded Zoll Medical Corp., a pioneer in
the manufacturing of defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Ann (Blumgart); a son, Ross, of Connecticut;
and a daughter, Mary, of Newton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
