<HEADER>
A1963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STARR-430&AMP;ADD     01-06 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STARR-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCLOSURE OF INFORMATION ABOUT LEWINSKY WOULD NOT BE ILLEGAL,
STARR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, HOUSE-HASTERT,
HOUSE, CONGRESS-ETHICS, CONGRESS-NY and IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(js) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel Kenneth Starr told a
federal judge who is investigating his office for possible illegal
grand jury leaks that it would have been appropriate for him to
disclose to reporters information about negotiations with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in court papers released Wednesday by Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson of U.S. District Court, does not say whether he or
anyone in his office were the sources for news accounts last year
about his office's intense discussions with Ms. Lewinsky over
whether she would testify against President Clinton. But Starr
argued that to have done so would not have been illegal because the
negotiations with Ms. Lewinsky did not involve the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's chief lawyer in the leaks
investigation, responded in court papers by saying that Starr had
starkly changed his position. Kendall told Judge Johnson that Starr
had argued earlier that none of his office's operations could be
disclosed but took a new approach when confronted with evidence
that he or his aides had discussed the Lewinsky negotiations with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether Starr or someone in his office violated
federal laws prohibiting prosecutors from disclosing matters before
a grand jury has been raised forcefully by the White House as part
of its effort to discredit the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The White House received a major victory last September when
Judge Johnson ruled that 24 news accounts about the investigation
of Clinton appeared to show that prosecutors in Starr's office
repeatedly and knowingly violated federal law by leaking grand jury
testimony or other secret information.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Judge Johnson also appointed a special master to
investigate possible illegal leaks by the prosecutors. The master,
John W. Kern III, a former judge in the District of Columbia, was
given the power to seize and examine the prosecutors' telephone
records and logs along with their appointment calendars,
memorandums and other documents to determine whether they disclosed
information to the press.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what progress, if any, Kern has made, although he
was expected to report to Judge Johnson by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the public knowledge of the leak investigation
comes with a built-in time lag. Judge Johnson has generally sealed
documents in the case, only disclosing them selectively months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the batch of documents disclosed Wednesday reflect the
status of the case only as of Oct. 30.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The last significant development contained in the new batch is
Judge Johnson's rejection of Starr's appeal to her to reconsider
her September ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed on Oct. 15, Starr had argued that 15 of the 24
news accounts did not violate grand jury secrecy rules. He said
that eight of those news accounts concerned the negotiations
between his office and Ms. Lewinsky's lawyer at the time, William
Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The eight news accounts appeared in The New York Times, The
Washington Post and Newsweek, were broadcast on NBC and CNN and
variously attributed their information about the negotiations to
``prosecutors,'' ``one official'' and ``federal investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly, a press spokesman for Starr, said he could not
comment on the case because much of it is still under seal. He
declined to say if Starr or prosecutors in the office were, in
fact, the source of the eight stories.
</P>
<P>
   But Bakaly has said that ``This office does not disclose grand
jury material.''
</P>
<P>
   He has said that journalists have used information from sources
outside the independent counsel's office. ``The short of the matter
is this: We have at all times conducted ourselves in an appropriate
and ethical manner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had argued that some of the other news accounts concerned
evidence gathered outside the grand jury process, like Ms.
Lewinsky's stained dress, which was obtained during a search of her
apartment to which she consented.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Starr's request for reconsideration, Judge Johnson
has ruled that that the 24 news accounts constitute ``prima facie''
evidence of wrongdoing, leaving the burden on Starr and his fellow
prosecutors to show they were not the source of the articles and
broadcast accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Starr argued in court filings that 15 of the news
accounts could not be violations of grand jury secrecy. The
remaining nine news accounts were not addressed, although Starr has
argued that none involved violations of grand jury secrecy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
