<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LOTT-NYT     01-06 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP CHIEF WALKS TIGHTROPE IN IMPEACHMENT CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Sen. Trent Lott moves from meeting to meeting in
search of an elusive bipartisan plan for an impeachment trial, he
says he wants a formula that is fair to all and speedy enough to
sate a scandal-weary nation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican majority leader is driven by other concerns,
too. Lott is trying to balance the demands of many conservative
groups, including some back home in Mississippi, who want President
Clinton to suffer a long, embarrassing trial, against what's best
for the 19 Senate Republicans up for re-election in 2000, who could
be hurt by that approach.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Any conservative group that sees an advantage in a lengthy
trial is foolish,'' said Sen. Larry Craig of Idaho, the
fourth-ranking Senate Republican. ``If they've watched what most
perceived to be a conservative Congress' ratings plummet 25 points
in the last month, would you argue it's to our advantage to have a
lengthy process?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny seems to have gotten under Lott's skin. The
normally gregarious Mississippian has been dodging reporters this
week, leaving his office by back doors, and on Tuesday he read a
statement to reporters but refused to answer any questions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Lott sounded defensive in attacking those who are
already asking whether he is up to the task.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before has so much been reported about what I was
thinking, doing or saying when I said so little,'' Lott said on the
Senate floor. ``I've been accused of holing up in my hometown of
Pascagoula, Mississippi. Where would you expect me to be during the
holidays?''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Lott sounded petulant, he had good reason. With impeachment's
fallout having already incinerated House Speaker Newt Gingrich and
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston, Lott is stepping carefully to avoid
becoming the next casualty in the impeachment minefield.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise he floated as a trial balloon to avert a lengthy
trial has been shot down by his own rank-and-file, and now Lott is
trying to pick up the pieces in the greatest test of his leadership
since he was elected majority leader in 1996.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's attempting to do what you have to do as a majority
leader, which is to keep the train on the tracks,'' said Sen. Judd
Gregg, R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Lott appears motivated both by duty and by pragmatism.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our duty is clear, to demonstrate anew our national commitment
to justice and fair play,'' Lott said Wednesday. ``That is what the
public expects from us regardless of their individual opinions
concerning the president.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lott's unusually close consultations with Sen. Tom Daschle of
South Dakota, the Democratic minority leader, reflect the majority
leader's desire to avoid the partisan battles that plagued the
impeachment proceedings in the House.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to our advantage to make sure that this is a fair,
non-partisan process,'' said Craig. ``That's where we win.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To help advise him, Lott this week hired Michael Wallace, a
Mississippi lawyer and former law clerk to Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, to be special counsel during the impeachment trial.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with phone calls to senators from his home over the
holidays, to the parade of senators trooping to his Capitol office
this week, to Wednesday's back-to-back meetings with all 55 Senate
Republicans, Lott has been discussing with colleagues a compromise,
crafted in part by his confidant, Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., that
he never publicly endorsed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing exactly what a leader should do,'' said Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who voiced her objections about the plan
to Lott at the Cotton Bowl football game in Dallas on New Year's
Day. ``He started with a proposal, wanted input on that, and is now
getting ready for modifications.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there are also practical reasons why Lott is gently trying
to steer his colleagues to set limits on a Senate trial. Lott
doesn't believe there are the 67 votes the Constitution requires to
remove Clinton, his confidants say.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lott was chastened by the November elections, and vowed to give
the public real legislative results, colleagues say. A lengthy
trial with numerous witnesses could bottle up his legislative
agenda and even imperil Republicans' hold on the Senate, and with
it, his job.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent is a very ordered person,'' said Clark Reed, the dean of
the Mississippi Republican Party. ``Chaos is not his thing.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Lott promised that the Senate would not grind to
halt just because the first impeachment trial in 130 years is
underway. He ticked off goals to increase military spending, shore
up Social Security and revamp the budget process.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have responsibilities that go forward, and we will do our
very best to have a dual-track,'' Lott said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But unlike in the House, where the rank-and-file typically fall
in line behind their party leaders, senators are a more independent
breed who often bridle and bolt when their leaders try to rein them
in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's first among equals and he's trying to establish a
consensus,'' said Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore. ``But that's one of the
perils of being the majority leader. It's like herding cats.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
