<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TOUTS $76 BILLION BUDGET SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton declared the era of budget
deficits over Wednesday as he unveiled new projections forecasting
a $76 billion surplus for the current fiscal year and urged
Congress to let nothing stand in the way of work on Social Security
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton touted the budget surplus as Congress convened a new
session that will focus on an impeachment trial on charges arising
from the president's affair with a former White House intern.
Clinton, however, did not mention the pending trial, instead
calling on the 106th Congress to focus its priorities on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I am proud to announce that we can say the era of big
deficits is over. We are now entering the second year of an era of
surpluses,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus for the 1999 fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, would
be only the second in three decades and likely will be revised
several times through the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics took issue with the bookkeeping by both the
White House and Congress that continues to forecast budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The Concord Coalition, a nonpartisan group advocating fiscal
restraint, maintained there would still be a deficit for the 1999
fiscal year. It contends the deficit is covered up because the
White House and Congress use the surplus in the Social Security
fund to paper over the red ink.
</P>
<P>
   The Concord Coalition reported the government would actually
have a deficit of $40 billion for 1999, a larger amount than the
$29 billion for fiscal year 1998. The Social Security fund
currently has a surplus of $117 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Security program is legally and officially
off-budget, and the time has come for that fact to be reflected in
the public announcements by the political leadership of both
parties,'' said Martha Phillips, Concord Coalition executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   However, those Social Security surpluses are expected to
evaporate in the next 30 years as the system plunges into
bankruptcy unless steps are taken.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly has called on Congress not to spend the
annual federal budget surpluses until it saves Social Security from
going broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must save Social Security for the 21st century, before we
consider new spending or other tax cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said last year he would make saving Social Security a
priority. He used his 1998 State of the Union to highlight the
issue. He attended two Social Security events where experts
discussed options. He also intends to appoint a commission to
review alternatives and wants Congress to enact some changes this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot use anything as an excuse not to deal with our most
pressing priorities,'' Clinton said. ``I do not intend to do it; I
do not think the American people expect us to do it, and I think
that we will surprise the skeptics by dealing with the Social
Security challenge over the next several months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
