<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-CHRISTIAN-AGENDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coalition will try to reinstate anti-sodomy law
 &HT;    By Kathy Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Christian Coalition leaders say they'll probably have to
amend the state Constitution to do it, but they're making a push to
reinstate Georgia's anti-sodomy law one of their priorities for the
upcoming legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Re-enacting the law, which the state Supreme Court this fall
struck down as unconstitutional, is among a list of familiar items
the coalition is pushing as lawmakers converge on the Capitol next
week. Leading Democratic lawmakers have vowed to oppose those
moves, and Republican Party leaders say they won't actively push
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition tapped a familiar figure to lead their charge.
Rep. Ron Crews (R-Tucker), who lost his seat in the November
elections, has accepted a paid position as the coalition's
legislative director. Crews, a minister and six-year lawmaker, was
one of the strongest legislative allies for social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   During a Wednesday press conference, Crews and coalition
chairwoman Sadie Fields blamed negative campaigning, in Georgia and
nationally, for turning off many conservatives. But they downplayed
predictions that the election outcome will make lawmakers less
receptive to their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pendulum swings one way one time and one way the next,''
Crews said. ``I don't think that necessarily represents turning
away from the traditional pro-family values I hold...and the
families of the state hold. Those values remain intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's legislative wish list, includes passage of the
''women's right to know'' act to provide graphic information about
abortion before the procedure is performed; strengthening of the
1997 ban on so-called partial-birth abortions coalition members say
was gutted by state settlement of a federal lawsuit; and
legislation to make instruction on ``the responsibilities and
sacrifices of marriage'' a part of the high school character
curriculum. Repealing the driver's license fingerprint requirement,
expanding school choice for at-risk students and providing tax
relief round out the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
