<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CAESAREAN-RISK-AR     01-06 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CAESAREAN-RISK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR LEADING DOCTORS CHALLENGE EFFORT TO REDUCE RATE OF CAESAREAN
BIRTHS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four leading childbirth specialists in Boston are challenging
the federal government's goal to reduce the rate of Caesarean
births, saying that the effort could in fact be endangering some
mothers and their babies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services,
concerned about unnecessary surgery and health care costs, set a
goal to reduce the national Caesarean rate to 15 percent by 2000.
At the time, 23.5 percent of babies were delivered by Caesarean
section. The current rate hovers around 21 percent, down from a
high of 25 percent in 1988 but still way above the 5 percent rate
in 1970 and not likely to reach 15 percent anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston experts, who published their views as an opinion
article in Thursday's issue of The New England Journal of Medicine,
fear that economic forces are driving efforts to reduce the number
of operative deliveries without sufficient study of how a lower
rate of Caesareans would affect the well-being of mothers and
babies in different situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption that lowering the Caesarean section rate would
reduce costs and represent better care is too simplistic,'' said
Dr. Benjamin P. Sachs, chief of obstetrics and gynecology at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center and chief author of the journal
paper. ``To go above the current rate is probably unacceptable, but
if we're going to go below that, we have to have a monitoring
system and safeguards in place to assure the safety of mothers and
babies. Quality of care, not costs, should matter first and
foremost.''
</P>
<P>
   His collaborator, Dr. Frederic Frigoletto, chief of obstetrics
at the Massachusetts General Hospital, said, ``We should begin by
identifying what the rate should be for given conditions _ multiple
births, breech presentation, diabetes in the mother, etc. We need
data to determine this so we can establish rates based on the best
outcomes, not rates set by bureaucrats with economically driven
motives.''
</P>
<P>
   The other collaborators on the paper were Dr. Cindy Kobelin of
the Beth Israel medical center, and Dr. Mary Ames Castro of
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs and his colleagues agree that a vaginal delivery is better
and cheaper than an operative one, ``but only if it is safe.'' For
example, they said, the use of vacuum extraction to assist in cases
of difficult labor results in brain bleeding in 6 percent of
births.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on the views of Sachs and his colleagues, Dr.
Roger Freeman, an obstetrician and perinatologist at Long Beach
Memorial Hospital in California, agreed that in some cases,
hospitals had ``gone too far'' in trying to bring down Caesarean
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said, however, that there was clearly room for
improvement. He pointed out, for example, that in low-risk
patients, ``there is great variability in the Caesarean rate _ from
a low of 5 percent to a high of 40 percent _ from doctor to doctor,
hospital to hospital and region to region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This tells me,'' he said, ``there is probably an opportunity
to lower the rate of Caesareans, at least among ordinary low-risk
patients. But what that rate should be, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Department of Health and Human Services,
Damon Thompson, told The Associated Press that the 15 percent goal
was based on consultation with hundreds of groups, and was only a
target, not a quota. Thompson said studies had shown that hospitals
could lower the C-section rate without compromising safety.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 percent goal, established in the report Healthy People
2000, grew out of concern that far too many operative deliveries
were being performed in this country, often for reasons not
medically justifiable, like the convenience of the doctor or the
pregnant woman. These reasons added to an already rising rate
prompted by the growing use of fetal monitoring during labor.
Monitors reveal when a fetus' health and survival are being
jeopardized by letting labor continue toward a vaginal delivery,
but they also sometimes falsely indicate difficulties, prompting
Caesarean deliveries that turn out to have been medically
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, obstetricians facing skyrocketing malpractice costs
and lawsuits when a delivery went awry, increasingly began
practicing defensive medicine. Rather than take a chance that a
baby would be injured during a difficult vaginal delivery _ for
example, one that required forceps _ many doctors elected to
perform Caesareans when faced with the slightest doubt about the
baby's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care companies are playing a major role in current
efforts to reduce the rate of Caesarean births, which usually
result in higher hospital and physician costs than a simple vaginal
delivery. While agreeing that vaginal births were generally safer
and cheaper, Sachs and his colleagues said that growing pressures
to avoid Caesareans were resulting in some ill-advised efforts at a
vaginal delivery that often end up costing far more than a
Caesarean and risk the health of mother and baby. They expressed
particular concern about pressures on doctors to encourage every
woman who has had a previous Caesarean delivery to try a vaginal
birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the woman's uterus ruptures, which happens in 1 percent of
these cases, the mom hemorrhages and may need a hysterectomy and
the baby may end up brain-damaged or dead,'' Sachs said. Even if
the baby is OK, he said, the costs would be much greater than if a
Caesarean had been performed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce L. Flamm, an obstetrician-gynecologist at the
Kaiser-Permanente Medical Center in Riverside, Calif., said that
``the cheapest way would be to operate electively in every case,
not that I'm an advocate of more Caesareans.'' Flamm explained that
in calculating the costs of vaginal versus operative deliveries,
experts often failed to take into account the time a woman having a
vaginal delivery spent in the hospital in labor.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors now stand in the way of a sharp reduction in the
Caesarean rate. One is the growing number of women having medically
assisted multiple pregnancies resulting in high-risk births and
those having first babies late in life. Older women are more likely
to encounter difficulties in labor and to have underlying medical
conditions that warrant an operative delivery. In addition, they
and their doctors tend to be less willing to risk fetal injury
during a vaginal delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anxiety definitely plays a part in the decision to do a
Caesarean,'' Sachs said. ``If a woman is having her first child at
46, neither she nor her doctor is willing to take any chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
