A1978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-JEWS-2TAKES-NY     01-06 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JEWS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S `WHO IS A JEW' PERENNIAL SPROUTS ANEW
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The chief judge of the Jerusalem district court
struck a profound nerve last week with a ruling that undermined the
overarching power of the Orthodox Chief Rabbinate to determine who
is a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   The judge compelled the Israeli government to accept and
register as Jews people who had been converted to Judaism in Israel
by Reform or Conservative rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion issue had been sitting on a shelf in Parliament
all year, but the judge's action provoked the religious faction
there to take it down and dust it off.
</P>
<P>
   What the religious parties want to do is to codify in law the
rabbinate's exclusive authority over conversions _ at a moment when
many Israelis are bridling at the rabbinate's exclusive control
over rituals like marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether Parliament will act now on a conversion
bill or will delay a vote until a new Parliament is elected in May.
But what is clear is that there is a pattern of outright combat
involving the courts, the religious parties and the Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling after ruling, the courts are striking at the power and
the privileges of the rigorously Orthodox. After each ruling, the
strong religious factions in the Parliament seek to restore that
power through legislation. And each punch and counterpunch
reawakens the unresolved culture war that episodically rends the
fabric of Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ferocity of the battle, many believe that it can only
end in a showdown in which Israel will be forced to reconcile the
contradictions of being the Jewish homeland and a secular
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Some predict that a popular backlash against the new political
power of the strictly Orthodox will find expression in laws that
disentangle religion and state to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the increasing political power in the hands of
the Orthodox and ultra-Orthodox, you're seeing a confrontation
pushing Israel in the direction of getting the government somewhat
out of the business of religion,'' Rabbi Ismar Schorsch, chancellor
of the Jewish Theological Seminary in New York, said in an
interview in Israel this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, the decisions have tumbled fast and
furious from the Israeli courts. In addition to the conversion
decision, the courts have recently ordered the inclusion of Reform
and Conservative representatives on the powerful municipal
religious councils; declared the army service exemptions of
strictly Orthodox yeshiva students to be illegal, and ruled that
kibbutz shops could be open for business on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   And in each case the religious parties have moved to block the
court's rulings, sometimes with not only the backing but the direct
assistance of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Some here have likened the conflict to the dueling between
Congress and the Supreme Court in the United States over issues
like civil rights and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this the lesson one recalls from American history?''
asked Rabbi Uri Regev, a leader of the Reform movement here. ``A
recalcitrant Congress motivated by less than noble considerations
and a court that emerges as the beacon of light and defender of
civil liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   But here the core issue, the relationship between religion and
state, is central to the identity of the country and of modern
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   It rubs at two key frictions _ that between secular and
religious Israelis and that between different kinds of practicing
Jews: the observant but modern, be they Reform, Conservative or
Orthodox, and those who dedicate their lives to strict observance
of centuries-old Jewish laws.
</P>
<P>
   By their very existence, the courts are a threat to the strictly
Orthodox when they rule on religious matters. The laws they
interpret are secular and not religious, and the principles that
they uphold are democratic and not theocratic.
</P>
<P>
   But an active court, like the Supreme Court under Chief Justice
Aharon Barak, is particularly offensive to religious purists
because, in their view, it seeks to mandate a reconciliation of the
irreconcilable. Strictly Orthodox Jews think that submitting
Judaism to a civil liberties test subverts the essence of the
religion. They believe Judaism to be built on God-given rules that
should not be bent. To the strictly Orthodox, Judaism is both a
privilege and a yoke. They see beauty in rigid observance of Jewish
law, or halacha, even or especially when obedience is taxing.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel misunderstood in what they see as their belief in
standards, which leads them to consider Reform and Conservative
Judaism a dilution of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The modern Jew understands why in baseball the base paths
cannot be shortened for the slow runners and the outfield fences
brought in for weaker hitters,'' Jonathan Rosenblum, an Orthodox
intellectual, wrote in The Jerusalem Post, ``but not why anyone
should ever be told they are not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is important; it rules are sacrosanct. Judaism
isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the strictly Orthodox view, only rabbinical leaders are
qualified to issue rulings that affect Jewish life. And secular
judges like Barak personify what the strictly Orthodox see as
incomprehension of Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is a secular democracy with secular laws, but it is
vastly different from the United States. Clearly, for instance, the
relationship between religion and state is an inherently cozy one,
given the fact that citizenship is automatically granted to any
Jew. It is one that few Israelis would want completely disengaged.
</P>
<P>
   What the courts have been trying to do is define and refine the
boundaries as the Orthodox and ultra-Orthodox have used their
growing political power to assert a greater role for religion and
to demand privileges like state-subsidized religious education.
</P>
<P>
   The army issue is the one that most stirs the secular Israeli
public. Many resent a system that not only exempts 30,000 strictly
Orthodox teen-agers from the mandatory three-year service, but also
pays their yeshiva bills while university students are left to
finance their own educations.
</P>
<P>
   To most Israelis the conversion issue is more abstract, and most
are unfamiliar with Reform and Conservative Judaism. But here and
especially in the diaspora, that issue has most galvanized the
religious community, because it touches directly on its concern
about who can and should be called a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Schorsch flew to Israel this week specifically to lobby
Parliament on what he considers ``a supremely important matter.''
American Reform Jews placed a quarter-page advertisement in
Wednesday's New York Times warning the Israeli Parliament,
``History will be your judge.''
</P>
<P>
   And a coalition of liberal groups here began a ``Freedom of
Religion in Israel'' campaign this week with its own newspaper
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Following Supreme Court rulings, the government has been
accepting as Jews those who were converted to Judaism abroad by
Reform or Conservative rabbis, then immigrated here.
</P>
<P>
   But a surge of immigration from former Soviet republics and
Ethiopia, including many non-Jewish relatives, forced the country
to deal with conversions in Israel too.
</P>
<P>
   Many turned to the Reform and Conservative synagogues for
conversion, only to find their conversions invalid in the eyes of
the government, which grants a good deal of control over religious
affairs to the Orthodox chief rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The strictly Orthodox see Reform and Conservative conversions as
``quickies,'' or as some put it, ``snip and dunk'' conversions that
ask little more than circumcision from the men and immersion in a
ritual bath from the women.
</P>
<P>
   But their basic complaint is with the more liberal movements
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about converts who underwent a conversion
process by Reform `rabbis' who themselves are prepared to betroth
single-sex couples and mixed Jewish and Christian couples,'' one of
Israel's two chief rabbis, Yisrael Meir Lau, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   A series of lawsuits drew attention to the issue two years ago.
The courts and Parliament agreed to back off while a government
commission tried to find a compromise solution.
</P>
<P>
   But the compromise _ the creation of a conversion institute with
Reform, Conservative and Orthodox teachers, whose graduates would
be judged by the Orthodox religious courts _ was deemed
unacceptable by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The situation remained frozen until the chief judge of Jerusalem
ruled last week, ordering the government to register as Jews 23
immigrants who had undergone Reform or Conservative conversions,
some in Israel and some abroad. The issue is due to go before the
Supreme Court in February.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis say the courts have proceeded gingerly on
decisions affecting religious issues, not compelling government
action until it became clear that the government would not act on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the army exemptions, for instance, the Supreme
Court asked Parliament to make the next move.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that the conflict is heading toward some kind
of denouement, in which the relationship between religion and state
could be altered.
</P>
<P>
   On a grass-roots level, for instance, many Israelis are
beginning to demand the legalization of civil weddings, which are
not recognized by the government.
</P>
<P>
   If the coming elections bring in a centrist or leftist
government, the strength of the religious parties could be hobbled
and the edge could be taken off these issues. Court decisions would
certainly not face the same opposition from the government.
</P>
<P>
   But close observers of religion and society here say the
passions raised are too deep-seated to be resolved easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see here is a clash between two codes, between Jewish
law and Western law,'' said Avirama Golan, a religion writer for
the newspaper Haaretz. ``Can we solve it? I don't know. It's a test
for us. But I'm not sure we're able to live in a normal state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
