<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SETTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS OF LOST DOLLARS LATER, NBA PLAYERS AND OWNERS SETTLE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ National Basketball Association players and owners
brought to an end the most calamitous and costly labor dispute in
league history, agreeing to an 11th-hour deal that saved the
1998-99 season from termination and perhaps the sport from
incalculable ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating for 12 hours and trading concessions until 6 a.m.
Wednesday morning at the league offices in Manhattan, NBA
Commissioner David Stern and Billy Hunter, the union executive
director, led a group of six people in hashing out a seven-year
collective bargaining agreement that ended the 194-day lockout.
</P>
<P>
   An abbreviated regular season of 52 games is expected to begin
Feb. 2 with a full compliment of playoffs beginning in early May.
The regular season could be extended one to two weeks, but the
playoffs will not spill over into July.
</P>
<P>
   Training camps and the signing of 200 free agents will not begin
until Jan. 18, when the deal is expected to be reduced to writing
by lawyers. The 30 regular season games lost translate total player
salary losses to about $400 million, and leaguewide revenue losses
were also huge.
</P>
<P>
   In divvying up $2 billion in annual revenue _ the crux of their
disagreement the past six months _ the league achieved its primary
goal of containing the contracts of high-salaried players and the
union significantly bettered the economic position of its middle
class, it's stated No. 1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   They split their differences in total revenue percentages, with
the union receiving 55 percent in the last three years of the deal.
The feeling among some of the union membership was that the players
had given in to many of the league's demands at the last possible
moment, but that some major concessions were achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the NBA came perilously close to becoming the first
major sports league to lose an entire season to labor strife after
having never lost a game to work stoppage in 52 seasons, few
considered Wednesday morning's surprise announcement anything but
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call at 6 a.m. in my hotel room this morning and I
couldn't believe it,'' the free agent center Joe Kleine said. ``We
will finally play again. Now we have a bigger job ahead of us:
getting our fans back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleine was one of 179 players who came to Manhattan the day
after Hunter said he would put the owners' final offer to a vote of
the general membership, a development that created major disruption
and near chaos in the union, as players flocked to New York unsure
of the parameters surrounding a vote.
</P>
<P>
   But after Hunter asked one of the union's outside counsels to go
over to the league's offices at 6 p.m. Wednesday night to meet with
the deputy commissioner Russ Granik and present several concessions
to the league, the bargaining began.
</P>
<P>
   The league announced that its labor relations committee had
unanimously approved the deal. The agreement was also approved
Wednesday by the membership of the union, upon the unanimous
recommendation of its negotiating committee, by a vote of 174-5.
Details will not be released until after the league ratifies the
agreement at its board of governors meeting Thursday at 11 a.m. at
a Manhattan hotel, but apparently both sides had their key concerns
met in the wee hours of Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we blink?'' Hunter asked rhetorically. ``I guess we both
blinked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the agreement to be ratified by the Board of
Governors at tomorrow's meeting,'' said David Stern in a prepared
statement ``I have agreed with Billy Hunter that I will not discuss
the agreement in detail until after its approval by the board. I
will say that I am elated that we will be playing basketball this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating secretly in a conference room at the league's
Olympic Tower offices, the two sides gave each other a list of
their desires. When they came across a disagreement, Hunter said,
they moved on.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE TO COME)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
