<SLUG> BC-NEW-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
106TH CONGRESS OPENS AS CLINTON TRIAL LOOMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 106th Congress opened Wednesday with new
pledges of bipartisanship, but the impeachment trial of President
Clinton threatened to upset the cooperative tone that new House
Speaker Dennis Hastert tried to set on his first day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks following his formal election as speaker, the
Illinois Republican told lawmakers that he wanted the 106th
Congress to be remembered for its accomplishments rather than the
partisan bickering that so divided the last House.
</P>
<P>
   So he called on Republicans and Democrats alike to put aside
their ill feelings over the impeachment proceedings and go to work
on ``the people's business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions to problems cannot be found in a pool of bitterness.
They can be found in an environment in which we trust one another's
word,'' Hastert said, adding that it was long past time for members
to ``respect one another.''
</P>
<P>
   His plea for more civility from members followed an earlier
appeal from House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., for more
cooperation between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's bury the hatchet,'' he told Hastert as he handed over
the gavel during the traditional swearing-in ceremony for the new
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put to rest the poisonous politics which have infected
this place,'' Gephardt added.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by the leaders drew a standing ovation from the
lawmakers assembled in the chamber along with family and friends
for their own swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But less than two hours later, the spirit of bipartisanship gave
way to divisiveness as the House moved on to one of its first
chores of the new year _ approving a resolution naming House
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and several of his
GOP colleagues as managers of the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   While Hyde argued that the managers, who will serve as
prosecutors, would ensure that fairness prevails and the ``rule of
law'' is upheld in the Senate trial, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Texas, contended that appointing managers would merely ``give
credence to the partisanship of this impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 221-197 that appointed the managers broke down along
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Like the House, the Senate also opened for business Wednesday
with with swearing-in ceremonies for 34 new or re-elected senators.
But the normally celebratory spirit of the occasion was also marred
somewhat by the turmoil surrounding the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his address following his formal re-election as Majority
Leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he was hopeful that impeachment
proceedings could be completed in reasonable time and without
upsetting regular business.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that the seriousness of the matter could
preoccupy the chamber for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our responsibilities under the Constitution and we
will meet those responsibilities in an orderly fashion,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott went on to outline a legislative agenda similar to that
offered by Hastert in his swearing-in speech. Both Republican
leaders said they wanted Congress to concentrate on preserving
Social Security, improving education, boosting defense spending and
reducing taxes over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impeachment controversy, many Republicans still
insist that Congress can get back to work in a bipartisan way.
House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, even predicted
in a recent interview that Clinton would be cooperative in dealing
with the Republican-controlled Congress on Social Security and
other important legislative matters because ``all of us still want
to put the business of the American people first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I will be surprised if any of this carries over into
the substantive issues,'' Archer said, adding that he hopes to
continue work on tax matters and other issues with the full
cooperation of his Democratic colleagues on the Ways and Means
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that we didn't get much accomplished (in the
105th Congress) because we were so focused on the impeachment
proceedings,'' Rep. Kevin Brady, R-Texas, said recently. ``But now
we won't be able to use impeachment as an excuse not to get
something done.''
</P>
<P>
   That was clearly Hastert's hope as he broke with tradition and
delivered his opening remarks from the well of the House rather
from the lofty perch of the speaker's chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am breaking tradition this once,'' he said, appealing for
more cooperation among members, ``because my legislative home is
here on the floor with you, and so is my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on his colleagues from both sides of the aisle to
focus less on politics and more on producing major legislation,
saying he would be ready to meet his Democratic counterparts
``halfway'' in order to compromise on difficult issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stalemate is not an option,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of bipartisanship, Hastert was sworn in by Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., the senior member of the House. Minutes
later, the new speaker administered the oath to the other 221
Republicans along with the 211 Democrats and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   The House is still one member short because of the retirement of
former Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga. A special election will be held
soon to select a replacement for Gingrich, who resigned in the wake
of GOP election losses in November.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to approving the prosecutors for the impeachment
trial, the House also passed a change in the gift ban rule that
will allow members and their aides to accept free meals and other
gifts under limited circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The change will make the rules governing House members the same
as the those that senators are required to observe. The new rule
will allow noncash gifts up to $50. The old House rules barred
members from accepting any free gifts or meals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
