<SLUG> BC-BIOGEN-MULLEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES C. MULLEN TO BECOME BIOGEN PRESIDENT, CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Biogen Inc. Wednesday called James C. Mullen, a 10-year
company veteran, back from Paris to be its president and chief
operating officer and, potentially, its next chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, 40, had headed the Cambridge-based biotechnology giant's
European operations since 1996. The appointment follows the abrupt
resignation of chief executive James Tobin on Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, 54, said he resigned over an unspecificed conflict with
Biogen's longtime board chairman and former chief executive, James
L. Vincent, 59, who has since served as interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent repeated Wednesday that he plans to remain in that job
for at least a year, but that Mullen is a front-runner to take over
after that. ``He certainly is leading the pack,'' Vincent said. ``I
think Jim will move in and take over responsibility at this company
in a very short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mullen, who had been vice president, international, and
based in Paris, had been tapped already by Vincent and Tobin to
return to Cambridge later this year as chief operating officer, a
post vacant since Tobin was elevated from it in 1997 to chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been working on this game plan for the last six to
eight months. We were going to be implementing it four or five
months from now,'' Vincent said. Along with Mullen's promotion
Wednesday, Biogen also named five new vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, despite his youth, described himself in a brief phone
interview Wednesday as ``one of the older guys on the management
team,'' familiar with most facets of Biogen's business.
</P>
<P>
   He said the organizational changes are designed to deal with
growth from ``a company that had gone from no sales only a few
years ago to $600 million to $700 million, as we add products to go
into the multibillion-dollar range.''
</P>
<P>
   Biogen reported sales of $389.2 million for the first nine
months of 1998, following full-year sales of $411.9 million in
1997. A First Call Corp. analyst survey last November reported an
average earnings estimate for 1998 of $1.80 per share, versus $1.17
in earnings for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen joined Biogen in 1989 as director of facilities and
engineering. He was promoted to vice president for operations in
1992 and was responsible for opening manufacturing operations in
Cambridge and in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Named vice president, international in 1996, he was stationed in
Paris and responsible for introducing Biogen's flagship drug for
multiple sclerosis, Avonex, to the European market _ a job that
thrust him into marketing and regulatory affairs roles.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen shares leapt 2 points Wednesday after Mullen's promotion
was announced, but ended the day on Nasdaq at 80 5/16, down 1/4.
Donald Stone, an analyst at Cowen &AMP; Co. in Boston, said these
fluctuations meant little, and called the appointment ``a positive
(that) resolves the uncertainty investors faced in not knowing who
was going to run the company.''
</P>
<P>
   While describing Biogen as on a solid business course, some
analysts said the company, and Mullen, must be prepared to deal
with Vincent's strong personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that this will be a permanent choice,'' Viren
Mehta, of Mehta Partners in New York, said. But, Mehta added,
``This will require an adjustment on both their parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News Wednesday reported Vincent confirmed that Tobin
had told the Biogen board, on Dec. 11, that he intended to resign
if Vincent, who had earlier indicated plans to retire, remained
with the company any longer. The board sided with Vincent.
</P>
</TEXT>
