<HEADER>
A1997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JOHNSON-2TAKE     01-06 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JOHNSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS AND THEATER IN THE OTHER IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR,
HOUSE-HASTERT, HOUSE, CONGRESS-ETHICS, CONGRESS-NY and
IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the hottest ticket to the biggest show in town, a pink
piece of pasteboard about the size of a dollar bill but worth much
more that fevered spring of 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admit the Bearer,'' it read in feathery script, to the
impeachment of the president of the United States, Andrew Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of three months, as the snows of the capital's
harsh winter gave way to spring flowers and the typically combative
Johnson kept a quiet vigil in the White House, the coveted tickets
were doled out, day by day, for seats in the airless galleries of
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The draw was a dramatic political spectacle, as much high
theater as a political stumble in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Like today's impeachment trial of Bill Clinton _ only the second
presidential impeachment in the country's history _ the trial of
Andrew Johnson posed unique procedural and constitutional questions
for the Congress. The Senate, the chief justice of the Supreme
Court, and the impeachment managers from the House of
Representatives all gingerly picked their way through uncharted
constitutional territory.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Johnson ultimately survived the ordeal, holding onto his
presidency by a one-vote margin in the Senate vote on May 16, after
37 days of speeches and testimony stretched from March to mid-May.
But his trial, conducted partly behind locked doors and partly in
public on the stage of the Senate chamber, changed the course of
reconstruction after the Civil War, held official Washington in
thrall and recalibrated the balance of power between Congress and
the executive.
</P>
<P>
   What saved Johnson, many historians say, were smart lawyers, a
pretty good case on legal grounds and the fact that some Republican
senators who started out undecided eventually allowed themselves to
be swayed by the defense arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear most senators wanted the impeachment to be a
serious event and took it very seriously,'' said Michael Les
Benedict, a political scientist at Ohio State University who has
written a book about the Johnson impeachment. Both houses, however,
had been at constant war with the president since he took office on
the death of Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   A politician who presented himself as the defender of the common
man, Johnson had risen from the post of a Democratic city alderman
in Tennessee to a seat in the House. Alone among southern
congressmen, he remained there after the secession of the
confederate states. Lincoln, a Republican, made him his
vice-presidential candidate on a Union ticket. But once he became
president in 1865, Johnson broke with the Republicans, chiefly over
how to treat the defeated South. The Radical faction within the
party wanted the confederate states kept out of the Union until
they guaranteed full civil and voting rights to freed slaves.
Moderate and conservative Republican factions had similar views,
although they did not go as far as the Radicals.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sided with the Democratic minority, in favor of swift
reunification of the country without conditions on the southern
states. House Republicans in 1867 twice tried to impeach him, but
were foiled by internal party squabbles. They jumped at the chance
again in late February 1868, when Johnson dismissed Secretary of
War Edwin M. Stanton, a close ally of the Radical Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   After only three days of debate, the House voted 126-47 to
impeach.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 articles of impeachment written after the vote , the House
majority accused Johnson of violating the Tenure of Office Act,
which had passed over the president's veto the year before. The law
barred the president from firing any government official who had
been appointed with congressional advise and consent. Some of the
articles also charged Johnson had shown disrespect to the Congress
in speeches and comments.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, the Senate was sworn in as a court to hear the
impeachment case and issued a summons to Johnson to appear the next
week _ a Friday the 13th, as it happened.
</P>
<P>
   An illustrator for Harper's Weekly (``Journal of Civilization,''
the magazine called itself) imagined how the scene played out when
the Senate's sergeant-at-arms called on the president. In the
drawing, Johnson, clean-shaven and dressed in a dark waistcoat,
wears a characteristically dour expression. Top hat in his hand,
the official hands him the summons. Johnson, it was reported at the
time, said only that he would ``attend to the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   When the day for Johnson's appearance arrived, the galleries
were packed with diplomats, congressional wives and others with
enough clout to secure a ticket. Many in the crowd and on the
Senate floor apparently believed that Johnson would indeed appear
in person.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant-at-arms called out, ``Andrew Johnson, president of
the United States! Andrew Johnson, president of the United States!
Appear and answer the articles of impeachment exhibited against you
by the House of Representatives of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The doors to the Senate chamber were thrown open. But Johnson
never appeared. Instead, his four lawyers entered through a side
door and proceeded to ask for a 40-day delay to prepare the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty days!'' declared Thaddeus Stevens, a Pennsylvania
representative and ardent Johnson enemy who had led the impeachment
drive in the House. ``As much as it took the Lord to destroy the
world by flood?'' The defense was given 10 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After another delay, the substantive part of the trial opened on
March 30. The House impeachment managers ran the show, calling 19
witnesses. Benjamin Butler, one of the managers, opened the
proceeding with a speech on the British legal precedents concerning
high crimes and misdemeanors and the powers of a tribunal.It was an
oddly legalistic speech for the former general, who as the
administrator of New Orleans after its fall to federal troops had
once warned the city's women that if any one of them again voiced
``contempt'' for Union soldiers she would be treated as ``a lady of
the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler soon switched to his well-known flamboyant and colorful
personal-attack style. ``By murder most foul he succeeded to the
presidency,'' Butler cried, ``and is the elect of an assassin to
that office!''
</P>
<P>
   Among the congressmen, there were squabbles. Should Benjamin
Wade, the Senate president, be allowed to vote since he stood to
succeed Johnson as president? It was decided he could. There was,
after all, one other known conflict of interest. One of the
Tennessee senators was Johnson's son-in-law. Then there was the
issue of the role of the chief justice of the Supreme Court, Salmon
T. Chase. Should he decide questions of law and procedure or simply
refer them to the senators for decision? After a vote, Chase was
given the power to decide questions of law, although they could be
appealed to the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defense, as put forth by his lead lawyers, Henry
Stanbery, former attorney general, and William M. Evarts, the head
of the New York bar association, was multi-tiered. They argued, on
one hand, that Stanton was not covered by the Tenure of Office Act.
On the other, they said that a president in rare cases can violate
a law if that is the only way to force it before the courts for a
ruling on its constitutionality. If the senators did not agree, the
lawyers also argued, they should accept that Johnson believed he
had that right when he dismissed Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after 37 days of hearings, the Senate voted. During
the trial, the senators had said little, speaking only to raise
points of order or object to witnesses. When they had something to
discuss, they left the chamber and huddled in what was called the
ladies' parlor. What was said during these private sessions was
never recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, meanwhile, secretly sought a compromise with moderate
Republicans, promising that if acquitted he would no longer stand
in the way of their reconstruction plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that he had never compromised with these moderates,
although he could have long before,'' said Hans L. Trefousse, the
author of books on the impeachment and several of its major
figures. ``If he had done so, he would not have been impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   When the vote took place, on May 16, Johnson's conciliatory
attitude and the legal arguments had their effect. Seven
Republicans joined the Democrats. To impeach, the majority needed
36 senators united. The vote was 35-19 and Andrew Johnson remained
in the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
