<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPEAKER, WELL-LIKED BUT UNTESTED, TO HEAD BITTERLY DIVIDED
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(subs to add 2nd take) 
(ATTN: Conn., Ill., Ind., Wis., Fla., Texas, Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Hastert has been sent (NYT16) to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
The following article was reported by Robert Pear, Pam Belluck and
Lizette Alvarez and written by Ms. Alvarez. 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only minutes after he was elected speaker of the
House on Wednesday, Dennis Hastert flashed the regular-guy charm
and Midwestern sensibility that his backers hope will insulate him
from the partisan warfare that toppled the previous speaker and a
would-be successor in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Speak...'' Hastert said, as Democratic Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt handed him the speaker's gavel, a slip of the
tongue that spoke volumes about his quest for bipartisanship and
perhaps, Democrats wish, an ability to see the future.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hastert handed Gephardt the gavel for safekeeping, stepped
down from the speaker's lofty perch and ambled back down to the
well of the House. ``Customarily, a new speaker gives his first
remarks from the speaker's chair,'' Hastert said as he addressed
his colleagues in the 106th Congress. ``While I have great respect
for the traditions of this House and the institution, I am breaking
tradition this once, because my legislative home is on the floor
here with you, and so is my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 12 years in Congress, Rep. John Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., a
bear-like lawmaker who was catapulted from obscurity and drafted
for the job of speaker only three weeks ago, has earned a
reputation as a ``nice guy.'' He is the kind of rare Washington
commodity who knows how to listen, stifles his temper and keeps his
word, members say, which is why he swiftly received the backing of
moderate and conservative Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   But, no matter how congenial and hard working, Hastert faces a
daunting double-barreled challenge: He comes to the job of speaker
as one of the most untested leaders in memory, a no-name
congressman new to to the battles of top- tier politics, and he
confronts one of the most sharply divided, least forgiving,
Congress' in years.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with only a slim, 10-vote Republican majority in the
House, Hastert will have to tread carefully between Republicans and
Democrats, conservatives and moderates, chairmen and ranking
members to sidestep last year's damaging tag of a ``Do Nothing
Congress'' and get legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   High on his list are a host of prickly, but popular, issues:
Shoring up Social Security, passing tax cuts, fixing schools,
pumping up the nation's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative ideologues, most of them from the rebel class of
1994, will watch Hastert closely for any tarnishing of the
impeccable conservative credentials that his votes have displayed.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the same time, he must work with Democrats who are both
emboldened by their gains in the November elections and embittered
over the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also the first to raise their suspicions about
Hastert's close ties as chief deputy whip to Rep. Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, the House's top vote counter and a powerful conservative.
DeLay locked up the votes for Hastert only hours after Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., who had been designated the next speaker,
announced his resignation Dec. 19. Democrats now wonder about
Hastert's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question mark,'' said Rep. Thomas Barrett, D-Wis.,
who has worked closely with Hastert on the Committee on government
Reform and Oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got his work cut out for him,'' Barrett said, alluding to
the narrow Republican majority in the House. He cited ``a deeply
divided Republican caucus, and a Democratic caucus that feels that
it has just been burned royally,'' adding, ``It's not an enviable
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans roll their eyes at the presumption that Hastert's
relationship with DeLay, his inexperience and his soft edge make
him a pushover. ``I've never seen anyone step on Denny,'' said Rep.
Chris Shays, R-Conn., a moderate who clashed with DeLay over
campaign finance legislation. ``I haven't seen anyone even get
close to it. And if anyone has tried, he got him in a good
headlock. It's probably that very few people saw it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans in the House call it getting ``Dennyized.''
</P>
<P>
   A bulky arm would suddenly drape over their shoulders and,
before long, they would pour their hearts out about an upcoming
vote on the House floor. Hastert, his thick glasses framing his
face, would genially press them to be part of the legislative team,
all the while making sure they they leave with their egos intact.
</P>
<P>
   It is a style that Hastert, 57, honed as a high-school wrestling
coach in the rural town of Yorkville, Ill., in the 1960s and 1970s.
Bob Evans, a friend and fellow coach, said Hastert knew instantly
what each boy would be good at, and knew how to talk to the boys
about their weaknesses and still ``make them feel good about
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knows how to get along with people,'' said Rep. Ray
LaHood, R-Ill., who has known Hastert since 1982. ``He has the
ability to sit down and listen 80 percent of the time. And when you
listen 80 percent of the time, you give people the feeling you are
concerned about what they are concerned about, and that endears you
to people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the vitriolic atmosphere that has pervaded the House in the
past two years, colleagues say Hastert's approach to politics,
which he has vowed to keep intact as speaker, could usher in
gentler time. Many saw him as the ideal antidote to the bitterness
and controversy that marked last year's turn of events: the
election losses, Rep. Newt Gingrich's ouster as speaker, followed
by Livingston's resignation under the cloud of a sex scandal and
then President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, people were really tired of controversy and
the high drama that had been going on,'' LaHood said of the hours
that followed Livingston's announcement. ``He is the most
noncontroversial person in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hastert's style could not be more different than
Gingrich's, something that members note with a sense of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Cast as the regular guy, Hastert is a plain-talker, more
comfortable working in the shadows than before the camera lights.
He has no plans to become a national party spokesman, leaving that
task to other members. He does not easily go off on tangents,
intellectual or otherwise. And he is not a talker.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert did not work his way up to speaker through the ranks of
the top leadership; he was never a majority leader or a whip or a
conference chairman. He doesn't even have a leadership PAC yet,
which is an invaluable tool to raise money and build support.
</P>
<P>
   Many people would see that as a liability. Most House
Republicans do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clean start, a new beginning,'' said Rep. David
McIntosh, R-Ind., echoing the conventional wisdom among House
Republicans. ``Here is a guy who is a family man, who is hymble,
not flashy, who connects with real people. He's not a Gingrich
figure, or a Ronald Reagan figure, but a good solid person in our
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
