<HEADLINE>
NBA, UNION SETTLE; 52-GAME SEASON SET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Basketball Association and its players'
union, locked in a contentious six-month labor dispute and 36 hours
from a drop-dead date, finally reached agreement early Wednesday to
save what remains of the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern and union executive director Billy
Hunter staged an all-night bargaining session which produced an
agreement in principle at 6 a.m. It was approved by the players
Wednesday afternoon, should be ratified by the owners Thursday; it
will result in a reduced season of 52 games commencing on or about
Feb. 2. No schedule was released.
</P>
<P>
   The league did not comment, other than to note that an agreement
was reached ending the lockout that began July 1. Had no agreement
been reached, Stern would have recommended Thursday that the owners
cancel the season. Hunter, who had invited all NBA players to a
meeting here ostensibly to support the union, said, ``They gave a
little and we gave a little. The deal overall is pretty balanced.''
The new deal will run for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials told players that training camps will open in
7-10 days, or once the agreement has been reduced to writing. There
will be roughly two weeks of practice before games begin. Most of
the 52 games will be played against conference opponents, with
perhaps a half-dozen against nonconference foes. The regular season
will end the first week of May _ a two-week extension _ and the NBA
Finals may even stretch into the first few days of July. But there
will be basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get it started,'' said Laker phenom Kobe Bryant, one of
about 200 players who attended Wednesday's union meeting. ``I think
this is a good deal for most of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no word from the game's most important player, Michael
Jordan, who is considering retirement. His agent, David Falk,
released a statement saying Jordan would continue to mull his
options. ``I'm not certain what his time frame is,'' Falk said.
</P>
<P>
   Most players familiar with Jordan think the Chicago superstar
will retire. Jordan was not at Wednesday's meeting; former teammate
Ron Harper said Jordan was playing golf in the Bahamas. Under the
terms of the new deal, Jordan could sign for 105 percent of what he
made last year, a deal which would earn him almost $35 million.
Only the Bulls could pay him that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new deal does not really help the Celtics. The
salary cap for this season was set at a lower-than-expected $30
million per team, which does not give Rick Pitino enough money
(less than $2 million) to sign even a mid-range free agent center.
However, the deal does mean that free agent-to-be Antoine Walker
will be limited to what he can earn. Once thought to be a player
worth $115 million or more, Walker can now receive no more on a
six-year extension (he has a year left on his contact) than $85.68
million. He still might be traded, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Most players arrived at Wednesday's meeting thinking there would
be some undefined vote supporting the union's executive committee,
which had rejected the owners' so-called ``final offer.'' All they
knew was that they already had lost half their salaries, their
season was on the brink of elimination, and their futures were
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were asked for reactions to a deal they knew
nothing about as they entered the General Motors Building on 5th
Avenue, fittingly adjacent to F.A.O. Schwartz. It was a pleasant
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to see the atmosphere in that room once the
guys realized that there was a deal,'' said Dee Brown, the player
representative for the Toronto Raptors. ``There were a lot of
smiling faces. I think it was so different because the agenda was
now different. If we didn't have a deal to vote on, I'm not sure
what would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Detroit's Jerome Williams put it, ``There was going to be
some blood on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter presented the deal and asked that it be endorsed. Union
president Patrick Ewing then spoke briefly and the players voted.
It was a no-brainer. The players put their name on a piece of paper
and voted, and the result was overwhelming _ 179-5, according to a
union official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone came out of the room smiling,'' said longtime NBA
player Rick Mahorn. ``The majority won.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Stern and several NBA officials arrived at the
meeting in yet another attempted display of newfound community.
Stern spoke for about 10 minutes and said it was time to forget the
often bitter tone of the negotiations and work on rebuilding the
league and the partnership between players and management. Many
players left the meeting wearing small blue buttons saying,
``SOLID,'' as well as big smiles.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal is more beneficial to the so-called ``middle
class,'' which is what the union said it wanted. It also has limits
on what players can earn, depending on length of service. The union
lowered the percentage of what it wants from overall income in the
final three years of the deal. Rookies now will be eligible for
free agency after four years instead of three, and minimum salaries
have been increased and scaled, again according to length of
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an extremely fair deal for most of the
players,'' said agent Steve Kauffman, most of whose clients are
mid-range earners. ``We didn't have any leverage. And Billy was in
a difficult situation with certain agents and high-end players. He
had to walk a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Many NBA and club officials withheld comment. However, John
Calipari, former coach at the University of Massachusetts and
currently coach and head basketball honcho for the New Jersey Nets,
said he was ``giddy'' when he woke up in the morning and heard the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was enjoying the time with my family, but it was time,''
Calipari said. ``I was going to college games, but it was like
studying without having any tests. Those are the games.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the union's critics, Toronto's Kevin Willis and New
Jersey's Jayson Williams, also were present. Both had called for a
secret ballot of the rank-and-file when it appeared that the sides
were not going to get a deal done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't against the union,'' Williams said. ``I said what was
on my mind. I always say what's on my mind. But we owe an apology
to the fans and to the people we've hurt whose livelihood depends
on us playing. We hurt these people at Christmas. Maybe we should
sit down with the league and do something for them. I just hope
they forgive us.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning back the fans could be the real test. Virtually every
poll conducted on fan reaction during the lockout registered
universal apathy. No one cared. One person wrote a letter to an
Atlanta newspaper two weeks ago saying, ``Thanks, NBA, for the best
season I've ever had. Keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' said free agent center Joe Kleine.
``They're not going to welcome us back with open arms. We know that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Keith Glass, whose clientele also consists of mid- and
minimum-level earners, said the fans are the ones now in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like the way things are being done, now is your
chance to be heard,'' Glass said. ``Speak up. Don't go to games.
Don't buy the jerseys. I'm already sick of reading my quotes in the
paper. Imagine how the fans feel. It's absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
