<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-1STLD-W     01-06 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: our leadership.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The son of working-class parents in Illinois' corn country,
Hastert clutches tightly to his Midwestern sensibilities. Every
weekend, he flies home to his modest ranch house on the Fox River.
He shops for his own groceries and eats in the Cozy Corner diner om
Yorkville. To relax, he carves wooden ducks and collects antique
cars, including a red firetruck that he takes to parades. And he
drives around with Max, a Labrador retriever, in the front seat of
his car. Hastert and his wife, Jean, have two grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get in his car and you get out, you got dog hairs all over
your suit,'' said state Rep. Tom Cross, who now holds Hastert's old
state House seat. ``But that's Denny.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of three sons, Hastert grew up about 45 miles
southwest of Chicago, in a heavily Republican area that includes
Ronald Reagan's boyhood home of Dixon. The district, which Hastert
represents, is now an amalgam of rich cornfields and suburban
bedroom communities.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Jack, was an embalmer for funeral homes during the
Depression and later operated a farm supply store near the family's
hometown of Oswego. Jack Hastert also owned a restaurant called the
Clock Tower.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Hastert delivered feed to farmers, and in
college, he got up at 3 a.m. to deliver milk.
</P>
<P>
   Religion was a strong force for Hastert, from his involvement
with his church's youth groups to his days at Wheaton College, an
evangelical Christian school near his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   In his professional life, Hastert says little about his
religious beliefs, but it is not unusual to find a Bible open in
his Capitol Hill apartment or see him thumbing through Scripture
before important votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion is in his heart and mind, and not on his sleeve,''
Shays said. ``We need a little more of that kind of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps three of Hastert's most talked about traits are his
integrity, patience and his ability to forge a compromise, all of
which he will need in abundance to handle the year's twist and
turns. ``He has been the most well-kept secret in the House,'' said
House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gingrich appointed Hastert to head a task force
assigned to cobble together a Republican bill that would address
the concerns of voters fed up with managed health care. It was an
issue that had divided the Republican caucus and left the party
vulnerable to Democratic accusations that they were turning their
backs on patients.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who has always been interested in health care, decided
early on to gather every shred of evidence he could find about
managed care, compile it for the group, and then just talk it out
for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He held his tongue, he held his patience,'' said Rep. Charles
Norwood, R-Ga., who wanted to permit all patients to sue their
managed care companies as a way of keeping them in check, an idea
unpopular with most Republicans. ``He managed that group by
listening more than talking. But when he needed to be firm, he was
firm. He would slam down his hand on the table _ that's it, wait a
minute, everybody is off track, everybody is wrong. He did it in
such a way that isn't offensive. Being a nice guy helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert filled the managed care legislation with a little bit of
everything. The strategy got him a bill that he managed to get
passed on the House floor, which were his orders from Gingrich, but
the bill angered Democrats, who saw it as a weak Republican
grab-bag. They voted against the bill and it died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker also handled another contentious issue that
frequently angered Democrats and some moderate Republicans. Rather
than risk a battle with Shays, a moderate, over the 2000 census,
Hastert simply moved the issue away from Shays to another
subcommittee. Shays did not mind, he said. It was the
common-sensical thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never loses sight of his goal,'' said Rep. Sue Kelly,
R-N.Y., who was part of the managed care panel and is a member of
the whip team. ``He never loses sight of the ball; maybe that's the
old coach coming out in him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the internecine wars among Republicans, Hastert has not only
survived, but gained a reputation as a man of his word. After the
November elections, as Republican losses shook the party
leadership, about 50 House members wanted to draft Hastert for
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert had already promised his vote to the current
majority leader, Armey. He asked Armey if he could withdraw his
support, but when the Texas congressman refused, saying he wanted
to keep the post, Hastert decided to abide by his earlier pledge.
</P>
<P>
   He was also called into action to smooth tensions between DeLay
and Gingrich, after the whip and a group of young conservatives
sought to oust the speaker in a 1997 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's voting record put him squarely in the camp of
conservative Republicans, and he recently received a 100 percent
approval rating from the Christian Coalition. He is also good at
steering money into his Illinois district; last September, he
funneled $250,000 of the defense budget to a Yorkville company for
a study of its caffeinated chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   But his affable attitude often has the disarming effect of
making moderates and even some Democrats believe he agrees with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'd he be similar to as a speaker?'' said former Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., who was chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee. ``I'd say it'd be Tip O'Neill'' _ a liberal whose
congeniality often won over members of both parties. O'Neill,
D-Mass., retired in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert never shies away from a sports metaphor, and Wednesday
was no different. ``A good coach knows when to step back and let
others shine in the spotlight,'' Hastert told the House. ``A coach
worth his salt will instill in his team a sense of fair play,
camaraderie, respect of the game and for the opposition. Without
those, victory is hollow,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A short distance away, DeLay beamed. His old friend, the man who
helped him get elected as whip in 1994, was assuming the speaker's
chair.
</P>
<P>
   And just across the room, former Republican Minority Leader Bob
Michel, R-Ill., who is known for his civility and amiability, also
watched his protege take the gavel. Hastert has been seeking advice
from his mentor, sometimes over a glass of bourbon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny, always be mindful of the minority and their rights
under the rules of the House and you'll be better for it, you'll be
respected,'' Michel told Hastert recently. ``The speaker is speaker
of the whole House.''
</P>
<P>
   In a House that has changed dramatically since Michel retired in
1994, ``It isn't going to be easy, but I think he understands
that,'' said another friend, Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
