<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      01-06 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK: MOVED ON. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   In reaching an agreement with the league, Hunter avoided the
heated confrontations that could have taken place with 210 of the
league's 430 players in one room and under so much strain. With
financial futures and playing careers dependent on the outcome of a
vote, players entered the day concerned that teammates would be
pitted against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we got everything settled before there was a
free-for-all,'' free-agent forward Charles Barkley said. ``It could
have been bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage was saved. But the damage of this labor dispute on
the union could linger. After agreeing to a deal that many believed
was only minimally better than the one the league had been offering
all along _ and at a cost of almost $600 million in player salaries
_ Hunter's leadership has been put into question and his future is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy negotiated them right into a hard cap and an escrow
system,'' Thomas said. ``There was a better deal on the table in
the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   No deal could be reached over the last three months during
negotiating sessions between the league and the union's leadership
that had been filled with finger-pointing and personal remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Ewing was perceived as the extended arm of agent David
Falk, someone seen by the league as an impediment to completing a
deal. Although he had been apart of the negotiations, Ewing was
kept out of Tuesday night's crucial meeting. Any Falk influence had
been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys felt that maybe I've been too tough,'' said Ewing,
referring to members of the union's executive committee. ``So we
gave Billy the OK to go in and get it done by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Alone, Hunter came to an agreement with Stern less than 30 hours
before the league's board of governors was to vote on canceling the
season. Although their potential to earn the astronomical salaries
of the past will be limited by maximums on the high-end players,
the six-year deal was approved, 206-4, by the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players have to take control and get the agents out,'' Thomas
said. ``That's what cost them $600 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, 250 players descended on Las Vegas and voted to
give the negotiating committee the authority to approve or reject
any proposals by the owners. The players sounded united. Any
players who spoke up, as did John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek, were
shouted down.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern of behavior by the negotiating committee continued
through the summer and fall and even this week. Several players who
spoke out over the past week were immediately reprimanded and
publicly scolded by the union's leadership. When Williams asked for
a vote on the owners' proposal and questioned the negotiating
team's ties to Falk, Ewing fired back. Alonzo Mourning, also a Falk
client and member of the negotiating committee, also took issue
with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tense,'' Williams said. ``Me and Patrick talked. I
talked to Alonzo. I've been taking a little heat from guys over how
I should have said what I did to their faces. But I did say it to
their faces. They got the message, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Just in time. As the voices of disapproval grew louder, Hunter
could not put the owners' proposal up for vote Wednesday without
knowing what the outcome would be. If the players repudiated the
negotiating committee and accepted the owners' offer, Hunter and
Ewing could have been overthrown and Thomas might have been asked
to step forward to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had come into the room, he was going to be thrown out of
the building,'' one union official said.
</P>
<P>
   But several star players would have been behind Thomas. And
superstars like O'Neal were ready to take charge and show
leadership to get a deal done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear his name,'' said Hawks' center Dikembe
Mutombo, who is a Falk client and on the negotiating committee.
``Enough of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's over now. Although a once solid union nearly collapsed in
the process, the season has been saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a right to their opinion,'' said Askins, who was
in opposition to his teammate, Mourning. ``Once we step on the
court together, we're brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
