</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONGRESS-ART-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER SWORN IN AS SENATOR; SIX FROM TRI-STATE AREA JOIN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Ill.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR,
HOUSE-HASTERT, HOUSE, CONGRESS-ETHICS, IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With left hand on his silver-and-jade-trimmed bar
mitzvah Bible, Charles Schumer was sworn in Wednesday as New York
state's newest senator, vowing to be a legislator who not only
passes bills but also _ in the tradition of the man he defeated,
Alfonse D'Amato _ delivers money and services to the state.
</P>
<P>
   On a bracingly cold and brilliantly clear day, Schumer, a
Democrat from Brooklyn, also vowed not to let ``the cloud of
impeachment'' distract him from working on what he considers the
state's top issues: health care, crime, jobs, Social Security,
education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the trial lasts six days, or six weeks or even six
months, I have six years to do the things that I want to do,''
Schumer told a group of about 50 friends and relatives at a
cookies-and-coffee reception sponsored by the National Soft Drink
Association on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Though he served nine terms in the House, Schumer sounded every
bit the freshman legislator on Wednesday, looking wide-eyed as he
pumped well-wishers' hands and confessing to feeling ``tingles down
my spine'' after passing the lighted Capitol dome the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready, excited and awe-struck at the chance to
legislate,'' Schumer, 48, said at a news conference before he was
sworn in by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, already known for his prowess as a bill writer, said
that he would work hard to help individual communities with their
problems, echoing a theme President Clinton raised while
campaigning for him in New York last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I never did was demean the title `Senator Pothole,'
'' he said, referring to D'Amato's sobriquet. ``I think that is an
important role for a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was one of eight new senators, four Democrats and four
Republicans, sworn in to Congress on Wednesday. On the House side,
40 new members were sworn in, 23 of them Democrats and 17
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer is the only new senator from New York, New Jersey or
Connecticut. There are six freshmen representatives from the
region: four from New York and one each from the other two states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a bit like homecoming week for several of the new members
from the New York metropolitan region Wednesday outside the
ceremonial room where the freshman representatives were being
photographed with the newly elected speaker of the House, Dennis
Hastert, a Republican from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   New York's four newest members of Congress are Anthony D.
Weiner, a Democrat from Brooklyn who was elected to Schumer's old
seat; Thomas M. Reynolds, a Republican from the Buffalo, N.Y.,
area; Joseph Crowley, a Queens Democrat; and John E. Sweeney, a
Republican from Troy. The last three had been in Albany until they
were elected last November, Reynolds and Crowley in the state
Assembly, and Sweeney as an aide to Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be working again,'' Crowley said as he exited the
House chamber after casting his first vote. ``I had been unemployed
for five days.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner, 34, also gave his inaugural floor speech Wednesday,
urging his colleagues to vote against reappointing the House
managers who will argue the impeachment against the president in
the Senate. But Weiner tripped a bit by calling for a no vote on
the motion when he wanted a yes one. (The managers were
reappointed).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame I'll be revising my first remarks, but it was a
bit of a nerve wracking experience,'' Weiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new members brought bus loads of friends, relatives
and former campaign workers to Washington to witness their solemn
oaths, and then party afterward.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest contingents _ about 350 people _ came from
New Jersey with Rep. Rush D. Holt, 50, a physicist from the
Princeton area who upset a Republican incumbent last November.
During a mid-day reception, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., quipped
that 60 years after the Manhattan project was inaugurated to build
an atomic bomb, ``We finally have someone in the House who
understands it.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's only new member of the House is Rep. John Larsen,
a Democrat from East Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
