</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SPIED ON IRAQ, USING U.N. COVER, AMERICAN OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. officials said on Wednesday that American spies had worked
undercover on teams of U.N. Special Commission inspectors ferreting
out secret Iraqi weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi leadership has long condemned the weapons inspectors
as tools of American intelligence. In October, it issued a formal
statement saying it would never cooperate with U.N. inspection
teams riddled with ``American spies and agents.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also said American intelligence agencies provided
information and technology to the special commission, known as
Unscom. In turn, they said, the United States and other nations
routinely received information on Iraqi weapons programs uncovered
by the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence-gathering devices supplied to the inspectors by
American agencies gave the United States a better understanding of
the secret weapons sites being hidden by Iraq, American officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM has been a unique attempt by the United Nations to create
an international intelligence unit. Its mission was to uncover
Iraqi weapons programs after the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure that American intelligence officers had worked as
U.N. inspectors came after The Boston Globe reported charges that
American intelligence agents had used the U.N. inspection effort as
a cover to spy on President Saddam Hussein. The Washington Post
also reported that Unscom worked with American spy agencies to
collect intelligence used by the United States to spy on Saddam or
undermine the Iraqi regime.
</P>
<P>
   American officials also said a former U.N. weapons inspector was
misinformed when he charged that the United States took over a U.N.
intelligence-gathering operation in Iraq and made it into an arm of
American espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Top U.N. officials said they had no evidence to support the
charge. A senior administration official said the former inspector,
Scott Ritter, was doing ``unconscionable'' damage to the United
States and the United Nations with the accusation and playing into
the hands of Saddam and his allies.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that while the United States had
participated in the U.N. teams' intelligence-gathering operation,
they had not taken it over. They strongly rejected reports that the
U.N. inspection teams had been used as a tool of American
intelligence, as did Secretary General Kofi Annan and UNSCOM's
present and former chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We not only have no convincing evidence of these allegations,
we have no evidence of any kind,'' said Annan's spokesman, Fred
Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unscom does not have an indigenous intelligence capability,''
said a senior administration official. ``That was provided by
member states. The information it gathered was used to help break
Saddam's concealment effort, and the information was passed on to
United Nations Security Council members.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ritter, a former U.S. Marines intelligence
officer, raised the question of whether Unscom improperly aided
U.S. intelligence in ways that threatened the international
inspectors' independence, or opened them up to charges of spying on
behalf of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said on Wednesday that Ritter was describing
a secret U.S.-assisted Unscom intelligence-gathering program which
he did not fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter said the inspectors had developed ``methodologies,''
which he refused to describe, that helped them understand how Iraqi
security services concealed Baghdad's programs to build biological
and chemical weapons. These same security services and concealment
methods were used to protect Saddam.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
