A2019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-NETCOM-COX     01-06 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-NETCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-flying Netcom lost ground as ISP rivals grew
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netcom was the MindSpring of the early 1990s, a high-flying
Internet pioneer with a stock that was flying even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock soared to $90 in 1995 as it served nearly 600,000
subscribers. Netcom, a Silicon Valley start-up, was the first
Internet provider to go public, doing so in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked them a lot,'' says Atlanta user Joe Thompson. ``Netcom
offered good, fast connections and its system was never down. The
company was a heck of lot better than America Online at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half of the '90s, America Online has soared
while Netcom has peaked and fallen back. The San Jose, Calif.-based
company's number of subscribers has declined to 500,000 and it has
now changed ownership twice in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netcom was one of the original Internet providers to serve the
average Joe, but it had a hard time when competition came in,''
says Brad Grimes, a senior editor at PC World magazine. ``It was a
bloodbath and MindSpring is one of the reasons why Netcom faded.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its decline, Netcom retains a strong reputation,
especially as a network. ``Netcom has maintained its own Internet
backbone and there aren't many companies that do that,'' says
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some of Netcom's longtime customers have noticed a
decline in its service. Thompson says after Denver-based telephone
company ICG bought Netcom a year ago, his service declined sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten to be an infrequent user, the service has become
such an irritating experience,'' says Thompson. Especially bad, he
says, is the reliability of Netcom's e-mail service.
</P>
<P>
   Netcom was started by Bob Rieger, whose vision was to provide a
low-cost, easy-to-use Internet connection for regular people.
</P>
<P>
   The business took off, with Netcom quickly becoming one of the
first big names in the consumer Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   The company went public in 1994 and then sold itself to ICG in
1997 for $225 million, with the deal closing in January of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months later, ICG announced it was putting Netcom up for
sale. ``We're not selling the part that we always wanted in
Netcom,'' says ICG President J. Shelby Bryan, referring to Netcom's
Internet backbone network.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, we realized that it would be better to sell
Netcom's customers,'' explains Bryan. ``Values for this type of
business were going up, so we took this opportunity to sell the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan said he hired investment banker Salomon Smith Barney to
shop Netcom, a process that eventually led to MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
