</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC IMPACT OF NBA LOCKOUT: WIDE-RANGING AND STAGGERING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the 191-day National Basketball Association lockout, the
economic losers weren't only the players and owners who made a
tentative deal Wednesday to bridge their financial chasm and split
$2 billion in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   There are the TV networks that lost lucrative programming and
advertisers who temporarily lost a key way to reach their ideal
audience, young male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   There are the companies that make T shirts, jackets and replica
uniforms licensed by the NBA, a potential $3 billion retail
business.
</P>
<P>
   There are the concession workers, vendors, novelty-sellers,
security guards and ushers _ some paid hourly wages, some who work
for commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't rely on this income,'' said Ed Piseck, 30, who made
about $100 a month as a bartender at McNichols Arena, home of the
Denver Nuggets. ``I just used it to pay off debt and for the new
baby's college fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of dollars have been rebated to season ticket holders
for unplayed November and December games. More will be refunded
next month for January. Millions more were lost by retailers who
cut back on NBA-licensed merchandise fans were avoiding. ``All
over, there were double-digit drops in sales,'' said Chris McEvoy,
editor-in-chief of Sporting Goods Business.
</P>
<P>
   The television networks that carry NBA games refocused their
programming. TNT and TBS, the Turner Sports cable network lost
about 40 telecasts, filling the gaps with films. NBC replaced its
Christmas Day games with ``It's A Wonderful Life.'' The Fox Sports
Net, which carries 700 games through local cable deals with 26 of
the 29 NBA teams, plugged in other sports, and would have added
more hockey and spring training games if the season were axed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard to replace the Bulls in Chicago and the Lakers
in Los Angeles, and the ratings that come with them,'' said Arthur
Smith, the executive vice president of the Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   How much fan apathy will affect viewership is unknown. The
uncertainty of post-lockout viewing is compounded by worries about
Michael Jordan's return.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Nielsen rating average last season was a 4.8, and the
finals won by the Bulls hit an an 18.7, an NBA television record.
TNT and TBS combined for a 1.7 regular-season rating and a 3.4
playoff average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a down year, but better to have a down year that's
a half season than no season at all,'' said Neal Pilson, a sports
industry consultant.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner paid their full season's rights fees _ a combined
$465 million _ knowing the season could be canceled. FSN paid
nothing in advance. NBC will pro rate its payments over the next
three seasons; Turner will get more games.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of advertising is at stake. Last season, gross advertising
sales to NBC totaled an estimated $427.7 million, according to
Competitive Media Reporting, an ad-tracking service. An estimated
$138.9 million flowed to TNT and TBS. Wednesday's settlement will
keep a lot of that money from fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   But during the lockout, some advertisers shifted their
commercial purchases to other programs on NBC, TNT, TBS and the
local FSN services like the MSG Network. But some advertisers,
about one-quarter of Turner's, left entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shifted to college basketball and football,'' said Vizhier
Mooney, a spokeswoman for Nike, an NBA sponsor, official outfitter
of 10 teams and licensed apparel manufacturer. ``Now we'll go back
to our usual plans.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney, the largest retailer of NBA-licensed merchandise,
will wait until the season starts to advise its stores on stocking
up its goods. Business fell 70 percent in markets with NBA teams,
leading stores to drastically cut back space devoted to
league-licensed goods.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Sporting Goods Business reported that the NBA-licensed
business was down nearly 50 percent for the fall and holiday season
and orders would tumble 80 percent for the spring. The magazine
forecast a smaller drop for basketball sneakers, which were already
in a recession for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok's basketball sales, led by Allen Iverson's $115 signature
brand, are down eight to 10 percent, less than the market's 10 to
15 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We produced 40 percent less of the Iverson product than last
year,'' and accelerate its focus on popular lines lines, like
running shoes, said Shawn Neville, senior vice president and
general manager of Reebok North America.
</P>
<P>
   Those markets may take a while to recover. ``When there are no
games, retailers don't reorder, they discount and get the
merchandise the heck out,'' said Frank Vuono, a former NFL
Properties executive who is the president of Integrated Sports
International, a New Jersey-based sports marketing firm. ``After
the NFL strike in 1981, it took three years to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the lockout compelled fans, owners, players, TV
executives, capmakers, retailers and shoe retailers to contemplate
a season without the NBA, it made part-time workers contemplate
their supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Morgan, 46, a part-time luxury suite attendant at America
West Arena in Phoenix, earned extra money to give to her daughter,
a college student, said Tuesday night at a Coyotes hockey game,
``If they don't care about the little peon, they sure should. If it
wasn't for us, they wouldn't be employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Gottlieb, 28, said his family's four parking lots near the
Fleet Center in Boston has lost $200,000 without Celtics games.
``Everyone loses,'' he said. ``You just go on, you know? You hope
it comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the lockout's settlement caused NBA-related stocks to
stage a comeback, on a day of broad market gains. Shares of Ascent
Entertainment, which owns the Nuggets, rose $.625 to $8.625. The
Boston Celtics Partnership jumped $4.125 to close at $14.625. And
Nike jumped $2.9375 to close at $43.625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
