</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SPECTER-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER POPS UP AS IMPEACHMENT SPOKESMAN, OFFERS EXPERTISE
ON TV
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 6, -- Just hours after being sworn in for his
fourth term in the Senate, Pennsylvania Republican Arlen Specter
was off to CNN's bureau to be interviewed yet again about
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Never-shy, Specter has used the impeachment of President Clinton
to vault into the national spotlight, appearing in recent weeks on
a dozen television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on NBC's Meet the Press, CBS's Face the Nation, and a
slew of CNN programs, including Wednesday night's edition of
Crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such a public and media interest in any issue
before,'' Specter said in an interview. ``This trial will be looked
at under a microscope for centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am viewing this as a heavy responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With no consensus in the Senate on how to proceed with the
impeachment trial against President Clinton, political observers
say Specter is in a prime position to assert himself as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a moderate Republican who has a stellar legal
background,'' said Tom Yu, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee. ``I think he has realized that this is an opportunity.
He has in the past been very outspoken when appropriate. It doesn't
surprise me that he recognized this as a chance to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, a Yale-educated attorney, was an assistant counsel on
the Warren Commission investigating the assassination of President
John F. Kennedy. He also was an assistant attorney general in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's spokesman John Ullyot said the Senator is in demand
because he can reach across party lines. He said when Specter
announced his presidential candidacy in 1995, he got support from
pro-choice activists for his liberal stance on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Specter is in demand because he speaks his mind and
appeals to many people,'' Ullyot said. ``Couple that with his being
a legal expert and he's the perfect spokesman or guest on a show.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Specter, R-Pa, didn't think Clinton should face
charges until after his term. But since the House impeached the
president, he's been among the Senate's most outspoken members on
the subject of how the trial should be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said there should be a full Senate trial with witnesses.
He said he doesn't support censure because he thinks it is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to punish the president,'' he said. ``We have
to convict him or not convict him.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the trial won't derail other issues and could be
limited to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He said witness testimony is necessary because, unlike some of
his colleagues, he thinks there are facts ``in dispute'' in the
case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Specter has written to Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Mississippi, outlining his views on the impeachment
trial, but he declined to make those letters public.
</P>
<P>
   Specter is no stranger to high profile and controversial legal
issues.
</P>
<P>
   When he was assistant counsel to the Warren Commission, he
pushed the ``single bullet theory'' in the assassination of
President John F. Kennedy. He is remembered for his
prosecutorial-style cross-examination of Anita Hill during the
Senate Judiciary Committee hearings into whether she was sexually
harassed by Clarence Thomas. He also helped block the appointment
of Robert H. Bork to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   While Specter is in a prime position to speak out on the
impeachment matter, the trial may make his more conservative
colleague Sen. Rick Santorum vulnerable in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum's support for a full trial with witnesses could make
him a target of Democratic attacks in future elections, according
to Yu, the RNC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Specter said he doesn't think his colleague will have any
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be able to win and has a very strong record,'' Specter
said. ``He is handling this fine and being interviewed heavily on
the subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
