<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUCATION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS $400 MILLION FOR AFTER-SCHOOL AND SUMMER SCHOOL
PROGRAMS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By JOHN M. BRODER  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The &UR;  &LR; Clinton administration is seeking a $400
million increase in funding for after-school and summer school
programs to tutor struggling students and to keep children of
working parents off the streets after school hours, the White House
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in an announcement planned for Thursday at
the White House, will ask Congress to increase spending for such
programs to $600 million from $200 million this year. The Education
Department would give the money to some of the school districts
that have adopted programs to end so-called social promotions, the
automatic passing of students to the next grade without regard to
academic progress, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is one of several unveiled this week intended to
showcase items in the president's agenda that polls have shown are
popular with the public and that demonstrate the White House staff
hard at work on policy matters as the senate opens the impeachment
trial of the president. Earlier this week, Clinton announced a plan
to subsidize long-term care for the elderly and a proposal to test
and treat federal prisoners for drug abuse.
 &UR;  &LR;  Officials have not yet specified how they intend to pay for these
proposals without dipping into the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The after-school program, started two years ago on a small
scale, has grown to benefit 380,000 students in 800 school
districts around the country this year.
</P>
<P>
   The new money, if approved as part of the budget for the fiscal
year beginning next Oct. 1, would expand the program to serve 1.1
million children.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department estimates that 5 million to 15 million
``latchkey'' children of working parents are left unsupervised
after school hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the peak hours for juvenile crime,'' said Bruce N.
Reed, the president's chief domestic policy adviser. ``That's the
time when kids get into trouble with crime, alcohol, drugs and
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal program allows schools to remain open into the
evening to provide tutoring and recreational activities.
</P>
<P>
   The government will give priority in distributing the money to
school districts that have adopted policies to end social
promotions. Such policies include special attention for failing
students, objective standards and tests to insure that students
have mastered grade-level work before being promoted, and the use
of extended school hours and summer schools to bring students up to
acceptable performance levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
