<SLUG> BC-MD-CLOGGED-COURTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALTIMORE'S PUSH ON CRIME CREATES BACKLOG OF CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ More aggressive efforts by the Baltimore police to
reduce the rate of homicides and other serious crime in the city
has created such a backlog of cases that a circuit judge has
dismissed first-degree murder charges against four men who had been
awaiting trial for almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy State's Attorney Haven Kodeck said Wednesday that his
office intended to appeal the decision. But Kodeck also said the
ruling, by Judge Roger Brown, reflects ``an overburdened court
system'' and an unintended consequence of recent efforts by Police
Commissioner Thomas Frazier to drive down crime rates as the city
tried to polish its image to attract new residents and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   Kodeck applauded the police work but conceded: ``There's not a
whole lot we can do, and when the system fails, it's regrettable.
We feel that that judge's decision was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, issued on Tuesday, followed a decision last month by
a Maryland appeals court to overturn a sex-charge conviction
against a man whose trial had been postponed nine times over 13
months because no judge was available on the next scheduled day for
the trial to begin. In general, a felony trial is supposed to begin
six months after arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Baltimore police grapple with about 300 homicide
cases a year, up to 1,500 nonfatal shootings, and thousands of drug
cases, the demand for judges, prosecutors and public defenders has
grown to an overwhelming level.
</P>
<P>
   The case on which Brown ruled involved four men _ Jay Anderson,
30; William Harrison, 21; Donte Spivey, 22, and Stacey Wilson, 29 _
who were accused of shooting to death Shawn Suggs in October 1995,
when he was 21.
</P>
<P>
   The four men spent several months in jail and then were released
on bail. While free, Spivey was arrested in another killing and was
held pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brown dropped charges against the men in the Suggs case after
the trial date was postponed 12 times because of the unavailability
of a judge, a prosecutor or a defender.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joseph Kaplan, chief judge of the Circuit Court for
Baltimore, said in an interview that the current backlog of felony
cases exceeds 5,000, ``and it is not inconceivable that some of
them go back more than a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the backlog, Kaplan said, is the availability of
only 11 courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Kodeck said that of the 170 lawyers in his office, only 18 were
assigned to violent crimes and each was carrying as many as 18
homicide cases.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gambrill, the public defender for Baltimore, said his
office had 109 lawyers, with 31 of them assigned to felony trials.
Their average caseload, Gambrill said, is 67 open cases, and some
of the defenders are handling more than 100 open cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to cover district courts, circuit courts and central
booking,'' he said. ``The need is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said he tried to ease the pressure last May by adding two
courtrooms for felony cases, only for them to go unused because the
public defender's office, which is financed by the state, did not
have the personnel to take advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shortage on both sides,'' Kaplan said. ``It's more
critical on the public defender side, but it's certainly a serious
situation. It's like trying to put 10 gallons in a 2-gallon jar.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambrill and Kaplan agreed that much of the backlog had evolved
from aggressive efforts by the police to reduce the level of
illegal drug activities.
</P>
<P>
   But problems arise, they said, when the police make sweeps,
arresting dozens of people at one time and charging all of them
with felony-level crimes, when the offenses by some might only be
misdemeanors. Unlike in some other jurisdictions where prosecutors
determine the charges, in Baltimore the police do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one addict is passing a capsule to another addict, the
police charge both with distribution, a felony,'' Gambrill said.
``Technically, it is distributing, but the question is, do you want
to put that case on the circuit court docket? We've got 60,000 drug
addicts in the metropolitan area. You can't arrest all those people
and not clog the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Weinhold, a spokesman for the police department, said,
``Officers are charging individuals within the legal framework set
forth by state legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinhold also said the police found it extremely frustrating
that an overworked criminal justice system was allowing suspects to
go free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
