<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-2NDTAKE-     01-06 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: protect Saddam. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ritter said his inspection team ``had a tremendous success using
these methodologies'' in March. A few weeks later, he said,
American officials approached Richard Butler, the chief of the U.N.
special commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``In April, the U.S. went to Butler and wanted to take over a
certain portion of the system of how we track these weapons,'' he
said. ``I wanted to make sure it was only for tracking weapons, but
the U.S. wanted to cut me out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could no longer guarantee that the methodology would be
used'' for weapons inspections alone, and not to the benefit of
United States military and intelligence agencies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butler will have to convince people that what the U.S. did was
for Unscom,'' said Ritter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were given assurances the information would not be
misused,'' he said. But, he added, he believed that the United
States ``used Butler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they set him up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter resigned in August, saying the United States and the
United Nations had undermined the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   A government official familiar with the dispute said that Ritter
was ill-informed. He said there had been a shift in Unscom's
intelligence-gathering methods last spring which the former
inspector did not fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unscom's efforts to collect information have gotten better,''
the official said. ``There was a period when Mr. Ritter was
familiar with these methods. The methods have since gotten better,
but Mr. Ritter wasn't totally witting of what was done. He may
think we were taking over. We weren't. But he felt cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   And a White House official lashed out at Ritter on Wednesday,
saying his allegations had delivered a pointless propaganda victory
to Iraq. ``The damage Scott Ritter has done to Unscom and U.S.
national security is unconscionable,'' said the official, who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. ``He should stop worrying about how
to get his face on the evening news and start worrying about the
harm he has caused.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler said the commission had asked for more advanced
technology after discovering in 1995 the sophisticated lies and
methods of concealment that Iraq had used to hide its nuclear,
biological and chemical weapons programs and its missile projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say this with all the force that I can: We have
never accepted or used any of that assistance for any other
purpose'' than disarming Iraq, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we facilitated spying?'' he said. ``Are we spies?
Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's predecessor, Rolf Ekeus, now Sweden's ambassador to the
United States, said that Unscom's teams had ``exclusively devoted
their activities in Iraq to identifying Iraq's holdings of weapons
of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ekeus also said that no eavesdropping equipment
had been installed by the United States to spy on Saddam or the
Iraqi special forces who protect him. Butler also denied that any
such eavesdropping or telephone-tapping took place.
</P>
<P>
   But Ekeus said that monitoring the efforts of Iraq's Republican
Guard and Special Security Services to conceal clandestine weapons
programs led to Iraqi protests that these troops were being spied
on for other reasons. These same forces protect Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   The Unscom inspectors were withdrawn in December, hours before
American and British attacks on Iraq. Saddam has said that they
will not be allowed to return unless the Special Commission is
restructured and Butler is replaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
