<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WERTHER-OPERA-HISTORY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WERTHER': SORROW IN DEEPER, DARKER TONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036. 
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes for The Atlantic Monthly, Opera
International and Art and Antiques. 
(bl) 
By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``He was the Pavarotti of his age.'' Thus Thomas
Hampson describes Mattia Battistini, whose nearly five-decade reign
as Don Giovanni and Rigoletto, as the William Tell of Rossini and
the Hamlet of Ambroise Thomas in opera houses from Rome to London
by way of St. Petersburg at the turn of the century featured no
episode stranger than his assumption of the title role of Jules
Massenet's ``Werther.''
</P>
<P>
   Goethe's manic-depressive standard-bearer of Sturm und Drang,
you see, entered the operatic realm as a tenor, while Battistini
was a baritone: ``the king of baritones,'' according to a phrase
that stuck. Hampson is a baritone, too, and it is Battistini's
Werther that he introduces at the Metropolitan Opera in the revival
opening Jan. 11. Massenet would no doubt approve, having prepared
this version himself.
</P>
<P>
   How singular is this case? In some ways, not at all. Since the
dawn of opera in the early 17th century, with or without
authorization from the creators, scores have been adjusted every
which way to capitalize on performers' gifts or to accommodate
their limitations. In the original printed score of Monteverdi's
``Orfeo,'' the genre's first lasting masterpiece, we discover the
hero's climactic address to the king of hell in two parallel
settings. One is plain, the other flamboyantly embellished. In the
mouth of the right singer, either stirs the heart. Stars of
Handel's and Mozart's day studded revivals of past seasons'
novelties with arias custom-tailored for them, often by hands not
the original composer's.
</P>
<P>
   As for switched vocal categories, they are scarcely rare. To
look no farther than the stable of warhorses, light sopranos
monopolized Rosina in ``Il Barbiere di Siviglia'' for generations,
never mind that Rossini intended the role for a mezzo-soprano.
Still, none of these instances match that of the baritone Werther,
whose lines Massenet's pencil rethreaded into the surrounding
musical fabric, leaving the rest untouched.
</P>
<P>
   We may never find out just how and why this curio came to be.
Paul Thomason's article ``Darkening `Werther,''' in the current
Opera News, summarizes the tale of its genesis, recent rediscovery
and only previous modern revival, by the Seattle Opera in 1991,
starring Dale Duesing. Rodney Milnes, the great Massenet champion,
provides other background in his article on the work for The New
Grove Dictionary of Opera. But mysteries remain.
</P>
<P>
   Some key points on the time line are these. Massenet completed
``Werther'' in 1887. Leon Carvalho, the director of the
Opera-Comique in Paris, dashed the composer's hopes for a premiere
at that most desirable of houses, finding the subject too morose.
</P>
<P>
   Not until 1892 did the work reach the stage, in Vienna, on the
coattails of the local premiere of ``Manon.'' The first Werther was
Ernest Van Dyck, a Belgian renowned as Wagner's Parsifal and
Lohengrin, though he failed to win Massenet's approval as Goethe's
Byronic suicide, shipwrecked on the reefs of bourgeois
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decade, productions followed in Paris, the French
provinces, the United States and Italy, but the work began really
to catch on only when the Opera-Comique (now directed by Albert
Carr) revived it in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Massenet felt that among the early exponents of the title role,
only Jean de Reszke, of Poland, was on the right track. In 1894,
his Werther made the rounds in Chicago, New York and London.
Another prize Wagnerian but less prone than the rest to
demonstrative operatic convention, de Reszke, at 44, captured the
character's unhinged quality, his vulnerability. The singer's
timbre _ dark and seductive _ was greatly admired, too; as it
happens, he began his career as a baritone.
</P>
<P>
   The Battistini version, a footnote in the performance history,
dates from 1902, when the dedicatee was 46. Who knows? If the Paris
audience, which never heard de Reszke as Werther at all, had heard
him perform the part in his prime, the baritone version might not
exist. But should the role ever have been entrusted to Wagnerians
in the first place? (Nowadays impresarios cast Werther no heavier
than a spinto; the most distinguished interpreter of the role in
the last quarter-century was Alfredo Kraus, of Spain, a lyric tenor
and proud of it.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Battistini experiment represents Massenet's last-ditch
attempt to rescue a score he loved from encroaching oblivion. Maybe
once the original found its place in the affections of the public,
the alternative lost its raison d'etre. In any case, it vanished
with Battistini, unperformed and unsought until Duesing learned of
it by chance. Hampson will be only the third singer to perform it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onstage, the more you suffer, the better,'' Placido Domingo
has said. ``It's what I like best.'' Suffering is Werther's stock
in trade, as Goethe's title, ``The Sorrows of Young Werther,''
attests. The novel, in epistolary form with editorial
interjections, contrives to present the hero both from his own
tempestuous point of view and with chilling clinical detachment:
understandably so, since, as the young Goethe knew all too well,
Werther's fate might have been his own. The hallmark of Massenet's
portrayal is compassion, yet he does not play Goethe false.
</P>
<P>
   Few roles in opera, and fewer still for baritone, combine
Werther's charismatic sheen, romantic tenderness and morbid gloom.
It stands to reason that a star among baritones would thrill to its
masochistic allure no less than the great Domingo. ``A good death
scene always helps,'' Hampson allowed recently between rehearsals
at the Met. But is grief as such what attracted him to Werther?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied. ``What attracts me are his ambiguities, the
demonstrative flaws. He's a very trying personality. Can you
imagine how intense this young man is? And there's the very complex
question of suicide as a response to one's fate.'' Like Hamlet,
another literary icon Hampson has embodied in the opera house,
Werther broods at the edge of the abyss, weighing whether to be or
not to be.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A matinee idol of deeply scholarly bent, Hampson acknowledges
certain scruples about his latest project: ``I don't want to be
busy doing `clever,' `novel' things. If there's an artistic
legitimacy that brings with it a certain novelty, fine. What
concerned me was that I would find that the baritone Werther was
just a transposition. In fact it's something else: a rewrite of the
character's psychology for a different kind of voice.''
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of the two versions bears out the subtlety of the
revisions. Given the decision to preserve the orchestration as it
was, Massenet had, note for note, fairly limited options. The
pitches in the middle range that he uses for conversational
passages could often be left alone; and in fact, they often are,
notably at the start and end of a longish musical paragraph. Where
the tenor's line soars, Massenet at times drops the pitches by two
or three steps, running the baritone's line as nearly parallel to
the tenor's as the harmony permits.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, he drops the baritone's pitches an entire
octave, surrendering the tenor's mounting excitement for a sense of
sudden emotional exhaustion in the baritone. This happens at the
very end, when the expiring hero imagines a woman coming in secret
to weep over his grave: ``and by that sweet tear, shed upon his
shade, the dead man, the poor dead man, will feel that he is
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   From Van Dyck on, interpreters of Werther have sung this on a
rising phrase, as if yearning toward that bittersweet rapture.
Battistini was asked to depart on a bleak, dying fall.
</P>
<P>
   As this instance suggests, the accumulation of microscopic
decisions indeed lends Werther a new complexion, perhaps even a new
temperament. As a general matter, of course, the phrases for
Battistini peak lower. More significant, they also tend to peak
later and more briefly, as if with greater psychic effort.
Conversely, the unaltered parlando episodes may sound more
``songful'' and less ``spoken'' _ thus more immediately emotional _
in the voice of a baritone, lying, as they do, somewhat higher in
his register and farther from neutral speech.
</P>
<P>
   On the page, the most haunting passages are those in which
Massenet seems to be rethinking the very purpose of song in
relation to words. At the climax of Werther's outburst ``Lorsque
s'ouvrait le ciel,'' the tenor hangs on to a high A flat for two
whole bars and into a third. Battistini's notes fall within the
chord, where the harmonic action is, wavering in a sob between E
flat and F flat: a far more jagged, anguished reading, and far less
concerned with vocal show.
</P>
<P>
   Werther's very first line is transformed in quite a different
way. ``Je ne sais si je veille ou si je reve encore'' is the gentle
text: I know not if I wake or if I'm dreaming still. As originally
set, it had an arching phrase: a tune. For Battistini, Massenet
stripped it down to a virtual monotone: a monotone left to the
singer's fantasy to shape and color.
</P>
<P>
   Massenet adopted this strategy of refinement by subtraction on
several later occasions, nowhere more tellingly than during
Werther's final agony, when a serene moonlit melody from the first
act returns in the orchestra. Tenors get to sing along, as if
consoled by the reminiscence. Battistini's Werther sings an
unrelated phrase, apparently deaf to the echo.
</P>
<P>
   Such passages support Hampson's belief that Massenet's
adjustments converge remarkably with Debussy's revolutionary
``Pelleas et Melisande,'' which pushed operatic expression still
farther away from vocal display into the realm of pure inflection.
Perhaps such developments were simply in the air. Debussy began
work on ``Pelleas'' in 1893, the year of the ``Werther'' premiere.
More striking still, the unveiling of ``Pelleas,'' at the
Opera-Comique, came in 1902, the year of the modified Werther.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, we may wonder whether Battistini sang the role as
Massenet reimagined it for him. Two souvenirs of the great divo's
performance exist, both sung in Italian. The robust vocalism is
mightily impressive, though as evocations of the character, the
readings seem totally off the mark. What is lacking, in this king
of baritones, is the sensitivity of a sweet (tenor) prince.
Massenet's appreciation was heartfelt all the same, though he may
have wondered why Battistini sang the opening of ``Pourquoi me
reveiller,'' Werther's best-known line, not in the strangely
dipping phrases invented just for him but in the impetuous surges
of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Skovhus, the Danish baritone whose recent album of arias on
Sony Classical also includes a tender account of this excerpt,
follows Battistini's precedent, reasoning (as Battistini may well
have done) that the bit was simply too familiar to tinker with.
Duesing took liberties, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson promises to respect the composer's second thoughts
throughout. ``I admire Battistini endlessly,'' he declares, ``but
I'm singing what Massenet wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
