<HEADLINE>
FRENCH PREMIER ASSAILS U.S. OVER IRAQ AIR STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin criticized U.S. and
British air strikes against Iraq in an interview published
Wednesday and said that France would soon be ready to propose ways
for ending the impasse with Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin told Le Monde, ``The United States often acts in a
unilateral way that undermines its ambition of mobilizing the
international community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was clear in the conflict with Iraq,'' he said. ``What's
the reality after the Anglo-American strikes? We've gone from a
situation where the entire international community, with the United
Nations, was reminding Iraq of its obligations, to a direct
confrontation between the Baghdad regime and our American and
British friends. I don't see how that's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   France, he said, was working on ideas to end the crisis in a way
that would insure ``lasting regional security'' but permit Iraq to
resume oil exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general,'' Jospin said, ``I believe there is a need for
France to assert itself more on the international scene, not
because of its power or wanting to teach anybody lessons, but
because it has a different way of seeing a certain number of
international realities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``France, a friend of the United States, does not automatically
share that great country's point of view,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac and other French officials expressed
disappointment at the British and U.S. decision to bomb Iraq in
December after it stopped cooperating with U.N. arms inspectors,
but the official French reaction held Saddam to blame for the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, a Socialist, observed in the interview with Le Monde
that presidential pronouncements on policy did not carry the same
weight now as they did when Chirac's conservatives controlled both
the presidency and the government, from 1995 to mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin is widely expected to run against Chirac in the next
presidential election, in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Put on the defensive by Le Monde about what effect his
government's plan to move to a 35-hour workweek would have on
France's 11.5 percent unemployment rate, Jospin replied that
joblessness stood at 12.6 percent when he was elected, with 190,000
more people on the unemployment rolls than at the end of last year.
Healthy economic growth stimulated by government measures created
350,000 jobs in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 35-hour week, he said it would encourage negotiations
between workers and managers at all levels of the economy on all
kinds of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the 35-hour week is not the only way to reduce
unemployment,'' he said, adding that the government would use
government money to create jobs for young people who have the most
trouble finding work.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin said that reducing juvenile delinquency and crime would
be his highest priority this year, after jobs. And asked about
growing strains within his leftist coalition, which includes
Communist and Greens ministers as well as Socialists, he said,
``Maybe we've accomplished more in 19 months than wearing ourselves
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
