<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 52 GAMES TO GO, EVERYONE IS TIED FOR FIRST  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the question that haunted the world of
professional basketball for the past six months has now been
answered, the National Basketball Association has by no means
returned to being the calm, settled and fantastic entity it once
was. Plenty of questions remain for Commissioner David Stern,
perhaps the most pressing being how to cram a six-month season into
three months while maintaining its legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   League officials were at the NBA office in Manhattan late
Wednesday night trying to work out a new schedule that will be a
mixture of the old and the new. Nothing has been solidified yet and
the league does not expect to release revamped schedules for its 29
teams until next week.
</P>
<P>
   Several players said they were told by Stern in Wednesday's
meeting that training camps probably would not open before Jan. 18.
That is also the date that players said teams will be able to start
signing the league's nearly 200 free agents. People within the
league say teams will begin playing either a 50- or 52-game
regular-season schedule the first week in February, most likely
Feb. 2. On the 82-game schedules that were released last fall,
teams play less than half of their games after Feb. 1, so 10 to 14
days will be added onto the regular season in order to play the
extra games. Thus, instead of ending the season on April 21, teams
might play into the first week of May.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the extra time, teams will be forced to play four and
sometimes five games a week rather than the typical three. Many
times, clubs will play three games in three nights. Such a format
was typical in the 1970s and early 1980s, but NBA teams have not
played on more than two consecutive days for the past decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous players admitted Wednesday that playing three straight
games would be hard on their bodies, especially after the extended
offseason. ``It's going to be tough to play back to back to back
games, but that's something we have to do as athletes,'' said
28-year-old Jimmy Jackson, one of the league's nearly 200 free
agents. ``But if you love this game, you'll do whatever it takes to
be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Johnson, who will be 40 by season's end, doesn't mind the
increased workload. ``Welcome to the old school _ that's what I
tell these young guys,'' said Johnson, who entered the league in
1981. ``I used to tell guys stories about playing three games in
three nights. Now they're going to get a taste of it for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Home games listed on the current schedules will most likely
remain the same as far as the dates are concerned, but the
opponents could change. For instance, the Knicks are scheduled to
host Orlando at Madison Square Garden on Feb. 2, but the Magic
could be replaced by another team on the new schedules that come
out next week. In an effort to retain as much equity as possible,
the league is working to insure that no team has more games on the
road than at home.
</P>
<P>
   While games that pit Eastern conference teams against Western
conference teams will be limited, the league wants to maintain
inter-conference play because of the many compelling individual
matchups that span the Eastern and Western conferences. For
example, if cross-conference games were eliminated, the Los Angeles
Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal would not face Miami's Alonzo Mourning, or
Philadelphia's Allen Iverson would not go against Minnesota's
Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   The playoff format will remain unchanged with eight teams from
each conference qualifying. Because they will start later, the
playoffs could run throughout June and into the first week of July.
They will not, however, extend to the fourth of July. Last year's
NBA finals series between Chicago and Utah ended on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   The schedules are not the only thing that will be different.
Most players said Wednesday that fans should not expect great
NBA-level basketball until March at best. ''When it starts out it's
going to be ugly, real ugly. Believe me,'' Orlando guard Nick
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why play will be many notches below
normal. While most players have been working out on their own
throughout the lockout, few, if any, of them are in game condition.
In addition to sullying the level of play, that could add to an
increase in injuries such as pulled hamstrings and sprained knees.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because almost half of the league's players are free
agents, teams will have problems with their chemistry. Teams such
as the Houston Rockets and Phoenix Suns have fewer than six players
under contract. With as many as eight or nine new faces on their
ballclubs, they will almost certainly struggle early on. ''It would
take something like a miracle to really get together on the floor
with eight new players,'' Miami's P.J. Brown said. ``It takes
longer than a couple of weeks to get chemistry and that's all the
time you're going to have.''
</P>
<P>
   In a shortened season, veteran teams that have been together for
awhile have the advantage. That's why many players feel that if
Michael Jordan retired from Chicago, the Indiana Pacers would be
the team to beat in the East. The Pacers' only free agents of note
are Rik Smits and Travis Best, and Smits is expected to resign with
Indiana. They have practiced together during much of the lockout
and are poised for a strong season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a great chance to win the championship,''
Pacers forward Antonio Davis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Utah is again a favorite in the West, with only two free agents
in Chris Morris and Antoine Carr. But San Antonio, with a nucleus
of veterans such as Avery Johnson, David Robinson and Sean Elliot
wrapped around second-year phenom Tim Duncan expects to challenge.
Johnson played with his teammates throughout the summer and fall
and hopes it pays off. ''I'm praying that the time we put in gives
us an advantage because I'll take a championship after a 10-game
season or an 80-game season,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
