<HEADLINE>
``CIVIL ACTION'' PREMIERES AMID STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston put on the fur and frills Wednesday night for a
transfusion of Hollywood star power that added a splash of Left
Coast glamour to a city facing a long New England winter.
</P>
<P>
   Searchlights swept the snowy skies above Tremont Street and
police barriers held back several hundred cheering onlookers as the
Wang Center played host to the world premiere of ``A Civil
Action,'' a $60 million film version of the best-selling book by
Northampton writer Jonathan Harr.
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrity guests parading down a 100-foot red-carpeted
walkway and into the lavishly appointed Wang lobby were ``A Civil
Action'' costars John Travolta and Robert Duvall, one an A-list box
office draw and the other an acclaimed Academy Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta arrived, unescorted and wearing a topcoat, just before
the film's scheduled 7:30 p.m. start. The actor, who portrays
crusading Boston attorney Jan Schlichtmann in the movie, was given
a megastar's reception as he strode into the theater lobby, pausing
to give impromptu interviews and sign autographs for a crush of
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had bothered with the coat, Travolta quipped, ``I'm
from Maine. When I left this morning, it was 9 below.''
</P>
<P>
   About the Boston opening, he added, ``I think it's great. I love
the atmosphere here. And I feel connected to both the movie and the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Duvall made his entrance, also unescorted, roughly 30 minutes
before Travolta. Dressed in a dark-blue suit, Duvall, who portrays
Hale and Dorr attorney Jerome Facher onscreen, waved warmly to the
cheering throng.
</P>
<P>
   Facher himself had an awkard moment when he arrived at the
theater and after fumbling around could not locate his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will a stub from Fenway Park do?'' asked the attorney whose
obsession with the Red Sox is one of the film's leitmotifs.
</P>
<P>
   The film's two marquee stars, both mentioned in early reviews as
possible Oscar nominees for their performances, rubbed elbows with
many of the real-life players in the Woburn chemical-spill case.
More than 850 invitees, some paying as much as $5,000 per table,
jammed into the Wang Center to nibble on smoked salmon and beef
tenderloin, sip Chardonnay, and mingle with the cast and crew of
the film, which shot location scenes in and around Boston last
year.
</P>
<P>
   To a city whose last brush with Hollywood stardust came almost a
year ago, when local heroes Matt Damon and Ben Affleck copped an
Oscar for ``Good Will Hunting,'' these were heady times indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Computer honcho William Podeska and his wife Susan glided
into the Wang Center saying, ``We're just here to see a movie.''
Which sounded a bit like going to L'Espalier just for the dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Ricci of Sharon, draped in a lush white mink coat with
fox trim, said she had bought her ticket to support the Jimmy Fund,
one of three local charities benefitting from the event. The others
are the Dana Farber Cancer Institute and Boston's Ronald McDonald
House, which serves children with cancer and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Most attendees no doubt showed up for some combination of all
three elements: to see the stars, to view the film, and to eat,
drink, and be merry on behalf of a worthy cause. The buffet dinner,
staged on all four levels of the Wang Center lobby, did not get
under way until well after 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of protestors outside the Wang Center made their
presence felt. Signs were held aloft calling attention to other
toxic-waste sites around the Commonwealth. W.R. Grace's proposed
expansion into North Cambridge was also the object of protest.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's event and its posh trappings stood in marked
contrast to the years of personal suffering and legal maneuvering
that marked the Woburn case. Among the families that brought suit
against W.R. Grace and Beatrice Foods for allegedly contaminating
their drinking water, five children and one adult died of leukemia.
Harr's book chronicled the decade-long effort to hold the companies
accountable for the contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``A Civil Action'' opened late last year for limited
runs in New York and Los Angeles, Wednesday night's screening was
considered the film's official world premiere. For Boston, that is
indeed a rarity. And when Hollywood designates an event as such,
all the stops _ plus plenty of champagne corks _ are typically
pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   A robust contingent of national media did turn out to cover the
premiere, however. Correspondents from CNN, ``Access Hollywood,''
``Entertainment Tonight,'' and the E! Channel beamed their
broadcasts to a national audience. WRKO radio host Howie Carr, who
plays himself in a brief scene opposite Travolta, basked in the
media spotlight as well.
</P>
<P>
   It was a friendly crowd, too. As the curtain went up on ``A
Civil Action'' and the screen was filled with a sweeping shot of
the Charles River, the roar was loud enough to hear all the way out
in Hollywood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
