<HEADLINE>
FINDINGS OF TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER PANEL RAISE DISCLOSURE ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House extended Wednesday the life of a special
committee in order to expedite the release of the committee's still
secret report on Chinese acquisition of U.S. technology.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will consult with the Clinton administration and
intelligence agencies over how quickly parts of the report can be
made public. Congress said the select committee would continue
until April 1 in order to get out the report soon, but already
there are complications.
</P>
<P>
   The White House received the 700-page report Monday night but
has allowed the rest of the government to read only the report's 38
recommendations, not its findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk of the report is being reviewed by law enforcement
officials to insure that no ongoing criminal investigation is
affected by circulation of the report,'' a White House spokesman,
David Leavy, said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee gave immunity to some witnesses who had been
involved in the transfer by U.S. satellite makers of space know-how
to China, administration officials said. These transfers are being
investigated by a federal grand jury here.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the witnesses could not be learned. But lawyers
familiar with the investigation said that the Justice Department
had reviewed the immunity arrangement and was working to insure
that federal investigations were not tainted by congressional
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the report focused on areas that overlap with federal
law enforcement responsibilities, including China's diversion of
machining equipment and the theft of nuclear design secrets from
U.S. weapons laboratories, officials who worked with the committee
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings can be declassifed by a vote of the House
after consultation with the administration and the House Permanent
Select Committee on Intelligence. The White House has pledged to
work with the special China committee, whose five Republicans and
four Democrats unanimously approved the report last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the report relies on highly classified data
and intersects with continuing criminal investigations will
complicate the balancing of the public's right to know with the
needs of law enforcement and intelligence officials.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman, Christopher Cox, R-Calif., said the needs
of national security shift the balance toward public disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very much in the national security interest to
declassify these findings,'' Cox said. ``There is no advantage
gained from covering up the findings.''
</P>
<P>
   The special committee, formally called the Select Committee on
United States National Security and Military/Commercial Concerns
with the People's Republic of China, was created last June and was
due to expire last week. It held 33 closed hearings and took
testimony from more than 100 witnesses, some of whom told the
members that much of their findings, while potentially explosive
and sensitive, could be declassified, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of what to disclose is usually resolved by the release
of general findings and the withholding of details that might
reveal how the sensitive information was acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's recommendations include ways to strengthen the
export control process, tighten security at American nuclear
laboratories and improve the handling and distribution of sensitive
intelligence data.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
