u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-WALLSTREET-     01-06 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-WALLSTREET-REGS-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIERS PLAN TO PUT CONTROLS ON DERIVATIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Conn., Texas) 
 (nk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON and TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the blessing of the federal government, some
of the world's largest financial institutions reached an agreement
Wednesday to try to set their own industry-wide standards in the
huge and volatile market of complex securities known as
derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   By setting its own voluntary guidelines, the industry hopes to
both prevent recurrences of the problems that have arisen in the
derivatives markets and keep stricter regulations from being
imposed by Washington. But previous attempts at self-regulation in
the derivatives markets have met with limited success. They did
little to stave off the near-collapse last September of Long-Term
Capital Management L.P., the huge Connecticut hedge fund. Long-Term
Capital had invested heavily in derivatives, which are financial
contracts that are supposed to manage a company's risks,
particularly during turbulent changes in the economic climate.
</P>
<P>
   Executives involved in crafting the agreement, which will be
formally announced on Thursday, said the group would begin to write
a set of industry guidelines by late spring, governing everything
from trading practices to lending standards and disclosure
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached in Manhattan at a meeting of top
executives from 12 leading foreign and domestic institutions and
senior federal officials including Arthur Levitt Jr., chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission. The agreement was warmly
embraced by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury
Secretary Robert E. Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin heads an interagency group that is considering what
changes may be necessary in the largely unregulated and steadily
growing market in derivatives, so named because their value is
derived from underlying products such as stocks, bonds or
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   It also illustrates a decided policy position by the Treasury
Department and regulators that both the underwriters and the
traders of these financial instruments have a pivotal role in
policing themselves, a view shared by Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will enable practitioners to implement the latest
improvements in risk management and to begin the cycle of
innovation all over again,'' said one senior executive on the
committee, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Russo, an authority on derivatives regulation and
managing director at Lehman Brothers, one of the companies serving
on the group, said the formation of the group ``is highly
significant and a credit to the government regulators for
encouraging a private initiative to have global best practices in
the risk-management area.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts disagreed and were either critical of the
effort or skeptical of what it would ultimately achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the fox guarding the henhouse,'' said Charles
Peabody, a banking analyst with Mitchell Securities Inc. in New
York. ``There's an inherent conflict because you won't police
something too carefully if you're making a lot of money on it. That
was the lesson of Long-Term Capital, and that's why you need an
independent outside regulator.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hu, a derivatives expert and professor at the University
of Texas Law School, said: ``To the extent that it establishes
norms about how people should behave, I think it is a good thing
because the people being regulated know more about the products
than the regulators. But a lot depends on whether it's merely
aspirational or meant to be mandatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Others questioned whether a group of companies with deeply
conflicting financial interests would be capable of mustering
consensus on the kinds of regulatory issues where agreement has
proved to be elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and industry executives praised the idea
Wednesday. Administration officials involved in an interagency
group set up after the collapse of Long-Term Capital and led by
Rubin said that its conclusions would not be affected by the
industry's work. Washington has so far moved cautiously in
formulating any new regulations on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industry group's members were involved in the
bailout of Long-Term Capital. The hedge fund, which borrowed
heavily and threatened to wreak havoc on the financial markets when
its investments began to sour, was rescued by Wall Street at the
intervention of officials from the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the companies involved in the new group have recently
taken significant hits on their earnings from either their
investments in Long-Term Capital or their investments in
derivatives, despite the intended role of derivatives as a tool of
risk management.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An American company doing business in Great Britain, for
example, might buy an option on the pound to protect itself against
a decline in the currency that could hurt its profits, posted in
dollars. Such a derivative is a standardized contract that trades
on regulated financial exchanges. But many other kinds of
derivative contracts are tailored for specific parties. In interest
rate swaps, for example, one party agrees to exchange a fixed
interest rate for a floating rate with another specific party for a
specified period. These kinds of contracts are traded over the
counter and remain off banks' balance sheets, making them difficult
for regulators to handle.
</P>
<P>
   The derivatives market has boomed over the last decade to become
one of the most lucrative activities on Wall Street. About $37
trillion worth of privately traded derivatives contracts are
outstanding, up from $865 billion in 1987, according to the
International Swap and Derivatives Association. That figure,
however, represents the paper, or ``notional,'' value of all of the
underlying financial products used to create a derivatives
contract. The actual exposure of most banks to the derivatives
contracts they carry is only a small percentage of the paper value,
in most cases well less than 1 percent of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   E. Gerald Corrigan, former president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York who is now a senior executive at Goldman, Sachs, and
Stephen G. Thieke, a top official at J.P. Morgan, will be
co-chairmen of the industry group. The other members of the group
are Barclays, Bear Stearns, Chase, Citigroup, Credit Suisse,
Deutsche Bank, Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and UBS.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for the banks' derivatives proposal was a meeting
convened in December by Levitt at Morgan Stanley's New York
headquarters. Two other investment banking firms _ Goldman, Sachs
and J.P. Morgan _ also were represented at that meeting, where it
was decided that Corrigan and Thieke would oversee the working
group assigned to create the self-regulatory proposal. Wednesday's
meeting was also held at Morgan Stanley's headquarters, and many of
the group's chairmen attended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2128EST &QL; 
