u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS TO PUSH FOR A TAX CUT OF UP TO $500 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: $1.8 trillion CQ in 6th graf.) 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Key Republicans in the House and the Senate said
Wednesday that they planned to push for a tax cut of as much as
$500 billion over the next decade, including cuts in income tax
rates, to take advantage of federal budget surpluses that appear to
be growing faster than previously projected.
</P>
<P>
   Even a general agreement on an approach would be a marked change
from the bitter fight among House and Senate Republicans last year
over how hard to push for tax cuts. The proposals are still in
tentative form, and aides said working out the details would be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort represents a concerted challenge to President
Clinton's strategy of blocking any substantial tax cuts until after
Congress and the administration settle on a plan to shore up Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts would probably be dependent on the surpluses
actually materializing, and would be financed only by that part of
the surpluses that do not come from excess Social Security tax
revenue, members of Congress and their aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, nearly all of the surpluses over the next decade have
been projected to come from Social Security taxes beyond what is
needed to pay current beneficiaries. As a result, Republican
tax-cutting plans have been attacked by the president and
congressional Democrats on the ground that they would endanger the
retirement system, which is already facing long-term financial
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But new estimates of the surplus being developed by the
Congressional Budget Office suggest that about $500 billion of the
$1.8 trillion in surpluses likely to materialize in the next decade
could come from outside Social Security, and that the non-Social
Security surpluses could begin showing up in sizable amounts as
soon as 2001, Republican aides said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also mounting political pressure on Republicans. With
their poll ratings plummeting as they pursue the ouster of Clinton,
Republicans are scrambling to present a positive agenda. Most of
the party's leaders see tax cutting as the most potent tool
available.
</P>
<P>
   But if they press ahead, they could find themselves in a heated
battle with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The president announced Wednesday that the White House now
expected the surplus for the current fiscal year to be $76 billion,
as compared to the last estimate from the Congressional Budget
Office of $63 billion. But Clinton vowed to continue opposing tax
cuts and spending increases that use the surplus until the
government deals with Social Security's looming financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any family with long-term financial needs and a little
more earnings than expected, we can't go out and spend the surplus
today,'' the president said in announcing the surplus forecast at
the White House. ``We have to plan for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 1999 fiscal year ends in a surplus, it will be the second
consecutive year after 29 years of deficits. In the fiscal year
1998 the government recorded a surplus of $70 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, whose tax-cutting efforts were paralyzed last year
by Clinton's Social Security strategy, now say they are
increasingly comfortable that they can cut taxes while assuring
voters that they are setting aside more than enough money for any
overhaul of Social Security. The White House had hoped to reach a
bipartisan agreement early this year on dealing with Social
Security, but negotiations on the issue have all but ceased because
of the impeachment proceedings against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan being considered by Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M.,
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, across-the-board
reductions in income tax rates could be phased in as the non-Social
Security surplus grows in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said one idea under consideration was to create a
``trigger'' that would put the tax cuts into effect only when the
surpluses actually materialized, so the cuts would not push the
budget into deficit if the economy and tax revenue faltered. The
Congressional Budget Office will release updated surplus estimates
at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans pushed hard last year for a big tax cut, but
found little support from their colleagues in the Senate, who were
more cautious about crossing Clinton on Social Security. Domenici
and his counterpart in the House, Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio,
chairman of the House Budget Committee, were at odds throughout
much of the year. Because of the impasse, Congress failed for the
first time in 25 years to adopt a basic tax and spending blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   But the approach being developed by Domenici and his staff
appears to have support in the House as well. Kasich said in an
interview that he had spoken with Domenici about the plan on
Tuesday, and that although it was too early to say how House
Republicans would respond, he was encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that Senator Domenici wants not only to reform Social
Security but to have substantial tax relief is music to my ears,''
Kasich said, adding that an across-the-board cut in income taxes of
as much as 10 percent ``is something I believe in very strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, has argued since last year that there is enough money to
deal with Social Security and cut taxes at the same time. Although
they would not be specific, aides to Archer said he wanted to focus
this year on tax cuts that would promote economic growth, a phrase
usually used to refer to rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
   There is likely to be continuing tension among Republicans,
though, over how hard to push for across-the-board tax cuts at the
expense of tax breaks favored by social conservatives, particularly
a reduction in the marriage penalty paid by many two-income
couples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
