<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REEVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINE OR COACHES' BOOTH? REEVES WILL DECIDE SOON. 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since he needed just two years to turn a franchise best known
for losing into a division champion with Super Bowl aspirations,
perhaps it's no surprise that Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves
plans another extraordinary comeback this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six days after quadruple-bypass surgery, and just 16 days
after his release from the hospital following minor complications
from that surgery, Reeves plans to be on the Falcons' sideline for
Saturday's playoff game with the San Francisco 49ers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will wait until Thursday or maybe even as late as
Saturday morning to make a final decision on whether he will watch
the game from the sideline or from the assistant coaches' booth
above the field, but Reeves said he was leaning toward assuming all
his normal coaching duties _ calling plays and patrolling the bench
area.
</P>
<P>
   The former New York Giants and Denver Broncos coach, however,
will make one concession to the circumstances of the last four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go out there screaming like I do sometimes,''
the 54-year-old Reeves said. ``But there are still going to be
times I'll holler _ if my heart allows me, which I hope it will.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days, Reeves has supervised his first Falcons
drills since his heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta safety Eugene Robinson said Reeves acted the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he never left,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, meanwhile, acknowledged he has felt better than he
expected to feel this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting more energy every day and that's really what will
be the determining factor in any decision I make,'' Reeves said.
``I'll gauge my energy level after our three practices this week.
I've been cleared medically to try to be on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't lift more than 30 pounds but I don't plan on my game
plan weighing that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has prepared for the 49ers with his coaching staff as he
normally would _ again, with minor concessions. As other coaches
watch film and analyze 49er tendencies, Reeves has occasionally
reclined on a couch in his office to relax as he watches the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't normally do that,'' said Reeves, whose daily
exercise has also included two 15-minute treadmill workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Reeves insists he anticipates a normal recovery. And
he denied rumors that his health may force a retirement from
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed,'' he said. ``There was no damage to the
heart. I've been assured that if anything, I'll feel better. I feel
good about the prognosis and about what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably would be more stress to be out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is also how Reeves feels about Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have wondered if I should go to the game,'' he
said. ``But it would be more stressful not to be there wondering
what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Convalescing at home and in Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta, he did
watch his Falcons win their final two regular-season games without
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't miss me, that's for sure,'' Reeves said with a
laugh. ``That actually was kind of fun for me because I stepped
away from it and watched the game like an outsider looking in. I'd
rather have been there, but there was some benefit to observing
from the outside, too.''
</P>
<P>
   His Falcons finished 14-2, an astounding 11-victory improvement
over the 1996 team Reeves inherited.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's beyond my wildest expectations,'' Reeves said. ``Our
goal was to get to 10-6. There was no way I thought we'd be 14-2.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not only the best record in franchise history, it is also
the Falcons' 10th winning season since joining the National
Football League 33 years ago. Atlanta won the National Football
Conference West title for the second time and for the first time
since the 49ers began their run as the dominant team in the
division in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Falcons find themselves favored to defeat the
famed 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we beat them at home earlier this year, it gave us a huge
boost of confidence,'' Reeves said. ``Because they had beaten us
before and beaten us badly. When we got past that, our fans
believed in us, too. There's no question there will be an
electricity in the stadium Saturday and that's because it's the
49ers we're trying to get past.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said: ``Who would have thought the Falcons would be
playing for the Super Bowl? It starts with San Francisco. That's a
great story.''
</P>
<P>
   A great story with an added twist, since the architect of the
turnaround plans to lead his charges just days since leaving his
hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to take total responsibility on the sideline,''
Reeves said. ``I just have to be smart when I'm out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
