<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF ACCORD MAY MEAN LENGTHY IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate will embark on a new course in modern
history Thursday as President Clinton goes on trial for alleged
``high crimes and misdemeanors'' amid widespread confusion and
rising anxiety about how the momentous proceedings will unfold and
when they might end.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's presidency at stake, Senate leaders remained
stymied Wednesday night in their attempts to forge a pretrial plan
to conduct the potentially explosive proceedings in a reasonably
swift, fair and dignified manner.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Senate is likely to hold ``a full trial'' that
will last a month or longer, said the majority leader, Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate left in limbo nearly every key player in the
drama, as Representative Henry J. Hyde, chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, prepared to launch the process by reciting the
two articles of impeachment to the divided Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate convicts Clinton, on charges that he committed
perjury and obstructed justice in trying to cover up his sexual
affair with a former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky, he
would be the first president to be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Fracturing the Senate was intense disagreement over whether Hyde
and 12 other House Republicans who will serve as managers, or
prosecutors, in the impeachment trial will be permitted to present
a relatively lengthy case by calling as many as 15 witnesses,
including Lewinsky, Clinton's friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr., and
several White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Senate's 55 Republicans support calling at least
some witnesses, according to several GOP senators. But the Senate
minority leader, Thomas A. Daschle, said Democrats share
``universal, unanimous opposition'' to calling witnesses, which he
said could prolong the trial for ``a matter of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott was pushing a possible compromise Wednesday night that
would permit senators to debate and vote on each prospective
witness requested by the House managers. A majority of 51 senators
would be required to approve each witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would want to know, `What is that witness going to do?' ''
Lott told reporters. He said the plan could allow the Senate to
complete the trial by Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an agreement on that plan, several GOP senators said,
Lott was circulating a proposal that would permit the House
managers to call between five and eight witnesses during a trial
that also could last about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said there was no hope left of reviving
a plan to hold a four-day proceeding next week, followed by a
``test vote'' that would end the process unless 67 senators voted
to continue to a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the standoff, Lott and Daschle waged an exhaustive struggle
to build support for any feasible compromise in the face of
enormous pressures on many fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators from both parties in the House and Senate continued
to haggle behind closed doors Wednesday night. And party leaders
said the talks could go on until 1 p.m. Thursday, when Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist is sworn in as the presiding officer
and all 100 senators take an oath to deliver ``impartial justice''
as they serve as jurors and judges in the historic case.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will be recessed after Thursday's swearing-in ceremony
and will resume next week at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to continue to talk and narrow the list of questions
and come forward with a proposal,'' Lott said Wednesday night on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the plan could be ``one that neither the House nor the
White House will necessarily think is wonderful, but will give all
parties a fair chance to make a case and get to a conclusion that
is an equitable one.''
</P>
<P>
   But resistance from nearly all 45 Senate Democrats and a small
number of Republicans is expected to remain a major roadblock to a
full trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the preference of the majority of the US Senate is not
to have witnesses,'' said Senator John F. Kerry, who is chairman of
the Senate Democratic Steering and Coordination Committee. ``I
don't think this will be resolved by tomorrow,'' he said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy also objected strongly to the
possiblity of a prolonged trial. ``The House process was tainted by
partisanship,'' Kennedy said. ``The Senate has no obligation to try
to validate what the House did by holding a full trial.''
</P>
<P>
   If a potentially lengthy trial begins Thursday, Kennedy said, a
motion to effectively dismiss the charges could be filed as early
as next week. The motion would require 51 votes for passage.
</P>
<P>
   For senators and their parties, the stakes were extraordinarily
high as the trial drew closer. A number of senators expressed
concern as they shuttled between impeachment meetings and
festivities marking the opening of the 106th Congress. At times,
the scene was surreal as many lawmakers celebrated over Chardonnay
and canapes amid the tense buildup to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nervousness among everybody here that this has to be
done right and the American people have to have some confidence in
it,'' said Senator Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican. ``The sense
among most of us is that it would be very dangerous to go forward
without a pretrial agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton's legal team expressed frustration
over the lingering uncertainty in the final hours before the trial.
Although Clinton's aides and attorneys said they are preparing for
the possibility of a full-scale trial, including calling their own
witnesses, they said the Senate's failure to provide any ground
rules has seriously impaired their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult when you are on the eve of the trial and
wanting to know what lies ahead and...it's a moving target,'' said
James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   This much was certain Wednesday night, according to Lott and his
aides:
</P>
<P>
   After Hyde and his House colleagues recite House Resolution 611,
which contains the articles of impeachment, the Senate sergeant of
arms will deliver a summons to the White House, notifying Clinton
that the trial has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist also will be formally notified, then will be escorted
into the Senate chamber by a battery of five senators, three
Republicans and two Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Strom Thurmond, the 96-year-old South Carolina
Republican who serves as president pro tempore of the Senate, is
scheduled to swear in Rehnquist. The chief justice then will
administer the oath to the senators, who will swear ``to do
impartial justice according to the Constitution and the laws, so
help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, ``there are a lot of gaps around,'' Lott
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the lawmakers trying to resolve the impasse was
Senator Olympia J. Snowe, a Maine Republican who urged Lott
Wednesday to push a plan that would require the House managers and
Clinton's lawyers to submit written briefs between Jan. 11 and Jan.
15 so senators can better decide how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In particular, it will enable the senators to make an informed
decision regarding the need for the submission of additional
evidence and, if so, in what form and over what period of time,''
Snowe wrote in a letter to Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Republican senators from New England said Snowe's
plan was part of a broad mix of possible alternatives under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Judd Gregg, a Republican who lives in maple syrup
country in New Hampshire, said lawamkers were engaged in a
``sugaring off'' process to distill the issues and reach a possible
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters was the insistence of some House managers
that such current and former White House advisers as Bruce E.
Lindsey, Sidney Blumenthal and Dick Morris be compelled to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Lindsey Graham, a South Carolina Republican, said
calling such witnesses would help determine Clinton's state of mind
during the circumstances surrounding the obstruction of justice
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat who
cosponsored the unsuccessful, bipartisan plan to complete the
impeachment process next week, echoed many other Democrats in
asserting there is no need to hear witnesses because of the breadth
of sworn testimony that already has been taken. And he clung to a
hope that a compromise based on his plan could still be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still broad bipartisan interest in achieving a kind
of open trial that will not get out of control and damage the
country and divide the Senate,'' Lieberman said. ``I think it's
still viable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ann Scales of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
