<HEADLINE>
MARKET INDEXES REACH NEW HIGHS IN BROAD ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rocketed to new heights Wednesday, with
the Dow Jones industrial average breaking the 9,500 mark as it
climbed 233.78 points, the biggest gain since Oct. 15, to pass its
previous record set just before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip gauge joined the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock and
Nasdaq composite indexes in uncharted territory as investors threw
bonuses, dividends, holiday gifts and retirement and reinvestment
money into the market at the beginning of the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas markets also powered ahead, with gains in Europe, the
Far East and Brazil mostly equaling the American performance.
Mexico, however, fell slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new-year rally has got real legs,'' said David Dietze,
president of Point View Financial Services in Summit, N.J.
``Instead of just big-cap and tech stocks doing well, the sectors
broadened out to include financials, energy and some deep
cyclicals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which rose 2.51 percent, to 9,544.97, was paced by
American Express, up 4 5/16, to 103|, and J.P. Morgan, up 3~, to
111\. But four other components surged more than 3 points, six rose
2 or more and only IBM, off ~, at 188}, was lower.
</P>
<P>
   Even steel stocks, which by some measures are at their lowest
point in a generation, caught fire Wednesday after an analyst at
Merrill Lynch raised his ratings and price targets for various
companies. USX-U.S. Steel jumped 2 15/16, to 27 7/16, and Bethlehem
Steel added 1 5/16, to 10 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar Tree Stores, which paced the retail group, soared 5 5/16,
to 48{, after the discounter reported a big gain in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stocks benefiting from the settlement of the National
Basketball Association labor dispute, which will salvage more than
half the season, were Boston Celtics, up 4[, to 14|, and Nike, up 2
15/16, to 43|.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was heavy as the market started strong and worked
steadily higher until just after 3 p.m., when it reached a Dow peak
of 9,608.05 before plateauing to the close.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was 986.9 million shares,
the fifth-busiest day on record, while 1.2 billion shares changed
hands on Nasdaq, the most in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues on the Big Board, whose own composite index
also set a record at 611.01, outnumbered declining issues by 2,009
to 1,120, with 154 stocks making new highs and 15 new lows.
</P>
<P>
   The gain for the S&AMP;P 500 was 27.56 points, to a new high of
1,272.34, or 2.21 percent, somewhat less than the blue-chip Dow
industrials. The Nasdaq gain was 69.59, to a new high of 2,320.86,
or 3.09 percent. Microsoft, up 4}, to 151\, and Intel, up 6\, to
129{, contributed to the jump, but Yahoo, up 33[, to 291, and
Amazon.com, up 13{, to 138, had the more eye-popping moves.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines also saw prominent gains as Delta Air Lines climbed 5,
to 59{; UAL rose 4], to 68, and AMR added 3 13/16, to 67~. Brokers
also thrived, the biggest gains being 4 7/16, to 53|, for Lehman
Brothers; 4|, to 58~, for Charles Schwab, and 4 9/16, to 41 15/16,
for Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Gains in leading foreign markets amounted to 3.41 percent in
Frankfurt, 3.2 percent in London, 2.24 percent in Paris, 3.09
percent in Sao Paulo, 3.47 percent in Hong Kong and 1.78 percent in
Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
