<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE BELIEVES TIME IS RIGHT TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Rhode Island coach Jim Harrick returned to
campus recently and reminded Pepperdine of what the basketball
program used to be. Not maliciously, but rather with great pride.
</P>
<P>
   It was during an era when NIT appearances were considered a
disappointment and an NCAA bid brought expectations of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   But it's been five seasons since the Waves made the postseason,
the longest drought since the mid-1970s. There is pressure, mostly
from within, to restore Pepperdine's basketball glory. And to do so
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get that Pepperdine tradition back,'' sophomore
guard David Lalazarian said. ``We have to start winning
championships here to get that tradition back. Not just this year,
but for a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   That biggest step can be taken with three straight wins at the
West Coast Conference tournament in seven weeks. But the process of
manicuring the path to a top seed, and subsequently an easier draw
in the conference tournament, begins today.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, selected to finish second in the WCC by the coaches,
open league play at Portland at 7 p.m. before heading to preseason
favorite Gonzaga on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to put ourselves back up there, and we have
the team to do it,'' Pepperdine guard Jelani Gardner said. ``The
history here is something we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine used to be a regular participant in the postseason,
especially during the Harrick years. From 1979 until 1994, the
Waves reached the NCAA Tournament eight times and played in the NIT
on four occasions.
</P>
<P>
   During that run the Waves never went more than one season
without a postseason appearance. But not since an overtime loss to
Michigan in the first round of the 1994 NCAAs have the Waves played
after the West Coast Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The program bottomed out in third-year coach Lorenzo Romar's
first season, a dreadful 6-21 campaign, but is now cresting.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the talent we have, with the defensive pressure we can
apply, we can get back to the days of when Pepperdine played
against Michigan in the first round and almost won,'' said
sophomore forward Kelvin Gibbs, a Bellflower High graduate. ``I
didn't learn about the tradition until I came here, and then all
the old players would come back and play with us, and we got to
know them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's when Gibbs, along with most of the other Waves, became
aware of the program with the second-best winning percentage (.604)
in Southern California over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   It's how the current Waves learned about the 38-game conference
winning streak in the early 1990s, and about the 30-game home
winning streak in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is one of the best teams Pepperdine's had in a
while, and we feel we should be able to achieve the same things
they did,'' Gibbs said. ``It'll be a disappointment if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why there's urgency to win this season. Because Gardner,
defensive stalwart Tommie Prince and forward Marc McDowell _ the
core of the Waves _ are seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Romar wanted to toughen his team for conference play so he put
Kansas, Rhode Island, Michigan State and Wisconsin on the preseason
schedule. The Waves (9-6) lost three of those games, but each was a
one-possession game in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the pieces are coming together, we like our team and
we think we have a nucleus to do well in the conference,'' Romar
said. ``It's whether we want to work hard enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
