u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JEFFERSON-HEMINGS-     01-06 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JEFFERSON-HEMINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va.) JEFFERSON'S DEFENDERS RENEW CRITICISM OF DNA ANALYSIS  By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DNA evidence of Thomas Jefferson's presumed affair with his
slave, Sally Hemings, continues to reverberate, with defenders of
the third president arguing that others in Jefferson's family could
have fathered her children.
</P>
<P>
   A DNA analysis of living descendants of Thomas Jefferson,
reported in November last year, was interpreted to show that
Jefferson had fathered at least one child with Hemings. Unease
about the certainty of that conclusion has been expressed by an
amateur historian who has had a rival theory and by the principal
author of the DNA study.
</P>
<P>
   The historian, Herbert Barger, whose wife is a Jefferson
descendant, said at a news conference in Washington Wednesday that
any of several of males in the Jefferson family could have fathered
Eston Hemings, the child whose descendants bear the Jefferson Y
chromosome.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the DNA analysis, Dr. Eugene A. Foster, complains
in a letter published in Thursday's issue of Nature that the
headline the journal put on his original study _ ``Jefferson
fathered slave's last child'' _ was misleading. Foster, a retired
pathology professor, said he concluded only that it was more
probable that Thomas Jefferson was Eston's father, rather than
other individuals suspected at the time, two of Jefferson's nephews
on his sister's side.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Joseph J. Ellis, author of a recent biography of
Jefferson, said the arguments of Barger and others had not changed
his view of the persuasiveness of the DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In his book on Jefferson, Ellis, like a long line of
Jeffersonian scholars, rejected the story of a liaison with Sally
Hemings, a charge first made during Jefferson's lifetime by a
political opponent. But he changed his mind after reading Foster's
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had originally believed the likelihood of a relationship was
remote,'' Ellis said. ``The new evidence persuaded me that I had
been wrong, and I felt a kind of moral and professional obligation
to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestions being made by Barger and others are
scientifically possible, Ellis said. They hinge on analysis of the
Y chromosome, which is passed unchanged from father to son,
allowing male lineages to be traced far back in history.
</P>
<P>
   But the available historical evidence does not match up with any
of the other candidates as tightly as it does with Thomas
Jefferson. The salient piece of evidence, gathered by the historian
Dumas Malone, is that Jefferson was present at Monticello at the
times of conception of all of Sally Hemings' children.
</P>
<P>
   The people arguing against Jefferson's liaison ``believe it
undermines his historical reputation,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel they are running against the steady current of the
evidence,'' Ellis added. ``The DNA study by Dr. Foster has
fundamentally altered the character of the debate in such a way as
to persuade me beyond a reasonable doubt that Jefferson fathered at
least one and as many as four of Hemings' children.''
</P>
<P>
   How could so many distinguished historians, from Malone to
Ellis, have misread the evidence when others interpreted it
correctly? For example Annette Gorden-Reed, an associate professor
at New York Law School in her book ``Thomas Jefferson and Sally
Hemings: An American Controversy'' marshaled the evidence from a
lawyer's point of view and concluded the historians were probably
wrong, a view subsequently confirmed by the DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon-Reed, who is African-American, asserts that the
historians erred because they approached the question from a racist
point of view, discounting the testimony of Eston Hemings that
Thomas Jefferson was the father of Sally Hemings' children and that
he had promised her the children would be freed, as almost uniquely
among Jefferson's slaves, they were.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said that Gordon-Reed's diagnosis of some of the
historians was correct but that ``it doesn't correctly and
accurately assess most of the scholarship on Jefferson of the last
20 to 25 years, which has been much more critical of Jefferson.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that prior to the DNA evidence there was compelling
evidence on both sides of the liaison issue. Jefferson's
contemporaries did not believe the accusation, first made in a
Richmond, Va., newspaper after the birth of Hemings' first son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would have been unduly reckless of Jefferson to
have continued the relationship when under scrutiny,'' Ellis said,
``but we recently have had reason to recognize that presidents of
the United States are perfectly capable of that degree of
recklessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis also noted that the character of Jefferson as it emerges
from his voluminous correspondence makes it extremely hard for
readers to believe he would have had an illicit relationship of any
kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you immerse yourself in the Jefferson papers,'' Ellis
said, ``the more difficult it becomes to imagine a liaison between
Jefferson and Sally Hemings. It's ironic, the more grounded you
are, the more likely you are to get this wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
