<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky tops witness list
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON_ As House prosecutors floated the names of witnesses
they would like to call in Presidetn Clinton's impeachment trial,
they also worked to dampen fears that such testimony would fill the
august Senate chamber with sex talk.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the witness wish list is Monica Lewinsky, the
former White House intern. Lewinsky's illicit relationship with the
president and her tape-recorded descriptions of it are the
underpinnings for the case against Clinton. The release of her
graphic grand jury testimony, included in independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's report to Congress, drew numerous complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans are not eager to witness a repeat. But Rep.
Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.), one of 13 House prosecutors, said, ``We
don't have to go into all the (sexual) details.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said any questioning of Lewinsky would be in a
limited fashion, focusing on the obstruction of justice charge
against Clinton. For example, she could be asked in greater detail
about Clinton's efforts to help her find a job.
</P>
<P>
   The same issue likely would await Clinton secretary Betty
Currie, another potential witness identified by Hutchinson.
Republicans in the House were persuaded that Clinton sought to
obstruct Starr's investigation, in part, by attemtping to coach
Currie about the details of his White House meetings with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Currie acted as a conduit for messages between Lewinsky and the
president. She was also the keeper of several gifts Clinton gave
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson also identified presidential friend Vernon Jordan as
a possible witness prosecutors would like to call. Jordan, who
appeared several times before the grand jury, would most likely be
asked to explain his role in helping Lewinsky find a job in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will seek to establish that the job search was part
of Clinton's scheme to derail Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) said he would like to interview
aides that were close to the president in an effort to uncover the
president's ``state of mind'' when he allegedly tried to cover up
his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides such as Sidney Blumenthal and Bruce Lindsey
could be subpoenaed to talk about how Clinton falsely denied that
he was having an affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Former aides such as Dick Morris could also be called to set the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, a former federal prosecutor, said the prosecutors
could present their case within two weeks. The big question mark is
whether they will be given that much time by the Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
