<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-HOMICIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GUN HOMICIDES BY YOUNG PEOPLE  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   The continuing decline in homicides in New York City and
elsewhere last year is cause for celebration, but it does not end
the need for strict gun-control laws. A new Justice Department
study shows that while the nation's overall homicide rate fell in
1997 to its lowest level in three decades, the number of firearm
homicides by young people remains alarmingly high. The report
offers no explanation for this discrepancy. But criminologists
point to the phenomenal spread of illegal handguns among young
people that began with the start of the crack epidemic around 1985
as a major reason for the continuing high level of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The number of firearm homicides committed by Americans 25 and
older declined remarkably between 1980 and 1997, by about 50
percent. But those committed by 18-to-24-year-olds actually
increased during that period by about the same percentage. The
6,076 killings by this age group in 1997, though fewer than the
all-time record of 8,171 gun homicides in 1993, is almost double
the number reported in 1976, the year the FBI began compiling such
statistics. Moreover, the Justice Department figures omit the even
greater number of firearm deaths through accidental shootings and
suicides each year by young people under 25.
</P>
<P>
   It can be expected that gun-control opponents will try to use
the overall decline in crime as an argument against reasonable
measures to keep guns out of the wrong hands, for example by
cracking down on illegal gun trafficking by limiting an
individual's gun purchases to one a month, and to require gun
manufacturers to sell products that can be fired only by authorized
users. Yet deadly gun violence by young people remains a pressing
problem. It calls for those firm steps, and more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
