<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     01-06 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DAVID'S DAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few minutes past three in the afternoon, with a
salvaged season and unprecedented union concessions in his pocket,
David Stern took the longest elevator ride of his 15-year life as
commissioner, from the low ground he had taken in dealing with his
desperate players, to the 25th floor of the Fifth Avenue high-rise
where about half of them were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Stern had with him his loyal deputy, Russ Granik, and two
National Basketball Association security people, Horace Balmer and
Larry Richardson. He had a message that he wanted to share, one
last hand to play, but he did not know what awaited him inside the
law office of Weil Gotshal &AMP; Manges.
</P>
<P>
   Here, about 200 of the NBA's players glimpsed in David Stern's
face what they had never once seen from across the bargaining
table. They saw doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first walked in, you could see this funny look on his
face, like he was thinking, `What kind of reception am I going to
get?' '' said Nick Anderson of the Orlando Magic. ``He had to be
thinking, `What do they think of me being here?'''
</P>
<P>
   A few players, Charles Oakley being one, didn't think much,
didn't want to hear what Stern had to say, and left. Most of them
remained, though, as Stern broke the ice by introducing Granik as
``the designated bad guy,'' before launching into a speech about
how this day had marked the end of a long blood feud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, thank you to the players for saving the season and
thank you to Billy Hunter and Patrick Ewing for being courteous
during the negotiations,'' said Kevin Johnson, who is about to
become a free agent guard in what is going to be a freewheeling
January market. ``He said, `It's our time to get back together.'
And then he said, `We're all part of the same family.'''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the high road, back in control of his tarnished product,
Stern finished, believe it or not, to a round of applause. What a
difference the imminent return of a pay check, a few dozen adoring
fans in the lobby and a slightly less imperious Stern had made.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, knowing he had the players right where he wanted
them, Stern finally moved off the craggy mountain he had climbed
atop last month. He accepted an 11th-hour appeal by Hunter, the
union's cornered executive director. He threw the players the
necessary collective bargaining scraps that allowed them a measure
of dignity, and after voting overwhelmingly to play, they were back
in the mobbed lobby by late in the afternoon, feeding on their
fame.
</P>
<P>
   The players wore small blue buttons inscribed with the word
``solid,'' and tried their best to discount the fact that, on top
of half a season's pay lost, they had swallowed cost controls that
will reduce many top salaries by tens of millions. Gone was the
mood of defiance, the talk of principle. One by one, the players
descended from the 25th floor, and said, no, they did not have
anything personal against Stern. This was about business, and he
was doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just we had players working for us, David was on the strings
of the owners,'' said Michael Curry, a member of the players'
negotiating committee.
</P>
<P>
   This was an interesting, new portrayal of Stern, as the
basketball owners' marionette. For years, while commissioners in
other sports were pilloried as obsequious owner stooges, Stern
managed to cast himself as the spiritual leader of the global
basketball revolution, representing all, from the richest owner to
the lowliest ball boy. ``Easy Dave,'' he once called himself. The
players' partner. Then his league grew, more crowded, more
corporate. At the end of the century, Stern, more than a
commissioner, now goes about his work like any other cold-blooded
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tyrant, a bully,'' one of the agents, Steve Kaufmann, said,
when asked how players might now view Stern. ``But then, they're so
relieved they probably won't even care.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any other calculating executive, Stern realized that, in
the end, people just have to work. He won big, mainly over the
agent, David Falk, and maybe he will use this coup as a springboard
into a higher corporate perch. Maybe, after training on basketball
players, he goes off one day to the kind of company that inflicts
real pain on its workers.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, when Stern was a rising young attorney at the
Manhattan firm Proskauer Rose Goetz &AMP; Mendelsohn, he did pro bono
work for a group in his integrated town of Teaneck, N.J. The group
was engaged in a landmark lawsuit against real estate brokers
accused of racial steering, the illegal practice of showing whites
and blacks homes in distinctly different areas. Stern helped win
the suit, but soon after left Teaneck behind for a less contentious
town, defining success in more upscale ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy Dave'' always tried to be one of the guys. Wednesday, the
finished corporate product left the GM Building and marched up
Fifth Avenue, bodyguards on both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
