<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2071 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-MUSEUMS-$ADV10     01-06 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MUSEUMS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE VENUES ARE VIRTUALLY INFINITE  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., The Netherlands)  Steven Henry Madoff is the deputy editor of Time Digital magazine. 
(af) 
 By STEVEN HENRY MADOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are plenty of unlikely places to see art in the physical
world, but for sheer range and pure oddity, terra firma has nothing
on cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The number of museums online has assumed proportions that only
Alice grown 10-feet tall could comprehend. According to the
listings provided by the authoritative online directory, the World
Wide Web Virtual Library, the strangely named Elsas Producties site
out of the Netherlands tallies links to more than 10,000 museums in
120 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bowen, webmaster of the Virtual Library's museum pages,
claims that a new museum is added to its own lists on an average of
one a day, every day.
</P>
<P>
   The directories themselves are spawning like so many baby
galaxies: all of the search services, like Yahoo and Lycos, stock
ample museum links; and then the specialized directories like the
Virtual Library, ArtNet, Musee and World Wide Arts Resources
provide immensely broad (though spottily updated) offerings.
</P>
<P>
   What is a virtual museum? It can be anything from a homemade
collection of images with accompanying texts that focuses on a
category of objects _ paintings, restaurant ware, wooden nickels _
to a slickly produced, elaborate summary of a physical museum, with
floor plans, descriptions of collections and exhibitions, images,
audio, even virtual-reality tours.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as in the physical world, on-line museums dedicated
to art are just a fraction of the virtual storehouses displaying
everything from the artifacts of science and history to the more
florid examples of humanity's full-bore nuttiness.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the Air Sickness Bag Virtual Museum or, back in the
realm of artworks, the only slightly less twisted Museum of Bad
Art, whose slogan is ``Art too bad to be ignored'' (but we'll try).
</P>
<P>
   The dizzying propagation of visual culture on the Web has its
bright sides, from the established international institutions (the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the Pompidou Center in
Paris, the Prado in Madrid) to the local (ever visited the National
Gallery of Slovenia or the Tokugawa Art Museum in Japan or the
Portland Art Museum in Oregon?) to the deeply strange (try the
Museum of Jurassic Technology's exhibit of fruit-stone carving).
</P>
<P>
   What is apparent is that museums now see the Internet as a
supplementary portal of value. The Museum of Modern Art in New York
has an extraordinarily rich site _ perhaps the best of its kind on
the Web _ and its numbers are intriguing. In 1997, 1.2 million art
aficionados surfed by, rapidly approaching the 1.65 million
visitors who passed through its actual doors. (To put the Modern's
yearly numbers in perspective, Yahoo, the most trafficked single
site on the Web, has more than one million visitors a day.)
</P>
<P>
   For artists attuned to the possibilities of such swelling
audiences, museums are offering new cyber venues. The Walker Art
Center's on-line Gallery 9 features Piotr Szyhalski's provocative
interactive pieces ``Ding an Sich'' and ``Harvest.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art recently purchased a
whole collection of Web works called ``RSUB'' from the
digital-design shop Razorfish Studios in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There is much, much more. Galleries? Hundreds. Auction houses
and live on-line auctions? Indeed. Art-locating services, advice
about collecting? A click away. All of them _ and who knows what
else? _ are now playing on a browser near you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-2NDTA     01-06 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: impeachment proceedings.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hastert was turned to by shocked Republicans after Newt Gingrich
stepped down under fire and their next choice, Bob Livingston,
abruptly resigned over revelations that he had had extra-marital
affairs. Livingston had toppled Gingrich just one month earlier,
capitalizing on anger that Republicans had lost five House seats in
a midterm election seen as a mandate against impeachment. The
election left them opening the new session Wednesday with a 10-seat
majority, one of the smallest House majorities this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions to problems cannot be found in a pool of
bitterness,'' Hastert said, delivering his first speech as speaker
from the well of the House chamber instead of the imposing
speaker's platform. ``In the turbulent days behind us, debate on
the merits often gave way to personal attacks,'' he said. ``Some
here have felt slighted, insulted or ignored. That is wrong, and
that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, called on the new
Congress to ``put to rest finally the poisonous politics that has
infected this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the impeachment of the president dominated a day which is
usually devoted to celebration and hopeful talk of legislative
goals and new party agendas. At times the confluence of events
almost seemed bizarre. At one point in the morning, Lott left a
Republican conference which was heatedly debating the trial of
Clinton on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice to receive
a quick greeting from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Looking tanned, Gore heartily called out New Year's greetings to
reporters waiting word of how impeachment would proceed. As the
presiding officer in the Senate, Gore then swore in the 34 senators
elected or re-elected in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, Lott and Sen. Tom Daschle also placed a
quick phone call to Clinton to tell him the new session had
convened, with Lott making pleasantries about college football.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of a new tone, the House plunged almost
immediately back into the impeachment issue, because of the
requirement that the new Congress reappoint the 13 Republicans that
the 105th Congress selected to prosecute the president in the
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the head of the House impeachment team, in a
futile effort to head off the debate, called the measure a ``simple
straightforward housekeeping resolution'' and said it was
``incidental to impeachment.'' He said his group planned to
prosecute the case ``as expeditiously and fairly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the Democrats who had fought against impeachment
from the House Judiciary Committee appealed to the new members of
the House not to cast one of their first votes to facilitate the
trial of the president. Rep. John Conyers Jr., the ranking Democrat
on the committee, said the House had carried out a partisan
impeachment ``totally lacking in credibility and overwhelmingly
rejected by the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Today we have a final opportunity to put this
salacious activity behind us. If we reject the motion to reappoint
managers we will send a signal that we are prepared to move from
the politics of personal destruction.'' But the managers were
reappointed 223-198 on a near party line vote, with the same five
Democrats who had supported Clinton's impeachment voting with the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate side of the Capitol, senators searched for a way
to reach a bipartisan plan for a trial that would overcome the
differences between the conservatives' push for witnesses and the
Democrats' opposition to them.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, the leader of the House impeachment team, told Lott in a
meeting Wednesday morning that House prosecutors want to call five
to eight witnesses and take two weeks to make their case against
Clinton, Republican senators said. Ms. Lewinsky, as well as White
House aides Betty Currie and Vernon Jordan, were likely to be on
the witness list, according to congressional officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that any witness list that we put together
will include the name of Monica Lewinsky,'' Rep. George Gekas, one
of the House managers, said in an interview on CNN. ``But the
extent of what testimony we would elicit from her, that has not
been fully decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said they wanted to back their colleagues in
the House. ``I would prefer not to have witnesses,'' said Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas. ``But if the House believes they have to have a few
witnesses to make their case, I'm not going to support some
political deal that denies them the ability to make their case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats took a firm stand against hearing from the
cast of characters who have become familiar to the nation in the
saga of the president's affair with Ms. Lewinsky. Assessing
Democratic sentiment, Daschle, the minority leader, said, ``I think
it is fair to say that there is universal, unanimous opposition to
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has refused to speculate on how much time it
might demand to prepare should the Senate permit the House managers
to call witnesses. But Democratic senators who have consulted
closely with the White House have suggested that calling just one
witness could lead the president's lawyers to call others and to
demand to review more documents in order to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Clinton have repeatedly complained that the House
Judiciary Committee and Kenneth W. Starr, the Whitewater
prosecutor, had access to information the White House has not seen.
The White House is likely to demand to review that information in
order to cross-examine witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans spent hours locked away in an ornate floor off the
Senate chamber trying to find a middle ground. Wednesday night they
emerged optimistic. ``It's gelled,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe,
R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Republicans wanted an actual vote on articles of
impeachment and not simply the test votes that had been contained
in an earlier compromise proposal for a highly expedited trial. And
in contrast to that plan's one-week timetable, he said that both
the House and White House could end up getting several weeks each
to present their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that takes you to January the 30th or February the 12th,
that's not as important as that you get these things achieved,'' he
said. ``I think everybody agrees to that. Everybody would like to
have it done in a speedy fashion, but only so speedy that it
doesn't cause people to feel like it's being shoved or that they
haven't had a chance to make their case.''
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators continued to try to hammer out a
plan in Lott's third-floor hideaway of the Capitol Wednesday night,
negotiating with Hyde and a three other House Republicans. Lott
described the session as a kind of pre-trial conference. The key
negotiators are Sens. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Carl Levin
of Michigan, Joseph Biden of Delaware, all of them Democrats; and
Ted Stevens of Alaska, Pete Domenici of New Mexico and Fred
Thompson of Tennessee for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A team of White House representatives, among them White House
counsel Charles Ruff and special counsel Gregory Craig, met by
invitation with some of the members of the bipartisan group who
have talked with the House managers who will prosecute the case.
</P>
<P>
   The senators hope to identify areas of evidence that both the
House and White House lawyers would stipulate to, to speed the
trial along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot has occurred between the House and the White HOse,
as we understand it, on that,'' Lott said, ``We're hoping that we
can facilitate that.'' He said, ``Obviously, it would be best if we
could get a broad stipulation out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   The group broke up at about 8:30 p.m., with Hyde saying
negotiations would continue. The lawmakers declined to say what if
any progress had been made.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the negotiations progress, the first impeachment
trial of the president is to begin Thursday morning when Hyde and
the 12 other House managers are invited into the Senate chamber at
10 a.m. There they will read the articles of impeachment charging
Clinton with perjury and obstruction of justice. Then the Senate
will notify the chief justice that it is ready to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 p.m. Rehnquist will be sworn in by the presiding officer of
the Senate. Although Gore could play that role, he is not expected
to. Rehnquist will likely be sworn in by Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., who at 96 is the oldest member of the Senate. Rehnquist in
turn will swear in senators as jurors in the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the ceremonies will mark the formal opening of the
trial, negotiations are expected to continue off the floor. Lott
said he planned to talk to Daschle Thursday as well as to his
fellow Republican senators to see if an agreement was in grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
