<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JANUARY 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OLY-DRUGS-NYT (Moved on Friday, Dec. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 25,
about concern over drug use in the Olympic movement misstated the
action taken against the German runner Uta Pippig after a test in
1998 showed an elevated hormone ratio. She was suspended according
to international rules pending the completion of an inquiry. She
was not officially punished for cheating.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Jan. 5,
about a new Protestant political party in Northern Ireland referred
imprecisely to the four politicians who are forming it, and to the
Northern Ireland Assembly. The Assembly includes more than 100
Unionist members, not 5; the politicians forming the Northern
Ireland Unionist Party have left the UK Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 21,
citing a BBC News report, misstated the number of Peruvian women in
poor areas who underwent forced sterilization in the last three
years according to an investigation by the Latin American and
Caribbean Committee for the Defense of Women's Rights. Many of the
250,000 women who were sterilized in the last three years were
forced to undergo the procedure, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GOODMORNING-TV-SHAKEUP-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 4,
about the naming of Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson as co-anchors
for the ABC program ``Good Morning America'' misstated the
involvement of Shelley Ross, the newly appointed executive
producer, in Ms. Sawyer's November interview with Kenneth W. Starr.
Ms. Ross assisted in preparations for the Starr interview, but
Chris Vlasto was the producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
