<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      01-06 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS PUSH TO HEAR WITNESSES DURING SENATE IMPEACHMENT
TRIAL OF CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton
opens Thursday against a backdrop of partisan division as House
Republicans pushed for testimony from witnesses, including former
presidential paramour Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently willing to continue bucking public opinion, House
prosecutors late Wednesday sought the right to call Lewinsky,
Washington power broker Vernon Jordan, presidential secretary Betty
Currie and others, according to congressional officials.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said an agreement
was near on how a ``full trial'' would be conducted into charges
that Clinton lied to a grand jury and obstructed justice in an
effort to cover-up his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will provide ``a substantial amount of time for the
House and the White House to put on their evidence,'' Lott said,
adding that the trial could go into mid-February. ``The date is not
as important as that we have a process that is understandable, an
opportunity for the trial ... and a vote on the articles of
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Late into the evening, eight Republican and eight Democratic
senators met privately with House prosecutors, all Republicans,
haggling over procedural details for only the second presidential
impeachment trial in U.S. history and the first since Andrew
Johnson was tried in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the 45 Senate Democrats oppose calling witnesses,
the 55 Republicans are divided over whether they want to hear any
testimony. ``We're not prepared to accept any witnesses,'' said
Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle, adding, ``As soon as the
first witness is called, all bets are off with regard to agreeing
on a procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, a South Dakota Democrat, complained that during the
House impeachment debate neither the Republicans nor Democrats
``chose not to use one witness, not to depose one witness, in (the)
entire investigative proceedings. It is, to me, puzzling at best
why they now insist on witnesses over here.''
</P>
<P>
   While the list of witnesses proposed by House prosecutors does
not include Linda Tripp, the woman who secretly tape recorded her
conversations with Lewinsky, some want to summon other women who
filed affidavits in connection with the Paula Jones lawsuit,
officials said. That sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton was
dismissed, but it led to accusations that he lied about Lewinsky
while being deposed for it.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, led by chief prosecutor Rep. Henry Hyde of
Chicago, had proposed a witness list of up to 15. However, Lott was
trying to hold Hyde and his 12 House colleagues to five to seven
witnesses, Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   If agreement is reached to call witnesses, Lott said he wants
the House prosecutors and the president's defense team to justify
their need for questioning each person. The majority leader said
the Senate would then vote on whether to hear that particular
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen blocks away, White House lawyers were crafting a plan to
force senators _ who will sit as jurors _ to conduct a vote early
in the trial to show the Senate does not have the two-thirds
majority needed to convict Clinton and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we show the two-thirds is not there, the message is, it's
just a show trial with no chance of conviction. And every day we
can remind the public of that,'' a White House official told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a CBS News poll of 1,175 adults early this week found
63 percent opposed to a full Senate impeachment trial. Thirty-two
percent favor a full trial, complete with witnesses. The same
survey showed 69 percent of adult Americans approving of the job
Clinton is doing as president, a rating that has remained fairly
constant during last year's House impeachment hearings and debate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impeachment trial formally begins shortly after the
Senate convenes at 9:45 a.m. EST. The 13 House managers who will
prosecute the case against Clinton will be escorted from the House
chamber on the south side of the Capitol to the marble and
gold-trimmed Senate chamber on the north side. There, Hyde and the
other managers will read the charges against the president.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, 96-year-old Senate Pro Tempore Strom Thurmond, a South
Carolina Republican and the oldest and longest serving senator in
the history of the Senate, will swear in Chief Justice William
Rehnquist to preside over the impeachment trial. Rehnquist then
will administer the jurors' oath to the 100 members of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   While no other major Senate business is expected on the Senate
floor until the trial is completed, Lott said committees will
continue to meet before and after senators sit as trial jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to go forward, and we will do our
best to have a dual track,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial had been expected to get under way next Monday, but
Republicans involved in closed-door negotiations over procedures
said that may now be pushed back to the middle of next week,
possibly later, so Clinton's legal team will have time to prepare a
formal response to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lott cautioned that although he hopes to have details worked out
within his own GOP caucus and with Democrats some time Thursday,
there is a chance no agreement will be reached on how to the trial
will proceed. ``You may not have the absolute answers (on witnesses
and procedures) until we get started'' next week, the Mississippi
Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans, including some who support not hindering
House prosecutors by barring witnesses, expressed concern about
getting into a trial without a bipartisan agreement on procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is clearly the sense of our caucus that it's
dangerous to start this kind of a process without some kind of
pretrial agreement on things like witnesses,'' said Sen. Chuck
Hagel, R-Neb. ``You get into procedural motions and questions and
then it just becomes a free-for-all as to people rising to debate
motions and changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate rules allow any senator to offer a motion at any time to
dismiss the case. If all 45 Democrats were to support a motion to
dismiss, they would still need the support of at least six
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., broke with his
Democratic colleagues by calling for a full-blown trial with
witnesses, particularly on the question of whether Clinton tampered
with witnesses or otherwise obstructed justice as alleged in one of
the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a critic of Clinton since he admitted the affair in
August and acknowledged misleading the nation for seven months,
said obstruction of justice is the only charge against the
president that might result in his removal from office. The perjury
allegation, if proven, is not a serious enough to warrant
terminating Clinton's presidency, Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
