<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-RHODEN-NYT &LR;      01-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-RHODEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ARMAGEDDON ... NOT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was not the Armageddon I'd been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   All summer and then into the fall, we saw prima-donna basketball
players turn to warriors. They battled 27 extremely wealthy team
owners and put a value on their muscle. July. August. September. By
November the owners realized they had a fight on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Only an edict from David Stern, the National Basketball
Association commissioner, prevented the owners from crying out in
pain and letting the players know that some of them were hurting,
too. So Wednesday morning I woke up with visions that the NBA, in
all its arrogance, would finally be put in its place. That more
than 400 professional basketball players, having fought and endured
for six months, would take a final vote and push the owners to the
brink, fling the ball in the owners' court. That they would make
the owners decide to end the season.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of truth, the players capitulated. ``Because my
guys were beginning to soften,'' Billy Hunter, the executive
director of the players association, said in an interview Wednesday
night. ``We were getting so many pleas from players that if the
season was going to get canceled, they wanted to have a say in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the middle of a bitterly cold January day, the General
Motors Building in New York City was turned into Appomattox Court
House, or the battleship Missouri in Tokyo Bay. This was the
players' surrender. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that I wanted the NBA players to do what has become
increasingly difficult for normal, work-a-day workers to do. These
players, despite their salaries and often glamorous life styles,
still bore the frustration of workers rendered defenseless against
corporations gobbling each other up, becoming larger, more arrogant
and callous, more insensitive to the well-being of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as players entered the General Motors Building
Wednesday, they passed by members of the National Association of
Broadcast Employees and Technicians who have been locked out since
early November, some of them skirmishing with workers who had
replaced them. Not far away, at a hotel on Seventh Avenue, members
of local 32B-32J, office building workers, were preparing for a
strike vote.
</P>
<P>
   But these basketball players work in an unusual industry and had
a rare opportunity to strike a blow against employers who, at the
end of the day, could never become so big, so fat that they could
do without the skills and charisma of the athletes who drive their
product. Had the players remained unified and strong for one more
day, the owners might well have made larger concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my belief, too,'' Hunter said. ``And I'd done it for
a while, managed to keep everyone together. But the guys at the
bottom _ not the top, the guys at the bottom, the little guys were
saying, `What about us?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter added: ``The owners are independently wealthy. They did
not earn their riches from basketball. They can function if the
season blows up. I did not want to be reckless. This is not like
the United Auto Workers and General Motors. They work together:
they make automobiles. If something happens, they will all suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the idea of Armageddon. I was not prepared to
play free and loose with my clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players were telling Hunter to take the gamble and stand
firm. Others said to give the players an opportunity to turn down
the NBA's offer.
</P>
<P>
   What should have enlightened the players about their value were
the hundreds of fans who stood out in the bitter cold Wednesday
just waiting to catch a glimpse of them. The players should have
gathered from that outpouring that they are the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Stern came in, no one called his name; only the news media
rushed to Stern, to get photos and quotes. There was even a
smattering of boos from those fans who recognized him. Otherwise,
no one knew; no one cared.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few months, players will get back into their
work-a-day world, ``digging deep down,'' ``going the extra mile,''
``gutting it out'' for coaches who have been getting paid through
all this and for franchises which have been subsidized through all
this. Toughing it out to bring home a victory _ something they
didn't do for themselves. At the moment of truth, the rank and file
panicked.
</P>
<P>
   The players learned not simply how much they loved the game;
they learned out how much they depended on the game. This is far
more distressing. For many the game had become the drug around
which they built their life style _car, house, clothes, jewelry.
When the drug was withdrawn, they were forced to pay a higher price
to get it back; some might spend the rest of their careers in
pursuit of the fix. They no longer love the game but need the game.
Their life styles dictate that it be so.
</P>
<P>
   A number of players said they had a newfound respect and love
for the game. They appreciate how easily it can be taken away. You
have not heard, and will not hear, similar sentiments expressed by
the owners, that they have new respect for the players, whom they
realize can be taken away at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the 191-day lockout proved what most owners have
always felt: players, literally, are a dime a dozen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
