<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2082 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN     01-06 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 PARITY CREATES CIRCUS ATMOSPHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA coach Steve Lavin walked into a press room in
Pauley Pavilion on Monday night, grabbed a chair and marveled at
what had transpired. Arizona State, 0-for-UCLA this decade, had
just taken the Bruins to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like this for 16 more games,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, and for the league. If the first weekend of conference
play was any indication, get ready for two months of unprecedented
mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Five of nine games were decided in the final seconds, and two
went overtime: USC held off Arizona State at the buzzer; Oregon
surprised Cal in OT; Washington State beat Washington on a
last-second shot; the Bruins escaped ASU; and Cal avoided a major
upset with a two-point win over Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   No team typified the wackiness better than the Bears. On Dec.
29, they defeated North Carolina in a thrilling finish to the
Newell Challenge. Four days later, they lost to Oregon; two days
after that, they narrowly defeated Oregon State, the worst team in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The offspring of parity and inconsistency is fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pac-10 has more going for it now than at any point in its
history,'' said former USC coach George Raveling, an analyst for
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   In five days (Dec. 24-29), the conference won three important
intersectional games: Washington over No.11 New Mexico, Stanford
over Temple, and Cal over No. 9 UNC.
</P>
<P>
   The old guard can protest all it wants, but this is a basketball
league. In the past four years, the Pac-10 is 7-12 in bowl games
and 36-16 in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's better geographic balance,'' Raveling said. ``The team
in Seattle is good. The teams in the Bay Area are good. The teams
in L.A. are good, and the teams in Arizona are good. As you walk
through the geography and the population bases, everyone is playing
well. That helps the fan base, it helps recruiting, and it helps
television.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not so good for the blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy him while you can: Several NBA scouts attended the
Arizona-UCLA game Saturday. At least one concentrated on the
matchup between UCLA's Baron Davis and Arizona's Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   NBA talent evaluators believe Davis will enter the draft this
spring if he has a good season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks he's coming out,'' the scout said. ``Some
people think it's already been decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing fan club: USC's Brian Scalabrine is the league's best
newcomer and has impressed every coach he's faced, particularly
Arizona's Lute Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an all-leaguer,'' Olson said. ``He's the closest thing
I've seen to Detlef Schrempf since Detlef Schrempf. He can bring it
on the break. He can pass it, and he can shoot it. He's a pro, no
question.''
</P>
<P>
   A dim bulb!: Miles Simon didn't distinguish himself as a student
at Arizona, but he set a new standard for stupidity last month
after finding out his former girlfriend was dating Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Dec. 14, Simon reportedly called Belle, who has
a home in the Tucson Mountains, and asked to speak to the woman.
When told she didn't want to speak to him, Simon told Belle he was
coming over. When Simon arrived, Belle refused to answer the door
and reportedly called the police, who cited Simon for misdemeanor
trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Belle's temper and track record, it could have been
a lot worse for Simon.
</P>
<P>
   A dim bulb II: Sophomore guard Cedric Clark's bio in the
Washington State media guide claims he was a scout team player for
Arizona in 1996-97 and traveled with the Wildcats to the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The Wildcats denied Clark's request to walk-on, so he
spent the season as a practice player with the women's team.
</P>
<P>
   Loading up for Ducks and Huskies: Oregon and Washington have a
huge disadvantage because their travel partners, Oregon State and
Washington State, respectively, are the worst teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Although they won't say it, opponents will devote an entire week
to preparing for the Ducks and Huskies, figuring they can defeat
OSU and WSU with minimal preparation and effort.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the point? Point guard, once the domain of Jason Kidd,
Damon Stoudamire, Tyus Edney, Brevin Knight, Kenya Wilkins and Mike
Bibby, is now the Pac-10's weakest position.
</P>
<P>
   Raveling notes that only three players are capable of breaking
down defenses with dribble penetration: Davis, Terry and Stanford's
Art Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When will they break? How did Oregon coach Ernie Kent celebrate
the victory at Cal? After dinner, the Ducks had a two-hour
walk-through at the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling without Femerling: The departure of 7-footer Patrick
Femerling was considered addition by subtraction for the Huskies
because it would create space for Todd MacCulloch and improve
Washington's speed.
</P>
<P>
   Both premises are true. But without Femerling, the Huskies are
woefully small when the 7-foot MacCulloch gets in foul trouble.
Only one other player is taller than 6-7: freshman Marlon Shelton,
and he's not ready to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
