<P>
   (NYT39) HILLSBORO, Ore. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSEPLANE-2, 1-6 --
Bruce Campbell plans to live in this Boeing 727, which will be
reassembled on his rural 10 acres in Oregon. It is, as Campbell, a
49-year-old electrical engineer and self-proclaimed ``lifelong
nerd,'' enthusiastically describes it, ``an aerospace-quality
sealed pressure canister with structural attributes that would put
a common home to shame.'' (Shane Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) HILLSBORO, Ore. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSEPLANE, 1-6 --
Bruce Campbell spiffying up the cabin of the Boeing 727 that will
be reassembled on his rural 10 acres in Oregon and turned into his
new home. ``I want it to look like a fully operational aircraft,''
Campbell says of his new dwelling. ``They look so sexy when they're
complete and clean.'' One option, though: a deck he might build on
top of one of the wings. (Shane Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) OAKLAND, Calif. -- Jan. 6, 1999 --
BLACK-PANTHER-POLITICIAN, 1-6 -- David Hilliard, with his former
Black Panther colleague Bobby Seale, in the background, announcing
his candidacy for Oakland City Council. The campaign purports to
fulfill the unfinished agenda of the Black Panther Party. That,
Seale says, was not about murder and drugs, but ``was always all
about power to all the people, whether they're black, white, yellow
or polka-dot.'' (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WINTER HAVEN, Fla. -- Jan. 5, 1999 -- FROST-FLOATER, 1-5
-- Curtis Dean, with the horticulture department at Cypress
Gardens, checks the fuel level in a kerosene heater being used to
protect plants on Wednesday after the temperature fell below
freezing. In various regions of the state the mercury dropped to 27
degrees Fahrenheit. (Pierre Ducharme/Lakeland Ledger photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) CHICAGO -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOG-PRICES-2, 1-6 -- The
slump in prices for hogs doesn't seem to affect what shoppers pay
for pork here - at Gepperth's Meat Market in Chicago - or
elsewhere. As a result, allegations of price-gouging are being
leveled against the meatpackers who turn hogs into pork products,
and to a lesser extent against the giant supermarket
chainsretailers that sell them. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ISRAEL-JEWS, 1-6 -- Rabbi
Ismar Schorsch, chancellor of the Jewish Theological Seminary in
New York, sees a confrontation brewing in Israel. ``As a result of
the increasing political power in the hands of the Orthodox and
ultra-Orthodox, you're seeing a confrontation pushing Israel in the
direction of getting the government somewhat out of the business of
religion,'' he says. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NANJIE, China -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CHINA-ANOMALY-2, 1-6 --
For Yao Tonglin, 63, who has lived in Nanjie for 40 years, Maoism
means free housing, free furniture and a daily bottle of beer, also
free.. As one admirer recently wrote, Nanjie is a place of ``truly
shared prosperity,'' where people ``uphold what is public and spurn
what is private.'' (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NANJIE, China -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CHINA-ANOMALY-1, 1-6 --
In May 1993, as seeds of reform sprouted in China, residents of the
Nanjie collective went the other way, erecting a towering statue of
Mao Zedong. Billed as a socialist model, this village in the
central province of Henan is often cited as a paragon by China's
``leftists'' - the dwindling, old-guard Communist critics of
China's rush from ideology and state planning. (Erik Eckholm/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) ABOARD USS CARL VINSON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- IRAQ-U.S., 1-6
-- A structural mechanic performs an inspection on an aircraft on
board the USS Carl Vinson on Monday as the aircraft carrier sailed
in the Persian Gulf. In the first confrontation between American
and Iraqi jet fighters in more than six years, American warplanes
on Tuesday fired on Iraqi jets that were reported to have
penetrated the ``no flight'' zone over southern Iraq. None of the
Iraqi fighters were reported hit. (Jose Cordero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WEST ROXBURY -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- REMISSION -MISSION-BOS,
1-6 -- Margie Levine, seen recently in her home, was told nine
years ago by her doctors that she had a year to live. But what
makes her tale of survival more riveting is her message that the
cancer led her to reorder her life's priorities. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WALPOLE, Mass. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- WOM-HAYDENETTES-BOS,
1-6 -- Members of The Haydenettes skating team practice a routine
in preperation for an upcoming competition in Providence. Although
still in the publicity shadows of singles and pairs skating and not
yet in the Olympics, the synchronized version of the sport as
performed by The Haydenettes is the fastest-growing of the five
disciplines under the auspices of the United States Figure Skating
Association. (Michael Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSE, 1-6 -- House
Speaker Dennis Hastert administers the oath to the new members of
Congress on Wednesday. The 106th Congress convened Wednesday
speaking plaintively of new agendas and an end to partisan rancor,
yet already preocuppied with the impeachment of President Clinton
that left the previous House enflamed and divided. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) GREEN CITY, Mo. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOG-PRICES, 1-6 --
The Premium Standard Farms giant hog farming operation in Green
City. A glut in the number of hogs being raised has sent hog prices
plummeting to Depression-era lows, yet the price of pork at the
meat counter has barely budged. As a result, allegations of
price-gouging are being leveled against the meatpackers who turn
hogs into pork products, and to a lesser extent against the giant
supermarket chainsretailers that sell them. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- MEDICARE, 1-6 -- Rep. Jim
McDermott (D-Wash.), talks with an aide during a public meeting of
the federal advisory commission on Medicare on Tuesday. Commission
leaders proposed radical changes in Medicare, under which the
government would offer a fixed amount of money or a voucher to each
beneficiary to buy private health insurance. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CONGRESS-NY, 1-6 -- Sen.
Charles Schumer looks at his daughter Jessica, 14, after being
sworn-in on Wednesday. Joining Schumer is his wife Iris, left, and
other daughter Alison, 9. Schumer had defeated Sen. Alfonse D'Amato
(R-N.Y.) following a long and bitter campaign. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- BKN-NBA-SETTLE, 1-6 -- The
NBA and its players' union Wednesday moved toward final approval of
a new labor contract that could end the owner-imposed lockout and
produce a shortened schedule. The players overwhelmingly voted on
Wednesday afternoon to ratify a deal agreed upon by NBA
Commissioner David Stern and union executive director Billy Hunter.
``It's a good deal for both sides,'' says Patrick Ewing, the union
president. ``It's over.'' (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- PHEDRE-THEATER-REVIEW, 1-6
-- Diana Rigg in the title role of ``Phedre,'' which opened Tuesday
night for a limited run at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic
Theater. She may be doomed from the start, but this Phedre goes
down fighting. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- BOOK-TALK, 1-6 -- A Rocket
eBook, one of several electronic books on the market. The device,
whose reading screen is 4 by 3 inches) costs $499 in the Levenger
catalog. With backlighting it can run for 17 hours on batteries
without being recharged; without backlight, for 33 hours. (Igor
Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- MET-LUERS, 1-6 -- William H.
Luers in a gallery of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In more than
a dozen years as president and chief executive of the Met, Luers
never really spoke out about the nation's biggest art museum or his
tenure there. That was the deal he cut with the museum's director,
Philippe de Montebello, to whom he'll be handing over the chief
executive's post on Jan. 31. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE, 1-6 -- Rep.
Bob Livingston (R-La.), second from right, on the floor of the
House of Representatives on Wednesday during the opening of the
106th Congress. Livingston dropped out of the running for speaker
of the House after admitting to having an extramartial affair.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSE, 1-6 -- As the 106th
Congress was about to be sworn-in, a House page shared her list of
new faces with a colleague on Wednesday. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSE-HASTERT-2, 1-6 -- In
a break with tradition, newly elected House Speaker Rep. Dennis
Hastert addresses his colleagues from the well of the House on
Wednesday. Hastert replaced Newt Gingrich who stepped down as
speaker following Republicans' dismal November midterm election
performances. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-2, 1-6 -- A ticket
issued by the U.S. Senate for those who want to view the trial
proceedings against President Clinton. Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist will open the impeachment trial of President Clinton on
Thursday, according to Sen. Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOUSE-HASTERT, 1-6 -- Rep.
Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.), is sworn in as speaker of the House of
Representatives by Rep. John Dingell, bottom, on Wednesday. Hastert
replaces Newt Gingrich who stepped down as speaker following
Republicans' dismal November midterm election performances. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
WERTHER-OPERA-HISTORY, 1-6 -- Thomas Hampson rehearsing
``Werther.'' A matinee idol of a deeply scholarly bent, he
acknowledges certain scruples about taking on the ``novel'' role of
Goethe's romantic young hero. ``I don't want to be busy doing
'clever,' 'novel' things,'' he says. ``If there's an artistic
legitimacy that brings with it a certain novelty, fine.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LAMY, N.M. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- FLINTSTONE-HOUSE-3, 1-6 --
Norah Pierson's home, encased in a rocky shell some 20 miles
southeast of Santa Fe, is known locally as the Flintstone house. It
may be the only house in America whose exterior was architecturally
inspired by a 50-foot-long, 14-foot-high polyurethane brontosaurus.
(Cary Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LAMY, N.M. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- FLINTSTONE-HOUSE-2, 1-6 --
Norah Pierson stands in the livingroom of her home about 20 miles
southeast of Santa Fe. Encased in a rocky shell, Ms. Pierson's home
may be the only house in America whose exterior was architecturally
inspired by a 50-foot-long, 14-foot-high polyurethane brontosaurus.
(Cary Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
OLD-BROADWAY-SHOWS-1, 1-6 -- Adam Cooper and Scott Ambler, right,
in Matthew Bourne's ``Swan Lake.'' To judge from recent trips to
the theater, the ballet production is thriving while ``On the
Town'' is doing less well. Critics and audiences tend to love the
first but can't make up their minds about the second. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
OLD-BROADWAY-SHOWS-1, 1-6 -- Perry Laylon Ojeda and a chorus girl
in George C. Wolfe's ``On the Town.'' To judge from recent trips to
the theater, ``Swan Lake'' thrives while ``On the Town'' is doing
less well. Critics and audiences tend to love the first but can't
make up their minds about the second. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
BLUE-NOTE-RECORDS, 1-6 -- Bruce Lundvall, 63, who has restored much
of the luster to Blue Note Records, in his Manhattan office. Over
the years, the label recorded Bud Powell, Miles Davis, Thelonious
Monk, Art Blakey, Freddie Hubbard and Wayne Shorter. No other
record label in jazz has been as consistent in quality. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
GLASS-MUSIC, 1-6 -- Philip Glass retains a fascination with hybrids
of music and theater. ``Monsters of Grace,'' a loose collaboration
with the director Robert Wilson, was given its premiere last month
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music. Billed as the ``first 3-D digital
opera,'' it promised revelation but delivered only titillation,
since its special effects seemed marginal to both scenario and
music. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
DAVID-LEVEAUX-THEATER-2, 1-6 -- Zoe Wanamaker (foreground), Daniel
Oreskes (white coat) and Michael Cumpsty in ``Electra'' at the
Ethel Barrymore Theater. Although the production's director, David
Leveaux, has worked only three times over the last 14 years on
Broadway, on each occasion he has come away with mostly raves.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
DAVID-LEVEAUX-THEATER-1, 1-6 -- The English director David Leveaux:
after ``Electra'' on Broadway, perhaps a return with Harold
Pinter's ``Old Times.'' Leveaux is drawn to plays that are
``killers,'' he says, and one could argue that this theater veteran
certainly knows how to slay the New York critics. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 1-6 --
Electrical boxes are available in different shapes (rectangular,
square and octagonal) and in several depths. Each box must be large
enough to accommodate the receptacle and all the wires without
crimping or damaging the connections. Undersized boxes should be
upgraded with larger boxes. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LAMY, N.M. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- FLINTSTONE-HOUSE, 1-6 -- A
bedroom window is tilted to show the view of the railroad town
about 20 miles southeast of Santa Fe. Encased in a rocky shell,
Norah Pierson's home may be the only house in America whose
exterior was architecturally inspired by a 50-foot-long,
14-foot-high polyurethane brontosaurus. (Cary Herz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- NY-FIRE-PREVENTION, 1-6 --
Gladys Bennette, a community coordinator for fire safety education,
distributes brochures at a Harlem bank. As part of an accelerated
outreach program in the city's neighborhoods, the New York City
Fire Department is out in force trying to teach fire prevention.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CIR-AMATEUR-VIDEO, 1-6 --
Philip Pelletier and Verne Lindner, who run a home-based filmmaking
company called Swankytown, in their office. Both produced a
five-minute, award-winning parody of American advertising excess
called ``New Testament.'' Digital technology is changing the way
small filmmakers can now have a major impact on the industry using
personal computers with off-the-shelf software. (Marissa Roth/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CIR-RARE-BOOKS, 1-6
-- Martha Blegen prepares to photogrpah pages from a work by
Copernicus for a CD-ROM by Octavo. The company specializes in
producing highly detailed versions of rare books. (Sam Morris/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH, 1-6 -- President
Clinton acknowledges applause from members of his economic team
during a gathering at the Old Executive Office Building next to the
White House on Wednesday. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist will
open the impeachment trial of President Clinton on Thursday,
according to Sen. Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
