<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
DAVID-LEVEAUX-THEATER-1, 1-6 -- The English director David Leveaux:
after ``Electra'' on Broadway, perhaps a return with Harold
Pinter's ``Old Times.'' Leveaux is drawn to plays that are
``killers,'' he says, and one could argue that this theater veteran
certainly knows how to slay the New York critics. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 1-6 --
Electrical boxes are available in different shapes (rectangular,
square and octagonal) and in several depths. Each box must be large
enough to accommodate the receptacle and all the wires without
crimping or damaging the connections. Undersized boxes should be
upgraded with larger boxes. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LAMY, N.M. -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- FLINTSTONE-HOUSE, 1-6 -- A
bedroom window is tilted to show the view of the railroad town
about 20 miles southeast of Santa Fe. Encased in a rocky shell,
Norah Pierson's home may be the only house in America whose
exterior was architecturally inspired by a 50-foot-long,
14-foot-high polyurethane brontosaurus. (Cary Herz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- NY-FIRE-PREVENTION, 1-6 --
Gladys Bennette, a community coordinator for fire safety education,
distributes brochures at a Harlem bank. As part of an accelerated
outreach program in the city's neighborhoods, the New York City
Fire Department is out in force trying to teach fire prevention.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- Jan. 6, 1999 -- CIR-AMATEUR-VIDEO, 1-6 --
Philip Pelletier and Verne Lindner, who run a home-based filmmaking
