<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBASETTLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERS, PLAYERS AGREE TO DEAL, SALVAGE NBA SEASON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL MURPHY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the verge of losing the 1998-99 National
Basketball Association season, the league's team owners and its
players union finally reached an agreement Wednesday that will put
players back on the court in early February.
</P>
<P>
   The 191-day lockout will end once the six-year agreement, with a
league option for a seventh year, is drawn up by lawyers and
ratified by the owners and the union, a process that will take
about a week.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout won't be lifted until lawyers draft the agreement
and that version is ratified by the league and union, NBA
commissioner David Stern has said.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Board of Governors will meet at 11 a.m. EST Thursday to
approve the deal, which is expected to be rubber-stamped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the agreement to be ratified by the Board of
Governors at (today's) meeting,'' said Stern, who declined to
elaborate on details of the agreement. ``I will say that I am
elated that we will be playing basketball this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp is expected to start Jan. 18, and the league will
begin play in the first week of February, with each team playing a
52-game schedule, abbreviated from the standard 82 games.
</P>
<P>
   After a bargaining session that began Tuesday evening, the
agreement in principle was finally struck between Stern and Billy
Hunter, executive director of the National Basketball Players
Association, at 6 a.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we blink?'' Hunter said. ``I guess we both blinked.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means that neither was prepared to lose the entire season,
which is why Hunter said he bowed to pressure from certain
superstars _ reportedly Hakeem Olajuwon of the Rockets, Shaquille
O'Neal of the Los Angeles Lakers and David Robinson of the San
Antonio Spurs, among others _ and called Stern for one last-ditch
negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had to be some horse trading to get the deal done,''
said Hunter when asked what broke the negotiating logjam. ``It's
not everything we wanted. That happens. The time was right for us
to talk. We both knew there was a lot to give up by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   That horse trading was clearly evident in a summary of the final
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes some of the owners' biggest wants _ a
limit on individual player salaries, a five-year pay scale for
rookies, and a decreased percentage of revenues going to the union
in the final three years of the six-year proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the union got more middle-class exceptions, a
graduated minimum salary based on experience, higher annual salary
increases and no limit on the percentage of revenue that will go to
salaries during the first three years of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great deal,'' Olajuwon said. ``I'm satisfied.
It shows a great strength from the players' point of view, the way
they stuck together. I think everybody is pretty much happy with
how it (the proposal) turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement caught many of the players by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Players had been summoned to New York for a vote on whether they
supported the union negotiating committee's recommendation that
they reject the owners' previous proposal, which had been submitted
Dec. 27. But when Hunter and Stern reached their agreement, players
found out they would be voting on the framework for the new
collective-bargaining agreement, which they approved by a reported
181-5 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The players, however, were prepared to approve the owners'
previous proposal, which Hunter and the rest of the union's
negotiating committee had tried to discourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would have voted for the (owners') deal as it
existed,'' said Orlando's Nick Anderson. ``We want to play
basketball, and that's what we're supposed to be doing. We avoided
a massive earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern and NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik talked to the
players after the vote, saying, ``Let's get together. It has been a
tough battle. We have to come back to work as a team and make this
the best sport in the world as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side wanted to name a winner and a loser in the
six-month labor war, but the owners wound up with a much better
agreement than the old one, especially with control of the high-end
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody won,'' Charles Barkley said. ``We gave some, and we
took some, but I'm just glad the deal is signed. We've done a great
disservice to the game, but business is business.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the compromises:
</P>
<P>
   _ The union agreed to a $14 million maximum salary for players
with 10 years' experience. Players with one to five years'
experience can get a maximum of $9 million, and players in years 6
to 9 can get $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ The union agreed to a three-year rookie scale, with teams
holding an option for the fourth year and the right of first
refusal in the fifth year. First-round draft picks will be grouped
into three categories by where they were selected _ picks 1-9,
10-19 and 20-29 _ with the highest picks eligible for higher
percentage increases in their salaries from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   _ To exceed the salary cap when signing free agents, the league
accepted the union's proposal for an ``average'' salary exception
and the $1 million exception, which increases by $100,000 every
year _ effectively becoming a ``median'' salary exception. As a
result, every team will have the right to sign two additional
players each season, even if it is over the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   _ The league agreed to higher minimum salaries than it had been
offering, starting at $287,500 and escalating to $850,000 for a
player with nine years of experience. A player with 10-plus years
in the league gets a minimum of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy in my situation, I don't think it could get too much
better,'' said Eldridge Recasner of the Atlanta Hawks. ``I think
everybody's pretty pleased with the deal. It's fair across the
board. It's more what the union wanted, so what else can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   Ratification of the agreement will trigger a three-week
whirlwind of teams attempting to sign free agents, make trades and
hold abbreviated training camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very busy,'' said agent Mark Bartelstein. ``We've
got a lot of free agents, so we've got to find them homes and
teams, get other guys into camps. I'm sure I'll probably talk to a
lot of teams (today).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
