<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETERS YAWN AT NBA'S RETURN
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Ore., Calif., Ga.) 
(See also BKN-NBA, BKN-NBA-SEASON, BKN-NBA-IMPACT, BKN-NBA-SETTLE,
BKN-NBA-FANS, BKN-NBA-PLAYERS, BKN-NBA-HUNTER, BKN-NBA-JORDAN,
BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN, BKN-ARATON-COLUMN, BKN-NBA-DEAL,
BKN-NBA-KNICKS) 
 (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agreement in principle reached Wednesday to salvage the
National Basketball Association season is being welcomed by most
marketers and agencies, particularly those that covet the younger
male consumers who fervently follow the Bulls, Knicks, Lakers and
all that Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But in an ominous sign for the long-term advertising appeal of
the league, many others _ apart from those executives directly
involved in marketing footwear and apparel _ described little if
any significant damage from the six-month lockout. And they
expressed concern that the late start to the season, as well as
lingering perceptions of players and officials more concerned about
salaries and selling than statistics and scoring, would alienate
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA got confused, thinking the fan base was the television
audience,'' said Jon Mandel, co-managing director of Mediacom, the
media services agency in New York owned by Grey Advertising, which
buys time and space for marketers like Reebok International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the fans who follow the game who are really in charge
of your brand image,'' he added. ``So if you tell them, `Let 'em
eat cake,' it's more than just a labor issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Donny Deutsch, chairman at Deutsch Inc. in New York, the agency
for the Foot Locker and Lady Foot Locker athletic retail chains
owned by Venator Group, echoed Mandel's cautionary comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this bad will has the NBA in trouble,'' Deutsch said.
``I'm a huge fan, but I will not go to a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is driven by individual athletes, more so than
other sports,'' he added. ``But the players are looking unlikable,
like fools.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene DeWitt, the chairman at DeWitt Media in New York, a media
services agency, compared the dispute between the players and
league officials to ``two sets of bankers having a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's attitude, he added, ``is like a pox on both their
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have formed other habits without NBA games,'' he said.
``The damage to the sport, certainly for this year, could be
tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two reasons given for the widespread opinions that
the difficulties inflicted upon advertisers were minimal. One was
the breadth of media alternatives to professional basketball,
particularly in an era of manufactured sports like the Winter X
Games and myriad cable and broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a variety of other male-targeted, very male-oriented
programming,'' said Monica Karo, the Los Angeles media director for
TBWA/Chiat/Day, a unit of Omnicom Group. ``For clients like Sony,
Apple, Kinko's, Nissan and Infiniti, we found other places to
advertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``To reach men 18 to 24, 18 to 34, 25 to 49 and 25 to 54,'' she
added, ``we've used other sports, primarily college basketball and
football, some cable like CNN and Discovery and syndication.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Donchin, vice president and director for national broadcast
at Carat North America in New York, a media services arm of Aegis
Group PLC, said that for advertisers like Alberto-Culver and Midas,
``we re-expressed the money into appropriate programming to give us
male viewership.'' He said that included the ``male-oriented
movies'' scheduled by the TNT cable network, part of Time Warner
Inc., in lieu of the NBA games that were to have appeared on the
network.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Igiel, executive vice president and broadcast director at
the Media Edge in New York, the media services unit of Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc., said: ``Some clients just wanted pro basketball and
held money back until play resumed. For those who needed media
weight in January and February, we used prime time, football and
college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tightened up the first-quarter TV market,'' he added,
referring to the shrinking inventory of commercial time that has
produced more robust demand than is usual for the post-holiday
season. Indeed, the trade publication Mediaweek reported this week
that commercials during network prime-time programs in the
so-called scatter market _ the spots that were not bought before
the 1998-99 season began _ were nearly sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The other main reason given for the commonly held belief that
the effect of the lockout on advertisers was slight was the rhythm
of the pro basketball season: Earlier games attract less attention
than later games and later games attract less attention than
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our attention is focused on the playoffs,'' said Brad
Shaw, a spokesman for the Pepsi-Cola Company unit of Pepsico Inc.
in Purchase, N.Y., ``so the impact on us was minimal.'' To help
introduce the Pepsi One soft-drink brand, aimed at younger men as
well as women, ``we've been largely on network prime time,'' he
added, ``which was the plan anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   A competitor that rarely agrees with Pepsi-Cola did so this
time. ``Ratings climb as the season progresses,'' said Scott
Jacobson, a spokesman for the Coca-Cola Co. in Atlanta, which bills
its long-term sponsorship agreement with the league as a ``100-year
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In most seasons, we tend to have heavier media weight toward
the end,'' he added, ``so while we'll be figuring out a way to make
up for some lost time, it was kind of business as usual; this was
not disruptive at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware before the lockout began that ``there might be a labor
situation,'' Jacobson said, Coca-Cola executives planned so that
their annual professional basketball promotion, for the Sprite
soft-drink brand, would work with or without games being played. In
fact, the promotion, called the Sprite Salary Cap, capitalized on
the publicity for the dispute with satirical spots by Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS in New York _ part of the Lowe Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies _ showing players like Grant Hill
and Tim Duncan pretending to need work.
</P>
<P>
   One commercial, which showed players performing chores for
callers to a make-believe job referral service, 1-800-TALL-MEN,
generated ``between 300,000 and 400,000 calls,'' Jacobson said,
adding that callers heard a recorded message from Hill in which he
said: ``I can't believe you really called. It's a joke, a joke,''
then described details of the Sprite promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers, of course, need the NBA more than others.
Sales of sneakers and other athletic paraphernalia, especially for
marketers that sponsor the NBA or have a stable of
player-endorsers, have been weakened by the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has hurt the industry overall,'' said Vizhier
Mooney, a spokeswoman for Nike Inc. in Beaverton, Ore., ``and Nike
is included in that.'' She said it was impossible to quantify the
sales decline ``because the industry was flat to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Mooney said, ``We're looking forward to being
able to showcase again our footwear and apparel and our
relationship with the athletes and the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike, too, parodied the lockout problems in advertising, running
a campaign by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., in which
celebrity fans of pro teams, like director Spike Lee and actress
Dyan Cannon, delivered spoof tributes to neighborhood pickup games
and eighth-grade girls' basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that will replace professional basketball,''
Ms. Mooney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
