<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TAYLOR-NY     01-06 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-TAYLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAY FROM SPOTLIGHT, TAYLOR THRIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ He is a National Football League rookie who
has toppled records the way he has toppled defensive backs: with an
explosive combination of power and speed. He has given the
Jacksonville Jaguars dimensions that frighten teams. Yet some teams
were afraid of him when he came out of college because of several
off-the-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   His name is not Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   It is Fred Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets will get a close look at Taylor, who has put up big
numbers in relative small-market obscurity, on Sunday when they
play the Jaguars in the American Football Conference divisional
playoffs at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really taken this league by storm,'' said Rich
Griffith, the tight end for the Jaguars. ``But I think he's been
overshadowed by Randy Moss. The kinds of numbers Fred has put up
are incredible. Normally, they'd be good enough to win him rookie
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss won that award by getting 44 votes from a panel of 47
sports writers and broadcasters. Indianapolis quarterback Peyton
Manning got two votes and Taylor got one. During any other season,
1,223 yards rushing and 14 touchdowns would be enough to win the
award. But this is a leap year _ watch Moss leap over this guy,
watch him leap over that guy _ and Moss had 17 touchdown catches,
the most ever by a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Moss, Taylor wasn't haunted by his past in last April's
NFL college draft. Normally, teams don't shy away from college
players with checkered pasts, but Lawrence Phillips changed all
that. Teams watched how the St. Louis Rams took a chance on
Phillips, accused of several incidents of violence against women
while at the University of Nebraska, only to see Phillips released
last season after the Rams were unhappy with his behavior on and
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Moss, who had been arrested because of marijuana
possession, an incident of domestic violence, and a racially
charged fight in high school. He was selected by Minnesota with the
21st pick in the draft, when a player of his talent normally would
have been a top-five selection.
</P>
<P>
   Moss was put under the microscope and burned, while Taylor
escaped the glare despite problems of his own. He was suspended at
the start of his junior season because of his role in a book-theft
incident, and was suspended the preceding year for fraudulent use
of a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   According to an NFL team security report, on Sept. 1, 1995,
Taylor was cited for violating the University of Florida student
code of conduct for throwing eggs at other students. Several
general managers who picked after the Jaguars were asked this week
if Taylor's problems would have prevented them from selecting him.
All answered no.
</P>
<P>
   Why were Moss and Taylor viewed so differently by various teams?
Some executives said they believed Moss' problems were worse than
Taylor's. Others said that Taylor was contrite in interviews prior
to the draft, and explained in detail what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't hide anything,'' said Jerald Ingram, the Jaguars
running backs coach, who interviewed Taylor at scouting combines
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, as Moss has proved in Minnesota, Taylor is showing
that the Jaguars made the right decision in drafting him.
</P>
<P>
   A 235-pound back with 4.3-second speed in the 40-yard dash,
Taylor is a combination bruiser and track star. Against the
Patriots last week, he rushed for 162 yards, the most yards gained
by a rookie in the playoffs behind Washington's Timmy Smith (204)
and Paul Lowe of the Los Angeles Chargers (165).
</P>
<P>
   As he has done all season, Taylor showed exceptional smarts in
picking holes last Sunday as the Jaguars defeated New England by
25-10. Most running backs need time to develop that very subtle,
but obviously important, skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always come into the game wanting the ball,'' said Taylor,
who set team records in attempts (264), rushing yards (1,223),
rushing touchdowns (14) and total touchdowns (17).
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred gives us an added dimension we've never had before,''
said Griffith. ``When he gets going, we're hard to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
