<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-INTERNET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMOR MILLS OF RIGHT, LEFT AIM AT IMPEACHMENT PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ As the Senate begins its first impeachment trial in
130 years, there are powerful forces on the right and left trying
to throw a monkey wrench into the process.
</P>
<P>
   The right, largely through the Internet and talk radio, is
pushing a 6-year-old rumor, resurrected by a supermarket tabloid,
that President Clinton has an illegitimate son by a prostitute in
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The editor of the ``Star'' tabloid, quoted by the Internet's
Drudge Report, said the story ``could be a 13-year-old hoax,'' but
that hasn't stopped talk radio from spreading it across the
airwaves in an apparent effort to pressure GOP members of the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, publication of ``Hustler'' magazine chief Larry
Flynt's one-time magazine, the ``Flynt Report,'' looms, and it,
too, appears to be shooting for scandals designed to incite popular
outrage at GOP politicians and affect the outcome of the Senate
trial in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt, a Democrat who proudly states that he is digging up dirt
on behalf of Clinton, promises a news conference early next week to
serve another helping of ``sex scandals by high government
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is: Will the scandal-mongering swamp the Senate
and undermine the impeachment trial?
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the down-and-dirty tactics are bound to take a
toll on the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton ``love child thing,'' said Berkeley political
scientist Bruce Cain, ``just poisons the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That matters because, when the atmosphere gets poisoned,
people don't necessarily do rational things. They do things out of
anger or revenge, and they dig in their heels,'' said Cain,
associate director of the Institute of Government Studies at the
University of California-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton rumor has been largely ignored by the mainstream
press, although the ``New York Post'' published a story in its
Sunday editions.
</P>
<P>
   It's also become fodder for late-night comedian Jay Leno, who
joked, ``Imagine that, Clinton a father again. Is that what Clinton
needs, another reason to pass out cigars?''
</P>
<P>
   But when reporters asked for White House comment Monday, Clinton
press aide Joe Lockhart dismissed them.
</P>
<P>
   He said reporters who ``come with no independent reporting to
repeat the gossip from tabloid, supermarket tabloids, are wasting
their time with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, CBS News' Bill Plante continued the questioning. ``Well,
Joe,'' he said, ``isn't it legitimate to ask about reports such as
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said, ``Not like that. As all of you know, those
reports have been around for years, and it's just a waste of your
time to waste my time here with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports bubbled up last week at a gathering of conservatives
at the Arizona Biltmore in Phoenix, when cyber-gossip columnist
Matt Drudge promised a ``huge story'' with a ``worldwide impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Drudge later delivered with a report on the ``Star's'' DNA
testing to determine whether the story had any basis. He said a
news conference would be held on the DNA tests, which were to be
completed this week, if they showed a positive connection.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the buzz on the Internet and talk radio
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feeds the fires of the right,'' Cain said. ``They just
continue to get more and more outraged about the fact Clinton is a
cad. They in turn will continue to put pressure on the Senate to
have a trial because they want to drag him through the mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its effect is more on the right than it is on general public
opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the House impeachment hearings, rumors of wild Clinton
sex tales sent some members, including Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz.,
to evidence hidden away in a government office building.
</P>
<P>
   The booming Hayworth took to the airwaves and said that the
secret information portrayed Clinton as a ``sexual predator.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., showed restraint,
pointing to legal arguments that the material should not be
considered because it was excluded from the House Judiciary
Committee report used as the basis to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona Sen. Dennis DeConcini, now a Washington lobbyist,
said the latest reports have yet to make a mark with senators. But
he said that, if proved true, they could be devastating to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are a little bit callous toward that right
now,'' said DeConcini, who has conferred with several senators
about the process.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he said an impeachment trial is ``very dangerous for Clinton
. . . if another shoe drops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will work unless it comes from other
sources,'' added DeConcini, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the key difference with the latest seamy Clinton
saga.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has largely been confined to the Internet, where
journalistic standards are non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Mark Petracca, who has studied the effects
of the Internet on the democratic process, said the Drudge Report
and other Clinton scandal sites lend credibility to stories once
confined to the Capitol Hill gossip network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's little difference between the CNN Web site and the
Matt Drudge Web site,'' said Petracca, head of the political
science department at UC-Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The form it takes, its presentation, adds legitimacy that
wouldn't ordinarily be there in the historic way in which political
gossip occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``When you hear gossip, you know it's gossip, so you
treat it as such. Now it becomes much more difficult to distinguish
between what's gossip and what's not gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Petracca said, the Internet has given rumors a new
legitimacy that can, in turn, have a powerful impact on the
political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does have a potentially more vicious consequence if it gets
taken up by mainstream news outlets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt also is promising to bypass the mainstream media by
posting the results of his investigation on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Since offering a $1 million bounty on philandering politicians,
which led to the downfall of House Speaker-elect Bob Livingston,
Flynt has emerged as a powerful force in Washington's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt says his investigators have dug up dirt on about a dozen
politicians, all but one of them Republican, in an attack on what
he sees as Clinton's hypocritical detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt, a self-described ``pornographer, pundit and social
outcast,'' has hinted only that his next target is a ``big fish''
Republican in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to unmask what Flynt calls hypocrisy in the Clinton
investigation is shaking up more than politicians. Some observers
fear that in driving the public discourse to new lows, Flynt will
deepen cynicism about the impeachment process and government in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dangerous to democracy,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at Claremont (Calif.) Graduate University.
``It's dangerous to the First Amendment and it only adds to the
cynicism we see out there. This is sexual bounty hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt had flushed out Livingston after putting an advertisement
in the ``Washington Post'' offering to pay up to $1 million for
verifiable information on adultery by members of Congress or other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt described his next victim as a GOP House member who has
been a strong critic of Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is really a gem,'' Flynt said. ``We've got enough to
go on now, but we are waiting for an affidavit from his ex-wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt said that he will probably name a third politician next
week, and that he is paying a total of about $4 million to women
who responded to his ad. At some point, he will publish details not
in ``Hustler,'' but in the ``Flynt'' ``Report.''
</P>
<P>
   His activities have Republicans across the nation cringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you wonder who's running the country,'' said national
GOP strategist Ray McNally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are the politicians going to start becoming the most
responsive to? Larry Flynt? This is crazy. It's like Armageddon.
It's just mutually assured destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole sorry process ultimately hurts everyone,'' McNally
said. &QL; 
Includes information from the Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
