<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-HNS &LR;      01-06 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
He is demanding, sometimes abusive, often critical. Bill Parcells
is not the typical ``player's coach.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets' free-speaking author/receiver, Keyshawn
Johnson, writes in this week's ESPN The Magazine: ``He made us a
better team by being willing to put up with all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And credit us for being willing to put up with Bill
Parcells.''
</P>
<P>
   They put up with Parcells because they know his methods result
in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Three times he has turned around moribund franchises _ the New
York Giants, NFL champions of the 1990 season; the New England
Patriots, AFC champs in '96; and now the Jets, who on Sunday will
play the Jacksonville Jaguars after earning a bye in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was 9-7 last year, his first with the Jets, who are
12-4 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The year before Parcells took over, the team was 1-15, and the
precocious rookie Johnson wrote a book, Just Give Me the Damn Ball,
that included disparaging remarks about teammates, among them
fellow receiver Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was accused of destroying team chemistry, to which he
says: ``What team chemistry?''
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet is not fond of Johnson: ``We are not friends; we do not
go out socially. All that high-fiving I do with him is for the good
of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is all Parcells asks _ not that players shut up, not
that they like each other, but that they do what's good for the
team when they're on the field.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with Johnson and Chrebet, who this season caught 83 and
75 passes, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   High-strung athletes who would have been problems for other
coaches _ Johnson, Lawrence Taylor, Bryan Cox _ Parcells accepts,
as long as they help him win.
</P>
<P>
   When Cox launched into a tirade about the NFL being racist after
he was fined $10,000 for late hitting, Parcells told him it was OK
to vent.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson complains about not getting the ball enough, that too
is permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson points out that Parcells does not discourage
selfishness, that the coach likes to say: ``I'm selfish. I do what
is going to help me win.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Parcells makes selfishness and teamwork mesh. As Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde observed, Parcells ``has a way of
getting everybody to play as a unit; he brings out the best in
every player.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Parcells' guidance, Testaverde has risen from the bench to
become the leading passer in the AFC. A quarterback who was known
for indecisiveness and heaving the football into crowds of
defenders is now, at age 35, a model of efficiency and composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did,'' Parcells said, ``was tell him that when he
decides to run, take the ball down and run. This year, he's making
all the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are 7{-point favorites over Jacksonville and are a
trendy pick to make the Super Bowl, based on their all-around
excellence _ solid defense, a tremendous passing game and a
reliable rushing attack.
</P>
<P>
   The team reflects Parcells' discipline by avoiding turnovers and
penalties. In their last two games, the Jets allowed a total of one
sack and committed only one turnover and four penalties. The Jets
are the hottest team in the AFC, having won their last six games
and 10 of their last 11.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, 57, has guided them masterfully down the stretch,
easing up in practices (no pads for the last month) to minimize the
risk of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jaguars have 13 players on injured reserve and
numerous others masking pain with cortisone, the Jets are,
relatively speaking, a picture of health. Their only concern is
star cornerback Aaron Glenn, who is recovering from a sprained
ankle but is expected to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The one flaw that often is cited with the Jets is their lack of
playoff experience. Only 19 of their players have ever appeared in
a postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose this game,'' Parcells said, ``everyone will say,
`Well, they don't have playoff experience.' Well, that's a crock. I
think I have enough guys who have been in the tournament _ about 35
percent of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about our preparation for this because with our
bye week, we'll have time. And winning those last four games makes
a believer out of me that we're going to try hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets closed the regular season with a comeback win against
Seattle and victories against three playoff teams _ Miami, Buffalo
and New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think we could win all four of those games,''
Parcells said. ``Those were like playoff games. That's why I say
they made a believer out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that didn't happen until he made believers out of
them. Bill Parcells has a history of doing that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
