<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOULAS-LAWYERS-BOS &LR;      01-06 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOULAS-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ALERTS DEMOULAS CASE LAWYERS TO POSSIBLE INDICTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The US Justice Department sent target letters,
considered the formal warning of an imminent criminal indictment,
to two of Boston's most prominent lawyers Tuesday for their role in
an elaborate last-ditch scheme to win the nasty battle for the $2
billion Demoulas supermarket fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the Justice Department have also prepared a
memo of prosecution and a draft indictment for the two lawyers,
former Assistant US Attorney Gary Crossen and former Nike President
Richard K. Donahue Sr., and three others involved in the plan,
several sources close to the Justice Department and the principals
told the Globe Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The letters informed the targets that they have until Jan. 15 to
make statements to the Justice Department before senior department
officials formally sign off on the indictment, which is expected
later this month or next.
</P>
<P>
   The five lawyers and private investigators have been under
federal investigation for 18 months on charges that they created
aliases and lured a young law clerk to job interviews as far away
as Nova Scotia and New York to try to get him to give taped
statements that the judge in the Demoulas case had been biased
against their client, patriarch Telemachus ``Mike'' Demoulas.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge in the indictment, several sources close
to the Justice Department and the principals said, is expected to
be interstate travel in aid of racketeering. Other likely charges
include conspiracy, mail fraud, wire fraud, and extortion, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawyers close to the investigation said they expect the
indictment to extend beyond the ``job interview'' plot to other
questionable behavior by the lawyers during the trial. For example,
Crossen and some investigators paid a stripper $500,000 to testify
on Mike Demoulas's behalf _ money Crossen argued was necessary to
keep a flighty witness from running away or using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, private investigators working under the attorneys
approached an elderly couple and offered free legal advice to get
the couple to file a complaint alleging that Middlesex Superior
Court Judge Maria I. Lopez was biased in their suit against a
former partner in a North End pasta shop.
</P>
<P>
   But the caper with the law clerk won the most notoriety because
it raised questions about just how far a lawyer _ even a highly
respected one _ would go to defend a client offering big fees. One
firm working for Mike Demoulas had already reaped $13 million for
its role in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The US Attorney's Office in Boston, which would ordinarily have
prosecuted the case, recused itself because Crossen is one of its
most well-liked and well-known former stars, having headed the
General Crimes Unit under former US Attorney William F. Weld. He
also served as the head of Weld's Judicial Nominating Committee,
and was Weld's counsel in his campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue is a former campaign aide to President John F. Kennedy,
and has remained a close adviser to the Kennedy family.
</P>
<P>
   Crossen and Donahue both expressed confidence Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did are things we were supposed to do, as lawyers, for
our clients,'' said Crossen, now a partner at Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot.
``I'm happy that the matter is approaching conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue said in a statement, ``My conscience is clear that
throughout the course of my involvement with this case, my actions
have been appropriate and ethical. I look forward to a resolution
in this matter and am confident that I will be found to have
commited no wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   The target letters were sent to private investigators Ernest
Reid and Richard Labonte and attorney Kevin Curry, but not to
investigator Joseph McCain, who had been investigated initially,
one source said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Crossen and Donahue said they would go to Washington
to argue that the plan, though unusual, was proper and appropriate
because it was in the interest of their clients. One said the
lawyers would fight so hard for their reputations and careers that
there would be a ``bloodbath.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Justice Department sent target letters
suggests it will indict the lawyers anyway, unless they can present
so unusually strong evidence in their favor, several former federal
prosecutors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get a higher-up to overturn a
recommendation to indict,'' said one former federal prosecutor who
knows Crossen. ``It's not impossible. It does happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against the lawyers began with the case against Mike
Demoulas by his late brother George's heirs. Over eight years and
multiple trials and appeals, a judge and juries have found Mike
Demoulas guilty on charges that he calculatedly stole stock from
his nieces and nephews over the 20 years after George died, despite
having made a dramatic vow to his brother to protect the stock and
the children's interest in the company the two brothers bought from
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The case spilled out into courtroom brawls between members of
both sides of the family, with so much bitterness that the family
refused to come together to mourn one nephew's tragic death.
</P>
<P>
   After Lopez ordered that control of the company be stripped from
Mike and given to George's heirs, Mike's lawyers trained their
energies on convincing a higher court that Lopez had been biased in
her statements and judgments against his side.
</P>
<P>
   They got several witnesses to testify that the judge had
improperly socialized with one of the key lawyers for George's side
at a popular Beacon Hill bistro. And they sent her clerk, Paul
Walsh, a letter soliciting his resume for a job at an international
insurance firm. They flew him to ``job interviews'' in Nova Scotia,
and then New York, where the law allowed them to tape him without
his consent, and got him to say on tape that Lopez had told him who
``the good guys'' and ``the bad guys'' in the case were before the
trial began.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as interviewers, the lawyers and investigators caught
Walsh in several embellishments regarding his role in the Demoulas
decision. Back in Boston, they confronted him with their real
identities and told him he should testify on their behalf, or they
could expose his lies.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh then went to the Justice Department, which provided him
with a wiretap that taped Crossen and Donahue repeating their
advice to tell the truth. Walsh characterized it as extortion;
Crossen and Donahue said it was typical prosecutorial tactics, to
get Walsh to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Crossen has said that Mike Demoulas's son Arthur dreamed up the
Walsh plot after getting a tip that the clerk had told other
lawyers about the judge's partiality. A state appeals court last
month rejected the claim that Lopez was biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have been looking for is justice,'' Arthur T. Demoulas
said Wednesday. ``We have the evidence to show the misconduct and
the impropriety on the part of Judge Lopez. We believe that the
judicial system as well as ourselves will benefit from such a
hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Judy Rakowsky, Stephen Kurkjian, and Shelley Murphy of the Globe
staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
