<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2103 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-SETTLE-ART-1S     01-06 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SETTLE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS OF LOST DOLLARS LATER, NBA PLAYERS AND OWNERS SETTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Tightens, smooths editing, adds photo, graphic note)  
(JT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ National Basketball Association players and owners
brought an end to the most calamitous and costly labor dispute in
league history Wednesday, agreeing to an 11th-hour deal that saved
the season only a day before the owners were to vote on canceling
it.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating for 12 hours and trading concessions until 6 a.m.
Wednesday at the league offices in Manhattan, Commissioner David
Stern and Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, worked out
a seven-year collective bargaining agreement that ended the 191-day
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   An abbreviated regular season of about 50 games _ there are 82
games in a full season _ was expected to begin in early February,
with a full complement of playoffs beginning in early May. The
regular season could be extended by one to two weeks, but the
playoffs were not expected to last into July and would certainly
end before July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout by the owners will not officially end until after
the deal is made final by lawyers for both sides and then signed.
Training camps and the signing of 200 free agents would then begin,
probably around Jan. 18. The games lost this season translate into
total player salary losses of about $400 million; leaguewide
revenue losses also ran into the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the disagreement for the past six months has been
how to divide the $2 billion in annual revenue that the league
generates. Although both sides made some concessions at the end,
the league achieved its main goal of containing the contracts of
high-salaried players, and received some unprecedented concessions
from the union.
</P>
<P>
   It insisted on and received a maximum salary provision, and no
other professional sport has a limit on individual salaries. It
also eliminated some of the crippling loopholes to its salary cap
that had sent salaries skyrocketing in the last five years, and it
refused to yield to the union's request for a greater percentage of
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the union was left to try to hold onto some of the
terms that had provided its players the highest average salary in
pro sports, $2.6 million. It also achieved its stated priority of
significantly bettering the economic position of its middle-class
players, those making around the median salary of $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The union will receive 55 percent of total revenue toward
salaries in the last three years of the deal. That was less than
the players had hoped for, and the feeling among many of them was
that they had given in to many of the league's demands at the last
moment. Still, it was better than the prospect of no season and
many more millions of dollars in lost paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the NBA came perilously close to becoming the first
major sports league to lose an entire season to labor strife, many
players considered Wednesday morning's surprise announcement
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call at 6 a.m. in my hotel room this morning and I
couldn't believe it,'' said Joe Kleine, a free-agent center. ``We
will finally play again. Now we have a bigger job ahead of us:
getting our fans back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleine was one of the 179 players who came to Manhattan
Wednesday for a vote called by the union's negotiating committee.
On Monday, Stern had rejected the union's final proposal, and
Hunter, succumbing to internal and external pressure to hold a
vote, summoned the players to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Though he said he still considered the owners' offer inadequate,
Hunter said he would put the issue before the general membership.
It was a risky move that may have led to uneasiness in the union,
prompting it to resume discussions. Amid talk of mounting
displeasure among the players, players flocked to New York unsure
of the parameters surrounding a vote.
</P>
<P>
   But what was supposed to result in a tense and potentially
divisive debate on the union's position instead turned into scenes
of relief in and around the General Motors Building on Fifth
Avenue, where the players had gathered at the offices of the
union's law firm. Hundreds of reporters and fans mingled inside and
outside the buildings, fighting to talk to the players as they
exited the building after voting, 179-5, to approve the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' said Steve Kerr, the Chicago Bulls guard. ``I
never expected this. Of course, at times I never expected a season,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   The league announced that its labor relations committee had
unanimously approved the deal. The agreement was also approved
Wednesday by the membership of the union, upon the unanimous
recommendation of its negotiating committee.
</P>
<P>
   Details will not be released until after the league ratifies the
agreement at its board of governors meeting Thursday at 11 a.m. at
a Manhattan hotel. But apparently both sides had their key concerns
met in the wee hours of Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we blink?'' Hunter asked. ``I guess we both blinked.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I expect the agreement to be ratified by the board of
governors at tomorrow's meeting,'' David Stern said in a prepared
statement ``I have agreed with Billy Hunter that I will not discuss
the agreement in detail until after its approval by the board. I
will say that I am elated that we will be playing basketball this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisive talks began Tuesday night after Hunter asked one of
the union's outside counsels to go over to the league's offices at
6 p.m. to meet with the deputy commissioner, Russ Granik, and
present several concessions to the league.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating secretly in a conference room at the league's
Olympic Tower offices, the two sides gave each other a list of
their desires. When they came across a disagreement, Hunter said,
they moved on.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching an agreement with the league, Hunter avoided the
heated confrontations that could have taken place with 210 of the
league's 430 players in one room and under so much strain. With
financial futures and playing careers dependent on the outcome of a
vote, players entered the day concerned that teammates would be
pitted against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we got everything settled before there was a
free-for-all,'' the free-agent forward Charles Barkley said. ``It
could have been bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage was avoided. But the damage of this labor dispute on
the union could linger.
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing to a deal that many believed was only minimally
better than the one the league had been offering all along _ and at
a cost of almost $600 million in player salaries _ Hunter's
leadership has been put into question and his future is uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
