<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETCOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 MindSpring Snares Netcom for $245 Million   By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Netcom, the San Jose Internet service provider, has been sold to
MindSpring Enterprises for $245 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   ICG Communications Inc., which bought Netcom 14 months ago, said
it will sell Netcom's dial-up, dedicated and Web hosting accounts
to the Atlanta ISP for $215 million and $30 million in MindSpring
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Netcom has 420,000 customers, but MindSpring officials said
consumers won't have to change their e-mail addresses or the phone
number they dial for Internet service. Prices are expected to
remain the same, though there could be new pricing plans down the
road, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers won't have to change a thing,'' said MindSpring CEO
Charles Brewer. ``Their software, their e-mail address, the price
plans, the number they call, all that stuff will stay the same,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, whose company has 455,000 customers, said he's been
eyeing Netcom for some time and bought it in order to increase his
company's market share. MindSpring, which has been beefing up its
customer base through acquisitions, bought both SpryNet and PSI
Net.
</P>
<P>
   The Netcom purchase will give MindSpring more than 1 million
customers, catapulting it to the No. 4 spot _ the same place as its
rival ISP EarthLink Network.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second sale of Netcom in less than two years. ICG, a
Denver telecommunications company, bought Netcom in October 1997 to
help it compete against regional phone companies, which offer both
voice and data products.
</P>
<P>
   But in November 1998, ICG said it wanted to sell off Netcom's
dial-up service, which was not part of its ``core
telecommunications business.'' ICG will keep the network backbone
of Netcom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
