<SLUG> BC-BANKAMERICA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 City Treasurer Rethinks San Francisco's Business With BofA  &HT;       
 By Edward Epstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bank of America chief executive Hugh McColl comes to San Francisco
next week on a fence-mending trip, and City Treasurer Susan Leal
had some troubling news for him yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sitting down with McColl, she is going to meet
with executives from Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. next week to see if they are
interested in bidding on all or part of the city government's huge
banking business. Almost all that business, which involves millions
of dollars a year in fees, is done with BofA.
</P>
<P>
   Several city officials, including Leal, Mayor Willie Brown and
Supervisors Mark Leno and Michael Yaki, have expressed
dissatisfaction with BofA since it was acquired last year by
NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   They have been troubled by a series of events at the bank, which
now is named BankAmerica but is based in Charlotte. David Coulter,
chief executive of the old BofA, was forced out shortly after the
merger became final, 10 senior female executives at the bank either
left or were demoted, and worries arose over the combined bank's
commitment to community lending in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary goal is to get the best deal for the city and its
money,'' Leal said. She will meet with McColl on Monday, when he
also will sit down with Brown. On Tuesday, McColl meets with Yaki
and Leno.
</P>
<P>
   The city's payroll of about $60 million monthly goes through
BofA, along with the ``concentration account,'' into which tax
receipts and other payments are consolidated, Leal said. In all, a
few billion dollars in city funds pass through the bank annually.
</P>
<P>
   She said the aim of her Wells Fargo meeting is to start finding
out if the bank is interested in bidding on all or some of the city
business. Leal has been talking about putting the city's business
out to bid since she became treasurer last January.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to see if the city can save money on banking fees
through competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Wells itself is merging with Norwest Corp. of Minneapolis, but
the combined bank will be based in San Francisco. That is a plus in
City Hall's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the first priority is getting the best deal
possible,'' said Leal, ``and then look if someone is a good
corporate citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wells is interested, the city could put its banking business
out to bid. But Leal stressed that only big banks can handle the
city's volume of business and the special demands it makes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she said, BofA counts the cash from Municipal
Railway fare boxes and also cashes monthly general-assistance
checks for the 11,000 or so recipients.
</P>
<P>
   BofA spokesman John Keane said, ``We have no fear of being
involved in a competitive opportunity to retain the city's
business. We're very proud of the way we've handled it over many
years and believe we offer an excellent combination of service and
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's needs are very complex, and it takes a strong
working relationship to tailor products that meet these needs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said BofA also has won the right through competitive bidding
to underwrite most of the city's bond issues for several years.
</P>
<P>
   That business led to a lawsuit filed by City Attorney Louise
Renne, which was settled last year. The city said the bank cheated
issuers of municipal bonds. But Keane pointed out that Brown has
praised the bank for saving the city millions of dollars on its
bond issues.
</P>
<P>
   If the business goes out to bid, Leal may ask the banks to do
even more. They may have to sell Muni Fast Passes at all branches
in the city, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he expects the meeting that he and Leal will hold
with McColl on Monday to be tense, at least at the outset, as city
officials outline their grievances against the bank.
</P>
<P>
   He said the only topic of the McColl meeting, for which he has
scheduled an hour, will be ``the maintenance of the Bank of
America's historic activities in San Francisco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
