A2113 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESHOP-SFCHRON &LR;      01-06 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESHOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-Shopping Hits Some Rough Spots  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Record numbers of shoppers went online this holiday season to avoid
the lines, the crowds and the traffic. But in its biggest test yet,
e-shopping didn't always deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet Santa didn't get it right his first big year either,''
said Jeff Atlas of San Francisco, who ordered books online twice &UR;  &LR; _
once from Barnesandnoble.com and once from Amazon.com. Each time,
the gifts he purchased were sent to him instead of the intended
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess a blizzard of orders resulted in an avalanche of
problems,'' Atlas said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, most online shoppers enjoyed the convenience of
ordering gifts from home or work. When problems arose, it was
usually because merchants underestimated demand and didn't have
sufficient computing power or fulfillment capabilities. In other
cases, a simple lack of human communication caused
misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline O'Donnell of Pacifica ran into big problems when she
tried to order a hibiscus tree from 1800flowers.com for her
brother's family in Oregon. She placed the order on December 12. In
an e-mail, the company told her the tree could not be delivered on
the date she'd chosen, but would be delivered on the next available
day by Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   When she spoke to her sister-in-law on December 23, no tree had
arrived. So O'Donnell picked up the phone and called 1-800-Flowers.
The company told her it had been waiting for her to confirm the new
Federal Express delivery date _ instructions she said she'd never
received. Her brother finally got the tree in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing business over the Internet is convenient, but it is much
better to actually talk to a person and confirm the orders and
information,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers spent an estimated $3 billion in Web purchases this
holiday season, according to various analysts. That's less than 1
percent of overall retail holiday sales, but it's more than double
last year's spending.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the spending came from first-time Web shoppers. Some
1.25 million customers America Online subscribers made purchases on
the Web for the first time between Thanksgiving and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet users polled by Zona Research, more than half had
spent nothing online in 1997. This year, those users and others
spent more than a quarter of their total family holiday budget on
the Web _ an average of $629 each, nearly triple last year's
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows Web shopping at the holidays is broad-based and not
just for kids and geeks any more,'' said Jack Staff, Zona's
director and chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   Not every online merchant was ready for the onslaught.
Heavier-than-expected traffic put several prominent Web stores
temporarily out of business, including those for toy giant Toys R
Us, book retailer Barnes and Noble and consumer electronics
e-tailer 800.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Everyone expected significant dollar volume. But some
retailers didn't anticipate their needs surrounding the demand,
whether it was (computing) capacity and technology infrastructure
for their site or the fulfillment capabilities it takes to get the
product there on time,'' said Nicole Vanderbilt, senior analyst in
Jupiter Communications Digital Commerce Group.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites were simply too slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Web, speed is a big part of customer service. The
longer it takes to download pages, the worse your customer
service,'' said Gene Shklar, vice president for marketing at
Keynote Systems, a San Mateo firm that measures site performance
and availability. Even a few seconds delay can be frustrating if a
shopper is trying to get through a site quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Online video retailer Reel.com prepared for the holidays by
buying more than a dozen new servers, the computers that process
much of the data on the site. As a result, the site kept working
and Reel.com was able to ship 99 percent of its orders within 48
hours, said Chris Deyo, president of the Emeryville company.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that are shopping online have different and higher
expectations in terms of turnaround time (than traditional
shoppers). There's a great sense of immediacy,'' Deyo said.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why online shoppers are easily discouraged when
things go wrong. According to Zona's research, a third of those who
ran into some obstacle, whether it was trouble negotiating the site
or trouble finding the product, simply gave up and didn't buy the
item. A quarter of those who ran into difficulty turned to
bricks-and-mortar stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do much Internet shopping, and some of what I have
done has been frustrating and inefficient,'' said Mary Barlow of
Tiburon. In one case, items she wanted were out of stock. When she
ordered a book from online mall shopping.com, she was sent the book
on tape instead of the print version.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you end up with is something you didn't want and now you
have to go to the post office and pay to return it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow did have good luck with reel.com, finding and ordering a
video _ the 1943 version of ``The Secret Garden'' _ that she
couldn't find anywhere else. ``If all Internet shopping was this
efficient and this reasonable, I'd probably never have to go to a
mall again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once orders were placed, most Web merchants performed fairly
well, Zona said. One-third of the shoppers polled said merchandise
was delivered within 72 hours, and 80 percent said merchandise was
delivered within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Mail-order goods ship in an average of two days, according to
the Direct Marketing Association. The association did not have
figures for delivery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I bought several Christmas gifts online this year: eight
toys, two books, one knickknack, one software program and several
household items,'' said Ron MacKenzie of San Francisco.
``Everything I ordered arrived quite quickly and in good shape. The
items from eToys arrived within three days,'' and this was two
weeks before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite problems, most Web shoppers said they'll keep coming
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I lived without (Web shopping). To me, the
convenience just about outweighs any shipping costs,'' said
Madeline Moore of Oakland. Moore said she'll keep shopping online
even though an order of books her daughter sent her from Amazon.com
was mixed up. ``They straightened it out beautifully, and I got the
right books in time for Christmas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
