<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACWORLD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Macworld Showgoers Hailing New Products  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Apple's new candy-colored iMacs and speedy high-end systems,
unveiled Tuesday at Macworld Expo in San Francisco, could fuel a
resurgence at the Cupertino company, according to consumers and
software developers interviewed at the trade show yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic, to put it mildly,'' said Darren Williams, CEO
of Active Concepts Pty Ltd., a networking software company in
Melbourne, Australia. ``We were seriously considering dropping Mac
development before iMac sales kicked in late last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Showgoers called the new products, including the iMac in five
colors and the redesigned Power Mac G3, among the strongest
offerings from the computer-maker in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally learned their lesson and came out with some
products of substance after years of empty announcements,'' said
Jeff Baudin, president of MicroMat, a utility-software company in
Windsor (Sonoma County). ``We were all getting a bit sick of
vaporware announcements,'' said Baudin, who was operating a
life-size replica of Robby the Robot from the TV series ``Lost in
Space'' in his company's booth.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Sutter, a self-described ``installer guy'' for software
distributor MindVision Software of Lincoln, Neb., added ``any
increase in Mac sales makes our lives easier. Until iMac, that
wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple was emerging from a dreary three-year stretch when it
announced the iMac last spring. The curvy, translucent Internet
computer quickly became a top-selling model, with unit shipments of
800,000 last year, according to PC Data in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Although the iMac was the single best-selling model in
December, all of Apple's computers currently account for only 5
percent of total PC sales, according to ZD Market Intelligence of
La Jolla (San Diego County).
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, people attending Macworld, which continues at the
Moscone Convention Center through tomorrow, said the addition of
colorful new iMacs as well as a $100 price-cut, to $1,199, should
continue Apple's recent sales momentum in the consumer market. They
also expect the high-margin G3 machines to be popular among graphic
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Many are so confident, in fact, they are willing to bet big on
Apple stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family ran out and bought $9,000 worth of Apple stock''
Tuesday morning, said Roxanne Brown, 24, an Oceanside (San Diego
County) graphic artist wearing a software box on her head. ``It's
about time they put out competitive products for general home
use.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's shares rose $2.06 on Tuesday to $43.31, but yesterday
they declined $1.56 to $41.75.
</P>
<P>
   Even Apple competitors admit the iMac could provide ``a great
wake-up call'' for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple appeals to simplicity,'' said Paul Otellini, &UR;  &LR; Intel
executive vice president. ``We all need to get away from beige.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every Macworld showgoer was overwhelmed by the colorful
iMacs, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should help the company make money,'' said Tim Van Wagner,
13, of Nevada City (Nevada County). ``The red one is OK. The green
is kinda ugly, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
