</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Las Vegas' Disneyland For Gizmos  &HT;       
 By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Most people still haven't taken down their Christmas lights, but
buyers for electronics stores already are starting holiday shopping
for this year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  About 90,000 buyers will swarm Las Vegas for the Consumer
Electronics Show, a four-day event where about 1,800 exhibitors
will showcase products as diverse as flat-panel TVs that hang on a
wall, car-navigation systems that give verbal directions, and
remotes &UR;  &LR; that let couch potatoes control all their home
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   The event, which opens today, ``is the toy department of the
information age,'' said Jim Barry, a spokesman for the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturers Association, the trade association that
sponsors CES. ``But it's not just toys for big boys and girls _ a
lot of this stuff has a real impact on the way we live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We come to CES to look at all the products and evaluate who
has the newest features and best price points,'' said Jayne
Spiegelman, senior vice president of merchandising and marketing at
Good Guys, a Brisbane chain of 80 electronics stores.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling over the Las Vegas Convention Center and several
nearby hotels, the show occupies the space of a couple of dozen
football fields and draws mainly buyers from electronics stores
like Circuit City and Good Guys and discounters like Wal-Mart and
Costco.
</P>
<P>
   CES also attracts high-powered Hollywood moguls. At past shows,
``I have literally bumped into people like (former MCA/Universal
Studios chief) Lew Wasserman and (director) Steven Spielberg
walking the floor,'' said CEMA's Barry. ``They're there because
they want to see the products that people are going to buy to watch
the movies they make.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendees endure hype as overblown as the splashiest casino.
``Just like Comdex (the world's largest computer show, also held in
Las Vegas), everybody's competing for your attention, but instead
of booth babes trying to make network-connector products sexy, they
actually have cool products,'' said Kevin Hause, an analyst with
International Data Corp. in Mountain View. ``This is a Disneyland
for people who are into electronics.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the products are going digital, &UR;  &LR; especially as
computer vendors venture into consumer electronics. ``Some of the
hottest new products were born out of the wizardry and digital
savvy of Silicon Valley,'' said Rick Doherty, director of research
at Envisioneering, a market research organization in Seaford, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   One hot new product category, courtesy of Silicon Valley, is a
digital TV recorder that lets you watch the first part of a show
while you record the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you're watching a program and the phone rings,
you can just hit a button to start digitally recording the show,
then return to it where you left off while the device continues
recording the rest of the program _ so you don't have to miss a
moment.
</P>
<P>
   You can even subtly speed up a recorded program so that you can
watch, say, a one-hour show in 55 minutes, with no noticeable
change.
</P>
<P>
   WebTV of Palo Alto, which Microsoft bought for $425 million in
1997, will jump into this market today, sources said, joining
neighbors Replay Network of Palo Alto and TiVo of Sunnyvale. Like
the others, WebTV's recorder is expected to start at $500 when it
ships this spring. (WebTV's main product is a set-top box that lets
you surf the Internet on your television.)
</P>
<P>
   TV is changing in lots of other ways, too.
</P>
<P>
   High-definition TVs, which provide crystal-clear images on wide
screens and CD-quality sound, will be all over the show floor from
manufacturers like Philips, Samsung, Sharp and Sony. At $5,000 or
so, the HDTVs won't be under too many trees this year, but the cost
is expected to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Super-duper HDTV models, costing $20,000 or more, will be
pitched for use in bars and public places _ just where most people
got their first glimpses of TV when it debuted 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   CBS will broadcast the football playoffs this weekend in HDTV,
giving CES showgoers a chance to cluster around display models and
see the picture and sound quality for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a regular TV, you see something white underfoot in a
hockey game _ it could be linoleum,'' Doherty said. ``With an HDTV,
you see that it's ice _ and you see every little particle of ice
being kicked up. The level of realism is stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital video disc players have finally gone mainstream, now
that rows of titles are available at Blockbuster and other video
rental stores. Some of the first DVD players that can also record
movies from a TV broadcast should debut at CES.
</P>
<P>
   Initially wary of technology that let people tape movies off TV,
Hollywood now considers home entertainment ``the best thing that
ever happened to them,'' Barry said. ``Movies at home are three
times as big as movies in theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as technology gets more sophisticated, the way users
control it is getting simpler _ a boon for the millions of people
who still can't program a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is getting easier to use all the time. New VCRs
program the time automatically, using signals coming in from atomic
clocks,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   To help tie together all those new electronic gadgets, tech
firms will be pushing the concept of home networking. Senior
Microsoft Vice President Craig Mundie will explain how the software
giant hopes to expand from your office to your living room _ with
home networking, new handheld Windows CE devices and ``intelligent
appliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco chief executive John Chambers will talk about his San Jose
company's plans to give consumers high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Although show organizers are loathe to acknowledge it, some of
the most bleeding-edge technology may crop up in adult
entertainment. Pornography helped inventions from VCRs to the
Internet take off, and it continues to push the tech envelope with
innovations like live, interactive two-way streaming video over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Adult Video Exhibition, sequestered in the Sands Hotel, will
feature such luminaries as Hustler publisher Larry Flynt, who will
take a break from investigating Republicans' sex lives to promote
Web sex site Vivid Video.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
