<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MP3 Is Well Worth the Hype  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  I'm hearing a lot about MP3, the technology for
downloading music over the Internet. Is the sound quality really as
good as people say it is? And do I need any special equipment to
play MP3 music?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  The sound quality is fabulous. I know this firsthand
because even as I write this column, Pink Floyd is coming through
the wall loud and clear from my son's bedroom, which adjoins my
home office.
</P>
<P>
   MP3, for those who don't know, is a compression technology that
reduces huge digital music files so that they can be downloaded in
minutes rather than hours and stored on a PC without gobbling up an
entire hard drive. (Music takes up lots of space. Beethoven's Ninth
Symphony, for instance, fills up an entire compact disc, which can
hold 650 megabytes!) MP3 opens the door for recording companies to
sell music online. It also has created an instant black market for
pirated music.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need any special equipment other than a computer with
speakers to listen to MP3 music. But you do need a software player.
The most popular one is WinAmp, a $10 shareware program that you
can download at  &LR; www.winamp.com.  &LR; With WinAmp, you can play MP3s on
your PC, either using its own speakers or through your stereo if
it's hooked up to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Want to listen to downloaded music away from your PC? There are
a couple of ways to do it. The most convenient is with an MP3
player such as the $199 Rio from Diamond Multimedia. Resembling in
size a Walkman cassette player, it stores up to an hour's worth of
music.
</P>
<P>
   Another way is to put MP3 tracks onto an audio CD. To do that,
you'll need a CD-Recorder ($200 and up). You'll also need a program
that can convert MP3 to .WAV files, which then can be burned onto a
CD. A number of such programs are available online, including a
good free program called FlipTech Visual Encoder &AMP; Decoder.
</P>
<P>
   What's in a Name?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I put together a database for my wife consisting of names and
addresses for a volunteer group called the Friends of the Library.
For some reason, the first name of one person, June, won't line up
with the rest of the names in the column. I tried deleting the name
and re-entering it, but it still won't line up. I constructed this
in Microsoft Works on a spreadsheet. Can you help me?
</P>
<P>
   A: The spreadsheet thinks June is a month, not a person.
Reformat the cell containing the name (or the entire column) as
general format. That should solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A Slipped Disc
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have Windows 3.11 installed. I purchased Windows 95 via
mail. It turns out that the CD is labeled ``For distribution only
with a new PC,'' yet the user's manual has a procedure for
upgrading from an earlier version of Windows. When I try to install
the CD, I'm informed that the upgrade can't be done and that I
should obtain the Win 95 upgrade disc. I tried contacting the
vendor with no luck. Any help would be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   A: The vendor probably is halfway to Argentina by this time.
However, you may be able to salvage the situation by removing
Windows 3.11 from your computer and then using the new disc to
install Windows 95. (I never tried this. You might have to reformat
your hard disk, in which case you'd lose all your data.) Before you
embark on such a drastic course, make sure there's a Certificate of
Authenticity on the cover of the Windows 95 user's manual. Above
the bar code on the certificate, there should be a product ID. If
that corresponds to the ID number of the program itself, you should
be able to install the program. But you won't know until you try,
and by that time, you'll already have deleted Windows 3.11. Am I
giving you a good feeling?
</P>
<P>
   Disappearing Toolbar
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, I had to reformat my hard disk, and when I reloaded
Microsoft Office 97, the Office toolbar did not restart. I have
tried reloading Office again, but this did not solve the problem.
How can I get the toolbar back?
</P>
<P>
   A: Try this: Click the Windows Start button, point to Programs,
then to Office Tools and choose Microsoft Office Shortcut Bar. This
should open the toolbar and also give you the option of having it
start each time you start Windows.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Once in a while, a Windows program will freeze. You can't
continue working, and you can't close the program using normal
procedures. But you may be able to close it using what's called a
local reboot. Press the Ctrl, Alt and Delete keys simultaneously to
display the Close Program dialog box. (You may have to hit the
Ctrl-Alt-Del combination several times for this to happen.) Then
click End Task to close the program. You'll probably lose any
unsaved work, but them's the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
