<HEADER>
A2122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PAC10-CAPSULES-LA     01-06 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PAC10-CAPSULES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC-10 AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
ARIZONA 
Overview: The Wildcats are replacing three All-Conference players
(Mike Bibby, Michael Dickerson and Miles Simon) and will be
hard-pressed to win their second consecutive league title. Coach
Lute Olson will combine one of the nation's top freshman classes
with the Pacific-10's best center (A.J. Bramlett) and its best
point guard (Jason Terry). 
The pressure's on: Terry, a senior from Seattle. As Arizona's only
experienced perimeter player, he'll be the focus of every defense. 
Player to watch: Freshman forward Michael Wright is the best
rebounder to enter the league in decades. 
Outlook: Because Arizona's fate depends on the freshmen, Wright,
Richard Jefferson and Ruben Douglas, anything can happen. Likely
NCAA bid. 
ARIZONA STATE 
Overview: The Sun Devils have a new coach, Rob Evans, but the same
trio of scorers: junior guard Eddie House and the league's best
forward tandem, seniors Bobby Lazor and Mike Batiste. 
The pressure's on: House has recovered from a jaw broken in
November to become one of the Pac-10's top perimeter threats.
Unlike predecessors Stevin Smith and Jeremy Veal, House plays with
discipline. 
Player to watch: Point guard Alton Mason, a transfer from Barton
County (Neb.) Junior College. His job is simple: get the ball to
House, Lazor and Batiste. 
Outlook: Evans, hired from Mississippi, is the anti-Bill Frieder in
that he preaches half-court defense and a patient attack. The Sun
Devils will improve steadily as Evans' system takes hold and seven
newcomers adjust to Pac-10 play. Probable NIT bid. 
CALIFORNIA 
Overview: The Bears start four seniors and have five of their
top-six scorers back. Their best player is guard Geno Carlisle, a
probable All-Pac-10 pick who has moved from wing guard to the
point. 
The pressure's on: Center Francisco Elson, a 7-footer from the
Netherlands who must rebound, defend and avoid foul trouble. If he
scores, it's a bonus. 
Player to watch: Sophomore forward Sean Lampley. He's athletic,
skilled and a rising star. 
Outlook: In one week, the Bears upset North Carolina, lost at home
to Oregon and narrowly escaped Oregon State. That inconsistency
infuriates coach Ben Braun, one of the league's best tacticians.
Chances are, Braun will get the problems corrected _ and soon.
Likely NCAA bid. 
OREGON 
Overview: The Ducks have a slew of role players, from forwards A.D.
Smith and Flo Hartenstein to transfer guards Alex Scales and Darius
Wright. Ernie Kent is the most underappreciated coach in the
league. There's enough talent for the Ducks to beat a few of the
elite. 
The pressure's on: Wright, a point guard from West Valley (Cal.)
Junior College. He must make the parts play together. 
Player to watch: Freshman guard Freddie Jones, a national-caliber
recruit from Portland. He scored 12 points in his Maples Pavilion
debut. 
Outlook: Looking for a sleeper pick? Try the Ducks. They're well
coached _ Kent is a former Stanford assistant _ and will be tough
to beat at McArthur Court. Their season hinges on winning a few
road games. Probable NIT bid. 
OREGON STATE 
Overview: Coach Eddie Payne could form a pretty good team with
players who have left his program in recent years: Carson
Cunningham, Corey Benjamin, John-Blair Bickerstaff and Ron Grady.
There's not much talent remaining. 
The pressure's on: Sophomore guard Deaundra Tanner, who must score,
pass, rebound and defend for the Beavers to have a respectable
season. 
Player to watch: Sophomore center Jason Heide, the lone frontcourt
scoring threat. He had 15 points Monday night at Cal. 
Outlook: It's grim, as usual. For better or worse, the Beavers
return just one of the top seven scorers from a team that went 3-15
in conference last year. Payne is a good coach in a bad situation.
In November, he signed the best recruit in the state, center Brian
Jackson, but will he be around to coach him? No postseason bid. 
STANFORD 
Overview: The Cardinal has size, experience, coaching and five
starters back from a Final Four team. But the vaunted depth that
separated Stanford from the pack has deteriorated because of
injuries. 
The pressure's on: Senior center Tim Young. Passiveness and a
nagging back injury have slowed his progress. 
Player to watch: Junior wing man David Moseley, who has become the
top backcourt reserve because of injuries to guards Ryan Mendez and
Mike McDonald. 
Outlook: With coach Mike Montgomery, forward Mark Madsen, point
guard Arthur Lee and shooter Kris Weems, Stanford is in a class by
itself. It's the only team capable of winning seven or eight road
games. Guaranteed NCAA bid. 
UCLA 
Overview: These Bruins play harder than any UCLA team since the
championship gang of '95. However, they have suspect defensive
fundamentals and a spotty half-court offense, which means they must
play with maximum effort to defeat the league's elite. 
The pressure's on: Sophomore guard Baron Davis. How's the knee?
How's the jumper? His teammates _ and NBA scouts _ will be watching
closely. 
Player to watch: Sophomore Ryan Bailey. Sure, he's a reserve who
rarely scores. But he was Penn State's starting point guard in
1997. His experience and savvy will be essential to UCLA's success
on the Pac-10 road. 
Outlook: When your top 10 players are freshmen and sophomores,
anything's possible. Bruins could go 12-6 in league play, or they
could finish 8-10. The most realistic goal: win seven at home, four
on the road, finish with 19 or 20 victories, and win a game in the
NCAAs. Make the Sweet 16, and it's been a great year. Likely NCAA
bid. 
USC 
Overview: Will the Trojans pick up where they left off at the end
of last season, when they swept the Arizona schools? There's enough
talent and coaching to compete for a postseason bid, although a
weak nonconference schedule won't help their power rating. 
The pressure's on: Junior forward Jarvis Turner. Brian Scalabrine
can't do it alone on the frontcourt, and Trojans don't want to
depend on freshman Sam Clancy. 
Player to watch: Sophomore guard Jeff Trepagnier, one of the
league's best athletes, who's steadily improving his skills and
adds size to the Trojans' otherwise tiny backcourt. 
Outlook: Coach Henry Bibby has raised the bar, and the Trojans must
respond to his challenge if they hope to join the Pac-10's first
division. They should win six or seven home games, but their
postseason fate depends on road performance. Is this the year they
finally beat UCLA? Probable NIT bid. 
WASHINGTON 
Overview: The Huskies have been the biggest disappointment in the
league so far, with losses to Boise State, Gonzaga and Washington
State. A rough early schedule and Donald Watts' sprained ankle _ he
missed a month _ contributed to the defeats. 
The pressure's on: Watts, a senior guard from Seattle. He has NBA
blood (son of Slick) and NBA ability, but he hasn't become the
dominant perimeter scorer Washington needs to challenge for second
place. 
Player to watch: Junior guard Deon Luton, a superb athlete and
dangerous shooter who has been inconsistent so far. 
Outlook: Not as bright as it was two months ago. If someone emerges
at point guard, and if Watts and Luton score consistently, the
Huskies will turn it around. If not, it may be the longest season
of coach Bob Bender's career. Possible NCAA bid. 
WASHINGTON STATE 
Overview: When the Cougars opened with a loss at Alaska-Fairbanks,
they appeared to be headed for a horrific season. But Sunday's
victory against Washington showed they may be competitive after
all. Four of their top five scorers return (All-Leaguer Carlos
Daniel has departed) but not even Cougars fans can name them. 
The pressure's on: Senior forward Kojo Mensah-Bonsu, who has a
great name and decent game. He's the Cougars' best chance to break
down defenses. 
Player to watch: Junior Jan-Michael Thomas, a sharpshooting guard
from San Joaquin (Calif.) Delta College whose jumper beat
Washington at the buzzer. 
Outlook: Coach Kevin Eastman is a solid teacher who hasn't
recruited well. The Cougars will win a few at home, if only because
no one is motivated to play there. But on the road, they're in big
trouble. No postseason bid. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
