<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PLAYERREAX-HNS &LR;      01-06 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYERREAX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Play ball!
<TEXT>
<P>
   That was the prevailing mood after the National Basketball
Players Association and the NBA finally worked out a new
collective-bargaining agreement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which is expected to be approved today by the
league at its Board of Governors meeting, will have players in camp
Jan. 18. The first games of what will be a 52-game schedule will be
played in the first week of February.
</P>
<P>
   The players had flown to New York for a vote on whether to back
the union negotiating committee's recommendation that the owners'
previous proposal be turned down.
</P>
<P>
   But after union executive director Billy Hunter and NBA
commissioner David Stern hammered out the framework for an
agreement during a 12-hour negotiating session that ended at 6 a.m.
New York time, the players found themselves voting on the final
agreement instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the owners' offer) is much better than it was before,''
said the Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon. ``We know that this is the
maximum we can get from the owners. The deal speaks for itself. It
is a good deal. It is a fair deal. Everybody is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means that this could be the first time anybody is happy
since the lockout began July 1. The negotiations had been hard,
even acrimonious at times, which may lead to lingering bad feelings
over the next couple of months from players who lost nearly half a
season's salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there's going to be (hard feelings),'' said Houston
free agent Charles Barkley. ``But we have to realize that we're in
this thing together. There has always been an adversarial
relationship between owners and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes (there is going to be lingering animosity), but that's
business. But once you sign a deal, it's a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rocket Kevin Willis, now with Toronto, was one of a
handful of players who criticized the union. But Willis feels the
partnership between the league and the players will quickly be
re-established.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it will, no question,'' Willis said. ``It's over with now.
It's time to play ball. We have to stick together and make good
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The players ``sacrificed'' the high-end players, limiting how
much they can get paid. But what they received in return, a higher
percentage of revenues for salary and more salary-cap exceptions
for middle-class free agents, more than made up for such an
important concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The percentages are a lot better, and there are more
exceptions there for the middle class,'' said Atlanta's Tyrone
Corbin, a member of the union's executive committee. ``The minus
that we have to accept is that we had to give up the guys at the
top. They have limits on the amounts that they can make, but we
have some things in there that will guarantee that the money will
come back down to the middle-class guys. So I think that's the
biggest thing. That and the fact that we worked it out together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, a free agent who was expecting to cash in after
making the All-Star team last season, said he doesn't mind that he
will be directly impacted by the high-end limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I lost a lot of money on my contract,'' Williams said.
``But, hey, how much money does one person need? That's what it all
comes down to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players were openly wondering why it took so long for
Hunter and Stern to sit down and work together to reach an
agreement, but Olajuwon waved off such questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this could have been achieved (earlier),'' he
said. ``It took all this (negotiation) from both sides, the give
and take, to get to this point. I think both parties are satisfied
and happy because they know it's a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's give and take. You have to give in some areas, and you
have to take in others. They work together, and that's the only way
you can have a good deal, when both parties are satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   And both parties are definitely satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy it's over,'' Barkley said. ``I'm just happy it's
over. I just care about the game. It's been frustrating not being
able to play. It's all about give and take, but we reached a deal
and that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta, another prominent free agent, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a sense of relief,'' Gugliotta said. ``We've
salvaged the season, and now we can get back to work, start
rebuilding the fans' trust and go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the best thing about a very busy Wednesday for the
players and the owners _ that everyone will be able to play ball.
Well, maybe the second-best thing, Barkley noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best thing about all this?'' he said. ``That it's
signed, that's what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
