<SLUG> BC-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INDUSTRY FINDS SURPRISES   AT THE END OF A RAINBOW YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 - SALES-ART-NYT   (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Last month was the best for auto sales since December
1986, lifting the industry's sales for 1998 to the highest level in
a dozen years despite a nearly eight-week strike last summer from
which the General Motors Corp. has not fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   With the last auto makers reporting their results Wednesday, the
industry's sales in the United States rose 7.1 percent last month
from December 1997. For the year, a total of 15.55 million cars,
sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and vans were sold, a 2.8
percent increase from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, sales soared when the impending expiration of certain
tax provisions for auto loans produced a race to dealerships late
in the year. By contrast, auto executives at the North American
International Auto Show here offered several reasons for the sales
surge last month, which followed brisk sales throughout the autumn.
</P>
<P>
   The explanations included the popularity of sport utility
vehicles and other light trucks, for which sales rose 10.5 percent
last month, as well as high consumer confidence, rising disposable
incomes and car prices flat or edging down.
</P>
<P>
   But even while citing these factors, executives seemed a little
surprised by how vigorous their business has been. ``The market is
stronger out there than anyone anticipated,'' said Robert J. Eaton,
co-chairman of DaimlerChrysler A.G., adding that the company might
raise its forecast of industry sales this year, from 15.2 million
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   While DaimlerChrysler, the Ford Motor Company, Toyota, Honda and
even struggling Nissan all posted big gains last month, GM reported
a gain of only 3.1 percent as its market share fell to 30.2 percent
from 31.3 percent a year earlier. GM sales for the entire year
tumbled 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Top GM executives at the auto show acknowledged that the
company, the world's largest auto maker, had not recovered from the
strike, which cost it close to $12 billion in lost production.
During the strike the company took a hard line that was based
partly on an assessment that sales could not maintain the brisk
pace of last spring. The continued strength of sales has left the
company's factories unable to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still short of product, there's no doubt about that, but
that gap is beginning to close,'' said John F. Smith Jr., GM's
chairman and chief executive. Roy Roberts, the group vice president
for North American sales and marketing, said that GM dealerships
now have 84 percent of their optimal inventories, barely up from 81
percent at the start of December.
</P>
<P>
   A few pockets of strength showed in GM's figures Wednesday. The
company's GMC division, which sells premium light trucks such as
the GMC Yukon full-size sport utility vehicle, posted a sixth
consecutive year of record sales last year as the industry's
overall sales of light trucks rose 8.1 percent and car sales fell
1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GM's Saturn division, which plans to introduce a midsize car
next summer but remains stuck in the shrinking market for small
cars, managed to eke out a surprising 6.4 percent increase. Mark
Hogan, the company's vice president for small cars, said the
division's showrooms had been busier since Thanksgiving, when it
introduced a car that looks like a traditional two-door vehicle but
has a small third door that folds open on the driver's side to make
it easier to load groceries or briefcases into the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan warned that the severe weather of last week, particularly
in the Middle West, might reduce the number of people visiting
dealerships. But Eaton predicted that the robust sales in November
and December would spill over into January. Industry sales in
December were calculated at a torrid seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 17.3 million vehicles, according to Ward's Auto Info Bank,
a data service.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reported on Tuesday that its sales climbed last month by
1.2 percent, as a 6.4 percent gain in light-truck sales more than
offset a 4.3 percent drop in car sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
