<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NEUVILLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACQUES NEUVILLE , FORGER FOR THE RESISTANCE , DIES AT 82
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: France, Germany, Austria, Calif. )  (Eds: Gunther is spelled with an umlaut over the u.) (DW) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacques Neuville, a forger for the French Resistance in World
War II who became a San Francisco department store executive, died
on Dec. 29 at his home in Sausalito, Calif. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Neuville was awarded the Croix de Guerre for his wartime service
in the anti-Nazi underground in Lyons and Paris. He had been born
and reared in Berlin as Gunther Neustadt, the child of a well-to-do
Jewish family in the clothing trade. As the Nazis took control of
Germany, he was sent by his family to Paris, where he studied
painting.
</P>
<P>
   There, as war drew closer, he found himself in an increasingly
precarious position as both a German national in France and a Jew.
He adopted a French version of his surname, changed Gunther to
Jacques and volunteered to serve in the French army. In 1940, he
was with an artillery unit north of Lyons that was overwhelmed by
German forces.
</P>
<P>
   Neuville made his way to a Resistance unit in Lyons and was put
to work forging the ration cards, passports, marriage and birth
certificates that were used to construct false identities. As he
later told his family, he was betrayed to the Gestapo by a woman
who had occasion to go through his trouser pockets one night and
found many ration cards.
</P>
<P>
   He was in prison for six weeks until a sympathetic French guard
left doors open, allowing Neuville and other prisoners to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking sanctuary, he knocked at random on the window of an
apartment belonging to a woman named Jeanne Lilaze, who took him
in. Late in 1940 he made his way to Paris where he worked with an
underground unit until the city's liberation.
</P>
<P>
   There his contribution to the Resistance involved working as a
street and cafe artist, drawing and painting portraits. He would
find his customers among German officers, engage them in
conversation and pass on what he learned to the Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   He received the Croix de Guerre in 1946 and later received a
citation from the United States for the information he had
forwarded on the location of allied pilots captured by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the war, he learned that his mother had been sent
to Auschwitz and that all of his family, except for a sister, who
was a doctor in San Francisco, had been killed. Neuville returned
to Lyons and married Christianne Lilaze, the daughter of the woman
who had given him refuge. He worked as a translator and assistant
in the Paris bureau of The New York Times and helped in the
coverage of the Nuremburg trials.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1952, he went to San Francisco with his wife and began a
marketing career. He eventually became the merchandising manager at
Macy's in San Francisco, where he helped to develop a marketing
concept called Macy's Fifth Floor, in which disparate items like
china, luggage and stationery were displayed together. He retired
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the war ended, Neuville began a campaign to obtain
payment on a life insurance policy his mother had taken out before
the war with the Swiss company La Baloise. For four decades he
pushed his claim as a matter not of compensation but of honor, with
the company insisting that it could not honor the claim without a
death certificate. But last year, as Neuville's health was failing
and as Swiss financial institutions were facing class-action suits
over their handling of the property of Holocaust victims, the
company settled the claim for $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two daughters,
Charlotte Neuville of New York and Madeline Bohrer of Salzburg,
Austria, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
