<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-1STLD-WRI     01-06 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PLANS FOR IMPEACHMENT TRIAL ARE NEARLY SET, LOTT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout to update and clarify; tightens   throughout.)  
 (ATTN: Pa., Maine, Texas)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-LOTT, IMPEACH-STARR,
HOUSE-HASTERT, HOUSE, CONGRESS-ETHICS, CONGRESS-NY and
IMPEACH-JOHNSON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, said
Wednesday night that the Senate was getting ``closer and closer''
to a plan for an impeachment trial of President Clinton that could
last as long as six weeks, and end with an actual vote on the two
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   His guardedly optimistic remarks about a possible agreement on a
plan, announced Wednesday on the Senate floor, just hours after the
106th Congress convened, appeared to put an end to any hopes by
Democrats and the White House for a bipartisan compromise plan that
might have avoided a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, Lott had conceded to senators that the emerging
plan for the first impeachment trial of a president in 130 years
would be one ``that neither the House nor the White House will just
necessarily think is wonderful but will give all parties a fair
chance to make the case and get to a conclusion that's an equitable
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist set to swear in
senators for the trial on Thursday, the two parties remained split
over whether to allow witnesses to testify in the trial of Clinton
on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. House Republicans
want to call such key witnesses as Monica Lewinsky and perhaps
Vernon Jordan, a Clinton confidante and Washington lawyer, but
Democrats have adamantly opposed calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lott did not say how the volatile issue of witnesses would be
handled, calling that question ``one of the critical points.''
Other lawmakers said the Senate might control the calling of
witnesses by taking a vote on whether to allow each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All sides of this Rubik's cube have been talked about,' Lott
said Wednesday evening. ``We hope to have this all resolved
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was not clear Wednesday that Democrats would agree
with whatever plan emerged. Ranit Schmelzer, the spokeswoman for
Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader, said Wednesday night that
there was ``no deal and no agreement on witnesses. Our position
continues to be, no witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott was also careful not to suggest he had yet found the magic
formula. ``I don't think it's safe to assume anything right now,''
he told reporters, ``so don't be trying to read my body English or
anything else. Nothing is written in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides declined to respond to Lott's brief
announcement of a possibly lengthier trial, saying that they still
did not know what procedures the Senate would adopt. ``I'm not
going to try to decipher the meaning of that,'' said Joseph
Lockhart, the White House spokesman. ``We will await an
announcement of what their process is before commenting further.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Capitol in the House, lawmakers elected a new,
little-known speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert, 57, who appealed for the
House to put aside the deep divisions that had engulfed it late
last year in the final days of its impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert was turned to by shocked Republicans after Newt Gingrich
stepped down under fire and their next choice, Bob Livingston,
abruptly resigned over revelations that he had had extra-marital
affairs. Livingston had toppled Gingrich just one month earlier,
capitalizing on anger that Republicans had lost five House seats in
a midterm election seen as a mandate against impeachment. The
election left them opening the new session Wednesday with a 10-seat
majority, one of the smallest House majorities this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions to problems cannot be found in a pool of
bitterness,'' Hastert said, delivering his first speech as speaker
from the well of the House chamber instead of the imposing
speaker's platform. ``In the turbulent days behind us, debate on
the merits often gave way to personal attacks,'' he said. ``Some
here have felt slighted, insulted or ignored. That is wrong, and
that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, called on the new
Congress to ``put to rest finally the poisonous politics that has
infected this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the impeachment of the president dominated a day that is
usually devoted to celebration and hopeful talk of legislative
goals and new party agendas. At times the confluence of events
almost seemed bizarre. At one point in the morning, Lott left a
Republican conference that was heatedly debating the trial of
Clinton to receive a quick greeting from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Looking tanned, Gore heartily called out New Year's greetings to
reporters waiting word of how impeachment would proceed. As the
presiding officer in the Senate, Gore then swore in the 34 senators
elected or re-elected in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, Lott and Daschle also placed a quick phone
call to Clinton to tell him the new session had convened, with Lott
making pleasantries about college football.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of a new tone, the House plunged almost
immediately back into the impeachment issue, because of the
requirement that the new Congress reappoint the 13 Republicans that
the 105th Congress selected to prosecute the president in the
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the head of the House impeachment team, in a
futile effort to head off the debate, called the measure a ``simple
straightforward housekeeping resolution'' and said it was
``incidental to impeachment.'' He said his group planned to
prosecute the case ``as expeditiously and fairly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the Democrats who had fought against impeachment
from the House Judiciary Committee appealed to the new members of
the House not to cast one of their first votes to facilitate the
trial of the president. Rep. John Conyers Jr., the ranking Democrat
on the committee, said the House had carried out a partisan
impeachment ``totally lacking in credibility and overwhelmingly
rejected by the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Today we have a final opportunity to put this
salacious activity behind us. If we reject the motion to reappoint
managers we will send a signal that we are prepared to move from
the politics of personal destruction.'' But the managers were
reappointed 223-198 on a near party-line vote, with the same five
Democrats who had supported Clinton's impeachment voting with the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate side of the Capitol, senators searched for a way
to reach a bipartisan plan for a trial that would overcome the
differences between the conservatives' push for witnesses and the
Democrats' opposition to them.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told Lott in a meeting Wednesday morning that House
prosecutors want to call five to eight witnesses and take two weeks
to make their case against Clinton, Republican senators said. Ms.
Lewinsky, as well as Clinton's secretary Betty Currie, and Jordan
were likely to be on the witness list, congressional officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that any witness list that we put together
will include the name of Monica Lewinsky,'' Rep. George Gekas,
R-Penn., one of the House managers, said on CNN. ``But the extent
of what testimony we would elicit from her, that has not been fully
decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said they wanted to back their colleagues in
the House. ``I would prefer not to have witnesses,'' said Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas. ``But if the House believes they have to have a few
witnesses to make their case, I'm not going to support some
political deal that denies them the ability to make their case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Democrats took a firm stand against hearing from the
cast of characters who have become familiar to the nation.
Assessing Democratic sentiment, Daschle, the minority leader, said,
``I think it is fair to say that there is universal, unanimous
opposition to witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has refused to speculate on how much time it
might demand to prepare should the Senate permit the House managers
to call witnesses. But Democratic senators who have consulted
closely with the White House have suggested that calling just one
witness could lead the president's lawyers to call others and to
demand to review more documents in order to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Clinton have repeatedly complained that the House
Judiciary Committee and Kenneth W. Starr, the independent counsel,
had access to information the White House has not seen. The White
House is likely to demand to review that information in order to
cross-examine witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans spent hours locked away in an ornate floor off the
Senate chamber trying to find a middle ground. Wednesday night they
emerged optimistic. ``It's gelled,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe,
R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Republicans wanted an actual vote on articles of
impeachment and not simply the test votes that had been contained
in an earlier compromise proposal for a highly expedited trial. And
in contrast to that plan's one-week timetable, he said that both
the House and White House could end up getting several weeks each
to present their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that takes you to January the 30th or February the 12th,
that's not as important as that you get these things achieved,'' he
said. ``I think everybody agrees to that. Everybody would like to
have it done in a speedy fashion, but only so speedy that it
doesn't cause people to feel like it's being shoved or that they
haven't had a chance to make their case.''
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators continued to try to hammer out a
plan in Lott's third-floor hideaway of the Capitol Wednesday night,
negotiating with Hyde and a three other House Republicans. Lott
described the session as a kind of pre-trial conference. The key
negotiators are Sens. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Carl Levin
of Michigan, Joseph Biden of Delaware, all of them Democrats; and
Ted Stevens of Alaska, Pete Domenici of New Mexico and Fred
Thompson of Tennessee for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A team of White House representatives, among them White House
counsel Charles Ruff and special counsel Gregory Craig, met by
invitation with some of the members of the bipartisan group who
have talked with the House managers who will prosecute the case.
</P>
<P>
   The senators hope to identify areas of evidence that both the
House and White House lawyers would stipulate to, to speed the
trial along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot has occurred between the House and the White House,
as we understand it, on that,'' Lott said, ``We're hoping that we
can facilitate that.Obviously, it would be best if we could get a
broad stipulation out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the negotiations progress, the first impeachment
trial of the president is to begin Thursday morning when Hyde and
the 12 other House managers are invited into the Senate chamber at
10 a.m. There they will read the articles of impeachment charging
Clinton with perjury and obstruction of justice. Then the Senate
will notify the chief justice that it is ready to proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-LINKS-N     01-06 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-ATLANTIC-LINKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC SEEKS TO SHOW ITS SYSTEM IS OPEN TO RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Texas) 
(af)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to show that its network is open to competitors, the Bell
Atlantic Corp. intends to announce Thursday that it has developed a
system that would allow its New York customers to change local
phone companies almost as easily as they switch long-distance
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Backing up that claim will be Allegiance Telecom Inc., a new
local phone company based in Dallas, executives close to the
announcement said Wednesday. Allegiance will certify that the new
system, which it developed with Bell Atlantic, cuts the time
necessary for a consumer to switch local phone providers from as
many as six weeks to one, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is sure to hold up the new system as evidence that
its local network is open to potential competitors, the main test
that any Bell must pass before winning entry to the lucrative
long-distance market. No Bell has passed yet.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, switching local phone companies has been arduous
if not impossible. Even in areas where the Bells face competition,
the new phone company must sometimes fax an order to switch a
customer to the Bell's offices, where it is then entered manually
into an antiquated computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and Allegiance intend to announce that they have
automated that process, allowing Bell Atlantic's computers to
communicate directly with Allegiance's.
</P>
<P>
   Having Allegiance alongside will increase Bell Atlantic's
credibility in touting the new system. Royce J. Holland,
Allegiance's chairman, was formerly president of the MFS
Communications Co., one of the first companies to broadly take on
the Bells in the local market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
