<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-ROWLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR VOWS TO REIN IN STATE SPENDING
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ John Grosvenor Rowland showed two political
faces as he was inaugurated Wednesday for a second term as governor
of Connecticut, calling for civility and moderation in government
even as he vowed to rein in state spending despite the economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, a Republican who at 41 is the nation's youngest
governor, used his inaugural address to project the moderate,
inclusive air that he has urged his national party to adopt. Then,
he strolled across the Capitol to a joint session of the General
Assembly and delivered a State of the State address stressing the
conservative touchstones that characterized most of his first term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we've had some great economic times,'' he told the
legislators, several of whom wore corsages and boutonnieres for the
big day. ``But that is no reason for us to return to the days of
big spending and tax increases. Our greatest challenge, over the
next four years, will be to continue to control the cost and the
growth of state government.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that his budget would not grow much over last year's
and that the rise was likely to be less than the inflation rate,
now about 2 percent. That would leave little room for new programs
proposed by legislators as they contemplated a budget surplus of as
much as $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lean government, free of excess programs, excessive rules
and regulations, helps us keep our budget in balance,'' the
governor said. ``It helps us provide tax relief. It helps us create
economic opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on Connecticut to ``resist the politics of personal
destruction that has paralyzed our federal government,'' and
offered instead a ``politics of results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When legitimate differences over policy descend into bitter
partisanship, the result is inaction, gridlock and the failure of
leadership,'' he said. ``The winner in such a power struggle wins
control of a government that is powerless to do any public good.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's message Wednesday was softer than his first
inaugural address, in which he warned against ``the notion that the
state government is the fountain of endless favors.'' Wednesday, he
emphasized the more moderate themes that helped him easily win
re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look forward to the next century, our responsibility is
to redefine the role of state government,'' he said. ``Policies of
inclusion must be practiced at every level of government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
