<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2298 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-Q&AMP;A-HNS &LR;      01-06 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-Q&AMP;A-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
With time running out, the NBA owners and players combined for a
buzzer-beater Wednesday, ending the 191-day lockout. Here's a look
at how it happened and what comes next:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What finally brought the sides together?
</P>
<P>
   A. When players began to gather in New York on Tuesday, a group
led by the Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon and the Lakers' Shaquille
O'Neal pressured union leader Billy Hunter to try to hammer out a
deal with NBA commissioner David Stern. By about 6 p.m., Hunter and
Stern had agreed to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Stern did a series of televised interviews in which he said if
the players moved enough toward the owners' final proposal, he
would try to persuade the owners to move toward the players. After
several hours of meetings between just Stern and Hunter, attorneys
and other league and union leaders were brought in. An agreement
was reached by about 6 a.m. New York time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who blinked?
</P>
<P>
   A. Hunter made the call, but both sides came off their
insistence they had gone as far as they could.
</P>
<P>
   The owners gave the players additional concessions on salary-cap
exceptions, allowing an extra annual exception to the cap for
players signed as free agents. They also increased the salaries
allowed for new contracts and the amount of raises available to
free agents who jump teams from 7.5 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The union backed off its fight for the highest-paid players and
against some of the rules it had argued would limit player
movement. And the union agreed to five-year rookie contracts, with
the team holding the option on the fourth year and right of first
refusal on the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The union agreed to make payments back to owners from an escrow
account if player salaries reach 55 percent of revenues in the
fourth, fifth and sixth years of the agreement. The owners accepted
the union proposal that the escrow payments would not be triggered
in the seventh year until salaries reach 57 percent _ if the owners
exercise the option on the agreement that season.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why did the settlement take so long?
</P>
<P>
   A. Egos. Stubbornness. Politics. Posturing. And given how far
apart philosophically the sides were when the lockout began in
July, each was bound to test the mettle of the other. But most of
all, until both sides stared into the abyss of a lost season and
the long-term damage it would cause, they were not ready to
compromise enough.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who won?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nobody. And everybody. Neither side could say it defeated the
other. The owners failed to get a deal with a hard cap and no
``Bird exceptions'' as they originally sought. The players accepted
a limit on salaries and additional limits on player movement. And
both sides will likely feel the wrath of fans left in lockout limbo
for six months.
</P>
<P>
   But if the deal creates a stronger league by giving more teams a
chance to compete for players, the owners will own franchises in a
financially sound industry, and the players will have more teams
able to vie for their services. And because the high-end contracts
can go only so high, more of the money can be spread to the
league's ``middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides will live with a system with more player freedom than
football but without the small-market/large-market problems of
baseball and hockey. And if the owners exercise their option for
the deal's final season, neither side will have to go through this
again for seven more years.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What kind of season will there be?
</P>
<P>
   A. Plans will be finalized to put in a 52-game schedule, likely
with teams playing only conference opponents. The revised schedule
would begin between Feb. 2 and Feb. 7, likely the latter date. The
playoffs would begin about two weeks later than usual, in May, and
could extend into July.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will the fans come back?
</P>
<P>
   A. Polls show obvious bitterness. But the track record of other
sports' work stoppages seems to indicate that eventually fans do
return. Baseball fans seem to have held a grudge longest, and the
NBA had better not count on the basketball equivalent of a
season-long Sammy Sosa-Mark McGwire home-run duel. But baseball
lost a World Series. The NBA lost 30 early-season games and an
All-Star Game. A 52-game season might be just enough for the season
to be considered credible and for the postseason to produce a
legitimate champion.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the anger of many fans will likely be seen at
the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What happens to season tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A. Teams will continue to refund the cost of tickets for games
not played, plus 6 percent. Other tickets will be used for the
revised schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How will the deal affect the Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are more than 200 free agents out there, and no one has
fewer signed players than the Rockets. The compromise included
changes that would allow the Rockets to pay a free agent, if not
quite as much as his previous team, enough for a contract to be
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who will play for the Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   A. No team in contention to land Suns forward Antonio McDyess,
including Phoenix, thinks as highly of him as do the Rockets. No
team is more determined to build around him to chase a championship
now and in the future. The Rockets will not be allowed to pay him
as much as the Suns, but they can come close enough to lure him to
Houston. They want Charles Barkley back but must move quickly on
him because he will count $6.6 million against the cap until he
signs or is renounced.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets also want Othella Harrington back, but he might need
to play the field to determine a price tag. It seems unlikely that
both Brent Price and Matt Maloney would be back. Price is under
contract, but coach Rudy Tomjanovich has given minutes the past two
seasons to Maloney. Matt Bullard could return. Mario Elie is
unlikely to be back. In addition to the four signed players _
Olajuwon, Rodrick Rhodes, Roy Rogers and Price _ this year's four
draftees _ Michael Dickerson, Bryce Drew, Mirsad Turkcan and
Cuttino Mobley _ will all likely make the roster. An additional
player willing to sign under the free-agent exception is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will Michael Jordan retire?
</P>
<P>
   A. He always said he would if Phil Jackson was not back as the
Chicago Bulls' coach. He also said after last season he wouldn't
``go through this again.'' And Barkley has repeatedly said his
friend was ready to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan has also made references to having to study the deal
and the future of the Bulls. The agreement provides a grandfather
exception to the salary cap and the other parameters for signing
free agents, permitting the Bulls to pay him 105 percent of last
season's $33.14 million salary. Still, he has the chance to go out
on top and is likely to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will the networks add more TV games to make up for lost time?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, let's assess the damage so far. By the time the season
begins, NBC will have lost five game dates and nine broadcasts plus
the All-Star Game from its 18-date, 32-game schedule. Turner Sports
will have lost 50 of its 80 game dates on TNT and TBS.
</P>
<P>
   NBC probably will stick with its current schedule of game
windows _ two Saturday games in April, two tripleheaders, six
doubleheaders and two single games on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays in March are booked for the PGA Tour, and Saturday
regular-season games usually aren't great shakes in the Nielsen
ratings anyway. So NBC's only extra games are likely to be in the
two or so weeks that will be added to the end of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   As for Turner Sports, its regular schedule includes Monday-night
games on TBS and a Tuesday doubleheader and Friday single game on
TNT. It's not out of the question that a fifth game each week could
be added to make up for some of Turner's lost game dates.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about Rockets broadcasts?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Rockets are among the few teams in the league that
televise every game, and fans have become accustomed to that. So
you can be assured that Fox Sports Southwest and KHTV (Channel 39)
will work with the team in every way possible to get each of the
remaining games on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   As for radio, the Rockets finally will make their debut on KPRC
(950 AM).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
