<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     01-06 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THERE was the mighty reach to the sky in the last seconds and the
fingertip block of John Starks' jumper that saved Game 6 against
the Knicks and the Rockets' first championship.
</P>
<P>
   There was the dramatic tip-in basket at the final tick of the
clock in overtime that concluded the Game 1 comeback and started
the back-to-back sweep of the 1995 NBA Finals in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   So many years and so many incredible efforts. Curling through
the lane for a jump hook. Spinning like a 7-foot top along the
baseline for another unstoppable fadeaway. Doing everything,
anything, whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, he is out front, the lead horse pulling the wagon. But
for what might have been the biggest, strongest, boldest, most
far-reaching play of his entire career, Hakeem Olajuwon worked
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the jubilation and the back-slapping by both sides of
self-centered, headline-grabbing leadership in recognition of the
end of the labor war, know this: Without Hakeem, basketball this
year might have been only a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Clutch City goes to the bargaining table. Or at least to
the New York offices of union negotiator Billy Hunter for a
polite-but-firm pronouncement that it was time to stop posturing,
put away hidden agendas and reach an agreement with the owners
before both sides burned down the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   It was a handful of players, tired of the politics and the
finger-pointing, who let Hunter know that a failure to strike a
deal with NBA commissioner David Stern could produce severe
consequences, possibly even legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a vote by the union Wednesday and a possible shutdown
decision by the owners today, a group consisting of Shaquille
O'Neal and his agent, Leonard Armato; Sam Mitchell and his agent,
Mike Curry; Jayson Williams; and Olajuwon cajoled, prodded and
eventually got Hunter to telephone Stern to arrange the 11th-hour
meeting that lasted all of Tuesday night and eventually resulted in
the new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wonderful feeling to have everything settled and be
able to get back to basketball,'' Olajuwon said from a hotel suite
in Manhattan. ``This new agreement is for the betterment of the
league, in the interest of both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the season had been canceled, it would have done tremendous
damage to the game, and it may have taken a long time to recover,
if ever. I believe that it was important to have some kind of
season, and it was getting late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to be here. I had to be pushed to get involved.
This is not about me.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is about him and all that he has become over the course
of a glorious 15-year career _ All-Star, Most Valuable Player, a
two-time champion and, most important at this critical juncture, a
respected figure, a keeper of the flame.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon had to be pushed by some of the union members who felt
their best interests were not being represented by Hunter and the
David Falk-Patrick Ewing-Michael Jordan cabal that was spending so
much time flexing its muscles like oiled-up bodybuilders. There
were members of the union who wanted to have their voices heard and
who needed someone with the on- and off-court stature of Olajuwon
to deliver the message.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem and Shaq, giants both literally and in image, represented
the present and future of the NBA. But while O'Neal carries
financial clout as a multimedia personality and unprecedented
physical strength, even he needed the thoughtful, statesmanlike
aura of Olajuwon to carry the banner of reason and compromise.
Olajuwon is nothing like the majority of NBA players in terms of
cultural and religious background, and yet their respect for him is
nearly universal.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's raw, uncanny abilities are held in awe by his peers.
Olajuwon's all-around character is regarded with admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it was time for his tact, his sense of ethics, to cut
through the bombast. He had sat back long enough, trusting others
to be reasonable men who could find common ground. But now the
clock was ticking down, and it was his time. Time to make a play.
So he came onto the scene like a steel hammer inside a velvet
sheath and pounded away at the concept of compromise. He had been
offended at the personal attacks in some of the previous talks, at
the profane language, the rancor and the bitterness. He was all
business, no showy emotion. There was a plan for him to address the
full union membership _ with O'Neal and Williams at his side _ if
that had been necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon is a man of few words. But when he speaks, people
usually listen. Hunter understood. Today, we have a season.
</P>
<P>
   Another slam dunk, Hakeem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
