<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PATAKI SETS COURSE DOWN FAMILIAR PATH
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EDIT-PATAKI) 
 (DW) 
 By   CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Rather than seeing his convincing re-election
victory as a mandate for daring new initiatives, Gov. George Pataki
seemed determined Wednesday to give New Yorkers more of what so
many of them liked the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   He could have used his annual address to the Legislature to try
and set his second term apart from his first. He could have made
bold promises and electric commitments. But the governor instead
hewed to his longstanding priorities: curbing state spending,
cutting taxes and toughening the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've laid a solid foundation on which to build,'' he said in
a speech so narrowly focused that it at times sounded repetitious.
</P>
<P>
   His stance had some of the Capitol cognoscenti griping about an
uninspiring performance and neglected opportunities. But Pataki
believes that with a disciplined agenda, he will preserve the
successes of his first term, allowing him to cement his legacy in
New York and giving him a platform to broaden his reputation
nationally, his advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the speech showed how much he has staked his
political future on a handful of landmark changes that he has
wrought in New York as the first Republican governor in a
generation. It suggested that Pataki feels that if these policies
are imperiled, then so is he.
</P>
<P>
   ``In four years, we have cut taxes and created a stronger
economy by suppressing government's built-in tendency to grow and
spend,'' he said, calling for a ``continued commitment to fiscal
prudence.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who fancies himself a student of Albany,
recognizes that successes here can be short-lived. Democratic
lawmakers tried to block most of his first-term accomplishments,
particularly his effort to impose more fiscal restraint. They
largely failed, but would no doubt like to scale back some of
governor's big-ticket items, like a big income tax cut and stiffer
criminal sentences. Even Republicans in the Legislature have not
always been the governor's most reliable backers.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's two centerpiece fiscal proposals Wednesday _ to
squirrel away the state's surplus of about $2 billion, and to
require a two-thirds majority of the Legislature to approve tax
increases _ seem intended to thwart any legislative attempt to
undermine his fiscal record.
</P>
<P>
   If the state spent the surplus, and then the economy slumped,
the governor might have to choose between steep, unpopular spending
cuts or repealing his beloved tax cuts _ a damaging fate that
befell his predecessor, Mario M. Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining his fiscal record, and therefore succeeding with his
new proposals, could have an important impact on the governor's
future; if he decides to run for national office in 2000, his
handling of the state budget would be important evidence of his
Republican bona fides.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a succession of initiatives that he can
dutifully herald,'' said Sen. Stephen M. Saland, a Republican from
Poughkeepsie, who, like many of the governor's allies, was eager to
talk about Pataki's future outside of the state. ``Certainly, I
believe that he was talking to a national audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor is expected to use these achievements to try to
fend off attacks from more conservative national Republicans over
his support for abortion rights and other moderate positions on
social issues. Pataki's advisers contend that the way to succeed
nationally is to get across the message that the party will
flourish by concentrating on such fundamental issues as tax cuts or
welfare _ and avoiding contentious social matters.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to lead that charge than Pataki, who tamed the
liberal Empire State?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the advisers also think that it would be foolish to
interpret the governor's landslide in November as a signal that the
public wants him to venture into new areas. People voted for
Pataki, these advisers contend, because they are pleased with his
record on crime, welfare and taxes, and to divert from this path
will only disappoint them.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is that New Yorkers will chafe at the governor's
reluctance to take on other issues, and some Democrats on Wednesday
repeatedly brought up matters that they thought he had ignored in
his speech. Assemblyman Richard N. Gottfried of Manhattan, chairman
of the Assembly Health Committee, reeled off a list of major
health-care matters that Pataki did not mention, from the problem
of people without health insurance to regulation of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listened to his speech, you would think that the issues
didn't exist, let alone any plan to solve them,'' Gottfried said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Pataki will tackle many matters in the coming months
that he did not discuss Wednesday. Governors typically use their
addresses to the Legislature to establish themes for their dealings
with lawmakers, not to present lists of proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Democrats criticized the governor's vision. ``He missed
a golden opportunity to reach out and talk about areas that need
job development in the city of New York and which really did not
support him last time,'' said Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, from the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But by doing it his way, Pataki sought to insure that the battle
between lawmakers and the governor _ an annual event _ would be
fought on his terms, not theirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
