<SLUG> BC-BKC-NBA-SETTLEMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TO START 52-GAME SEASON FEB. 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After an 11th-hour negotiation session, NBA players
union Executive Director Billy Hunter and Commissioner David Stern
reached an early morning deal on a collective bargaining agreement
yesterday to end the 191-day lockout and save the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an unprecedented loss of the season, players will
report Jan. 18 for an abbreviated training camp. After a frenzied
free-agent period when 200 players will sign contracts, the
National Basketball Association will begin a 52-game regular season
Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a joke all along,'' Mavericks forward Chris Anstey
said. ``A lot of us never understood what we were fighting for in
the first place. Now we can quit talking and sitting and start
playing. I'm glad we came to our senses. It's a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the National Basketball Players Association voted
179-5 to ratify the six-year agreement reached by Hunter and Stern
about 5 a.m. CST. Owners, who were within 29 hours of a vote on
canceling the season, are expected to give a slam-dunk ratification
to the deal at the NBA Board of Governors meeting this morning.
Mavericks owner Ross Perot Jr. and club President Terdema Ussery
will represent Dallas at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't love it, but we'll deal with it,'' said Minnesota
Timberwolves All-Star Tom Gugliotta, who is a free agent. ``I'm
sure both sides are saying that. But after the dust clears, we'll
all make plenty of money doing what we love. And that's the bottom
line, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   After six months of contentious negotiations on how to fairly
divide the league's annual $2 billion revenue, NBA teams lost about
30 games each of revenue and players lost more than $500 million in
salaries. Hunter, desperate after calling all players to New York
for a vote on the owners' ``final'' offer on Monday, called Stern
after the commissioner's appearance on ``Larry King Live'' on
Tuesday night. The two began talking at 8:30 p.m. CST, were joined
by Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik about midnight and reached a
deal just before sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, it just seemed like it was time to talk, just
the two of us,'' Hunter said. ``The clock was ticking and the
timing was right. We both had a sense of urgency, and I think we
both blinked for the good of the league.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Stern and the owners won the longest and most
damaging lockout in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Although players will again start receiving paychecks and
remain, on average, the highest-paid athletes in the world, their
last-minute cave-in cost them. The biggest chip for owners is an
individual player salary cap, allowing players with six years'
experience or less to earn a salary of $9 million; from 7-9 years,
$11 million; and 10-plus years, $14 million. It is the first such
cap in American professional sports history and provides a stark
contrast to the old system, which allowed Chicago Bulls star
Michael Jordan to make $33 million last season.
</P>
<P>
   Players also compromised their once-hardened positions on rookie
wage scales (up from three to five years) and on percentage of
revenue committed to salaries in the last three years of the deal
(down from 57 percent to 55 percent). In exchange, the players won
battles via minimum salary increases and salary-cap exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear who the five dissenters were in the vote, but
20-year-old phenom Kobe Bryant of the Lakers _ one of the players
talented and popular enough to demand $30 million a year _ stormed
out of the meeting 30 minutes before the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no winners,'' Seattle SuperSonics center Jim
McIlvaine said. ``Only degrees of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Players, most wearing blue ``Solid'' buttons, took a secret
ballot on paper, then greeted Stern and Hunter about 3:15 p.m. on
the 25th floor of the GM building across from Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very calm and focused,'' former Mavericks player Dennis
Scott said. ``Then it was like `Whew!' _ big relief when Billy read
the totals and we were sure we were going to start playing again.
What almost happened was pretty damn scary if you want to know the
truth. We almost killed 52 years of progress just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing players now is fan support. Apathetic toward
the lockout since midsummer, 50,000 fans responded to an ESPN
Internet poll yesterday by indicating 55 percent were ``not
interested'' in the resumption of the season, while only 11 percent
were ``excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Connor, 24, of Fort Worth expressed a degree of enthusiasm
for the NBA as he talked about the lockout in between pickup
basketball games at the Fort Worth YMCA yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy ... I'll still watch them ... The \Rlockout\S really
didn't change my opinion,'' said O'Connor, a former Houston Rockets
season-ticket holder who recently moved from Houston to Fort Worth.
``I don't know if you can say they are greedy, but it's awfully
difficult to understand how people can't get together to decide how
to divide up $4 billion or whatever the amount is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Gette said he considered himself a fan until the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season's over with,'' said Gette, 52, of Arlington. ``As
far as I'm concerned, they've ruined it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Major League Baseball four years and a historic home-run
chase to earn fans back after canceling the 1994 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get out and apologize to the parking lot
attendant and the guy who sells nachos,'' New Jersey Nets forward
Jayson Williams said. ``We've got to say `We're sorry' and mean it
sincerely. The fans did nothing to deserve this. Maybe we need a
fan appreciation day where we all sign autographs all day or maybe
I'll call the owners and have them lower ticket prices. Something
to get things back to the way they used to be.''
</P>
