<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MAVERICKS-SETTLEMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SAY THEY'RE AT DISADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Some of the talk after the settlement of the 191-day
NBA lockout yesterday assessed the winners and losers in the labor
impasse. But for the Mavericks, the lockout may be the difference
between winning and losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this long, long layover, it's going to hurt everyone,
especially teams like the Mavericks,'' said Mavericks guard Robert
Pack, who traveled to New York yesterday where approximately 200
members of the players union voted to ratify a new collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get in and work out our wrinkles and get to know
each other,'' Pack continued. ``We needed training camp and the
time to make mistakes, so we can try to be ready and be hitting our
strides by this time of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp cannot begin before Jan. 17, when NBA teams can
also begin signing more than 200 free agents. A 52-game regular
season is slated to begin Feb. 2. That could have the Mavericks and
the other 28 teams playing four games a week, and possibly pushing
the players to the brink of injuries by playing games on three
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   But the feeling coming out of New York seemed to indicate that
this abbreviated season is better than no season. With the deadline
the NBA owners set two weeks ago to cancel the season 29 hours
away, Billy Hunter, executive director of the players association,
and NBA commissioner David Stern went into an all-night bargaining
session that produced the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed to make more concessions than the owners for
the deal, which included an unprecedented individual player salary
cap. The NBA is the first professional sports league to put a
maximum on what players can earn, which ranged from $9 million for
younger players to $14 million for 10-year-plus veterans under the
terms of the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't put a damper on the settlement for Pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely glad the lockout's all over,'' he said from his
hotel room in New York. ``I think guys really want to play, and
they're going to make the best of it. Hopefully, this deal is
something everybody can be pleased with.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in this thing, nobody wins. Hopefully it's something we
can live with and get the season started.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Samaki Walker also is glad a settlement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never thought in a million years that we would
have been locked out for 190 days,'' Walker said. ``But I don't
want to be naive, because anything like that is possible when
you're in a business with big money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the Mavericks trade away Jason Kidd, and I never
thought that would happen. So anything's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything's possible might be a good mantra for a team coming off
a 20-62 record last season and fifth-place finish in the NBA's
Midwest Division.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting free-agent forward Kurt Thomas, Dallas already has
a 12-player training-camp roster intact. That includes guards
Michael Finley, Steve Nash, Hubert Davis, Erick Strickland, Khalid
Reeves and Pack, forwards A.C. Green and Walker, centers Shawn
Bradley and Chris Anstey, and rookies Dirk Nowitzki and Ansu Sesay.
Dallas would like to sign Thomas to a one-year deal, and Thomas has
already said he doesn't have a problem signing a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks also have to address the situation with forward
Cedric Ceballos, a veteran free agent who is well-liked among his
teammates and a proven scorer. Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson said he's willing to offer Ceballos only a short-term deal,
while Ceballos wants a five-to-seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   But since Nowitzki obviously is the Mavericks' small forward of
the future, it's highly unlikely they'll re-sign Ceballos, who was
acquired Feb. 18 from Phoenix for Dennis Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Slaughter, the agent who represents Ceballos, said
yesterday: ``The problem with having Cedric is he's interested in a
multiyear contract, and when I last talked with Don Nelson he's
only interested in a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason they traded for him, and now they want to only
give him one year. That's something that can't be done. It's my
hope that Nellie is really just posturing, but if they're not
interested in Cedric, we'll just have to talk to some other people
who have interest.''
</P>
<P>
   While the season now appears to be a rush job for all teams,
Pack believes the Mavericks would have been better prepared going
into this season had they gone through the summer-league program
and a regular training camp.
</P>
<P>
   And if it is a rush job, well, Pack is just happy to be playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can get back to doing ultimately what we all want to
do, which is play ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
