<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI OFFERS LIGHT AGENDA; CLASH ON SURPLUS LIKELY
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
(See also NY-PATAKI-ASSESS) 
By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Treading cautiously as he begins his second term,
Gov. George Pataki on Wednesday delivered a State of the State
message notably light on new initiatives, while proposing that the
state's budget surplus be set aside to pay for the ballooning tax
cuts already enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan to salt away most of a budget surplus that
is expected to reach $2 billion is certain to be a flash point in
his relations with the state Senate and Assembly, because it would
deny the Legislature one of its favorite roles, that of dividing up
the spoils of a healthy economy. While legislators might balk at
creating a reserve fund, they also realize Pataki can achieve the
same end by vetoing spending they approve, as he did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's annual speech to the Legislature, his first major
policy address since his re-election, was heavy on criminal justice
proposals: abolishing parole, logging the DNA of all felons into a
state computer database and increasing penalties for underage
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But he paid little attention to an issue that he had pledged in
October to make one of his priorities, reforming the state's
campaign finance laws. He devoted only half a sentence in his
hourlong speech to the topic.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in which conservative groups have accused him of
runaway spending, the Republican governor pledged a return to the
budget stringency he brought to Albany four years ago, proposing an
amendment to the state constitution to require a two-thirds vote of
both houses of the Legislature to increase taxes. ``The act of
raising taxes is a destructive act, and should therefore be a
difficult act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He promised that the budget he proposes later this month will
increase spending at less than the rate of inflation. And he
proposed requiring that two-thirds of the voters, rather than the
current simple majority, approve local school districts' property
tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must take bold steps to insure that this government
continues to live within its means,'' Pataki said in the newly
renovated Assembly chamber here. ``To protect taxpayers now and in
the future, we must make lower taxes and fiscal integrity the law
of the land in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speech was most striking for what it omitted, as the
governor avoided the most divisive issues facing the state.
</P>
<P>
   Health care was a major issue in last year's campaigns, and it
promises to be one of this year's legislative battlegrounds, with
New York facing a rapid rise in the number of uninsured people, the
expiration of its law governing hospital charges and growing calls
to regulate health maintenance organizations. Yet Pataki said
little about health care.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he repeat his call for a law guaranteeing women's access
to family planning clinics, first made in December, after a Buffalo
doctor who performed abortions was murdered. And he did not raise
what has been his frequent call to restrict late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators on both sides of the aisle were in agreement that
the speech had almost as much to do with Pataki's ambitions for
national office in 2000 as with New York's concerns. Democrats
accused the governor of showing his most conservative face to
appeal to Republican voters in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, said New Yorkers
``don't want to know if in Arizona they're impressed with a
two-thirds vote'' to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising was the response of Republican legislators, who
had unanimously refused to discuss openly the governor's national
prospects when he was running for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the script had obviously changed, as they sought out
reporters to crow that Pataki had demonstrated his presidential
bona fides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an eminently presidential speech,'' said Sen. Roy
Goodman, R- Manhattan. ``It touched on a number of areas which make
New York a national model.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the governor's new proposals seemed aimed for
rocky shoals in the Legislature. The Democrats who control the
Assembly raised objections to nearly all of his criminal justice
plans and said his budgeting notions would hinder their plans to
spend money on schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders of the Senate complained that Pataki's
plan to save the surplus would stand in the way of lowering taxes.
``We see it as a pot for tax cuts,'' said Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   The icy relations Pataki has with the Democrats were amply on
display Wednesday. His speech drew lusty applause and cheers from
the south side of the Assembly chamber, where the Republicans were
seated, while the Democrats made barely enough noise to scare off a
flock of birds.
</P>
<P>
   The governor spent far more time dwelling on the accomplishments
of his first term, particularly the deep tax cuts, than laying out
a vision for the second. And he continued to slay the dragons of
1994, when he was first elected. ``In New York,'' he said,
``government had become that uninvited dinner guest, who arrived
too early, ate too much and stayed too long,'' he said, and the
state was leading the nation in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki revived a number of proposals he has made in the past,
including tougher penalties for juvenile criminals, eliminating
tenure for school principals, giving teachers the right to expel
chronic trouble-makers from their classrooms, a law against hate
crimes and summer school for immigrant children to immerse them in
English.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new ideas in the speech was one long advocated by
environmentalists: expansion of the state's Superfund program for
cleaning up toxic waste sites to include hundreds of less severely
polluted tracts.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for the creation of a biotechnology research
center in Buffalo, to be run jointly by the State University of New
York campus there and the Roswell Park Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's only proposals on health care were to have
schools take a greater role in caring for children with diabetes,
and a pilot project for more aggressive treatment of childhood
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to save this year's surplus for future use was a nod to
the independent fiscal monitors who warn that the state will have
trouble paying for the tax cuts it has already enacted, but which
have not yet come due _ more than $4 billion a year. The tax cuts,
including reductions in property and business taxes, and the
elimination of the sales tax on clothing, are being phased in over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Enacting a requirement for a two-thirds vote to raise taxes is
an even taller order, requiring a change in the state constitution
and a statewide referendum. Many Democrats in the Assembly were
declaring the idea dead on arrival. ``What he's trying to do is
limit the ability to legislate,'' said Assemblyman Herman Farrell,
D-Manhattan, who chairs the Ways and Means Committee. ``I'm opposed
to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
