<SLUG> BC-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS STOCKS RISE ON THE CONTINENT, EURO FALLS AGAINST THE DOLLAR
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The euro fell sharply against the dollar Wednesday, marring what
was expected to be a pleasant honeymoon after the currency's
introduction on Monday. A drop of 1.5 percent to a value of
$1.15920 left the new currency below the initial reference rate of
$1.16675 set on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Its decline came despite a continued rally in European stock
markets, some of which are up 8 percent in just the first three
trading days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and traders said the euro selling was caused by several
factors. One was rumors _ which were not confirmed _ that there
were problems in settling trades in the new euro. A spokesman for
the European Central Bank denied there were any problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the dollar rallied against the Japanese yen after a
seven-day decline, a move that seemed to spill over into euro
trading. And trading in the new euro is still cautious and
relatively light, which means that its moves during one day can be
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also got a boost from a sharp rise in U.S. stocks,
which sent the Dow Jones industrial average and other indexes to
new highs, and from automobile sales and housing data that showed
that the American economy is still healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it means it has emptied the tank of the euro,''
said David Gilmore, a partner in Foreign Exchange Analytics in
Essex, Conn. ``There is still an argument for a stronger euro. But
it is a setback.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had expected the euro to climb steadily and quickly
to a value of $1.20. So the decline was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst said that traders were ``jumpy'' but that it was
too early to say the decline would set a trend for the euro's
value.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the euro has not been able to hold its own in its
first three days of trading _ its only up day was Monday _ Friday
could be very important for the new currency. That is when the
Labor Department releases the December employment report and
Germany announces its employment data.
</P>
<P>
   Given current expectations _ for a weak German report and
moderately robust American data _ the euro could face some more
selling pressure. ``I would argue at this point that the U.S.
economy has more momentum going into 1999 than Euroland does,''
Gilmore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
