<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   1998 AUTO SALES POST BEST GAIN IN 12 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Last month was the best for auto sales since December 1986,
lifting the industry's sales for 1998 to the highest level in a
dozen years despite a nearly eight-week strike last summer from
which General Motors has not fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   With the last auto makers reporting their results, the
industry's sales in the United States rose 7.1 percent last month
from December 1997. For the year, 15.55 million cars, sport utility
vehicles, pickup trucks and vans were sold, a 2.8 percent increase
from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   COKE BOTTLER ACCUSED OF FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   In court papers disclosed this week, Coca-Cola Enterprises, the
world's largest Coca-Cola bottler, is accused of engaging in fraud,
wiretapping and other tactics to drive a Maryland soft-drink
distributor out of business.
</P>
<P>
   EISNER BONUS TO BE CUT IN HALF
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. Eisner, chairman of Walt Disney, is about to have his
bonus cut in half, to $5 million from $9.9 million, because of the
company's weak performance in the 1998 fiscal year. The company
also said it would revamp the formula that determines the bonus but
did not elaborate on a new formula, saying only that it planned to
submit a revised plan for shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SAYS DEAL WEAKENS CASE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made its most concerted effort yet to convince a judge
that the recent deal that brings together three of its rivals _
America Online, Netscape Communications and Sun Microsystems _
seriously weakens the government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS MAKES GAINS AGAINST BOEING
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie made further inroads against rival Boeing when
Boullioun Aviation Services, a fast-growing aircraft leasing
company founded by a former Boeing executive, announced its first
purchase of Airbus jets.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman, the nation's largest maker of airframes for
commercial aircraft, said it would take a $125 million
fourth-quarter charge and that 1999 annual profits would be about
20 percent below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTOUCH CONSIDERS RIVAL SUITORS
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of three telecommunications giants holed up in
New York as negotiators met to discuss whether Bell Atlantic or
Vodafone would be the best partner for Airtouch Communications, the
nation's largest independent wireless carrier.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH RAISES ITS STAKE IN GUCCI
</P>
<P>
   LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the world's biggest luxury
goods maker, said that it had raised its stake in Gucci Group, the
fashion goods company, to more than 5 percent from 4.9 percent. The
news sent shares in both companies soaring on speculation that LVMH
might be seeking a takeover of Gucci. In New York, shares of Gucci
rose $12.8125, or 23 percent, to $68.625. The American depository
receipts of LVMH rose $2.125, to $46.50.
</P>
<P>
   EURO FALLS AGAINST DOLLAR
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell sharply against the dollar, marring what was
expected to be a pleasant honeymoon after the currency's
introduction on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO TO ANNOUNCE DATA STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the computer-networking company, is expected to
announce its strategy for blending Internet data with voice
communications to reach consumer households.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC SEEKS TO OPEN SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic intends to announce Thursday that it has developed
a system that would allow its New York customers to change local
phone companies almost as easily as they switch long-distance
carriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
