<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-PANTHER-POLITIC     01-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-PANTHER-POLITICIAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BLACK PANTHERS LOOK HOPEFULLY AT OAKLAND
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Calif., Pa.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ There were times, David Hilliard concedes,
when the Black Panther Party carried a stigma, conjuring images of
violence rather than community empowerment, of black separatism
rather than multiculturalism.
</P>
<P>
   But Hilliard, 56, is still proud to say he was a member of the
radical Panther group of the late 1960s _ its chief of staff, in
fact. And so Wednesday, when he announced his bid for an Oakland
City Council seat, Hilliard introduced Bobby Seale, who co-founded
the Black Panther Party here, as his campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was inspired by the new mayor, Edmund G. Brown Jr.,
and his progressive politics, Hilliard said, and represents
fulfilling the unfinished agenda of the Black Panther Party. That,
Seale told reporters, was not about murder and drugs, but ``was
always all about power to all the people, whether they're black,
white, yellow or polka-dot.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing with supporters in front of a high school that is
languishing academically, across the street from a row of houses
with burglar bars on the windows, the aging revolutionaries said it
was obvious that the poverty and lack of education and jobs in the
inner cities that the Panthers had hoped to address still existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is right to do this,'' Hilliard said of his bid for
the council seat opening next year. ``We now have a progressive
mayor who sounds more like a Black Panther with every speech he
makes. We can help him realize his goals for better schools, health
care and jobs. We realize he can't do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Seale, who has been living in Philadelphia for many
years, announced he was planning to move his family back to Oakland
permanently, as soon as his son finished medical school this
summer, to help ``bring about what we all advocated in the 60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of this, Brown, the former governor who
became mayor on Monday, sounded pleased, saying, ``You're going to
find a lot of very interesting people moving to Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   He described Hilliard's campaign as ``about the magic of
democracy that allows anyone who avails him or herself of the
process to participate,'' and added, ``I say, Right on.''
</P>
<P>
   Seale ran for mayor of Oakland as a Black Panther in 1973,
losing to a white incumbent in a runoff that brought out more black
voters than any other election in the city's history. Four years
later, the group was credited with helping to elect the city's
first black mayor, Lionel Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Several former Black Panthers have also run for office _ and
won. Bobby L. Rush is serving his fourth term as a member of the
House of Representatives from Chicago and is planning a run for
mayor. A few others have held local offices, Hilliard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history of being involved in this political
process,'' he said. ``We're no upstarts. Building a community _
that was always the Black Panthers' concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of the Black Panther Party includes starting a free
breakfast program, health clinics and bus service for the elderly.
It also includes frequent run-ins with the law. About 2,000
Panthers were arrested around the country during a five-year period
beginning in 1967. Some 20 Panthers were killed in shootouts with
one another, other revolutionaries, the police or the FBI. Huey
Newton, the group's other co-founder, died on the streets of
Oakland in 1989 in what is usually described as a drug deal gone
sour. Hilliard himself spent several years in prison in the 1970s
on charges stemming from a shootout between Panthers and the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very violent era,'' Hilliard said. ``This was the
era of George Wallace standing in the schoolhouse door declaring
segregation forever and whites lynching blacks. The Black Panthers
had a self-defense posture. When America grew up, we laid down our
arms and we started working within the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard has spent a great deal of energy preserving the more
noble aspects of the Panthers' legacy. In 1993, he published an
autobiography, ``This Side of Glory'' (Little, Brown &AMP; Company)
that tried to explain both the youthful idealism and anger that
inspired the party's formation. Last year, he began a Black Panther
Legacy Tour, where for $20, he gave a 60- to 90-minute lesson on
the party on a bus ambling through the humble streets of the city's
west side. With Newton's widow, he also started the Huey P. Newton
Foundation, a kind of information bank. He regularly gives talks
about the Panthers in the local schools. In the spring, he said, he
will begin teaching a course on the history of the Panthers at a
local college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Panthers' ideals have just as much relevance today
as ever,'' Hilliard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
