A2331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ABCNEWS-NYT &LR;      01-06 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABCNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MORE THAN A GOOD MORNING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Thursday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   After several sleepy years, ABC News &UR;  &LR; finally has decided to do
something about ``Good Morning America,'' a daily decaffeination
that now ranks a distant second in the networks' wake-up time slot.
Like CBS, whose morning show has struggled for years, ABC seemed
inclined to cede this rich territory to NBC's ``Today,'' where the
warm chatter is paired with a daily bracing of hard, cold news.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the lucrative ``Today'' program, ABC News has called
in two morning stars from earlier eras _ Diane Sawyer and Charles
Gibson. While their return has the whiff of a desperate publicity
stunt and undoubtedly reflects pressure from the network's
television affiliates around the country, the change at ``Good
Morning America'' also &UR;  &LR; has raised hopes that the network now owned
by Walt Disney Co. still values a morning dollop of news as viewers
start the day. Although both stars can do the cooking segments,
they pride themselves on expert interviews, and even hard news.
</P>
<P>
   Such hopes for news at ABC definitely need raising. The network
has faced a technicians' strike in recent months that has hobbled
ABC News during one of the biggest news seasons in television
history. But ABC News is not alone.
 &UR;  &LR;  As the old broadcast networks steadily lose viewers to cable, the
Internet or places unknown, the big reporting teams that made
network news crucial for many Americans are being steadily eroded.
 &UR;  &LR;  Outside Washington, network television bureaus have been closing,
especially those outside the country. News operations are being
pared down as the big corporations that now run these networks
recognize that even if news shows are cheaper than entertainment to
produce, the actual reporting of news is still very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks could get worse. Lawrence Grossman, a former
president of both NBC News and PBS, has been warning the television
news industry to look over its shoulder at radio news. Radio is now
the most profitable medium of all, and one of the reasons is that
the owners of radio stations are rapidly shedding their news
operations, choosing instead to use many of the same radio wire
services. Grossman estimates that out of 10,000 commercial radio
stations in this country, only 15 are genuine all-news outlets that
employ news staffs large enough to report on their communities. One
big money-maker using such tactics in the radio boom, Grossman
notes, was Mel Karmazin, who is now the president of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   It may be too much to hope that even Diane Sawyer and Charles
Gibson can fight for more and better reporting for a mere morning
show. But it is also worth noting that NBC has earned its steady
first-place audience, in part because Matt Lauer, Katie Couric and
Tim Russert bring a healthy serving of news each morning to the
nation's breakfast table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL WRITERS QUIRKY, BUT `JUST SIX' MISSED BOAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last thing anyone wants to read in a newspaper is provincial
whining. This business should not be about turf protection. Leave
that to a lawn service.
</P>
<P>
   But in falling off this high-road journalistic note, I do have
one question.
</P>
<P>
   What in the bleepity-bleep-bleepity-bleep were the ``Just Six''
thinking about? Did the brain temporarily malfunction? Is medical
help needed?
</P>
<P>
   How could Nolan Ryan's name appear on a Baseball Hall of Fame
ballot, and the little box next to his name not be marked? I don't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the ``Just Six'' all had good reasons. But when Ryan
received 491 votes out of a record 497 ballots cast by select
members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America, it became
a lonely ledge for those six.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone can come up with a good reason for not voting for
Nolan Ryan, I'd like to hear it,'' said BBWA secretary Jack
O'Connell of Hartford, Conn. ``Since Nolan wasn't a unanimous
choice, that means we will never have one.''
</P>
<P>
   The first BBWA voting for the Hall of Fame began more than 60
years ago. Remarkably, no player has ever been unanimous, and just
think of some of those names now in Cooperstown. The ultimate
tribute to Ryan is 491 of 497 voters approved him, the
second-highest percentage ever.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, who is in charge of the vote-counting, telephoned
Ryan in Alvin to give him the good news on Tuesday. ``He was
extremely humbled he had received that many votes,'' said
O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to the time several years ago when O'Connell made the
same kind of call to Mike Schmidt. Told he had been elected 16
votes short of unanimous, Schmidt paused, then asked O'Connell,
``Can you give me the names of those 16?''
</P>
<P>
   In other BBWA elections (Cy Young, MVP, etc), voting can be made
public upon request. But not for the Hall of Fame, which is
restricted to BBWA members with a minimum 10 years of membership.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ``Just Six,'' however, is columnist Bill Conlin of
the ``Philadelphia Daily News''. Conlin, a highly respected former
baseball writer, wrote a column a month ago explaining why he
wouldn't vote for Ryan. He also was a guest on Chuck Cooperstein's
WBAP talk show Tuesday night, giving his reasons. There is no hide
in Conlin.
</P>
<P>
   And the other five probably followed close to the same Conlin
logic _ that Ryan lost 292 games in his career, while winning 324.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Nolan Ryan a Hall of Famer? Absolutely,'' Conlin wrote in
his column, while also admitting Ryan would be voted in
immediately. But Conlin said he didn't think Ryan deserved to be a
first-time-on-the-ballot selection, mainly due to the 292 Ls.
Conlin did vote for two first-timers, George Brett and Carlton
Fisk, along with Gary Carter. Only Brett of his three was elected.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame voting is all about opinion and theory on
qualifications. But having now voted in 17 of these things, I'd say
this is the 17th consecutive year of strong disagreement with some
of the opinion and theory, and none more so than with Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still, however, severely hacked the baseball writers never
elected Nellie Fox. It's just ... well, stupid. Nellie's game was
not about gaudy offensive numbers, but he may have been the best
defensive second baseman/top-of-the-order hitter who ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, however, was all about gaudy numbers and baseball records.
But there was and still is a segment of baseball aficionados who
give a turned-up nose to Ryan's winning percentage over 27 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching is all about winning,'' they tell us, and tell us,
and tell us.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching is all about pitching.
</P>
<P>
   When a hitter goes to the plate, he is in complete control of
his destiny. It's strictly about putting wood on ball.
</P>
<P>
   But there are three elements that go into being a successful
pitcher, and the pitcher controls only one _ what kind of pitch he
makes.
</P>
<P>
   But then it comes down to the defense behind him _ unless
there's a strikeout _ and how many runs did his team give him in
support.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's 1987 season in Houston is a classic example. Pitching for
a team that would finish 10 games under .500, he went 8-16. But
Nolan led the league in ERA (2.76) _ no one else was under 3.00 _
and strikeouts (270). This despite a pitch limit of 100 for half
the season due to an injured elbow from the year before. The
opponent's batting average against Ryan that season was .199 over
211 innings. Tell me again. Pitching is about what?
</P>
<P>
   True confession. While Ryan was a shoo-in to be elected this
week, I'm shocked his vote percentage was that high, based on
notorious quirks of BBWA voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed we'd have one player, much less two (Ryan and
Brett), go over 98 percent,'' said O'Connell. ``In our
organization, that's unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   But we still can say the ``Just Six'' upheld a longstanding and
strange tradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
