<HEADER>
A2335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      01-06 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATAKI'S STATE OF MIND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Thursday, Jan. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Freshly re-elected, Gov. George Pataki gave a State of the State
address Wednesday that was a disappointing effort to make the
incremental sound grand. Politically unadventurous, the speech
allowed New York's governor to stick to his old, comfortable
issues. He was tough on crime and taxes and offered a jot for
education, a tittle on the environment. In a long hour, however,
Pataki spoke only a few seconds on health care, not a word on how
to allocate the tobacco settlement and one sentence, an
afterthought perhaps, promising to clean up the state's abysmal
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he focused on proposals like a New York state
constitutional amendment that would require a two-thirds vote by
both legislative houses to raise taxes. A two-thirds-for-taxes
requirement has a nice ring to it politically, but might not mean
much in Albany, where any tax has traditionally become law as part
of a last-minute budget deal that passes with hefty majorities.
</P>
<P>
   For felons, Pataki proposes an end to parole and the beginning
of universal DNA testing, a costly change with an uncertain
outcome. Moreover, he made no mention of the important but
politically difficult need to reform the Draconian Rockefeller drug
laws, which have helped to overload the state's prisons.
</P>
<P>
   A more promising proposal is the governor's plan to place in
reserve about $1 billion of the budget surplus this year as a way
to protect tax decreases already in effect. Although we would
prefer that at least some of the surplus from these fatter years be
used to help chip away at the state's huge debt, the governor's
plan is better than using the surplus to pay for another tax cut or
higher spending that would eventually make the state's balance
sheet even worse.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, as disappointment wafted over Democrats trying
to assess the political prospects for subjects barely mentioned or
avoided altogether, Pataki's Republican friends began collaring
reporters to make sure they got a larger political point _ that
this governor has talent to go national.
</P>
<P>
   ``An eminently presidential speech,'' one colleague purred to
the press. If this speech is an application for the big time, it
clearly needed a little work and a good deal of polish. Still, if
Pataki did not rouse the GOP to the nearest barricades, his speech
was safe enough not to raise any hackles, which made it sound at
least eminently vice-presidential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
