<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2337 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     01-06 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADERS PAY PRICE AFTER MISJUDGING SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It pretty much took a public castration to get it done, but the
NBA lockout ended yesterday with the collapse of the players union
and an overwhelming victory for the owners.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopee.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Billy Hunter and Patrick Ewing, for, unwillingly or
not, paying the ``ultimate'' price. Symbolically, of course, though
I'd bet that Hunter, the union's chief negotiator, and Ewing, its
president, have both checked several times to be sure that all
vital parts are still intact.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players, teetering on the verge of casting a vote of ``no
support'' for Hunter, Ewing and the other union leaders in an
emergency meeting in New York called for yesterday morning, were
instead stunned to learn when they arrived that an abashed Hunter
and commissioner David Stern had hammered out an agreement during
an all-night bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a genius to figure out that Hunter must have
finally got a read on the temperament of his constituents and
realized it was time to cut the best deal he could and save face.
</P>
<P>
   Or whatever he could save, which wasn't much.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, when Hunter brought Stern's offer to the players, was
an all-but-unanimous 179-5 to accept. Those against must have
included five of the six who didn't vote for Nolan Ryan for the
Baseball Hall of Fame either.
</P>
<P>
   One unconfirmed rumor circulating yesterday was that LA's
Shaquille O'Neal and the New Jersey Nets' Jayson Williams went to
Hunter's New York hotel room Tuesday night and strongly
``suggested'' that the rank-and-file members weren't going to be
intimidated by veteran players like Ewing and others in union
leadership and that it was time for Hunter to sit down with Stern
and work something out.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, it's rather pleasant to envision that, or something
similar, happening.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the owners got many of the concessions they were
looking for, most important a hard cap on veteran salaries. No
sports union had ever agreed to a maximum salary for players until
the NBA's did yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your hearts out, baseball owners.
</P>
<P>
   The next Michael Jordan to come along, whoever he is, can't make
more than $14 million a year. You listening, Michael Finley?
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody really won, of course. Nobody ever does when
things get this bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the owners and the players have done irreparable
damage to their sport and its once exciting and highly marketable
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't put a bandage on what both sides have done,'' Knicks
forward Terry Cummings told the ``New York Post'' even before the
agreement had been reached. ``We must sew it up in the 40 or so
games remaining and let the fans fall back in love with the game.
Let us fall back in love with it ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, this is the easiest money we'll ever make That
anyone can ever make.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the message that finally got through to Hunter, who leads
a union of players who average $2.6 million a year, by far the
highest in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for pity's sake, did it take this long? Why, with
baseball's 1994 strike sitting there as the perfect example of how
not to do things, did the NBA _ both sides _ pick up that script
and read from it almost line by line? In the end, the offer the
players accepted was virtually the same one, with a few tweaks here
and there, that had been on the table for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the rank-and-file players hadn't made a stand, who knows
when NBA basketball as we've known it would have been played again?
</P>
<P>
   Hunter and Ewing thought they had the support vote locked in in
their favor. They'd all but rigged it that way, announcing through
Larry King's TV show that all NBA players had to come to New York
yesterday to vote, whether or not they supported their union
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left by players to the union offices went unanswered.
Players couldn't find out where to report or when. The union's
hotline number had a recording last updated Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   What Hunter and Ewing wanted was a low voter turnout, allowing
the union reps to intimidate those who managed to show up. That's
also why it was announced that the vote would not be by secret
ballot but by a verbal ``yea or nay'' count.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peer pressure in that room would have been tremendous,''
an NBA executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the vote showed reluctant support for Hunter and Ewing _
and you know it would have been announced as ``unanimous'' _ then
they could have thumbed their noses at Stern, who had claimed that
most players wouldn't support the union's position.
</P>
<P>
   Stern was right, but before we applaud him too much, let's
remember that he's equally responsible for this appalling mess. All
Hunter did was beat him to the phone anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There are no heroes here. That's the message that was driven
home to the fans once again as they watched multimillionaires
squabble over how to split $2 billion in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   An abbreviated 52-game season, they say, will begin on Feb. 2,
with full playoffs to follow. Thank God, we can now get Ewing out
of his suit and tie, off the podium and away from the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   I never thought I'd be so happy seeing a grown man in his
underwear again.
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, like it or not, the NBA is back.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
