<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPIKE-LEE-NYT &LR;      01-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPIKE-LEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE GOT GAME AGAIN, AND IT'S ABOUT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 (See also BKN-NBA, BKN-NBA-SEASON, BKN-NBA-IMPACT, BKN-NBA-SETTLE,
BKN-NBA-FANS, BKN-NBA-PLAYERS, BKN-NBA-HUNTER, BKN-NBA-JORDAN,
BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN, BKN-ARATON-COLUMN, BKN-NBA-DEAL, BKN-NBA-KNICKS,
BKN-NBA-EWING) 
By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's been a rough three months for Spike Lee, the
filmmaker and famous Knicks fan, who has weathered the lockout as
well as can be expected for a man who once jetted back from the
Cannes Film Festival rather than miss a regular game. ``Actually I
flew back twice in one week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not an understatement to say Lee has been made whole
again now that the owners and the players have tentatively settled
their differences. ``I'm ready to get back to the game,'' he said
Wednesday, upon learning the happy news. ``The nightmare is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling the void has not been easy. He has had to make do with
college football while grumbling about greedy team owners and
enduring remarks from strangers who imagine him a personal adviser
to Patrick Ewing, the players' union president. ``As if I had any
influence,'' Lee said, shaking his head with a bemused grin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people could be forgiven for thinking that he has
some pull with basketball's rank and file. Besides his friendship
with players like Ewing, Michael Jordan and Ray Allen, Lee is known
as the Knicks' unofficial coach and one of its most zealous
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, his $1,500-a-game seats on Celebrity Row have
given the public frequent glimpses of his boisterous boosterism _
and his habit of taunting the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious episode occurred during a nationally
televised playoff game in 1994, when Reggie Miller, the voluble
Indiana Pacers guard, obscenely heckled Lee while sinking 25
long-range points that stole the game. The next day, Lee found
himself a front-page demon in the city's tabloids, the scapegoat
for the home team's ugly defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really wanted my neck,'' recalled Lee, who says he
sweated through the final playoff game that summer, worried that a
Knicks loss might bring out an angry mob. ``I felt like I had more
at stake than the players,'' he said. The Knicks won that night,
and Lee got to keep his neck.
</P>
<P>
   While the union's executive director and the league's
commissioner were negotiating in secret on Tuesday night, Lee was
working out at an Equinox gym in midtown, dressed in his trademark
orange and blue (the Knicks' colors, for those born yesterday).
Besides the Stairmaster and softball, Lee, 41, says he isn't much
of an athlete. ``I was never any good at basketball,'' he said,
sitting down with a cup of carrot juice at the gym's health bar.
``I really miss the game,'' he said, glancing up at a television
screen that showed David Stern, the National Basketball
Association's commissioner. Lee rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he is editing his latest film, ``Summer of Sam,''
set in the summer of 1977, when the serial killer known as Son of
Sam terrorized New York. ``It's my first all-Italian-American
film,'' he said, referring to the cast. ``There aren't any black
stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Race often plays a starring role in Lee's films, and the subject
is often on his mind. Basketball is no different, and Lee believes
that the racially polarized league _ the owners all white and the
players mostly black _ has worsened the strife. ``I think a lot of
white America has a problem with these young black men making so
much money,'' he said, referring to the disputed cap on salaries.
``No other industry places a limit on what a person can earn. Can
you imagine if Hollywood tried to cap Tom Cruise or Leonardo
DiCaprio's salary? No way.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that some players had misjudged public sentiment
with statements like those of Ewing, who said the owners were
trying to force his colleagues into poverty. ``It's unfortunate,''
Lee said, ``but these guys aren't used to talking to the media,
unless it's about how they won or lost the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee says his love of basketball came from his father, Bill, a
bass player who dragged his young son to the old Madison Square
Garden on Eighth Avenue at 49th Street. As a teen-ager he rode the
subway alone from Brooklyn to cheer the Knicks from the blues, as
the top tier of the Garden is called. More often he would sneak
past the ushers so his hoots might reach the players' ears.
</P>
<P>
   As a 14-year-old, he watched as a limping Willis Reed scored the
first two baskets that led to the Knicks' unexpected
championship-game victory in 1970 over the Lakers. Lee was so moved
by the scene, he reconstructed it in his film ``Crooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the year Ewing was drafted by the Knicks, Lee finally
splurged and bought season tickets for about $400. They were in the
lofty green section, but with each new film he directed, Lee says,
he edged closer to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrities have come and gone from the courtside seats
opposite the Knicks bench, but Lee is always there, usually with
his wife, Tonya, or with one of their two children, Jackson and
Satchel. He shows up two hours early for games so he can schmooze
with the players and hold court with movie fans. When the warm-ups
begin, it is Lee who tosses out the ball.
</P>
<P>
   If a last-minute impasse ends up killing the season, Lee says he
will start following college basketball. (``Write down that I'm
looking for a ticket to the St. John's game,'' he said, referring
to the Big East team from Queens.) Even if he has to wait until
2000 to see the Knicks play again, his ardor will not be
diminished, ``just as long as I get my season ticket money back,''
he said, adding, ``with 6 percent interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
