<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FARRIS-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARRIS TO APPLY FOR NFL DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he arrived at UCLA in 1995, offensive tackle
Kris Farris set three goals: make the All-Pacific-10 team, make the
All-American team, and win the Outland Trophy as the nation's best
interior lineman.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-week span that began in late November, Farris
accomplished all three. So in a 20-minute press conference
Wednesday, he announced he will forgo his senior season and apply
for the NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   His decision seemingly was not based on money or draft position.
He's considered a late first- or early second-round pick, and a
senior season probably would have increased his value
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Farris said goodbye to UCLA because he was saying
goodbye to his linemates, seniors Shawn Stuart and Andy Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I belong here anymore,'' said Farris, a
fourth-year junior. ``When the seniors graduated last year, it was
hard for me because I grew up with them. Now that (Meyers and
Stuart) are leaving, it makes it harder to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris wavered after the loss to Miami. But the postseason
honors, a solid Rose Bowl performance and an offensive line meeting
made him realize his time had come _ and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a meeting one day (before Christmas), and Andy and
(Stuart) were at Andy's grandfather's funeral,'' Farris said. ``I
looked around, and it was just me....
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been viewed as a senior. Every time there's a
senior meeting, I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo believed all along that Farris would
choose the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pretty good idea,'' Toledo said. ``It was his
personality. He acted like a senior.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris' departure leaves a gaping hole at left tackle. Toledo
said the Bruins have several candidates: reserve David Wilford,
converted defensive lineman Josh Webb and two promising freshmen,
Blake Worley and Mike Saffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody will emerge,'' Toledo said, ``but we'll be young.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990106.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2344 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-MONEY-TEX     01-06 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-MONEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUTS LINGERING EFFECTS ON REVENUE UNCLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Damaged, but not destroyed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's how sports marketing experts view the business of the NBA
in the wake of the six-month owners' lockout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, the shutdown cost players millions in salaries
and owners millions in lost ticket sales. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the lingering ill will could cost professional basketball
much more in future revenue, both at the gate _ where disgruntled
fans might stay away in protest or disinterest _ and in boardrooms
_ where corporations might decide to sponsor other sports. The
lockout's effects also could be felt in stores where licensed
merchandise sales already have declined, and in living rooms where
television viewership of NBA games might wane. That would drive
down advertising rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How much revenue will be lost because of the lockout won't be
known until after the shortened 1999 season when attendance and
sales figures are calculated and when sponsorship contracts are
renewed and ad rates set. But marketers said the figures likely
won't be pretty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The players and owners have been exposed. They came off like
two spoiled kids,'' said David Smith, president of Steiner Sports
Marketing, a New York sports marketing firm. ``There's no question
that has an impact. The NBA was at its height last year, with
\RMichael\S Jordan winning another championship and with
\Rcommissioner\S David Stern having built a phenomenal marketing
vehicle. Now, you have all this dirty laundry out there. There is
this perception of greediness.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been significant short-term damage to the sport,''
said Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports Services, which
matches advertisers with sports figures. ``Will fan excitement
eventually get back to the level of last year? I don't think so.
The players have revealed that greed and arrogance is what's
driving them and that they're out of touch with their fans. Couple
that greed with the eventual retirement of Jordan and it'll be hard
to recover.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The situation, however, is not entirely hopeless, analysts said.
Much depends on Jordan, whose return for one more season was deemed
essential to rebuilding fan interest. Jordan has not announced if
he will play this season. Also critical: another exciting
postseason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To counter the negative publicity of the lockout, marketers
said, the NBA and its teams will probably not soon increase the
price of tickets, sponsorships or licensing agreements, all of
which have been skyrocketing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effect on some teams, including the Mavericks,
apparently has been minimal. Mavericks officials said there has not
been a significant erosion of ticket sales or corporate support
during the lockout. In fact, a Mavericks official said the team
actually sold several ticket packages yesterday after word of the
settlement came. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NBA does have one other asset in its favor as it tries to
recover from lockout-related damage _ its lucrative multiyear
national TV contract. The deal kept revenue flowing throughout the
lockout and won't expire until 2002. By the time negotiations on a
new contract begin, sports media analysts said, the league's image
could be fully restored and the value of its next TV contract
enhanced. NBA clubs are to receive more than $600 million this
season from NBC and Turner Sports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether basketball fans will continue to tune in NBA games at
levels established in recent seasons is uncertain. Media analysts
note that TV ratings for baseball have yet to recover from that
sport's strike in 1994-95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basketball-related merchandise sales have declined this season,
in part because retailers, anticipating a lockout, didn't order as
much inventory as in past seasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retaining corporate sponsors also could be a difficult task.
Sports marketers said that companies might now perceive the NBA as
a risky marketing proposition and decide to allocate advertising
and marketing dollars to other sports. Companies, they said, might
not want to be associated with a league whose owners and players
are perceived as greedy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-06-99 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
