<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-Q&AMP;A-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS TAKE ROYAL BEATING IN LONG BATTLE WITH OWNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pertinent questions and answers surrounding yesterday's end of
the NBA lockout:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was commissioner David Stern serious about canceling the
season, and how close did we come to that disaster?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, and very. Players who arrived in New York said yesterday
they weren't sure how the vote to approve the owners' supposed
final offer would have went. Of those polled, it seemed about
50-50. If rejected, owners had already decided to cancel the
season. Stern made the deal because owners asked him to; Hunter
because players demanded him to.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After six months of contentious posturing, did either side
win?
</P>
<P>
   A: Huge win for the owners in several areas, including a
lengthened rookie wage scale to five years and percentage of
revenue designated for salaries (i.e. salary cap) down to 55
percent from the players' original stance of 63. The biggest win,
however, is the fact that players' salaries are now limited.
Whereas Michael Jordan made $33 million last season, a future
superstar like the Lakers' Kobe Bryant will have to play 10 years
just to get to $14 million a season. The players didn't want a hard
cap and they didn't get one, they got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were the other losers in this ordeal?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rookies, who now must play five years with the same team
under a slotted salary. And agents, who will get many less
negotiating opportunities with rookies and free agents and smaller
percentages of smaller salaries. The days of contracts like Kevin
Garnett's seven-year, $126 million deal are history.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   A: Owners will ratify the agreement today at their board of
governors meeting, then lawyers will put the deal in writing over
the next week. Teams will begin calling players, pondering trades
and evaluating free-agent moves for the frenzied period that will
begin Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When do we get to see NBA games again?
</P>
<P>
   A: After a two-week training camp starting Jan. 18, a 52-game
regular season begins Feb. 2. Though the All-Star Weekend was
canceled long ago, a regular format of playoffs is scheduled to
begin May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will the shortened schedule work?
</P>
<P>
   A: The original format is scrapped, meaning your pocket schedule
is useless. Teams will likely play every team at least once, with
most of the focus on intra-conference games. Games on three
consecutive days had been talked about, but the basic thinking now
is to play four games a week for the 13-week season.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who will be the teams coming to Reunion Arena from the
Eastern Conference?
</P>
<P>
   A: That hasn't been finalized yet, but there's a possibility
Michael Jordan and the Bulls could play in Dallas after all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the likelihood of Jordan returning to play one more
season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not good. Close friends like teammate Ron Harper indicate
Jordan's absence from yesterday's meeting (he was in the Bahamas
playing golf) is a strong signal he is distancing himself from the
league. However, Jordan, a free agent, could be intrigued by the
shorter regular season and chance to win a title for a new coach
and a new team like the Knicks. After his stance all last season,
if he returns to play for coach Tim Floyd and the Bulls, he will
lose as much face as the players have during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the Bulls all but broken apart with a new coach and
Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman in the free-agent market,
who are the favorites to win the NBA's shortened title?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Pacers and Jazz have the most players under contract (11)
of teams that went far in last year's playoffs. The Bulls and
Rockets have only four players under contract while the Mavericks
have 10, not including rookie Dirk Nowitzki. And, of course, there
are the Clippers, who have managed to still not hire a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the lockout do to the Mavericks?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ends their undefeated run, for one. Actually, coach Don
Nelson's team is in good shape in that it has its roster pretty
much set. The Mavericks need to quickly sign Nowitzki and re-sign
Kurt Thomas. Other than that, they have a long-shot chance at
landing Cedric Ceballos or trading one of their many point guards
like Khalid Reeves or Robert Pack to make way for Steve Nash's
takeover of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With only 52 games and little time to prepare, what quality
of play can we expect?
</P>
<P>
   A: Poor, at first. But with the fewer games carrying increased
significance, games should be incredibly intense after the first
month. Injuries, of course, will be a major factor as players won't
be in game shape right away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Besides 30 games, what did the NBA lose in the lockout?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tons of respect from fans, and any momentum created by last
summer's stirring Bulls-Jazz Finals. If Jordan retires as most
believe he will, that void coupled with the abbreviated season will
take a major bite out of the league's popularity.
</P>
</TEXT>
